<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES AGAIN BEAT METS IN LAST AT-BAT, 10-5 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Burrell and Jason Tyner were teammates on an
Olympic development team, and the two rookies remain friends. Tyner
has a fragile hold on a New York Mets roster spot, but Burrell's
situation is different. As Tyner said the other day, Burrell, the
Philadelphia Phillies' first baseman, is ``the man.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Mets now understand what Tyner means. For the
second game in a row, the Phillies beat the Mets in their final
at-bat at Shea Stadium, and Burrell played a major role both times.
Wednesday night, he hit a pair of home runs, the second off Armando
Benitez, in a 10-5 victory. On Tuesday, he hit a game-tying homer
off Benitez and the Phillies won in the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell, the No. 1 overall draft pick in 1998, homered in the
sixth inning to snap a 3-3 tie Wednesday night and then crushed a
grand slam off Benitez to blow the game open in the ninth. One
batter before the slam, the Mets reliever John Franco had walked in
the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have gone 9-8 in their last 17 games, but they have
held a lead in each of their defeats. The losses have been hard to
take _ a blown save, a missed scoring opportunity, a wild throw _
and Wednesday night's may have been the most bitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored three early runs off the Phillies' ace, Curt
Schilling. They gave that lead to their most reliable pitcher, Al
Leiter. Then the Phillies came back to take a 5-3 lead. Then the
Mets came back to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Then Franco came into the game. Doug Glanville led off the ninth
with a single, a high chopper to second that skittered through the
infield when Edgardo Alfonzo could not bare-hand it. Ron Gant
doubled, and after a strikeout, Franco issued an intentional walk
and faced Kevin Jordan with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who had allowed only nine walks before Wednesday night,
walked Jordan on a 3-2 pitch to force in the tie-breaking run.
Benitez then entered to boos, the fans recalling his blown save on
Tuesday, and Burrell blasted his first career slam to left.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are in the midst of their longest homestand of the
year, a stretch of 13 games, with the first nine against sub-.500
clubs and the last four against the first-place Atlanta Braves. If
the Mets were hoping to gain ground, they lost a chance Wednesday
night. The Braves lost to the Cubs, and the Mets remain four and a
half games out of first.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost for only the second time in Leiter's 14 starts.
Leiter, a left-hander, worked six and a third innings, allowing
five runs on eight hits and three walks. The Phillies put at least
one runner on base every inning, and Leiter never got into a
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart, Schilling, was not throwing as hard as he did
before off-season shoulder surgery. Schilling is a power pitcher _
he struck out 11 in eight innings to beat Atlanta last week _ but
his fastball was only in the range of 85 to 90 mph Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling made up for it with curveballs and sliders, and after
the second inning, the Mets could do little against him, managing
just three singles. Schilling gave up three runs on six hits in
seven innings, striking out five.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling struck out the first two Mets in the first inning, but
he walked Alfonzo and gave up a tremendous home run to Mike Piazza,
the Mets' catcher. Piazza, who also hit a two-run homer in his
first at-bat Tuesday, smoked his 20th of the season, the ball
striking a railing on the side of the second deck and caroming back
to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton nearly homered in the second, driving a pitch off the
fence in left-center for a double and sending Todd Zeile to third
with no outs. Zeile scored on a ground out by Tyner, but Leiter
fanned and Melvin Mora flied out, ending the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had a 3-0 lead, but they have led at some point in
every game since May 29, the day of Leiter's only loss.
</P>
<P>
   After the third inning Wednesday night, the Mets' lead was
history. With one out Glanville, the Phillies' leadoff man, rolled
a grounder to third. But Robin Ventura's throw pulled Zeile off
first, and Glanville was safe on the throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Gant doubled, a walk loaded the bases, and Mike Lieberthal, a
.429 career hitter off Leiter, doubled in two runs. Kevin Jordan's
sacrifice fly brought in the third run, tying the score at 3-3. Two
of the runs were unearned.
</P>
<P>
   After Burrell's first homer in the sixth, a line drive over the
left field wall, Gant contributed a bases-empty home run in the
seventh, increasing the Phillies' lead to 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   While the Phillies were figuring out Leiter, the Mets' bats went
silent off Schilling. Schilling can be one of baseball's dominant
starters, and if he were available, he would be attractive to any
contending team. The Phillies will almost certainly trade another
starter, Andy Ashby, but they have no plans to trade Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling has a complete no-trade clause, and though he said he
would waive it to play for a New York team, that does not change
the Phillies' thinking, a club official said. Schilling will make
$6.5 million next year, the last year of his contract, and if the
Phillies are going to contend next year, it is Schilling who will
front their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez Out for Season
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez, the three-time Gold Glove winner at shortstop for
the Mets, who has been out for three weeks with a broken forearm,
will have season-ending surgery on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles are scouting the Mets' farm system and are
discussing the idea of trading Mike Bordick to New York. For the
moment, though, the Mets will continue to use Kurt Abbott and
Melvin Mora at short.
</P>
<P>
   A pregame conversation with manager Bobby Valentine led Mora to
believe he will be playing more often. ``He said he likes the way I
play short and he said I know Alfonzo for a long time,'' Mora said.
``And then, as soon as you feel comfortable over there, the middle
of the infield is going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mora and second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo are from Venezuela,
and they have played together in winter ball. Valentine would not
characterize the conversation, other than to say he told Mora he
would be playing less often in the outfield. Mora has been used
infrequently in the outfield since Ordonez's injury on May 29. He
has started seven games at short; Abbott has started 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez was injured in Los Angeles while applying the tag on a
pickoff play. He had leaped into the air for a wide throw from
first baseman Todd Zeile, and his left forearm was exposed when he
came down to go for the tag. The Dodgers' F.P. Santangelo was
sliding headfirst, and his helmet crashed into Ordonez's arm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
