<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BOTCH IT IN BOSTON AS RELIEVERS OFFER NO RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It would not have mattered in the seventh inning
Wednesday night if the New York Yankees had Juan Gonzalez, Sammy
Sosa or both. It would not have mattered if they had fielded nine
superstars. Nothing else matters when pitchers do not throw
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took a 5-4 lead into the bottom of the seventh for
David Cone, before the relievers Jason Grimsley and Mike Stanton
gave it away, walking five hitters in the half-inning _ four in a
row at one point _ and propelling the Boston Red Sox to a 9-7
victory. The disastrous relief prevented the Yankees from winning
the third game of this four-game series, and ruined any chance of a
four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 36-30, a half-game ahead of the Red Sox (36-31).
The rookie Jake Westbrook pitches Thursday night for the Yankees,
against Boston's Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has not won a decision since April, but it was his lead
that was turned over to the bullpen in the Boston seventh. Grimsley
allowed a leadoff single to Nomar Garciaparra, before walking Carl
Everett. Third baseman Scott Brosius made a diving stop on a
grounder by Mike Stanley, and threw to first for the first out of
the inning, with the runners advancing.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg grounded sharply to second and Garciaparra was
able to score the tying run. But Grimsley walked the pinch-hitter
Brian Daubach, and then Manny Alexander, loading the bases. Of the
15 pitches Grimsley threw in the inning, five were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton took over, but he walked Jose Offerman on four pitches,
forcing home Everett with the go-ahead run. When Stanton walked the
next hitter, Jeff Frye, to score another run, he whirled on the
mound angrily, furious, his mood worsened by the screaming Red Sox
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon lined a double over the head of Paul O'Neill, and two
more runs scored. At that point Stanton was removed. Like Grimsley,
he threw only five strikes among 15 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The five-run seventh by the Red Sox was more than enough to
offset a two-run homer by Bernie Williams with two out in the
Yankee ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Summer arrived here, pushed along by a strong wind that blew
over the stands along the first-base line and gusted over the
left-field wall and toward the Charles River; for pitchers trying
to keep fly balls within the confines of Fenway Park, the most
imperfect of storms.
</P>
<P>
   The gales came into play immediately. Offerman doubled to right
to lead off the Boston first, moved to third on a ground out and
scored on a wild pitch. Nixon then lifted a high fly to center
field, and Williams, the Yankees' center fielder, moved back
steadily onto the warning track, without any panic, reaching for
the wall with his right hand, leery of banging against the fence.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled up, reached up _ and the ball carried over his head,
ricocheting against the wall. Nixon sprinted round the bases for a
triple, and he eventually scored on a grounder to first. Boston
led, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schourek shut out the Yankees through the first four
innings, but as the fifth inning began, he seemed uncomfortable on
the mound, kicking at the dirt in front of the rubber before and
after his first pitch. He walked the first two batters in the
inning, and with one out, Chris Turner _ the backup catcher who
always seems to contribute something when he plays _ dumped a
broken-bat single into short-center field, driving home Jorge
Posada.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox still led, 2-1. But O'Neill smashed a lead-off
double in the sixth and Hipolito Pichardo replaced Schourek. Two
batters later, Posada _ who played first base Wednesday night _
lined a single to right field, and O'Neill rambled around third
with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had good stuff, his fastball consistently reaching 89 to 90
mph; he finished with four strikeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
