<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SHIELDING TOBACCO FROM A LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 22:
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the House are engaged in a brazen effort to
protect the tobacco industry from a federal lawsuit. The House is
expected to vote today on an appropriations bill with a provision
that would make it practically impossible for the Justice
Department to finance its lawsuit against the industry. If this
provision survives, Congress will have allowed a powerful lobby to
stop legitimate federal litigation simply because it has bought the
allegiance of some members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Justice filed a civil suit against the industry last September
seeking to recover the more than $20 billion a year that the
federal government spends to treat people with smoking-related
diseases under Medicare and other federal programs. The suit also
asks for a permanent injunction against industry deceptions about
smoking's hazards. The states have already reached settlements
totaling $246 billion over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the billions involved, Congress refused last year to
give Justice $20 million to hire lawyers and experts. But the
department went forward by using $6 million from its general budget
and raising nearly $8 million from other agencies that oversee the
largest federal health programs.
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected an earlier effort to prohibit one of the
agencies, the Department of Veterans Affairs, from helping to
underwrite the litigation. But the House leadership does not give
up easily. The Justice Department spending bill up for a vote today
would prevent the department from using funds from other agencies
to support lawsuits initiated by the government, including the
tobacco case. This latest tactic deserves another rebuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
