u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     06-22 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TIGHTER RULES FOR 527 GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 22:
</P>
<P>
   After an earlier setback, the drive to end the secrecy
surrounding a pernicious form of campaign fund-raising is gaining
in the House. Today a House subcommittee is to begin drafting a
bill that could stop shadowy political slush funds from raising and
spending undisclosed sums for campaign ads. A disclosure
requirement for these groups, which have been created under Section
527 of the tax code, passed the Senate two weeks ago. It fell short
in the House the next day because of promises that supporters of
disclosure would get a chance to vote on an alternative later. The
moment to cast such a vote has now arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The abuses of the Section 527 groups have spread this year,
blowing another hole in campaign fund-raising laws. Those laws were
largely obviated when the Justice Department allowed elected
officials and party organizations to use ``soft money'' to
circumvent longstanding limits on donations. But at least the
parties disclosed the donors. This year, Rep. Tom DeLay and others
have set up what they say are independent units that run ads
attacking candidates but do not have to make their donors known.
The most notorious example occurred in March, when secret donors
who later turned out to be supporters of Gov. George W. Bush ran
attack ads against Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Joining with Sens. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin and Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut, McCain got the disclosure requirement for
Section 527 groups passed in the Senate. Foes of reform struck
back, proposing an alternative bill that would require disclosure
of donors for a wide array of public affairs and charitable groups.
Their approach was actually tailored to repel lawmakers by making
it overly broad and punitive toward unions.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Christopher Shays of Connecticut and Michael
Castle of Delaware, both Republicans, are joining a Democrat,
Martin Meehan of Massachusetts, to push a bill to broaden the
disclosure requirements beyond the 527 groups without making it so
inclusive that it violates the constitutional right to privacy of
advocacy organizations. Their measure would impose disclosure
requirements only on groups that spend $10,000 or more per year on
ads that mention a candidate 90 days before a general election or
60 days before a primary. Organizations that sponsor campaign
advertising would have the option of setting up separate accounts
for that purpose. Donors for these accounts would have to be
disclosed, a requirement not applying to donors supporting other
activities.
</P>
<P>
   This approach has emerged as the best opportunity for reform in
the House. Other lawmakers are pushing for even broader disclosure
requirements. But they should take care not to undermine the bill's
bipartisan backing by doing anything one-sided or destructive of
the constitutional rights of organizations involved in political
activities. After so many disappointments, if Congress cannot even
stop the clandestine fund-raising infecting the process this year,
it will be consigning the election system to the dark pre-Watergate
days of corruption and backdoor financial dealings.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
