<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADE-VIOLENCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENT MOB DEFIES LAPD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writer Alexa Haussler contributed to this report 
BY BETH BARRETT and ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Despite the presence of 600 police officers, a
mob surged down Figueroa Street after the Lakers' victory parade
Wednesday, stealing from vendors, smashing cars and store windows,
and terrorizing motorists and bus riders.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the worst violence, an MTA bus stopped in gridlocked
traffic under the Santa Monica (405) Freeway was attacked and
vandalized by as many as 50 people, according to riders and
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Police caught up with the destructive crowd by the Shrine
Auditorium - some 1.5 miles from Staples Center - and arrested
about 12 people for investigation of crimes including disturbing
the peace and assaulting a police horse, said LAPD Cmdr. David
Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of what they were doing was just minor hooliganism as
they were leaving the event,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's massive police turnout and forceful reaction sharply
contrasted with Monday night, when the rowdy crowd burned cars and
smashed windows while the Los Angeles Police Department waited
before taking control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good show of force, and it was a different
crowd,'' said Lt. Horace Frank, an LAPD spokesman. ``People just
pretty much came and just celebrated the Laker victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalish stressed that despite the turnout of 250,000 people,
``the problems were relatively minor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I think our personnel performed admirably, did an
outstanding job and the event was successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The five passengers and driver of the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority bus that was attacked saw the parade from
a different, more terrifying perspective.
</P>
<P>
   As their bus traveled north on Figueroa just before Venice
Boulevard, they watched a mob surging toward them shortly before 2
p.m. Witnesses estimated that between 20 and 50 people ran into the
street and began to destroy the bus, ripping apart the computer
system, breaking windows and rendering it inoperable.
</P>
<P>
   No police were in sight, they said, even though they were near
an automobile dealership vandalized after Monday night's
championship game, witnesses on the street and aboard the bus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the mob down the road, and then they attacked the bus
from both sides,'' said Margaret Sowma of Hancock Park. ``The bus
was tossed from side to side. I thought of the (1992) riot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid they'd kick the bus over; they started kicking it
with their feet,'' said Morrie Sanchez, who had delayed leaving a
meeting for a half-hour to avoid possible post-parade disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   The riders estimated that it took anywhere from five to 10
minutes before officers in riot gear rescued them.
</P>
<P>
   Two older women on the bus said they were going home from a
seniors meeting when the bus was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Bus driver Carlos Griffen said it was the worst violence he'd
seen in his 10-year MTA career. He hit the bus's emergency alarm,
but said police took 10 minutes to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said that when Wednesday's violence began, police
scrambled to contain it but heavy traffic in the area made it
difficult to respond.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 50 people jumped onto the bus, said Elvia Rodriguez,
the receptionist at the Toyota dealership. ``Gangsters were doing
signs. There were no police,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the bus, the crowd turned a lighted-arrow lane-closure
marker on its side just as helmeted police officers arrived to
chase them away.
</P>
<P>
   As the same crowd continued south, young men jumped onto cars,
denting roofs and splintering windshields. At one point, the
hooligans rushed a catering truck and stole its contents.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the roving mob passed through, Naveed Ulhaq, 19,
of Torrance surveyed the smashed windshield and dented hood of his
silver Acura. About 15 feet behind the car was Alondra Sandoval,
20, of Ontario, whose compact sedan had a large indentation on its
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   At 21st and Figueroa, Tiffany Craft, an import-export manager,
looked out from the grating protecting the front door of Bisou
Bisou, a designer clothing company, and praised the way police
reacted to the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were actually awesome as far as protecting the buildings
in the area, but there were some things they couldn't prevent,''
Craft said.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed across the street to the facade of Alarms Depot
Inc., which had its narrow plate-glass storefront smashed in.
``That's sad, because their window had just gotten smashed Monday
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vandalism occurred during the parade.
</P>
<P>
   As police chased away people who had occupied the roof of a
KCBS-TV (Channel 2) news truck across from Staples Center,
44-year-old Deborah Willis of Pacoima stood crestfallen next to her
white Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   The car's windshield was broken and its roof, hood and trunk
looked as if they, too, had been used as a viewing platform for the
parade. ``I can't start it,'' she said mournfully as her son and
daughter huddled about her.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
