<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S VICTORINE STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ After a quick start that included a goal and
two assists in his MLS debut, a 4-0 victory over MLS champion D.C.
United on March 25, Galaxy rookie Sasha Victorine has struggled to
stay effective. He has only one point since, an assist against New
England, May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Victorine has been pushed around by physical defenders such as
San Jose's John Doyle, but Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said he's not
worried that his former UCLA standout will find his rhythm again.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said that breaking in as a striker is much tougher than
breaking in anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young, the easiest place to step into is a
marker,'' said Schmid. ``A (defensive) marker just comes in and
shuts his guy down, you don't have the responsibility to come in
and make the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hardest to break in as a midfielder and especially a
forward. There's more demanded of you. Sasha, he's kind of going
through a curve, he's in a little bit of a valley, but I feel
confident he'll come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) If the MLS all-star voting was final, the Galaxy would
have six players on the West squad for the July 29 game in
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy leads all MLS teams in voting. Cobi Jones (forward),
Mauricio Cienfuegos (midfielder), Robin Fraser (defender) and Kevin
Hartman (goalkeeper) lead voting in their positions. Defender's
Greg Vanney and Ezra Hendrickson are among the top four in
defensive votes.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) The Galaxy leaves on a crucial 10-day, three game road
trip this afternoon. They face MLS and Western Division leader
Kansas City on Saturday, followed by D.C. United (June 28) and
Dallas (July 1). The team returns to the Rose Bowl, July 4, against
Columbus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
