u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-22 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEGACIES AWAIT IMPRINT OF YOUNG STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Maybe Tiger Woods isn't the next Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's the next Bjorn Borg, the genius filled with grace and
ice-water execution who wakes up the morning of a major tournament
and finds, deep in his heart, the fire suddenly extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Six times in seven years, Borg won the French Open. Five
consecutive times Borg won Wimbledon. Tennis was a boom sport
during those long-haired 1970s, and Borg was leading the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's summer, with Wimbledon around the corner, you can
rattle the memory bank and see that famous image of the new king
Borg after his epic victory.
</P>
<P>
   He is kneeling on the worn grass at Centre Court, hands raised
to his savior-like face, his eyes rolling back in disbelief as if
to say no one can stop him. The only one who could was himself.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Borg eventually did.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Woods' intelligence and emotional strength are far
greater than Borg's, but what happens if Woods runs out of
incentive?
</P>
<P>
   He won't need more money. He doesn't have anyone to play
against, not David Duval or Sergio Garcia or Ernie Els. Soon, he'll
give us a round of 58, so that will be another milestone passed.
</P>
<P>
   And, at this rate, the 18 major titles that would match Jack
Nicklaus are considered a foregone conclusion. But does he have
some other mark in mind to distance himself completely from prior
champions such as Nicklaus, Ben Hogan, Gene Sarazen or Gary Player?
</P>
<P>
   Amidst the awe inspired by this 24-year-old, one does question
how we are supposed to know what his legend and legacy is going to
be.
</P>
<P>
   This has become an intriguing season of comparing new champions
to old. It has happened time and again this summer, but are the
right factors being considered?
</P>
<P>
   Aren't Woods, Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant products of a new
generation _ child prodigies bred in an era of television and
marketing, groomed to arrive at this lofty place?
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that changes the dynamics of who they are and what they
could become.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you have to consider that maybe O'Neal isn't the next
Wilt Chamberlain or Kareem Abdul-Jabbar or Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Shaq is just Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's big and a lot more lovable than most of his early
detractors gave him credit for. Maybe he's Shaq the champion this
week and Shaq ``Kazaam'' the next week and Shaq ``Three Rings is
Good Enough'' some time down the line.
</P>
<P>
   One championship, though significant, does not script his
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bryant, is it right to put him in a box that says he's
the new Michael Jordan and that the Lakers are the new Bulls, or
the reincarnation of the old Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   Please. How can these new Lakers, who will undergo changes this
off-season, since Glen Rice is not the perfect triangle-mate, be
talked about in the same breath as the Magic Johnson/Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar/James Worthy Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   But back to Kobe. Granted, being like Mike is a desirable box to
be put in.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe's voice sure sounds like Jordan's. His adidas commercials
are knockoffs of Air Jordan's soaring Nike ads. The young Lakers
star is as handsome as Jordan. His moves mimic the greatest
basketball player of all time.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something strange about watching Bryant perform
inside this Michael Jordan mold. We don't really know yet who this
21-year-old will grow up to be. On the court, in his heart, in his
mind. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   His coach questions how comparisons to Jordan continue. Surely,
at this stage of his young career, Bryant can beam out the promise
of being like Mike, but this is an entirely differently person who
may never have the coldness, the will, the drive to approach what
Jordan became.
</P>
<P>
   And so what if Bryant does not get there?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the longer the comparison continues, the less likely we
will see who Kobe Bryant is becoming. Worse, the less likely it
might be that Bryant will establish his own image, his own way, his
own mark on the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. has long been called the next Willie Mays, the
next Hank Aaron, the Michael Jordan of baseball. The over-the-back
catches, the prodigious home-run production and the charisma have
warranted comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, back home in Cincinnati, Griffey is working
through a season that will ensure his career his uniquely his own.
</P>
<P>
   The need for comparison is understandable. It is a sign of
appreciation, of acknowledging we're watching something rare,
startling. But sometimes, it takes the test of time, the unfolding
of seasons and of a personality, for the real image to emerge and
lasting impact to be known.
</P>
<P>
   The splendor isn't in comparing what was. It's in watching what
is.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
