   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-OIL (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Worried that voters will blame the
Clinton administration _ and Vice President Al Gore _ for the
recent surge in oil prices, the Gore campaign has begun an effort
paint Gov. George W. Bush, a one-time oil company executive, as a
tool of the oil interests it says are relentlessly gouging
consumers. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOT-COM-LAYOFFS (San Francisco) _ As quickly and aggressively as
they filled their cubicles last year, dozens of dot-coms across the
country are unloading employees in an effort to meet a seemingly
obvious goal heretofore put on indefinite hold: Make a profit. The
layoffs signal an end to the unbounded optimism of some dot-com
employees who flocked to start-ups in hopes of developing sudden
wealth, but who now say they are approaching new job offers with
more caution. And the very stock market that once held the keys to
new wealth now may be equally responsible not just for lowered
expectations, but for lost jobs. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-SPRINT (Undated) _ Facing mounting opposition from
regulators to its $115 billion deal to acquire Sprint Corp.,
Worldcom Inc. is considering selling off broad swaths of Sprint's
operations, including Sprint's entire long-distance unit, the
third-largest in the nation, people close to the companies said
Wednesday. By Seth Schiesel with Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   UAL-USAIR (Undated) _ James E. Goodwin, the chief executive of
UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, describes his proposed
$4.3 billion purchase of US Airways as a ``win-win for consumers''
that will usher in a glorious new era of global air service. But
many passengers see the proposed merger rather differently. For
them, air travel is already a grim reality of high fares,
interminable check-in lines, overcrowded planes, endless delays and
stingy in-flight meals. Those two visions are now on a collision
course in Washington. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-RIGHTS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ When he voted against the
Civil Rights Act of 1964, Barry Goldwater declared, ``The problems
of discrimination cannot be cured by laws alone.'' More than three
decades of experience suggests that Goldwater was wrong, although
not entirely. There is abundant evidence that the act did much to
improve prospects for blacks, but discrimination persists, taking
on more subtle forms that are less amenable to correction by
legislation. Still, existing laws could combat discrimination more
effectively. By Alan B. Krueger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDERS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Regulators have suspended and
fined the former owner of Founders Asset Management, which manages
more than $8 billion, for failing to disclose that some of the
firm's clients paid excessive commissions on stock trades in the
early 1990s. Bjorn Erik Borgen, the sole owner of Founders during
the three-year period in question, agreed to a 180-day suspension
from the investment business. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-AD-COLUMN (Detroit) _ Stung by accusations of racism for
having used makeup to darken the face of a nonunion, white stunt
driver during the filming of a television commercial, Ford Motor
Co. said Wednesday that it would postpone filming new commercials
until a strike by unionized actors is resolved, and that it would
review its policies on makeup. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
