<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The computer column: Spector and
eBlaster are snoopware. They are the computer equivalent of a VCR
that secretly records everything that shows up on a computer screen
_ every piece of e-mail, every Web page, every instant message,
every program and file opened, every keystroke and every password
or credit card number. Many people entrust their most intimate and
sensitive information to their computers. So snoopware makes
possible the computer equivalent of reading other people's private
diaries, opening their mail, going through their garbage, scanning
their bank statements and portfolios, cracking their safes, tapping
their phones and peeping through their windows, all at once. By
Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-AMIGA-REBORN (Undated) _ Amiga starts up again. A former
trucker and Amiga devotee is determined to put the Amiga operating
system, known for its streamlined code and graphics, onto a new
Amiga computer, personal digital assistants and cellphones around
the world. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Techno news and notes: Dell wants to
bring MP3 music into the living room; after online pictures, the
online photo album is here; a new online literature group tries to
get respect, more.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The column: Clothing, soap, toys
and even cameras: how to buy what's left at the airport carousel,
at Unclaimedbaggage.com. By Michelle Slatalla.
