<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Techno questions answered: Why does my
computer disconnect from the Internet when I am downloading files?
How can I get off a software company's mailing list? By J.D.
Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-MUSIC-MUSEUM (Undated) _ Music museum in Seattle. By Michel
Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-STOLEN-ART (Undated) _ Sites to look up stolen artworks. By
Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CHAT-ROOMS (Undated) _ Keeping online debate clean of
cursing and spam-free: a look at chat-room moderators. By Sally
McGrane.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-STRATEGY-GAME (Undated) _ Ground Control, a strategy game
from Sweden where getting there is half the fun. By Peter Olafson.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CYBERBOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Book review of ``Cyberselfish:
A Critical Romp Through the Terribly Libertarian Culture of
High-Tech,'' by Paulina Borsook. A former Wired writer takes on the
prevailing libertarian attitudes of Silicon Valley. By Lisa
Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-DNA-INK (Undated) _ Using scannable ink with embedded DNA
for labels and commercial identification. By Daniel Sorid.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BOMB-DETECTION (Undated) _ Bomb detecting. By Daniel Sorid.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-TRACKING-COWS (Undated) _ Cows with GPS tracking collars. By
Shelly Freierman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOM-FURNITURE (Undated) _ For anyone unsatisfied by the
styles, quality or general similarity of mass-produced furniture,
or frustrated by the prices of vintage furniture, commissioning a
piece produces furniture specific to your tastes and needs. In some
cases, it is an opportunity to work with an architect or designer
on a project smaller than a house or an interior. In some cases, it
solves a problem that couldn't be solved with existing furniture.
Commissioning custom work can be comparable to the cost and
delivery time of more expensive, mass-produced items. And it's
cheaper than antiques. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   REAL-ESTATE-RAGE (Undated) _ New Yorkers are mad about real
estate. So are Californians. Texans, too. Boiling mad. After eight
years of relentless price escalation, angry customers are slamming
down phones, brokers said, and picking pointless fights with
sellers. They are even stalking out of negotiations. Many house
hunters are suffering from battle fatigue brought on by the highest
real estate prices in history. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI-GARDENS (Jackson, Miss.) _ On Felder Rushing, a
Mississippi storyteller and agricultural extension agent. When he
took on the lawn industry, explaining on his radio show why
``weed-and-feed'' is bad for your lawn, the University of
Mississippi tried to fire him, but a public outcry saved his job.
So he roams the state dispensing information and collecting
``passalong plants'' from ``old lady gardens.'' By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   SLEEPING-PORCH (Undated) _ Just outside the door of my writing
room here in Hollywood there is a collage of snapshots my mother
put together for a family reunion some years back. The snapshot
that catches my eye every time was taken when I was about 6. My
brother Frank and I were asleep on a couple of cots on my
grandparents' sleeping porch, sheets thrown back exposing our
scrawny little bodies, the fetid darkness of a Washington D.C.
summer night visible through the screened walls of the porch. We
spent every summer sleeping on a screen porch in those days, when
air conditioning was an exclusive feature of the movie theater
downtown, nowhere in evidence in our home or the homes of anyone we
knew. The sleeping porch was something we looked forward to, when
the heat and humidity would finally build to the point that the
cots would be dragged out and once again we'd be exposed to the
elements _ cooled, if only slightly, by an itinerant breeze, sung
to sleep by the insistent nighttime chatter of cicadas. By Lucian
K. Truscott IV.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
