<HEADLINE>
SHAW WILL SHARE CLOSER'S ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON - Jeff Shaw's arm and shoulder are healthy, but after he
allowed a solo homer to Houston's Jeff Bagwell on Tuesday, the
closer's spot isn't solely his.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said matchups will dictate whom he
uses to close games. The decision comes after Shaw blew his sixth
save in 18 chances when he allowed the ninth-inning homer to
Bagwell. The struggle was compounded when Shaw yielded a double to
Lance Berkman and walked Moises Alou before being bailed out by
rookie Matt Herges.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago Shaw blew a save against the Mets, and afterward
it was learned Shaw was experiencing weakness in the back of his
shoulder. He didn't pitch for a week, then returned in non-closing
situations before earning his first save in a month Sunday against
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still consider (Shaw) to be the prime guy, but I'm going to
look at the matchups and make sure the matchups are in his favor,''
Johnson said. ``I think he's been making progress. His previous
four outings were pretty good. Hopefully, he'll get back to where
he was, but I'm not going to just hand it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he thought about using Terry Adams to pitch the
ninth with the Dodgers holding a one-run lead in Tuesday's 9-6 win
in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Shaw) just didn't locate,'' Johnson said. ``He tried to throw
it away and he threw it right down the middle. I think it's
something where I'm still going to have to watch his workload,
watch the matchup. The matchup wasn't real good to begin with -
Bagwell was hitting .500 off him before, but being the masochist
that I am, I wanted to see where he was at.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz due today: When Jose Vizcaino arrived at Fenway Park to
greet his new Yankees teammates Wednesday, Jim Leyritz was still
packing up his gear. Leyritz, acquired by the Dodgers in exchange
for Vizcaino, is expected to be available for today's series finale
with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has always said I'm an ideal National League player
because I can play everywhere,'' said Leyritz, who's batted .218
with a homer and four RBI for the Yankees. ``I haven't talked to
Davey about what my role is going to be, but I think, in the
National League with no DH, the double switches, hitting for the
pitcher, there'll be something for me to do pretty much every day.
I'm looking at it as an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz is to be paid $1 million this season while Vizcaino is
owed $3.5 million in the final year of his contract. The Dodgers
will pick up just shy of $1 million of Vizcaino's deal.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz has played with the Yankees, Boston, the Angels and San
Diego. He has 89 career homers, and eight in the postseason, but
none more memorable than his eighth-inning shot off Atlanta's Mark
Wohlers in the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, I just think he's not afraid of the pressure,
not bothered by big situations,'' said Dodgers ace Kevin Brown, who
played with Leyritz for the 1998 NL-champion Padres. ``He kind of
thrives on it. I think he's a good one to have, someone that enjoys
and thrives under those conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino was thrilled to arrive in the Yankees clubhouse, even
if it was on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching the Yankees on TV Sunday, and I was saying, 'I
hope I get a chance to play in Yankee Stadium before I retire,' ''
Vizcaino said. ``Now I'm going to be wearing Yankee pinstripes.
It's a privilege to wear the uniform of the greatest organization
in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley return set: Though the timetable is a little slower than
he hoped, injured Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley will begin a rehab
assignment Friday in Triple-A Albuquerque with a targeted return
for Monday's series opener with San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
