<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-LAKERS-PARADE-2ndTake     06-22 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-PARADE-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: It's good craziness.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most fans only caught a glimpse or two of the stars because the
players were mixed in with other people on the buses. At Staples
Center, the sound system was poor and the viewing stage far away
from the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for most, it seemed to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neal shouted, ``Can You Dig It?'' the crowd erupted, as
they did when Kobe Bryant, the Lakers' dizzyingly talented,
21-year-old guard, said, ``We love you!''
</P>
<P>
   The day, many said, wasn't just about seeing the Lakers stars up
close. It was also about feeling good about Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fans began to arrive by car, light rail, bus, and even bicycle
before 7 a.m., mingling with each other and the street vendors.
Many shared water or stories of past Lakers greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Martinez, a delivery driver in Rosemead, told his boss
he'd be back later, jumped on his bicycle and pedaled 23 miles with
a buddy to the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 12 years since we've seen this,'' said Martinez,
wearing his new, $69.99 Lakers jersey. ``That makes it just that
much more special.''
</P>
<P>
   Many passed the time at the arena listening to the Lakers band
and monitoring the parade, which began at the Department of Water
and Power headquarters on Hope Street, where about 3,000 people
heard Jackson and O'Neal predict a dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal then gave L.A. Police Chief Bernard C. Parks a check from
himself and the Lakers to pay for two $42,000 patrol cars destroyed
in Monday's melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to say when we get one next year, we just want to be
safe and everybody to do the right thing because we're going to get
one next year,'' O'Neal told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The act of generosity had already rippled far ahead through the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq's paying for the police cars,'' said Johnny Razo of Los
Angeles, the man who tried to sell his cool spot under a skimpy
tree, and the word rippled along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're Laker family,'' another man said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No color lines, peace,'' a third chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who endeared himself to the city both for his superhuman
basketball skills and his penchant for bestowing grand, yet
self-deprecating nicknames upon himself, added another to the
string.
</P>
<P>
   ``And from now on, I am no longer `the Big Aristotle,''' O'Neal
joked, playing to the crowd. ``I want to be known as `the Big
Shakespeare' because it was Shakespeare who said: `Some men are
born great, some achieve greatness, some have greatness thrust upon
them.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great doing this this year for the city and for
everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this for the city,'' agreed Jackson, who won six
championships with the Chicago Bulls before joining the Lakers less
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The team was showered with confetti from spectators sitting on
sidewalks, rooftops and balconies.
</P>
<P>
   At times, some fans had to be ushered back to the sidewalk by
officers in riot gear. A few people were handcuffed and taken away
from the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Bryant flashed peace signs to the crowd as
screaming celebrants snapped pictures and tossed T-shirts and caps
up to the players for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   As a skywriter wrote ``Lakers'' in the sky and the Lakers band
played ``We Are the Champions,'' people in the crowd at Staples
Center stood on their toes and screamed as the team finally arrived
nearly an hour late.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that the speeches were short or the players
hard to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see them on TV, but with the expensive Staples tickets,
you can't see them,'' Sean Telles, a college student from San
Gabriel, said. ``When you're here, you feel the energy, and it's
good energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Orozco of West Covina cradled his video camera as he sat
in a lawn chair and waited for the crowd to clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shot in the arm in terms of love,'' he said. ``The
city's getting together to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
