<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-PARADE-1stLd-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. WHOOPS IT UP FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writer Eric Nelson contributed to this report 
BY BETH BARRETT, ALEXA HAUSSLER and RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal and his Lakers teammates lifted
the spirit Wednesday of a city starved for greatness onto their
shoulders for a few glorious hours that made everyone feel like
world champions.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating their first NBA Championship in a dozen years with
Los Angeles' largest-ever sports parade, the Lakers rode through
the heart of downtown on red double-decker buses as 250,000 or more
fans cheered themselves hoarse in a sea of purple and gold jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers took turns holding aloft their NBA Championship
trophy, the caravan inched its way to City Hall, where Mayor
Richard Riordan and other city dignitaries thanked them. Then, in
fits and starts, the parade crept along an 11-block route to
Staples Center, where a roaring crowd jammed parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Lakers,'' exulted Tyesha Anthony, a Chatsworth
resident wearing a Glen Rice jersey, who said she skipped work to
be at the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them, because they're a team that works together and
that's what it's all about. They're what's uniting us now. They
give the city pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan proclaimed the Lakers ``a new dynasty,'' and Coach Phil
Jackson promised the championship will simply be ``the first of the
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   And MVP O'Neal, with all the raw power of his smashing dunks,
hit the joy of victory hardest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you dig it? Can you dig it? Can you dig it?'' he roared to
the crowd gathered at Staples Center. The crowd roared back.
</P>
<P>
   Police were on alert early, with more than 600 officers on foot
and dozens of others on motorcycles and horseback and in patrol
cars. Their massive presence contrasted with their passive stance
Monday night, when cars were burned and property destroyed after
the Lakers defeated the Indiana Pacers, 116-111, for the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was some violence after the parade and police moved
quickly against troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what takes the fun away from the sport,'' said Henry
Hernandez, 37, of Canoga Park, who saw one, then another, glass
bottle smash on the street near where he stood. ``I've been out
here since 5 a.m. and all of a sudden, you get somebody throwing a
bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   A relentless sun forced hundreds of people to seek medical
treatment for heat exhaustion, most of them elderly fans or young
children. Supplies of oxygen and ice were quickly used up, but most
problems were considered minor.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that dampened the sky-high spirits of the adoring
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Mestaz drove in from the Mojave Desert for his dad, who
died about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to talk to my dad about the Lakers, and though
he liked them, he'd always say, 'They'll never make it,''' Mestaz
said. ``When they won, my wife said, 'You owe it to your dad to
go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many people used a sick day, took a long lunch hour or skipped
school to join the throng with their cardboard cutouts of O'Neal,
Lakers banners, posters of the Lakers cut out of the Los Angeles
Daily News and various noisemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff and Liz Tanalega of Northridge said they were awakened
early by their 15-day-old daughter, Jeliza Rose, took one look at
each other and knew they had to drive to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, 'Let's go!,''' Liz Tanalega said. ``We're such big
fans and it's such an experience being out here. There's so much
adrenaline. It's good craziness.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Most fans only caught a glimpse or two of the stars because the
players were mixed in with other people on the buses. At Staples
Center, the sound system was poor and the viewing stage far away
from the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for most, it seemed to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neal shouted, ``Can You Dig It?'' the crowd erupted, as
they did when Kobe Bryant, the Lakers' dizzyingly talented,
21-year-old guard, said, ``We love you!''
</P>
<P>
   The day, many said, wasn't just about seeing the Lakers stars up
close. It was also about feeling good about Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fans began to arrive by car, light rail, bus, and even bicycle
before 7 a.m., mingling with each other and the street vendors.
Many shared water or stories of past Lakers greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Martinez, a delivery driver in Rosemead, told his boss
he'd be back later, jumped on his bicycle and pedaled 23 miles with
a buddy to the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 12 years since we've seen this,'' said Martinez,
wearing his new, $69.99 Lakers jersey. ``That makes it just that
much more special.''
</P>
<P>
   Many passed the time at the arena listening to the Lakers band
and monitoring the parade, which began at the Department of Water
and Power headquarters on Hope Street, where about 3,000 people
heard Jackson and O'Neal predict a dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal then gave L.A. Police Chief Bernard C. Parks a check from
himself and the Lakers to pay for two $42,000 patrol cars destroyed
in Monday's melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to say when we get one next year, we just want to be
safe and everybody to do the right thing because we're going to get
one next year,'' O'Neal told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The act of generosity had already rippled far ahead through the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq's paying for the police cars,'' said Johnny Razo of Los
Angeles, the man who tried to sell his cool spot under a skimpy
tree, and the word rippled along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're Laker family,'' another man said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No color lines, peace,'' a third chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who endeared himself to the city both for his superhuman
basketball skills and his penchant for bestowing grand, yet
self-deprecating nicknames upon himself, added another to the
string.
</P>
<P>
   ``And from now on, I am no longer `the Big Aristotle,''' O'Neal
joked, playing to the crowd. ``I want to be known as `the Big
Shakespeare' because it was Shakespeare who said: `Some men are
born great, some achieve greatness, some have greatness thrust upon
them.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great doing this this year for the city and for
everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this for the city,'' agreed Jackson, who won six
championships with the Chicago Bulls before joining the Lakers less
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The team was showered with confetti from spectators sitting on
sidewalks, rooftops and balconies.
</P>
<P>
   At times, some fans had to be ushered back to the sidewalk by
officers in riot gear. A few people were handcuffed and taken away
from the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Bryant flashed peace signs to the crowd as
screaming celebrants snapped pictures and tossed T-shirts and caps
up to the players for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   As a skywriter wrote ``Lakers'' in the sky and the Lakers band
played ``We Are the Champions,'' people in the crowd at Staples
Center stood on their toes and screamed as the team finally arrived
nearly an hour late.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that the speeches were short or the players
hard to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see them on TV, but with the expensive Staples tickets,
you can't see them,'' Sean Telles, a college student from San
Gabriel, said. ``When you're here, you feel the energy, and it's
good energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Orozco of West Covina cradled his video camera as he sat
in a lawn chair and waited for the crowd to clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shot in the arm in terms of love,'' he said. ``The
city's getting together to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
