<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TAKE ADVANTAGE OF MISTAKE-PRONE TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This is called a winning streak, and it's not
just a midsummer night's dream.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have seen it before, even if it has been a couple of
weeks. But it does happen, especially when the other team is the
one kicking the ball, dropping it or throwing it into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins put on such a slapstick exhibition with
their defense last night, and the Rangers took full advantage of it
with a 7-5 victory at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to win a game, regardless of how you do it,''
shortstop Royce Clayton said. ``The object is to win, however you
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Twins errors, two by pitcher Bob Wells in one
record-breaking inning, led to three unearned runs, and shortstop
Cristian Guzman failed to handle Dave Martinez's one-hop smash in
the fifth inning, turning a potential inning-ending double play
into a two-run double. Put it all together and the Rangers were
able to win for the second consecutive game, a two-game winning
streak last accomplished June 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Esteban Loaiza, trying to maintain his tenuous
spot in the rotation, battled through six innings to get the
victory, his first since May 25. His offense and the Twins' defense
combined to give him a 6-4 lead through six innings, and the
bullpen combination of Mike Venafro, Jeff Zimmerman and John
Wetteland made it stand up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time,'' Loaiza said. ``We need to win games
after a bad \R1-8\S road trip. We just need to keep swinging the
bats and pitch the way we have the last couple nights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers weren't completely dependent on the Twins' futility
against starter Brad Radke. Designated hitter David Segui was
3-for-4 with three runs scored, and the Rangers received no less
than four two-out run-scoring hits: a double by Mike Lamb in the
second and singles by Clayton in the fourth, Ivan Rodriguez in the
sixth and Rusty Greer in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things we weren't able to do when we weren't winning
games,'' Clayton said. ``We were leaving runners in scoring
position and not getting the big hits. Tonight and last night we
were able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers would have been in deep trouble if the Twins had
played a little better defense, starting with Guzman in the fourth.
With Segui at second and two outs, he fielded Gabe Kapler's routine
grounder and proceeded to bounce his throw past first baseman Butch
Huskey. It ended up in the Rangers' dugout, allowing Segui to
score. That erased the Twins' 2-1 lead and, after Kapler went to
second, Clayton put the Rangers ahead with his single to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen, and you have to take advantage of it,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins tied it in the fifth, but the Rangers went ahead in
the bottom of the inning. With runners at first and second,
Martinez smashed a one-hop grounder that caromed off Guzman's glove
and out to right-center field, allowing both runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got one more in the sixth when Wells, who relieved
Radke, dropped Kapler's popup for an error and later tried to pick
him off second with nobody covering. Kapler went to third and
scored on Rodriguez's single. Wells did throw out two runners on a
grounder and a bunt, giving him four fielding chances in one
inning, a dubious American League record for pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Another run scored in the eighth after Clayton led off with a
single. Pitcher Travis Miller picked him off first, but first
baseman David Ortiz threw wildly as Clayton went to second,
allowing him to end up at third. Greer, with his fourth consecutive
multihit game, drove him home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard the last two games and made the Twins make
mistakes,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got a long ways to go,'' Clayton said. ``But we
just need to play good, solid baseball. We've got a good stretch of
games at home, and we've played well at home so hopefully history
will repeat itself.''
nn
</P>
