<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT FUN TO BE AT THE YMCA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Bad Day, Definition No. 743:
<P>
   In the parking lot of the Marin YMCA Tuesday, a man backed his
car out of a handicapped-parking spot.
</P>
<P>
   Crash. He crunched into the left front panel of a parked,
late-model sedan. There was enough damage that the driver's car had
to be towed.
</P>
<P>
   While our guy was filling out a police report, someone ran out
of the YMCA building and told him he had an urgent phone call
inside _ from the San Rafael Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The SRFD informed our guy that his house was on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, our guy caught a break. It turned out that his
house was not ablaze. A field near his house was burning.
</P>
<P>
   But for a minute there, the guy had a great hard-luck story
going.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS kissed his U.S. Open trophy, a long kiss; it's a
good thing it wasn't a freezing cold day.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal kissed and hugged his NBA Finals MVP trophy,
and Laker teammate Kobe Bryant carried on with the NBA championship
trophy until you wanted to yell at the screen, ``Get a room!''
</P>
<P>
   Gives a whole new meaning to the term ``trophy wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``WE'RE STILL in business.'' That is the message of an ad in The
Chronicle placed by Stanford Hospital and clinics, currently
experiencing a nurses' strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucile Packard Children's Hospital ... had 43 women who
delivered new babies this past weekend alone,'' the ad brags.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tileston wonders, ``Why is there no mention of the number
of  &UR; old  &LR; babies that were delivered?'' Age discrimination?
</P>
<P>
   And if the hospital is well-staffed, why did those 43 women give
birth alone?
</P>
<P>
   TOO MANY CARS in San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   Solution: Lakerize 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Invite a couple of busloads of Laker fans up here for a
celebration party. They would roll and torch a few hundred
vehicles. It's not vandalism, it's thinning the herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those aren't real Laker fans,'' city and team officials are
saying in Los Angeles about the rioters and vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Sure they are. Look at the pictures. They're wearing Laker
jerseys. They were out there in the arena parking lot, watching the
video screen, cheering the team on.
</P>
<P>
   So they  &UR; are  &LR; Laker fans. Stupid and mindlessly violent Laker
fans, but still.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not like L.A. doesn't have cars to burn.
</P>
<P>
   CAR STUFF: Allen Duzak spotted a car with a bumper sticker,
``Hang up and drive.'' The driver was reading a book. ... Yana
Murphy saw a woman driving a blue Audi, license plate ``INNIE.'' It
took Yana a second to figure it out. ... Walt Giachini says to stop
griping about the $3 toll on the big bridge and the $2 tab on the
others. He saw a Disney Channel documentary on bridges. A new
suspension bridge in Kobe, Japan, has a toll of $27. ... The Old
Homeboy suggests Toyota pull those TV commercials of Steve Young
driving around with hot-looking dates. Steve is married. Do
Toyota's ad people have concussions? ... And John Jamison was
trying to walk across Montgomery, but had to wait to allow three
red-light-running cars to zoom past. An elderly gent beside John
muttered, ``There oughtta be a law.''
</P>
<P>
   OVERHEARD near Union Square, one Delta flight attendant telling
another how she handled an in-flight emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-to-SFO flight was full, the attendants were busy
serving dinner when a passenger rang his call button and told the
attendant, ``My baked potato is bad!''
</P>
<P>
   Attendant: ``So I picked it up off his tray, gave it a couple of
good spanks and said, `Bad potato! Bad potato!' I put it back on
his tray and told him, `Sir, if that potato gives you any more
problems, you just let me know.' ''
</P>
<P>
   THAR SHE BLOWS: The suggestion here that it might be exciting to
watch authorities dispose of a beached whale carcass by blowing it
up with dynamite stirred the memory of George Seaman.
</P>
<P>
   George takes us back to about '55, when he was the gunnery
officer aboard a Coast Guard cutter in the Atlantic. The ship came
across a dead whale and George thought it would be a good target
for gunnery practice. The crew fired its 40mm guns at the whale.
They thought they might even be able to sink it.
</P>
<P>
   The shelling did nothing, although Seaman says it was a hoot.
Then the commanding officer decided the carcass was a navigational
hazard and ordered Seaman to blow it up with dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   George had no experience with dynamite. He and another crewman
rowed out to the carcass, chopped a hole in the top of the whale
with a fire axe and stuffed in the dynamite. But they didn't use
enough, and the explosion was nothing more than a muffled poof.
</P>
<P>
   So the commander ordered the cutter to ram the whale several
times, finally slicing it in two.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions remain:
</P>
<P>
   -- Doesn't every whale already have a hole on top?
</P>
<P>
   -- George  &UR; Seaman? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Will the book open with the line, ``Call me Ishmael
Caulfield?''
</P>
<P>
   -- In the movie version, will Shaquille O'Neal prevent a
Titanic-like disaster, shredding the carcass by standing on the
cutter's bow and shooting free throws at the dead whale?
</P>
<P>
   -- Were they sure the whale wasn't merely napping?
</P>
</TEXT>
