<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-WATER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACECRAFT SPOTS EVIDENCE OF WATER ON THE RED PLANET
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Scientists monitoring images from a spacecraft orbiting Mars
are cautiously suggesting that craters in the planet's southern
hemisphere may have recently been seeping water into the planet's
surface and atmosphere.
<P>
   If the scientists' interpretation is correct, it could prompt
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration to pursue more
intensive searches for life beneath the Martian surface, despite
the catastrophic failures of two relatively recent Mars missions.
</P>
<P>
   A fresh look at pictures from the Mars Global Surveyor has led
scientists to infer that fan-shaped depressions near the rim of at
least one Martian crater could be evidence for recent outflows of
water emerging to the surface very much the way underground springs
do on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Vivid images of the Martian surface, taken by spacecraft ever
since Mariner orbited the Red Planet in 1971, have revealed long
sinuous canyons that must have once been surging watercourses, and
flat plains that could have been vast lake beds.
</P>
<P>
   But if the planet's surface did in fact hold liquid water
billions of years ago, it has long vanished _ either deep
underground or evaporating into the thin Martian atmosphere and
then diffusing as vapor throughout the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Water has been detected on Mars, but only in the form of ice
trapped at the poles. With a temperature of more than 220 degrees
below zero on the surface, any Martian water that might emerge from
underground now would instantly turn to vapor.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Global Surveyor has been orbiting the Red Planet since
September 1997. The search for water _ a necessary ingredient for
life _ has been one of the main objectives of NASA's long-term plan
to explore Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Weiler, NASA's space science chief, in a discussion
earlier this month, reminded a meeting of the National Academy of
Sciences Space Studies Board that, ``Without water, there was no
life as we know it in the past, and there is no life now. It's all
about the water.''
</P>
<P>
   A full report on the Global Surveyor's images by some of NASA's
most expert team members was to be published in the journal Science
next week. The space agency had tried to keep the report secret
until a briefing next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But as word leaked out this week, officials said some of the
speculation was inaccurate, and they hastily rescheduled their
press conference to this morning. Editors of the journal Science
announced they will release the full paper publicly Thursday as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the space agency's headquarters refused to talk
about the water question Wednesday, but an announcement from the
agency's public affairs office said that Thursday's rescheduled
press conference will ``discuss the recent discovery of evidence
for liquid water on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Malin, founder and chief scientist of Malin Space
Science Systems, which manufactures the Global Surveyor's high-tech
cameras, is the major co-author of next week's Science article, and
he will be featured on the panel at Thursday's press conference.
</P>
<P>
   So will Kenneth Edgett, Malin's staff scientist, who is a
co-author of the Science paper, while the lead-off panel member
will be Weiler, the space agency's associate administrator for
space science at NASA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of the importance NASA attaches to the report
Thursday is the list of the panel's other members: One is Michael
Carr, a planetary geologist at the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo
Park who has studied how major bodies of Martian surface water a
billion or more years ago could have sunk far beneath the surface
due primarily to volcanic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Bruce Jakosky, a geophysicist and director of the
center for Astrobiology at the University of Colorado. He is
currently studying the possibility of Martian life.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth panel member is James J. Garvin, a Mars Program
Scientist at NASA Headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
