r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     06-22 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD SAVES THE DAY FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- In the boxscore, the save went to Troy Percival. But
there was no denying it was left fielder Darin Erstad who truly
saved the Angels' 3-1 victory over the Kansas City Royals Wednesday
night before 16,169 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Percival entered the game in the ninth inning with two on and
one out and the Angels leading, 3-0, thanks to 8 &UR;  &LR; 1/3 scoreless
innings by starter Jarrod Washburn. But Percival, who blew a save
opportunity Tuesday night and another eight days ago, came in and
immediately gave up an RBI single to Carlos Beltran (the run
charged to Washburn).
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Jermaine Dye, who was the American League player
of the month in April. Dye didn't get all of a Percival fastball,
but got enough of it to reach the seats beyond the short fence down
the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   But before it could land safely in the hands of an awaiting fan,
Erstad fought off the fan for the ball and made the game-saving
catch, pulling the ball back into the field of play and robbing Dye
of a three-run homer. Percival retired Mike Sweeney on a fly to
right for his 18th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened to the `hometown' fans?'' Erstad asked.
``You get some interesting plays in the corner there. It was like a
war zone, you get to the wall and it's a free-for-all. I guess the
fans have as much right to it as we do. It's not enough you got to
catch the ball, you also got to fight the fans for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival had Erstad to thank for saving this one, but he didn't
think it would come to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a jam shot,'' Percival said of Dye's fly
ball. ``It didn't sound good (of the bat). But it was great to get
a great play by Ersty. I never thought it was going that far. But
nothing he does surprises me at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Percy made a great pitch,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said.
``Believe it or not, he jammed him a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also drove in all three Angels' runs, two on a
fifth-inning homer, and one on a seventh-inning groundout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the Darin Erstad show tonight,'' Scioscia said. ``This
guy comes up big anywhere on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Washburn (3-1) and Royals starter Mac Suzuki (3-1) sailed
through the first four innings. Each pitcher allowed only one hit,
and only one baserunner -- the Angels' Garret Anderson in the
second inning -- got as far as second base.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fifth, Adam Kennedy rolled a single through the hole
at short for a two-out single. Erstad then got the count in his
favor at 3-1 before hitting his 14th homer of the season to give
the Angels a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Washburn continued to pitch almost flawlessly. The
only hits he allowed through eight innings were a line-drive single
to center by Sweeney in the second inning, and and infield single
by Beltran in the seventh. Beltran's single snapped a streak of 10
in a row retired by Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy keyed the Angels' third run of the game with a one-out
triple in the seventh. With the infield in, Erstad followed with a
chopper that bounced over the outstretched glove of Suzuki to
shortstop Rey Sanchez, allowing Kennedy to race home for a 3-0
Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn was allowed to go out for the ninth inning, unlike last
week when Scioscia took Brian Cooper out despite eight shutout
innings and a 2-0 lead. In that one, Percival gave up three runs in
the ninth, including a game-ending two-run homer by Fred McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   But Washburn had made only 87 pitches through eight innings, and
Scioscia said he felt comfortable sticking with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a couple of things,'' Scioscia said. ``One thing about
Cooper was in his eighth inning I didn't think his stuff was as
crisp. And I liked the matchups today with (left-handed hitting
Johnny) Damon coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had made only 80-some pitches, I would have been surprised
if I was taken out,'' Washburn said. ``But I wouldn't be
disappointed because that's Percy's job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had a lump in his throat watching Dye's fly ball,
Washburn said: ``I don't know if it was a lump in my throat, but I
was pretty nervous. My heart jumped up. (Erstad) made a great
play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
