<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOSSEN MAY JOIN DE LA HOYA'S TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Not only is Oscar De La Hoya not retiring, he
apparently is looking for fresh help in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   A rematch of Saturday's Shane Mosley-Oscar De La Hoya fight will
take place in November or February, probably in Las Vegas, promoter
Bob Arum told the Las Vegas Review-Journal.
</P>
<P>
   And Joe Goossen, the Van Nuys-based trainer, could work with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen said he was approached by someone associated with De La
Hoya about the possibility of taking over his training, although
Goossen declined to say who it was.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has been trained by the much-maligned Robert Alcazar
for most of his career, although several other trainers have come
and gone.
</P>
<P>
   Arum strongly implied that Alcazar is through.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was back, in all probability, the outcome would be the
same,'' Arum told the Review-Journal. ``You saw one guy (Mosley)
adjust midway through the fight, and you saw the other guy doing
the same thing round after round after round.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, who has guided several fighters to world championships,
would love the opportunity to step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had won three straight fights, I wouldn't be saying
this,'' Goossen said. ``We're talking about a guy who has lost two
of his last three. It's obvious that when you're as gifted as he
is, something is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I would just say that it's time for Oscar to get some
leadership. He needs someone who can actually lead him into a
fight, someone with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, known as much as anything for his ability to motivate
his fighters and give sound advice in the corner, has worked with
such champions as Gabriel and Rafael Ruelas, Michael Nunn and
current champ Joel Casamayor.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's one fight with Wilfredo Rivera that best applies
here.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen was in Rivera's corner when he gave Mosley all he could
handle in the new champ's first bout at 147 pounds in September.
Mosley won by a 10th-round knockout, but he had a more difficult
time with Rivera than he did with De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen said the almost-recklessly aggressive De La Hoya simply
fought the wrong fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what brought him to the dance,'' Goossen said.
``What it boils down to is this: Why is he trying to be a slugger?
Oscar's one of the best boxers ever to lace 'em up. No one ever
said he's one of the greatest (begin ital)sluggers(end ital) or
brawlers ever to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what he tried to do. When I saw it, I said to myself,
'Man, I wish I had an opportunity to train this kid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya spoke of retirement the night Mosley beat him by a
split decision but Arum said he now wants a chance to avenge the
disappointing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch clause in the original contract guarantees each
fighter $10.1 million for the rematch, Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fighters have yet to come to terms on a second
bout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
