<HEADER>
A1382 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-22 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD CARRIES DODGERS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON - In spring training, Dodgers left fielder Gary
Sheffield talked about hitting 50 homers in a season, and it raised
a few eyebrows and caused a few eyes to roll.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sheffield's one of the leading candidates in the early
stages of the MVP race, and he's knocking baseballs all over the
place. He hit two solo homers, tied a career-high with four runs
scored and had four hits as the Dodgers rallied to beat Houston 7-6
Wednesday at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what about Sheff? Is he just picking us up and carrying
us on his shoulders?'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He's
beyond amazing to me. It's big hit after big hit. You almost expect
it every time up. It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's homer in the eighth broke a 6-6 tie, and after
bouncing off the light standard above the left-field roof, laid to
rest in the street.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sheffield's team-leading 23rd homer. He's hitting .361
with 63 RBI, and is in the midst of an unreal stretch. Sheffield's
hit in 11 straight games, during which he's batting .548 (23 for
42) with six homers, four doubles, 16 RBI and 14 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just relaxed and healthy, and when I'm like that I don't
worry about my performance,'' Sheffield said. ``I knew (the second
homer) hit something, but I don't know what it hit. There's a lot
of things going on in this park, a lot of bars and walls and fences
and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's helped bring focus to a hectic time. Suspensions are
pending after a tiring day in which 14 of the roster players
attended an appeals hearing. The Dodgers also have dealt with
injuries to key starters through the first 11 weeks of the season,
but they have been able to hold things together.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that they entered the day two games behind Arizona in
the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Eric Karros) and (Shawn) Green and the middle guys on
this team that are supposed to do something, we talked about when
things are not going well, that builds character,'' Sheffield said.
``We have to look at ourselves as individuals and find out what we
can do and reach back to help this team. Sometimes we don't have
that enthusiasm that we're trying to win this whole thing, and it
takes that one guy to take the lead and everybody else to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, along with Karros - his two-run homer in the seventh
tied it 6-6 - gave the Dodgers the win, but the bullpen did a
masterful job in cleaning up a messy Carlos Perez start to put them
in that position.
</P>
<P>
   Perez lasted just 3 innings, allowing six runs on seven hits,
and again bringing to mind the June 25 deadline in which the
Dodgers can send him to the minors. Certainly, that will be
discussed in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   However, Antonio Osuna pitched 2 innings of perfect relief and
the surprising Matt Herges (5-0) won for the second straight night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think not much is expected, so maybe that helps me
sneak up on people,'' Herges said. ``I know the league doesn't help
me, so that helps.''
</P>
<P>
   But this win for Herges was a little tougher than the night
before, in which he bailed Jeff Shaw out of a two-on, none-out
situation in the bottom of the ninth to force extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Herges threw three scoreless innings of relief. And
with Shaw again stripped of his exclusive closer's tag, Herges
pitched a perfect ninth to close out the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Herges is that one guy that I don't think anyone was
counting on to play that significant of a role up to this point,''
Karros said. ``He's been unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
