<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-FORK-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING WEIGHS SCRAPPING MERGER PLANS OR SELLING KEY ASSETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sprint Corp. may face the choice of selling
all the company's Internet and long-distance assets, or calling off
its proposed merger with WorldCom Inc., people close to the
companies said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Once an unthinkable alternative for the Westwood-based company,
which employs nearly 20,000 people in the metropolitan area,
dismantling the company and selling it in parts may be required to
overcome antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The long-troubled $129 billion merger, announced last October,
would join the second- and third-largest long-distance companies in
the country, and two of the top four Internet providers in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies would not discuss the matter on Wednesday. Any
decision to go forward with such a sale would probably require the
approval of both companies' boards of directors. Sprint's board
members declined to comment or could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at the U.S. Justice Department have recommended that the
deal be blocked because it would concentrate almost 80 percent of
the U.S. long-distance industry under the newly merged company and
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of significant concessions from the companies _
beyond their stated willingness to sell Sprint's Internet business
_ senior Justice officials are reportedly inclined to oppose the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulators are not in a fixing mode,'' said Scott Cleland, an
analyst with Legg Mason Precursor in Washington. ``They didn't like
the merger. They want WorldCom and Sprint as competitors, not
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   On a second front, the European Commission reportedly is also
preparing to block the merger because the combined company would
control too much Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, European Competition Commissioner Mario Monti
began a six-day visit to Washington, where he is reportedly
scheduled to meet with Justice Department antitrust chief Joel
Klein, Attorney General Janet Reno, members of the Senate's
antitrust subcommittee, and William Kennard, chairman of the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got to fight the war on two fronts, most reasonable
people would say it's not worth going forward,'' said Andy
Copenhaver, an antitrust attorney with Womble Carlyle in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Sprint's entire long-distance division, including
the Internet backbone, may assuage European and U.S. regulators,
allowing them to claim an outright victory in a politically
sensitive fight to preserve competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and WorldCom executives have dismissed suggestions that
concentration in the long-distance industry is an antitrust
problem. They see a highly competitive market now and think
competition will increase as the regional Bell companies get
regulatory permission to enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clash is that the companies can't realize that the
government has a different purpose than they do,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint and WorldCom are looking out and seeing a fiercely
competitive future. They don't like that future and want to
consolidate to preserve their margins. The government likes what it
sees: fierce competition that lowers prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up Sprint might also give WorldCom Chief Executive
Bernie Ebbers what he was after all along _ Sprint's fast-growing
wireless unit, Sprint PCS _ without the burden of integrating the
company's long-distance networks. The companies expected to save
$15 billion combining their respective networks and customer bases.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is to sell off Sprint in parts, a decision
already supported by WorldCom executives, according to a report in
the Financial Times on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of some 11th-hour alternative, Sprint's board
essentially faces two choices: Dismantle the company, possibly
renegotiating the $76 per share offer from WorldCom to reflect the
sale of long-distance assets; or scrap the deal, effectively
putting the company back on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, a long line of potential buyers would be interested
in Sprint's Internet and long-distance businesses. And with a
limited supply of such networks, they could be worth significantly
more than the roughly $30 billion that investment bankers
calculated when valuing them during the initial merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   But selling the long-distance division to a third party would be
far from an easy financial decision for Sprint's board.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes could eat a significant chunk of any price that the board
would be able to realize for the long-distance and Internet
businesses. It's also unclear how the sale of the long-distance
business would be structured, as a simultaneous three-way
transaction, or Sprint selling the division and turning the
proceeds over to WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Such a sale also could have implications for Sprint's new $1
billion office campus in Overland Park, and it could throw the
lives of 6,500 area long-distance employees into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's board faces pressure to make the deal work.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the time and money already invested in regulatory
process, the company potentially faces a $2.5 billion breakup fee
if it pulls out of the deal with WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   The board could also face a raft of shareholder lawsuits
stemming from the accelerated vesting of employee stock options,
which took effect with the shareholder vote in favor of the merger
and gave employees a benefit it might otherwise have taken years to
accrue. Similar situations have prompted shareholder suits in
previous failed mergers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sprint Chief Executive Officer William T.
Esrey may be able to realize a higher price for the entire company
with a third party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really opens up a can of worms,'' said David Neil, an
analyst with the Gartner Group in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint needs both an international and domestic partner: an
international one to serve lucrative multinational business
customers, and a domestic one to bypass the regional Bell
companies' stranglehold on local lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
