<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FORTUNATE TO GET A TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- It was hard to tell which was worse.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos' flop in the penalty area
in the final moments of Wednesday's match with Chicago. Or, referee
Tom Babadilla, who was actually sold by Cienfuegos' fall, awarding
the Galaxy a penalty kick in the 89th minute of a game the Fire
deserved to win for out-hustling and out-playing Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Greg Vanney converted the penalty kick, enabling
the Galaxy to sneak away with a 1-1 draw after two five minute
sudden death overtime periods in front of 10,271 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The play started when Galaxy striker Luis Hernandez chipped a
pass for Cienfuegos. The little El Salvadoran tried to run past
Jesse Marsch, but Marsch's body and arm rubbed up against
Cienfuegos. Marsch actually tugged lightly on Cienfuegos' jersey,
but Cienfuegos fell down hard, drawing the game-tying call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a tough call at that point in the game,'' said
Chicago coach Bob Bradley. ``It's very frustrating because we feel
like we did play well tonight. What can you do? We're disappointed
we did not get the three points, but we're satisfied with the
effort we gave.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another night in which Galaxy striker Luis Hernandez
failed to score in his sixth straight MLS game since leaving
Mexico. Hernandez waved his hands like a politician, trying to draw
the attention of his teammates, but the Fire did a good job marking
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of players frustrated their not getting the ball
when they're asking for the ball,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid.
``That's something that we have to do better. But give them credit,
they did a good job on him (Hernandez) tonight. C.J. Brown marked
him and didn't give him a lot of space.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley offered his assessment of Hernandez. Earlier in the
week, Hernandez said the quantity and quality of passes he gets
with the Galaxy is not what he's used to getting in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quick and alert but it's always difficult when a player
comes to a team halfway through a season,'' said Bradley. ``I would
also say that the MLS is more difficult than people think. MLS
doesn't get that much respect in Mexico. I don't know why, we all
understand our league needs to grow, but if you look at the foreign
players in this league, a lot of them in an honest moment will tell
you this league is a lot better than anybody gives it credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chicago (9-7-2, 29 points), Josh Wolff hammered home their
lone goal in the 75th minute after a combination of passes from
Diego Gutierrez and Ante Razov. With the draw, the Galaxy (7-3-7,
29 points) managed to stay within striking distance of Kansas City
(10-2-4, 34 points).
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy visits the Wizards Saturday at Arrowhead Stadium, the
first of a three-game road trip. Schmid hopes to see more grit from
his bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coach told me once that a team that commits the most fouls
usually wins the game,'' said Schmid. Kansas City committed 21
fouls to the Galaxy's 11. ``Obviously we didn't committ very many
fouls because fouls represent a level of aggression. We need some
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to strike early, Hernandez dropped a pass back for Paul
Caligiuri in the 11th minute. Caligiuri sent a one-touch cross into
the middle of the penalty area. Peter Vagenas leaped, sending a
header straight at Chicago goalkeeper Zach Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   On a similar play, Chicago midfielder Peter Nowak curled a free
kick in the box, where Wolff snapped a sharp header to the right
side, but Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman dove to his left to make
the save.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking near the back of the net, Vagenas tried to finish a Greg
Vanney corner kick in the 38th minute. He picked the ball out of
the air, sending a left-footed shot off the side netting.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the half, Hernandez flopped to the ground,
trying to draw a penalty kick as Fire defender Carlos Bocanegra
cleared a pass away from Hernandez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
