<HEADLINE>
CONSIDERING SHADEGG'S FI
 NAL SOLU TION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic (Phoenix) - President Bill Clinton is
scheduled to arrive today at Sky Harbor International Airport,
where spectators will gather in hopes of getting a glimpse at the
big black swastikas painted on Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a military color guard will salute the president with
stiffly held right arms, raised at an angle, and all through the
crowd there will be chants of, ``Seig heil! Seig heil! Seig heil!''
as Clinton disembarks.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, that doesn't hap pen. In which case
Congressman John Shadegg may want to rethink his recent remarks
comparing Clin ton to Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler was responsible for systemati cally annihilating 6
million Jews and others during World War II. Clinton is responsible
for deciding to system atically protect . . . some trees.
</P>
<P>
   Same thing, according to Shadegg, who represents Arizona's
District 4.
</P>
<P>
   He said of Clinton's recent decision to create Ironwood Forest
National Monument outside Tucson, ``I would draw a parallel to
Hitler. He eroded the will of the German people to resist evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman's comments were `'taken out of context,'' his
spokes man, John Pappas, told me Wednes day.
</P>
<P>
   Really? I asked.
</P>
<P>
   In exactly which context would it be OK to compare Clinton to
Hitler?
</P>
<P>
   `'Regrettably,'' he said, ``that refer ence was used.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more regrettably, Shadegg and his people didn't leave it
with a simple apology. Instead, they tried to explain it away, and
even went on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evil isn't the creation of a national monument,'' Pappas
said. ``But the evil is the flagrant disre gard of the law by this
administra tion, over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said his boss believes it was illegal for Clinton to
establish the monument, since it includes land not under the
control of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the pattern of not following the law of this
administra tion,'' Pappas said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's enough to make Clinton a Hitler?
</P>
<P>
   It was a too much for a press aide to answer. After Pappas got
off the phone, Shadegg himself called.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president stepped outside the law (in creating the
monument),'' Shadegg said, ``I don't regret having pointed out this
is a violation of the law. Do I regret having publicly articulated
the Hitler parallel? Yeah. Because that's been construed that I
think the monument is evil, and I don't think that.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you think Clinton is evil, he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government acting outside the law is evil,'' he said,
``and I see a pattern of it in this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg is an ambitious man. When John McCain steps down,
Shadegg hopes to stand before the assembled voters of Arizona and
say, ````Ich bin ein U.S. senator.''''``
</P>
<P>
   In order for that to happen, however, he'll have to beat the
always-on-TV Rep. J.D. Hayworth. For that, he needs publicity.
Attacking Clinton gets it. Shadegg has done so once before,
refusing to attend the Clin ton's State of the Union address. He
did it again with the Hitler remark.
</P>
<P>
   Both times, he was way off base. But I guess when you're trying
to estab lish your very own political dynasty, you figure any
publicity is good publicity. Apparently, no one ever told the
congressman that two wrongs don't make a Reich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
