<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCH CO-FOUNDER TO RETIRE IN SEPTEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block co-founder Henry W. Bloch, 77,
plans to retire as chairman after the firm's annual meeting in
September, the company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The change will leave Block without a Bloch family member at the
helm for the first time since brothers Henry, Richard and Leon
Bloch founded a company in 1946 that ultimately became H&AMP;R Block.
</P>
<P>
   The diversified tax and financial services company also said it
earned $251.9 million, or $2.55 a share during the fiscal year that
ended April 30. The results were up more than 10 percent from a
year-earlier $215.4 million, or $2.14 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Those earnings landed at the upper end of a range that Block
executives had estimated earlier this month. At that time, Block
warned Wall Street analysts that the company would not achieve even
higher profits because of last-minute overstaffing in its tax
offices and e-commerce operations losses.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Bloch's retirement, the company outlined further
changes in senior management and on its board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   - Frank L. Salizzoni, 61, the chief executive officer, will
become chairman, succeeding Bloch in September. He will then retire
as chief executive officer Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   - Mark Ernst, 41, president and chief operating officer, will
become president and chief executive, succeeding Salizonni. A
successor to Ernst as chief operating officer was not named.
</P>
<P>
   These management changes are part of a succession plan that
Salizzoni began working on soon after agreeing to become interim
chief executive in 1996, said Linda McDougall, company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   - Henry W.Bloch will resign from the board and become honorary
chairman. He and his brother Richard founded H&AMP;R Block in 1955 as a
successor to United Business Co.
</P>
<P>
   - Kansas City publisher Morton Sosland, 75, also announced he
was retiring from Block's board. He has served on the board for 37
years.
</P>
<P>
   - Block directors nominated Thomas M. Bloch, 46, and Rayford
Wilkins Jr. 48, president of SBC Communications Services, to
succeed Henry W. Bloch and Sosland as directors if shareholders
approve at the Sept. 13 annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bloch, whose father is Henry W.Bloch, worked for H&AMP;R
Block 19 years, including three as president and chief executive.
He left the company in 1995 to become a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Block once again reported increased earnings and revenues as it
has virtually every year since it became publicly traded. But the
results were more complex than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 49.1 percent, to $2.5 billion from a year-earlier
$1.6 billion. The improvement stemmed from increased volume at
Block's tax office and a diversification drive in which Block
acquired RSM McGladrey, a major regional business service and
accounting firm, and Olde Financial Corp., a nationwide discount
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Block's tax service operations reported a nearly 2 percent
increase in pretax profits to $320 million, on a 13.7 percent
increase in revenues. Block preparers handled a record 14 percent
of all the returns IRS received last season for a market share
record. The company also retained more repeat customers than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings, however, didn't reach expectations because of
larger-than-expected losses in its e-commerce operations. The
company also suffered from overstaffing of tax offices for a
last-minute surge of filing that didn't occur, Salizzoni said.
</P>
<P>
   Block's other primary businesses turned in strong perfomances,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services operations, which include mortgage lending at
Option One Mortgage Corp. and, since Dec. 1, Olde Financial,
reported a 112.3 percent increase in pretax earnings to $129.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Business services, which since Aug. 1 include RSM McGladrey and
other accounting and financial services firms Block acquired,
contributed $17.1 million in pretax profits, a 140.3 percent
increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
