A1402 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 MARINERS ROLL 7, HOLD ON TO BEAT DEVIL RAYS   (For use by New York
Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Given that the Mariners scored seven runs in the
second inning, winning this one probably should not have been as
difficult as it was.
</P>
<P>
   In the final accounting, however, Seattle beat Tampa Bay 8-5
Wednesday night, using some of that old Safeco Field alchemy to
transmute one big inning early, against nemesis Esteban Yan, and
lots of good relief pitching late, against one of the hottest teams
in baseball, into the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele started and collected his eighth win, but this was
clearly not Sele's finest outing. He walked four, matching his
season high. And after being gifted with a 7-0 lead, he had to be
taken out of the game in the sixth inning with the potential tying
run coming to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have all that offense to work with,'' Sele said.
``I didn't have my control tonight again, just like last time in
Minnesota. I've got to get back to a good rhythm, where I'm not
walking people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the kind of pitcher who can get by walking a lot of
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many pitchers who can. And one of the major
successes of the first 11 weeks of the season has been the
bullpen's ability to throw strikes and avoid the walks that
inevitably lead to big innings.
</P>
<P>
   Upon Sele's exit, the Mariners dipped liberally into their
ever-improving bullpen. Jose Paniagua, Arthur Rhodes, Jose Mesa and
Kazuhiro Sasaki all contributed heavily to the win, which clinched
Seattle's sixth consecutive series victory, tying the club record.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners haven't lost a series since dropping two of three
to Chicago at Safeco Field May 29-31, one major reason why Seattle
has been able to stay close to Oakland in the West with the A's
having won 17 of 20, including a three-game sweep of Baltimore, the
team that comes to town for four games starting Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think we're playing as good as we can,'' said
shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who had one of two bases-loaded doubles
in the second inning. Rodriguez drove in two runs and John Olerud
followed with a three-run double as Yan succumbed to control
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yan got all of three outs. He walked five, hit a batter and saw
the first eight batters of the second inning reach base. The first
seven scored, and that would prove to be enough to win, although
Sele's tough night made the game closer than the Mariners would
have liked.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bullpen has been dominant enough that, unlike in past
years, there is no fear when the call goes to the pen.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, whose work has been nearly flawless of late, took over
in a tough spot _ men on second and third with none out in the
sixth. Paniagua got three quick outs, although one run scored on a
medium-deep fly ball. That would be the end of the line for the
Tampa Bay offense.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua and Rhodes got the Mariners through the seventh, Rhodes
striking out pinch-hitter Bubba Trammell on three pitches as the
potential tying run. After the Mariners added a run on Rickey
Henderson's single in the seventh, Rhodes and Mesa combined to
pitch a 1-2-3 eighth inning, and Sasaki closed it out with a
scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The four shutout innings for the bullpen followed Tuesday's
effort, when Rhodes and Sasaki provided two shutout innings in a
4-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about matchups,'' Rhodes said. ``Lou (Piniella) has
the option to go to put guys in good situations, and tonight we all
pitched great.''
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Sele needed the help. After a streak in which he
went 5-0 in six starts, Sele has hit a bump in the road. He gave up
five runs in five-plus innings. In his past two starts he's walked
eight, after walking just 12 in the previous six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Porous defense behind him caused some of Sele's problems, but he
brought much of his grief upon himself. He walked the leadoff
batter twice. Both times that lapse resulted in a run.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Sele stuck around long enough to get the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had a score to settle with Yan. It was Yan, back on
May 20 at Safeco who, the Mariners felt, threw at Mark McLemore.
The second baseman was slapped with a five-day suspension for
having charged the mound, while Yan wasn't disciplined at all.
</P>
<P>
   Now Yan was pitching and McLemore was out of uniform, serving
the second of a four-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Mariners would admit to any vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to get a win,'' Rodriguez said. ``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   They got that. And a little vengeance on the side, running Yan
out of the game in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's seven-run explosion was full of everything a team
wants at the plate _ except hits. Seattle had only two hits in the
inning, but both were bases-loaded doubles by Rodriguez and Olerud
that accounted for five of the seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   Bases-loaded offense has been a weak point for the Mariners this
year, but they came through once Tuesday with the sacks full, then
twice more Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of the season, it's going to balance out,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at
</P>
<P>
   206-448-8004 or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
