<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARTINEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' DAVE MARTINEZ FINALLY HAS IMPACT IN WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ With the possible exception of starting
pitcher Esteban Loaiza, who won for the first time since May 25,
it's doubtful if anyone was happier with the Rangers' 7-5 victory
against the Minnesota Twins last night than Dave Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The right fielder had the biggest hit in the game, a double that
drove in Rafael Palmeiro and David Segui to break a 3-3 tie in the
fifth inning. The ball was hit at Cristian Guzman, but was smacked
so sharply that it glanced off the Twins' shortstop and rolled into
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was thrown out trying to stretch the hit into a triple,
but that scarcely mattered. What was important was that it was the
first time Martinez contributed to a victory since the club traded
for him June 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come to a new team, you want everything to go well,''
Martinez said. ``You hope you're not the bad luck charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez knew better than that. Even though the Rangers lost the
first six games after he joined the club, and even though he took
an 0-for-18 slump into yesterday's game, the veteran outfielder
knew things would change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of time,'' he said. ``I've been in this
game 141/2 years, and I've always hit. The same thing with this
club. They've won the division three of the last four years, and
they knew they were going to come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Martinez did hit in his first couple of games with the
team, but it didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   When general manager Doug Melvin swung the three-team deal with
the Florida Marlins and Chicago Cubs to land Martinez, the
outfielder with the .274 career average wasn't presented as the
final piece of the puzzle, but was expected to be a significant
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as he joined the club, victories became nonexistent.
He reached base in seven of his first 11 plate appearances in a
Texas uniform, but the club dropped all three games.
</P>
<P>
   As the losses continued to mount, Martinez began to reflect the
team. He stopped hitting.
</P>
<P>
   The club finally won on Saturday, the first victory in
Martinez's seven games with the club, but he couldn't even enjoy
that one much. He went 0-for-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won again on Tuesday, but Martinez didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   When he struck out and grounded out in his first two at-bats
last night, his hitless streak reached 20 trips to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   He was afraid the streak was about to reach 21 when the ball
headed toward Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I hit it pretty hard, but I thought it was going to be
a right-at-him ball,'' Martinez said. ``When I saw it hit his shoe,
I was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels real good. But the bottom line is that it feels good
to win two in a row.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
