<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN25-COX     06-22 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Good manners prevail in Texas prayer ruling
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Called on to referee between two powerful religions, the U.S.
Supreme Court wisely chose to shield high school football in Texas
from gratuitous Christian praying.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, that's not exactly how the six-justice majority put
it.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority, Justice John Paul Stevens said, ``The
religious liberty protected by the Constitution is abridged when
the state affirmatively sponsors the particular practice of
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this case, involving the small Santa Fe school district,
Stevens could have gone further and written ``aggressively''
instead of just ``affirmatively.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to sly claims that its pre-game prayers were private
student utterances, district officials supervised a school election
to choose the student prayer leader, provided the PA system, laid
on faculty oversight and, in effect, assembled the audience. A
practice that so explicitly encourages public prayer cannot, as the
court found, be ``properly characterized as 'private' speech.''
</P>
<P>
   The result _ and it is impossible not to suspect that for some
the intent as well _ was to intimidate any present who believed
differently or not at all or who simply preferred their
Christianity in rather different form.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is such an outcome idle, worst-case speculation. The courts
found the religious atmosphere of the community so potentially
dangerous they allowed a Mormon family and a Catholic family to
file their legal dissent anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   The necessity for that protection is itself a powerful argument
for keeping governments out of the proper realms of faith, but
Chief Justice William Rehnquist, on behalf of the court's
hard-right minority, accused the essentially conservative majority
of issuing a ruling that ``bristles with hostility to all things
religious in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the ruling only extends _ logically and not at all
surprisingly _ the established security of the village common from
sectarian warfare and the wanton exercise of religious
marjoritarian muscle. That was the clear purpose and is, by now,
the traditional understanding of church-state separation.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff has been, in addition to the not inconsiderable boon
of civil peace, a prosperity of religious conviction and practice
in this country that is unequaled by any comparably situated
nation.
</P>
<P>
   You know, constitutional matters aside, there is another,
humbler but vital concern at play here, too: plain good manners.
</P>
<P>
   While most religions welcome converts and many seek them
actively, this impulse to push prayer into public venues is almost
exclusive to conservative, evangelical Christians and if that suits
the purpose of affirmation, it is also proselytizing, and is meant
to be.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is to either force other faiths to jump into an
evangelical battle that is unnatural to them and start fighting for
the microphone or to suffer the unwelcome proselyzation
(proselytizing) dumbly. Simple good manners would not put friends
or neighbors into that kind of bind.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
