<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1484 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KOREA-SIDE-$ADV25-COX     06-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-SIDE-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. 'INTERFERENCE' STOKING ANTI-AMERICAN SENTIMENT AMONG SOUTH
KOREANS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOREA-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV25.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ When Christopher McCarthy, a 22-year-old American
soldier, escaped from U.S. military custody after he was accused of
murdering a South Korean bar hostess for refusing sex with him, it
fed the belief among South Koreans that Americans believe they're
above the law.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was apprehended eight hours later and was sentenced by
a South Korean court this month to eight years in prison. However,
that incident was the latest in a series of events, including the
surprisingly successful summit between North and South Korea, that
has stoked calls for less interference from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a very strong anti-American sentiment
right now, but I think it's growing,'' said Jung-Hoon Lee,
professor of international relations at Yonsei University in Seoul.
``The summit contributed to it because of its focus on independence
and autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reunification of the two Koreas is seen by some South Koreans as
an issue that can be resolved by Koreans only.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Kim Jong Il's new look ... (showing) he can be friendly,
smile, be jovial, a very confident leader, (some people) feel, we
can do some business with this guy and Americans only serve as a
possible roadblock,'' said Lee. ``So that sort of feeds on
anti-American sentiment that was already there. There's a sense
that we should do this alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have always been factions in Korea _ especially
among the left-wing and the younger generations - who believe U.S.
troops should go home.
</P>
<P>
   Massive student demonstrations in the 1970s and '80s are
characterized as anti-American but were more directed at the
military dictators who ruled South Korea, said Lee. But because of
the military alliance between the two countries, the United States
was seen as tolerating or approving of the dictatorships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many students still feel Korea is being used by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States thinks of Korea as their colony,'' said Soo
Jin Park, a 25-year-old student at Yonsei University. ``Not on
paper, but by the way they act, Koreans get that impression.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the 37,000 American troops in Korea should leave
``because we're not at war and I see no reason for them to stay in
Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   While such sentiments are common on university campuses,
analysts agree they do not represent the mainstream view in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a growing belief _ even among people who would
identify themselves as pro-American and have no desire to see
American troops withdraw _ that Washington needs to treat Korea as
more of an equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some sense, I must say Korea is controlled by the United
States in many ways,'' said Rev. Young Joon Cho, pastor of Chung
Dong First Methodist Church in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Pagoda Park in downtown Seoul is filled with elderly men playing
chess, practicing calligraphy or just passing the time. In one
corner, a retired sociology teacher who would give his name only as
Mr. Kim is holding court with an audience of at least a couple
dozen, lecturing on U.S.-Korean relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States shouldn't look down at Korea,'' he said.
``We're not the Korea of 50 years ago. They should respect Korea as
a full sovereign country and let us solve our own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Foreign Ministry believes it is ready for an adjustment
in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, our relationship has been one of dependence on
U.S. aid,'' said Sung-Hwan Kim, deputy director of the Ministry's
North American bureau. ``Now I feel we're equipped with the
requirements (for a more equal partnership).''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. recognizes that the relationship is an evolving one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea has changed from the poorest country in the world in the
fifties and sixties to one of the richest,'' said a U.S. official
based in Korea who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``There's a
constant need to re-evaluate the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the displeasure towards Americans stems from the Status
of Forces Agreement, which in part governs how U.S. soldiers who
commit crimes or wrongdoings in Korea are handled. From little
things, like not paying traffic tickets, to violent crimes, such as
murder, Koreans feel Americans get away with too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (American soldiers) are outside of their campus, they are
not restricted by Korean law, and that's not right,'' said Byung
Chan Son, who owns a small energy consulting firm in Seoul.
``Korean people are very unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the agreement is currently being renegotiated, as it
periodically is. Kim of the Foreign Ministry said Korea has
proposed several changes, such as requiring indicted American
soldiers to remain in Korean custody instead of American military
custody and requiring American military facilities _ where air and
ground pollution are not subject to regulations _ to adhere to
basic environmental guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the United States must make an effort to ... give the
Korean public at least an appearance that it respects Korea, treats
Korea as an equal partner and that there's a balance in the
bilateral relations,'' said Lee.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on commemoration activities, see:
</P>
<P>
   U.S military Korea page:
</P>
<P>
   www.korea.army.mil/50anniv/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Korean War Commemoration Committee:
</P>
<P>
   www.koreanwar.go.kr/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
