<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN25-CO     06-22 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Here's to you, my naked Mrs. Robinson
 &HT;    For release June 25, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confession No.1: I'd never heard of Jerry Hall until a week or
so ago.
</P>
<P>
   Confession No. 2: My knowledge of today's obstreperous rock
music world is extremely limited.
</P>
<P>
   (Parenthetical Confession No. 3: My music appreciation lapsed
with the deaths of George Gershwin and Cole Porter, and is only
occasionally revived through something done by Andrew Lloyd
Webber.)
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Hall's fame, I have read, is that she is the ex-wife of
rocker Mick Jagger and is a model. I assume that although it was
not mentioned, Ms. Hall also is an actress; why else would she have
been chosen to replace Kathleen Turner beginning July 31 in the
London production of ``The Graduate''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe because she's agreed to do a nude scene. You don't
have to be much of an actress to stand on stage in your
all-together, just uninhibited.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Ms. Turner last month in the London play at the Gielgud
Theater. I didn't think she was so hot _ either as an actress or as
a nude.
</P>
<P>
   When the great actor Sir John Gielgud died several weeks ago, I
attributed it, in addition to his advanced age, to the fact that
this fatuous scene was being put on in the West End theater named
in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Graduate,'' an acclaimed 1967 film with no nude scene has
been resurrected as a fast-paced stage comedy _ with nudity. It has
been playing to sellout audiences since it opened in April,
principally because the 45-year-old Turner spends 20 seconds
catching the London evening chill on stage -- in the shadows, I
might add.
</P>
<P>
   This is a shame because, to me, the play would have been an
artistic success without the nude scene, and without Turner as the
carnal Mrs. Robinson. Nevertheless, the nudity has been selling the
tickets, getting the headlines and will be continued by the
43-year-old Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The scene could be done in a full slip and be just as funny.
Yes, it's a funny scene, thanks to the antics of the young,
mortified-by-middle-aged-nudity male lead Matthew Rhys. But that
apparently is not what sells tickets.
</P>
<P>
   What is marketable is what is acceptable these days. If the
public fills the house because there's a nude scene and only
two-thirds fill it without one, the nude scene prevails.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite similar to how other domains are being marketed. A
Time Magazine writer, James Poniewozik, recently reported his
earlier firing by an online publication was because of something
called ``page views.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Poniewozik, the tenure of writers and the judgment
of material is based on how many ``hits'' or ``page views''
articles receive on the Web. If an online publication posts, say,
five stories -- ranging from 10 Ways to Please Your Spouse in Bed
to How to Improve Your Child's Reading Skills and there is a
predominance of ``hits'' on the sex story, then future stories will
deal more with that area, and writers will be judged (and employed)
based on what kind of stories they bring in. (''Another education
piece, Faversham, and you're fired!'')
</P>
<P>
   How much stronger would be sales for ``The Taming of the Shrew''
might we had been able to see Petruchio peel Katharina on the night
of her ultimate submission?
</P>
<P>
   I wonder had Hall held out to do her scene with some manner of
attire whether the producers would have accepted her, and whether
ticket sales would have dropped. We're not going to know, at least
not until the initial reviews of her ``appearance'' hit the London
tabloids at the first of August.
</P>
<P>
   Likely, it will be similar to that of Turner in April, when a
London tabloid began: ``Kathleen Turner, the Hollywood film star
who started off in Body Heat and has never lost the art of sexual
provocation, made an absolutely sensational London stage debut last
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, it referred to her wafting around the stage clad in
little more than sex appeal. In the film ``The Graduate,'' Anne
Bancroft was cited for her acting ability. (And Mike Nichols got an
Oscar for direction.) That's the difference between then and now. I
expect Jerry Hall to emulate Turner rather than Bancroft. That's
probably why the house will continue to be sold out.
</P>
<P>
   And so you should ask, why did I buy tickets to see Kathleen
Turner? Good question. Hypocritical prurient interest, I guess,
just like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
