<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1506 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV25-C     06-22 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: IS IT DUMB TO SHUN SMART CARDS?
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Folks stare when I enter or leave Washington's
Metro system without breaking stride. The gates swing open because
I carry a broadcast-type smart card with an antenna and a memory
bank that debits the fare.
</P>
<P>
   Recent advances in miniature radio technology make it possible
for people to have similar smart cards that embed their medical and
insurance history on a chip. The medical card could then be
``read'' when you visited your doctor's office or a hospital
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   You could carry other ``proximity cards'' programmed to open
office doors, feed parking meters, pay expressway tolls or grocery
bills, trigger calls at pay phones, check out library books, or
enable automatic teller machines worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, if this comes to pass, you might get the feeling
that you were packing too many smart cards. A technically feasible
solution would be to acquire just one super-smart card chock full
of essential and occasional services for both work and play.
</P>
<P>
   But what if such an omnibus device were to be lost or stolen?
Wouldn't such an event lift the chilling prospect of ``identify
theft'' to a fearsome level?
</P>
<P>
   Once again, 21st century technology has answers. Cards can be
programmed to respond to a secure biometric identification system,
like a fingerprint, a unique speech pattern or even the retinas of
your eyes. Any attempt to monkey around with security codes would
cause the cards to self-destruct while sending an alarm.
</P>
<P>
   So, if these new smart cards are all so great, why haven't they
become an integral part of our digital culture?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that even smart technologies often need lots of
incubation time. The Washington Metro card, for example, is still
being used sparingly, although it will also soon be available to
riders on the London Underground and in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   A deeper reason is that a technology that lets you store your
full-blown identity on a microchip smacks of a universal
identification system spawned by an Orwellian Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Some totalitarian states require internal passports. But a
democratic society has yet to successfully implement a national
identity system. The Australian government tried it in 1987, and
the South Koreans tried it a decade later. Both attempts failed
after triggering widescale protests by privacy-minded critics.
</P>
<P>
   That's why universal smart cards, while clearly beneficial,
should always remain as a voluntary contract between the issuing
authority and the individual user. As a practical matter, the most
likely path that such smart cards will take in the new economy is
through successive upgrades of the 1.75 billion credit cards that
have already issued by Visa, MasterCard and American Express.
</P>
<P>
   If government has a role, it is to ensure that the huge body of
individual and collective data that smart cards can generate about
personal aspects of our lives are not abused by predatory
commercial ventures or by the government itself.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
