<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN23-COX     06-22 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death penalty on trial
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When several Black Panthers showed up with assault rifles
outside the Republican convention in Houston last Friday, someone
with a perverse sense of humor could have described it as a
gun-rights demonstration. Or a right-to-life rally.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the gun-toters were there protesting the scheduled
execution of Gary Graham, who now goes by the name of Shaka
Sankofa.
</P>
<P>
   The guys were scary looking, but the Houston cops didn't seem
fazed. They seemed to realize it was a way to get on television.
</P>
<P>
   And it worked. Some news folks otherwise wouldn't have shown up
_ certainly not in helicopters, which hovered like hummingbirds _
and other TV newsfolks shifted their focus from the ho-hum dealings
inside the convention hall to the dramatic video outside.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush's run for the presidency is putting
Texas' death penalty on trial. And the convention to celebrate
Bush's choice to carry the national GOP banner provided a
made-to-order backdrop for the execution protests.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, with Texas Senate President Pro Tem Rodney
Ellis of Houston sitting in the governor's chair because Bush was
out of state campaigning and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry was in Europe,
Bush acquiesced to demands that Ricky McGinn's execution be
postponed for 30 days for new DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case had requested the new test. And even
though the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals and the Board of Pardons
and Paroles turned down the appeal on divided votes, Bush _ who has
maintained that all of the 134 convicts put to death on his watch
were guilty _ said if DNA evidence can prove guilt or innocence of
a person on death row, ``we need to use it.'' Texas is no
namby-pamby, hand-wringing state when it comes to the ultimate
penalty. The state gained worldwide publicity during the nasty
gubernatorial campaign of 1990 between former Gov. Mark White,
then-Attorney General Jim Mattox and then-Treasurer Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   What got the publicity was an ad, produced by Ray Strother, that
had White ominously walking past a series of huge pictures of
convicts who had been executed while he'd been governor. What
precipitated it had been Mattox's talking about attending
executions as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   And these were Democrats _ who are less likely to support the
death penalty. A February 1999 Texas Poll showed 88 percent of
Republicans favor the death penalty, compared with 65 percent of
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gary Graham case, the lone witness on whose
identification Graham's conviction rested broke many years of
silence last week to reiterate that she is positive Graham was the
man who gunned down businessman Bobby Lambert outside a grocery
store.
</P>
<P>
   But those protesting Graham's execution say:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  She was the only one of six witnesses who identified Graham.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Graham's trial attorney, who presented no defense for his
client, failed to call the other five.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Graham's four alibi witnesses were never called.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ballistics tests did not match a gun Graham was carrying
when arrested.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lambert's widow has asked that Graham not be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Whether one agrees with the death penalty or not, Graham's case
underlines yet again larger questions about whether it is fairly
applied in Texas and whether defendants are afforded adequate legal
representation.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is being discussed in Congress from both sides of
the aisle that would expand rights of the accused to DNA testing.
Another bill with sponsors from both parties would increase money
to states to hire defense lawyers for poor defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, perhaps the question to be asked of Gov. Bush is not
whether he is convinced Graham is guilty. Graham may well be.
</P>
<P>
   The question should be, ``If you were accused of a murder, your
defense attorney had failed to bring forth the information listed
above, but you were still being denied a new trial and were going
to die, how would you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin (Texas)
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
