<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS0623-COLUMN     06-22 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS0623-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: EMBARGOED for Sunday.
 &HT;    Before it's over, insects are going to rule
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Lord, the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one good thing about a drought, which doesn't
outweigh the harm it causes in lost crops, dying lawns and trees,
hungry livestock and a general pessimistic attitude among people
used to seeing the clouds open on a regular basis: There are fewer
bugs.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know for sure if the drought is over here behind the
Pine Curtain, but my rain gauge has measured more than six inches
through the first half of this month, and annual rainfall is back
to average for the first time in three years. It's rained so much
that a perfectly healthy oak tree in my backyard toppled over from
the roots and crashed through my neighbor's fence last week, the
victim not of drought but of saturated ground.
</P>
<P>
   My wife does not understand this rain-gauge thing. Men run down
to the Big Discount Store and buy a rain gauge first thing when
they move into a new house. They tack it up on the fence and
religiously slog through the muck to see how much it rained. As if
it matters, she says. But it does matter, though only in the sense
of being a topic of conversation, not something about which one
actually has any control. Still, you stick a menagerie of men in a
room after a rain, and the first topic of conversation will be:
</P>
<P>
   ``I got six-tenths of an inch out at my place last night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really! I only got a tenth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, I got nearly two inches. Nearly lost the dachsund out
there trying to take his evening constitutional. Little fella was
dog-paddlin' for all he was worth.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what we men do: Keep track of Mother Nature's vagaries.
Rain gauges are cheap entertainment, rarely costing more than $3,
about the price of a bodice-ripping video rental, not that I have
anything against bodice ripping.
</P>
<P>
   With the rain and constant warm weather brought about by too
many unmufflered autos burning a hole in the ozone layer, comes the
bugs. (Anybody who doesn't believe in global warming hasn't lived
in the South, where winter has become a season completed at most in
a long weekend. It used to at last at least a week.)
</P>
<P>
   Being the month of the summer solstice, the June bugs, those
pesky Yankee beetles, are in full force, gleefully committing
suicide in such innovative ways as:
</P>
<P>
   Kamakazi-bombing into one's mouth as it cracks open for a gulp
of a favorite libation.
</P>
<P>
   Ingratiating themselves between your eyeball and your glasses
until you make an appointment for lasik surgery just to prevent
such episodes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Or inserting themselves further inside your ear canal further
than deemed safe by the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants are in their heyday. These are the bugs from hell.
Nothing kills them, I believe. I have tried every chemical known to
man, and after years of scientific experimentation have concluded
that:
</P>
<P>
   Chemicals on the market are designed to force fire ants to get
stoned, have a party, trash out their present mound and move five
feet away a few days later. Sort of like college students.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to have even a semblance of control over fireants
is to vary the treatment, using Amdro one week, Dursban the next,
boiling water on the third week, maybe Agent Orange on the fourth,
and my favorite _ setting the lawn mower blade low and scalping the
little demons _ the next. If you're not much into owning a lawn
that looks like the 16th fairway at Pebble Beach, a bit of kerosene
and a match will do wonders for your psyche if not for your
landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   A word to the wise. Don't use gasoline. It's tempting but
dangerous. I speak from experience, having once doused a large
mound in a pasture and then set it on fire using a piece of rope
soaked in lighter fluid. I never realized that dirt would burn, or
leave such a large hole. For a few minutes, I thought I had created
a new eternal torch.
</P>
<P>
   Boiling water is significantly less flammable but a lot more
trouble. Hauling buckets from the stove to the yard is a pain, and
there's that risk factor again if you stumble.
</P>
<P>
   The only effective deterrent against mosquitoes I've found is
cigar smoke. The cheaper the cigar, the better. Forget bug zappers,
which provide great entertainment but only attract the bugs, since
of course they enjoy light. ``Off'' may work but smells bad and
feels yucky. A Prince Edwards cigar, or better yet a Swisher Sweet
will keep mosquitoes and all other living creatures away, including
your wife.
</P>
<P>
   You could always just stay inside, but where' s the fun in that?
Besides, don't forget about the fleas, flies and those water bugs
big as squirrels, all of whom just love air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
