<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-ERNEST-MURRAY-COLUMN0     06-22 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNEST-MURRAY-COLUMN0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once again Texas prisons are bursting at the seams
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ An article in The Wall Street Journal offers some
unsettling news about Texas prisons. The Texas Department of
Criminal Justice is already out of room and there will be at least
3,500 more inmates than beds in state prisons by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gov. Ann Richards, the state jumped headlong into a
prison-building program that cost $1.7 billion. But now, even with
a capacity of 152,000 beds, the prison system is bursting at its
seams. Estimates are that by 2005 the state will be renting space
in county jails for an additional 14,000 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by the Criminal Justice Policy Council,
the state agency that tracks prison populations, the reason behind
the burgeoning inmate population is that the state is allowing
fewer paroles and inmates are serving longer sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The agency says short of building yet more prisons, the state
could at least slow down the growing inmate numbers by reducing
prison time for nonviolent criminals and sending parolees who
violate minor rules to halfway houses instead of prison.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to run a prison system?
</P>
<P>
   Even Gov. George Bush's efforts to keep Death Row cleaned out
can't keep up with what is a tidal wave of offenders flowing into
the prison system.
</P>
<P>
   While building more prisons takes care of the situation for a
few short years, the state and the taxpayers cannot continue to
foot the bill on a problem that goes much deeper than merely
finding enough beds for lawbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have the answers, but it is not so farfetched to
imagine that at some point, the best solution will be to build a
wall around the state and for those of us not yet convicted to get
out.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
