<SLUG> BC-CPT-IBM-MICRODRIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM CREATES 1-GB MINIATURE HARD DRIVE FOR POCKET PCS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plunging deeply into the world of pocket-sized personal
computing, IBM on Tuesday will introduce a version of its tiny
Microdrive hard drive with a storage capacity of 1 billion bytes of
information.
</P>
<P>
   The new drive, which is the size of a book of matches, is a
milestone in the evolution of magnetic storage, IBM executives
said, because it surpasses the same 1-gigabyte barrier the
company's original refrigerator-sized 3380 hard drive surmounted in
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller size and accelerating density of magnetic storage
systems is one of the remarkable stories of Silicon Valley. Disk
storage is now increasing at a rate faster than the legendary
Moore's Law improvement rate of the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's Law is the observation that the number of transistors
that can be squeezed onto a silicon chip doubles roughly every 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   When the first 340-megabyte Microdrive was introduced a year
ago, it had a storage density of 5.04 billion bits per square inch.
The current drive, which will ship commercially in September, has
increased that density to 15.2 billion bits per square inch. The
higher density means the tiny new drive is within 10 percent of the
most advanced IBM storage products now on the market, said John
Osterhout, the marketing director for IBM's storage business.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it expects about one-third of the market
for the new drives to be as storage devices for digital cameras. A
1-GB drive, which fits in the same storage slot as a flash memory
card, could hold up to 1,000 high-resolution photographs, a
thousand 200-page novels, or nearly 10 hours of high-quality
digital audio music, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that another third of the market will be as a
backup and data-transfer medium for notebook and desktop computers.
But in the future the company is most interested in an array of new
markets based on hand-held computing devices, like personal digital
assistants and advanced digital cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of IBM Monday rose $6.375, to $120.125 .
</P>
<P>
   To make its disk drives more attractive for the coming market in
wearable computers, IBM said it had increased the shock resistance
of the newest generation Microdrive, which will sell for $499, to
the ability to withstand a 1500-G shock. That is the equivalent to
a drop from a normal office desk onto a medium thickness carpet,
Osterhout said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM has added tiny rubber bumpers to the corners of its newest
drives to add to their reliability.
</P>
<P>
   One company that has already built a version of a tiny personal
computer based around the Microdrive is Tiqit Computers, a Palo
Alto, Calif., company started by Vaughan Pratt, a Stanford computer
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   The company makes a palm-sized computer that it advertises as
the world's smallest system that can run operating systems such as
Windows 95, Windows NT and Linux. The tiny computer, which
currently has 486-class processor manufactured by Advanced Micro
Devices, is 5 cubic inches and weighs 3.3 ounces. The Tiqit
Matchbox PC is priced at $1,495.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-00 2321EDT &QL;
</P>
