<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-AOL-WEB-TV-ART-NY     06-22 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOL-WEB-TV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOLTV COUPLES ONLINE CHAT WITH TV, TARGETS CURRENT AOL USERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT10 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchae one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the features most responsible for America Online's
success has been the buddy list _ the small box on the computer
screen showing a user which friends are logged on and available for
an instant online conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is testing the power of buddyship even more.
Monday it will introduce AOLTV, the centerpiece of the company's
AOL Anywhere strategy to move beyond the personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   AOLTV, like Microsoft's WebTV, is a black box enabling people to
surf the Internet on their television screens. But with only 1
million subscribers after three years, Web TV has been a
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   So AOLTV, in contrast, is being marketed for its use to existing
America Online members who want to keep access to their e-mail,
chat rooms and buddy list while watching television.
</P>
<P>
   Push one button on the AOLTV wireless keyboard, and the same
buddy-list window from the PC-based service will appear in
translucent letters over the television image. One more click can
start a chat with someone, whether they are on AOLTV or on their
computer, or soon, on their AOL-enabled cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Want new friends? Push a different button, and you're in a chat
room with people watching the same show. The TV image, reduced,
remains in a corner of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   America Online says that many people have computers in their
family rooms so they can chat while watching television, and AOLTV
will make this easier.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also gambling that prospective customers are willing
to pay $249 for a set-top box, made by Philips, and connect it to
the cable box and the video recorder, as well as to a phone line.
Subscribers will also have to pay an additional $15 a month if they
are already AOL members or $26 a month if they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit of a stretch that chat and instant messaging will
drive all these people to attach another box to their television
set, said Josh Bernoff, an interactive-television analyst with
Forrester Research. ``Fifteen dollars is a lot of money, plus it
uses another phone line, and the value people are getting is
relatively low.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Schuler, the president of AOL's interactive services, is
unapologetic about the price. ``AOL is a premium product,'' he
said. ``We don't sell AOL on price.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuler said he expects it to catch on with consumers slowly,
selling a few hundred thousand units in the first year. ``If you
look at the history of consumer electronics, it takes 10 years for
a new platform to become established,'' he said. ``If this category
was started with WebTV, we're only two years in.''
</P>
<P>
   And he acknowledges that there are better ways to deliver this
service than by putting another black box on top of the television
set. AOL has already announced a deal to combine AOLTV with the
TiVo video recorder and another to incorporate it into the set-top
box used to decode the DirecTV satellite system.
</P>
<P>
   With America Online buying Time Warner, there are plans for a
version built into that company's cable television boxes. Cable,
but not satellite, offers the advantage of two-way communication,
eliminating the need for another phone line.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, AOL will simply try to sell the existing
Philips box through Time Warner's cable unit.
</P>
<P>
   But Schuler says that even the current configuration will have a
following among families where several children have developed the
habit of chatting online with their friends so much that fights
erupt over access to the computer. For the more affluent of these
households, he reckons, an additional phone line and the AOLTV
service may be a better way to keep the peace than buying another
computer.
</P>
<P>
   With the audience likely to be small for the foreseeable future,
America Online has not sold any advertising yet, but it has built
in lots of potential for commerce. There is a shopping channel.
There is the ability for broadcast networks to add shopping content
to their programs, splitting revenue with America Online. (Click to
buy Oprah's book club selection, for example.) And ads are
sprinkled through an elaborate, searchable on-screen program guide.
America Online figures the biggest buyer will be TV networks trying
to attract viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also created ``channels'' on sports, weather and
news that mix text information, advertising, and a small video
window. It plans to auction off the rights to television networks
to be the featured program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-18-00 2116EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
