<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-SAVVY0620-CO     06-22 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-SAVVY0620-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Send audio e-mail files to friends
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to send a voice message as a .wav file via e-mail. I
have a PowerMac G4. Can you tell me how to record one?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mrs. J. L. Ricketson, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Many people are into sending their voices through the
Internet these days. Simple audio files seem to be an easy way to
pop off a quick message to a friend. I've seen a few of the
Internet postcard sites. They make it easy to send along a voice
message with your virtual card.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You can really get into this audio stuff. There are all
kinds of file types, different ways to record voice, music and
more. You can also convert files to the format you desire, and you
can create lists of audio that can be digitally altered to your
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: OK, OK. Let's keep it simple. So, you wanna say ``hey'' to
your friend? A WAV (pronounced ``wave'') file is an uncompressed
computer recording. It can be heard by anyone using a Mac or PC. I
downloaded Ultra Recorder 2.4.1 (members.aol.com/ejc3/Ultra.html).
It's a Mac shareware application ($20). I also tested SoundBuilder
2.0.3 (freeware from MacWorld downloads). Both of these apps let
you record your voice quickly and easily. Once you record your file
with a standard microphone, it's a no-brainer to convert it to
Windows WAV and send it to a PC friend.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Yeah, I created several little annoying voice WAV files
within seconds. I told jokes, said ``hi'' and made weird little
noises.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I have a beautiful new background on my desktop, but I can't see
it because of all the icons. How can I remove icons from the
desktop? I still want the programs. I'll just go to ``Programs'' to
get them. I can't seem to find the answer.
</P>
<P>
   _ April Cleman
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Sounds like you need to do a little spring cleaning and
organizing. It can be confusing and scary if you do not know what's
what on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: I'm the resident expert on how to manage a messy desktop.
I haven't seen my desktop picture in years. In order for me to find
files, I close my eyes and play pin-the-tail on the computer
screen. One thing I have learned on a Mac is that your desktop can
take a hike (become corrupt) and you can lose all your data. I'm
still recovering.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Some people will never learn. An easy way to deal with this
is to create a folder on the hard drive (could be the C drive for
PC, Macintosh HD for the Mac). Next, alias or shortcut the folder
to the desktop. Then save your files, downloads and other documents
to that folder. If the desktop become corrupt, you only lose the
alias, not the contents of the folder.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
