r l BC-CAMPING-GADGETS0623-C     06-22 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPING-GADGETS0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Camping gadgets make the great outdoors that much greater
 &HT;    By Leigh-Anne Jackson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The call of the wild doesn't chime in to the
tune of ``La Cucaracha.'' It appeals to your desire to break free
from your cubicle's confines and actually rough it. But since so
many of us have been domesticated by our cells, pagers, Palm Pilots
and laptops, there's that initial fear that our ``roughness''
amounts to lounging in the backyard hammock without sunscreen or
citronella. Fear not the flora and fauna of that forest or state
park. Who says the return to nature has to be one of complete
asceticism? Armed with a few discreet gadgets, you can escape the
city limits without venturing too far outside your own personal
comfort boundaries. Compiled here is a survival guide for that
high-maintenance camper whose heart's in the right place, but whose
feral instinct requires a AA battery or two.
</P>
<P>
   CALLING ALL CAMPERS
</P>
<P>
   To avoid those ``Blair Witch''-style separation anxieties and
consequent spooked-out search parties, keep in touch with your tent
entourage with a Kenwood Freetalk F.R.S. two-way radio ($149.95;
www.altrec.com). This modern take on the walkie-talkie comes with a
two mile transmit radius, a call ringing feature and scrambling
capabilities for the super sleuth in you.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER NATURE'S SPY
</P>
<P>
   If you're reluctant to leave behind the homebound trappings of
your voyeurism _ ``Behind the Music,'' ``Real World,'' ``Who Wants
to Be A Millionaire'' _ The Sharper Image's 10-30x25 Compact Zoom
binoculars ($199.95; www.sharperimage .com) offer a
behind-the-scenes look at what's going on in that hot spot known as
nature. The lenses have a ruby coating for UV protection while
you're bird watching or deer spotting. And their ability to zoom
your view from 10 to 30 times can help in your surveillance of rare
botanics or pesky interlopers.
</P>
<P>
   DEPTH SENSITIVITY TRAINING
</P>
<P>
   Some cast their lures for the meditative aspect of fishing;
others, because they're hungry. If appetite quelling is your key
motivation, try the Garmin Fishfinder 240 ($364; www.garmin.com).
The on-screen display tracks both weak and strong underwater fish
signals and offers depth sensitivity so you can nab your prey
regardless of where they might be swimming.
</P>
<P>
   TIME AND TEMPERATURE
</P>
<P>
   Don't embark upon your impossible missions without these
all-in-one essentials. The conveniently hands-free Suunto Vector
Wristop Computer ($189.95; www.austinoutdoors.com) displays an
altimeter, barometer, compass and . . . oh yeah, it also tells
time. Brunton's Sherpa Atmospheric Data Center ($154.95;
www.austinoutdoors.com) tells time and gives hikers and rock
climbers their positional altitude, the temperature, barometric
pressure, wind speed and wind chill. Available at Austin Outdoor
Gear and Guidance.
</P>
<P>
   KEEP A SUNNY DISPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   With the Oregon Scientific Weather Forecaster ($65;
www.austinoutdoors .com), you can anticipate the forces of nature,
whether it's showers or severe temperatures. The monitor keeps
campers abreast of local forecasts for up to 24 hours. It even
features an alarm that sounds when storms are on the horizon. If
only TV meteorologists were this reliable. Available at Austin
Outdoor Gear and Guidance.
</P>
<P>
   KNOW WHERE YOU ARE IN THE MIDDLE OF NOWHERE
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that tree really does look familiar. Keep your pride intact
with the Garmin GPS 12 Map ($360; www .austinoutdoors.com), a
sure-fire guarantee that you won't have to ever ask another soul
for directions. The handheld navigator offers moving interstate
maps, a trip timer with speed calculations and a feature that
retraces your steps. It's also compatible with data from MapSource
CDs ($117), travel cheat sheets with intricate coastline, lakeway
and recreational area details. Accessories available at Austin
Outdoor Gear and Guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Storyy. We monitored nightly the stoic blob that was the Davidians'
bullet-riddled home. We all knew what we saw.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd that none of us was called as an expert this week as
the civil trial on the matter began in federal court. Instead, the
court summoned those who actually were there.
</P>
<P>
   This trial will get closer to the truth than our cathode-ray
truth tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in court it only took a few minutes to start shedding
light on pieces that all the world's satellites apparently couldn't
put together for the masses:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Davidians set their own building on fire April 19. It may
not have been ``the'' fire. Or it may have been one of several.
Attorney Mike Caddell e
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
