<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-     06-22 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-CARS-ONLINE06-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Buying a car online
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it came time for Julie Smith to buy a new car,
she wasn't sure exactly what she wanted. But she was sure she
didn't want to haggle over the price.
</P>
<P>
   After researching vehicles in publications such as Consumer
Reports and looking at them up close on dealer lots, the inside
sales representative for McKesson HBOC turned to the Internet to
price and purchase her 2000 Lexus RX 300 sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole buying experience was great. I didn't have to
dicker,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She went first to Edmunds.com, a site that has car-buying tips
as well as the dealer invoice for pricing a vehicle. There Smith
found a link to Autobytel.com, a car-buying service that puts
prospective buyers in touch with local dealers for a no-haggle
price on the vehicle they want, from color choice to option
packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not have been the best deal, but I was getting a decent
price,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience is being shared by an increasing number of car
buyers who may feel intimidated by the car-buying process or who
want the convenience of car shopping from home.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of all used-car shoppers used the Internet
for assistance during the shopping process, according to an August
survey by J.D. Power and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the transaction, another Power study
showed the number of auto dealers working with online buying
services has doubled in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Cyber Dialogue, an Internet consulting company, found
that 21 million people used the Net last year to get data on new
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 8.4 million reported that they bought vehicles, but
170,000 did so directly over the Internet, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, it seems, another dot-com company is adding a new
tool to the buyers' workbench. You'll find ways to find, price,
finance, insure and take delivery of a new or used car.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to the first question a prospective buyer should ask:
Do I want a new or used vehicle?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is important. If you're buying a new car you must go
through a dealer. With used cars, there are varying paths to choose
from.
</P>
<P>
   With new cars, state franchise laws require a dealer to be part
of the process, but there are no prohibitions on buying new cars
via the Internet or even from out-of-state dealers, noted Bill
Morie, president of the Georgia Automobile Dealers Association, a
trade group for new-car dealers. In most situations, Internet
buyers will sign the papers with a dealer in their area.
</P>
<P>
   Car buyers are embracing the Internet for buying all sorts of
things, noted Gayle Troberman, director of marketing for
Microsoft's CarPoint buying service. ``It's the first place to go
to get information at their fingertips and feel comfortable about
the money they are spending.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, price isn't the only factor, she said. ``They want
to get the right car for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet allows consumers to make comparisons between makes
and models, determine what tradeoffs they have to make and get a
fair price, which may not always be the absolutely lowest price,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dealerships in the past have been more resistant to the Internet
than some other retailers. Despite the extensive consolidation
going on in the industry, most dealerships are owned by individual
entrepreneurs, many of whom have been in the auto business for
decades and are reluctant to accept new ways of doing business.
Still, there are some innovators.
</P>
<P>
   One who has embraced the Internet is Mark Bowen, general manager
for Hyundai, Subaru and Oldsmobile for the Ed Voyles automotive
dealership group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best thing that ever happened to honest car
dealers,'' he said. ``The Internet has done for car selling what
the Model T did. It's that big.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers can find the dealer's invoice amount easily, including
the base price and options packages. ``Everything's out there. Why
should we play games?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   From Internet traffic that was next to nothing last year, Bowen
says about 40 percent of his Subaru customers and nearly a third of
those looking at Hyundais have made contact online.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership between the sites and the dealers is the key,
Bowen said: The Internet provides the contacts; the dealers provide
the cars.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers in the J.D. Power survey reported that customers who
used an online service saved an average of $490 on a new car,
compared with traditional showroom shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, online customers usually are quoted a lower price
up front without having to make an offer, the survey added.
</P>
<P>
   While the Voyles dealership is not a no-haggle environment,
Bowen insists he's providing a fair price, usually a fixed amount
over the dealer invoice, to Internet customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The online services are particularly effective for shoppers
who feel intimidated by salespeople and want to find a dealer that
is willing to give them their best price right upfront,'' said
Chris Denove, J.D. Power's director of automotive
retail/distribution analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Most car-buying sites have links to other sources of
information, including Kelley Blue Book (www.kbb.com), a popular
price guide for used cars, as well as reviews of new and older
vehicles and model comparisons. Many include links to financing and
insurance services. Manufacturers' sites also provide pictures,
specifications and options packages, along with the manufacturers
suggested retail price (MSRP, also known as the sticker price).
</P>
<P>
   But few vehicles are sold at the sticker price unless they are
in high demand or have a no-haggle tradition like Saturn. Instead,
buyers expect to begin their negotiations from the lower dealer
invoice price. That figure is a common feature on Edmunds.com and
many other buying service sites.
</P>
<P>
   Even that is not the dealer's cost for the vehicle because it
doesn't factor in ``holdback,'' an amount that the manufacturer
rebates to the dealer once the vehicle is sold. The refund is meant
to help offset the dealer's expenses for keeping the vehicle in
inventory. There also are other charges, including freight, dealer
back-office fees, sales tax and state title fees. There may also be
consumer or dealer rebates.
</P>
<P>
   Once customers have gathered information on price, style and
options _ and maybe even arranged financing _ they may be directed
to a dealer's own Web site or e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of franchised new-car dealerships have
Internet sites, according to the National Automobile Dealers
Association. Of them, 93 percent allow customers to send e-mail,
order online or obtain financing. Of those without sites,
two-thy,'' said Denove.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Internet shopping process isn't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports recently conducted research on five referral
sites. The magazine reported that only 35 percent of its panel of
1,056 online shoppers received a price quote within two days. When
they did get a quote, it wasn't always for the exact car specified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going online is a terrific way to do auto-related research,
but you can't kick the tires through your computer monitor, and you
can't slide behind the wheel with your mouse,'' said Lou Richman,
the magazine's finance editor.
</P>
<P>
   A test drive before ordering is still a good idea. ``The best
time is when the consumer has narrowed down the choices to two or
three cars,'' advises Alison Wagonfeld, Greenlight.com's vice
president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SHOPPERS SAY
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports conducted a panel of 1,056 online car shoppers.
The findings are reported in the April issue of the magazine:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly a quarter of the shoppers, 22 percent, were told they
would have to visit the dealership for a firm price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only two of three dealers who responded said they had the car
in stock or could get it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Overall, quoted prices were 5 percent to 10 percent below
manufacturers suggested retail prices, reasonably competitive for
some models but pricey for others.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 60 percent who got a price quote said they would
consider shopping in the future on the sites they tested.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-00 1200EDT &QL;
</P>
