<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-WEEWEB0620-C     06-22 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-WEEWEB0620-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Learn to draw your favorite cartoons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   www.cartooncorner.com _ Learn the secrets of animation from
cartoonist Emmett Scott. For the beginning artist, there is an
easy-to-follow tutorial on the basics of drawing characters. He
starts with drawing the four parts of the face that show emotion:
eyes, eyebrows, eyelids and mouth. The site also features single
panel cartoons, cartoon strips, short poems, rhyming stories,
hidden pictures and word games. Most of the time, the site
encourages participation, either by drawing, solving a riddle,
rhyming or making props like paper hats or maracas. Also, the site
explains the difference between kinds of cartoons: animation, spot
drawing, editorial cartoons and caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   www.goosehead.com _ See what all the hype's about and visit the
popular teen content web site created by 15-year-old California
native Ashley Power (apparently, her real name). Ashley offers
relationship au to be a genius to see how an accidental call like
that could be downright awful under the wrong circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Most people seem to have more cellular airtime than they have
something to say. Now I get calls from friends, driving in their
cars, who want to ask me if I've seen the latest model of the Ford
Explorer, or to muse about what they plan to have for dinner. Now
that free long-distance calling is part of most plans, I keep
hearing from folks all over the country who want to tell me about
the traffic jam that they've encountered in Cincinnati or about
their dog's medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is a wonderful thing, but it's just about to bore me
to death.
</P>
<P>
   So today, at the risk of hurting your feelings, let's talk about
how to act right. Think of it as Husted's Rules for Cellular
Etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 1. If you are so busy that you have to make and take calls
on the golf course, in the movies and other places where decent
folk are trying to get away from it all, then you are too busy to
have fun. Stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 2. Turn the danged thing off when you go to church, the
movies or a play. That weird nee-nah, nee-nah sound frightens
children and annoys adults.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 3. Unless you are having a really interesting conversation
_ something that could be turned into a soap opera _ don't have it
within my earshot.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 4. If you really don't have anything to say and simply
enjoy making calls, get a job as a motel switchboard operator.
</P>
<P>
   And please, if you disagree, send an e-mail. Don't call me using
your cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
