 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Origami meets two-wheeler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Riding a bicycle is one of the most
energy-efficient ways to get around, but using a bike to travel is
sometimes impractical. Perhaps the route is too long or too steep,
or perhaps you don't have a secure place to stash your bike. The
Montague Corp.'s line of folding bicycles may help you get around
some of those obstacles. The Montague CX 21-speed Comfort Bike
($450; www.montagueco.com), one of the company's newest models,
comes with either an 18- or 20-inch aluminum frame. It weighs 30
pounds and folds to 36 inches by 28 inches by 12 inches. Montague
says its bikes are full-size vehicles that fold down to half their
size in less than a minute without the use of tools. To fold a
Montague bike, the rider loosens a quick release bolt to remove the
front wheel. Two quick-release bolts on the seat post are then
loosened, and the rear wheel swings around to fold over the middle
of the bike frame. Other models include a mountain bike, an
off-road bike, an urban bike, an electric bike and a tandem bike _
all of which fold for easy storage.
</P>
<P>
