 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Perfect Dark is a perfect follow-up
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Long awaited and, frankly, long overdue, Perfect Dark ($50;
www.nintendo.com; for the Nintendo 64) is finally here. The
follow-up to the smash hit ``Goldeneye 007'' _ which still is
praised as the best first-person sneaky shooter on any console _
Perfect Dark surpasses its predecessor with sophisticated
artificial intelligence, superior lighting and sound effects and
``secondary firing'' features for some 35 weapons _ all the while
remaining true to the immersive, story-driven gameplay of the James
Bond game. Lead heroine Joanna Dark is a stealthy, secret-agent and
tactician with a license to kill, which she uses extremely
liberally. Blocky and hazy graphics are easily forgiven as players
are immersed in an intricate series of commando mission of seek and
discover, sneak and destroy, and tiptoe through a rampage.
Alternately, gameplay includes a variety of multiplayer modes;
co-operative mini-missions, flat-out death matches or variants. A
lot of game, and well worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   For those who need constant Sim-stimulation, there is Sim City
3000 Unlimited ($40; www.simcity.com; for Windows), an expanded,
colossal version of the 1999 game. New features include a new set
of buildings _ Asian and European _ new scenarios, new disasters
(plague of locusts, anyone?), seasons, customizable trees and
terrain, and an architect tool that lets you design your own homes
and buildings. While some of us still prefer the more personal,
addictive ``The Sims,'' Sim City 3000 fans will get a dose of new
things with the game, although the price may be steep for what it
essentially the same game with a few new extras. Luckily, owners of
the original game can get a $10 rebate if they buy Unlimited before
June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
