 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Sites teach how to understand Internet lingo, with Netiquette
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've used the Internet to get your daily horoscope,
to do marketing research for work, to check the weather for your
picnic next Saturday. Now it's only logical that you use the Net to
find out about the Net.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start at a site that helps you learn the language of the
Internet. Before long you'll be speaking of TCP and IP and port
surfing with the big folks. Just drop in at Surf Lingo at
www.zdnet.com/yil/content/surfschool/lingo/lingotoc.html and you'll
soon know the language from Arpanet (the precursor to the Internet)
to zmodem (a now outdated data transfer method).
</P>
<P>
   A slightly more technical guide is the Internet Encyclopedia at
freesoft.org/CIE/index.htm where you'll learn about the technical
operation of the Net. It's a searchable database, and you'll find
help on almost any technical term, but you may come away as
confused as you arrived. For instance, here's the beginning of the
explanation of subnetting: ``Engineers gradually realized that the
original class-based addressing design was too inflexible for many
applications. In the mid-1980s, subnetting was introduced as an
extension to the original scheme. ... For example, 255.255.0.0 is a
standard class B subnet mask, since the first two bytes are all
ones (network), and the last two bytes are all zeros (host). In a
subnetted network, the network portion is extended.''
</P>
<P>
   The good thing is that you really don't have to understand
subnetting to impress others, just cut and paste several of the
explanations into the report your boss wants about the challenges
ahead for your company in e-commerce and you'll be an instant
Internet expert.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that most newcomers notice, almost immediately, is
that there is a different set of rules for polite behavior on the
Internet. When one of those rules is violated (something as simple
as typing in all capital letters), new users are almost certain to
hear about it, sometimes in a rude and abusive way. While that in
itself isn't great Internet etiquette, there are ways to avoid
these confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to learn the culture and etiquette of the Internet is
at a site called Netiquette at www.albion.com/netiquette/. If you
want a quick and basic course, there's a link to a section called
``core rules,'' but if you want even more, if you have aspirations
to become the Emily Post of the Net, then there is a link to a
complete guide to Netiquette too.
</P>
<P>
   Most old hands at the Net will be glad to see that _ included in
the complete guide _ there is a strong admonition not to pass on
electronic chain letters, or to naively send along dire warnings of
viruses that never lived outside phony e-mail warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you know how to behave and can speak the language,
you'll want to visit a comprehensive site called Learn the Net at
www.learnthenet.com/english/index.html. You've graduated from basic
training and now it's time for advanced work. This is a site that
offers more depth and discusses some of the lesser known areas of
the Net such as newsgroups and listservs (which are discussion
groups carried on by e-mail _ make sure you read about them before
joining one, since you can end up with more e-mail than a normal
person would wish for).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-00 1158EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
