 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Cell phone insanity is spreading, so here are some rules
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The man was obviously insane, maybe dangerously so,
waving his arms, speaking loudly as he walked alone along the
street on a dusky evening near the newspaper where I work.
</P>
<P>
   As near as I could tell he was either excited about a baseball
game or explaining t things. It's because of those danged low cell
phone rates and free airtime offers.
</P>
<P>
   I yearn for the days when the only people having monologues were
wearing three jackets and mismatched shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not the only danger from cell phone addicts. If they
don't kill you on the road, they'll drive you crazy in the
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Just this morning on the elevator at work, a fellow standing 8
inches away from me was explaining to his wife why his golf round
lasted 18 hours on Saturday. It was obvious, from listening to his
end of the conve
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-00 1156EDT &QL;
</P>
