<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ASIA-ALBRIGHT-0623-CO     06-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-ALBRIGHT-0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBRIGHT URGES 'FLEXIBILITY' TO CHINESE LEADERS ON TAIWAN ISSUE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In what is likely to be her last visit to China as
Secretary of State, Madeleine Albright urged top Chinese leaders to
resume dialogue with Taiwan, saying flexibility was better than
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   In a marathon series of meetings in here in Beijing Thursday,
Albright said the United States is eager to see a lowering of
tension between mainland China and the island of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's newly-elected president, Chen Shui-bian, said Tuesday
he would like to meet Chinese President Jiang Zemin in a summit
much like the one that took place between leaders of North and
South Korea last week.
</P>
<P>
   China, however, has continued to insist that Taiwan recognize
the ``one China'' policy, meaning that Taiwan is part of China,
before any talks can take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly more will be gained through flexibility and appeals
to shared interest than could possibly be achieved through efforts
to intimidate,'' Albright said about the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said China doesn't feel is has enough information
about Taiwan's new president, and is still trying to figure him
out. ``They are questioning, basically, who he is, what his motives
are, how he's going to operate,'' Albright told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to China is her first since March 1999, and marks a
slow but steady improvement in relations between the two countries,
which hit a low last May following the U.S. bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said the bombing, which killed
three Chinese nationals, was accidental, but Beijing has not fully
accepted its explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp differences remain in the areas of human rights and Tibet,
Albright said. Although Beijing and Washington have resumed
bilateral dialogue in several areas since last May, human rights is
one area where conversation has remained at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   While the talks were wide-ranging _ covering everything from
China's accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO) to
environmental protection and peace in the Middle East _ the other
main purpose of Albright's visit was to discuss the Korean
peninsula, where the leaders historic summit buoyed hopes for
unification of North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said China and the United States share common goals in
Korea, such as wanting to see the reunion of divided families and
long-term peace. But top aides say the Clinton administration will
continue to explore an expensive missile defense program as a
shield against a North Korean missile attack _ which Beijing fears
could neutralize its tiny nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to arriving in Beijing, Albright's said she hoped to hear
first-hand from Chinese officials about North Korea's reclusive
leader, Kim Jong Il, who made a secret trip to Beijing just before
the summit. However, if Albright gleaned any additional insight
into Kim's thinking, she did not reveal it to reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She indicated only that, while the summit was historic, it was
merely a first step towards genuine peace on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be rightfully termed as naive to think everything has
been dealt with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the success of the Korean summit, questions have arisen
about the continued need for the 37,000 American soldiers stationed
in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   However, Albright indicated troop withdrawal was not on her
agenda with South Korean officials, whom she is meeting in Seoul
Friday and Saturday, nor did the subject come up with Chinese
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much agreed our troops on the peninsula are a
stabilizing factor,'' she said. ``It's clear that's not an issue
for discussion (in South Korea).''
</P>
<P>
   The hastily arranged visit to China, her fifth as Secretary of
State, included lunch with her counterpart, Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan, afternoon meetings with Vice Premier Qian Qichen and
Premier Zhu Rongji, and an evening meeting with President Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Albright is scheduled to meet with some American
businessmen, visit an Internet cafe, then fly to Seoul, where she
will stay less than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
