<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS ENJOY FREE TRIP TO ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHOSHANA LONDON SAPPIR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ At the age of 19, Julie Aronow-Frieden, a theater
student at Northeastern University, has traveled to places as
remote as Uzbekistan, India, Turkey and Thailand, but had never
felt the desire to visit her religious homeland, Israel. Halfway
through a 10-day, all-expenses-paid trip aimed at reconnecting her
to her Jewish roots, however, Aronow-Frieden is thinking about
joining the Israeli Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt I had to sweep my religion under the carpet,''
said the freckled native of Tempe, Ariz., during a tour of Israeli
national monuments in Jerusalem. ``I hardly knew any Jewish people.
I always felt alone. Here I feel completely connected. I can't even
describe it. I don't have to feel ashamed anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Aronow-Frieden is one of 8,000 students to date who have been
the beneficiaries of an ambitious $210 million, five-year program
by Jewish philanthropists, the government of Israel and Jewish
communities worldwide, whose goal is to spur a Jewish revival by
providing a free educational trip to Israel for every Jewish person
between the ages of 15 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Birthright Israel,'' the program is a response to the
assimilation of Jews worldwide into secular societies, which has
been accompanied by a sharp decline of Jewish affiliation in the
last decades. A key statistic that alarms Jewish community leaders
is the rate of intermarriage, which some studies say exceeds 50
percent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for many kids this is the last Jewish hope,'' said
Michael Steinhardt of New York, a retired investment manager who
co-sponsors Birthright with Charles Bronfman, co-chairman of
Seagram Co. ``Ten intensive days can really change lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In Aronow-Frieden's case, they certainly might.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend who went to Israel and served in the army,''
she said, wiping her face as sweat mingled with tears of emotion.
``I used to make fun of him. Now I want to do it too. I picked up a
brochure. I would like to come next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, launched last December, has sparked controversy in
the Jewish community worldwide and in Israel. Critics wonder
whether a crash course on Jewish identity can really curb the
historic tides that pull Jewish youth towards assimilation. The
critics ask whether the funds could be more effectively applied to
existing educational programs, or to establishing new ones.
Israelis have questioned the government's contribution of $70
million when there are many needy people in their own country.
</P>
<P>
   World Jewish Congress Chairman Isi Liebler called the Birthright
Israel concept ``bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That Jews are in deep trouble in the Diaspora, especially in
America, goes without saying,'' he wrote in the Jewish World
Review. ``Devoted, well-meaning American Jewish philanthropists,
desperate for solutions, have mistakenly adopted the quick fix: a
free trip for every youngster to overcome all of the problems of
Jewish identity and miraculously generate a Jewish renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   Birthright officials said their follow-up evaluations have
already shown the program to be a great success: some 10 percent of
participants in the first round of trips last winter, which brought
5,000 students, plan to come back to Israel this summer. The Hillel
organization, which provides Jewish social and educational programs
on college campuses across the United States and in other
countries, has had to expand quickly to accommodate a sharp rise in
interest, and large numbers of Birthright participants have
enrolled in Jewish studies courses when they returned to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear to me the money is not wasted if even 10 percent
of these kids get involved,'' said Steinhardt, who would like to
bring some 200,000 young Jews to Israel in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day tours, which draw on a long tradition of Israel tours
for young Jews, are carefully designed to provide balanced doses of
education, fun, and spiritual awakening ``to get students thinking
about their Jewishness and to fuse education with recreation,'' in
the words of a Birthright brochure. No Birthright trip is complete
without meetings with young Israelis, who, in their late teens and
early 20s, are likely to be in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting Israelis our age and seeing their passion for their
country really brought it all home for me,'' said Makenzie Mazin,
22, another member of the Northeastern group. ``I never once
thought about coming to Israel. But seeing those soldiers, and kids
who immigrated from Ethiopia, and people praying at the wall has
made me want to know more about my Jewishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazin is just the kind of young Jew Birthright seeks to attract.
To qualify for the trip, applicants have to be Jews who have never
been on a peer-trip to Israel. Priority is given to those who are
not affiliated with any Jewish organization. Seventy-five percent
of participants are from North America.
</P>
<P>
   Birthright recruits applicants through letters to Jewish
students, conversations with Jewish professors, posters, e-mail,
and word of mouth. A key word in the pitch is ``free.''
</P>
<P>
   Birthright adopts an inclusive definition of ``Jewish,'' a
deeply divisive question within the Jewish community. According to
Israeli law, which follows the Orthodox doctrine, Mazin, for
instance, does not qualify. Her father is Jewish and her Catholic
mother ``converted, but not ceremonially, just in her faith,''
Mazin said. Israel considers only the child of a Jewish mother or
someone who converted according to religious law to be a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they do not probe applicants' Jewish backgrounds
and are aware that a high number of participants are children of
mixed marriages, which is exactly the phenomenon the program seeks
to combat.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Meltzer, director of Hillel at Northeastern, who
accompanied the 22 students on the trip, considered the impact the
trip might have:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they'll think twice before dating someone who is
not Jewish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
