<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1604 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-SOY-SAUCE-HNS &LR;      06-22 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOY-SAUCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOY SAUCE: MORE THAN JUST TABLE DRESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SANFORD NOWLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just for a moment, forget lemon grass, hoisin sauce and
fermented black beans. Put fish sauce and five-spice powder in the
back of your mind as well.
</P>
<P>
   The first Asian seasoning most Americans have any exposure to is
soy sauce, a staple on virtually every Chinese restaurant table and
in most kitchen cupboards.
</P>
<P>
   It has been around in the United States since the 1800s, making
it one of the least exotic, yet also one of the least understood,
Asian ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Soy sauce comes in different varieties _ some spiked with added
flavors such as mushroom, for example _ in different strengths, and
in varying degrees of quality.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding this essential Asian ingredient is an important
step to unlocking the cuisines of the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can taste the differences between red wines you can
taste the differences between soy sauces,'' said Barbara Tropp, a
California restaurateur and author of the ``China Moon Cookbook.''
``If it's good soy sauce, it tastes round _ not just salty _ and,
like wine, has a good beginning, middle and finish.''
</P>
<P>
   The origins of soy sauce date back more than 2,500 years, making
it one of the world's oldest condiments.
</P>
<P>
   The prehistoric people of Asia preserved meat and fish by
salt-packing them, which drew out the moisture. The resulting salty
juices from the meat were then used to season foods or form the
base for sauces or soups.
</P>
<P>
   Later, with the rise of Buddhism, and its vegetarian diet, the
need arose for an alternate condiment to take the place of the
salty, meaty sauce. That substitute, developed by Chinese monks,
was a salty paste of fermented grains, which eventually evolved
into soy sauce and spread through much of the rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Today, quality soy sauces are prepared, much as they were
hundreds of years ago, by combining soybeans and wheat with a
special mold, then fermenting them with water and salt for several
months. At the end of the process, the liquid is separated from
solid materials, filtered and bottled.
</P>
<P>
   That fermentation process gives soy sauce depth, mellowness and
flavor-enhancing qualities, making it much more than simply a
substitute for salt, as many Western cooks treat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly adds character to the sauce,'' said Dan Miller,
administration manager for sauce-maker Kikkoman's U.S. production
facility in Walworth, Wis. ``That's one of the advantages to our
product. It not only has its own flavor but enhances the flavors of
the foods that are being prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all soy sauces undergo a natural brewing process, however.
</P>
<P>
   Low-quality sauces, generally produced in the United States, are
chemically created and forgo the lengthy aging process.
</P>
<P>
   Those sauces, which use adjunct ingredients such as hydrolyzed
vegetable protein and caramel coloring, lack the depth of taste of
traditionally fermented soy sauce, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The taste of these sauces often is harshly salty, chemical and
overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really tell the difference,'' said Ming Tsai, host of
the Food Network's ``East Meets West'' and owner of the Blue Ginger
restaurant in Wellesley, Mass. ``Fermented soy sauce smells
pleasant and slightly sweet; the other kind smells like a chemical
factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Tropp says: ``It's the difference between a bottle of
moonshine and a bottle of Mondavi.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most commonly used quality soy sauces are Japanese and
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   In Chinese cooking, the two principal types of soy sauce are
categorized as light and dark. Confusingly (at least for Western
chefs), light soy sauce is often labeled ``superior soy,'' while
the dark is labeled ``soy superior.''
</P>
<P>
   Light sauce, which is the saltier of the two, is lighter in
color and thinner. It's used more frequently in cooking stir fries
and other dishes and as a table condiment.
</P>
<P>
   Dark soy sauce is aged longer and contains molasses, giving it a
darker color and more pungent smell. Dark soy sauce is usually
reserved for use in braised and barbecued dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese recipes sometimes call for mushroom- or shrimp-flavored
soy sauces that are generally available at Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Japanese soy sauce is less salty and often sweeter than
its Chinese cousin.
</P>
<P>
   And like China, Japan also produces other soy sauce varieties
such as a wheat-free variety called Tamari. Another is white soy
sauce, a delicately flavored, amber-colored variety that's heavier
on wheat than soy.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese cookbooks and chefs caution against using Japanese
soy sauce in Chinese recipes and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   However, many Asian chefs in the United States _ including those
who work in Chinese cuisine _ stand behind the Japanese brands,
saying they tend to have better quality control and therefore a
more consistent flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Kikkoman, the soy sauce with the largest U.S. market share, is
the overwhelming favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kikkoman is usually my favorite because it's less salty,''
said Nicole Routhier, the Houston-based author of ``Foods of
Vietnam.'' ``The Chinese and Vietnamese varieties can be very
potent and overpowering. Kikkoman has a more balanced flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropp said those who insist on buying a Chinese sauce might try
the Pearl River Bridge brand available at many Asian groceries. But
even that has been ``fraught with difficulties'' of inconsistency,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tsai said he doesn't buy the argument that Japanese soy
sauce shouldn't be used in other types of Asian cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's like saying `don't use California wine in a
French recipe,''' Tsai said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sanford Nowlin by e-mail at
snowlin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
