<HEADLINE>
AT FIDELITY, THE YOUNG TAKE THEIR PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Fidelity Investments moving its executives around is a
lot like following an entertaining chess match.
</P>
<P>
   There is usually more than one motive for everything and
observers always wonder what the plan is two or three moves ahead.
Analysis is muddled by divided opinions and is often wrong in
retrospect. That never stopped us.
</P>
<P>
   One safe observation about the latest developments at the
world's largest mutual fund company: the slow but certain
generational shift taking place in the senior ranks of Fidelity's
management.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than a younger manager moving into the job of an
older executive. New chief operating officer Robert Reynolds, 48,
is different in experience, corporate background, and people he
would consider professional contemporaries than the man leaving
that post, James Curvey, 65.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, another of Fidelity chairman Edward C.
Johnson's longtime lieutenants, J. Gary Burkhead, retired and was
replaced by Gail McGovern, 48, as head of the company's retail fund
sales and brokerage operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there is a thought process to involve some younger
people in the very high levels of the company because we're going
to be around for a long time and you need the people to run it,''
Reynolds said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Amid some of these changes, the most interesting question
surrounds Johnson's daughter and whether she will step into a more
prominent role at the company.
</P>
<P>
   Abigail Johnson, 38, has worked as a fund manager and executive
in other capacities at Fidelity. But whether she ever wants to
succeed her father, who turns 70 this month, as chairman and would
take on more important interim roles remains an open question.
</P>
<P>
   As executive chairs are shuffled this week, Curvey is stepping
aside as chief operating officer but hardly fading away. By moving
back to his old post overseeing Fidelity's venture capital and
other private investment operations, he keeps control of some of
the company's most valuable assets.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fidelity's principal business and image as an investment
management firm, a large part of the company's value is tied up in
telecommunications today.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity owns a controlling interest in British-based COLT
Telecom Group PLC worth roughly $14 billion. Fidelity's stakes in
similar but less developed telecommunications companies in South
America and Asia could be big hits in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey moved into the chief operating officer role three years
ago when Fidelity was in serious trouble and he is due considerable
credit for improving the company's position.
</P>
<P>
   Huge sums of money flowing into mutual funds during the last
three years certainly helped float every boat in the industry. But
Fidelity had been hurting badly in 1997 and might not have been
able to take advantage of the flood of customer cash flow without
better management.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pozen, the corporate lawyer who took over management of
the company's actual investment arm at the same time, could claim
at least as much credit for fixing Fidelity. He stemmed the nonstop
defection of Fidelity fund managers and restored stability in a key
part of the business that had appeared dangerously rocky.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the current changes, Pozen stands out as an intriguing
character. He seems to have been around Fidelity in important roles
forever and part of the older generation, but Pozen is only 53
years old and undeniably ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pozen and Curvey were given titles as vice chairmen
Wednesday. So was Reynolds. In a corporate culture that tends to
get the most out of managers by pitting one against another, the
possibilities of their arrangement are intriguing and geometric in
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds didn't arrive on Fidelity's Devonshire Street doorstep
Wednesday. He came out of a banking trust background 16 years ago
and started selling similar products at Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   His career was boosted by the chance to get in on the ground
floor of the fund industry's biggest catalyst of the last decade:
the defined contribution retirement plan business.
</P>
<P>
   He got Fidelity's unit off the ground in 1989 and today those
401(k) plans and other retirement vehicles are the single largest
source of new customer cash at Fidelity, just like they are at most
big fund companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now Reynolds will run a lot more, including Fidelity's brokerage
operation and other business lines that are new to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about the opportunity,'' he said. ``I've been
here 16 years. I know Fidelity and I know the business.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, we're waiting for the next move.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
