<HEADLINE>
FIBER-CEMENT _ A NEW SIDING FOR A NEW AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Homo sapiens appeared many millennia ago, he sought shelter
in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   Then, growing bolder, he built a house of straw. Then came
stone, then more sophisticated adobe and fired brick.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, wood truimphed, and ruled, with masonry for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The wood, painted many colors, was wonderful, until the paint
started to peel. Then, tired of the chore and cost of painting, man
turned to (horrors!) fake siding, not to solve the problem but to
cover it.
</P>
<P>
   First there was asphalt, which was like putting roof shingles on
walls. It was ugly. Then came asbestos cement, a good cover, but
not pretty. It was hazardous when asbestos fibers were released.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, when aluminum again became plentiful, came
the tinmen, the sharpies who sold the nation a bill of goods:
aluminum siding. Neither was that pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the ultimate assault on our long-suffering houses:
vinyl siding. This too was ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Like all fake siding, each product was considered the be-all and
end-all when it came out. It would last forever. There was no
maintenance. It was beautiful(?).
</P>
<P>
   And, like all fake siding, each had its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   So the beat goes on, looking for a better product, a better
substitute for wood (save the wood!), a better fake siding, and a
way to make a buck.
</P>
<P>
   James Hardie Building Products, Inc. of Mission Viego, Calif.,
has come up with the ultimate: fiber-cement siding _ clapboards and
other horizontal boards, vertical boards, stucco panels, and
shingles. It just might be the be-all and end-all.
</P>
<P>
   While it may imitate cedar and other wood, it is its own
material, and looks pretty good, far better than other fake siding.
It has to be painted, but the company says the paint will last
longer than on wood, with a minimum of peeling.
</P>
<P>
   It is basically concrete, a cementitious (cement-based) material
consisting of Portland cement, ground sand, cellulose fiber, select
additives and water. It is interesting that such a modern product
still contains wood, in the form of cellulose, like the cellulose
insulation used today.
</P>
<P>
   These materials _ Portland cement (made from limestone),
cellulose (scrap wood and paper), and sand _are in ample supply and
not endangered. And, the company adds, the product contains no
asbestos, glass fibers, or formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   The Hardie shingles, shingle panels, and lap siding are
virtually the same thickness as the shingles and clapboards they
are simulating, and are attached to the house the same way wood is.
Vertical boards are 516 inch thick, not as thick as the boards they
simulate, but just as strong, and are applied the same away as wood
boards.
</P>
<P>
   We talked to Freddy Scharf, technical supervisor at the
California headquarters, who said the cellulose in the Hardiplank,
Hardipanel, and Hardie Shingleside gives the material flexibility
and nailability.
</P>
<P>
   You can nail it just as you can nail wood, he said, with no need
to predrill, and nails can be driven to 3/8 inch from the sides.
You can't countersink the nails but you can drive them flush with
the material, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the boards are rigid and heavy enough to lie flat no
matter where they go, and even lap siding can be blind-nailed; that
is, nailed at the top so that the next board above will cover the
nails. Such boards will continue to lie flat.
</P>
<P>
   All shingles and shingle panels are blind-nailed: the
fiber-cement boards are the first boards that can be blind-nailed.
</P>
<P>
   Scharf said the various sidings can be applied on new or old
houses, and are also designed for the do-it-yourselfer. But he
added that the company recommends not putting its product over old
shingles or clapboards, but over level and even sheathing. So old
material should be removed first.
</P>
<P>
   The siding comes in several styles: lap siding (clapboards) with
wood grain or smooth; beaded lap siding; Colonial rough-sawn or
smooth lap siding, which looks like horizontal siding spaced with
grooves; individual shingles; shingle panels; stucco vertical
siding; and vertical siding, grooved or ungrooved.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber-cement siding must be painted. Most of the siding comes
primed with a latex primer, which requires only two coats of a
100-percent acrylic or water-based topcoat, said Scharf. Some
shingles are not primed; in that case they can be primed with an
alkaline-resistant (water-based) primer before painting. A solid
color latex stain can be substituted for the paint, Scharf said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the siding has a limited warranty of 50 years. Some
shingles are guaranteed for 30 years. The company said that the
paint lasts so long you probably won't paint again until you're
ready to change colors.
</P>
<P>
   The fiber-cement is stable, and will not expand and contract the
way wood and vinyl can.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber-cement technology is only about 10 years old, but has
grown precipitously in that decade, so much so that some stores are
having trouble keeping up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Hardie also makes trim boards for fascias, eaves and soffits,
and backerboard for ceramic tile floors and walls.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you and I can buy these materials at stores and put them up
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Hardie company has been working with cement since it started
in 1883 in Australia. It inaugurated fiber-cement products in 1990
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today the company's production capacity exceeds 700 million
square feet annually, and will grow to 900 million soon. If it
takes 2,500 square feet of product to cover a typical house, those
700 million square feet represent 280,000 houses.
</P>
<P>
   That'll give vinyl a run for its money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
