<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS &LR;      06-22 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TEXAS CASE, EYEWITNESS ROLE GETS A HARD LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The case against Gary Graham, the latest in a
series of Texas death-row inmates to test Governor George W. Bush's
judgment with a claim of innocence, is notable not because it is
unique, but because it is so typical.
</P>
<P>
   As with most of the more than 600 men and women nationally who
have been executed since the death penalty was revived in 1977,
Graham was found guilty and sentenced to death without the
scientific certainty provided by DNA testing of physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Bush or his appointees on the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles intervene, Graham was ordered executed on the kind of
evidence that typifies most criminal cases: a single and unwavering
_ but controversial _ eyewitness identification.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Graham case returns the death penalty debate to where
it stood before the laboratory magic of DNA came upon the scene,
and where it still stands in most cases today _ with a very human
system displaying both its strengths and shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by chanting foes of capital punishment on a campaign
swing through California this week, Bush vowed to ``uphold the law
of the land,'' but gave no further indication of how he might rule
on Graham's appeals for a stay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the case of Ricky McGinn, who won a 30-day reprieve from
Bush this month so that DNA tests could be conducted, the killer
left no blood, hair, or semen in the Graham case. Bobby Lambert,
the victim, was shot in a bungled hold-up in a supermarket parking
lot, and the police did not find any physical evidence linking the
murderer to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   There was no DNA to damn Graham, or save his life. No
fingerprints. No hair to be matched. No confession. No forensic
firearms tests.
</P>
<P>
   There is Graham, a 17-year-old on a cocaine-fueled crime spree
at the time, who by his own admission spent the two weeks that
followed Lambert's murder staging 10 robberies and shooting two
victims in parking lot hold-ups.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Bernadine Skillern, who says she saw Graham come up
behind Lambert in a Safeway parking lot one May night in Houston in
1981 and put a .22 caliber pistol to his head. She was sitting in
her car, some 30 to 40 feet away, and leaned on her horn to scare
the gunman away. She heard a shot, started up her car, and pursued
the killer before her terrified children persuaded her to give up
the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Mr. Graham shoot and kill Mr. Lambert on that parking
lot in 1981,'' Skillern, now 53, told reporters at a Houston press
conference last week. ``That has not changed. That is not going to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in another of the dueling press conferences in Texas by
supporters and opponents of the death penalty in the last 10 days,
a rape victim from North Carolina traveled to Texas to tell the
press about the fallibility of eyewitness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Thompson was 22 when she was raped in 1984. She
intently focused on her rapist's features _ and still accused an
innocent man of the crime. The man she identified as her assailant
spent 11 years in jail before DNA tests cleared him in 1995. In the
course of the investigation she was shown a photo of her real
assailant, and said it was not him. ``Eyewitnesses can make
mistakes,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is not alone. Participants in a 1996 study by the US
Department of Justice examined 28 cases where innocent men were
convicted of serious crimes only to be absolved by DNA evidence. In
these cases, which included three of the eight cases where death
row inmates have been freed by DNA testing, ``eyewitness testimony
was the most compelling evidence,'' the study concluded. ``Clearly
. . . these eyewitness identifications were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambiguities exist in the Graham case, too. His lawyers note that
several other witnesses failed to support Skillern's
identification, and that the police initially showed Skillern a
photo lineup of five men, in which Graham was the only one who fit
her description of a killer without facial hair. Skillern was drawn
to Graham's photo, and then picked him out of a live lineup the
next day _ a suggestive sequence of events that tainted her
identification, said his attorney, Richard Burr.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case offers fodder to those who contend that the
United States has gotten carried away with enthusiasm for capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   But Joshua Marquis, a member of the board of directors of the
National District Attorneys Association, said that the adversarial
justice system remains a sound forum on which juries and judges can
weigh matters like eyewitness testimony and circumstantial evidence
and make sound convictions short of scientific certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``DNA can be a marvelous forensic tool, but it is not a magic
bullet,'' Marquis said. ``We must never forget the other, massively
larger part of this risk-benefit analysis _ the thousands of truly
innocent victims who die at the hands of criminals that the legal
system has failed to hold accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country we have an incredibly elaborate appellate
system that recognizes that police, prosecutors, judges, and juries
are not infallible,'' he said. ``Opponents . . . are attempting to
reshape the discussion in the form of a new urban myth: that our
justice system is growing increasingly reckless in its zeal to
execute and, worse yet, that significant numbers of innocents are
ending up on death row. This is a myth in search of a crisis that
doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Aloysius Farrell reported from Washington and Austin,
Texas. Material from wire services was used to prepare this
article.
</P>
</TEXT>
