<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAS REMAINS IN COALITION GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The linchpin Shas political party retracted its
resignation from the government Thursday, leaving Prime Minister
Ehud Barak's broad coalition battered but intact to head into a
critical stage of peacemaking with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the prime minister, first of all, the umbrella that he
has a government,'' said Shlomo Benizri, a Shas official and the
health minister. ``And that with this government, he will be able
to travel to the United States in the near future, within two
weeks, to continue with the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, the U.S. peace envoy, arrived for meetings here
Thursday and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will follow next
week as part of the Americans' intensifying effort to lay the
foundation for a successful retreat-style summit meeting in July.
The goal of that meeting would be a final peace agreement and an
end to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, although a partial
solution is considered more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a year of tense co-existence with the leftists in
Barak's government, Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party, succeeded in
forcing the leftist Meretz Party out of the Cabinet so that Shas
members could remain.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz's three ministers quit their posts on Wednesday night.
The three included the education minister, Yossi Sarid, a staunch
secularist who has become Shas' nemesis. Meretz will stay in the
government to support the peace effort that it champions, but it
relinquished its ministries, essentially opting out of its
hard-fought battles with Shas, to end the uncertainty about whether
the government would survive.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister agreed, maybe against his true wishes, to
give up Meretz, and Meretz agreed to lie down over the fence for
him,'' Sarid said, invoking an image in which one soldier throws
himself over the barbed wires so that others can walk over him to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did not try to persuade the Meretz ministers to stay,
although he said that their departure hurts both them and him. ``I
regret that we have reached this stage, but appreciate Meretz'
concession and continue to see Meretz as a natural partner,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Barak will learn whether the political crisis has been
worth it: whether Shas backs the peace effort, too. He included
Shas in his government, and withstood its full-time balkiness, in
order to have the party's backing for a peace deal with the
Palestinians. But that support is not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The specific issues in contention between Shas and Barak
concerned the finances and oversight of the religious party's
indebted school system and the legalization of its pirate radio
stations, which have been nicknamed ``the holy channels.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Shas' rabbis instructed their politicians to resign
from the coalition last week, they also cited Barak's plan ``to
forsake'' the West Bank. There is a deeply embedded resistance
inside the party to territorial concessions, despite a one-time
ruling by Shas' spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, that it is
valid to give up land if it serves to end the violence and save
Jewish lives.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's party, One Israel, ``has not discounted the possibility
that in a month or two, if he presents an agreement with the
Palestinians, Shas will stick a knife in his back,'' Yossi Verter
wrote in the Haaretz newspaper Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But Benizri cautioned Israelis against assuming that Shas was
``a satellite faction of the right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sarid, who is also the Meretz leader, his
resignation will have ``saved the government and maybe even the
peace process'' if Shas backs the prime minister. ``But if this
step of ours, which is so unusual, does not help, no one can put
the blame on us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Formed a year ago, Barak's broad coalition was his effort to
learn from the mistakes of his mentor, the late Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin, and to forge a national consensus for his
peacemaking. But the rifts between various segments of Israeli
society go very deep, and they are probably even more intense at
the leadership level. Instead of bridging differences, the broad
government has seemed to exacerbate them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A demonstration of the deep-seated enmity between Sarid and Eli
Yishai, the Shas leader, played out like hostile theater in the
Israeli parliament on Wednesday. Sarid mocked what he said was
Yishai's weakness as a party leader, repeatedly saying: ``Try to
refrain from lying. I know it's not easy.'' Yishai accused Sarid of
persecuting Shas in an obsessed way, and referred to him as
``wicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the bickering, Barak sighed. ``You hear the
argument,'' he said, ``and you really understand why when the
teacher in the second grade sees her pupils misbehaving she says to
them, `This isn't the Knesset, get a hold of yourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis have been disgusted and disillusioned by the
political crisis. Nahum Barnea, a senior columnist for Yedioth
Ahronoth, compared the politicians' displays of rage to a recent
rash of impulse murders. ``The ministers are no better than the
drivers who kick each other to death because of a quarrel over the
right of way at a traffic light,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
