<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1625 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-CONTINENT-BOS &LR;      06-22 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CONTINENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGHING IT IN A LAND OF WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE EIGHTH CONTINENT 
Life, Death, and Discovery in the Lost World of Madagascar 
By Peter Tyson 
Morrow, 368 pp., $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madagascar is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   So many formerly exotic destinations for Western travelers have
become all theme park and tented luxury. But not the Great Red
Island. It effortlessly retains the romance of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Thrill-seeking ecotourists still don't brave it in great
numbers. But biologists, archeologists, paleontologists, and even
paleoecologists flock here, drawn by its endless natural riddles.
</P>
<P>
   Madagascar is the fourth largest island in the world. A
biodiversity hotspot, it is, like Darwin's Galapagos Islands, a
living laboratory unlike any other place on the planet. Some 250
miles off the east coast of Africa, this Texas-sized island split
off from other land masses 160 million years ago. Over all this
time, plants and animals evolved here in isolation. And today, you
can find creatures and vegetation that exist nowhere else on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this is the most species-rich spot in the world.
Eighty-three percent of Madagascar's wildlife is unique, including
8,000 of its 10,000 plants species. This is the place to find those
Dr. Seuss-like primitive primates, the lemurs. And chameleons and
orchids beyond measure.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, there's not all that much in the current general
literature about this incredible place. With ``The Eighth
Continent,'' Peter Tyson, a science writer and online producer for
PBS's ``Nova,'' goes a long way toward filling the gap. And he does
it with a sense of urgency, since 90 percent of Madagascar's
original vegetation is gone _ one of the worst cases of destruction
on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson visited Madagascar four times between 1993 and 1997,
tagging along with scientists on a mission: a herpetologist
cataloguing the amazing array of reptiles; a paleoecologist
searching for clues in the disappearance of the island's bigger
animals thousands of years ago; a primatologist trying to save
lemurs and negotiate the complicated politics of conservation; and
an archeologist digging for answers to a very basic question: Where
did the people of Madagascar come from?
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is at his best when he's on the ground in Madagascar,
roughing it in a very rough place, and weaving into the story its
curious natural history. On one outing, Tyson peels back a strip of
bark to find ``a seething mass of tarantulas, scorpions, and giant
hissing cockroaches.'' Two kinds of vines make walking in the
forest miserable: one with fish-hook barbs grabs at your legs;
another kind causes a painful, burning sensation on contact with
the skin. It is often unbearably hot _ in the 100s. Insects swarm
around the exposed orifices of trekkers.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is traveling where few other Westerners ever have. In one
village, he is only the fourth ``vazaha,'' or light-skinned
foreigner, to have visited in living memory. And not everyone is
happy to see him. Some still believe that vazaha want to cut their
hearts out.
</P>
<P>
   In another enclave, Tyson learns an amazing trick _ how to get
past the thousands of fine spines that guard the fruit of the
prickly pear. The Malagasy driver captures a fly, holds it close to
the fruit by the wings, and lets ``its scrabbling feet pull out the
cactus spines.''
</P>
<P>
   A thorough researcher, Tyson packs this book with solid
information. Why did the 10-foot-tall flightless elephant bird,
gorilla-sized lemurs, and pygmy hippos go extinct right around the
time humans came to the island perhaps 2,000 years ago? The answer
isn't as simple as you might suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson investigates tales in remote regions of the continued
existence of the pygmy hippo. The Malagasy language is filled with
impossibly long words, but this hippo has one of the best names
going: kilopilopitsofy (pronounced ke-loop-ee-loop-ee-tsoofy).
</P>
<P>
   But too often, instead of integrating the exciting present with
the complex past, Tyson walls them off from one another in chunks
of text connected by artless transitions. Some of the writing is
downright odd: Looking into the night sky, he describes ``the stars
like stabs of harmless needles,'' for instance. And take this
clumsy introduction to a fact: ``You may not know, so I'll tell
you: There are no large, ground-dwelling lemurs in Madagascar.''
There are too many formers and latters. Too many Malagasy have
``wet eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tyson navigates this place of astounding taboos and
little-understood natural history with confidence. And he covers an
amazing amount of terrain with a scholar's love of detail.
</P>
<P>
   All that information and it only makes this place more
intriguing. As Tyson himself says, ``As research on Madagascar
continues, the mystery only seems to deepen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
