<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1626 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN23-COX     06-22 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black-white portrayal of two sides at Mount Carmel won't wash
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What were you doing on the day of April 19, 1993?
</P>
<P>
   Probably watching the Branch Davidian compound burn on TV.
</P>
<P>
   This makes you an expert _ and us a nation of them. After all,
we saw fire, and footage of the botched ATF raid in February. We
monitored nightly the stoic blob that was the Davidians'
bullet-riddled home. We all knew what we saw.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd that none of us was called as an expert this week as
the civil trial on the matter began in federal court. Instead, the
court summoned those who actually were there.
</P>
<P>
   This trial will get closer to the truth than our cathode-ray
truth tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in court it only took a few minutes to start shedding
light on pieces that all the world's satellites apparently couldn't
put together for the masses:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Davidians set their own building on fire April 19. It may
not have been ``the'' fire. Or it may have been one of several.
Attorney Mike Caddell essentially conceded in the trial's opening
day that the Davidians set a fire in the gym that adjoined living
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   If an incendiary FBI grenade found outside the compound could
become Page 1 news across the country _ minus any evidence that it
contributed to the blaze _ what does this revelation deserve?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  David Koresh raped little girls. This is not news, thanks to
DNA. But now it's under oath. Surviving Branch Davidian Rita Riddle
was matter-of-fact about it in court: Koresh bedded and in some
cases impregnated minors. Michele Jones gave birth when she was 14.
``Willing'' or not, Michele was raped.
</P>
<P>
   That changes the complexion of the ``summer camp'' Caddell
touts: go-karts, sing-a-longs. At Camp Koresh, the director had his
way with the campers.
</P>
<P>
   Did this justify a guns-blazing battle in which many would die?
No. A thousand times no. But that's not the issue before the court.
(The underlying issue could have, should have been settled, and
peacefully, with Koresh's arrest when out buying guitars or flexing
his Camaro's pistons.)
</P>
<P>
   The issue before the court now is negligence. All said and done,
there is more negligence shared by both sides than there was
smoldering ash.
</P>
<P>
   Did ATF agents fire indiscriminately into the building? To be
honest, that's an odd question to ask about one who is being fired
at. Does this excuse the raid as carried out? Not even close. The
ATF blew its cover. Even under cover, a SWAT approach to a heavily
armed group harboring innocents runs counter to every notion of
hostage rescue.
</P>
<P>
   It may be impossible to figure out who shot first. However, the
first ``shot'' bystanders say they heard came not from a gun but
from a flash-bang grenade, a scary-as-heck diversionary device. If
I were hell-fire loaded for Armageddon and heard such a boom, I'd
probably fire away, deciding it was my day to die.
</P>
<P>
   These are matters suitable for a court. Was the ATF more
interested in showing off noisy toys than making a peaceable
arrest?
</P>
<P>
   As for the ensuing disaster by fire, the court is asked to
consider the rushed conclusion to this terrible episode. The United
States has waited months, even years, to free hostages safely. It
didn't take the same care with Koresh's hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Did it consider the potential that kerosene lanterns toppled
over by armored vehicles might cause an inferno? That a prairie
wind might have made it unsurvivable? Or that a mass suicide might
ensue to give a wounded prophet the last word?
</P>
<P>
   Why the rush? This almost matches up with the shuttle Challenger
disaster in the way officials rushed matters to the launching pad
with bad conditions, without reason, and with disastrous
consequences watched by the world.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom is the proper place for answering these questions,
while the rest of us test our expertise.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the Opinion page editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
