<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD CLOSES IN ON NEW NIEMAN CURATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a series of fits and starts, in part precipitated by the
decision of leading candidate John Carroll to become editor at The
Los Angeles Times, Harvard may be close to naming a new Nieman
Foundation curator to replace retiring Bill Kovach.
</P>
<P>
   While the school has kept a pretty tight lid on the process,
names being bandied about include Roy Guttman, international
affairs writer and Pulitzer prize winner for Newsday, and Robert
Giles, a senior vice president at the Freedom Forum, a foundation
devoted to journalistic principles and free speech. (Both Giles and
Guttman could not be reached Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   Another wrinkle developed recently when some Nieman alumns who
belong to the National Association of Black Journalists (NABJ)
decided to come up with minority candidates for the job. According
to Newsday columnist Sheryl McCarthy, they included Ellis Cose,
columnist and contributing editor at Newsweek, Les Payne, assistant
managing editor at Newsday, and Jerelyn Eddings, director of the
Freedom Forum's African Center.
</P>
<P>
   NABJ president Will Sutton says he sent a letter to Harvard
president Neil Rudenstine indicating, among other things, that the
organization was interested in having a diverse search committee
for a new curator and ``having a diverse pool of candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddings and Payne also could not be reached Wednesday. Cose says
McCarthy contacted him about a month ago, and he gave her
preliminary permission to submit his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what has transpired since then,'' he says. ``I
haven't heard a word.'' He, and everyone else waiting for the puffs
of white smoke to rise out of Harvard Yard, probably won't have to
wait much longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to various theories, the search for a new Boston
magazine editor to replace Craig Unger will focus on (choose any
combination): a) a local editor who really understands urban Boston
so that the magazine can shake its stubborn image as a suburban
service book b) a star editor who can attract talent and, c) a
female editor who could shake up the place.
</P>
<P>
   It's early in the selection process, although owner Herb
Lipson's appearance in Boston this week means things are starting
to heat up. And names of potential editor candidates _ some
logical, some fanciful _ are beginning to surface in media circles.
Here, in no particular order, are some who get mentioned in the
gossip, rumors, and innuendo (including some who may have no
interest) not only for the top job, but for the executive editor
job just vacated by John Strahinich.
</P>
<P>
   From The Boston Globe, associate editor Ande Zellman and
business columnist Steve Bailey. From the Boston Phoenix, editor
Peter Kadzis and Nancy Gaines, who handles the Stuff and
Stuff(at)Night publications. From the Boston magazine family,
contributing editor Mark Leccese and former staffer Stephen
Rodrick, now a contributing editor at George magazine. From Yankee
magazine, managing editor David Gibson. Add in Sandra Shea, an
ex-Phoenix features editor and assistant managing editor at The
Philadelphia Daily News, and Mark Starr, Newsweek's Boston bureau
chief who drew major interest from Boston magazine the last time
the editor's job was open.
</P>
<P>
   Given the preliminary stage of the search, all these candidates
should be considered long shots at this point. The Globe called all
of them Wednesday, and most were not talking. The interesting
question is whether Lipson can pluck a new editor from the
relatively thin ranks of Hub talent or whether he'll end up turning
south to New York or Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raising an issue some in the Beltway have wondered about, the
new issue of Brill's Content has a story quoting New Republic owner
Martin Peretz, saying he would keep the magazine if his good friend
Al Gore won the presidency, but ``might sell it if he's not
elected.'' Peretz told Brill's he was speaking ``very casually,''
but might this foreshadow a change of ownership after more than a
quarter century?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once every four months, I hear a real cockamamie story about
it,'' says a New Republic spokeswoman.``Everything we know suggests
Marty is not going to sell the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We know what she's selling. Number of times the image of Oprah
Winfrey appears in the new (second) issue of her O, The Oprah
Magazine: 12. Number of times it appears if you count the tearout
subscriptions cards: 19.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mark Jurkowitz covers the media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
