<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-DUBUS-2TAKES-A     06-22 1566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-DUBUS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ANDRE DUBUS III SHAKES OFF THE SHADOW OF HIS FAMOUS FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURYPORT, Mass. _ Andre Dubus III is standing in a vacant
lot. It is an unremarkable piece of property, formerly occupied by
a mobile home and plagued by mosquitos that breed in its marshy
core. But the shady 2-acre site, purchased with the proceeds of his
most recent novel, is the first land Dubus has ever owned. After a
lifetime of unpaid-rent notices and sagging porches, it looks to
him like the lush meadows of Tara.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last, the po' kid gets land!'' Dubus shouts triumphantly at
a cluster of pine trees. He strides quickly through the knee-high
grasses, detailing the farmhouse he plans to build for his three
children. There'll be a wraparound porch here. A small home for his
in-laws there. He pauses at a massive gray rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock, I own you!'' he exults. ``I own this rock!''
</P>
<P>
   Spooked by his voice, a rabbit scurries into sight. Dubus turns
in mock pursuit, calling, ``Hey, rabbit! You're my rabbit. Get to
work. Go plant something, rabbit.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a singular moment in a life that has not been easy. After
two decades of laboring in the shadow of his famous father Andre
Dubus, the celebrated short-story writer and essayist whose 1991
book ``Broken Vessels'' was a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize, of
seeing his own works routinely credited to the elder of the two,
and of turning away the middle-aged ladies in their floral hats who
flock to the podium to congratulate him for something he did not
write, Andre Dubus III has come into his own. Last year, Dubus's
novel, ``House of Sand and Fog,'' was named a finalist for the
National Book Award and there is talk of a film based on it. That
his success comes mingled with the pain of his father's death _
Dubus the elder died two days after the book was published in
February 1999 _ somehow does not come as a real surprise to one who
considers hardship life's natural state. Dubus and his brother,
Jeb, built their father's coffin out of pine the night after he
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray to him every day,'' Dubus, 40, said softly. ``And then
I say OK, Dad. OK! You can come back now. I get it you are dead.
You can come back now. OK?????''
</P>
<P>
   Like any man who bears his father's name, much less one who
shares his profession, Dubus's relationship with his father was
flammably complex. Add to a combustible mix the fact that the older
Dubus left home when his son was 10 _ Dubus would marry three times
_ and the stage was set for some classic hostility.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't materialize, much. Dubus is a steadier soul than was
his volcanic father. While he has wrestled with a certain anger at
his father throughout his life, for the most part the two men
remained comrades. They drank beer together. They played poker and
watched the pay-per-view fights. It was the confusion that others
had about their names that grated so. Like when their books were
mingled together on library shelves. Or fan mail intended for the
father routinely landed in the son's mailbox. Or when the online
service Amazon.com credited all books by Andre Dubus to the father.
And it all got a little worse after Dubus was hit by a car in 1986
while helping a pair of stranded motorists and was crippled for
life, thus attaining a near-iconic status that seemed to dwarf the
son all the more.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that when Andre Dubus III got a phone call from a
local reporter last year telling him that ``House of Sand and Fog''
had been named a National Book Award finalist, he suspected a
terrible mistake had been made. Other finalists, he sooned learned,
had been called by the award foundation itself. Why not Dubus?
Obviously, they had intended the award for his father, ``but my
father was dead. So who are you going to call? Not the dead guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The prestigious award was indeed for the son. Award officials
say the phone calls just hadn't caught up with the press release.
Either way, the moment was a telling reflection of Dubus's lifelong
grappling with his weighty name, one that continues even with the
publication of his third book.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a name like Andre Dubus III, you are forever
linked to your father and it's a pain,'' declared Dubus, a muscular
figure with a touch of gray at his longish sideburns. ``I've been
on my own since I was 10. I can't stand my name. I can't stand the
III. People expect the rich boy riding around on Daddy's coattails
when it's just not true. Well . . . I didn't even get the big
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Dubus the father, whose gritty stories of working-class
New England and lyrical essays won a host of awards and are ranked
by some on the top shelf of American letters, was a man's man. He
was a flamboyant ex-Marine with a full beard and a commanding
voice. He was shy. He was a man of unthrottled passions, who kept
one eye on the ladies and another on God. He died at 62, thrice
divorced, the father of six.
</P>
<P>
   The son is moved by equal, if somewhat more tempered, energy. An
actor at heart, he speaks in large, declarative sentences shot
through with expletives and exclamation marks. He is in relentless
motion whether remodeling with the tools that float in the back of
his battered mustard 1984 Toyota or penciling his essays and
fiction in black-and-white notebooks on the unheated third floor of
the family's rented half-house or serving as a male ``flesh prop''
in the modern dance troupe the Exit Dance Theater, of which his
wife, Fontaine, is artistic director. Above all he is a father (two
boys, one girl, no Andres) who is at home a lot, cooking eggplant
parmigiana and reading Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre's lack of fatherhood has made him one of the best dads I
have ever seen,'' declared his mother, Pat Dubus, director of the
battered women's program HAWC in Salem, who lives in nearby
Amesbury. ``He works at it very hard.
</P>
<P>
   Dubus's father moved across the Merrimack River from the
family's home in Haverhill to the Bradford College campus in
Bradford in 1969 and taught there for 18 years, at times secluded
from his children by his writing. But the younger Dubus has used
the flexibility of a writer's schedule to spend as much time with
his children as possible. In years past, Dubus supported himself
doing carpentry but has increasingly relied upon teaching writing
at Emerson and Tufts. Although the $75,000 he has earned from
``House of Sand and Fog,'' has eased the financial pressure a bit,
Dubus is religious about his daily schedule. There's three hours of
writing in the morning. Teaching in the day. A several-mile run or
weight workout in the evening. And in between there's Austin, 7,
Ariadne, 4, and Elias, 3. Two of Dubus's siblings live in Amesbury,
a third is in California, while his two half-sisters by his
father's third wife live in Andover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I hear Andre say all the time is that he wants
the composition of his daily life to be the composition of his
overall life so that each day reflects the larger truths of his
life,'' said his brother Jeb Dubus, 39, a carpenter and painter.
``He thinks very hard about what the next true thing should be. He
wants to find the truth in himself and others.''
</P>
<P>
   And also in his writing. Dubus's first two books _ a collection
of short stories called ``The Cage Keeper and Other Stories,''
published in 1989, and the novel ``Bluesman,'' published in 1993,
are peopled by working-class characters, drifters and dropouts, the
abused and the abject. So, too, ``House of Sand and Fog,'' is a
story of unrooted souls: an immigrant, a recovering drug addict,
and a sheriff's deputy, brought together over a house. Reviewers
who had paid modest attention to Dubus's first books glowed sagely
that the third had to do with the immigrant experience, with
visions of the American Dream. But Dubus says all he wanted was to
get to the truth of the story that lay within him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace Paley said, `We write what we don't know we know,' and I
think that is very true,'' said Dubus, seated in a corner of the
Irish bar The Burren in Somerville. ``I have found when I try to
say something in particular it kills the fiction. It seems to me
the art is surrendering to the self and becoming another. There's
something deeply religious about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubus fought long and hard not to be a writer partly because he
knew it would be hard, but also because the admonitions of his
childhood echoed in his memory. ``We all had to be quiet so Daddy
could write. You know, Daddy is writing,'' Dubus recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Born in California, where his father was stationed as a Marine,
Dubus and his family moved half a dozen times before they headed to
Bradford in 1966 and ended up living in the then-hardscrabble city
of Newburyport and later Haverhill. With his father soon gone and
his mother working nights as a nurse's aide, Dubus and his three
siblings had plenty of opportunity to get into trouble, and they
used it. Picked on by the neighborhood toughs, Dubus, the oldest of
the boys, turned to boxing and gained a reputation as a fighter and
a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``A single mother in poverty is a recipe for disaster,'' Dubus
says of his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-22 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUAR XKR HAS CATS WORKING UNDER THE HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a pair of hood louvers and a mesh grille can
make.
</P>
<P>
   They distinguish the Jaguar XKR from the XK8. But that's really
just eye candy. Add a supercharger, give the rear deck an
insouciant little flip, let it crouch on Z-rated Pirelli tires
mounted on 18-inch wheels, and you've got a much quicker Cat.
</P>
<P>
   Opt for the convertible and you've got a drop-top that will run
with many Porsches and is more fun than any open-air Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   All this and a classic front end that holds the lines and
lineage of the XK series of Jags from the 120 on down. If its lines
are lacking at all, it is only that the flip at the tail could have
been even a bit more insolent, and a flexing bulge to the rear
fenders would have made the crouch look even more intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the XKR swathes you in leather from seats to wheel. The
seats are stiff everywhere your body touches them _ stiff in a
good, supportive way, right up to the high headrests. The front
buckets are adjustable in myriad ways and front legroom is
plentiful. The rear seat, meant for two, is really not suitable on
long trips for adults or even large children. It sits too low and
legroom is cramped at best. Great place for groceries or luggage
when two are on board, however.
</P>
<P>
   The ergonomics are simple with stems on the steering column
controlling wipers and lights and gauges behind the wheel grouped
tightly and easy to read while driving. Controls at center dash _
for audio and climate _ are a bit too small and can be distracting
to use while rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The optional ($2,400) navigation system was a bit disappointing
in that it seemed to lack many of the secondary roads that have
already been added to other systems _ I'm thinking Mercedes, Acura,
and Lincoln, specifically. The generations of navigation systems
are coming and going in rapid succession and it behooves makers of
luxury cars to keep up with the most complex.
</P>
<P>
   Storage is limited _ particularly if the rear seats are
occupied. Bins in the doors are small and the center console bin is
quite shallow. The trunk has moderate space, but two on a trip
using the rear seat and trunk for luggage would be in fine shape.
</P>
<P>
   The view from the driver's seat is classic Jag _ all nose.
</P>
<P>
   So point the nose and go.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, you think Porsche, you think 'Vette.
</P>
<P>
   That's as in silky like a Porsche, muscular like a Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a Porsche, which seems to lower itself to the ground
as you feed its horses, the Jag lifts its nose as it surges
forward. And unlike the 'Vette, it does not push you back in your
seat so much as pin you down and into it.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the surge that sends two tons of convertible (about 300
pounds more than the coupe version) hurtling down the road is a
370-horsepower, supercharged, 4.0-liter V8. Feeding on almost 400
lb.-ft. of torque, it cranks 0-60 in just over 5 seconds. I did not
get the convertible onto an abandoned airport runway, as I did the
coupe, but that car went from 80-100 miles per hour in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   For all its power, it managed to deliver 16 miles per gallon _
about one m.p.g. less than the coupe, maybe owing to the extra and
the aerodynamic drag of the ragtop.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of the convertible top: Its fit, from the inside,
looked amazingly tight. One passenger thought he was in a hardtop,
the fit appeared so seamless. Yet on the road, there was a fairly
constant, low-level wind sound and I could not figure its source.
That is, until I took the Jag through a brushless carwash. At the
upper front corners of both the driver and passenger side windows,
water came flowing in. It makes sense that if water can find its
way through whatever gaps lurked there, so could wind.
</P>
<P>
   But back to driving performance. To handle the XKR's quickness
and speed, the underpinnings best be good. Start with 18-inch
wheels _ they look positively dominant on this low-slung car. Add
those Pirellis and they handle that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   They held on long, carved turns like the rig was on rails. On
snaps through corners they seemed to dig in. In the coupe, I
noticed a slight weight shift to the rear in the tightest of
corners. It was slightly more pronounced in the convertible, which
by nature of being topless is bound to flex a bit more, but even
with the soft top, this is a highly responsive car.
</P>
<P>
   It fights body roll, yaw, squat and dive with _ cute in a Jag,
CATS _ its Computer Active Technology System. CATS monitors speed,
steering wheel position, and brakes and adjusts the stiffness of
the shocks to compensate. Feed CATS with stiff springs, stiff
antiroll bars, traction control, and you've got a scampering,
surefooted Cat.
</P>
<P>
   If I have one major criticism of this car, it's the shifter. The
automatic mode seemed to shift up when it should (though sometimes
earlier than I would like), while the manual option really isn't
that at all (as in a Porsche, for instance) as it seems to hold
back on your decisions, trying to make up its own mind despite what
you may have decided.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The ease of raising and lowering the convertible roof. No
manual latches. One button does it all.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The AM radio. Where is it written that all European cars must
have AM radios with poor reception?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
