<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHIL-GRAMM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS' `ELDER STATESMAN' COMES OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As Gov. George W. Bush dominated the Texas
Republican Party in the late 1990s, Sen. Phil Gramm was moving
toward the status of elder statesman.
</P>
<P>
   And at the GOP's state convention in Houston last weekend, Gramm
embraced the role, delivering the most significant, farsighted
speech of anyone who set foot on the stage during the three-day
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who has two years remaining in current term (his third),
told the 7,400 delegates who attended the final session of the
convention that the GOP must stay true to the core issues working
Texans care about. And opposition to abortion was not on the list.
Free enterprise, individual freedom and responsibility were the
issues that Gramm cited.
</P>
<P>
   The omission was significant; Gramm could have raised the roof
by playing to the party's religious-right activists, who packed the
convention and approved a platform far to the right of most voters
and elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the state party platform is much closer to maverick
South Texas Rep. Ron Paul's worldview than it is to that of Bush,
the likely Republican presidential nominee. Bush, who skipped his
home state convention, wants the national party to have a more
moderate platform while keeping its steadfast opposition to
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm didn't pander in his speech to the convention. Instead, he
issued a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' senior senator took the expected shots at Democrats, but
he said Republicans should learn a lesson from the Texas Democratic
Party's dissipated condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago in Fort Worth, the Democrats met in a phone
booth. They assured us two weeks ago that they were going to be
back,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Democrat Party will not be back because in its current
incarnation it would not be welcome. I say this not to gloat about
the fact that we're the majority party now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a lesson in all this. No political party has a
monopoly on vision or truth. God's not on our side. It's up to us
to be on his side.''
</P>
<P>
   The mention of God was Gramm's biggest applause line despite the
fact it fell short of the ``God's Official Party'' sentiment some
activists embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm continued, ``The Democrats became the minority party in
Texas the old-fashioned way. They earned it. They turned their
backs on working Texans, and Texans turned their back on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And let's take a warning. We're the majority party today
because we're the party of opportunity and freedom. We're the party
of the open door. And as long as we represent those basic values of
free enterprise and individual freedom and responsibility, as long
as we stand for those things, Texans will stand with us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a comment that seemed designed for single-issue activists,
Gramm said, ``If you have views that are important to you, stand up
and speak out on their behalf, but let's keep the Republican Party
focused on those who do the work and pay the taxes and pull the
wagon in this state.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as long as they are our primary concern we will be the
majority party. We will govern. And families in Texas will be
limited only by the size of their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're about. That's why I'm proud to be a
Republican,'' Gramm concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's message should spur social conservatives with a narrow
agenda to reflect on their need for the traditional wing of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm has said he will seek a fourth term in the Senate in 2002,
although his plans are frequently the subject of speculation as the
growing legion of GOP officeholders looks for new heights to
conquer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he runs again, Gramm isn't touring the state
these days in the never-ending campaign style he once embodied. He
presents a more mellow persona than he did before losing his bid
for the Republican presidential nomination in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And his speeches are lot more interesting than they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bruce Davidson can be reached by e-mail at
bdavidson(at)express-news.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
