<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARS THAT WERE STARS START WITH A '67 MUSTANG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The premiere-night party was in full swing as I
stepped off the escalator and spotted her far across the room.
Sheathed in tight silver that clung to every curve, she dominated a
room full of movie stars. Nice set of headlights, great bumpers.
Overhead lights danced off her body with every turn she made.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage was there. So were Angelina Jolie, Robert Duvall,
Jon Voight, Billy Bob Thornton, and many, many older men of
Hollywood who had kindly brought their nieces with them to the
premiere and later, this party, for the new movie ``Gone in 60
Seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   I only had eyes for Eleanor _ a customized 1967 Ford Mustang
GT500 KR _ the choicest of the 50 prime cars that Cage, Jolie,
Duvall, and cohorts are forced by bad guys to steal in this remake
of a 1970s cult film. I approached Eleanor, watched her spin on the
giant turntable, and wondered: Will she go down with the great cars
we've seen in the movies and on television? Will she assume a place
at the top of my list of favorites?
</P>
<P>
   Would she make your list?
</P>
<P>
   Here's mine as I pick through a genre that includes trashy
television such as ``Charlie's Angels'' and ``The Dukes of
Hazard,'' B movies including ``Hot Rod Gang,'' ``Teenage Thunder,''
and ``Chopper Chicks in Zombie Town,'' and some better film fare
and cult classics such as ``Vanishing Point'' and ``Two Lane
Blacktop.''
</P>
<P>
   --The yellow, 1932 Ford 5-window coupe hot rod that Paul Le Matt
drove in ``American Graffiti.'' Classic street-rod looks though
built as a film car. Also loved Harrison Ford's 1955 two-door
Chevrolet. Quiz: Where was this car seen in an earlier movie?
Answer below.
</P>
<P>
   --Steve McQueen's 1968 Mustang GT 390 from the great chase scene
in ``Bullit.''
</P>
<P>
   --And speaking of Mustangs, how about Robert Urich's black 1966
Ford Mustang fastback from the television series ``Spenser for
Hire''?
</P>
<P>
   --And dreadful though the show was, I still remember the Mustang
II Cobra that Charlie's Angels tooled around in.
</P>
<P>
   --``Vanishing Point'' featured what is certainly one of my
favorite film cars, Kowalski's 1970 Challenger R/T Hemi. I have
read that if you watch closely at the end, the filmmakers
substitute a Chevrolet for the Challenger just before it hits the
bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   --``Starsky and Hutch''? That was a 1976 Ford Grand Torino with
a 460 V-8 in which the blow-dried pair pursued the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   --They had beer, cigarettes, a full tank of gas; it was dark out
and they were wearing sunglasses. So Jake and Elwood Blues _ Dan
Akyroyd and John Belushi _ hit the road in their 1974 Dodge Monaco
440. But not to worry. It was a cop car.
</P>
<P>
   --I have to include it because it may be the most famous movie
car ever built _ George Barris's Batmobile. Barris took a 1955
Lincoln Futura _ built in Italy by Ghia to Lincoln-Mercury design _
and turned it into the Batmobile in 1966. Before that, as the
Futura, it had been seen in the movie ``It Started With a Kiss,''
starring Glenn Ford and Debbie Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   --I leave out the ``Back to the Future'' DeLorean because that's
a car that never should have been built in the first place, much
less used as an example of where the automotive future might take
us.
</P>
<P>
   --Remember Mel Gibson's ``Mad Max'' movies? I include his 1973
Australian-built Ford Falcon XB Coupe for the impact it had on
future movies. I'd like a dollar for every movie that followed in
which filmmakers took old cars, sprayed them flat black or primer
gray, and crashed them around in some desert. An entire genre was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Others of note?
</P>
<P>
   The 1969 Charger R/T 440 of ``Dirty Mary and Crazy Larry'';
Banacek's Barris-custom AMC AMX; the more than 100 1969 Dodge
Chargers that were reportedly wrecked in the making of ``The Dukes
of Hazard'' television series; Nash Bridges's 1971 Hemi Barracuda;
the modified 1968 Oldsmobile Toronado that Mannix drove; the 1958
Plymouth Fury, malevolent and furious, from the Stephen King movie
``Christine''; the AMC Pacer from ``Wayne's World,'' so perfect as
Queen blasts from its sound system.
</P>
<P>
   The quiz answer?
</P>
<P>
   On an ``American Graffiti'' Web site _
kathyschrock.net/graffiti/ _ it is reported that the 1955 Chevrolet
driven by Harrison Ford was a composite of two earlier 55s used in
the movie ``Two Lane Blacktop,' which featured James Taylor and
Dennis Wilson roaming America and eventually racing for titles with
Warren Oates in a 1970 GTO.
</P>
<P>
   Add those to my list, too. But on this night, Eleanor stole my
heart _ both Eleanors. I say both, because as I left the party, her
silver image still dancing in my mind, I came across another
Eleanor, the 1973 Mustang Mach I from the original ``Gone in 60
Seconds'' from 1974.
</P>
<P>
   This Eleanor looked forlorn _ battered at the edges, paint job
sloppy and touched up, hanging on like an aging starlet. Hollywood
can use you that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
