<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-DUBUS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     06-22 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-DUBUS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NEWBURYPORT, Mass.: ... his childhood.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dubus set off. He roamed from Bradford College to the University
of Texas in Austin, from which he graduated; to the University of
Wisconsin at Madison, where he studied Marxism for four days; to
Colorado, where he worked as a corrections officer for several
months; to New York, where he studied acting; and finally moved
home and settled on writing. He wrote his first story,
``Blackberries,'' at age 21 to impress a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never chose writing. It chose me,'' said Dubus. ``Because
when I finished the story I had this incredible feeling. All the
rage was gone. It was epiphanous.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was still Andre Jules Dubus and there were two of them.
It was confusing. Which one of them wrote that story about the fat
girl, anyway? people would ask. Perhaps his father helped him out?
The answer was no, ``never even asked the old man what a semicolon
was.'' Seething at the confusion, Dubus would sometimes eye the
trucks of father-and-son teams speeding by and think, ``How sorry I
felt for those (guys), you know, Ralph and Sons. I mean, couldn't
you get your own truck, man???''
</P>
<P>
   Dubus had long wanted to confront his father about his
childhood, ``to tell him that it sucked not having a father
around.'' But just as he was ready to do so, his father was struck
by a car on Interstate 93. His left leg was amputated and his right
so shattered that he needed a wheelchair for the rest of his life.
After the rage, Dubus became a reflective, some say easier, man.
Dubus shaved his father every morning. He mowed his lawn. He and
his brother Jeb built a series of wooden wheelchair ramps around
his father's Haverhill home. And he spotted his father as he
fumblingly learned to lift weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Andre was extremely proud of little Andre,'' recalled Pat
Dubus. ``He was big and muscular, all those things big Andre never
thought he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Andre remembers the last time he saw his father. It was a
snowy winter night a year ago February, a few days before he died,
and Big Andre had invited him over to watch boxer Oscar De La Hoya
on TV. The two men sat late into the night, sipping brandy, as
Dubus told his son stories about his childhood and his own father.
Finally, the son said, ``he kissed me on the lips and I said, `I
love you.' The last thing I saw was him sitting at the top of the
ramp, his profile outlined in the snow.''
</P>
<P>
   The junior members of Ralph and Sons may have had obvious
benefits thanks to their father, but assessing the significance of
being a famous writer's offspring is harder to gauge. The
conventional wisdom in the publishing industry is that writers'
children may get noticed because of their names, but their work
will only survive if it can stand on its merit.
</P>
<P>
   When Alane Salierno Mason, an editor at W.W. Norton, received
the manuscript of ``House of Sand and Fog,'' it had (unbeknownst to
her) been rejected by 22 publishers. Mason, an ardent fan of the
elder Dubus, says she was skeptical but quickly changed her mind as
she read. ``I kept thinking, `this is the real thing,' '' said
Mason.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a long time in coming. Dubus worked on the book for
four years. Three of those years he wrote by pencil sitting in his
car in the Oak Hill cemetery next to the worn headstone of Hylas T.
Wheeler (died in 1866). (``The police don't bother you if you're
writing in the cemetery. They think you're writing to your
grandmother.'') The fourth year he spent typing the 22 notebooks he
had filled. When his father finished reading the book, he called
his son and told him it was ``Shakespearean.''
</P>
<P>
   With reviews trumpeting Dubus's ``elegant writing'' and
``gripping plot,'' ``House of Sand and Fog'' was published on Feb.
22 and Dubus set off on a 11-city tour. Two days into it, he was
standing in the lobby of a San Francisco hotel about to go to a
reading when the phone rang. His father had died of a heart attack.
Dubus headed East and the tour was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed such a tragic irony that when he had finally come
into his own limelight and the spotlight was firmly focused on him,
his father died,'' said Mason. ``He was almost being upstaged at
the most impossible time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubus said he feels no resentment, just the throbbing ache of
his loss. It has been more than a year since his father died and
while Dubus thinks of him daily, life is moving on. His father's
house has been sold. Dubus is making plans for building his own
home and hopes to pour the foundation this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the third floor where he writes, Dubus pulls on a set of
untethered earphones to muffle the sound of his children playing
below and is hard at work on two pieces, although he will not say
about what. The confusion still happens. Not long ago a Seattle
newspaper ran his father's picture alongside a review of ``House of
Sand and Fog.'' But it happens a lot less than it used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like he's made his own name, finally,'' said his
wife, Fontaine. ``You know, he actually meets people who don't know
he had a father who wrote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
