<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BAKER-BOS &LR;      06-22 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAD BAKER'S MAKING HIS WAY THROUGH THE RED SOX FARM SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAGERSTOWN, Md. _ The heat index was over 100 degrees. Another
day, another stop in this bottom rung of steps toward The Show.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Municipal Stadium, only the diehard fans and regulars
are willing to come out to see the Hagerstown Suns battle the
Augusta GreenJackets in a Single A South Atlantic League game.
</P>
<P>
   The GreenJackets arrived early Saturday morning, after an
all-night bus ride from Asheville, N.C. They would stay two more
days before getting back on the bus for the 9 1/2-hour trip back to
Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   It is very much the world of Crash Davis and the other
characters of ``Bull Durham,'' with one exception, said Brad Baker
with a smile and a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no women meeting us when we get off the bus,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, Baker is starting his journey toward Fenway Park. Less
than two months into his first full professional season, everything
is new and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the bus all night coming from Asheville,'' said
Augusta manager Mike Boulanger, who has spent nearly three decades
watching prospects come and go. ``And he comes up to me and he
says, `Man, I love this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Baker is slightly more than a year removed from Pioneer Valley
High School, a regional school in Northfield, Mass. His girlfriend
is back home in Bernardston, finishing up her junior year at
Pioneer Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were the hot couple,'' said Baker with a smile
and a laugh, remembering things like senior proms and homecoming
parades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Baker is the hot pitcher in the Red Sox' minor league
system. The righthander won seven of his first eight decisions, was
the Red Sox' minor league pitcher of the month for April, and made
the South Atlantic All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Heady stuff for someone who seems to be working on a ``How I
Spent My Summer Vacation'' project.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is something different about Baker. Baseball is a
business, a career, and he realizes that.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to pitch Monday night, so he is in his normal
day-before-the-game routine.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the third row behind home plate in a blue sports
shirt, khaki shorts, and sneakers, Baker charts pitches, checking
speed with a radar gun that sits in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go over the hitters anyway,'' he said. ``But just
getting to know what certain hitters like helps.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baker concedes he is still living a fantasy. A year ago, he came
out of Pioneer Valley with a hot reputation and a scholarship offer
to play baseball at the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I was considering,'' said Baker with a smile,
picking through a buffet breakfast at the Tortuga restaurant,
adjacent to the Ramada Inn where the GreenJackets have hunkered
down for the weekend. ``But then the Red Sox picked me.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that more than matter of factly. Pitching in Fenway was
a dream of a boy who grew up in the sheltered environment of
Leyden, Mass., a rural enclave just north of Greenfield. For Baker,
it was more than that. It remains a cocoon of comfort. The center
of town is a Baker enclave, with parents, a brother, a sister,
grandparents, uncles, aunts, and cousins all within shouting
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandparents live right next door,'' said Baker, who
acknowledges that on summer nights when there is nothing else going
on, it is also the heart of Red Sox nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer, when we are home, chances are the game is going
to be on somewhere in the house,'' said Vicki Baker, who has
watched with pride as her oldest son has moved beyond the family
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Baker can recall the day in June last summer when he did receive
the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sitting there with my family and friends fooling
around,'' said Baker. ``I always joked that the Red Sox would pick
me. This time when the phone did ring and it was them, I couldn't'
speak for a minute. I wanted to cry I was so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had selected Baker as a supplemental first-round
pick. Suddenly, everything was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Fagnant had scouted him and we had seen him in a high
school tryout,'' said Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, a
fellow native of Western Massachusetts. ``We try and emphasize
signing kids from New England. He had a good competitive makeup
with a good talent, a good fastball, and a good curveball. He was
also mature for his age.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker has always been mature, dating back to his days in Little
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I first saw him,'' said Pioneer Valley baseball
coach Dex Ross. ``He just stood out, not only for his ability, but
for his poise.'
</P>
<P>
   By the time, Bradley was in eighth grade, he had developed into
a poised pitcher with potential. ``He came up to me and said he
wanted to try out for the varsity,'' said Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said it was more of a whim than anything. ``I just wanted
to see if I could do it,''he said. ``I said if I don't make it,
fine. I just want to see where I stand.''
</P>
<P>
   He made the team, although he concedes he was more awe-struck
than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game I pitched, I walked out on the mound and
thought to myself, `Those guys are men,' '' he said when he looked
at the juniors and seniors in the opposing Mohawk Valley lineup he
beat, 7-4, in his first game.
</P>
<P>
   Baker progressed through high school. By the time he was a
junior, he started to seriously consider a career beyond high
school. ``When he played with the New England Mariners and started
traveling, we thought this could be a possibility,' said Vicki
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than pitching. It was his work ethic. His
attitude. ``If I had any problems with anyone, Brad would the one
to step in and make them toe the line,'' said Ross. ``It's just the
way he was. He knew what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The routine seldom varies. Sleep in, although Baker conceded he
was up before 9 each morning, before his teammates threaten to
boycott him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go out and get a nice dinner, go out to the ballpark, play a
game, and do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that way every day since April. Seldom is there a day
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules say that if you have to travel more than 500 miles,
you get a day off,'' said Baker, who shows no signs of wear.
</P>
<P>
   Baker says he has blinkers on in terms of his career. Sure, he
wants to go to The Show and play in Fenway for the Red Sox. But for
now, he is happy where he is, doing what he is doing. The Red Sox
say he will be in Augusta all season, and probably the
Instructional League in Florida after that.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Baker. He likes where he is, sharing an
apartment with some teammates a long drive away from the first tee
at Augusta National Golf Club, home of The Masters each April.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Southern Division roster in the South
Atlantic All-Star Game, but did not play in Tuesday's game. Halfway
through the season, he has become the GreenJackets' ace. He is 7-2
after 14 starts, with 66 strikeouts and 19 walks in 70 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this game 29 years,'' said Boulanger, ``and he
got the look of the great ones when they were 19. He's wise beyond
his years and he's got unbelievable work habits. All I can say was
that he was raised right.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, whose fastball tops out at 93 miles per hour, has already
started to pick up the nuances of his profession, learning that
throwing strikes is not nearly enough to be successful at the next
level. He has to pick out parts of the strike zone. The thing he
wants to work on in the Instructional League is improving his
pick-off move and holding runners on.
</P>
<P>
   He is diligent in his routine, from charting pitches the day
before the game and making mental notes, to getting in his running
during his other off days.
</P>
<P>
   He is already somewhat of a celebrity because he is on a
baseball card. He says, with amusement, that can be found on eBay,
currently selling for a bargain price of $1.04.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, it's been a constant upward curve. He was bounced
early May 1, getting knocked out after two innings against
Piedmont, the top team in the Northern Division. ``I had trouble
getting the ball down,'' said Baker. ``The manager comes up to me
in the dugout and says you've thrown 50 pitches in two innings,
given up five hits and six runs. I think you can call it a day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't argue with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker didn't argue much that Monday night in Hagerstown when he
was chased after three innings. The Suns got to him for six hits
and three earned runs in what turned into a 15-7 loss by the
GreenJackets. Baker was not charged with the loss because Augusta
came back to tie the game before a ninth-inning explosion gave
Hagerstown the win.
</P>
<P>
   But appearances like that have been rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now this is fun,'' he said. ``There are no negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 19, he is pitching in the Red Sox organization, and he has
a plan and a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't even been homesick,'' said Vicki Baker, who sits
around with the family on nights her son is scheduled to pitch,
trying to find broadcasts of the game on the Internet. ``He doesn't
miss us a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he does. There is still part of Brad Baker that goes back
to Leyden, where he can hunt and fish and share dreams with his
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back there last fall and they said I've changed,'' said
Baker, who concedes that hanging out with 22- and 23-year-olds has
changed some parts of him.
</P>
<P>
   He is smart enough to realize that, at this level, baseball is
an individual sport as well as a team game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is checking their stats, comparing them to other
people in the organization,'' he said. ``That's what how they judge
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker also knows the people making the decisions on Yawkey Way
are making other judgments as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream is to get to Fenway,'' he said, picking up his
clipboard and radar gun and heading to the clubhouse. ``But right
now, there is nothing wrong with this. I don't see any negatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
