<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS &LR;      06-22 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM AND FIELD SET SIGHTS ON WEBB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ The stage was in France, but you didn't need
sub-titles to figure out the plot to last weekend's LPGA Tour stop
in Evian-Les-Bains. The word rivalry is universal and requires no
translation.
</P>
<P>
   When Annika Sorenstam defeated Karrie Webb on the first hole of
a playoff in the Evian Masters it did much more than secure the
biggest payday ($270,000) in women's professional golf; it
established the presence of something far more priceless _
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, personally, it means a lot,'' said Sorenstam, 29,
whose hold on the top spot in women's professional golf began to
crack with the emergence of Se Ri Pak in 1998, then completely fell
apart last year when first Juli Inkster sizzled, then Webb went
into a Tiger Woods-like run to leave competitors in her divots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karrie right now is the No. 1 player, and when you beat
somebody like that, it gives you more confidence. To know that you
can beat her, that means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly since Webb, 25, had been virtually unbeatable for
most of the past year. She put together one of the best seasons in
LPGA Tour history last year _ six wins, including the du Maurier,
her first major _ and stormed out of the gates in 2000 with three
wins in three starts, including the Nabisco Championship.
</P>
<P>
   That remarkable stretch of golf was poorly timed, however, lost
in the glare of Woods's highly publicized six-tournament winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has uncannilly paralleled Tiger's (they both were
Tour rookies in 1996; she has 20 wins and two majors, he has 20
wins and three majors),'' said Webb, ``and I think it has hurt the
LPGA Tour because the attention has been to what he's been doing a
little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Webb prepares for the start of the season's second major,
the McDonald's LPGA Championship at Du Pont Country Club (she could
become the fourth player in LPGA Tour history to win three straight
majors), she doesn't have to look far for something Woods _ at
least in light of his dominating performances at the Memorial
Tournament and US Open _ cannot find. That is, a serious
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   And she's not complaining, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great motivator (to have competition,)'' said
Webb, who has not exactly cooled off since her three-tournament
winning streak came to an end in March with a second at the
Standard Register Ping. Since then she has won once, finished
second twice, fourth once, sixth once, and 13th another time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Juli pushed me all the way for the whole year. Just
to go head-to-head with her, it did motivate me to keep up my
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Different year, same situation for Webb, though the player
pushing her is a familiar foe _ Sorenstam. ``When I play
head-to-head with her,'' said Webb, of the game's former queen from
Sweden, ``I know that I have to play my best golf to beat her.
Neither of us probably played our best golf the last two rounds
last week, but we pushed each other to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's what I'm out here for. I love that
competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Sorenstam, who cringes when reminded of her major
performances since she won that second US Women's Open in 1996 _ in
13 starts she has been Top 10 six times, but painfully has to
accept three missed cuts and the mysterious ``DNP'' at the du
Maurier last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not impatient,'' she said, asked if she has pressed too
hard when these majors rolled around. ``But I think I'm due.''
</P>
<P>
   Most definitely, Sorenstam has proven she is not going to fade
into to the background, as have so many of her counterparts on the
PGA Tour. David Duval, Davis Love, Phil Mickelson &AMP; Co. may have
trouble providing competition for Woods, but Sorenstam, for one, is
quite capable of doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to shake off a 1999 season that was sub-standard for
her (her lowest output of wins _ two _ since her sophomore year on
Tour, 1995), Sorenstam in just her second start of the 2000 season
got a chance at Webb, only to lose in a playoff at the Takefuji
Classic in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Having squandered a one-shot lead entering the final round,
Sorenstam was not as upset about the loss to Webb as she was with
the reason. Her putting. It was the part of her game that started
to push Sorenstam into the shadows cast by Webb, Inkster, and Pak,
though a chance meeting with Dave Stockton Sr. almost a year ago is
starting to pay dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so concerned about how I took the putter back,'' said
Sorenstam. ``He said it doesn't matter. Just strike the ball with
the hand forward. He really turned that around and now I enjoy
practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   The week after her playoff loss to Webb in Hawaii, Sorenstam won
the Welch's/Circle K Championship which earned her enough points to
earn entry into the LPGA Hall of Fame. A nice honor, she said, but
just as pleasing was a victory at the Firstar LPGA Classic in May,
then last Saturday's meeting with Webb at the Royal Golf Club
Evian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karrie beat me in a playoff in Hawaii,'' said Sorenstam, who
was forced into extra holes when Webb birdied the par-5 18th, then
won with a 5-foot eagle putt on that same hole. ``So this was kind
of my revenge a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it temporary satisfaction, because Sorenstam has a more
long-term goal. She wants to be where she once was _ the game's
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be No. 1 in the world, but it's tough to stay
up there. I don't want to be here (a notch or two below Webb), and
now you have to climb back up again. The motivation is there. Now
I'm chasing somebody and know what I want, and I think that's what
drives me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb glances in the rear-view mirror and welcomes the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got beat by an eagle (last week),'' said Webb. ``When it's
against Annika, I know that my most competitive nature comes out as
far as knowing that I'm just going to have to grit this one out all
the way to the end to beat her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
