<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-PROFILE-CHICKEN-     06-22 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-CHICKEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOUL THOUGHTS ABOUND DURING CHICKING FILMING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE WESTBROOK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of molding hundreds of clay chickens, animators
Nick Park and Peter Lord had some foul moods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick and I often expressed unkind thoughts about chickens
during the shoot,'' Lord said of Chicken Run, an animated film he
and Park directed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd had about enough of them. It was a love-hate thing, I
must confess.''
</P>
<P>
   The men even caught themselves craving chicken meals - as
revenge for their painstaking work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ashamed to say,'' Park said, ``I am not a vegetarian.''
</P>
<P>
   But somehow they retained a certain love for the funny fowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally we liked them as creatures,'' Lord said,
``because they're so absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Absurd mirth is just part of the fun of Chicken Run, the
ambitious first feature film from Britain's Aardman, a studio that
specializes in stop-motion animation.
</P>
<P>
   That involves making miniature sets for clay or mechanical
models of characters, which are minutely reshaped and shifted for
each frame of film.
</P>
<P>
   Since a single second requires 24 frames, a week's labor at
Aardman might produce just 100 seconds of film.
</P>
<P>
   Such work has graced movies since the silent era. The giant ape
of 1933's King Kong was stop-motion, as were the goblins of 1993's
The Nightmare Before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, fanciful effects have become dominated by
CGI or computer images.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aardman proudly carries the torch as the world's chief
stop-motion studio.
</P>
<P>
   It is best known for three short films with Wallace &AMP; Gromit, a
cheese-loving British inventor and his smarter dog. Their
adventures in The Wrong Trousers, directed by Park and produced by
Lord, won 1994's Oscar for best animated short.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you haven't seen such films on video or TV, you may have
seen Aardman's work for TV ads, such as Chevron spots with rubbery
talking cars.
</P>
<P>
   Disregarding Wallace &AMP; Gromit for its first feature irked some
fans - especially in England, where the characters have become ``a
national treasure,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Lord ``wanted to start with a new idea and a clean
slate.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, a Wallace &AMP; Gromit movie will be made. Chicken Run is
Aardman's first film in a five-picture deal with DreamWorks, and
Wallace &AMP; Gromit will follow the second, The Tortoise and the Hare.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Chicken Run has rewards along the same lines.
</P>
<P>
   For its tale of a rooster (voice of Mel Gibson) helping Ginger
(voice of Julia Sawalha) and other chickens escape a farm, an
elaborate Pie-O-Matic device evokes Wallace's wacky inventions.
</P>
<P>
   Guard dogs wear spiky collars akin to Preston's in A Close
Shave, and a coal bin is inscribed with ``Feathers was here,'' a
nod to evil penguin Feathers McGraw of The Wrong Trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Run also has Aardman's trademark faces, with bright rows
of teeth in wide maws and remarkably distinctive eyes. (Almost
1,000 eyes were created.)But true fowl form was needed, so some of
the crew of 385 went to a chicken farm to study the real animals.
</P>
<P>
   The farm turned out to be an ideal parallel for a film loosely
based on such World War II movies as Stalag 17 and The Great
Escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken farms really are like prison camps with barracks,''
Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly wouldn't have worked so well if it was The Great
Escape with cows,'' Park added.
</P>
<P>
   For scenes shot from a distance or featuring human characters,
the filmmakers used small-scale chicken models, 3 inches high. For
close-ups and concerted ``acting,'' they used 10-inch models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginger's larger head is barely 2 inches high, yet that makes a
very powerful close-up for the big screen,'' Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 chickens were created.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume they're locked in a vault back in Bristol,'' Lord
said of Aardman's British home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably should give them to members of the crew as
mementos. We don't expect to make a sequel, though I guess that's
been said before.''
</P>
<P>
   Having so many chickens in the same shot was ``maddening,'' Lord
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you had one chicken in the foreground acting her heart
out, you had a dozen in the background who all had to be animated
and kept alive.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least they had a coup for their coop: signing superstar
Gibson, who, it turns out, is a Wallace &AMP; Gromit fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleasantly surprised,'' Park said. ``We kept thinking
he must have better roles to take than a chicken film.''
</P>
<P>
   The men hatched their idea four years ago, and after getting
financing, the production took 18 months, during which Aardman had
much autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great being on the other side of the Atlantic,'' Park
said. ``We weren't dealing so much with men in suits. There was
some tug of war; there always is. But they really wanted us to make
an Aardman movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Park admits using some CGI effects (for rain and a fountain of
gravy).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to embrace new technology,'' he said. ``Some things
are impossible with clay. But the CGI is minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop-motion work has ``a rawness, a reality of performance''
that computers can't convey, Park said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it hasn't gotten any easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very traditional technique, and this is really the only
way to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hesitate to call it a dying breed because we've grown a lot
in the past three years,'' Lord said. ``But generally it's an art
form that's dying out. I think that's because it's difficult.
People want easier, safer solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop-motion is ``risky'' because ``you only get one chance at a
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tweak it, as you do with computers or drawn
animation. If a shot doesn't work - if it's really bad - you have
to go back and do another take.''
</P>
<P>
   But extra work can come from being good, not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We test-screened the film for a live audience, and the
reaction was: more rats,'' Lord said, referring to the chickens'
bartering rat allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in the last few months we extended their scenes, including
a bit at the very end.
</P>
<P>
   ``By chance, I got to do an awful lot of work on the rats,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day, more rats. But at least they weren't chickens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
