<HEADER>
A1640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS &LR;      06-22 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STIFF `ANNA,' STORMY GILBERT AND SULLIVAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE WESTERBROOK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King''
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Foster is a deal maker or breaker in Hollywood, and as
such she helped green-light this ill-advised nonmusical remake of
the fact-based tale from The King and I.
</P>
<P>
   Anna and the King is handsomely produced (with Malaysia subbing
for 1862 Siam), but it suffers due to Foster's woefully stiff
performance as a widowed English teacher trying to expand horizons
for the king's many children.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Chow Yun-Fat is superb as the king. Sporting an
uncannily fresh haircut in each scene, he's commanding without
being pompous - stern without being uncompassionate.
</P>
<P>
   The tale is peppered with palace intrigue and scenes of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially it's a romantic adventure with touches of comedy,
but, sadly for some viewers, no songs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Chow's romantic attraction to Anna is absurd,
nonsensical, unbelievable, etc. etc. But if you can focus on the
charming Chow instead of Foster's pinched fussiness, this Anna can
be rewarding as old-fashioned entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Fox, CC, VHS priced for rental, no DVD, 147 min.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Topsy-Turvy''
</P>
<P>
   You could call this Gilbert and Sullivan Not in Love. You
definitely can call it an entertaining and informative portrait of
the great composing team of Victorian-era British theater.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship became stormy in the mid-1880s when Gilbert's
formulaic plots pushed a restless Sullivan to the edge. But when
Gilbert was inspired by a Japanese exhibit, The Mikado was born.
</P>
<P>
   Topsy-Turvy follows that light opera's creation, offering chunks
of the show as rehearsals or public performances. But mostly it's a
backstage look at art warring with commerce, at great talents beset
by human frailties, and at a special blend of creative juices.
</P>
<P>
   Though knowledge of Gilbert and Sullivan would grease the wheels
of appreciation, it isn't required. Besides, part of the reward can
lie in the learning.
</P>
<P>
   Director Mike Leigh (Secrets &AMP; Lies) again assembles a strong
ensemble for sustained scenes of brilliant acting. Though leisurely
(the film runs 160 minutes), Topsy-Turvy is never less than
absorbing, and its period-piece trappings couldn't be better.
</P>
<P>
   Topsy-Turvy won Oscars for its makeup and costume design, and
was nominated for art direction, along with original screenplay.
The last makes marvelously eloquent use of the English language.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cast, Jim Broadbent is a study in stubborn resolve and
gruff authority as Gilbert, while Allan Corduner is richly assured
as the self-amused, carousing Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Timothy Spall who steals the show as a key actor whose
juicy part is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, we witness creation of either ``grand Japanese
opera'' or ``low burlesque in a small theater on the banks of the
river Thames,'' as Gilbert puts it. The truth lies somewhere in
between, and artistic truth is what this fine film is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, USA, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.95
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo''
</P>
<P>
   Like The Wedding Singer _ whose Adam Sandler executive-produced
this _ Deuce Bigalow offers raucous humor redeemed in part by a
sympathetic antihero.
</P>
<P>
   He's Deuce (Rob Schneider), a pool cleaner who's desperate for
cash. So he claims the clients of a gigolo while house-sitting for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Deuce is no lover; he's a naive slob. But he pleases women by
giving them what they really want, which can be simply an
understanding ear.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that each of his clients, for no logical reason,
suffers from a painfully real ailment.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to poke fun at handicapped people once in a film,
but the jabs here are monotonous and ultimately cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Schneider is a good-hearted guy who isn't trying to exploit
or hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's a romantic, and there's a genuine sweetness in his
budding relationship with Arija Bareikis, who - here we go again -
has a wooden leg.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a strong song score, the film is comically uneven, but
it does offer enough good guffaws to stretch its thin plot over a
tidy 88 minutes. For a Saturday Night Live veteran's vehicle, you
can do worse.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Touchstone, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $32.99
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
