<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARNS OF TERRORIST THREAT AGAINST EMBASSY IN JORDAN  
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The U.S. Embassy in Amman, Jordan, issued an
official warning Thursday morning that it has ``information
concerning terrorist targeting'' of the embassy and ``cannot rule
out'' the possibility of terrorist attacks on U.S. citizens
elsewhere in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   An embassy spokeswoman in Amman said the embassy could not
divulge the nature of the feared attack, the identity of the
suspected terrorists or the source of its information.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the United States has full confidence in the government
of Jordan's demonstrated ability and willingness to address
security threats, the full dimensions of the threat are not
known,'' the embassy said in its statement.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jordan has no recent history of terrorist attacks on
Americans or other foreigners, 28 members of an alleged terror ring
are currently on trial in Amman for what Jordanian prosecutors say
were planned bombings and assaults on local hotels and tourist
sites timed to coincide with Christmas and millennium celebrations
at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. tourists were to have been singled out in those aborted
attacks, prosecutors contend. The defendants are said to have been
enlisted and trained by associates of Osama bin Laden, the Saudi
Islamist militant now based in Afghanistan, who is accused of
responsibility for the 1998 bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``American citizens traveling or residing in Jordan should
exercise prudence, and are urged to review their security practices
and to remain alert to changing situations,'' the embassy said in
its statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``American citizens should avoid large crowds and gatherings,
keep a low profile and vary routes and times of all required
travel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
