<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK HELPS SHAKE SHADOW OF '78 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No sweep. What a relief. We had been getting ready to revisit
some bad history. Here at the Globe, we were preparing one of those
nifty graphics, comparing the Red Sox June swoon of 2000 with the
bloody September of 1978. We live and work in Boston. It is what we
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry to be disappointing all the panic-striken people,'' said
Red Sox pitching guru Joe Kerrigan. ``Now you'll have to reset and
start over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox finally fought back Wednesday night. Trailing by a
run in the bottom of the seventh, they rallied for five runs (on
two hits) against a clueless New York bullpen to win the third game
of this goofy series and put some fire back in the ancient rivalry.
It was New York's turn to be embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Yankees were. Boss Steinbrenner, walking in the
concourse under the stands toward his clubhouse after the game, had
to endure a hoard of Red Sox fans chanting ``Yankees suck.'' It's a
time-tested form of civil disobedience sanctioned by all
card-carrying members of Red Sox Nation. King George must have felt
like Bob Kraft at a Hartford Chamber of Commerce luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the first two games didn't bother us that much,''
said Red Sox right fielder Trot Nixon, who had a triple and a
game-breaking, bases-loaded double. ``It was really important for
us to come back. We're never down-and-out. A lot of teams would
say, `Oh, we've lost a few in a row and this is the Yankees.' But
not us. We've got gamers here.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the Red Sox and Yankees, Nixon is too young to
understand what this game meant to veteran Sox watchers. How could
he know that 22 years ago _ nine months after the birth of Wilton
Veras and almost a full year after the birth of Yankee pitcher Jake
Westbrook _ the Yankees came into Fenway and decimated the Red Sox
in four straight games by an aggregate count of 42-9? A 15-3
trouncing was followed by 13-2, 7-0, and 7-4. The Yankees outhit
the Red Sox, 67-21, and Boston committed 12 errors. Boston never
recovered. Still hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   That is why so many were so nervous Wednesday night when the
locals trailed the hated Yankees in the seventh inning of the third
game of a four-game set. The Yankees had won the series opener,
22-1, to move back into first place Monday. It was the worst Fenway
loss in Red Sox history. Then the Yankees beat Pedro Martinez (New
York's Ron Guidry was Pedro in '78), 3-0. That's 25-1 over two
days. Scary shades of '78.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was more kind. It could not have been a more
perfect night for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN brought its cameras and announcers to record some new
Sox-Yankee history, and Luis Tiant watched from behind the screen.
Several other grizzled vets of the summer of '78 were back at the
site of the massacre. Jim Rice, MVP in that fateful season, sat in
the Red Sox dugout, staring across the way at Yankee coaches Willie
Randolph and Chris Chambliss. Man of infamy Don Zimmer, who has
switched sides, sat at the right hand of Joe Torre. Jerry Remy
barked into a microphone. Peter Gammons, the Boston baseball bard
of '78, prowled the premises in his new capacity as de facto
commissioner. Yankee trainer Gene Monaham and Steinbrenner were
back at Fenway in the same positions they held 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tight game in the early innings and Boston fans sat on
their hands even when the Red Sox took a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees scored their first run in the fifth, Derek
Jeter ended the bases-loaded threat with a harmless fly to center.
Carl Everett caught the ball, then turned and fired it into the
bleachers before returning to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   If you love the Red Sox, you've got to love Everett because of
his hated for all things New York. He believes the Yankees
seriously derailed his professional career and still thinks they
mess with him on everything from room service to ticket orders when
the Red Sox play at Yankee Stadium. Tuesday he refused to be
interviewed by Yankee flagship station MSG.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox led, 4-2, when '78 stuff started happening in the top of
the seventh. With two on and none out, New York pinch hitter Jose
Vizcaino failed on two bunt attempts, then cracked a hard hopper up
the middle. Sox steady second baseman Jeff Frye went to his right,
but he misread the ball and it skipped past him into center for an
error. Sox fans with long memories (and they are legion) might have
been reminded of Lou Piniella's weak pop fly that fell between five
Boston fielders in Game 3 of the '78 Massacre. Second baseman Frank
Duffy took the fall for the fluffy hit that broke open the ballgame
for the Yankees. Now Frye.
</P>
<P>
   New York's three-run seventh gave the Yankees a 5-4 lead. Nabobs
of negativity remembered that 5-4 was the final score of the Bucky
Dent playoff game in '78. Happily, this bad-luck number was taken
off the board when the Sox roared ahead with a five-spot in the
bottom of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was the Yankees who were choking. Relievers Jason
Grimsley and Mike Stanton could not throw strikes. With two out,
Grimsley walked (itals)Manny Alexander(unitals) to load the bases,
then Stanton walked Jose Offerman on four pitches to force home the
go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans came to life with their first ``Yankees suck'' chants
of the night. Then Stanton walked Frye to force home another run.
From the Boston dugout, Pedro openly mocked Stanton. Our only
regret is that ESPN hadn't pinned a microphone on Boss Steinbrenner
for his reaction to the embarrassing exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The game lurched to its ugly finish with the Sox on top.
</P>
<P>
   Breathe deep, Boston fans. Your team has restored calm on Yawkey
Way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
