u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF MIDLIFE, MONKEYS, AND MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an interesting news item: ``A new study suggests that the
fall in estrogen levels associated with the mid-life change can
enhance spatial memory, making it easier to remember where car
keys, handbags, and glasses have been left, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   They could have fooled me. Not that it takes much to fool me
these days, when I seem to spend half my time wandering around
looking for one thing or another, saying to myself, ``Now I know I
left it somewhere around here, it's got to be here someplace, I'm
not losing my mind, am I?''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, I forgot where I'd put a couple of pages of notes for
this column. I suppose that qualifies as irony, although I suppose
I have to put it down to stupidity, now that I can no longer blame
my hormones, or lack of them.
</P>
<P>
   But back to this study, an account of which appears in the
current issue of the journal Behavior Neuroscience. I haven't read
the full report, only a brief story about it in Monday's Daily
Telegraph. But even though I know only the barest facts about the
study, I'd be willing to bet that the research was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's common knowledge that women in midlife experience
one memory crisis after another. The phrase, ``Where did I put
that?'' is never far from their lips. As somebody once said (I
can't remember who it was) the real reason women over 50 can't have
babies is because they'd put them down somewhere and forget where
they left them.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to Dr. Agnes Lacreuse of Emory University,
I suspect she might have reached different conclusions if she'd
based her study on humans instead of monkeys. It's a rare monkey
who misplaces her handbag.
</P>
<P>
   According to the news account, Dr. Lacreuse ``compared the
performance in memory and decision-making tests of six female
monkeys whose ovaries had been removed with monkeys whose ovaries
were intact. Monkeys without ovaries were poor at recognizing
objects, but had far better spatial memories, even performing as
well as young monkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea if glasses or handbags and car keys figured in
the research methodology, or whether other factors that impinge
upon memory were incorporated into the study. For instance, did the
research factor in stress? Because if the monkeys in the study had
jobs, families, and a million other commitments they'd lose their
car keys, ovaries or no ovaries.
</P>
<P>
   Memory failure in midlife isn't strictly sex-linked, so it can't
all be estrogen-related. Last week, Time magazine's cover story
considered the memory crisis afflicting the aging population, male
and female. Middle-aged men, too, are grappling with the great
plague of forgetting. According to the Time story, science knows
very little about how memory works. It used to be thought that it
worked less well as the years passed because the neurons used to
store memories gradually died off and the body was incapable of
replacing them. But recent research indicates that the brain seems
to be capable of making thousands of new neurons a day, in monkeys
at least, and presumably in humans too, although given Dr.
LaCreuse's memory findings, I'm not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   While scientists wrestle with the mystery of memory, the
forgetful are going to great lengths to try to sharpen their aging
brains with vitamin and herbal supplements, memory books and tapes,
memory classes, and mnemonic systems that seem dauntingly
complicated. Toning the memory is hard work. It may be a struggle
against the inevitable. Some researchers think the brain may have a
natural mechanism for retaining what's important and discarding
what's not. That doesn't explain why I keep misplacing my car keys.
I blame it on hormones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
