<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 1815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ADOPTION ISSUE: KEEP IT PRIVATE, BUT NOT SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Keri and Peter T. moved from one suburb to another earlier
this year, they knew their first-grade son and third-grade daughter
might need help adjusting. But the crisis that confronted Keri at
the kitchen table one day after school wasn't at all what they
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess what?'' said Jason. ``At circle, I shared that I was
adopted!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you do something stupid like that?!'' screeched his
sister. ``You had no right to tell! I want it to be a secret!''
</P>
<P>
   Jason was dumbfounded as Rebecca dissolved into angry tears. So
was Keri. Was this the same daughter who, in first grade, had
shared her adoptive status as proudly and openly as Jason?
</P>
<P>
   ``Developmentally, she was at a new place,'' says her mother,
``and I was scrambling to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   As children grow, their view of adoption changes, sometimes
surprising or hurting parents. ``We feel terrific about being an
adoptive family,'' says Keri. ``To think our child might not . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   Most adoptees today grow up knowing the story of their birth and
adoption. Indeed, adoption specialists counsel parents to use
phrases like ``birth mother'' even with an infant, not because a
baby will understand but so the words begin to feel comfortable in
a parent's mouth. In the preschool years, adoptees who have heard
their story will talk about it with the same pride and pleasure
their parents do. Don't fool yourself, though, cautions child
psychiatrist Steven L. Nickman: ``They know the words but not the
meanings behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   That typically happens at age 6 or 7, when a developmental shift
causes them to want more privacy. It can unfold in several ways:
</P>
<P>
   --A need for control. ``Kids start to compartmentalize, to put
boundaries in their lives,'' says psychologist Joyce Maguire Pavao,
a nationally recognized adoption specialist. As a 5-year-old, a
child may be happy to share crayons and markers with siblings and
keep them in a community box in a kitchen drawer. ``At 7, just as
she wants her own drawer with her own supplies, she wants control
over who knows what about her,'' says Pavao. She is director of the
Center for Family Connection in Cambridge, Mass. and New York, and
the author of ``The Family of Adoption'' (Beacon Press).
</P>
<P>
   --An internal struggle. By about 7, any child is increasingly
able to look at an issue from more than one perspective. ``For an
adoptee, this can be the first inkling of a loss: `Most people who
have children parent them. Why didn't my birth mother?' '' says
educator and adoptive parent Joan Clark. That question turns
egocentric _ ``There must have been something wrong with me that my
birth mother didn't parent me'' _ which may lead him to conclude
there is something shameful about him. That, in turn, may lead him
to be more closemouthed, Clark says. She is executive director of
the Open Door Society, an information and support organization for
those touched by adoption.
</P>
<P>
   --A push from peers. Although the information an adoptee shares
about herself may be warmly accepted by classmates in kindergarten
or first grade, sooner or later the classmates see it in a new,
typically threatening, light: Not every child stays with the family
he or she comes to. That's both scary and wonderful to a child
living with biological parents, says Pavao: ``On the one hand, she
worries, `If my best friend's parents gave her away, maybe this
could happen to me, too.' On the other hand, if she's angry with
her mother, she may think, `Maybe I can get a nicer mother!' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's the worry (Nickman says it's more like terror) that prompts
her to ask her best friend, usually out of the blue, ``How come
your first mother didn't keep you?'' Although it's a question meant
to gain information _ ``I don't want this to happen to me, so I
better make sure I don't do what she did'' _ it takes on a mean
edge, says Nickman. ``The speaker wants to distance herself from an
issue that is very threatening: `` `You must have been really bad
for your parents not to keep you; I could never be that bad.' ''
Nickman is director of the adoption-and-custody unit at
Massachusetts General Hospital and in private practice in
Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As a child gets slightly older, new issues surface:
</P>
<P>
   --Between 8 and 11: Most preteens become angry and controlling,
adoptees even more so. ``It's a cover for sadness and hurt,'' says
Pavao, ``a way to counteract the lack of control they had over the
beginning of their lives.'' She tells parents this is the time for
a conversation, hard as it is, about loss and sadness, including
your own, and she suggests we look for openings in the culture to
get at our child's feelings. ``The movie `Stuart Little' or the
(new network TV) show `MYOB' (about a girl's search for birth
parents) may be full of offensive stereotypes, but I see them as
opportunities to get kids talking,'' she says. Openings like these
are much better than direct questions. ``Avoid at all costs, `What
do you think about your adoption?' '' says Pavao. ``The word
`adoption' doesn't cross their minds, but the image of who their
birth mother was is always there.''
</P>
<P>
   --Between 9 and 12: ``All children this age are motivated by the
need to fit in, but adoptees in particular can get very
self-conscious about being different,'' says Clark. She tells of a
sixth-grader who lied in class, saying he was born in Boston
instead of China, in order not to draw attention to himself. Her
advice to parents: If you do hear about this behavior (and most of
the time you won't), don't make a big deal about it. ``Ask why he
lied, express the hope he'll get more comfortable with his
adoption, then leave it at that,'' she says. Even when parents came
to her for advice about dealing with lies their 12-year-old wrote
in his autobiography, Clark's advice didn't change: ``It doesn't
help to make him go to the school and say, `I lied.' What helps is
for him to know it's always better to be truthful, but being
truthful doesn't mean you have to share everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's a difference between privacy and
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   When a stranger stops us and asks ``Where did you get those
adorable Asian children?'' the tendency is to go into great detail.
``It's fine to model to your child that you are proud of being an
adoptive family,'' says Pavao, ``but it's also important to model
that you have boundaries.'' A good response to a stranger: ``We
love to talk about adoption in our family, but we don't talk about
private matters with strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   This is language children can fall back on when peers become
intrusive, which happens even at age 4 or 5 for transracial
adoptees. ``You want him to know some information is private and
that it's up to him to decide what to share,'' says social worker
Carol Rogers of the Newton schools.
</P>
<P>
   She advocates a proactive approach: ``Tell even a 5-year-old,
`Not everyone understands adoption the way we do. Sometimes people
say hurtful things. I'd like to help you so you'll have some
answers and feel prepared.' '' Here are some questions peers
typically ask, with suggested responses:
</P>
<P>
   --How come your real mother didn't keep you? ``My birth mother
knew she couldn't take care of me.'' ``My birth mother chose
adoption for me.'' The use of the term ``birth mother'' helps
children avoid frustrating, circular conversations.
</P>
<P>
   --How come nobody in your family looks like you? ``My birth mom
is in Korea. She looks like me.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helps if an adoptee's repertoire includes a polite
version of ``It's none of your business,'' for instance: ``I'm not
comfortable talking about this'' or ``This is something I talk
about only with my family or my best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Given all that goes on developmentally, it's not surprising that
Rebecca T. wanted to keep her adoption secret at her new school.
Indeed, Pavao says, she wouldn't have been surprised if Rebecca
also had said, ``I wish I had never been adopted!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that a child wishes you weren't her parents, or that
she doesn't love you,'' she says. ``It's a wish for a life that is
less complicated.'' Rather than respond defensively (``What a
terrible thing to say!''), she tells parents to clarify the
statement: ``I bet you're wishing your life was easy, like your
friends' lives, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   While parents always need to respect a child's desire for
privacy, Pavao counsels not making promises you can't keep. Keri at
first, for instance, agreed not to tell anyone in their new town
that Rebecca was adopted. As she made new friends, however, she
began to feel deceitful: ``I told her I would always ask her before
I talked about it to anyone from school, but could she trust me to
talk to friends I trusted?''
</P>
<P>
   The family also talked about how Jason had to have the freedom
to be able to tell his story if he wanted, and that if someone
asked him about his sister, he would say, ``I can talk about me,
but only Rebecca can talk about Rebecca.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed just right to both of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOW YOU CAN HELP
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Should you tell teachers or not? On the pro side, if a teacher
doesn't know and the subject comes up in the classroom, the teacher
might not be as sensitive as he could be; on the other hand,
adoption can become a label that is applied to any problem that
arises. Professionals generally recommend not putting it on a
child's record, and telling a teacher only after you get to know
him/her. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Be knowledgeable about how adoption comes up in the school
curriculum; be sure appropriate language is used (``A birth mother
chose adoption,'' she didn't ``give the baby away''); offer
yourself as a resource; offer alternatives for some projects: a
family orchard instead of a family tree.
</P>
<P>
   --Girls more than boys may share intimate feelings about
adoption with a best friend, only to have the friend turn around
and blab the details. If you see a friendship going bad, try to
start a conversation about it: ``Sometimes when best friends fight,
they share secrets you wish they hadn't . . . '' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Without telling you, a 12- to 15-year-old may use the Internet
to search for birth parents. This is part of the adolescent search
for self, but the Internet can make a reunion possible without a
teenager's really being prepared. Does your teen have all the
information you have? Offer to see if more is available. If they
want to search, be part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ With more family time available now that summer
is here, try this book for good conversation starters: ``201
Questions to Ask Your Parents/Kids,'' by Pepper Schwartz (Avon).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
