<HEADER>
A1646 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MYSTIC VISITOR, A BREAK IN REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has this ever happened to you?
</P>
<P>
   You're going along, minding your own business, when a crack in
the cosmos opens at your feet. Your sense of well-being is
shattered by a betrayal, an unexpected assault, a breach of trust,
an act of deception, a knife in the back, the loss of a dream, the
sudden end of a career.
</P>
<P>
   As you stare into the crevice, reality shifts. The beliefs on
which you base your life tremble. Your sense of security vanishes.
Suddenly, the world darkens and feels dangerous beyond measure.
Suddenly, you mistrust not only those whom you once trusted, but
your own judgment as well. While you're stopped in your tracks,
your mind leaps from one terrible thought to another, like a crazed
monkey trapped in a cage.
</P>
<P>
   How do you repair your sense of the world? In time of need, is
it possible the universe sends messengers to restore your sanity?
</P>
<P>
   The other day, out of the blue, a woman I've never met called to
ask if we'd take a guest into our home. The person she had in mind
was a Mayan from Guatemala, a native healer named Gerado who
traveled the world, sharing his rituals with other indigenous
peoples, keeping the old ways alive. He was in Boston before
leading a trip to a tiny village in Colombia. Oh, yes, he spoke
only Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Fate must have sent him.
</P>
<P>
   On his second night in our home, Gerado asked if I'd like him to
read his stones for me. He laid a colorful hand-woven cloth on our
dining room table and unzipped the bright red-and-yellow bag he
carried with him everywhere. A jumble of stones, beans, and strange
objects spilled out. My husband and I watched him arrange them.
</P>
<P>
   In a line at the top of the cloth, he placed 20 stone objects,
each representing a divine energy in his religion. To his right, he
made a pile of perhaps 25 rocks, each one carefully selected from
some place on earth he had visited. Beside them, he placed a pile
of dried red beans.
</P>
<P>
   As I sat across the table from him, he laid out a handful of
beans in groups of four. Touching each pile, he recited the names
of the 20 divinities and stopped at a certain stone. ``IIQ,'' he
wrote on a sheet of paper. Jack translated the words that followed:
``The wind, which sweeps everything before it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding the cylindrical stone, Gerado reported that I was caught
in a web, or a net, Jack wasn't sure which. I explained that I was
having violent dreams, that I felt possessed by angry obsessive
thoughts. Gerardo made slashing motions. I must sever that net, cut
myself free.
</P>
<P>
   This was the ritual he prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   I was to create a sacred space by setting out four candles: red
to the north, white to the east, blue to the south, yellow to the
west, each exactly an arm's length away. These would create a
circle of safety within which I should seat myself. Gazing at the
red candle, I was to breathe slowly and deeply until I felt
centered. Then I was to make four petitions. After a pause, I was
to visualize each of the petitions as having been granted. All that
was required was to repeat this for 20 straight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``El mente (the mind) must tell el cuerpo (the body), and el
espiritu (the spirit) must tell el corazon (the heart),'' Gerado
said, gesturing. Of course. The way out was to tell myself over and
over what I wanted most deeply, but how should I address my
petitions? Each night I tried a different name for God. None felt
right until I settled on Gerado's choice, IIQ, power of the wind. I
asked to be free of angry thoughts. I asked for peaceful dreams and
headache-free awakenings. I asked to feel more loving and more
loved. I asked for greater balance and pleasure in my life.
</P>
<P>
   I, who could never make myself meditate, have done this ritual
now for eight nights running. I sit in this circle of fire,
listening to Paul Winter's ``Prayer for the Wild Things'' on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Each night my feeling of safety deepens. Each night I reflect
that like a candle, my one precious life is also beautiful, bright,
and brief. Some nights I sense that my pain is shared by all of
creation. Some nights I feel bathed in a healing golden haze. On
others I see the glittering shafts of light from the candles as
swords, cutting me free from my entanglement in ego, judgment, and
rage.
</P>
<P>
   Last night the wind signaled its presence, casting flickering
shadows on my living room walls. If Gerado was sent to guide me,
which I do believe, this is the message he has delivered:
</P>
<P>
   There is a refuge. Seek, and you will find it within.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
