<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      06-22 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN ONE WAY TO FROST A WINDOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I frost a garage window? Or any window, really.
</P>
<P>
   SUE McDERMOTT, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Easiest and quickest is frost Contact paper. It is easily
removed and a new piece applied when the original deteriorates.
There are two paints you can use instead: Zynolite, an aeorol
spray; two coats for more opaqueness. It can be cleaned off with
Windex. The other is frosting paint made by Sapolin, sold in paint
stores.
</P>
<P>
   And here's what G.D. of Melrose, Mass. did: Put up a plastic
ceiling light panel, cut to fit, secured with glazing points.
</P>
<P>
   All these applications go on the inside of the window.
</P>
<P>
   And here is what C.K. of Wilmington, Mass. learned about it, by
accident. He said he was sandblasting something with a hand-held
sandblasting blower when he inadvertently hit a pane of glass.
``Perfect frosting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am buying a 19-year-old house. I was told the kitchen floor
is ceramic tile, but it doesn't look like it to me. It is brick red
and has no shine, and is quite dingy looking, with white marks. Is
it ceramic, and if so,how can I clean it? What if it is ruined?
</P>
<P>
   KATHY DOLAN, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's ceramic tile all right, but not the shiny tile you are
used to. It is quarry tile, unglazed and with no shine, and it
quickly and naturally gets dirty because it is unglazed. It is not
ruined, but it really is not a good choice for a kitchen or most
other floors because it is unglazed. Those white spot are water
marks.
</P>
<P>
   You can clean it, with effort, by rubbing with steel wool soaked
in paint thinner, or steel wool dipped in a strong solution of Spic
and Span and water. Rinse and dry off the tile; the Spic and Span
could cause more white spots. Once you get it clean, you can apply
a coat of Future, which will give it a shine and make it easier to
keep clean. Try the Future in a small area to ensure it will not
make the tile look worse. The handyman got in big trouble some time
ago when he suggested Future on a quarry tile floor and it came out
horribly, probably because it was already finished with something.
Someday, if you get tired of all this work, you can have glazed
tile installed. It is really easy to keep clean; just swipe it with
a wet sponge.
</P>
<P>
   The only place quarry tile should be used, in my opinion, is on
a sunroom floor, where the solar heat will be absorbed by the tile
and stored until it is needed when the sun goes down. Shiny, glazed
tile would reflect this solar heat, making the sunroom less
effective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is wrapped in Typar, and I plan to put up cedar
shingles on the walls. Should I put on cedar breather, a
1/4-inch-thick spacing blanket to allow air to flow between
shingles and sheathing?
</P>
<P>
   ED GERMAIN, Dublin, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. Hm. I have never heard of cedar breather going under wall
shingles, only under cedar shingles on the roof. The air space on
the roof allows the shingles to breathe both up and down, keeping
them from decaying. If the shingles were applied directly to the
sheathing, they would decay long before their time.
</P>
<P>
   While cedar breather is not designed for walls, it is a good
idea, because it will provide an air space, so if water vapor tends
to migrate from inside the house through the sheathing (and that
has happened in many houses in New England) the condensing vapor
will run down the air space before it pushes the paint off the
shingles. If you are putting up white cedar shingles, and don't
paint or treat them in any way, then you don't need the cedars
breather. But it won't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to the cedar breather is 3/8-inch insulation,
which will prevent water vapor from condensing into water. This
also will not hurt if you paint or stain or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to hang a shelf on a plastered wall? Should I
use brackets and Molly bolts, or can I use the stick-on brackets
that claim to hold 10 pounds?
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY COSTELLO, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Use brackets, but I would try to screw them into studs. I am
always wary of stick-ons. One reason: You can use them on paint but
generally they work less well on wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot locate the studs for hanging brackets, you can use
Molly bolts, which will work well in a plastered wall with some
kind of lath behind it. In other words, if the wall is thick enough
to hold the bolts and brackets securely.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another idea that you might find useful: Nail two
boards together into an ``L'' shape, one board to be the shelf and
other to be its support, setting against the wall. Then you can
nail through that bottom board into studs.
</P>
<P>
   Use brackets to bolster the shelf. They can be screwed into the
bottom board and the underside of the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
