<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-DUKE-ART-BOS &LR;      06-22 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DUKE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 TOUR TO SHOW HOW THE DUKES OF NEWPORT LIVED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, Mass. _ Hidden behind a stone wall and a thick screen
of trees at the end of Bellevue Avenue, the legendary street where
summer ``cottages'' stand as monuments to the excess of America's
Gilded Age, lies Rough Point, Doris Duke's baronial mansion.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be as grand as the homes of the Vanderbilts and
Astors, who spent fortunes trying to outmarble, outgild, and
outbuild one another at the turn of the century. But the dark
granite and sandstone structure, which mirrors the craggy,
forbidding coastline below, surely commands the most sweeping views
_ and holds the most secrets.
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, the gates of Rough Point will be thrown open to the
public for the first time. Visitors will be able to explore more
than a dozen rooms in the 30-room, 40,000-square-foot house and its
formal gardens and grounds. They will be able to walk through a
world that Duke, once known as ``the richest girl in the world,''
fiercely guarded before her death at age 80 in 1993. She abhorred
being photographed, traveled under aliases and behind sunglasses,
and always heeded her father's dying words _ ``Trust no one.'' Now
details of her everyday life will be accessible to all.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been altered since the lonely billionairess last
walked out the back door. Even a used piece of soap still nestles
in a dish in an upstairs bathroom. And telephones and televisions
coexist with priceless antiques and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a time capsule,'' says Pieter Roos, executive
director of the Newport Restoration Foundation, which was founded
by Duke in 1968 and owns Rough Point along with 80 other historic
buildings that she restored throughout the city. ``We want to keep
it as the house was lived in during the 1980s. We want people to
know a little bit more about Doris, the contents of her house, and
how she lived in the house. Although little has changed through the
years (Duke's father bought the house in 1922), Doris was
constantly adding to the collection, especially after her mother,
whom she didn't get along with, died in the late 1950s. It was then
that she began decorating in her own taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only relative who claimed anything after Doris's death was
her half nephew, Walker Inman Jr.,'' continues Roos. ``But he just
took a few objects for sentimental reasons _ a Tiffany teapot and
some mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's two beloved dogs, however, remain. They roam the estate's
10 acres but don't have to contend with their mistress's two pet
camels, which in summers slept in a tent on the side lawn and wore
custom-made garlands and pink bridles to their coming-out party.
And the trust-fund pooches no longer sleep in their mistress's
bedroom, with its collection of elaborate mother-of-pearl
furnishings, or lounge in the solarium on humid afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   What awaits visitors in the rooms open to the public is an
astonishing collection of 16th-century tapestries; paintings by
Gainsborough, Anthony Van Dyck, and Renoir; Ming Dynasty garden
seats and large jars; exquisite Isfahan and Savonnerie rugs; ornate
chandeliers; and Flemish and English furniture.
</P>
<P>
   What they will not see are any photographs. Not one framed
picture of Duke's father, the American Tobacco Co. baron James B.
Duke, or of his second wife and Duke's mother, Nanaline Lee Holt
Inman Duke. Not one photo of Duke herself, who was frightfully
self-conscious about her more-than-6-foot height. No shots of her
two husbands _ the second was Dominican playboy Porfirio Rubirosa,
who wedded another fabulously wealthy woman, Barbara Hutton _ nor
of her friends Jacqueline Onassis; Elizabeth Taylor, to whom she
gave $1 million for AIDS research; or Imelda Marcos, a frequent
visitor at Rough Point for whom Duke posted $5 million in bail when
Marcos was accused of helping her husband loot the Philippines.
There are also no pictures of her adopted, then disinherited
daughter, former bellydancer and Hare Krishna member Chandi
Heffner. Nor of Hollywood set designer Eduardo Tirella, whom she
accidentally crushed to death with her car against the gates of
Rough Point in the mid-'60s. Nor her beloved but alcoholic and
semiliterate butler, Bernard Lafferty, whom she named executor of
her $1.5 billion estate shortly before her death.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, one life-size oil painting of Duke herself,
at 12, hanging at the top of the main staircase. Duke reportedly
told people that sitting for the portrait ruined her summer except
for the day the artist, John de Tosta, put the wrong end of the
brush in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Rough Point, which was built in the late 1880s for Frederick
Vanderbilt about the same time William K. Vanderbilt's Marble House
was being built a few blocks away, was only one of Duke's
residences. She owned a 2,700-acre farm in New Jersey; a
Moroccan-style home filled with Islamic art in Hawaii; a penthouse
in Manhattan; and Rudolph Valentino's former home, Falcon Lair, in
the Hollywood Hills.
</P>
<P>
   But she spent more time at Rough Point, from May to Thanksgiving
with trips to New York and Europe in between, than elsewhere,
according to estate manager Philip Mello.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main misconceptions about her is that she threw
large parties. She didn't,'' says Mello. ``She'd have four or six
people for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, an early riser, always had breakfast served in bed. The
dogs would sometimes jump on the bed and spill things, but she
didn't seem to care, according to Mello.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogs were number one around here,'' he says. ``She loved
animals. And, yes, she was very demanding. But she was OK to work
for. It was a job. And we were great chatterers and argued about
everthing _ politics, religion, philosophy. She read several
newspapers each day _ The Wall Street Journal, The New York Times,
and sometimes The Washington Post _ but I never saw her with a
book.''
</P>
<P>
   She swam twice a day, took lunch in the solarium, and composed
pieces on the piano. She'd dress for dinner when she had guests but
wore slacks and blouses most days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Duke played with people,'' says Mello. `` ``She'd act as
if she were on their side, you know, play along with them. Then
she'd look away and roll her eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Two needlepoint pillows in the cozy, comparatively small morning
room speak volumes about Duke. One pillow says ``Familiarity
breeds''; the other, ``My decision is maybe and that's final.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its name, the morning room is where Duke brought guests
after dinner for drinks and conversation before a huge fire. The
room, with its comfortable modern couches, is home to Duke's last
major purchase, in 1985 _ a 17th-century Dutch marine painting by
Jan Van DeCapelle. Other treasures include a portrait by Joshua
Reynolds and a set of Dutch inlaid chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's interest in textiles is evident in the dining room, where
the walls are covered with 16th-century and 18th-century Flemish
and French tapestries. Ornate plaster ceilings look down on Van
Dyck's 17th-century portrait of Charles II, two John Hoppner
portraits, a pair of Della Robbia glazed-earthenware fruit baskets,
and a 25-by-25-foot 19th-century rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke had very good taste; she was very particular about
everything and she was constantly tweaking her collection,'' says
Roos, leading visitors into the great hall. ``The hall with its
monumental scale is similar to the austere halls of British homes;
it definitely has a baronial feel to it. The matched set of
tapestries are from Brussels and were woven around 1510. The
collection of Ming garden seats and jars is outstanding, and the
paintings are by Gainsborough, Van Dyck, and Ferdinand Bol. The
carpet is a 17th-century Isfahan and the three silver-plate
chandeliers are early-1700s French.''
</P>
<P>
   The other rooms on the first floor include the very French
yellow room, with its 16th-century Florentine screens and Louis XVI
furniture. The ballroom-size music room has breathtaking
hand-painted 18th-century Chinese wallpaper with a peony-and-cherry
motif, rock-crystal chandeliers that shine down on a vast
Savonnerie carpet, and a set of 1780 French chairs with their
original upholstery. This room and the yellow room have
18th-century parquet floors that originally graced a chateau near
Versailles and spent time on the floor of her Hawaii mansion before
being brought to Newport.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is Duke's favorite spot _ the solarium, with its three
glass walls overlooking the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a southwest breeze here, which the other houses
on Bellevue don't get,'' says Roos, ``mainly because this house
blocks them from that breeze. So the house is never unbearably hot.
And the mirror over there is broken because during Hurricane Bob,
the camels were brought inside and hay spread on the floor. It
seems one of the camels, Princess, whipped her head around and
broke the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   The two rooms open to the public upstairs are Duke's purple
bedroom, filled with mother-of-pearl furniture from the 1820s, and
her music room. There's a collection of small trophies in her desk
in the bedroom, honoring her prowess at the tango, Monday tennis,
and sandcastles. Duke was an accomplished pianist who practiced
twice daily, had a passion for jazz and gospel music, and studied
modern dance with Martha Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Duke's home can step back in time but can also catch
a glimpse of the future and perhaps the beginnings of a new Gilded
Age. But this time around, it could be called the Golden Chip Age,
since the money pouring into Newport is coming from dot-coms, not
steel, coal, railroads, and tobacco. Over the hedge from Rough
Point, a waterfront house is undergoing a reported $6 million in
renovations. Its owner is from Chicago. It will be his summer home,
or cottage. Just like a hundred years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tickets and shuttle bus at Newport Visitors' Center, 23 America's
Cup Avenue. Telephone: 401-845-9130. Tours daily at 10 a.m., 12:30
p.m., and 3:00 p.m. Cost is $25 for adults, $22 for seniors and
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
