<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COM-PLATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKER ROLLS OUT A DOT-COM LICENSE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A Silicon Valley assemblyman who is running
for Congress has introduced a bill to create a new ``dot-com''
license plate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which the Transportation Committee of the state
Senate approved this week, is sponsored by the computer industry as
a way to raise money to buy computers for needy public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Motor Vehicles and the California Highway
Patrol would design the plates. Right now, the only requirement is
that ``.com'' would be placed somewhere on the right side of the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Jim Cunneen, R-Cupertino, said the new plates are
``a perfect way of honoring the contributions of the industry''
while raising money to ``bridge the digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   California is already spending plenty of money on school
computers. The state budget for school technology and Internet
access will soon reach $1 billion. If 10,000 dot-com license plates
are sold, another $500,000 would be raised for school computers and
technology, minus the DMV's costs for making the plates.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the plates came from Namezero.com, a privately held
Los Gatos company with about 15 employees. The year-old company
registers domain names on the Internet for free, and it promised to
get 10,000 people to sign up for the new dot-com plates.
</P>
<P>
   In his press release on the bill, Cunneen included this
promotional plug from Namezero.com President Bruce Keiser: ``As the
only internet domain name registrar to provide fee .com domain
names ... Namezero believes that a .com license plate is a great
way to extend an Internet identity.''
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, the Senate Transportation Committee agreed
to stop approving new specialty license plates because the state
was making so many different varieties. The CHP complains because
its officers have trouble identifying the plates.
</P>
<P>
   But the Legislature makes exceptions. The most recent was a
plate honoring Ronald Reagan, the former governor and president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-EDITORIAL-PRISONS-COX     06-22 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PRISONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Reforms needed to avoid costly building spree
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, the Texas prison system has moved from
crisis to crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Unless action is taken quickly, the free world's largest prison
system will be hit with another crisis that again will hit Texas
taxpayers in the pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal punishment in Texas has come a long way from the
15-prison, 18,000-inmate prison system in 1979 to today's
110-prison, 150,000-inmate system.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' 1979 prison system was placed under federal control after
evidence emerged that prisoners were treated unconstitutionally.
</P>
<P>
   The next crisis occurred when lawmakers kept increasing
penalties in an effort to crack down on crime. Texas prisons became
so overcrowded that the backlog filled up county jails across the
state and forced the early release of violent criminals to make
room for the incoming prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1987, Texas had a mandatory release program for violent
criminals after they collected sufficient ``good time'' credits. It
was a stupid requirement even if it did relieve overcrowding. The
last prisoners society wants back on the streets before their
sentences are fully served are violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Overcrowding finally convinced the Legislature to ask Texans for
approval to launch a multi-billion-dollar prison building program.
Texas voters gave the lawmakers the go-ahead that resulted in a
prison system reportedly larger than those of any state and any
nation except China.
</P>
<P>
   Texas incarcerates 739 people for every 100,000 residents
compared to 530 for every 100,000 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, where the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles was
releasing nearly 80 percent of inmates when they first became
eligible for parole in 1994, only 20 percent are now being
released.
</P>
<P>
   Now the free world's largest prison system is again about to
overflow. Texans can either undertake another prison building binge
or find a better way punish criminals. The better way is best.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the 18-member parole board should begin releasing
non-violent prisoners when they become eligible for parole.
Thousands of prisoners are locked away for using drugs, not selling
drugs. Other prisoners have been sentenced due to their addiction
to alcohol. These addicted, non-violent prisoners should be
considered for release when they become eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, prosecutors and judges should develop alternative
sentencing for non-violent crimes. Alternative sentencing should
include participation in community service projects as well as
restitution to victims.
</P>
<P>
   More needs to be done to utilize the state jail program that
offers education and drug treatment to non-violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Prisons should do more to protect prisoners and break up prison
gangs that indoctrinate prisoners with racial hatred and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Parole oversight should be beefed up.
</P>
<P>
   More should be done to prevent crime by investing in children
who need to stay in school and obtain the education required to
become responsible, tax-paying adults.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1343EDT &QL; 
