<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1659 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     06-22 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME TEST SCORES ARE BETTER LEFT UNKNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a recent staff meeting a colleague of mine at the newspaper
announced that he had been accepted into Mensa, the society of
people with high IQs.
</P>
<P>
   It was an awkward moment, I can assure you. Five seconds
earlier, the man had been just like the rest of us: a burned-out
drudge working out of a dim cubicle, wondering where it all went
wrong. Then, in an instant, he was transformed into someone else:
someone finer, someone sharper, someone from whom we could possibly
borrow money.
</P>
<P>
   As I fought off the urge to run my thumb along the throbbing
vein in his bulging forehead, I wondered: Are these intelligence
tests really trustworthy? I mean, if he is so smart, what is he
doing working here?
</P>
<P>
   Also, does this man now feel pressured by higher expectations?
When he writes his next hurricane story, will he not feel compelled
to use more big words or perhaps preface his story with a quote
from Shakespeare? (One possibility: ``Blow, winds, and crack your
cheeks! Rage! Blow!'')
</P>
<P>
   Is life not easier for people like me, for whom the $100
questions on Who Wants to be a Millionaire are an intellectual
challenge?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, but I do think this testing thing has gotten out
of hand. One could argue that there are good reasons to test
students and teachers and possibly even over-achieving weather
reporters, but do we really need an intelligence test for dogs?
</P>
<P>
   There is one, you know. It's found in the book ``The
Intelligence of Dogs: A Guide to the Thoughts, Emotions and Inner
Lives of Our Canine Companions'' by Stanley Coren (Bantam, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Coren, there are three types of dog
intelligence: Adaptive intelligence (learning and problem-solving
ability), instinctive intelligence (specific to individual animal
and measured by canine IQ test) and working/obedience intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   As I write this, my pug dog, Buster, is standing by the
sliding-glass door, barking insanely at what must seem to him a
highly threatening oxygen molecule. Buster is similarly affected by
TV doorbells. I would say that this falls under the category of
``instinctive intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   When I take Buster outside, I encourage him to chase rabbits
because I feel that rabbits generally lead a pretty dull existence
and deserve a good laugh. When I point to a rabbit, or throw him on
top of a rabbit, he invariably tears off in the opposite direction.
I would call this ``working/obedience intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   When given a choice between whatever we are eating (steak) and
whatever he is eating (hard, dry, cracker-like substance from a
50-pound bag), Buster will always choose the former. This is an
example of ``adaptive intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to my surprise, Dr. Coren ranked pugs 57th in intelligence
out of 79 breeds. (Border collies were the smartest and Afghan
hounds the stupidest.) Apparently unaware of Buster's unwavering
commitment to protecting his home against uninvited oxygen
molecules and TV doorbells, Dr. Coren also ranked pugs among the
dogs that are ``least likely to succeed at watchdog barking.''
</P>
<P>
   Buster is asleep now, but I can tell that this low intelligence
ranking has him deeply troubled. (His snoring seems more melancholy
and despairing.) Perhaps his self-esteem will be harmed to the
point that he will no longer jump on the furniture or accept a
doggie treat when I wave it under his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but not likely.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
