<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1708 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOSSES CAN LEARN A THING OR TWO FROM TIGER WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Suppose you have an employee who is nearly as
talented in your field as Tiger Woods is in his. Could you bring
out the best in that worker?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Sorry to say, but most bosses are better suited to
managing mediocrity than promoting talent.
</P>
<P>
   To understand why, let's go back three years. At age 21, Woods
had just won the Masters by 12 strokes in arguably the greatest
golfing accomplishment of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose golfers were managed like white-collar workers, and
you were in charge of supervising Woods and 19 other golfers _ some
good, some mediocre and a couple downright lousy. Be honest now:
How much time would you end up spending with Woods?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, probably.
</P>
<P>
   After all, you'd say to yourself, he's already a success. What
more can he do?
</P>
<P>
   As Marcus Buckingham and Curt Coffman point out in their great
book, ``First, Break All the Rules,'' typical bosses spend most of
their time concentrating on inferior workers, trying to bring them
up to some semblance of mediocrity. Only the best bosses realize
that they will get more by concentrating on the top people, because
their potential is almost unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, a mediocre worker can turn into a lovelier shade of
mediocre. But a superstar can change the world.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was smart and didn't surround himself with a bunch of
``yes'' people, Woods realized after he won the Masters that his
game still needed to improve substantially if he wanted to achieve
his goal of being the best golfer in history. He worked with a
coach for hours and hours to change his swing, and gradually became
the dominant golfer in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Woods topped himself last weekend, winning the U.S. Open by 15
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   One great scene on Sunday was when Woods looked fired up after
sinking a 12-foot putt to save par on the 16th hole. He was already
miles ahead of the competition, but making that putt helped him
finish the final round without making a bogey, one of his goals.
</P>
<P>
   That's how motivated Woods is. Certainly he makes a ton of
money, but he also challenges himself even when money and
competition are not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   All star workers have some sort of internal motivation. As the
Houston Rockets fought back to win their second consecutive
National Basketball Association championship in 1995, Coach Rudy
Tomjanovich came up with a rallying cry: ``Never underestimate the
heart of a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boss, you have to figure out what motivates your stars and
not automatically assume it is the same thing that motivates you.
Maybe they don't care about money or prestige or corner offices;
maybe they would prefer to be recognized in front of their family
or peers, or get more time off, or have an executive assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Don't limit your thinking or theirs. If your quota for
salespeople is $80,000 and someone gets to $120,000, it's easy to
just give her a plaque and be thankful. But maybe she could get to
$300,000, with the right encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   God knows she makes your job easy enough, but what can you do to
make her job easier? Could an assistant handle her paperwork so she
could spend more time selling? Could you pay for a nanny so she
wouldn't worry so much about child care? Could you excuse her from
mundane meetings or send her to a prestigious training program in
Paris?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know what you can do, here is a wild and crazy
thought: Ask.
</P>
<P>
   Don't use this as an excuse to micromanage, but even the
greatest workers can use help. Woods needs coaches to help with his
swing, and Michael Jordan certainly recognized the importance of
Coach Phil Jackson. The best bosses help great talents achieve
their potential.
</P>
<P>
   Inferior bosses say that they can't play favorites. That is
certainly true, if all your workers are equal. But if some are
giving you extra effort or extra production, you owe it to
yourself, your employee and your company to help your best workers
become even better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without help, spectacular workers can fade away. Orson Welles
was 25 when he made ``Citizen Kane.'' That was certainly a
wonderful achievement, but you have to wonder if Welles could have
topped himself if he had found the right encouragement. A lot of
directors get better as they gain experience.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest boxer of the 20th century was Muhammad Ali, but
Mike Tyson had the potential to be even better. He was a juvenile
delinquent, but he hooked up with a father figure and coach in Cus
D'Amato, who help him develop as both a boxer and a human being.
But when D'Amato died, no one really took his place, and Tyson
eventually self-destructed.
</P>
<P>
   Keep this in mind, though: Tyson was far better in his sport at
age 20 than Woods was. By the time he turned 21, he had millions of
dollars and a heavyweight championship, but his coach had already
passed away.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you're lucky enough to hire a great talent,
remember Tiger Woods. And never forget Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
