   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-DANCERS (New York) _ What makes a dancer stand out from the
crowd? A dazzling technique helps, though multiple turns and high
jumps are par for the course today. Beautiful bodies and appealing
faces draw the eye. But stages are full of performers who fit the
prescibed notion of physical perfection. There are so many dancers
to claim the heart and mind and eye, yet only a few do each season.
Ease, physical eloquence and quiet daring are common denominators
among seven outstanding new or unfamiliar performers who will dance
this weekend in New York, as well as the three former Alvin Ailey
dancers whose new modern-dance troupe has made its debut this week
at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in the Berkshires. All occupy
the stage with a look of unassuming ownership. Each catches the eye
with something more than skill or physical beauty, an often elusive
quality that remains in the mind, like a flash of bright unexpected
color on a bustling city street, long after the curtain falls. By
Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-THEATERS (Undated) _ When you want to orient yourself in a
new city or to see a familiar one in a new way, it is useful to
have an obsession. Over the last two years I revisited three cities
I know well: Boston, Buffalo and Philadelphia. During those visits
I looked at them from the idiosyncratic standpoint of what had
become of their historic theaters, I also made a trip to Washington
to visit the nation's most famous and sacred historic theater,
Ford's; actually, it is a facsimile, as the original structure in
which Abraham Lincoln was assassinated was torn down. In the course
of these trips I learned much about the dynamics and histories of
the cities themselves. I saw the tremendous energy and sometimes
heartbreaking compromises necessary to maintain a performing-arts
center today. And I learned how intensely it is possible to love a
theater and to believe in a city, so much so that some people may
devote most of their adult lives, sometimes as volunteers, to
keeping an old theater alive. By Mindy Aloff.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-WARHOL-GWATHMEY (Philadelphia) _ Here's a stretch: one of
the more improbable pairings in recent exhibition history. It puts
the work of Andy Warhol (1928-1987) with that of the social realist
painter Robert Gwathmey (1903-1988), the idea being that the
under-appreciated Gwathmey and the canonized Warhol shared an
outlook as ``social commentators'' on American life. At the
Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts, each is given a separate
show, ``Robert Gwathmey: Master Painter'' and ``Andy Warhol: Social
Observer.'' But each is meant to complement the other in this
ill-conceived double feature. The Academy's aim in mounting the two
together, it says, is nothing less than reshaping conceptions of
postwar American art. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-LOS-ANGELES (Los Angeles) _ More than anywhere else in
America, Los Angeles has been defined by popular culture _ that is,
by the entertainment industry. But they are mere fragments of
reality, snippets of grainy black-and-white or gaudy Technicolor,
and splicing them together into an accurate picture is a tall
order. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
