<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1734 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-LENO-BOS &LR;      06-22 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-LENO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENO'S INNER CHILD INDULGES IN RARE CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ The man cannot contain the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leno opens the door to a 1956 Chrysler Imperial to show off
a really unusual automotive option _ a record player built into the
dashboard _ and the boy within him jumps out. Blue eyes sparkling,
he bursts into hearty song: ``Davy, Davy Crockett, king of the wild
frontier . . .''
</P>
<P>
   In their day, the records that fit the dashboard phonograph
could be purchased only from Chrysler, and Leno has been able to
acquire only two: the Davy Crockett theme song and music from the
movie ``The Pajama Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it Jay's Playhouse, two enormous garages near the airport
here that hold his fabulous and eclectic gathering of things
automotive: classic cars, souped-up cars, muscle cars, sports cars,
old race cars, motorcycles, petrobilia, automobilia, toys, posters,
badges.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a public place. Here one finds the private side of the
public man. When he is not on the set of the ``Tonight'' show, or
doing a standup routine in Las Vegas, this is where he likes to
hang out. He comes here almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go out to eat. I don't go out to clubs,'' says Leno,
dressed in his perpetual private-time outfit of denim shirt and
jeans. ``This is what I like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   David Brownell, former editor of Hemmings Motor News magazine,
the bible for auto fanatics, says Leno is doing what he likes quite
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay's got some of the best examples of desirable cars and
motorcycles in the country,'' says Brownell, and they range from
classically restored or preserved to mechanically unique.
</P>
<P>
   Leno walks to a 1934 Rolls-Royce Phantom II, its chassis fitted
with a wood-and-metal body that looks like a giant open cockpit
racer. It is powered by a 27-liter Merlin aircraft engine that
cranks out 1,000 horsepower. It is a car, he says, that ``starts to
walk around on you'' once you get it up over 120 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, that's fast,'' he says of the car. It will not be the
last time he uses the phrase in a tour of his immaculate garages.
</P>
<P>
   This is where he comes to dwell in a quiet place, paradoxically
finding relaxation amid the thundering and thumping engines and the
metal-on-metal cacophony of a garage.
</P>
<P>
   He comes to tinker and tune, to talk technology with some of the
specialists with whom he has surrounded himself to help maintain
and preserve rare cars, and to relive childhood fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all the cars I used to read about when I was a
kid,'' he says, acknowledging that he never dreamed he would
someday be able to own them. But through talent, hard work, and
good fortune, they are his.
</P>
<P>
   They are the tangible dreams of a boy who grew up in Andover and
who once worked prepping new autos at Foreign Motors on
Commonwealth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   He's owned cars and motorcycles since his teens when, he says,
he worked at a McDonald's and at the garage while other kids played
sports. He sometimes owned several vehicles at a time, even then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had the stuff,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he has much more stuff. But he doesn't call what his
garages house a collection. He will not call himself a collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of pick them up here and there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And don't ask him how many cars and motorcycles he has, or what
they are worth. Because this is not about numbers to Leno.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, people would come up to you and ask, `What is
it?' '' when you had a special car, Leno complains. ``Now they ask,
`How much is it worth?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Leno's penchant for autos is well known, particularly in the
world of aficionados. Some people, he says, have tried to use his
name, implying that he was interested in what they were selling, to
drive up their prices to other buyers. He has heard reports of Leno
sightings at auctions, hat pulled down, jacket collar rolled up, as
he quietly bid up the prices.
</P>
<P>
   But he buys mostly through clubs and collectors, he says. He is
not out to drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
   To Leno, cars are about fun and function: everything he owns, he
drives. Or they can be about pedigree, as in a Stutz racer with a
proven track record, or about mechanical challenge, such as fitting
a V-12 Jaguar engine into an XKE that originally had a V-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all interests me,'' he says. ``I like stuff that's
technologically interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   He walks to the side of a 1925 Brough Superior motorcycle that
had been raced on the Isle of Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the Vincent Black Shadows before there were Vincent
Black Shadows,'' he says, referring to the legendary British
motorcycle of the 1950s that came with instructions to shift into
high gear at 110 miles per hour. He's got several Broughs, a whole
parcel of Vincents _ including an ugly and rare shrouded Vincent
Black Knight _ and other motorcycles: Harley-Davidson, Triumph,
Ducati, Agusta, and Henderson among them.
</P>
<P>
   The car collection is impressively eclectic: Bugati, Duesenberg,
Stutz, Jaguar, Bentley, Stanley, Baker Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Perched among the Duesenbergs is an aerodynamic Duesenberg
coupe, its flowing lines in sharp contrast to the solid,
rectangular look of most of its mates. In the old days, when you
bought a Duesenberg, you bought a ready-to-roll chassis. You went
to a coachmaker for the body. The scion of the Eli Lilly drug
empire had this aerodynamic coupe constructed; it is a huge
automobile, though it only seats two people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing it was good for was running over poor people,''
Leno laughs.
</P>
<P>
   There is a 1924 Bentley whose 3-liter engine has been replaced
with an 8-liter. It has had twin turbochargers added and is now a
500-horsepower charger, faster than Leno's Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going that fast in something 80 years old,'' he says in
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   There's a 1957 Buick Roadmaster, a 1955 Packard Caribbean
looking like a Creamsicle, and a 1966 Dodge Coronet with a 426 Hemi
engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't stop, it doesn't corner,'' he says of the Dodge,
and you need not finish the next sentence for him: ``But, geez,
it's fast.''
</P>
<P>
   His ``offices'' at the garages are more like playrooms: couches,
chairs, pictures, posters, collectibles, and toys everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He stops to show off a toy. It is a re-creation of a drag-strip
staging area. A Plymouth Barracuda sits at the light. Leno flips a
switch. An announcer introduces the car and driver and the crowd
cheers. Suddenly, the body of the Barracuda rises, revealing the
driver and the engine, which spits what looks like flames from its
exhausts. The body lowers, the staging lights run through to green,
the engine roars, and the 'Cuda rises in a wheelie.
</P>
<P>
   Leno cackles, seemingly as happy with this toy as he is with
each car, each motorcycle, in his garages.
</P>
<P>
   Back out on the garage floor _ a Vegas appearance is coming up
in hours _ he looks around a final time during this tour of his
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like Mia Farrow,'' he says of the actress who has adopted
many children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I like. I like saving cars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
