<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUAR XKR HAS CATS WORKING UNDER THE HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a pair of hood louvers and a mesh grille can
make.
</P>
<P>
   They distinguish the Jaguar XKR from the XK8. But that's really
just eye candy. Add a supercharger, give the rear deck an
insouciant little flip, let it crouch on Z-rated Pirelli tires
mounted on 18-inch wheels, and you've got a much quicker Cat.
</P>
<P>
   Opt for the convertible and you've got a drop-top that will run
with many Porsches and is more fun than any open-air Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   All this and a classic front end that holds the lines and
lineage of the XK series of Jags from the 120 on down. If its lines
are lacking at all, it is only that the flip at the tail could have
been even a bit more insolent, and a flexing bulge to the rear
fenders would have made the crouch look even more intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the XKR swathes you in leather from seats to wheel. The
seats are stiff everywhere your body touches them _ stiff in a
good, supportive way, right up to the high headrests. The front
buckets are adjustable in myriad ways and front legroom is
plentiful. The rear seat, meant for two, is really not suitable on
long trips for adults or even large children. It sits too low and
legroom is cramped at best. Great place for groceries or luggage
when two are on board, however.
</P>
<P>
   The ergonomics are simple with stems on the steering column
controlling wipers and lights and gauges behind the wheel grouped
tightly and easy to read while driving. Controls at center dash _
for audio and climate _ are a bit too small and can be distracting
to use while rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The optional ($2,400) navigation system was a bit disappointing
in that it seemed to lack many of the secondary roads that have
already been added to other systems _ I'm thinking Mercedes, Acura,
and Lincoln, specifically. The generations of navigation systems
are coming and going in rapid succession and it behooves makers of
luxury cars to keep up with the most complex.
</P>
<P>
   Storage is limited _ particularly if the rear seats are
occupied. Bins in the doors are small and the center console bin is
quite shallow. The trunk has moderate space, but two on a trip
using the rear seat and trunk for luggage would be in fine shape.
</P>
<P>
   The view from the driver's seat is classic Jag _ all nose.
</P>
<P>
   So point the nose and go.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, you think Porsche, you think 'Vette.
</P>
<P>
   That's as in silky like a Porsche, muscular like a Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a Porsche, which seems to lower itself to the ground
as you feed its horses, the Jag lifts its nose as it surges
forward. And unlike the 'Vette, it does not push you back in your
seat so much as pin you down and into it.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the surge that sends two tons of convertible (about 300
pounds more than the coupe version) hurtling down the road is a
370-horsepower, supercharged, 4.0-liter V8. Feeding on almost 400
lb.-ft. of torque, it cranks 0-60 in just over 5 seconds. I did not
get the convertible onto an abandoned airport runway, as I did the
coupe, but that car went from 80-100 miles per hour in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   For all its power, it managed to deliver 16 miles per gallon _
about one m.p.g. less than the coupe, maybe owing to the extra and
the aerodynamic drag of the ragtop.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of the convertible top: Its fit, from the inside,
looked amazingly tight. One passenger thought he was in a hardtop,
the fit appeared so seamless. Yet on the road, there was a fairly
constant, low-level wind sound and I could not figure its source.
That is, until I took the Jag through a brushless carwash. At the
upper front corners of both the driver and passenger side windows,
water came flowing in. It makes sense that if water can find its
way through whatever gaps lurked there, so could wind.
</P>
<P>
   But back to driving performance. To handle the XKR's quickness
and speed, the underpinnings best be good. Start with 18-inch
wheels _ they look positively dominant on this low-slung car. Add
those Pirellis and they handle that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   They held on long, carved turns like the rig was on rails. On
snaps through corners they seemed to dig in. In the coupe, I
noticed a slight weight shift to the rear in the tightest of
corners. It was slightly more pronounced in the convertible, which
by nature of being topless is bound to flex a bit more, but even
with the soft top, this is a highly responsive car.
</P>
<P>
   It fights body roll, yaw, squat and dive with _ cute in a Jag,
CATS _ its Computer Active Technology System. CATS monitors speed,
steering wheel position, and brakes and adjusts the stiffness of
the shocks to compensate. Feed CATS with stiff springs, stiff
antiroll bars, traction control, and you've got a scampering,
surefooted Cat.
</P>
<P>
   If I have one major criticism of this car, it's the shifter. The
automatic mode seemed to shift up when it should (though sometimes
earlier than I would like), while the manual option really isn't
that at all (as in a Porsche, for instance) as it seems to hold
back on your decisions, trying to make up its own mind despite what
you may have decided.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The ease of raising and lowering the convertible roof. No
manual latches. One button does it all.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The AM radio. Where is it written that all European cars must
have AM radios with poor reception?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $81,800 &QL; 
Price as tested: $84,200 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 370/387 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 101.9 inches/187.4 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 72 inches/50.7 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 4,021 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 4 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
