<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-CHINA-890&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA AND U.S. RECOGNIZE IMPROVED RELATIONS DURING ALBRIGHT VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ More than a year after the NATO bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, the United States and China officially
declared Thursday, during a visit by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, that the interlude of bitterness had given way to
improved relations.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, both sides said that the firmer footing of the
relationship, based on the recent passage in the House of
Representatives of a broad trade agreement with China, was now
focused on the sensitive issue of Taiwan and the Clinton
administration's plans for an anti-missile defensive shield.
</P>
<P>
   On human rights, an area on which Washington and Beijing remain
far apart, an official traveling with Albright said the Chinese
leadership had remained ``noncommittal'' on a request to restart an
official dialogue on human rights that was broken off more than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who is on a visit of less than 36 hours to China _
probably her last as secretary of state _ said at a news conference
that she had encouraged the Chinese leadership to resume a dialogue
with Taiwan. It did not matter, she said, whether it began at a
fairly low level or with a summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our major goal is that there be a resumption in the
cross-strait dialogue,'' Albright said. ``More will be gained
through flexibility and appeals to shared interest than could
possibly be achieved through efforts to intimidate.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese leaders whom she met, including the prime
minister, Zhu Rongji, and the president, Jiang Zemin, deflected her
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry said at its weekly news briefing Thursday
that relations between China and the United States had ``greatly
improved'' because of efforts by both sides. But the foreign
ministry spokesman, Zhu Bangzao, focused most of his comments on
Taiwan and said that Washington must stop its plans to include
Taiwan in the theater missile defense system ``in any capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, in the wake of the successful summit meeting
between the two Koreas, the new president of Taiwan, Chen
Shui-bian, invited Beijing to participate in a summit meeting. But
the Chinese foreign ministry swiftly turned away the idea, saying
that Taiwan had to first agree to the ``one China'' policy that
describes Taiwan and mainland China as one country.
</P>
<P>
   Differences between Washington and Beijing over the future of
Taiwan will persist as long as Washington continues to support a
theater missile defense system for Taiwan, said a senior Chinese
foreign policy analyst, Chu Shulong, in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theater missile defense is a total national security issue for
China, and China wants a clear commitment from Washington not to
provide theater missile defense to Taiwan,'' said Chu, a senior
research fellow at the China Institute of Contemporary
International Relations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Beijing was particularly alarmed by the proposed defense system
because it would result in what Chu called the ``integration'' of
U.S. and Taiwanese armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Chu said that the proposed defense system for Taiwan would
continue to roil Chinese-U.S. relations because, for domestic
political reasons, Washington would not be able to give the
assurances of non-deployment that the Chinese were seeking. The
Chinese are particularly upset about theater missile defense
because it would give the United States the ability to detect and
destroy Chinese missiles as they were launched.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Albright arrived at her meetings Thursday expecting a full dose
of criticism about the Clinton administration's plans for a
national missile defensive shield, but Chinese officials did not
dwell on that issue, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Albright's goals was to learn how the Chinese had
interpreted the meeting between the North Korean leader, Kim Jong
Il, and Kim Dae-jung of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States share common ground in their
interest in seeing reconciliation between the two Koreas, and
administration officials have gone out of their way to note
Beijing's help in encouraging North Korea to be more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright's aides said considerable time was spent
discussing Korea, Albright offered few new details Thursday on the
Korean summit meeting. The Chinese, she said, described Kim Jong Il
as ``jovial,'' ``forthcoming'' and ``knowledgeable,'' all familiar
adjectives from the past week. An aide to Albright said Thursday
night that Jiang had noted the North Korean leader's wit and said
that he was ``very polite.''
</P>
<P>
   A continual irritant in Washington's relationship with Beijing,
China's transfer of missiles and missile parts to Pakistan and
other countries, was discussed, but no progress was made, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright gave the Chinese qualified praise for ``the overall
record'' of ``becoming part of various arms control regimes,''
including the Chemical Weapons Treaty and the Non-Proliferation
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be encouragement to get the Chinese to improve
their export controls on nuclear-related materials. The
administration is facing intense criticism from Congress for being
too lax toward the Chinese on such matters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two senior non-proliferation officials, including the assistant
secretary of state for non-proliferation, Robert Einhorn, visited
Beijing last week in an attempt to resolve a problem involving
China's transfer of M-11 ballistic missiles to Pakistan nearly a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Central Intelligence Agency to Congress last
year stated that Pakistan had acquired the missiles from China, the
first time that the United States has publicly acknowledged that
China sent the weapons to Pakistan. Under U.S. law, such a transfer
by China requires the administration to impose economic sanctions,
including on space systems, a move that the White House would like
to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official traveling with Albright said
Thursday night that the problem of the transfer of weapons to
Pakistan had not been resolved. The State Department's senior
adviser on arms control, John Holum, will visit Beijing next month
to pursue a solution, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The national security adviser, Sandy Berger, has said that the
administration would like China to become a full member of the
Missile Technology Control Regime, the main global missile
non-proliferation pact, but that China has consistently resisted,
arguing that Washington should first stop selling advanced weapons
to Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1532EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
