<SLUG> BC-FILM-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLOR OF MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
  The faces are more varied, but green is still the most important
shade 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may have noticed something different about the movies you've
seen in these first six months of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   They look like America.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever before, films are reflecting the multiracial
character of this society. From both Hollywood and the independent
sector, picture after picture acknowledges that this is a nation of
African, Asian, Latino, Native and European folks who are all in it
together.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the movies employ race as a key subject, such as the
Jackie Chan western ``Shanghai Noon,'' the spring's hip-hop/kung fu
crime thriller ``Romeo Must Die,'' the examination of white kids
and gangsta culture in ``Black and White'' and even ``Me, Myself &AMP;
Irene,'' the goofy comedy in which Jim Carrey raises three
African-American sons. Others never so much as mention the
multicolored nature of their casts; ``Mission: Impossible 2,''
``Rules of Engagement,'' ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' ``Groove'' and
Kenneth Branagh's Shakespeare update ``Love's Labours Lost'' fit in
that category.
</P>
<P>
   But what all of these films share with many more 2000 releases
(``Shaft,'' ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce,'' ``Ghost Dog: The Way
of the Samurai,'' ``Luminarias'' and upcoming films ranging from
the spoof ``Scary Movie'' to the more serious likes of ``The
Patriot,'' ``Girlfight,'' ``Nurse Betty,'' ``What's Cooking'' and
``Remember the Titans,'' among others) is a perception that the
racial barriers that have historically undermined the egalitarian
American dream are crumbling fast.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not fast enough, both in society at large and in the
movies that reflect it. But, with notable reservations, talent,
businesspeople and observers of the film scene see the current
trend as a positive one, especially for an artform that, from its
beginnings until very recently, wallowed in segregation when it
wasn't actively practicing exclusion and stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I would say that this is something that is mostly
happening organically, it's something that we're certainly
conscious of and have spoken about,'' says Buena Vista Motion
Picture Group President Nina Jacobson, whose various Disney labels
has or will distribute ``Shanghai,'' ``60 Seconds'' and ``Titans''
this year. ``Our movies have, in the past, certainly been whiter
than the world we live in. And although we feel that it's our
responsibility that any time you cast a movie to cast the best
person for the part, we are aware of the fact that our movies ought
to reflect our world.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, altruism in studio executive suites is about as
common as domestic cars in their assigned parking spaces; present,
perhaps, but not prevalent. And movie-money people freely admit
there's a strong commercial incentive for multiracial casting.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a marketing point of view, you're trying to involve all
groups,'' notes entertainment industry analyst Art Rockwell of
Burbank-based Rockwell Capital. ``There's something of a parallel
to be drawn with the music business today, the great Latin music
explosion and the intermingling of races in rap groups. Much of
this movement is catering to the widest possible audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Paramount Motion Picture Group Vice-Chairman Robert
Friedman, whose studio made ``M:I-2,'' ``Shaft,'' ``Rules'' and the
upcoming ``Bless the Child'' with Kim Basinger and Jimmy Smits and
``Along Came a Spider'' with Morgan Freeman and Monica Potter,
``It's a combination of both trying to do the right thing and
knowing that the non-Caucasian moviegoing population represents
about 30 percent of the business. So, obviously, there's real value
there from just a purely commercial sense.'' When we get properties
that are creatively exciting to us and, by the way, also are
multicultural, then we see it as an opportunity and it's something
we like to try to do.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial considerations have driven studio thinking on race
since, at least, the huge commercial success of D.W. Griffith's
virulently racist, ``Birth of a Nation'' in 1915. For decades
following, African-Americans were overwhelmingly represented in a
negative light, American Indians were westerns' designated bad
guys, Charlie Chan was played by white actors wearing heavy makeup
and the breakthrough ethnic leading ladies such as Dolores Del Rio
and Anna May Wong were constantly typecast as fetishized exotics.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s and '60s, things were changing, often in token but
fundamentally well-meaning terms (check the Sidney Poitier ouvrage)
_ although the sensibilities of white audiences in the
still-segregated South remained a constant concern for
distributors. Black/white buddy comedies blossomed in the late '70s
and early '80s, but their energy was based more on contrast than
inclusion. A serious African-American cinema was finally
established by the 1990s, while substantially smaller Asian and
Latino equivalents are still striving to sustain footholds.
</P>
<P>
   Now multiracial pictures are the latest step on this path of
cultural evolution. And in keeping with the movies' past
performance, there is some inevitable stumbling on the way toward
the admirable goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about including everyone under the color spectrum
in film and television, it sounds really good,'' National Hispanic
Media Coalition Chairman Alex Nogales points out. ``But when it
comes into practice, we're taken for granted, somehow expected to
respond to non-Latino films and characters. It's very
disheartening, but we intend to keep addressing this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Berry, western regional director of the NAACP, whose
organization was at the forefront of last year's effort to make
network television more inclusive, also sees a long road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may represent more inclusion, but there's a long way to go
in terms of proper portrayal,'' he observes. ``The problem is all
the crime stories, all the gang activities, all the hip-hop, when
there's a much broader spectrum of the African-American community.
They'll even go abroad to get someone who comes from a different
culture to, it seems, avoid a proper portrayal of our culture
coming forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry is referring to English-African actress Thandie Newton's
romantic lead opposite Tom Cruise in ``M:I-2''; a film, by the way,
which was directed by Hong Kong transplant John Woo. He's a prime
example of the recent upsurge of Asian talent in American cinema.
But that development, too, leaves much to be developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive thing is that they are using Asians as, at least,
the co-stars of films, like Jet Li in 'Romeo Must Die' and Jackie
Chan in 'Shanghai Noon,''' acknowledges Guy Aoki, president of the
Media Action Network for Asian Americans, an industry watchdog
group. ``The bad side of that is that they're all from Asia, and
they're usually action stars or martial artists.'' From our point
of view, that's a bit frustrating because we feel there is so much
Asian-American talent here that is not made use of; not given the
chance. It's a good thing overall, but it's still a long ways away
from where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best progress, as is often the case, is being made
by independent filmmakers. Chi Muoi Lo wrote, produced, directed
and co-starred in ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce,'' a film inspired
by his experiences as a Vietnamese refugee growing up in an
African-American neighborhood of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Lo feels that a new generation's attitudes are bound to overcome
old prejudices and stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race is not the first thing that we see,'' he says of today's
youth. ``And when it is, we've gone by that in, like, a minute, and
start judging a person by their character. In my world, I have all
different multicultures around me, and I find it very comforting.
And now you're dealing with a new group of directors and writers
who come from that same perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Puerto Rican-born director Miguel Arteta, whose
well- reviewed, upcoming indie feature ``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' has no
intrinsic ethnic angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's very important, as a minority filmmaker, to
burst through the burden of representation into an area where
you're simply telling stories that matter and you're trying to make
the best movies that you can,'' Arteta says. ``Latinos will
hopefully fit into those equations.''
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Chuck &AMP; Buck,'' one has. Veteran actress Lupe Ontiveros
plays a key role in the film as a novice stage director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lupe is one of the great Latino talents that has, kind of, yet
to be discovered by mainstream Hollywood, yet she's been in
Hollywood for 30 years,'' Arteta notes. ``And although she's done a
few important roles _ she was the woman who killed Selena in that
film _ mostly, she's been asked to play maids, more than 300 in
television and films. That's really sad to look at in such a great
talent like her.''
</P>
<P>
   And while exposure is one thing, the movie business on both the
indie and corporate levels remains primarily a money-driven
enterprise. Not surprisingly, minority talent views the pay scale
as the next equality hurdle to jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line: Green is the only color that really matters in
this day and age,'' observes the rising African-American star
Anthony Anderson, who has already appeared in ``Romeo,'' ``Irene''
and ``Big Momma's House'' this year. ``Whoever they need to put on
the screen, be it white, black, yellow or brown, they'll put them
up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I honestly can't complain, but here I am, barely getting
paid beyond scale, and I've worked with the Barry Levinsons and the
Ron Howards and the Jim Carreys and the Farrelly brothers. All I
ask is for fair market value for my talent, but that aspect of the
business is not as equal as things may be looking on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the inequities that still need to be overcome,
the American film industry appears to be committed to making movies
for, and with, all Americans _ which, at its best, could be the
most hopeful reflection of society yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just like we should do it because, oh, it's p.c.,''
Buena Vista's Jacobson affirms. ``We're a movie studio, we want as
many people as possible to see our movies, and they ought to
reflect the audiences we're trying to appeal to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that we believe in,'' Paramount's Friedman
concludes. ``I don't know how to say it any better than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
