<HEADLINE>
MINGHELLA MET THE CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who had read Michael Ondaatje's ``The English Patient''
must have been amazed when they heard it was being turned into a
movie. The poetic novel has an unconventional, complicated
narrative that moves seamlessly between memory and the present.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who doubted it could be done was proved wrong
_ at least on some critical and commercial levels. The 1996 film
won the Oscar for best picture and did profitable business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The English Patient's'' director-screenwriter, Anthony
Minghella, then took up another challenge: adapting Patricia
Highsmith's ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' which comes out on video
next Tuesday. While Highsmith's 1952 thriller has a more
conventional narrative, its protagonist, Tom Ripley, is a
psychopathic chameleon _ hardly an attractive character, even if
you do cast glamour boy Matt Damon to play him.
</P>
<P>
   The question here isn't whether Minghella has done a good
adaption, but rather has he created a film that stands on its own?
``Ripley'' does do that, even better than ``The English Patient,''
though it didn't fare as well at the Oscars. (There's an irony in
that.) Billed as a lush romance (though it wasn't much of that),
much of ``Patient'' is too detached and postcard pretty, deadening
its themes of passion and regret.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ripley,'' Minghella has given us another sumptuous picture
to look at, but under its cool '50s, jazzy surfaces is a deadly
vibrancy _ literally _ that gives the film its life. Highsmith
described her novel as being about ``two young men with a certain
resemblance _ not much _ one of whom kills the other and assumes
his identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripley is an orphan in his mid-20s with a gift for mimicry.
Mistaken for a Princeton grad, he is hired by a rich businessman to
go to an Italian resort village to persuade the man's son, Dickie
Greenleaf (Jude Law), to return home. Ripley's masquerade allows
him into Greenleaf's rather decadent but dazzling world, which
includes Dickie's girlfriend Marge (Gwyneth Paltrow). At first
Ripley is happy to just be part of it, but soon becomes aware of
how tenuous is his hold.
</P>
<P>
   Envy and fear of discovery turn to something more sinister. As
the story develops, Minghella skillfully plays with questions of
morality and consequences for one's actions. And while Ripley lacks
a conscience, there is almost a sadness about him, as if he
recognizes a dim light of conscience but is unable to turn toward
it. Damon captures this duality brilliantly. Pasty white compared
to the bronzed Law, he's like a stray dog whose cute and harmless
look makes you forget he has teeth.
</P>
<P>
   What Minghella has fashioned is a rich and intelligent thriller
in ``Ripley''; the film's complexities merit repeated viewing. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
Give me 'Liberty': In ``Liberty Heights,'' which is already in
video stores, director Barry Levinson (``Rainman'') returns to his
hometown of Baltimore for the fourth time. ``Heights'' joins
``Diner,'' ``Tin Men'' and ``Avalon'' as affectionate, smart,
entertaining films that also explore the social changes that shaped
in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Like his other Baltimore films, Levinson keeps a number of
storylines going in ``Heights,'' but the film centers on a
teen-ager named Ben (Ben Foster) who learns after living a
sheltered life that most of the world is not Jewish. The time is
the mid-'50s, when school integration was first mandated. In high
school, Ben is an outsider, returning at night to his Jewish
community. Eventually, Ben becomes friends with another outsider,
Sylvia (Rebekah Johnson), one of the token African-Americans at his
school. A delicate relationship develops, and Levinson, who has a
wonderful touch with such things, never overplays his hand in this
charming, heartfelt film. &QL; 
--- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' (Paramount) is priced for rental on
VHS; sale price is $103.99. The DVD is $29.99 and includes
commentary from Minghella and interviews with the cast and crew.
``Liberty Heights'' (Warners) is priced at $106.99 on VHS. The DVD
is $24.98 and includes interviews with and commentary by the cast
and Levinson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
