<HEADER>
A1770 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FACTORY-KILLER-HNS &LR;      06-22 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACTORY-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAUSAGE MAKER SUSPECTED IN DEATHS OF THREE FOOD INSPECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA,  
 &HT;     JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     and MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LEANDRO, Calif. _ A sausage maker accused of killing three
food inspectors at his downtown factory had grown furious with the
government's scrutiny in recent months and may have snapped,
according to people who know him.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Charles Alexander, 39, was in custody Thursday in
connection with the shootings of two U.S. Department of Agriculture
inspectors and an investigator from the California Department of
Food and Agriculture who were at his Santos Linguisa Factory to
document conditions Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Waving and firing his handgun, Alexander then chased another
state food inspectors out of the small factory, the police said,
before stopping and surrendering to a bicycle officer a half-block
away in this community south of Oakland. The fourth inspector was
unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were described only as two men and a woman, ages 30
to 50, who were shot many times at about 3:30 p.m. One was carrying
a camera to take pictures of conditions at the factory, said San
Leandro police Lt. Dan Marchetti.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander had shut his factory in January after the USDA ordered
him to raise cooking temperatures to acceptable levels, according
to a February report in the San Leandro Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Food inspectors visited frequently in subsequent months, with
Alexander's shop closing and reopening several times.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who has a history of legal and financial woes, and
ran for mayor in 1998, called for public donations to aid his
fight. He posted a sign that read: ``To all our great customers,
the USDA is coming into our plant harassing my employees and me,
making it impossible to make our great product.'' The sign was
still up on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspectors were on him, and he was getting nasty and they
were getting nasty,'' said Mike Smith, 71, of San Leandro, who
described himself as a father-figure to Alexander and one of his
closest friends. ``They kept pushing, pushing, pushing. It was too
much pressure. I told Stuart, `You better cool it, buddy.' He was a
good guy, but people snap.``
</P>
<P>
   San Leandro police detectives and FBI agents swarmed the
one-story sausage factory, which sits among a row of houses and is
connected to a bar. The FBI was involved because federal employees
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting stunned residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shocker. I came out here after I heard it on the news
just to see if it's really possible,'' said David Teles, 43, who
used to live just a block from the factory and was one of many
people to claim that Alexander's sausage was some of the best
around.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis issued a statement late Wednesday, mourning the
deaths and calling the shooting ``an unspeakably barbarous act.''
He ordered that flags be flown at half staff at state buildings to
commemorate the state food inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Officers arrived at the factory after the police received
numerous reports of gunshots. Bicycle patrolman Rick Cahall found
Alexander standing on the sidewalk unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   After Alexander was arrested, officers broke through a window of
the factory because all the doors were locked. They found the
victims' bodies in the front of the store, where customers would
pay for and pick up sausages at a counter, Marchetti said. At least
three handguns were also found inside, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was booked on suspicion of three counts of murder and
one count of attempted murder, Marchetti said.
</P>
<P>
   San Leandro Detective Sgt. Chris Lux said a female employee, one
of about 10 at the factory, was in the store when the shooting
happened. They planned to interview her and another potential
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Lux said this was not the first time the government agents had
dropped by Alexander's store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out here (Wednesday) on an inspection for hygienic
problems at the plant. That's been going on for a while, since
about January,'' Lux said. ``The (business) has been open, closed,
open, closed. He would lose his permit, and then correct the
problems, and then get the permit back again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In California's ``sausage capital'' _ San Leandro has at least
eight sausage companies _ many people seemed to know the story of
the third-generation linguisa procurer.
</P>
<P>
   During his mayoral campaign two years ago, Alexander frequently
parked a truck full of live pigs outside his factory, a memory
recalled with both humor and anguish after Wednesday's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were huge pinkish pigs just sitting in the truck,'' said
City Councilman Gordon Galvan, who dealt with the complaints. ``We
had lots of complaints like that. Stuart is not the type of guy who
would just say, `Sorry. It won't happen again.' He defended his
turf. That's the way he is.'''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander grew up in San Leandro and inherited his meat business
from his father, Herman ``Tweety'' Alexander, who had run it for
more than 40 years. It was founded in 1921 by Stuart Alexander's
grandfather.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
