<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA'S HIGH COURT TAKES NIKE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California Supreme Court has agreed to
decide whether a San Francisco activist can sue Nike Inc. for
allegedly lying about conditions in its Asian factories.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit by Marc Kasky was dismissed by a lower court on
free-speech grounds. But the state's high court voted to take up
Kasky's appeal and decide whether his claims, if proved, would show
that the world's largest athletic shoe maker violated a broad
California law against unfair business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Ronald George and Justices Stanley Mosk, Joyce
Kennard, Kathryn Mickle Werdegar and Janice Rogers Brown voted
Wednesday to review the case.
</P>
<P>
   The suit attacks Nike's statements to the public and its
stockholders about its treatment of hundreds of thousands of
workers, mostly women, in Asian factories run by contractors that
make the company's shoes and other apparel.
</P>
<P>
   After reports in the news media and elsewhere that the women
were working for low pay in dangerous conditions, Nike commissioned
a study led by Andrew Young, the former U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations, and declared its workers were well-treated. The
company said the factories complied with their home countries' laws
on pay and safety and that workers were provided health care, paid
an average of twice the local minimum wage and protected from
physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Kasky, represented by some of the same lawyers who successfully
challenged the Joe Camel cigarette advertising campaign, likened
Nike's statements to deceptive advertising and said they were
intended to lure customers by whitewashing factory conditions. He
sought to require the company to return illegally obtained profits
to customers and the state and conduct a corrective public
information campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge David Garcia dismissed the suit without a
trial and was upheld last March by the 1st District Court of
Appeal, which said Nike's statements were more like political
speech than commercial advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The company's campaign did not focus on any of its products, but
was intended to ``promote a favorable corporate image'' and
influence the public debate over global corporate practices, said
Justice Douglas Swager in the 3-0 ruling. He said the suit ``seeks
judicial intervention in a public debate'' that was
constitutionally shielded from government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Kasky's attorneys urged the state Supreme Court to intervene,
arguing that public relations campaigns could amount to false
advertising. Attorney Alan M. Caplan said reinstatement of the suit
would allow the lawyers to gather evidence from Nike and determine
the truth about factory conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Nike spokesman Vada Manager said the company considered Kasky's
suit ``a case without merit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
