<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPECTOR-RONETTES-ART-     06-22 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECTOR-RONETTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONNIE SPECTOR, JUST WALKING IN A RAINBOW
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Can you just stay focused, sweetheart?'' Jonathan
Greenfield says tersely to his wife as they settle into a hotel
lobby in Danbury, Conn., near their home. ``It's so important for
you to listen to the question and not just open your guts.'' He
apologizes for his wife, whom he manages professionally. ``We
always have this discussion!''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Spector Greenfield is nervous and scattered, but if her
thoughts, in a froggy smoker's voice, scamper off in exultation,
why not?
</P>
<P>
   After all, a 13-year-old lawsuit over royalties from songs she
recorded when she was clambering out of her teens has just been
resolved in her favor.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that for such glorious '60s hits like ``Be My
Baby,'' ``Baby I Love You'' and ``Walking in the Rain,'' Ronnie and
the Ronettes, the shimmying bad girls once so famous that their
opening act was the Rolling Stones, received only a one-time check
of $14,482.30 from Phil Spector, Greenfield's former husband. Last
week, a New York state Supreme Court justice ruled that Spector,
who repackaged Ronettes' songs for oldies collections, commercials
and movies like ``Dirty Dancing,'' owed Greenfield and the
Ronettes, her sister and cousin, $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed it's over,'' says Greenfield, 56, who still wears
her luxuriant dark hair long, as she did as a teen-ager, her eyes
made up with liquid black liner, her much-imitated look. Even now,
a mother of two teen-agers, she has an irrepressible girlish
eagerness that is endearing and, despite her flinty ambition,
vulnerable. ``I can have my career back!''
</P>
<P>
   Getting her career back has pretty much been her goal since that
morning in 1972 when Ronnie Spector finally got her husband's
permission to take a sunlit stroll. She walked out of the gloomy,
guarded Beverly Hills mansion barefoot so as not to arouse his
suspicions and just kept going. Spector paid her divorce lawyers in
nickels and stamped her alimony checks with an expletive.
</P>
<P>
   As she wrote in her 1990 autobiography, ``Be My Baby'' (foreword
by Cher, another comeback queen who knows from Svengalis), the
brilliant Spector adored her voice and what she calls her ``Spanish
Harlem half-breedishness.'' Her mother, a hard-working waitress,
was black and American Indian, her father, a happy-go-lucky drinker
and unemployed drummer, was white.
</P>
<P>
   It all crested when the Fabulous Ronettes were touring England
and ``Be My Baby'' was a worldwide hit. She was 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I was waiting for all my life,'' she says with a
throaty laugh. ``I was in love with the man I adored and he even
flew over to England to see me. And Phil hates to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was my audience! The applause! We had girls who
wanted to wear their hair like us, in beehives, the Chinese bangs,
the long braid! The kids would be screaming and tearing your
clothes off! I loved it! `Want my shirt? Here! Want a shoe?
Here!'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, after the Ronettes dissolved, the couple married. She
has often described her reclusive, gilded life. His gift of a
Camaro came with a mannequin in the passenger seat wearing
Spector's trademark cap, so it would always look as if he was
accompanying her. Opera, which she hates, resounded through their
home. He made her sit through screenings of ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That girl couldn't sing,'' Greenfield says, hurt shadowing her
face. ``Was Phil trying to tell me something?''
</P>
<P>
   Bored, isolated: ``I'd get drunk so I could go to rehab, just to
get out of the house.'' She adds brightly, ``I got to hear Carole
King's `Tapestry' in rehab!''
</P>
<P>
   After she left Spector, she asked the impresario Murray the K
for work. ``I'm only 29 but I'm an oldie but goodie? I just poured
vodka into my soda.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she was plucky and blessed with a much-admired
sin-'n'-innocence tremolo. Billy Joel wrote ``Say Goodbye to
Hollywood'' for her. She toured with oldies shows and Bruce
Springsteen's E Street Band. Last fall she released a five-song
collection, ``She Talks to Rainbows,'' whose co-producer was Joey
Ramone. She kept bobbing back up, even performing for President
Clinton (who greeted her, arms wide, singing, ``Be my little
baby!'').
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, at 36, she met Greenfield, 15 years her junior, who had
seen her show when he was a smoldering, smitten teen-ager. ``He
didn't pull on me right away like most guys,'' Greenfield says.
``So we were friends first. If I thought a date was trying to kiss
me before we went out to dinner, I'd call up Jonathan and say, `I
need you to fix something!' And he would get rid of the guy for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   When she credits Greenfield for the lawsuit, he erupts,
excoriating her low self-esteem, but ending with a pep talk. ``You
were the trailblazer 35 years ago and after you filed the lawsuit,
you wouldn't go away! That's what the Bad Girl is about!''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie, how have you changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm my own person,'' she replies. ``I was so controlled by
Phil and now I have my own ideas. With this lawsuit over, I'm only
looking forward; to my future, to singing rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's beautiful, sweetheart,'' her husband says.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, along with singers like Mary Chapin Carpenter and
Sheryl Crow, Greenfield appeared at a House subcommittee hearing on
a new copyright law. When she was introduced, she broke into
``Wuh-uh-uh-oh, be my, be my baby,'' startling her buttoned-up
audience. ``I just felt the urge,'' she explains. Afterward, she
was swarmed by autograph seekers. ``I saw Mary Bono and said: `Hi!
How are the kids?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
