u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD     06-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(850)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAS AGREES TO REMAIN IN COALITION GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for complete writethru to update, add background and
restructure.)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The linchpin Shas political party retracted its
resignation from Israel's government Thursday afternoon, leaving
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's broad coalition battered but intact to
head into a crucial stage of peacemaking with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his strongest speeches since taking office, Barak then
appealed to his nation to reflect on and rise above the recent
internal turmoil, which, he said, threatened to sour ``everything
that the Jewish nation fought for and dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What sort of Israel do we want?'' Barak said in a live radio
broadcast from a Labor Party meeting. ``Do we want an Israel of
violence and division?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want an Israel of hatred? Where will this lead? I am
afraid that we all know, and I believe that we are all afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends, we cannot make peace with our neighbors without
making peace first among ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this gut-wrenching day for many Israelis, when
their country was spared the immediate turmoil of a government's
collapse but witnessed the denouement of what many considered a sad
spectacle, Dennis Ross, the U.S. peace envoy, arrived here to
tackle the external peace issue.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will follow on Tuesday as
part of the Americans' intensifying effort to lay the foundation
for a successful retreat-style summit meeting in July. The
meeting's goal would be a final peace agreement and an end to the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, although a partial solution is
considered more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Those peace talks are the backdrop for Thursday's political
events.
</P>
<P>
   Shas officials, in fact, specifically noted that their
re-enlistment in the government would permit Barak to proceed with
the negotiations that are his central project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the prime minister, first of all, the umbrella that he
has a government,'' said Shlomo Benizri, a Shas official and the
health minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``And with this government, he will be able to travel to the
United States in the near future, within two weeks, to continue
with the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a year of tense co-existence with the leftists in
Barak's government, Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party, won a primary
battle by forcing the leftist Meretz Party out of the Cabinet so
that it could remain.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz's three ministers, including the education minister,
Yossi Sarid, a staunch secularist who has become Shas' nemesis,
quit their posts on Wednesday night. Meretz will stay in the
government to support the peace effort that it champions, but the
leaders relinquished their ministries to end the uncertainty about
whether the government would survive, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister agreed, maybe against his true wishes, to
give up Meretz,'' Sarid said. ``And Meretz agreed to lie down over
the fence for him.'' He was using a well-known army expression,
referring to a soldier who throws himself over barbed wire so that
others can walk over him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who now has a cabinet similar to that of his rightist
predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, did not try to convince the Meretz
ministers to stay. He did say that he appreciated their
``concession,'' but he seemed to cast blame widely, calling on all
parties to ``stop with the invective and the arm-twisting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is not the toy of any party or any individual,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Barak will learn whether the political crisis has been
worth it: whether Shas backs him and the peace effort or whether it
continues to act like an opposition party that sits in the
government. He originally included Shas in his coalition, and
withstood its full-time balkiness, in order to have the party's
backing for a peace deal with the Palestinians. But that support is
not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The overt issues in contention between Shas and Barak concerned
the finances and oversight of the religious party's indebted school
system and the legalization of its pirate radio stations, which
have been nicknamed ``the holy channels.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Shas' rabbis instructed their politicians to resign
from the coalition last week, they also cited as an incentive
Barak's plan ``to forsake'' the West Bank. There is a deeply
embedded resistance inside the party to territorial concessions,
despite a one-time ruling by Shas' spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef, that it is valid to give up land if it serves to end the
violence and save Jewish lives.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's party, One Israel, ``has not discounted the possibility
that in a month or two, if he presents an agreement with the
Palestinians, Shas will stick a knife in his back,'' Yossi Verter
wrote in the Haaretz newspaper Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Formed a year ago, Barak's broad coalition was his effort to
learn from the mistakes of his mentor, the late Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin, and to forge a national consensus for his
peacemaking. But the rifts between various segments of Israeli
society go deep, and they are probably even more intense at the
leadership level. Instead of bridging differences, the broad
government has seemed to exacerbate them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A demonstration of the deep-seated enmity between Sarid and Eli
Yishai, the Shas leader, played out like hostile theater in the
Israeli parliament on Wednesday. Sarid mocked what he said was
Yishai's weakness as a party leader, repeatedly saying: ``Try to
refrain from lying. I know it's not easy.'' Yishai accused Sarid of
persecuting Shas in an obsessed way and referred to him as
``wicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the bickering, Barak sighed. ``You hear the
argument,'' he said, ``and you really understand why when the
teacher in the second grade sees her pupils misbehaving she says to
them: `This isn't the Knesset, get a hold of yourselves.''' The
Knesset is the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis have been disgusted and disillusioned by the
political crisis. Nahum Barnea, a senior columnist for Yedioth
Ahronoth, compared the politicians' displays of rage to a recent
rash of impulse murders. ``The ministers are no better than the
drivers who kick each other to death because of a quarrel over the
right of way at a traffic light,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gabi Lalouche, who is the right-wing mayor of Dimona, a poor
town, noted that he strongly opposed Sarid's views on the peace
effort. ``But I've been mayor for 11 years, and what Sarid and Ran
Cohen,'' another Meretz minister, ``have done in the last year for
the development towns has not been done in many years. Their exit
is a dirge for generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Political experts heaped a lot of blame on Barak, a former
general, for handling the situation like an inexperienced
politician. They said he ended up doing belatedly and publicly what
he could have done much earlier and more quietly: pressuring Meretz
and capitulating to Shas' demands.
</P>
<P>
   But the same experts said that the political world in general is
to blame; politicians have become so hermetically sealed in their
air-conditioned parliament that they don't seem to understand the
Israeli public's desire for peace with its Arab neighbors and peace
at home, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madmen, get down from the roof!'' Sima Kadmon, another
newspaper columnist, wrote to the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   For the Shas school system, Barak offered millions in debt
relief as well as tax forgiveness. He also proposed that the
system's problems be administered by a special team reporting to
him and taken out of the Education Ministry's hands. The radio
stations will come under the umbrella of Israel's second
broadcasting authority, where they have been promised almost
complete independence.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Shas will withdraw its support for early elections,
killing the idea for the time being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
