<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Second Thought on `Moon' Trip
</P>
<P>
   The deal was this: Periodically the actors would vote on whether
to let the filmmakers back into rehearsals; if the vote was no, the
film would be burned. Under that not altogether comfortable set of
conditions, D.A. Pennebaker and Chris Hegedus began work on ``Moon
Over Broadway,'' their acclaimed documentary about the putting
together of the 1995 play ``Moon Over Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   When Docurama releases the film on tape and DVD on July 5, there
should be none of the unsettling elements that surrounded either
the documentary or the making of the troubled Broadway comedy,
which starred Carol Burnett and Philip Bosco. Noted for a
cinema-verite approach that allows the camera to observe but never
intrude, Pennebaker documentaries have famously watched
show-business scenes unfolding. For this assignment he and Hegedus
appeared with their cameras at the start of rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take anything for granted,'' Pennebaker said the
other day. ``You're going into private areas of people's lives.''
Burnett had not been on Broadway in 30 years. ``No matter how
engaging they might be initially when they shake hands and tell you
how much they like your films, when you start to poke around you
aren't sure how they're going to take it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the disc, Bosco; Tom Moore, the play's director; Ken Ludwig,
the playwright; and Rocco Landesman, one of the producers, indicate
that they took the documentary makers' presence well enough to join
in on the director's commentary several years later. Burnett's
reflections, recorded separately, are stirred in.
</P>
<P>
   During rehearsals they spoke their minds, and they do so again
on the disc, which is one reason DVD commentaries can be fun and
instructive even if they are about an old Broadway show that had
its problems from the start but lasted 9 months and 301
performances.
</P>
<P>
   In the commentary Bosco is as critical of the play as he was
during rehearsals, when he reacted angrily to what he perceived as
the director's and the playwright's attempts to stifle the actors'
interpretations of their roles. Bosco initially joined the project
because he thought the comedy, about the farcical troubles of a
flamboyant and once-renowned older theatrical couple, had been
written for him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it had been, but other elements crept in _ Hollywood,
he notes, by which he means the necessity in the end to create a
star vehicle. But he joins the others in lauding Burnett, who
worked hard to adjust from her years in television.
</P>
<P>
   But the real hero of the documentary is Ludwig. ``Time and `Moon
Over Buffalo' have also reinforced my long-held suspicion that
Burnett can locate a laugh in an empty laundry hamper,'' Vincent
Canby wrote in his review in The New York Times, a not exactly rave
referral to the play's humor. The playwright, rewriting like mad
all through the rehearsal process, , takes criticism in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I met them all at the same birthday party, they wouldn't be
a happy group,'' Pennebaker said. ``I liked them all individually
because I see the terrible ordeal they go through.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `Liberty Heights'
</P>
<P>
   Barry Levinson's fourth Baltimore-based film chronicles the rise
of '50s television, rock 'n' roll and the teen-age car culture.
Avoiding ``Happy Days'' stereotypes is no mean trick, but here is a
fresh perspective from two young brothers (Ben Foster, above, and
Adrien Brody) growing up in a middle-class Jewish family in a
gentile-dominated world. Luckily they have solid, caring parents
(Joe Mantegna and Bebe Neuwirth). ``Again,'' Stephen Holden wrote
in The New York Times, ``Levinson shows a special knack for
capturing the boastful, clinging camaraderie and cultural fetishes
of innocents trying to invent themselves in a more restrictive
era.''
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Warner. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 127 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Gun Shy
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to share more than anyone I've ever known,'' an
undercover Fed named Charlie Mayo (Liam Neeson) is told by his
psychiatrist (Michael Mantell). During an operation Charlie was
caught and tortured face down in a pile of watermelon and ever
since he has been looking for his lost nerve. His new assignment
lands him between a yuppie Colombian thug (Jose Zuniga) and a
violent cohort, Fulvio (Oliver Platt). Charlie's stomach growls
like a Rottweiler, but comfort comes from a nurse named Judy
(Sandra Bullock) in ``one of the most subtle and inspired comedies
you'll see this year'' (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   _2000. Hollywood. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 102 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Leila
</P>
<P>
   Learning that her daughter-in-law, Leila (Leila Hatami), is
infertile, an imperious mother-in-law (Jamileh Sheikhi)
systematically undermines the marriage of her only son (Ali
Mosaffa). Dariush Mehrjui's heartbreaking film is set in Iran, but
the parent's selfishness and pride put her in the same elite league
with some of Hollywood's most formidable Gorgons. Born to wealth
and privilege, Leila is thrown by the relentless campaign to have
her husband take a second wife who can bear him a son. While he
remains devoted, she gradually falls apart in a film that ``is, in
a word, devastating'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. First Run Features. $79.95; DVD, $29.95. 129 minutes.
Farsi with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful People
</P>
<P>
   In a London hospital after a brawl with a Serb, a Croat winds up
in the bed next to his opponent, and they fall to arguing over who
started it all. Jan Dizdar's film follows an agglomeration of
Balkan characters and others around the multicultural city, trying
to find some sense in a situation that has none. But his movie,
crammed with disparate stories, is anything but grim. Dizdar
``directs with extraordinary exuberance and self-confidence, in a
style that combines documentary realism with a playful,
improvisatory sense of possibility'' (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Trimark. $69.99; DVD, $24.99. 117 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   TOO JEWISH? Avi Hoffman's delightful musical revue does its best
to keep Yiddish and Yiddish theater alive, evoking the past when it
flourished from the shtetls of Eastern Europe to the Bronx. ``A
warm and winning mixture of nostalgia, song, comedy and cultural
and social history,'' Lawrence Van Gelder wrote in The New York
Times. 1995. Ergo Media. $29.95. 100 minutes. Information: (800)
695-3746.
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM SONG. Keeping sentimentality largely at bay, Phil Alden
Robinson's film recounts a time of mounting racial violence in the
South in the early 1960's. A disillusioned idealist (Danny Glover)
tries to deal with his angry son (Vicellous Reon Shannon), who
allies himself with the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee
as tensions lead to murder, demonstrations, beatings and jailings.
Robinson, William McDonald wrote in The New York Times, ``has
avoided falling into the trap of peopling his microcosm with
representative types.''
</P>
<P>
   DRUNKEN ANGEL; I LIVE IN FEAR. Two films by Akira Kurosawa are
available for the first time. In ``Drunken Angel'' (1948, 102
minutes), with Toshiro Mifune and Takashi Shimura, a gangster with
tuberculosis and a bullet lodged in his hand relates to the
alcoholic doctor who treats him. In ``I Live in Fear'' (1955, 105
minutes), an aging foundry owner (Mifune) terrified of nuclear
conflict, moves to Brazil. Home Vision. $19.99 each. Japanese with
English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
