<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YOUTH-ORCHESTRA-NYT &LR;      06-22 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-ORCHESTRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH ORCHESTRA FESTIVAL BEGINS IN SARASOTA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Texas, Wis., Minn, Va., Ohio, Mich., Mass.)   By CHARLIE HUISKING   Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Five hundred teen-agers are converging on
Sarasota this week to participate in the National Youth Orchestra
Festival, an intensive week of rehearsals, coaching sessions,
workshops and public concerts that began Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Five youth orchestras from around the country qualified for the
event: Northern Virginia's American Youth Philharmonic, the Atlanta
Symphony Youth Orchestra, the Greater Dallas Youth Orchestra, the
Milwaukee Youth Symphony Orchestra and the Minnesota Youth
Symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   Each ensemble will perform once with its own conductor at the
Sarasota Opera House. Then, the musicians will be regrouped into
four festival orchestras. They will perform such works as
Stravinsky's ``Firebird Suite,'' Elgar's ``Enigma Variations'' and
Mussorgorsky's ``Pictures at an Exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   An 18-member faculty of guest conductors and musicians will work
with the students. The roster includes Christopher Wilkins, music
director and conductor of the San Antonio Symphony; Robert Vernon,
principal viola, Cleveland Orchestra; and Ann Hobson Pilot,
principal harp, Boston Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is co-sponsored by the American Symphony Orchestra
League and Sarasota's Florida West Coast Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial event was first held in 1998 at the Interlochen
Center for the Arts in Michigan. While the inaugural festival was a
success, scheduling problems forced organizers to look for a new
home. Sarasota was chosen largely because of the reputation of the
Florida West Coast Symphony, said Debra McKeon, the festival's
managing director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symphony has such a commitment to education, to young
people,'' she said. ``They have the same mission, the same
philosophy that we do. It seemed like the perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said youth orchestra festivals are common in Europe,
``but until 1998, we'd never had a forum in the United States to
celebrate the success of the youth orchestra movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have a lot to celebrate. The level of musicianship is
increasing at a fast pace. That's happening in part because young
people are studying music at an earlier age. Also, I think we as a
country are coming to realize that music education is important,
not only to those who want to be musicians, but to us as a
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 200 youth orchestras in the nation, 25 auditioned
for the festival. The winners were chosen based on audio tapes of
their performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1794 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-CHICKENRUN-TEX     06-22 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHICKENRUN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE AND GROMIT FANS, GET YOURSELVES TO THE THEATER _ COOP
SUITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' and ``M:I-2.'' Anyone who has seen
the Oscar-winning Wallace and Gromit short films knows that nobody,
but nobody does a chase scene better than Nick Park.
</P>
<P>
   And at the climax of ``Chicken Run,'' DreamWorks' new
stop-motion animated feature, Park and co-director Peter Lord
deliver, with a breakout sequence that's not likely to have a rival
this summer. But despite such brilliance from the directors and
their team of animators, ``Chicken Run'' occasionally flags a
little as it makes its way to this rousing conclusion; it's proof
that a movie can be worthwhile, entertaining and a little
disappointing all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Park brings a lot of good will to the project,
thanks to his popular Wallace and Gromit series. Charming and
hilarious, these imaginative short animated films _ featuring
eccentric inventor Wallace and his loyal dog Gromit _ have earned
Park quite a cult following, some of whom have been awaiting a
feature film for nearly a decade. That's long enough that anything
but a total bomb is probably going to seem a satisfactory payoff.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Chicken Run'' is far from a bomb. It's funny, it's
fast-paced and it's laced with other winning Park trademarks, such
as Rube Goldberg-style inventions and wry dialogue. But it suffers
from the dangers inherent in expanding to feature films after a
career of making shorts _ especially the kind of exhaustively
animated films that Park, Lord and their England-based Aardman
Animations specialize in. Most Aardman films clock in at under 30
minutes, with only one or two speaking voices and a thriftiness
with peripheral characters. With ``Chicken Run,'' Park, Lord and
their team of animators have created a movie nearly three times as
long, with a 10-member principal ``cast'' and a coopful of extras.
</P>
<P>
   They keep the story simple: It's about a flock of chickens'
attempts to escape England's moody Tweedy Farm, which looks like a
concentration camp with the ``Psycho'' house as headquarters.
Leading the breakout attempts is Ginger (voiced by ``Absolutely
Fabulous''' Julia Sawalha), a plucky clucker who's hamstrung by
barbed wire, chicken-hearted or bird-brained coopmates, and her
inability simply to fly over the fence. One look at the cruel Mrs.
Tweedy (Miranda Richardson), though, and you understand Ginger's
desperation: If you're a Tweedy Farm hen and you've stopped laying
eggs, then you're tomorrow night's dinner. And Mrs. Tweedy is about
to hatch a new profit-making scheme involving a machine that makes
chicken-pot pies.
</P>
<P>
   But Ginger thinks she's found a solution when Rocky, a strutting
American rooster voiced by Mel Gibson (whose first line is a riff
on ``Braveheart''), inadvertently lands in the coop. Rocky has
apparently discovered the secret of chicken flight, but we in the
audience know he's a fraud _ and yet we also know that somehow
he'll come through in the end, albeit reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Chicken Run'' is dedicated to the romantic tension
between Ginger and Rocky, and to his scheming attempts to whip the
coop into shape for an escape. And Park, Lord and screenwriter
Karey Kirkpatrick concoct an amusing variety of sight gags and
chicken puns to fill the time between the movie's best moments,
which include the initial series of ``Great Escape''-inspired
escape attempts (all of which end with Ginger in ``solitary
confinement''), a near-miss for Rocky and Ginger in the pot-pie
machine, a dance number, and the wild and woolly _ er, feathery _
climax. This is good stuff indeed, but the tightness of Park and
Lord's earlier work is missing, even as this movie whisks by at a
brief 85 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   What's also missing is the uniqueness and intimacy. Wallace and
Gromit, especially, are thoroughly original characters, one a
blabby, cheese-loving, somewhat clueless chap, and the other a dog
who's unusually expressive and understanding even for his
empathetic species. The chickens in ``Chicken Run,'' and the
villains that threaten them, are more generic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it can be guilt-inducing to carp about it. Park and Lord
avoid the mistake of making the animation so flashy, as in the
recent ``Dinosaur,'' that the story and characters suffer because
of it. Within minutes, you've accepted these characters as
characters, rather than cartoons. This, and a love of Park and
Lord's previous work, might help blind the duo's fans to ``Chicken
Run's'' flaws. Then again, they also might find its occasional
slackness to be a minor letdown. But they won't find the movie to
be a waste of time, because it's true to the Aardman style and
holds the promise of better things to come.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Chicken Run''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Nick Park, Peter Lord
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Julia Sawalha, Mel Gibson
</P>
<P>
   Length: 85 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: G _ family entertainment, with some scary bits and at
least one implication that a chicken is having its head cut off
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
