<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-IRENE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-22 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRENE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ME, MYSELF AND IRENE': WITH BAD TASTE FOR ALL AND CHARITY FOR
NONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' Peter and Bobby Farrelly, proud
sons of Cumberland, R.I., extend the string of heartfelt,
stomach-turning comedies that began with ``Kingpin,'' still the
greatest Amish-bowler road picture ever made, and continued with
``Dumb and Dumber'' and the seminal gross-out masterpiece,
``There's Something About Mary.'' Their characteristic
preoccupations are much in evidence here: characters gratuitously
named Dick or Dickie; animals in medical distress; and an almost
connoisseurial regard for onanism, scatology and _ how to put it? _
sticking things where the sun doesn't shine (in this case, an
oversized sex toy and a live chicken).
</P>
<P>
   If ``There's Something About Mary'' disgusted you with its
callous mockery of hair and pet care and its whimsical views of
stalking and serial killing, ``Me, Myself and Irene'' will make you
miserable indeed. As a character squats down to defecate on a
neighbor's lawn, the brothers (who directed from a script they
wrote with Mike Cerrone) cut to a shot of chocolate soft-serve ice
cream swirling into a cup. They serve up bodily fluids with all the
gusto of deranged sommeliers proffering rare vintage wines. But
``Me, Myself and Irene'' shares with the Farrelly brothers' earlier
movies a kind of dopey, boyish sincerity and a good-natured
sympathy for the underdog that may prove capable of winning over
even the dourest spirits.
</P>
<P>
   The superior ``Mary,'' it's true, had a more inventive story,
the indelible presence of Jonathan Richman as a guitar-strumming
narrator and a range of inspired comic performances, notably
Cameron Diaz's sweet-tempered spitfire and Matt Dillon's besotted
private investigator. What ``Me, Myself and Irene'' has is Jim
Carrey, whose rubberized body and latex fright-mask face dominate
the screen, making the rest of the cast look like well-meaning,
ordinary folk.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey plays Charlie Baileygates, a proud member of ``the
greatest law enforcement organization in the land'' (the Rhode
Island State Police, naturally), who lives with his three sons in a
modest waterfront bungalow. Because of a plot twist I'll refrain
from divulging, Charlie's triplets are African-American academic
prodigies. They humor their adoring dad in his attempts to speak
their language: ``I don't want to have to bust a cap,'' he says,
reminding them to clean up their rooms and do their homework.
</P>
<P>
   The Farrellys like to poke at cultural sensitivities, daring the
audience to take offense and at the same time daring it not to.
Charlie's sons are obvious racial stereotypes but they also mock
the very idea of racial identity. Growing up in a suburban
backwater in one of the whitest little states in the union, Jamaal
(Anthony Anderson), Lee Harvey (Mongo Brownlee) and Shonte Junior
(Jerod Mixon) talk like characters in one of Ice Cube's ``Friday''
movies, a result of their youthful exposure to the stand-up comedy
of Richard Pryor. The most striking thing about this family,
though, is not the color of its members but how loving and loyal
they are to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Some literal-minded souls have objected to this movie's
portrayal of mental illness, since its shambling plot turns on
Charlie's affliction with ``advanced hallucinatory schizophrenia''
accompanied by ``involuntary narcissistic rage.'' Yes, the etiology
of Charlie's disorder is flagrantly inaccurate, but the movie's
message, to the extent that it has one, is one of compassion,
self-awareness and emotional balance. Or maybe I'm crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, in layman's terms, Charlie's diagnosis arises from the
fact that after enduring 18 years of milquetoast humiliation at the
hands of his first wife, his neighbors and the good people of
southern Rhode Island, he suddenly turns into Hank, a lustful
sociopath who expresses himself in skewed tough-guy catchphrases.
``Just because I rock doesn't mean I'm made of stone,'' he tells
Irene, a fugitive golf-course superintendent played with the right
mixture of moxie and bewilderment by Renee Zellweger.
</P>
<P>
   As Hank, Carrey shows the edge of creepiness that made him so
repellent, and so fascinating, in the underrated ``Cable Guy.'' As
Charlie he manifests a dorky sincerity somewhere between ``The
Truman Show'' and ``Dumb and Dumber.'' The two performances become
less distinct as the movie careens toward its climax _ the most
amazing one-man wrestling match since Steve Martin grappled with
the ghost of Lily Tomlin in ``All of Me'' _ but somehow add up to a
credible romantic lead. It's a rare comedian who can be so
completely repulsive and at the same time so lovable.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Me, Myself and Irene'' doesn't really bear
thinking about; at any rate, Cerrone and the Farrellys don't seem
to have given it much thought. Something about crooked dealings
between an upstate New York golf course developer and the
Environmental Protection Agency, and a clutch of standard-issue bad
guys (notably Richard Jenkins and Chris Cooper, in a succession of
Hawaiian shirt and blazer ensembles) _ just enough to send Hank,
Charlie and Irene on a scenic ramble from gag to gag.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they acquire an albino sidekick named Whitey, a
character whose treatment is a perfect illustration of the
Farrellys' comic sensibilities. When Hank first meets Whitey
(Michael Bowman), he subjects him to a torrent of unprovoked, and
hilarious, abuse, which turns to tears of remorse when he realizes
he has hurt the young man's feelings. The audience's feelings after
this sudden tonal shift lie somewhere between guilt and
bewilderment, but they are soon swept away by the next round of
jokes. The humor in ``Me, Myself and Irene'' is often outrageous
but rarely cruel. I hope I don't embarrass the filmmakers, who work
so hard to give offense, by pointing out the streak of tender
humanity that runs through their work. They commit acts of flagrant
bad taste in the service of decency.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Me Myself and Irene'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes _ where to
begin?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ME, MYSELF AND IRENE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bobby Farrelly and Peter Farrelly; written by Peter
Farrelly, Mike Cerrone and Bobby Farrelly; director of photography,
Mark Irwin; edited by Christopher Greenbury; music by Peter Yorn
and Lee Scott; production designer, Sidney J. Bartholomew Jr.;
produced by Bradley Thomas, Bobby Farrelly and Peter Farrelly;
released by 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jim Carrey (Charlie/Hank), Renee Zellweger (Irene),
Anthony Anderson (Jamaal), Mongo Brownlee (Lee Harvey), Jerod Mixon
(Shonte Junior), Chris Cooper (Lieutenant Gerke), Michael Bowman
(Whitey), Richard Jenkins (Agent Boshane) and Robert Forster
(Colonel Partington).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 100 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
