<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1798 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-IRENE-TEX     06-22 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IRENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ME, MYSELF' AND MY TIRED HUMOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no surprise that gross-out masters Peter and Bobby Farrelly
would want to take on split-personality disorder with their latest
movie, ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' because these are guys who want to
have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Guys who want to mock mental illness while convincing you that
they're sympathetic to the afflicted. Guys who treat women as sex
objects, yet generally make them the most grounded, intelligent
characters in their movies. Guys who make a career out of promoting
ethnic stereotypes, but who throw in just enough positive twists to
escape accusations of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Guys who make a movie like ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' which has a
dual personality of its own: It is, at times, laugh-out-loud funny,
albeit in the most outrageous and disgusting ways. But just as
often, it's draggy and slack, and appears to be in need of a good
editing job.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the first time the Farrellys have given the sense that
instead of topping themselves, they're repeating themselves _ and
worse, repeating other movies before them. Because as crass and
politically incorrect as the Farrellys can be, they're usually
wholly original. But in ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' they borrow from
the time-honored ``Jekyll and Hyde/Nutty Professor'' tradition:
Nice guy has badder guy inside him, trying to get out.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal to the Farrellys is obvious: One reason their
particular brand of crude humor works with audiences is that it's
so outlandish, you can believe it's all in fun. But it's often
mean-spirited, and the Farrellys are expert at covering that up by
giving themselves all kinds of loopholes. Heck, after one
vituperative scene in ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' the offending
character actually apologizes for being offensive _ and then has a
brief, ``I just wanna be loved'' breakdown afterward. You can't
give yourself much more of an escape clause than that.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey, returning to his maniacal comic style after more
controlled turns in ``The Truman Show'' and the woefully
underappreciated ``Man on the Moon,'' plays the two-faced character
who's the ``Me, Myself'' of the title. Carrey is Charlie
Baileygates, a mild-mannered Rhode Island state trooper whose life
comes crashing down when his sweetheart (Traylor Howard) makes a
love connection with the angry chauffeur who brought the couple
home from their wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Left in the lurch with triplets who obviously aren't his _ they
grow into strapping and overweight African-American teens _ Charlie
suppresses his anger for 18 years, until one particularly bad day
finally brings out his alter-ego, the hyperaggressive Hank. Hank
speaks in the growl of mid-career Clint Eastwood, and his manner is
something like what might happen if the smarmiest Vegas Elvis
merged with the smuttiest Howard Stern. Carrey's slow burn as he
approaches the transformation is masterful, and his spin into Hank
has an amusing but cruel-edged (and at one point, nauseating)
payoff. Fortunately, he can control the disorder with medication.
Unfortunately, he leaves the meds behind at a crucial point.
</P>
<P>
   That comes when _ through plot convolutions we won't go into
here _ he winds up going on the lam with Irene (an ill-fitting
Renee Zellweger, whose own physical attributes are lampooned).
She's a golf-course maintenance expert who has been set up by her
sleazy ex-boyfriend (Farrelly veteran Daniel Greene) and a crooked
Upstate New York cop (''American Beauty's'' Chris Cooper). Charlie
is assigned to extradite Irene to New York, but when it becomes
clear that she's in danger, bad boy Hank comes to the rescue. He'd
be a hero, except that he has the social skills of a pit bull in
heat.
</P>
<P>
   The American Psychiatric Association recently sent out an e-mail
to film critics condemning ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' for making fun of
the mentally ill _ and for the constant, erroneous description of
Charlie's disorder as ``schizophrenia'' (actually, it's a much
longer description than that, but never mind). Of course, this
being a Farrelly brothers movie, it wouldn't be surprising if
People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, the NAACP, Little
People of America and the National Organization of Albinism and
Hypopigmentation joined the chorus. They all represent groups that
are held up for ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   But something about the Farrellys' envelope- and button-pushing
humor is getting tired. In ``There's Something About Mary,'' their
torture of the little ``Puffy'' dog inspired guilty guffaws; in
``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' a cow gets the animal-mauling treatment,
and it only leads to forced chuckles. One of the key props is what
this newspaper once genteelly referred to as ``an artificial sex
toy,'' but it feels like a mere echo of the zipper and hair-gel
scenes from ``Mary.'' And how many more disasters are the Farrellys
going to contrive for guys alone in bathrooms?
</P>
<P>
   As for Carrey, he performs his own little duality trick by both
rising above the humor with his performance and still managing to
keep in the spirit of the movie's indecent behavior. But his
showcase scene, in which Charlie and Hank finally have a showdown,
is such an overblown piece of self-indulgent physical comedy that
the preview audience _ which up to that point, had laughed
frequently, but not uproariously _ seemed more stunned than amused.
</P>
<P>
   Upstaging Carrey are Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee and Jerod
Mixon, who play Charlie's African-American ``sons'' with verve, wit
and rowdy warmth. They're the best-written characters in the movie,
brilliant students who speak in the most foul-mouthed street
vernacular while discussing such matters as quantum physics. Even
that idea isn't exactly original, but it's entertaining in this
context, and it makes you wonder if the Farrellys focused on the
wrong central idea for a film. Then again, we probably don't want
to see any of these guys in an embarrassing bathroom situation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Peter and Bobby Farrelly
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jim Carrey, Renee Zellweger
</P>
<P>
   Length: 120 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ sexual references, political incorrectness, bathroom
humor in the literal and figurative senses, strong language, and
not-quite-dead-cow abuse
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
