<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ABYSSINIAN-BOOK-REVIE     06-22 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABYSSINIAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ABYSSINIAN CHRONICLES': IN A LAWLESS LAND, A BOY MUST FIND HIS OWN
RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many first novels, Moses Isegawa's ``Abyssinian
Chronicles'' is a first-person account of a young man's coming of
age: a discursive tale of familial struggles, thwarted romances and
picaresque adventures. Isegawa's book, however, takes place in the
1970s and '80s in Uganda, a country wracked by Idi Amin's brutal
reign of terror and the fallout of civil war; and his story not
only traces his hero's loss of innocence but the dissolution of his
entire family and by implication that of an entire country and way
of life.
</P>
<P>
   Isegawa's narrator, Mugezi, is a latter-day descendant of
Fielding and Thackeray's blackguards, transported to the peculiarly
lawless landscape of Amin's Uganda. A malcontent and sometime
scoundrel, Mugezi has learned to manipulate and dissemble in the
course of surviving a Dickensian childhood of alarming violence and
barbarity. He tells the story of his life in a blunt, rough-hewn
narrative devoid of anything resembling rationalization or
emotional censorship. He does nothing to conceal the rage he feels
against his parents and refuses to sentimentalize, or justify, his
own unsavory actions. As a result his story has a strange amoral
power, an immediacy and raw energy that capture the chaotic mood of
his times.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the book is remorseless, its language overheated.
``Uganda was in a state of siege, writhing like a dying moth on the
floor,'' Isegawa writes. ``The bugles of defeat were poised,
waiting to blow the walls down. The inside of the country was like
a grenade whose pin had already been drawn. There was an explosive
feeling in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of two decades of political and social turmoil
Mugezi's family suffers a succession of violent losses. His
grandfather's sister, who worked as the village midwife, is killed
during the coup in which Idi Amin seized power in 1971. One of his
aunts is gang-raped by soldiers during a clash between Amin's
forces and the guerrillas. Another aunt, who was tortured for her
work with anti-Amin forces, comes to power in the aftermath of his
overthrow but soon dies of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mugezi's other relatives, they will succumb to the
centrifugal forces of history and domestic discord, leaving their
small ancestral village for the alienating streets of Kampala, and
in the case of Mugezi, eventually leaving Kampala for a life of
exile abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Mugezi repeatedly refers to his parents as ``the two
dictators,'' drawing implicit comparisons between their tyrannical
rule over their children and Amin's tyrannical rule over Uganda.
Mugezi's mother, Padlock, is a former nun who was expelled from the
convent for beating her students, and her six children bear the
brunt of her frequent and irrational rages. His father, Serenity,
tends to hold himself apart from their domestic wrangles but on one
occasion beats Mugezi so severely that the boy thinks he is going
to die.
</P>
<P>
   To get back at his parents, Mugezi contrives a series of cruel
practical jokes. He forges a love letter from one of his mother's
admirers, causing his father to suspect a heated love affair; he
steals the bobbin from his mother's sewing machine, undermining her
business as a seamstress. (Such is the economic reality of Uganda
that it takes her 90 days to get a new one through the black
market.) His pranks continue when he is sent away to a seminary
school: he vandalizes a car belonging to one of the priests and
defaces the boat of another school official.
</P>
<P>
   It is at the seminary that Mugezi inadvertently discovers a love
of books: in a mercenary effort to get an easy white-collar job at
the school, he finagles himself a position in the library and
stumbles into the realization that books offer a respite from the
dog-eat-dog world around him: they offer ``a reliable escape route
into a safer reality crammed with fantasy and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the reader, Mugezi's accounts of his travails
at home and school quickly grow long-winded. Though his darkly
comic descriptions of his parent's abusive behavior are initially
shocking, they soon devolve into a repetitive pattern of complaint,
and the reader begins to tire of his crude put-downs and even
cruder vows of revenge. When Mugezi looks beyond the suffocating
world of his own travails, however, he proves himself a perceptive
observer, setting down the stories of friends and family members
with a mixture of nostalgia, sadness and regret.
</P>
<P>
   There's his uncle Kawayida, a meter reader for the local energy
company and a master storyteller, who loses a girlfriend and his
youngest child to AIDS. There's his former schoolmate Lwendo, who
persuades Mugezi to join him in a get-rich-quick scheme involving
piracy and blackmail. And there's his grandfather, who warned of
the political ``powder keg'' created by colonialism, and who dies a
violent death during the turmoil surrounding Amin's downfall in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Mugezi's own tale, the stories of these characters
provide a window on recent Ugandan history, a window that enables
us to understand the terrible ways in which public history can
intrude upon private lives, the ways in which the political becomes
the personal.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ABYSSINIAN CHRONICLES'
</P>
<P>
   By Moses Isegawa
</P>
<P>
   462 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
