<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WhirlGirl leads way to timely sites
 &HT;    By Dann Stupp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you're looking for a central place to find
previews of the summer's hottest movies or the latest music videos,
Showtime's scantly clad superheroine is likely the tour guide
you've been looking for.
</P>
<P>
   WhirlGirl, Showtime Networks' cartoon freedom fighter (often
decked out in electric blue pleather), is your host on a
Web-enabled CD-ROM that combines entertainment with one of the
Web's most-impressive new technologies. Install the HyperCD disk,
and you can view clips with instantaneous broadcast quality with as
little as a 33.6k connection to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   SHO.com, Showtime's official Web site, is your home-based movie
theater thanks to this free CD-ROM. Choppy broadcast video is a
thing of the past with HyperCD's new format. You'll get legitimate
DVD-quality video that simply doesn't need hefty data-transfer
rates. Your dial-up connection is more than adequate.
</P>
<P>
   HyperCD technology, a product of BroadBridge Media, allows for
television-like audio and video with no download time. Information
on a CD combines with material on the Web to produce another reason
to become an online addict.
</P>
<P>
   Web users are getting a taste of future Internet broadcasts with
this CD, which is part of SHO.com's Whirl 'N Win Sweepstakes. In
addition to the sneak peak of the future of Internet entertainment,
you can win some high-tech prizes, such as an Italijet Formula
Scooter, a JVC DVD player or even a limited-edition WhirlGirl
action figure.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the sweepstakes, which ends July 14,
stop by SHO.com/whirlgirl. To get the free CD, stop by
participating Electronics Boutique stores or National Amusements
Showcase and Multiplex Cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
