u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-22 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the mind of your average theatergoer, the musical
``Footloose,'' which posted a July 2 closing this week, bears many
of the hallmarks of a long-running Broadway hit.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of its run, after all, it will have staged 737
performances, playing at the Richard Rodgers Theater for well over
a year and half; it will have been seen by hundreds of thousands of
people; and it will have spawned a cast album, a national tour
(with another planned) and promises of future companies in London,
Australia and points beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all that, it is to date, and without a doubt, a
financial flop.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the show is a case study in the always daunting risks
and unseen pitfalls faced by today's producers of Broadway
musicals, a group often faulted for their taste but never their
checkbooks. It also re-emphasizes, despite the faith in the power
of marketing, the steep climb faced by shows with bad reviews
trying to return their investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose'' opened in October 1998 at an estimated cost of
$6.5 million and to a bushel of poor notices with a few good ones
mixed in. Still, producers pushed ahead, and their effort was not
without precedent. In recent years, after all, shows like ``Annie
Get Your Gun'' and ``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' have overcome negative
reviews to build audiences with newfangled demographic direct mail
and old-fashioned advertising blitzes. In the case of
``Footloose,'' producers targeted suburban radio and newspapers,
hoping to tap into fans of the musical's source material, the hit
1984 film that starred Kevin Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The musical's backers were also banking on another time-tested
strategy: brand building. Producers are often willing to take a
loss in New York with hopes of making it back on the road, where
costs are lower, and any ``Broadway musical'' is often the biggest
_ and only _ show in town. Indeed ``Footloose'' begat a tour almost
immediately, sending a troupe out just two months after the show's
Broadway debut.
</P>
<P>
   The producers' stratagems showed some early success, and weekly
sales in New York reached the $550,000 range in November 1998, a
profit of roughly $150,000 a week. At year's end, during the
Christmas rush, the sales topped $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also problems. One was that the costs of running
``Footloose'' were more than expected because of advertising in New
York, which often reached $400,000 a week. Initial projections
called for operating costs of $350,000 or less. The show's brand
also proved less lucrative than expected on the road, with
half-filled houses in some cities. And unlike musicals or plays
that might become films, ``Footloose'' did not hold out the hope of
a sale to another medium; the movie, after all, was already made.
</P>
<P>
   Michael David, the president of the Dodger Theatricals, which
produced ``Footloose,'' did not return several calls for comment.
But an investor who has seen the show's financial statements said
that by last December the show had returned only 5 percent of its
initial investment, a figure that may have grown to about 20
percent by its closing. Still, producers soldiered on, some weeks
losing money, others earning some.
</P>
<P>
   By this spring a new show, ``Seussical,'' a musical based on the
canon of Dr. Seuss, announced it would take over the Richard
Rodgers Theater in the fall, meaning ``Footloose'' would have to
fold or move. In recent months producers retooled parts of the show
and began a new ``Footloose Five'' advertising campaign, featuring
the five young male leads, a strategy aimed at cashing in on the
current boy-band craze. It showed some effect, but in recent weeks
box office grosses dropped precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   In the end there was simply no more gas in the tank. As one
producer not connected to the show said, ```Footloose' burned, but
never exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   Many a New Day
</P>
<P>
   There were subtle signals this week that the production of
``Oklahoma!,'' tentatively scheduled to open on Broadway on Dec. 7,
was inching closer to fruition, and that its theater of choice
would likely be the Ford Center for the Performing Arts, home to
``Jesus Christ Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for neither show would confirm the rumors, but sales
for ``Superstar'' have not been, well, stellar. Last week it sold
54 percent of its seats. A ``Superstar'' cast member who spoke on
condition of anonymity said rumors were flying backstage that the
show would close shortly after Labor Day, adding, ``It has
certainly not been lost upon us that attendance is not great.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility of making way for ``Oklahoma!,''
Adrian Bryan-Brown, a spokesman for ``Superstar,'' said the
producers were about to ``launch a very aggressive advertising and
marketing campaign, because they believe the show has a very large
summer audience.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the fall, when ``Oklahoma!'' is due?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have supreme confidence `Superstar' will find a summer
audience,'' Bryan-Brown reiterated.
</P>
<P>
   Arbor Day
</P>
<P>
   The last time Jeffrey Wright performed in Central Park, in 1991,
the city was in a recession, Christopher Walken and Raul Julia were
playing Iago and Othello, and Wright was playing, in his own words,
``the third cyprus tree from the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed. Beginning on Aug. 8 Wright will be playing
Marc Antony in ``Julius Caesar,'' at the Delacorte Theater,
alongside Jamey Sheridan (Brutus) and David McCallum (Caesar).
</P>
<P>
   The production is nicely timed, Wright said. ``There's something
perfect about doing this Roman play in the middle of this Roman
city,'' he said, referring to New York's imperial pre-eminence.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's transition from tree to leading man has been a steady
one, including performances on Broadway (``Angels in America,''
``Bring in da Noise, Bring in da Funk'') and on film
(``Basquiat''). Currently most people probably associate him with
his film-stealing performance in ``Shaft,'' in which he plays a
drug dealer named Peoples Hernandez, prone to malapropism (``You
can't turn off the dogs of war''), mangled English and menace.
</P>
<P>
   Since the movie opened last week Wright has been besieged with
offers, but he said he couldn't pass up the chance to play a man
``who becomes the very thing that he despises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back onstage,'' he said, ``is a chance to control what I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
