<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ One of the main reasons Robert Rodat, screenwriter
of 1998's ``Saving Private Ryan,'' decided to set his follow-up
film during the American Revolution was that it was a period and a
setting that movie audiences had not seen, at least not in many
years, and not in such an epic, sweeping format.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, there haven't been a lot of films about the
American Revolution, and I don't know why,'' Rodat said. ``I
thought about it a lot lately. I think part of it may be the degree
to which the Western mythology, beginning in the 1860s and coming
right up to the modern day, became so dominant in American
mythology. The Revolution doesn't tap into that classic American
mythology; it feels more like an English conflict, with the wigs
and people talking about principles.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Patriot,'' directed by Roland Emmerich, Mel Gibson
plays a South Carolina landowner who decides to sit out the war to
protect his motherless brood but is eventually forced, by
circumstances and the prodding of a patriotic son, to take up the
musket. At 2 hours and 40 minutes, it is the most epic in scope of
the three big movies scheduled to open in time for the Independence
Day weekend, probably the most competitive weekend of the summer.
(The others are ``The Perfect Storm'' and ``The Adventures of Rocky
and Bullwinkle.'')
</P>
<P>
   This holiday promises to be particularly lucrative because it
falls on a Tuesday. The long Fourth of July holiday weekend is
always a major period at the box office, with big films often
opening the previous Wednesday (``The Patriot'' opens on Wednesday,
the other films on Friday) and running strongly through the
weekend. But with the holiday on a Tuesday, there is a strong
chance that the moviegoing will continue at a holiday pace for two
extra days, providing a movie that opens the previous Wednesday
with a full week of holiday weekend box-office steam.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gordon, one of the movie's three producers (there were also
three executive producers and two associate producers), said he
remembered sitting down with Rodat, with whom he has worked on
several films, right after the release of ``Saving Private Ryan''
and trying to decide what backdrop they would choose for their next
project. ``Bob mentioned the American Revolution,'' Gordon said,
``and we both thought, yes, this was something that hadn't been
seen in a while, something that would feel fresh to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodat and Gordon sold the idea for the film to Columbia Pictures
and developed the screenplay over 18 months. Initially they thought
they would use an actual historical figure (Francis Marion, the
legendary Swamp Fox, who bedeviled British troops from the marshes
of the coastal Carolinas), but eventually they turned their
character into an amalgam of several guerrilla fighters from the
Southern campaign, most particularly Andrew Pickens, who, like
Gibson's character, had a large family and tried to stay out of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like watching big-canvas movies and I enjoy writing them,
but the essence of a big-canvas movie has to be a tiny story,''
Rodat said. ``That's certainly what David Lean taught us. So I find
when I'm writing a big, sweeping sort of screenplay, I am wearing
two hats. I'm the miniaturist and the painter of the big canvas,
all at the same time. I must write something that has scope and
scale, but at the same time has that little human window that
allows us to enter that big world.''
</P>
<P>
   A Nod to Wireless
</P>
<P>
   When executives from the French conglomerate Vivendi announced
this week that they were purchasing Seagram and its Universal
Studios, they hung their future prospects upon the economic
viability of the coming generation of wireless hand-held devices
that many in Hollywood believe will be the entertainment industry's
next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi's device, called Vizzavi (as in vis-a-vis), is just one
of many being developed in hopes that people will very soon be able
to connect to the Internet from wherever they are, without phone
lines, to download music, video games, short films, television-like
programs and even, some think, feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely true that wireless is going to be
big,'' said John Hegeman, who has long straddled the worlds of the
Web and the movie industry, first helping put together Internet
marketing campaigns for films, including last summer's ``Blair
Witch Project,'' and now as a partner with Joe Roth, a former
Disney executive, in Distantcorners.com, an Internet entertainment
site aimed at young science-fiction and horror fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd say it's going to be something more like a radio or a
portable television set than a portable movie theater,'' he said.
While Hegeman said he could certainly see people whipping out their
hand-held devices to watch a five-minute short, or check the news,
or send e-mail, he has a harder time imagining that many people
will want to watch big Hollywood movies on something that can fit
into their hand.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the results, there is certainly growing ferment in
Hollywood over how the Internet will affect the way movies are
distributed. This is, of course, a matter of some concern to those
who have based their strategies on the long-established way of
doing things, in which movies are first released in theaters and
only then sent out to subsidiary venues like television and
videotape. Will the Internet somehow threaten the primacy of the
theatrical release?
</P>
<P>
   In part to bolster this theatrical primacy, the Academy of
Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences issued a statement this week
clarifying its rules about what films are eligible to compete for
the Academy Awards, making it clear that only those films that have
their first showings in a Los Angeles movie theater can compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board just wants to make it crystal clear so that in the
rush to embrace new technologies, a legitimate theatrical motion
picture doesn't inadvertently jeopardize its eligibility,'' said
Bruce Davis, the academy's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if Universal or any other studio decides in the
future to release a film initially on the Internet _ perhaps to
show off some new technological advance _ the film will be treated
in the same way as one shown for the first time on television.
</P>
<P>
   In response, IFilm, one of the leading companies offering
streaming video on the Internet, scrambled and put together a deal
with the AMC theater chain to allow some of Ifilm's shorts to be
shown to paying audiences for three consecutive days in a Los
Angeles cinema before being released on the Web. This is all that
is required to qualify for the Oscars, said IFilm's chairman, Kevin
Wendle.
</P>
<P>
   The official 73rd Academy Awards booklet will be sent to members
in early August. If you want to mark your calendar, nominations for
films released in 2000 will be announced on Feb. 13 and the Oscar
ceremonies will be, once again, at the Shrine Auditorium in Los
Angeles on March 25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
