   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-EXECUTION (Huntsville, Texas) _ The Texas pardons board
declines to halt the execution of convicted killer Gary Graham,
clearing the way for his death by injection to take place this
evening. By SALATHEIA BRYANT, LISA TEACHEY and MIKE TOLSON.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-WATER (Houston) _ Scientists say cameras aboard NASA's Mars
Global Surveyor photographed 120 areas where it appears water has
recently flowed down gullies and quickly evaporated into the
planet's thin atmosphere. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Thawing relations between North
and South Korea, with the growing possibility that Pyongyang might
dismantle its intercontinental ballistic missile program,
dramatically undercut the rationale for a costly U.S. defense
system, military experts say. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FUNDING (Washington) _ House negotiators have agreed to
trim San Francisco's share of federal AIDS funding over five years
while increasing money for 50 other cities. House members from the
San Francisco Bay Area are upset. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NADER-HOFFA (Washington) _ Consumer activist Ralph Nader, the
likely Green Party presidential candidate, holds a news conference
with Teamsters President James Hoffa. Hoffa offers no endorsement
of Nader, but says the candidate is more in step with working
Americans and the labor movement than Democrat Al Gore. By JOHN
HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-VENTURA (St. Paul, Minn.) _ Vice President Al gore calls on
Gov. Jesse Ventura at a school in Minnesota, using the opportunity
to discuss his plans
</P>
<P>
   to improve special education. Ventura has a teen-age daughter
with a learning disability. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is about
to do a good deed for the country and his own political prospects.
He has ordered that the Republican National Convention dump the
party's 20-year-old plank demanding that the Department of
Education be abolished. The GOP took this position at the
insistence of the religious right, but the negative symbolism of
trying to downgrade the status of education has been a loser for
the Republicans. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ECONOMY (Havana, Cuba) _ Cuba, playing up its tropical good
times and rogue reputation, hopes to reap a tourist bonanza. Fidel
Castro expects a boost in tourist dollars to help the island nation
dig out of its economic hole created by the U.S. trade embargo and
the loss of Eastern Bloc subsidies. The House is expected to vote
next week to partially lift the embargo by ending sanctions on U.S.
sales of food, medicine and medical supplies to Cuba. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
