<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CROUPIER0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Croupier can't keep his distance as temptation builds
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Pity the poor casino croupiers. They watch
impassively, hour after hour, as customers lose vast sums of money,
grow hostile and hurl abuse. From their bosses, they must endure
the assumption that they are untrustworthy and dishonest. Of
course, much of the time, the bosses are absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Manfred is not your run-of-the-mill casino drone. He
tells us in the even-toned voice-over narration of Mike Hodges'
cerebral little thriller ``Croupier'' that he is not drawn to
gamble. He is content to be an observer of life rather than a
participant. After all, he keeps reminding himself, the only reason
he is dealing blackjack and working a roulette wheel is to gather
material for his long-sought novel.
</P>
<P>
   But in the course of this well-observed, low-key morality play,
Jack and his ethical compass will be sorely tested. Slowly and
inexorably, we come to understand just how human he is beneath his
emotionless exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the lavish fantasy world of Las Vegas. ``Croupier''
exists in the cramped, tawdry gaming clubs of London, a domain that
screenwriter Paul Meyersberg understands and director Hodges (''Get
Carter'') captures in all its paranoid glory.
</P>
<P>
   Strapped for cash, Jack goes against his instincts when his
father calls and tips him off to a croupier job at the Golden Lion
casino. And from the way Jack manipulates the chips at his
interview, he evidently has a history of being around casinos. On
his shift, he looks robotically dispassionate, but from his
thoughts we learn that he is getting hooked again, taking vicarious
enjoyment from watching players lose. As Jack, Clive Owen
understands the value of a poker face. His performance is
understated in the extreme, but it is right for the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Croupier'' defies most expectations of conventional thrillers,
but Jack's downfall still comes at the hands of seductive women.
When deciding whom not to trust, be wary of Bella (Kate Hardie),
the dealer who undresses too casually in the unisex locker room and
breaks fraternization rules by seducing Jack. Be suspicious of Jani
(''ER''s Alex Kingston), more adept at gambling than she lets on,
who will woo Jack into scamming the casino.
</P>
<P>
   And while you are at it, watch out for Jack's live-in fiancee
Marion (''Notting Hill's'' Gina McKee), who far prefers the
romantic notion of marrying a novelist than a croupier.
</P>
<P>
   As his novel progresses, Jack starts thinking like his dealer
alter ego Jake, a literary conceit that never has much dramatic
payoff. Gradually, perhaps inevitably, ``Croupier `` reduces down
to being about the casino scam and the question of who is behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   The gritty texture of the film and Jack/Jake's deadpan narration
both prove more satisfying than the plot's wrap-up, so enjoy the
verbal and visual atmosphere as it wends its way to the conclusion.
``Croupier'' needs more of a knockout punch line, but for an icy,
dark, yet harshly lit tale, this is a bet worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
