<SLUG> BC-BLESSEDRETREATS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONASTERIES OFFER ROOMS, MEALS AND REMARKABLE HOSPITALITY TO WEARY
TRAVELERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAGANI, Italy _ The server in the simple dining room of our
hotel set down our first course _ expertly cooked penne tossed with
prosciutto, olive oil and freshly shaved Parmesan _ and looked at
us expectantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vino?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   We just stared at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhh ... wine?'' she said, groping for the English word,
assuming we hadn't understood.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we'd heard her; we just hadn't believed her, just as
we couldn't believe the courses she kept bringing: A salad of
tender butter lettuce, dressed in a fresh lemon vinaigrette; thin
pan-fried pork steaks, with more lemon; crusty Italian bread;
eggplant and portobello mushrooms sauteed with a touch of balsamic
vinegar. Fresh tangerines and strong coffee with real cream. And a
chaser of iced ``limoncello,'' the locally produced lemon liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   This was a monastery?
</P>
<P>
   True, the Monastero di Santa Maria della Purita in Pagani, near
Naples, wasn't a five-star hotel _ our upstairs double room
resembled a Catholic boarding school, circa 1970, and it would have
been unbearably cold if the staff hadn't thoughtfully hauled in an
ancient space heater. But for $22 a night apiece _ including two
meals _ we weren't about to complain.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder more American travelers in Italy, and to a lesser
extent the rest of Europe, are catching on to this centuries-old
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who are looking for a different way to experience
Italy, this is the perfect niche,'' says Eileen Barish, author of
``The Guide to Lodging in Italy's Monasteries'' (Anacapa Press;
$22.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're inexpensive, you know you will be safe, you know the
innkeepers will be respectful ... and some of them are in the most
gorgeous locations and the most gorgeous old buildings you could
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   In Italy alone, there are at least 500 inns, apartments or
full-fledged hotels run by religious orders _ everything from
converted 13th-century castles to modern 1960s-style high-rises to
country villas to a four-star hotel on the Italian Riviera. The
majority accept both male and female guests without regard to
denomination, and charge just enough to cover their costs or
perhaps make a small profit.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition dates back hundreds of years, says Barish,
beginning when friars traveling to see family or make pilgrimages
were invited to stay at monasteries along the way. The monasteries
and convents eventually expanded to take in other guests;
Europeans, especially families and singles, have traveled this way
for decades, Barish says.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, however, were slow to catch on, partly because
information was hard to find. Italy's tourism organizations don't
offer much help in finding such lodging; insiders say that's
because they're pressured not to by commercial hotels, which see
the religious institutions as competition. There was little
information in English until Barish's book and another similar
guide came out, both, coincidentally, last year.
</P>
<P>
   The other guidebook, ``Bed and Blessings Italy: A Guide to
Convents and Monasteries Available for Overnight Lodging'' (Paulist
Press; $16.95), was written by American mother-daughter team Anne
and June Walsh, who took three long trips to Italy to research the
book, staying at a number of convents. (The Walshes are currently
working on similar guides for the United Kingdom, France and the
Middle East.)
</P>
<P>
   The word is getting around. In Rome, for instance, I met a group
of three American women traveling across northern Italy this way;
they were staying in a convent near the Vatican, perfect for
touring the papal state. The rooms were often a bit austere, they
said, but the hosts and hostesses had been gracious and helpful.
And nowhere had they paid more than $30 apiece, a true bargain in
cities where even the simplest ``pensione'' can charge at least
$50.
</P>
<P>
   If the positives are obvious, so are the negatives. Some
convents and monasteries have curfews. Most rooms are on the simple
side; some don't even supply towels and sheets, much less shampoo
and soap. You probably won't have a TV or a phone. Sometimes, baths
are down the hall and must be shared with other guests. And the
inns are often run by nuns, monks or priests who have other duties
and may lack the tourism expertise you'd get at a similar-size
hotel. You may not find many people who speak English, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, even with the new guides, finding a room at a convent
or missionary when and where you want it will take some legwork;
some fill up with groups, others close for the winter or for entire
months in the summer. But those who are persistent _ and a bit
lucky _ can find a whole new way to see Italy.
</P>
<P>
   After our first attempt at staying at a convent, we were not
sure it was a way we were going to like.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   My friend Nichele and I had booked a room in an apartment owned
by a small order of nuns in Scala, a tiny town perched on the top
of a hillside on the Amalfi coast, with beautiful views of the
lemon groves and terra-cotta-roofed villas tumbling down to the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cold day, spitting sleet and snow, when we arrived in
the village to find the convent, which proved not so easy to
locate. It was not well-marked, and no one answered the door the
first time we knocked. Our cab driver kindly drove us up and down
the town's main street, going with us to knock on doors until we
finally found a priest who figured out what we wanted. It took more
than an hour of inept charades and mangled Italian before we were
settled.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment, which was next to a small, friendly inn where we
could take our meals, was clean and spacious and stocked with
towels and linens. But its other amenities were sparse. It was
dimly lit, the hot water worked only sporadically, and though the
heaters made a great deal of noise, we never coaxed them to produce
any actual heat. After dinner, we pulled all the extra blankets off
the unused beds and went to sleep wearing our coats and gloves. We
woke up considering canceling that night's reservation in a second
monastery.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, that second institution, the Monastero di
Santa Maria della Purita, did not seem to hold much more promise.
It was located in the nondescript town of Pagani, part of the vast
urban sprawl surrounding Mount Vesuvius and the ruins of Pompeii.
Again, we found it only by accident, having jumped off the bus at
the wrong spot and thus being forced to ask passersby for
directions. From the outside, with its ornate but weathered facade
stuck in a not-very-prosperous-looking strip of clothing stores,
shoe shops and small groceries, the place looked a little cold and
run-down.
</P>
<P>
   But inside, we were pleasantly surprised. The 18th-century
monastery was built around a courtyard filled with green tropical
plants, lemon trees and wrought-iron furniture. As we reached the
end of the hallway, we were greeted by the director, who dispatched
assistants to help us to our room and to inquire when we wanted to
eat dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms themselves were small and simple _ plain twin beds,
crucifixes, a simple but clean private bathroom, and an unadorned
particleboard desk. The tiled hallways were much more interesting,
filled with dark antique furniture, religious paintings and,
downstairs, a large, old-fashioned birdcage filled with parakeets.
The dining room was reminiscent of a private-college dining hall _
plain wooden tables were covered with utilitarian plastic covers
over the white tablecloths, glass-fronted wooden cabinets held
large numbers of glasses and china, and a large TV sat unused.
</P>
<P>
   But the food, and the service, were excellent. Dinner took
nearly two hours, partly because our young servers kept pressing us
with more food and more red wine from bottles labeled with the
monastery's name, and partly because assorted nuns, priests and
other workers kept stopping in to check on us. No one spoke any
more English than we spoke Italian _ which is to say, none of us
had a clue what the other was saying _ but everyone was cheerful,
and intent on making us eat and drink more.
</P>
<P>
   After joining us for shots of ``limoncello,'' the director
proudly insisted on showing us through the monastery. The order was
locally famous for nativity scenes _ the monks collect them from
around the world, and half a dozen large glass cases are filled
with Christmas sets from more than 30 countries. The Dutch ones
featured windmills; Nigerian ones depicted Joseph and Mary wearing
kente cloth; the Chinese ones had a pagoda in the background. There
were sets from France, from Brazil, from Japan and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   But outside was the real centerpiece. Each winter, the monks
create a vast dollhouse-scale nativity scene in six massive
tableaux, complete with moving angels, intricate hand-built street
scenes, piped-in music and fake blowing snow. It took them more
than a month to build; they kept it up until February so that
everyone in town could enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, after we'd enjoyed a quiet (and warm) night's
sleep, the director insisted on driving us to the train station; we
were headed to Rome and a night at a commercial three-star hotel.
Just the day before, we couldn't wait to get back to a ``real''
hotel. Now we finally understood why rooms in religious houses have
appealed to travelers for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
