<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-22 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REPATRIATION' BECOMES A DEALER'S COUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, France, Switzerland)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Auction houses may make a lot of news but they don't score all
the coups in acquiring private collections to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett, the 135-year-old London antiques dealer, recently
snared a major collection of neoclassical English furniture from an
American Anglophile who decided to ``repatriate'' his antiques.
They went on view in Mallett's Bond Street gallery last week in an
exhibition titled ``The Age of Matthew Boulton: Masterpieces of
Neoclassicism.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes works by Robert Adam (1728-1792), the
architect and designer of country houses in England and Scotland;
the royal cabinetmakers Mayhew &AMP; Ince (circa 1770); and Matthew
Boulton (1728-1809), a lesser-known designer who was called the
``master of English ormolu.''
</P>
<P>
   The consigner wants to remain anonymous, said Lanto Synge, chief
executive of Mallett. ``We've known him for a long time,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   For the past 30 years he has acquired from us, at auction and
all sorts of places. He is an industrialist who is approaching
retirement. He has been very discerning, even persnickety. He built
up a collection of superlative standards and condition. Now he is
having a change of direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes a pair of torcheres that Adam supplied
for the Earl of Bathurst, the first owner of Apsley House in
London, which was donated to the Duke of Wellington after he
defeated Napoleon. Adam designed the interiors of Apsley House, now
open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition reminds visitors how neoclassical taste goes in
and out of style. As Synge put it, ``It seems to have come in waves
ever since the Renaissance.'' After the discovery of Herculaneum in
the 1700s, designers from England, France, Sweden and even America
flocked to Italy for inspiration. Adam went to sketch temples,
tombs, monuments and the walls of Pompeii and Herculaneum. Those
motifs then showed up in his design repertory. ``Adam was the
greatest Grand Tourist of them all,'' Synge said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's George III giltwood and gesso torcheres and candelabra,
from about 1780, are in the exhibition. They have triangular
plinths on claw feet, with oval medallions depicting women in
classical dress playing music. The corners have ram heads. Seated
griffins are separated by a classical urn.
</P>
<P>
   Another Adam piece is a stand he designed for his friend George
Keate. It is made of tulipwood and satinwood, to complement a
precious 1711 Italian pietra-dura medals cabinet that Keate had
bought in Rome. The small oak box has ebony veneers inset with
colorful hardstone fruits and flowers. On the top, a toucan perches
on a cherry branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few miniature jewel-like boxes like this,''
Synge said, ``and we know Adam designed its stand because we found
his drawing for this very piece in the Sir John Soane Museum.'' The
museum has 9,000 Adam drawings, which Soane bought from Adam's
daughters years after his death, when they desperately needed the
money.
</P>
<P>
   The stand is in Adam's Etruscan style, with neoclassical motifs
on an ebony ground. Each side has a frieze with a pair of ormolu
griffins flanking a vase. Beneath are ormolu laurel swags and bows.
``There was a big following for neoclassical taste in the late
1700s,'' Synge said. ``But Adam was its grandest proponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett is selling an equally neoclassical George III rolltop
desk attributed to the fashionable London cabinetmakers Mayhew &AMP;
Ince, contemporaries of Adam. The ladylike rolltop was made about
1775. The frieze on the front of the single drawer also has
griffins, but they are done in penwork, on partridgewood panels.
The tambour top has satinwood and yew bands decorated with inlaid
wavy lines. The four tapering legs are decorated with zigzag,
so-called shark-tooth marquetry. It was on loan to the Metropolitan
Museum of Art until January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayhew &AMP; Ince probably invented the rolltop desk,'' Synge
said. ``There are two or three known, but this is the greatest one.
It must have been inspired by the French cylinder desk.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had unearthed some of the desk's history: ``It was
acquired by Archibald, fifth Earl of Rosebery, and his wife, Hannah
de Rothschild, of Mentmore, in 1875. Lord Dalmeny, Rosebery's heir,
looked it up for us in the family records and found the bill _ it
was (PS)500.''
</P>
<P>
   England was suffering through an agricultural depression at the
time, and land prices had collapsed. ``The Roseberys took advantage
of the dispersal of collections formed during the 18th century,''
Synge said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Earl of Rosebery (1847-1929) had his own financial
concerns. Synge said he had insisted on inserting a proviso into
the bill for the desk, which was an expensive piece of furniture
even then. The earl was a famous horse breeder. He stipulated that
he could forfeit the desk and return it if his racehorse did not
win the English Derby that year. Fortunately for the cabinetmakers,
the horse won and he paid his bill. Mallett is asking about
$983,000 for the desk.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett is also selling 20 pieces by Boulton, a 19th-century
engineer from the Midlands of England who was a pioneer in the
development of early locomotives and made a fortune. At some point
he decided he would design items like clocks and candelabra in
bronze gilded to look like solid gold.
</P>
<P>
   Because Boulton was an engineer, not a classicist, his
``repertoire of ornament was drawn from books, models borrowed from
other makers, plaster casts, other artifacts, architects, indeed
from anywhere and anyone,'' Nicholas Goodison writes in the Mallett
catalog. ``He set out to rival the French bronziers.'' It is rare
to have 20 pieces on display at one time, according to Mallett.
</P>
<P>
   One perfume burner has a plinth with a medallion showing an
allegory of the death of Adonis. Beneath it, a mourning Venus and
crying Cupid are putting out the Flame of Love, as a Dove of Peace
looks on, perched on a quiver of arrows. Another piece, a clock,
shows a gilded Minerva in armor and helmet, carrying a spear. The
shield of Medusa rests at her feet.
</P>
<P>
   Boulton works can often be identified because he used local
stones with his ormolu mounts. He especially liked Derbyshire
``blue john,'' a type of amethyst fluorspar. But the Boulton story
has an unhappy ending. ``He tried to cash into the luxury market
and ended up going bust,'' Synge said. ``But he did great work.''
Proust Galleys
</P>
<P>
   The 52 long-lost galley sheets for Proust's ``Swann's Way,''
auctioned at Christie's in London on June 7, sold for $1,012,218, a
world record at auction for a work of French literature. The buyer
was the Martin Bodmer Collection in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Felix de Marez-Oyens, director of Christie's international book
department, said the manuscript was acquired for the Martin Bodmer
collection at the Bibliotecca Bodmericana, a library in
French-speaking Switzerland, which will make it available to
literary scholars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
