<SLUG> BC-GORE-OIL-PANIC-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVOUS GORE ATTACKS `GOUGING' OIL COMPANIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Midwest Editors)   (This 500-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore launched a broadside against
the oil companies Wednesday, accusing them of ``oil-gouging and
price-fixing.'' His accusations added to the outcry from America's
car-dependent consumers and electioneering politicians about the
sharply rising price of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, he said that he was ``extremely
concerned about the conduct of the oil companies that may have led
to these unreasonable price increases.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures, Gore said, showed that oil company profits
had increased by as much as 500 percent in the first part of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Without waiting for the FTC's findings, he said: ``These
enormous and unreasonable profits suggest that big oil is gouging
American consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The worry for Gore as the Democratic presidential candidate is
twofold. Price rises through last autumn and winter were almost
uniform across the country, drawing complaints from the more
northerly states that use large quantities of heating oil, as well
as from states like California and Virginia with large numbers of
long-distance car commuters, not to speak of truck drivers all over
America.
</P>
<P>
   Recent fuel price rises, however, have been especially sharp in
the Midwest, in and around cities such as Chicago and Milwaukee,
where the price of gas has reached the almost unimaginable (to an
American) heights of two dollars a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, the price across the United States was only
just over one dollar, dipping in some places in some weeks even
below that.
</P>
<P>
   The big Midwestern states are widely regarded as the ground on
which November's presidential election will be won or lost. Gore is
currently running neck and neck with his Republican rival, George
W. Bush, in such key swing states as Illinois and Ohio _ which Bill
Clinton won for the Democrats last time around.
</P>
<P>
   Bush must be careful how he handles the oil price issue; much of
the Bush family's wealth derives from oil, and any conclusion that
U.S. oil companies, as opposed to ``foreigners,'' have been
profiteering could have an adverse effect on his electoral chances.
</P>
<P>
   The greater danger, though, is to Gore. While the rise in gas
prices, if not stemmed soon, could damage his prospects in the
crucial Midwest, they could also have a knock-on effect on the
economy generally, as truckers find their margins shrinking and the
price of road distribution and delivery raises prices generally.
</P>
<P>
   The country's current economic well-being is a pillar of Gore's
election strategy; ``prosperity and progress'' was the slogan
chosen to headline his three-week campaign swing across the United
States that ends next week.
</P>
<P>
   But some signs of an economic slowdown _ fewer house sales,
fewer new housing starts, a slight fall in imports and a similarly
slight decline in orders in some parts of the country _ are already
appearing.
</P>
<P>
   If higher oil prices compound the subduing effect of recent
interest rate rises, Gore's claim to a record of ultra-successful
economic stewardship could start to ring very hollow. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
