<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     06-22 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: entertaining (Scott.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``M:I-2,'' starring Tom Cruise, Thandie Newton and Sir Anthony
Hopkins. Directed by John Woo (PG-13, 120 minutes). Cruise returns
as the daredevil secret agent Ethan Hunt in Woo's loud, flashy,
incoherent new blockbuster. The film is jampacked with movie
references _ to Hitchcock, to the first ``Mission: Impossible''
movie and to Woo's superior Hong Kong action films _ but it's at
once overheated and flat. The plot, involving killer viruses, is
baffling rather than twisty. The introduction of a love interest (
Newton) who also happens to be the bad guy's ex-girlfriend adds an
element of melodrama that's more grating than affecting. Some good
car chases and explosions, though (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``SHAFT,'' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa Williams, Jeffrey
Wright, Christian Bale, Toni Collette, Richard Roundtree and Mekhi
Phifer. The always dependable and indomitable Jackson stars as John
Shaft, nephew of the seminal freelance crime fighter ( Roundtree).
A Manhattan police detective when introduced, Shaft leaves the
force to bring to justice a wealthy, heartless WASP racist ( Bale)
who has beaten a black man ( Phifer) to death. Aware that racial
politics have changed since the 1971 original, the picture wants to
trade on the not-so-subtle differences between stereotype and
archetype, and breaks a sweat trying to shatter each. When
``Shaft'' scores at the box office, it will be a cheap,
opportunistic victory, but an enjoyable one (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``SHANGHAI NOON,'' starring Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson.
Directed by Tom Dey (PG-13, 110 minutes). Chan is one of the great
physical comedians, and this martial arts western spoof is a
high-spirited, marvelously silly showcase for his talents. Chan
plays Chon Wang, an Imperial Guard dispatched from Beijing to the
Old West to rescue a princess played by Lucy Liu. But the heart of
the movie is the interplay between Chan and Wilson, who depicts his
inept outlaw sidekick with goofy, spacey charm. After the glum
bullying of ``Gladiator'' and the noisy bombast of ``M:I-2,'' it's
refreshing to see a movie so good-natured, so confident in its
ability to provoke not queasy awe or numb exhaustion but pure
delight (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``SUNSHINE,'' starring Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer
Ehle, Rosemary Harris and James Frian. Directed by Istvan Szabo (R,
180 minutes). In Szabo's tale of 20th-century Hungarian history,
Fiennes plays three members of a wealthy Jewish Budapest family _
grandfather, father and son _ who endure the corruption of the
Austro-Hungarian empire, the viciousness of fascism and the
brutality of Communism. Fiennes' performances, and those of Ehle
and Harris (playing the same character at different stages of life)
help save the film from melodramatic excess. ``Sunshine'' is a
serious, humane and thought-provoking attempt to make sense of
complicated and painful historical experiences (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``TITAN A.E.'' With the voices of Matt Damon, Drew Barrymore and
Bill Pullman. Directed by Don Bluth and Gary Coleman (PG, 90
minutes). This animated sci-fi fantasy, set in the 31st century,
imagines that Earth has been destroyed by aliens and what is left
of humanity is scattered about the universe in drifter colonies.
Guided by a magic ring left to him by his father, Cale ( Damon), a
teen-age space explorer, searches for the Titan, a hidden spaceship
with the key to humanity's future. The technology is innovative,
and there are some gorgeous special effects. But the screenplay and
characters are too bland for the story to catch fire (Holden)
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571,'' starring Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Jon Bon
Jovi, David Keith and Harvey Keitel. Directed by Jonathan Mostow
(PG-13, 120 minutes). Mostow, whose previous film, ``Breakdown,''
was a marvel of B-picture minimalism, shifts from the wide-open
spaces to the cramped interior of a World War II submarine movie.
McConaughey, whose knotted-with-unease face makes it look as if he
were cramming for finals, is part of a secret mission to capture a
Nazi code-encryption machine and get it back to the Allies. He and
his crew have to do so on a Nazi U-boat they have hijacked. Mostow
does a fine job of building tension, given that he is working in a
minor genre whose climactic notes you will know if you have ever
seen a movie set on a sub (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE VIRGIN SUICIDES,'' starring Kirsten Dunst, James Woods and
Kathleen Turner. Directed by Sofia Coppola (R, 97 minutes).
Coppola's directorial debut, adapted from Jeffrey Eugenides' 1993
novel about the self-destruction of five sisters in a 1970s
Michigan suburb, shows her to be a filmmaker with fine visual and
emotional instincts, adept at matching the book's hypnotic, sensual
black humor. The movie's best moments have an inspired feeling of
playfulness and freedom matched by Dunst's smart, beguiling
performance as Lux Lisbon, whose sexual awakening propels her and
her sisters to their doom. But despite Coppola's keen instincts,
and the beautifully understated acting of Woods and Turner as the
Lisbon parents, ``The Virgin Suicides'' is marred by the
self-conscious aestheticism and emotional detachment of its source
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
