u f BC-AOL23-COX     06-22 1915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REGULATORS, NOT SHAREHOLDERS, MAY BE KEY TO AOL-TIME WARNER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When shareholders of America Online Inc. and Time
Warner Inc. meet Friday morning, they almost certainly will approve
the merger of the media behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   But the combination of one of the world's largest entertainment
and news companies with the No. 1 Internet provider, worth roughly
$120 billion, still needs the approval of the Federal Trade
Commission, the Federal Communications Commission and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates are pushing those regulators to block the
merger, or at least limit the power of the new media giant. While
AOL predicts it will win regulatory approval by fall, consumer
groups say their battle against the merger is gaining momentum for
two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ Recent actions by AOL involving its Instant Messager and by
Time Warner involving cable TV programming demonstrate ``that the
companies cannot be trusted to act properly without more rules in
place,'' said Harold Feld, associate director of the Media Access
Project, a non-profit public interest group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ The European Union is taking a much tougher stance towards
mergers. On Monday, European antitrust authorities announced they
would take as many as four more months to review AOL and Time
Warner, which have extensive operations there. On Tuesday, the
Washington Post reported the EU is likely to scuttle a separate but
somewhat similar merger, that of MCI WorldCom Inc. and Sprint
Corp., because of questions about control of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very heartened by the EU,'' said Jeffrey Chester,
executive director of the Center for Media Education, a non-profit
group in Washington. By taking tough antitrust stands, ``the
Europeans have created a political moment here _ an opportunity to
preserve the vitality of the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL shareholders will meet at 10 a.m. EDT Friday in a hotel not
far from its Dulles, Va., headquarters. Time Warner shareholders
will meet at the same hour in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced Jan. 10, AOL's stock price has
fallen to $56.50 from $72.69, while Time Warner stock has risen to
$81.4375 from $64.75.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts and corporate executives expect
shareholders to approve the creation of the world's largest media
company, one capable of providing a wealth of proprietary content
to AOL's 23 million subscribers over high-speed Time Warner cable
lines.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what has regulators concerned.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, much of the worry centers on the online delivery of
entertainment. There, AOL has a four-year agreement with
Bertelsmann AG, Germany's largest media company, guaranteeing that
company will have access to AOL as a marketplace for its music,
television and publishing content. By absorbing Time Warner, AOL
also will gain ``preferential access to the leading source of music
publishing rights and music repertoire'' in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Given such advantages, there is a danger AOL will become not
just another competitor in the music industry, but rather the
``gatekeeper in the emerging online music distribution channel,''
the European Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   To appease regulators, AOL has offered some concessions, but the
commission called them ``insufficient'' to ease concerns about
competition.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, consumer groups, regulators and some
lawmakers are questioning whether AOL Time Warner could monopolize
the Internet by leveraging its position as a high-speed Internet
provider and a marketer of proprietary content and services.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say the key issue is ``open access.'' They
argue that the Internet has grown wildly because its operating
standards allow everyone to use it. For example, a person who gets
access to the Internet through EarthLink Inc. can send e-mail to an
AOL customer.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL is seen as moving away from an open model with its
Instant Messager software, which allows users to send quick
messages to people on their ``buddy lists.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC wants Internet companies to establish a standard that
would allow instant message providers to interact. But AOL has
battled hard to prevent competitors, such as Microsoft Corp. and
Tribal Voice Inc., from connecting with AOL Instant Messenger and
AOL's other closed system, ICQ.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, AOL submitted a proposal to an Internet standards
group to create the technical specifications to allow interaction,
but critics still accuse the company of foot-dragging. The FCC has
asked AOL to explain its Instant Messenger policies as part of its
review of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner also stirred up fears about monopolistic tendencies
after it shut down ABC programming for 3.5 million cable
subscribers during a contract dispute this spring. Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
condemned the company's willingness to ``restrict consumer choice
to gain market leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates fear that once AOL and Time Warner put
together immense marketing power with broadband Internet services,
they will kill the open nature of the Internet and reduce consumer
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of an Internet where everyone can connect, they want
to turn it into a private network where their content will be
featured and favored,'' Chester said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   America Online, www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Inc., www.timewarner.com
</P>
<P>
   Media Access Project, www.mediaacess.org
</P>
<P>
   Center for Media Education, www.cme.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use AREHOLDERS, MAY BE KEY TO AOL-TIME WARNER
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
