<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SADDAM-REARMED?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. WEAPONS COP FEARS IRAQ HAS REARMED; WARNS OF AUGUST CRISIS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EXCLUSIVE `Independent' Interview)   (This 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANNE PENKETH  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Butler, the outspoken Australian who led the
United Nations efforts to strip Iraq of its weapons of mass
destruction after the Gulf War, says he fears that Iraq has used
the 18 months without U.N. monitors to rearm.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has been under sanctions since the 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
but in an interview with the Independent, Butler said that Iraq had
exploited divisions among the five U.N. Security Council permanent
members _ Britain, China, France, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has even ensured that ``Saddam has a veto at the Council
table'' by insisting that Iraq must approve of the future
inspection procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence from Iraq of such (disarmament) work should be a
source of grave concern,'' says Butler.
</P>
<P>
   If the Big Five U.N. members are united, then military action
should not be necessary to enforce international law, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who has just published a book ``Saddam Defiant'' on his
own frustrating experience as top weapons inspector, said that
``The world will never be the same'' if a missile loaded with nerve
gas were to hit Tel Aviv, a single canister of VX nerve gas were
released into the New York City subway system, or a single nuclear
explosion hollowed out central London.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is now faced with a tough policy decision on Iraq in the
coming weeks when the new disarmament body prepares to test Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein's willingness to allow intrusive
inspections aimed at ensuring that he has given up the capacity to
build weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   If Iraq defies U.N. provisions by refusing entry to the U.N.
inspectors, the Security Council will once again have to decide
whether to take military action to force the sanctions-hit country
to comply with international law.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's last refusal to cooperate with UNSCOM inspectors led by
Butler prompted the United States and Britain to launch Operation
Desert Fox in December 1998. The two countries have kept up a
low-level bombing campaign in allied-patrolled ``no-fly'' zones
since that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a crunch in August,'' Butler predicted.
</P>
<P>
   That is when UNMOVIC, the new organization which he describes as
the ``sickly son of UNSCOM,'' will have recruited and trained up
its politically- and geographically-correct team of experts.
</P>
<P>
   They were mandated by the Security Council last December to
complete the elimination of Iraqi nuclear, biological and chemical
weapons, and long-range missiles capable of striking Iraq's
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM fell apart in the aftermath of Desert Fox, which split
the Security Council, amid accusations that UNSCOM was being used
by the U.S. and Israel for spying purposes, and was disturbing
Iraqi sensibilities through its ``cowboy'' methods.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, backed by Russia and China, continues to insist that it
has already complied with U.N. disarmament requirements and that
sanctions should be lifted forthwith. Baghdad has also warned that
it will not cooperate with UNMOVIC.
</P>
<P>
   Once the UNMOVIC teams, now led by former IAEA chief Hans Blix,
are up and running at the end of August, the Security Council will
have to decide whether to force the issue by attempting to send
them back to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who is now diplomat in residence at the Council for
Foreign Relations in New York, says that Britain will come under
huge pressure in the Security Council from the Russians and
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will call for a shift in policy, then they can get
UNMOVIC in,'' he says. ``Russia, China and France say first lift
the sanctions on the promise to let the monitors in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice for the West is: will they take Iraq's word for
it?... And then the Council will have been conned,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that August is only three months ahead of the U.S.
presidential election, Butler says that the attitude of the other
hard-liner on Iraq in the Security Council cannot be predicted at
this stage.
</P>
<P>
   Washington seems somewhat disengaged on Iraq at present,
according to U.N. diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats commented that Butler may be premature in
predicting a new crisis with Iraq in August, and that the Security
Council may continue to sit on its hands when presented with the
new-look inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The current deadlock, under which Iraq is benefiting from a
loosened oil-for-food humanitarian program while receiving the
occasional bomb from a U.S. or British warplane, may actually
benefit all the players concerned, including Britain and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if the inspectors go back this side of
Christmas,'' one diplomat said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
