<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d BC-FOOD-MANGOES0623-COX     06-22 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MANGOES0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fruit with universal appeal
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hard to believe, looking at all the mangoes
hanging on trees here, that the juicy tropical fruit grows anywhere
else on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Don't we have enough in our own back yards?
</P>
<P>
   Equally hard to believe is that mangoes are more well-known in
most of the world than apples; the mango is the world's No. 1 fruit
eaten out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Most scientists agree mangoes got their start in Southeast Asia.
India is the main producer in Asia today; but they're grown in hot
climates around the world including South Africa, the Caribbean and
South and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Every country that eats mangoes has its own twist on using them
in dishes. Indians give us lahssies _ a type of smoothie made with
yogurt. Their yogurt tastes nothing like our commercial varieties;
so to get the more tart flavor, add buttermilk to the plain yogurt
along with honey and fresh mango for an ice-cold treat.
</P>
<P>
   In the Caribbean islands and throughout Latin America, a mango
is reamed into a juice or pureed in a blender, mixed with sweetened
condensed milk and served over crushed ice for a batido.
</P>
<P>
   Chutneys also come from India, though the Brits have perfected
this dish.
</P>
<P>
   Mangoes with curry may sound like an odd combo, but it's also
indicative of some areas in India, and also Trinidad, which has
adopted curry-flavored preparations for many of its fish stews.
Curry with shrimp and mangoes is an exotically beautiful dish as
well as being tasty.
</P>
<P>
   Also from the islands, we get mango bread, a sweet breakfast
staple that freezes well. Jamaicans use fruit in many of their
baked goods, likely inspired by the British fruitcake.
</P>
<P>
   Green mangoes are eaten in Vietnam and Thailand; green mango
pickles are a specialty, typically served with fish. Salads or
slaws, made with mangoes and other fruits and dressed with vinegar,
are inspired by their cuisines.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican chefs often use cilantro with mangoes. You'll see the
combination in a version of tropical gazpacho, a decidedly Spanish
dish with a Mexican flair.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest American chefs are using mangoes with their
chile-fired dishes; smoked chiles (anchos) go especially well with
the sweet, ripe fruit in a chicken dish.
</P>
<P>
   Here in South Florida, mango salsa is on many menus, paired with
chicken, fish and pork. The fruit salsa would also work as a dip
served with fried strips of yuca that have been dusted with garlic
powder for a touch of Cuban cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   However you use mangoes, here are tips for choosing them and
storing them:
</P>
<P>
   Mangoes will ripen in a paper bag if not picked too soon. Choose
mangoes that are beginning to ripen, but not yet soft. Place them
in a paper bag and seal the end; leave on the counter overnight.
Avoid putting ripe mangoes in the refrigerator; this will inhibit
their ripening.
</P>
<P>
   The small black ``sugar'' spots on a mango's skin won't affect
the flavor, but avoid bruising the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   To get maximum fruit off a mango, slice it parallel to the pit.
Hold the mango in one hand at eye level. Turn the mango to find the
narrowest side, and run the knife vertically in a wide slice from
the top. Continue on the opposite side of the mango.
</P>
<P>
   Cube, slice or puree fresh mangoes and put into freezer
containers to preserve them. They keep well in the freezer for up
to six months. (They should be peeled first; the peel is toxic if
eaten in quantity.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are samples of how mangoes are used in cuisines around the
world:
</P>
<P>
   India: Some Indians use the mango in their curry dishes, while
others create the famous lahssie _ a fruit-yogurt smoothie. Mango
chutney comes from India as well.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean: Mango bread and mangoes with curry and fish are
common on certain islands.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Batidos, milkshake of mangoes and condensed milk, are
often found in streetside booths here.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest U.S.: Mangoes are matched with chiles and pork or
chicken by American chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Southeast Asia: Thai and Vietnamese cooks use green mangoes for
pickling and in salads. French cooks from Vietnam have contributed
the green mango pie (or tart).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
