<HEADER>
A1834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d BC-MANGOES-RECIPES0623-C     06-22 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANGOES-RECIPES0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mangoes popular with cooks around world
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes taken from several cuisines where mangoes are
grown.
</P>
<P>
   'Mangos flameados' (Flambeed mangoes)
</P>
<P>
   2 mangoes, about 1 pound, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Thinly pared and julienned rind of 1/2 orange
</P>
<P>
   Thinly pared and julienned rind of 1/2 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Triple Sec or Cointreau
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 orange
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce white tequila
</P>
<P>
   Peel the mangoes, remove the pit, and cut the flesh into thick
strips. Set aside. Melt the butter in the chafing dish, stir in the
sugar, and continue stirring until it has dissolved. Add the rinds
together with the Triple Sec, heat the mixture, and flame it.
</P>
<P>
   When the flames have died down, add the juices and cook until
reduced _ about 2 minutes. Add the mango strips and heat until the
syrup begins to bubble. Add the tequila, heat through, and flame
again. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 to 3 servings
</P>
<P>
   (From ``The Cuisines of Mexico,'' Harper &AMP; Row Publishers.)
</P>
<P>
   Cold papaya, mango and cape gooseberry bisque
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mangoes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds papayas
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh cape gooseberries (ground cherries)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pineapple juice, or enough to cover fruit
</P>
<P>
   1 large piece peeled fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon allspice powder
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cornstarch mixed with 1/2 cup water, for thickening, as
needed
</P>
<P>
   Lemon juice to taste
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Toasted macadamia nuts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Peel, seed and chop the mangoes and papayas. Husk the cape
gooseberries and leave them whole. Place the fruit in a saucepan,
cover with pineapple juice, add the spices and honey, and simmer
until the fruit is tender. Discard the cinnamon stick. Puree the
mixture in a blender until very smooth. Strain, if desired. Return
the soup to the saucepan and bring to a simmer. If necessary,
thicken by adding cornstarch mixture a little at a time to the
simmering soup, stirring constantly until desired consistency is
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Adjust the flavor with lemon juice. Chill thoroughly. Just
before serving, garnish each portion with a dollop of sour cream
and a sprinkling of toasted macadamia nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Mango bread
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peeled and diced fresh mango
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup macadamia nuts or walnuts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated coconut
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350(degrees). Grease and flour two 9x5-inch
loaf pans. Sift the flour, baking soda, baking powder and cinnamon
into a small bowl. In a large mixing bowl, combine the eggs, oil
and sugar. Combine with dry nuts and coconut. Pour into the loaf
pans and bake for 45-60 minutes, or until the bread is golden
brown. To test if bread is done, insert a toothpick in the center
of the loaf. When it comes out clean, the bread is done. Let the
loaves cool in the pans for 10 to 15 minutes; then unmold and let
cool completely on racks.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 loaves.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Sam Choy's Island Flavors,'' Hyperion.)
</P>
<P>
   Prawn, green mango and potato curry
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garam masala
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground jeera of cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chili powder or fresh chile, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 curry leaves (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ghee or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh ginger, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 tomatoes, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pint water or stock
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces potato, peeled and cut into cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 small green mango, peeled and sliced or diced
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds prawns, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Mix all the spices in a little warm water or stock to form a
paste. Cook the onions, garlic and ginger in ghee or margarine
until soft. Add the masala and cook for 5 minutes, stirring to
prevent burning or sticking. Add the tomatoes and stir well.
Slowly, add the water or stock, stirring, then the potato. Let the
curry cook on a moderate heat for 20 minutes, then add the sugar,
mango, salt and prawns.
</P>
<P>
   Cook for 10 to 15 minutes longer. Serve with rice and cucumber
and tomato salad.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Rosamund Grant's Caribbean and African Cookery,'' Grub
Street.)
</P>
<P>
   Sweet pale orange-mango lahssie
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped, ripe mango
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cardamom seeds
</P>
<P>
   8 ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   Combine all the ingredients in an electric blender and blend.
Some ice pieces may remain. Pour into 2 or 3 glasses and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 to 3 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Madhur Jaffrey's Quick and Easy Indian Cooking,''
Chronicle Books.)
</P>
<P>
   Tofu-tomato-mango soup 1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mango, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe tomato, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk (can use soy milk)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dash of hot sauce
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces soft tofu
</P>
<P>
   Fresh parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion and garlic in olive oil over medium heat for about 3
minutes or until transparent. Add tomato and mango, drizzle with
lime juice and saute for 2 to 3 more minutes. Add milk, salt,
pepper and hot sauce, stir over heat for another minute. Allow to
cool briefly, then add tofu and blend in blender until smooth.
Chill and serve with parsley garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from the Web site: www.freshmangos.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
