<P>
   ALBRIGHT-CHINA (Beijing) _ More than a year after the NATO
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, the United
States and China officially declared Thursday during a visit by
secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright that the interlude of
bitterness had given way to an era of improved relations. Even so,
both sides said that the firmer footing of the relationship, based
on the recent passage in the House of Representatives of a broad
trade bill dealing with China, was now focused on the sensitive
issue of Taiwan and the Clinton administration's plans for an
anti-missile defensive shield. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-LAUNDERING (Washington) _ With evidence mounting that bank
secrecy laws can threaten financial stability everywhere, the
world's rich nations Thursday took the unprecedented step of naming
15 countries, including Israel, Russia and the Philippines, as
potential havens for ill-gotten wealth. The public blacklist is the
culmination of a decade-long diplomatic effort to take action
against money-laundering centers. The action does not punish the
named countries or cut them off from the world financial system.
But it does pressure banks and brokerage houses to scrutinize all
financial transactions with clients there as possibly linked to
crime or high-risk financial transactions. And it threatens the
nations because they could lose legitimate financial business, a
lucrative source of tax revenue. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
