<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GASPRICES06     06-22 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GASPRICES0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Don't blame Big Oil, OPEC for high gas prices
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Democrats, the obvious villain in the rapid rise of gasoline
prices is Big Oil, which they suspect of driving up prices to
increase profits. As a result, the Federal Trade Commission is
investigating the oil industry's role in Midwestern gas prices,
where the rise has been most rapid, and Vice President Al Gore is
even suggesting that ``Big Oil may have gotten too big.''
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the villain in the rapid rise of gas prices is
equally obvious: the federal government. By protecting the Arctic
National Wildlife Refuge from oil drilling, by failing to coerce
OPEC nations into raising oil production, by insisting on
cleaner-burning blends of gasoline, the Clinton administration has
brought the nation to this crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, there is no single villain, no single
explanation, no single solution. In February 1999, gasoline was
selling at less than 70 cents a gallon in some Georgia locations.
Have government policies changed so much in 16 months to force a
doubling of gas prices? Hardly. Likewise, if Big Oil had the
control over gas prices that some Democrats suggest, would the
industry have allowed prices to decline so much back in February?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of our predicament lies elsewhere, in simple supply
and demand. In economic terms, the demand for gasoline is
inelastic, meaning it doesn't change much in response to price.
People tend to buy the same amount of gasoline each week no matter
how high _ or how low _ the price is. That makes gasoline prices
extremely volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: When a widgetmaker finds himself with too many
widgets on hand, he merely cuts his price a little, people buy more
widgets, and his excess inventory disappears. But gasoline doesn't
work like that. If refineries have too much gasoline to sell, they
have to cut their prices by a whole lot if they hope to increase
gas consumption even a little bit. That's what happened last
February. The reverse is also true. When gasoline supplies get
tight, the price has to rise by an awful lot before it starts to
discourage consumption and restore balance to the market. That's
what's happening now.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that complicated a story. But since it lacks a villain,
it also lacks sex appeal, and politicians can't use it to scare up
votes. So it's a story not often told.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the closest thing to a villain in this story is you. As
in us. As in we, the American people. We have treated gasoline as
liquid sunshine, something that pours into our cars and trucks and
sport-utility vehicles just as naturally and inevitably as the sun
rises each morning.
</P>
<P>
   We have the same fuel-efficiency standards in effect today as we
did in the 1970s, when auto technology was much more crude. And
we've taken advantage of a loophole in those standards by turning
en masse to gas-guzzling light trucks and SUVs that make up an
increasing percentage of our fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians don't like that story either, for obvious
reasons. Instead of concentrating on the demand for gasoline, which
is something we can influence, they prefer to focus on its supply,
which is something we can't influence.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the claim that gas prices would fall if we opened
the Arctic wildlife refuge to drilling conveniently overlooks the
fact that American-produced oil is no cheaper than the oil coming
out of Saudi Arabia. Take a look: The price of oil from Texas oil
fields today is $31 a barrel, right in line with OPEC's price.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the popular ploy of blaming OPEC for our problems is
like blaming Mexico and Columbia for our drug problem. Yes, they're
taking advantage of our addiction, but we're the ones hooked on the
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And like a lot of addicts, we want to blame anybody but
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
