<HEADER>
A1837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-HATE0623-CO     06-22 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HATE0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Hate crimes bill offers shield not stamp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As soon as long-overdue legislation to broaden federal authority
to fight hate crimes cleared a hurdle in the U.S. Senate, a couple
more obstacles came into view.
</P>
<P>
   First, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.), no friend of
the measure, said he would hold up action on the overall defense
bill, to which the hate crimes language is attached as an
amendment. Even if the amendment survives Lott's stalling tactics,
it faces an arduous route to passage in the House, which is
decidedly cooler to the proposal than the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to get it passed is worth the effort. America needs
it.
</P>
<P>
   Current U.S. law on hate crimes only covers protected civic
activities such as trying to vote or registering for school; it
doesn't apply to, say, an assault on a person because of his or her
race, ethnicity, etc. In 1998, the last year for which there is a
complete tally, 8,000 hate crimes were reported in the United
States: 56 percent motivated by race, 18 percent by religion and 16
percent by sexual orientation _ with the latter percentage said to
be rising.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment is not intended to heap penalties on perpetrators
but to assist local jurisdictions, some of which don't have
adequate legal protections or the investigative wherewithal to deal
with suspected hate crimes. This is not intervention, just federal
consultation and assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be honest about this issue. This initiative would be
sailing through both houses were it not for the fact it covers gays
and lesbians. Some on Capitol Hill and in sanctimonious circles
elsewhere argue illogically that this would legitimize
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment applies no such stamp of approval. It would merely
protect gays and lesbians from persecution just as it would
safeguard racial, religious and ethnic minorities or the
handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   As a co-sponsor of the amendment, Sen. Gordon Smith (R-Ore.)
said this week: ``In many ways, passage of the Hate Crimes
Prevention Act would be nothing more than a symbol. But it is a
symbol that can be filled with substance by changing hearts and
minds and by better protecting all our citizens, be they disabled,
female, black or gay. They are Americans all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
