<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE ARRIVAL OF EMP, IT'S NOT YOUR FATHER'S SEATTLE ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ MSFT forever changed our image. So did WTO. Now it is
EMP's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, amidst a blitz of international hype and hoopla, Paul
Allen's curvaceous, gaudily clad Experience Music Project opens its
doors to the public and our once-shy, shades-of-gray city will
again be subject to double-takes and once-overs from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Get an eyeful, rubberneckers. The Old Gray Mare, we ain't.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago it would have been insane to put up this
museum,'' says Charles Cross, editor-in-chief of the Northwest rock
magazine The Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no music scene, no club scene. But people want to
come to Seattle now to vist in many ways has become the most
vibrant city in America in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Allen's timing couldn't be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft _ MSFT to its triple-split stockholders changed our
image from folksy Pioneer Square Squared into Silicon North, and
helped raise the area's per-capita income by 11 percent in 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks gave us the jagged caffeine edge of a Turkish coffee
house.
</P>
<P>
   Grunge _ that sonic, early-'90s growl that spread across the
country like moshed Mudhoney _ convinced Rolling Stone magazine to
declare us Rock City.
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization ``Battle of Seattle'' protests late
last year put us on the map as a budding Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Now the EMP _ the world's most expensive rock 'n' roll museum,
with a heady entry fee of $19.95 _ is threatening to reshape
Seattle's public image into a high-amp, defiantly idiosyncratic,
brave-new Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the amps, baby, and ditch the beige raincoat. Mold's
out. Bold's in. It could be permanent Hawaiian shirt day in
Seattle, if that red and purple and blue and silver and gold
whatzit at the foot of the Space Needle looks anything like our
future.
</P>
<P>
   It very well could.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind the EMP curtain, jet-setting Microsoft co-founder
Allen, has always had a foot _ maybe two _ in the future. It's
where fellow Da Vinci-ites with that rich Renaissance right-brain,
left-brain, art-and-science thinking tend to dwell.
</P>
<P>
   It was Allen, remember, who helped dream up that pie-in-the-sky
cyber-highway called the World Wide Web. In the early days at MSFT,
his partner, Bill Gates, referred to him simply as ``the idea
man.'' The new term for Allen is ``visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his idea for EMP began modestly enough. He wanted to do
right by his guitar guru, Jimi Hendrix, a mind-blowing Fender
bender as far ahead of his time musically as Allen is ahead of his
technologically.
</P>
<P>
   Allen planned a $50 million shrine to the Seattle-born
guitarist, with 6,000 artifacts and 10,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   A couple hundred million dollars later, the focus has grown to
embrace rock gospel, funk, hip-hop, jazz, blues, punk and grunge,
with 80,000 artifacts, 140,000 square feet, 50 patents pending on
techie innovations, and a most curious and incendiary architectural
design by Frank Gehry that has stirred pundits in Seattle to vivid
metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   You can't judge a book by its cover. But passing judgment on the
EMP _ based on the colors of its skin and its endomorphic bulges _
has become a regular Seattle pasttime.
</P>
<P>
   Graphic naysayers compare the building to the organs of a
slaughtered cow, a dumped-over garbage can, open heart surgery gone
awry, the crash site of an airplane. The architect, some complain,
is nothing but a big showoff. And the idea just plain stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Admirers, in turn, praise its ``massive coolness'' and
double-dare-ya chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Some are wonderfully poetic. ``It's a Matisse odalisque purring
at the nervous gang of male buildings standing on the street
corners in the downtown skyline,'' says Tom Corddry, leader of the
team that created Microsoft's Encarta. ``Or maybe it's just the
Space Needle's pet pot-bellied pig, heavily tattooed.''
</P>
<P>
   Press-shy Allen _ who is suddenly popping up in everything from
Rolling Stone magazine to the New York Times to promote EMP _
describes the museum as fresh, audacious, exuberant, unabashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think big,'' he has told his staff. They have. When your boss'
imagination runs on Quicken Deluxe _ with a personal wealth that
fluctuates around $30 billion, depending on the mood swings of the
stock market _ the sky's no limit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are the conventional trappings of traditional Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has long been a city of grinding process, where civic
decisions can take days, or weeks, and nobody leaves the table
completely satisifed. The EMP _ totally funded by Allen _ flies in
the face of that.
</P>
<P>
   The city didn't ask for this. It didn't pay for it. Mr. Allen
can pretty much do whatever he wants in his rock 'n' tech temple.
</P>
<P>
   See what happens when you don't compromise?
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is doing a good job of being a tycoon,'' says Corddry.
``He is too quick and unpredictable and brassy for the neighborhood
process junkies to keep up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the EMP about modesty _ Seattle has long been the high
exalted capital of Scandinavian understatement. This radical
high-volt temple to rock isn't designed to whisper. It's designed
to howl, to rock, to boogie all night long.
</P>
<P>
   It's about the Seattle we're becoming. Not the Seattle we've
been. That plugged-in city is not only growing wealthier, it is
growing younger (average age about 38) and hipper (the city has the
seventh largest population of artists in the nation). And rock 'n'
roll is at its heart 'n' soul. ``We're a generation of people who
grew up with rock and pop music and culture built into our lives.
We take it for granted,'' says the museum's curatorial director,
Chris Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``EMP is a natural product of the times and culture we live
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Or will live in, if EMP projections are correct. Staffers
estimates annual attendance at the museum will average at least
800,000. First-year figures, they say, could be more than 1
million.
</P>
<P>
   That's almost twice the annual attendance of Cleveland's Rock
'n' Roll Hall of Fame _ and the Seattle Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   It's also twice the population of Seattle proper.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce describes the estimate as modest. Others say it may be
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether EMP can create a museum that is vibrant, that people
want to return to again and again, is going to be quite a task,''
says Rocket editor Charles Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The key, he says is soul. The city's. The museum's.
</P>
<P>
   And he, for one, hopes the two can tango.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think rock 'n' roll does deserve a cultural place in our
history,'' says Cross, ``and I'm glad that Paul Allen appreciates
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the equivalent of someone saying I'm building the
Seattle Public Library for music and I' m doing it on my own
dime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
