<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-EMP-ALLEN-SPI &LR;      06-22 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMP-ALLEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUITAR GOD SET OFF A SPARK IN ROCK 'N' ROLL BILLIONAIRE'S
IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ His broad face expressionless as he gazes out a
window, Paul Allen is thinking back to the last time he saw his
idol, Jimi Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a hint of awe in the billionaire's voice as he
recalls a mystic summer day in 1970, a day filled with vivid
memories of a rock star with an extraordinary command of the
electric guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of other Seattle teenagers who jammed Sick's
Stadium on July 26, 1970, Allen was mesmerized by the hippie prince
with the wild Afro and Fender Strat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen anybody with such absolute control of his
instrument,'' Allen says during an interview at Vulcan Northwest in
Bellevue, the hub of his sports, entertainment and high-tech
empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd just close his eyes and have these amazingly fluid
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix, a Seattle native, had dazzled audiences at the 1967
Monterey Pop Festival and '69 Woodstock festival with his fiery
guitar style, billowing scarves and psychedelic voodoo. But his
final Seattle show was electrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Allen _ whose Experience Music Project was inspired by Hendrix _
was standing only 20 feet away from the guitar god that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a chance of rain, so they built a plastic awning
that Jimi could stand under,'' Allen says. ``It started to sprinkle
and became progressively stronger, not a downpour, but a good
Seattle rain.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no way Jimi was going to be under that awning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right at the edge of the stage in a silk jumpsuit.
There was water running off the guitar, and he had his eyes closed
as he played. It was incredibly loud, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen had seen Hendrix the year before, in May 1969, at the
Seattle Center Coliseum. But the Sick's Stadium concert would be
the guitarist's last hometown stand. Hendrix died in London less
than two months later, on Sept. 18, 1970, choking to death in his
sleep after mixing alcohol and barbiturates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, there are a number of different videos that
capture some of Jimi's performances. But seeing him live was
something else,'' Allen says wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   Cradled in a big leather chair and surrounded by high-tech
hardware in a plush conference room, Allen chuckles at the memory
of the guitarist's last Seattle show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are given special talents and special
creativity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Allen could be talking about himself. He's a man of abundant
ideas _ and the wealth to implement them.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Seattle on Jan. 21, 1953, he grew up in the Ravenna
district and attended Lakeside School, where he met Bill Gates.
They founded Microsoft in the early 1970s. Allen left the software
giant in 1983 after being diagnosed with Hodgkin's disease, which
is now in remission.
</P>
<P>
   His portfolio includes stakes in more than 100 companies and his
net worth is around $30 billion, depending on which way the stock
market goes on a given day.
</P>
<P>
   In pro sports, he owns the Portland Trail Blazers and Seattle
Seahawks. His movie investments include $500 million in DreamWorks
and $3.75 million in Seattle's Cinerama theater. He's a major
player in cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   His collection of lavish abodes includes a high-tech palace on
Mercer Island, Wash.; a 16-room condo in Manhattan; a mansion in
Beverly Hills; a house in London's Holland Park; a villa in the
hills above Cannes, France; and several houses on Lopez Island,
Wash., at the site of a former children's camp.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's hobbies include movies, chess, scuba diving, playing
guitar in his own band and throwing ultra-lavish parties, including
a star-studded 1996 bash at his villa in Southern France during the
Cannes film festival and a cruise aboard a chartered ship from
Juneau to Seattle in 1998 that Rolling Stone estimated cost $9
million.
</P>
<P>
   EMP's opening weekend features more arena-level headliners than
any other local festival this summer. But Allen's band, Grown Men,
won't perform.
</P>
<P>
   The group rehearses at Allen's private studio and occasionally
plays at local clubs. It includes Marc Willett (bass and vocals),
Mike Chadderton (piano, organ and synthesizer), Rick Boice (drums,
percussion and vocals), Eric Robison (sax, flutes, whistle and
``wind controller'') and Terry Davison (guitar, pedal steel,
mandolin and vocals).
</P>
<P>
   Allen plays guitar and writes lyrics and music, sharing credits
with Willett and Davison.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the new CD, ``Grown Men,'' depicts a toddler in a
purple bandana, a la Hendrix, dousing a burning toy guitar with
lighter fluid as he kneels before it. It has a warm and fuzzy look.
</P>
<P>
   But the music has a dark edge. Allen's brooding songs about
failed love, disillusionment and catastrophe are a bit surprising
from a man with so much economic power and entrepreneurial
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The song ``Kingdom of the Lonely'' includes the lines, ``In the
country of the blind, the one-eyed man is king/ I thought I had an
answer, but I did not know a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mushroom Cloud,'' Allen writes, ``Millions have planned and
worked for this day/ Targets are locked in, it's missiles away/
Brighter than the sunniest day/ It's falling, we're falling, it's
tumbling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Most surprising is the vengeful ``Time Bomb'': ``Underestimate
me if you want/ I can take every jeer and taunt/ Don't even try to
box me in a corner/ The fire I set will be made to order.''
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, the music recalls Bob Dylan, Tom Petty and
particularly Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Allen tried to break the Hendrixian guitar code,
hoping to master some of the riffs that had given him chills at
Sick's Stadium in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   His admiration for Hendrix, as well as his growing wealth,
inspired him to buy hundreds of artifacts that now fill the Hendrix
gallery at EMP.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's collection grew to include shards of the guitar Hendrix
destroyed during his incendiary performance at the '67 Monterey Pop
Festival, the guitar on which he played ``The Star Spangled
Banner'' at Woodstock and the mixing console from his Electric Lady
studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these things, if you're a guitar player or someone who
loves this kind of music, it gives you shivers,'' says Allen, who
wears black slacks, light-blue shirt, blue wire-frame glasses and a
large turquoise ring that belonged to his late father.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you realize that these were just the tools of the
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed Seattle had no Hendrix shrine, save for a
commemorative rock at the Woodland Park Zoo, Allen proposed a
Hendrix museum at Seattle Center in 1992. Al Hendrix, the
guitarist's father, enthusiastically supported the idea, but Allen
and the Hendrix family later had a falling out and the museum
evolved into the much larger, costlier and innovative EMP designed
by Frank Gehry.
</P>
<P>
   Allen instructed Gehry to make his museum look ``swoopy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the idea goes back to Jimi's music itself,'' Allen
says. ``There was the way he played, where he'd go way up and out
into the stratosphere and come down, and the music itself would
swoop around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of exploratory creativity was something that I
wanted to somehow get across in the architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Electric guitars, with their bright colors and curved shapes,
were the inspiration for the museum's exterior, which is covered
with painted metal shingles.
</P>
<P>
   Others have suggested the multisegment building resembles a
human heart, the human inner ear, or worse. ``Hydroplane wreck''
and ``open-heart surgery gone awry'' are among the less-flattering
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen shrugs off criticisms of the building's design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Frank a couple of times, and I've told him how
excited I was about the project,'' he says. ``The last time I saw
him, when the museum was coming off the ground, I said, `This is
going to be fantastic.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank is someone who is always pushing boundaries of what
architecture can be, and I think we encouraged him to go even
further than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest attractions at the 18-room museum is Sky
Church, a great hall inspired by Hendrix's concept of a place where
people of all ages, interests and backgrounds could come together
to experience music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jimi expressed in some of his interviews, and in his
songs, the idea that music serves as a magic carpet that can take
you to different places,'' Allen says. ``There's a churchlike
feeling there, and great music makes the spirit soar.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Sound Lab, a futuristic studio where visitors can
create music, regardless of their level of skill, using various
instruments. They can learn basic skills or work on improving their
existing ones. They also can be virtual rock stars, performing in a
booth that simulates the arena-rock experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a challenge to come up with things that were
hands-on, yet robust enough to stand up to thousands of people
using them and still allow a level of instruction for someone who
hasn't had much experience playing an instrument,'' Allen says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to get them excited about music and think, `Hey,
here's a door I can go through.' There's a lot of fun and
excitement in self-expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen also wants his museum to be a place where music fans and
musicians can come together. Punk-rock icon Patti Smith, who
performs at the opening festival, has already agreed to do a
workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the museum will be a focal point, a place where you
have all sorts of different levels of live performance as well as
things that are more innovative and educational, more of a
master-class nature,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a key set of experiences that really got them
excited about music. Music is one of those things that people are
very passionate about. And the people who make music are very
passionate about it too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
