<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0623-COX     06-22 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Another special counsel, just in time for the
elections?
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A top Justice Department prosecutor has recommended a special
counsel be appointed to investigate Al Gore in the 1996 campaign
fund-raising controversy. The recommendation reportedly came from
Robert Conrad, supervising attorney for the Justice Department task
force investigating 1996 fund-raising abuses. Sen. Arlen Spector
(R-Pa.) of the Judiciary administrative oversight subcommittee,
said today that Attorney General Janet Reno ``has done a great
disservice to Vice President Gore, because these matters should
have been investigated a long time ago.'' Reno repeatedly declined
to seek appointment of an independent counsel before the statute
expired a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS RIGHT UP THERE WITH THE BUDDHIST NUNS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest teachers' union, which reports to the IRS
that it spends none of its $200 million a year in teachers' dues on
politics, spent millions of dollars to help elect ``pro-education
candidates.'' National Education Association documents reviewed by
the Associated Press show that $4.9 million was budgeted in a July
1999 union strategic plan for the 2000 election for such things as
``organizational partnerships with political parties, campaign
committees and political organizations.'' The documents raise
questions about the group's tax returns. The union, funded by about
$200 million a year in teachers' dues, said today it believes it
has complied with the law.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONS OF LIFE AND DEATH
</P>
<P>
   After days of being heckled by death penalty opponents, George
W. Bush retreated to the quiet of his office in the Texas Capitol
today and awaited the state pardon board's decision that convicted
murderer Gary Graham should be put to death. And the governor
refused to bow to protests that followed him throughout a three-day
West Coast tour, shrugging off any consequences the execution could
pose to his White House bid. Al Gore, a death penalty supporter,
entered the debate for the first time, saying the goal of both
sides of the issue should be getting erroneous executions ``down to
the virtual zero point.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH DOUBLES UP ON GORE NATIONALLY . . .
</P>
<P>
   A new poll has troubling news for Al Gore. The bipartisan
Voter.com Battleground survey shows George W. Bush with a
double-digit lead. It also indicates Bush is running even among
groups Gore probably needs to win: women and union members. Getting
more credit as the candidate who would keep America prosperous,
Bush had 52 percent support among likely voters, while Gore had 40
percent. Bush's lead in the same poll last month was only 6 points.
The Texas governor also led 49-41 percent in a just-released
NBC-Wall Street Journal poll.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND CATCHES UP IN CONNECTICUT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has erased the 9-point advantage Al Gore had
among Connecticut voters in April, a new poll released by
Quinnipiac University showed. The two presidential candidates are
now in a virtual tie in the state, with Gore at 43 percent and Bush
at 42 percent, well within the poll's margin of sampling error of
2.7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   AND MAYBE SOME OF THAT ALPHA STUFF'LL RUB OFF
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Jesse Ventura, their new political friendship on
display, joined forces today at a junior high school in St. Paul to
promote special education after some late-night bonding time. ``I'm
not working on his endorsement; I'm working on his vote,'' said
Gore. Ventura, the ex-pro wrestler who gained fame for winning the
Minnesota governor's job as a Reform Party candidate, said he's
committed to the third party movement and that he'd ``feel that I'd
betray that movement'' by endorsing Gore. ``We don't talk much on
issues when we get together; we tell old war stories,'' Ventura
said. Added Gore: ``We stayed up until way past midnight talking
about everything under the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE MORE COMPETITION MIGHT BE INTERESTING . . .
</P>
<P>
   After meeting today with Green Party candidate Ralph Nader,
Teamsters President James P. Hoffa said that neither Al Gore nor
George W. Bush have taken strong enough stands on trade and other
issues important to labor. For that reason, Hoffa said Nader and
Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan should be allowed to
participate in the presidential debates. ``Who really wants to see
a debate between Gore and Bush? I mean they're somewhat the same on
trade, the same mindless debate on Social Security goes on and
on,'' he said. ``We want to broaden the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   . . . BUT NOT EVERY TEAM MAKES THE PLAYOFFS
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Commission on Presidential Debates defended their
decision to exclude candidates who draw less than 15 percent in
national polls, arguing that anyone falling below that threshold
doesn't have a realistic shot at the presidency. Their defense
comes as Pat Buchanan and Ralph Nader are complaining they can't
win if they are shut out of the high-profile, prime-time fall
debates. ``Our role is not to jump start your campaign and all of a
sudden make you competitive,'' said Paul Kirk Jr., co-chairman of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
   NOW LOOK WHO'S FAVORING EXCLUSION
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan, who's been complaining
about his exclusion from the presidential debates this fall, is
himself refusing to debate party rival John Hagelin. Hagelin had
issued a challenge to Buchanan for a series of debates in advance
of the Reform Party's mail-in primary, but Buchanan manager and
sister, Bay Buchanan belittled the idea: ``We received their
request, and our response is, `John Who?' ... How many delegates to
the convention does he have?''
</P>
<P>
   JUST ASK HIM, HE'LL TAKE IT
</P>
<P>
   HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo said today he'd agree to be Al Gore's
running mate if asked. The son of ex-New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, 42,
also said he might seek his party's nomination for governor of New
York in 2002. Cuomo was asked the question while in Israel to
create a commission of Israeli and U.S. experts to look for ways to
increase the supply of affordable housing in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING, EATING, AND BRINGING IN SOME BUCKS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will be in Los Angeles the next two days
speaking and raising funds. Friday, it's receptions for the state
Democratic Party and the Democratic National Committee Saxophone
Club, and a DNC dinner. On Saturday, Clinton will appear at a
Convention Host Committee breakfast, and a brunch and reception for
California Victory 2000.
</P>
<P>
   GAY PRIDE PARADE NOT FOR LAZIO
</P>
<P>
   A group of Democrats and gay elected officials criticized Rick
Lazio's decision to campaign upstate instead of marching in this
weekend's Gay Pride parade in Manhattan. During the last two
weekends, Lazio marched in the Salute to Israel parade, the
Filipino Independence Day parade and the Puerto Rican Day parade.
He was invited to march in Sunday's gay pride parade with the Log
Cabin Republicans. ``It very much shows symbolically where Rick
Lazio is on issues of concern to the gay community, which is
nowhere,'' said state Sen. Tom Duane, a gay Democrat from
Manhattan. Hillary Clinton plans to participate. So does Rudy
Giuliani, whom Lazio replaced in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST THE POLLING PLACES, THEN THE COURTHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon LaRouche, a perennial candidate who runs for president as
a Democrat every four years, goes into court Friday in Little Rock,
trying to get the seven delegates he says he's entitled to for
winning nearly 22 percent of Arkansas primary vote. Arkansas
Democrats have refused to seat LaRouche's backers, accusing him of
racism and wackiness and saying he isn't a legitimate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL ADS, ILLEGAL ADS: ANY REAL DIFFERENCE?
</P>
<P>
   Two groups said they'll demand a criminal probe of the Gore and
Bush campaigns for allegedly misusing political parties' TV ``issue
ads'' to promote presidential candidates and ``engaging in an
illegal scheme.'' Common Cause and Democracy 21 said they'll ask
the Justice Department to investigate, because ``the presidential
campaigns design, create, target and control the ad campaigns,
which are no different in kind or approach than other campaign ads
being run by the Gore and Bush campaigns.'' Both parties defended
their advertising.
</P>
<P>
   NAILING DOWN HISPANIC SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush continued his quest for Latino support by wooing
the National Association of Hispanic Journalists in Houston. He
said he's ``proud of the Hispanic heritage and traditions in the
state. I intend to take that attitude to the White House should I
be fortunate enough to win. He added that if elected he'd support
bilingualism: ``I will pledge to you that I will welcome the
Hispanic heritage in America. I will reject the English-only
movements.''
</P>
<P>
   GLAD TO BREAK BREAD ANYTIME
</P>
<P>
   A group of moderate Republican senators who support abortion
rights sent a letter to George W. Bush, asking him to ``take the
lead'' in changing the Republican platform's anti-abortion plank.
They also invited Bush to lunch. They got a response _ to the lunch
invitation. Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania said he's still
seeking a ``more specific response'' on abortion and remains
hopeful he'll get it.
</P>
<P>
   TALK ABOUT CONVENTION CHAOS!
</P>
<P>
   Just days after a basketball-related riot in L.A., a police
union announced it will be joining protesters at the Democratic
convention. The Los Angeles Police Protective League and protesters
from eight other major police unions have applied for permission to
hold demonstrations outside the downtown Staples Center in
mid-August. The cops are upset with the Clinton administration,
which is threatening the city with a court order to impose reforms
on the city police that were demanded by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING DOWN WITH THE WORKING CLASS
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to blue-collar union workers, Al Gore said that only
the wealthy would gain from George W. Bush's proposals. ``This is
the choice in this election,'' Gore said. ``Are you for working
people?'' Making his arguments with charts and testimonials at a
carpenter's union hall in Des Moines, Iowa, Gore said Bush's tax
cut and retirement plans would bankrupt Social Security and harm
middle-class Americans. He warned that ``Governor Bush has proposed
a plan that's very different'' and ``doesn't work very well for
working families.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW CHOICE IN MICHIGAN RACE
</P>
<P>
   The already close Michigan Senate race between freshman
Republican Spencer Abraham, and his Democratic challenger, Rep.
Debbie Stabenow, has tightened a bit further with the entry of Mark
Forton, a Reform Party candidate and supporter of Pat Buchanan.
Forton, an ex-Republican who said he'll make immigration a top
issue, could cause Abraham problems by attracting Republicans upset
by the senator's efforts to help loosen immigration restrictions to
let companies hire more foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
