<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of strong thunderstorms will bring the threat of
flooding to parts of the upper Midwest through the end of the week.
The thunderstorms will erupt as disturbances in the jet stream
intersect a plume of very warm, moist air flowing north from the
western Gulf of Mexico. The heaviest rain is expected over southern
Minnesota, northern Iowa and western Wisconsin where one to three
inches of rain will be common by late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will have ample sunshine, comfortable humidity and
seasonable warmth Friday. Some puffy afternoon clouds will mix with
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Summery heat will cover the southern tier of states. The
Southeast will be partly to mostly sunny, although scattered
thunderstorms will develop near the Atlantic and Gulf coasts. In
the Southwest, afternoon thunder will form over many mountain
peaks.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SUMMER LAG
</P>
<P>
   The duration of daylight has begun to dwindle gradually, but,
the most intense heat of summer typically accompanies the reduced
daylight. Two effects combine to cause the hottest weather to lag
behind the sun. The atmosphere is heated indirectly. Energy from
the sun first heats the surface of the earth, which then warms the
air above. At this time of year, 20,000 to 30,000 feet aloft, the
lingering chill of the past winter is still being erased. Moreover,
the ocean surface responds more slowly to the incoming energy than
does the land, further delaying the warming of the atmosphere over
the oceans.
</P>
</TEXT>
