<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-IAN-ANDERSON0623-COX     06-22 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IAN-ANDERSON0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jethro Tull looks to future, nods to past
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ask Jethro Tull frontman Ian Anderson if he
sees a connection between his band and the cinematic rock spoof
``This Is Spinal Tap'' and he responds with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose Jethro Tull along with Black Sabbath, Deep Purple
and a whole bunch of other bands contributed wittingly and
unwittingly to the movie,'' he says, speaking by phone from his
home in England. ``I'm a great fan of it. It's not too far away
from real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's hard to take Tull too seriously. This was the
British band, after all, that wedded rock, blues and folk in a kind
of mystical package _ and named itself after an 18th-century
farmer/inventor. And there was Anderson, who played the flute and
danced on stage like a man possessed. Even by the psychedelic
standards of the '60s and '70s, it was not your typical group.
</P>
<P>
   Jump ahead more than three decades and Jethro Tull is still
going strong. Oh, the band has lost a few members along the way,
but Anderson and longtime guitarist Martin Barre remain. And while
its music is anything but commercial these days _ you have as much
chance of hearing Jethro Tull on a Top 40 station as you do a
Mozart symphony _ it continues to be loved by legions of older
fans.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ALBUMS
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder Anderson and the band have been able to release
two albums in the last year _ Anderson with his solo project ``The
Secret Language of Birds'' and the band with ``j-tull Dot Com'' _
and mount a national tour that comes to the Sunrise Musical Theatre
on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And while you can still laugh at the band's seemingly
Druid-inspired approach to rock spectacle and the philosophical
musings that creep into Anderson's lyrics, you can't laugh at the
facts. Jethro Tull has sold 60 million recordings and played more
than 2,500 concerts since its inception in 1967. Its releases from
the early '70s _ ``Aqualung,'' ``Thick As a Brick'' and ``A Passion
Play'' _ are still considered some of the most ambitious projects
of the concept-album era. It even managed to win its first Grammy _
for best hard rock/heavy metal performance _ with the release of
``Crest of a Knave'' in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   There's also something refreshingly honest about the group, both
in terms of its ability to laugh at itself and its faith in the
music it plays. Of the former, the 52-year-old Anderson says it's
better to be aware of one's reputation ``and build upon it
knowingly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been making a living on the self-deprecating side of
humor for the last 30 years,'' he explains. ``It's something I've
always based part of my presentation on, making fun of myself and
the others in the band.''
</P>
<P>
   TULL WON'T TRY TO CONFORM
</P>
<P>
   As for the music, that's another story. Anderson has no desire
to try to bring Jethro Tull up to speed in a music scene dominated
by trash-talking metal rappers or poster-boy pop stars. Mention
Carlos Santana's recent success with the ``Supernatural'' album
that joined the guitar great with several current chart-toppers and
you can practically hear Anderson sneer over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what you're looking for is some measure of commercial
success, you do what the guy at the record company tells you to do,
and that's epitomized by Carlos Santana becoming a guest on his own
album,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe radio won't play Anderson's recently released ``Secret
Language of Birds.'' In a way, it's the industry's loss. The
disarmingly simple acoustic album represents a gentler side of
Anderson, all pastoral melodies, fluttering flutes and the
occasional exotic instrument. The Jethro Tull frontman, who has
recorded two previous solo albums, says he relishes the opportunity
to create songs that don't necessarily have to work for his band.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm writing songs for a solo album then I don't have to
worry about making the drummer happy,'' he explains. ``You're
completely selfish and you let (the music) go where it wants to go.
And lyrically, I can be a little bit more intimate, a little bit
more personal, than in the context of a rock album.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the album's most touching songs is ``Postcard Day,'' a
sun-baked reflection on the joys of vacation, written during a trip
to Barbados. ``Well, I may be a hostage to summer, but I'm a
hostage, not a slave,'' Anderson sings in his soothing manner.
Still, the composer acknowledges the song stretches the truth a
bit. ``I'm not a great vacation person. . . . I start throwing
things around after three days and being rude to people,'' he says
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The album also explores some darker corners. In ``Sanctuary,''
Anderson contrasts the plight of child prostitutes in India with
aging zoo animals left abandoned. He admits that when he revisited
the song after completion, it made him cry. ``There are things I
have written that when I go back and listen to them, I do find them
quite emotional,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-FARMING ANDERSON
</P>
<P>
   But if you get the impression that Anderson is turning all
touchy-feely, just ask him about his salmon-farming business.
That's right, one of England's most beloved rock stars spends a
good portion of his time raising fish _ and overseeing the 350
employees who work in his operation. If you dare question if
commercially harvested fish can compare taste-wise to the wild
variety, be prepared for an earful. Anderson will talk about the
cleanliness of the water and the diet of the fish and throw out a
whole range of technical terms. The bottom line? ``Farm fish have a
much more consistent taste,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   The rock star is just as serious when he discusses the recent
shooting of Lake Worth, Fla. middle school teacher Barry Grunow, a
devout Jethro Tull fan. The news of the murder reached Anderson
right away. He doesn't blame the tragic situation on the gun
manufacturers. ``I was brought up around guns. . . . When it's part
of your society in a sporting context, you learn the responsible
attitude,'' he says. But he does have a different point of view
when discussing the culture of violence that today's children are
raised in _ just ask him about the Arnold Schwarzenegger movie he
caught by accident on television the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was blowing people away with a total lack of emotion . . .
that kind of violence breeds a complete lack of understanding,'' he
concludes. ``Schwarzenegger and the whole industry that supports
that, those are your killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
