<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMP-HENDRIX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUITAR GOD LIT UP ROCK _ AND BURNED OUT HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was a question that oozed sex, drugs and rock 'n'
roll, posed by an imaginative 24-year-old whose freak flag was
flying high and whose blistering Fender Stratocaster was cranked to
max.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you experienced?'' Jimi Hendrix cried on his debut album
in 1967. ``Have you ever been experienced?''
</P>
<P>
   James Marshall Hendrix _ the shy, dreamy kid from Seattle who
played his guitar left-handed and upside-down _ would stand the
world of rock on its ear, set it afire, put blues to the acid test,
blow the minds of his tuned-in, turned-on generation, and, in the
waning days of the 20th century, stir a music-minded
multibillionaire to build the world's most expensive rock 'n' roll
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was incredibly creative and set a standard that
prevails even today. He was one of a kind,'' said Paul Allen, the
Microsoft co-founder bankrolling the Experience Music Project and a
longtime collector of Hendrix memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Hendrixians, the techno-billionaire spent hours
trying to master the complicated licks of a man who never learned
to read music. ``After long nights of programming at Microsoft, I'd
pick up my Strat and try in vain to figure out one of Jimi's guitar
solos,'' said Allen, guitarist in his own band, the Grown Men.
</P>
<P>
   It was to honor Hendrix that Allen first proposed building a $50
million-$60 million museum at Seattle Center. The
10,000-square-foot rock 'n' roll shrine would be called the Jimi
Hendrix Museum, and house Allen's sizable collection of
Jimi-abilia. A decade, $200 million and 130,000 square feet later,
the idea has grown to encompass all of pop music and culture.
</P>
<P>
   But Hendrix's voodoo chile soul still lies at the heart of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Hendrix story begins on Nov. 27, 1942, at the King County
Hospital with the birth of a large baby boy, part black, part
Cherokee, part white. A teenage mom named Lucille, said to be as
interested in partying as mothering, named her big baby Johnny
Allen Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   It was the boy's father, James A. ``Al'' Hendrix, who renamed
his firstborn James Marshall after returning from the Army and
taking over the boy's care.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of young Jimmy's fascination with the guitar are
legendary.
</P>
<P>
   He transformed a cigar box into a guitar, worked out on a
one-string ukulele, played air guitar on a broom, begged his father
for five bucks to buy his neighbor's funky acoustic, and, finally,
convinced his dad to buy him his first electric, a Super Ozark
1560S.
</P>
<P>
   Singing would come later. ``Jimmy used to say he couldn't carry
a tune in a paper bag,'' said Al Hendrix. ``He just didn't have no
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Jimmy learned by ear, playing along to 45s and LPs of B.B.
King, Muddy Waters, Chuck Berry and other greats. Before dropping
out of Garfield High School and enlisting in the Army, he played in
several local dance bands with names like The Rocking Kings, the
Velvetones, Thomas &AMP; His Tomcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy would walk right across town if somebody said he could
probably play there,'' said his brother, Leon.
</P>
<P>
   After a medical discharge from the Army _ Hendrix injured
himself parachuting _ he set out to make a name for himself,
traveling as sideman with the King Curtis Combo, the Isley Brothers
and other hot R&AMP;B bands, often upstaging the players.
</P>
<P>
   He was already developing the flamboyant stage style that would
become his trademark, taking fashion advice from an over-the-top
showman named Little Richard and working out attention-grabbing
tricks on his amplified six-string. He played with his teeth,
played behind his back, played between his legs, flirting
suggestively with his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Soon his huge, wandering hands were doing things to a guitar
that no God-fearing folk mama would approve of. He spanked it,
yanked its springs, set off on steamy runs and perilous dives,
using his ring or microphone stand for a slide. He bent notes,
shattered riffs, distorted feedback and, always, turned up the
volume. His amps had two settings: off and high.
</P>
<P>
   On more than one occasion, he literally brought down the house,
with pieces of plaster falling onto the stage.
</P>
<P>
   A teenage Jimmy had told his dad he would be famous one day. By
1966, with the Age of Aquarius in full flush, he was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   Critics would one day call him the Black Elvis, the Charlie
Mingus of rock. And on his way to the top, Hendrix had tried on
names of his own: Jimmy James, Maurice James, Cupcake, The Bat, The
Creep.
</P>
<P>
   But the hook that stuck in 1966 was Jimi. In London, with his
new name and a new band called the Jimi Hendrix Experience, the
young virtuoso released two hits that would soon become anthems:
`Hey Joe'' and ``Purple Haze.''
</P>
<P>
   European rockers loved the American hippie with the
here-there-everywhere Afro, the peace-and-love philosophy, the
rainbow clothes, the scarves and waistcoats, the onstage antics and
the backstage reputation for psychedelic drugs and free-love
groupies. ``The youngsters go wild for the ugly man with a perm,''
read an Italian tabloid headline.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, the band smashed into the American consciousness
with a performance at the Monterey Pop Festival, a show-buster that
climaxed with Hendrix dousing his guitar with lighter fluid and
setting it afire. America soon fell into its own guitar-induced
purple haze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible to be assaulted with all these screaming
winds,'' said guitar great Carlos Santana, one of hundreds
influenced by Jimi's style. ``He would really control that
instrument like a jazz player or a blues player would. It was like
controlling a demon and making it sing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next three dizzying years, the broom-playing kid from
Seattle's Central District became the top concert draw in the rock
industry and one of rock's highest-paid stars. He deconstructed the
``Star Spangled Banner'' at Woodstock, reconstructed Bob Dylan's
``All Along the Watchtower'' in the studio and tripped out
audiences at every major Love Gen concert.
</P>
<P>
   They were three years of living high, drinking hard, moving fast
and, ultimately, burning out. In early September 1970, a
27-year-old Hendrix admitted to a Danish journalist that he didn't
think he would live to be 28. Before month's end, he was dead. He
suffocated in his sleep after mixing red wine and sleeping pills.
</P>
<P>
   The groovin' guitar god, often described as rock's answer to
John Coltrane or Miles Davis, had joined the Dead Musician Club, a
club that would soon include Janis Joplin, Jim Morrison _ and, in
1994, the Northwest punk icon Kurt Cobain, all dead at age 27 after
brief, incendiary stints at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix had thought often about death, dropping remarks about
having jam sessions in heaven, getting busted at his own funeral,
returning to Seattle in a pine box.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't meet you no more in this world,'' he sang on
``Voodoo Child (slight return),'' ``then I'll meet you in the next
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't be late.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 30 years since his death, an estimated 2,000 posthumous
recordings featuring his music or spoken word have been released,
along with hundreds of covers and tribute albums of varying
quality.
</P>
<P>
   His life has been microscopically examined in dozens of books,
most notably the acclaimed ``Crosstown Traffic'' and ``Jimi
Hendrix: Electric Gypsy.'' Al Hendrix recently released his own
book with Aljas Enterprises, ``My Son Jimi.''
</P>
<P>
   A biopic from Showtime is shooting now in Toronto, to air in
September. And Friday the form-shattering, $240 million museum
designed to honor him opens in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Elvis, Jimi lives.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny the way most people love death,'' a prophetic
Hendrix once said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you are dead, you are made for life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
