<SLUG> BC-IVOR-GEORGE-CLOONEY-IN-THE-PERFECT-STORM-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STORM' SIGNALS: GEORGE CLOONEY BRACES FOR `THE PERFECT STORM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of George Clooney
in scenes from ``The Perfect Storm.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    If ``The Perfect Storm'' is the monster hit that many are
predicting, there may be only one thing left afloat after things
blow over: George Clooney's movie career.
 &HT;    The fates of television stars who dump their shows for the big
screen have been checkered at best, but Clooney is determined not
to end up in the also-ran column. Since leaving the megahit ``ER,''
he has been working at warp speed to carve out a movie career to
match.
 &HT;    Clooney may have made a nostalgic return to his old stamping
grounds for Julianna Margulies' final episode of ``ER'' back in
May, but otherwise he's been focusing on the silver screen ever
since he hung up Dr. Ross's emergency-room blues.
 &HT;    Sure, his 1997 outing in the Batman suit proved little _ it
seldom does for anyone. And indeed he has yet to snare the
box-office equivalent of the brass ring.
 &HT;    But film fans and critics alike have been impressed as Clooney
has tackled a wide variety of films, from romances such as ``One
Fine Day'' (1996) and thrillers such as ``The Peacemaker'' (1997)
to quirky crime capers such as ``Out of Sight'' (1998) and war
movies such as ``Three Kings'' (1999).
 &HT;    In the process, he's held up well opposite such established
female stars as Michelle Pfeiffer, Nicole Kidman and Jennifer
Lopez, while working with top directors such as Steven Soderbergh
and Terrence Malick, for whom Clooney appeared in ``The Thin Red
Line'' (1998).
 &HT;    He's proven himself to be a rare commodity on screen: an
old-fashioned man's man _ think Gable with a sensitive side, Peck
with a sense of humor _ who also displays an aw-shucks,
all-American-boy quality reminiscent of Jimmy Stewart with sex
appeal.
 &HT;    Now he's bringing those assets to one of the most eagerly
awaited movies of the year, playing Billy Tyne, skipper of the
doomed fishing ship Andrea Gail, in the $100 million-plus epic
``The Perfect Storm,'' opening nationwide on June 30.
 &HT;    Originally Clooney was to play a supporting role to Mel Gibson
as Tyne, with Steven Spielberg directing. But when Gibson dropped
out _ reportedly, his $25 million asking price was too rich for the
film's already-straining budget _ Clooney stepped up, despite
misgivings that he might be too young to play the skipper.
 &HT;    Ironically, Clooney and Gibson will go head-to-head at the box
office as well, with ``The Perfect Storm'' opening the same weekend
as Gibson's Revolutionary War saga ``The Patriot.''
 &HT;    Based on Sebastian Junger's best-selling book, ``The Perfect
Storm'' was filmed partly in Gloucester, Mass., from which the
actual Andrea Gail sailed, and on a Los Angeles sound stage, where
some of the most terrifying storm scenes were shot using a computer
that can digitally generate 100-foot waves.
 &HT;    Those waves _ especially the immense one which concludes the
film's buzz-generating trailer _ are already the talk of the town,
but Clooney says that the core of the movie is still the people.
 &HT;    ``You've got to connect with the cast,'' the 39-year-old actor
says, wearing a black outfit topped with a Navy baseball cap and a
two-day beard stubble. ``You've got to feel for them, otherwise it
won't work.''
 &HT;    Filling out that cast are Mark Wahlberg, Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio, John C. Reilly, Diane Lane and Karen Allen, working
for German director Wolfgang Petersen, who knows all about
dangerous seas: He directed the classic submarine movie ``Das
Boot'' (l981), as well as ``In the Line of Fire'' (1993) and ``Air
Force One'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``The Perfect Storm'' is only part of Clooney's personal
whirlwind of activity. Besides his return cameo on ``ER,'' he also
recently produced and starred in the CBS live-television remake of
the classic Cold War thriller ``Fail Safe'' (1964). He's just back
from the Cannes Film Festival, where he was promoting his next
film, the Coen Brothers' Depression-era jailbreak film, ``Brother,
Where Art Thou?''
 &HT;    In addition to that one, due to open in October, Clooney is also
preparing for a remake of the old Rat Pack comedy/thriller
``Ocean's Eleven'' (1960), which starred Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin
and Sammy Davis Jr. in a saga about a bunch of guys in Las Vegas
who plan to rob a casino. Directed by Steven Soderbergh, who worked
with Clooney on ``Out of Sight,'' the film will have a star-studded
ensemble cast that, rumor has it, may include such heavy hitters as
Bruce Willis, Julia Roberts and Michael Douglas.
 &HT;    Those are big names for a former television actor to see paired
with his own, and imply that his campaign for movie stardom may yet
win out. At the very least, he's one of the hardest-working men in
Hollywood, barely resting between pictures.
 &HT;    He admits that his eagerness to work has put stress on other
aspects of his life, and says that it may have undermined his
recently ended three-year relationship with French kindergarten
teacher Celine Balitran.
 &HT;    ``I'm a workaholic,'' he concedes, ``and sometimes it impinges
upon my personal life.''
 &HT;    Not that he's planning to change. He won't be hot forever, and
Clooney _ the offspring of a show-business family _ knows that it
pays to seize the moment. After all, he spent 13 years toiling in
the television trenches, appearing in more than a dozen dead-end
pilots, before his ``ER'' breakthrough.
 &HT;    ``But I always told myself I was a film actor who just happened
to be doing TV,'' Clooney says. ``When things go well for you,
everyone compliments you and tells you you're great. When things
aren't going well, it's your fault and you're an idiot. As long as
you don't listen to the latter and don't buy the former, you'll be
fine.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Perfect Storm,'' consult
the official Web site at www.perfectstorm.net. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
