<SLUG> BC-TOURING-MONTREAL-TRAVEL-DOING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN MONTREAL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By JAMES BROOKE  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Every summer, after the steel bonds of winter fall away,
Montrealers leap forth for an outdoor season of street festivals,
cafe-hopping, bicycling along canals or simply strolling streets
imbued with the history of a city founded in 1642.
 &HT;    This bubble of Latin culture, the world's second-largest
French-speaking city, after Paris, has drawn Americans since the
days of Benjamin Franklin.
 &HT;    Promoting itself this summer as ``Paris without jet lag,''
Montreal can now throw in ``without the long ride from the
airport.'' All commercial air traffic now goes to Dorval
International Airport, a 15-minute cab ride from downtown, as
opposed to the 40-mile ride from Mirabel, the old airport.
 &HT;    Then there is the money: restaurant checks may look steep, but
subtract a third, because $1 American buys almost $1.50 Canadian.
 &HT;    As Americans reserve Montreal hotel rooms at the fastest clip
since the Expo 67 World's Fair, they will discover an attitude
change here. Montreal is on the economic rebound as investors
finally accept the ``French fact.''
 &HT;    With a huge concentration of college students, Montreal is
churning out a French-speaking middle class. With the French
language more dominant in Montreal than it has been since the
1760s, separatism is on the back burner and Quebecers are
increasingly self-confident and outward looking.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    Fireworks set to music is the theme of the Benson &AMP; Hedges
International Fireworks Competition on 10 nights, which began on
June 18 and ends on July 30, over the old World's Fair grounds on
Ile Ste.-Helene. Among the competitors are Japan, Germany, Italy
and the United States. From 10 p.m. Seats range from $21 to $28 and
can be ordered from (800) 361-4595. Information: (514) 872-6222.
 &HT;    The Montreal Jazz Festival will include 400 concerts, 300 of
them free, largely in and around Place des Arts downtown, from June
29 to July 9. It is dedicated to Louis Armstrong and is expected to
draw 2,000 musicians and an audience of 1.5 million.
 &HT;    Among the performers expected are the trumpet player Arturo
Sandoval, the bassist Dave Holland and the vocalist Ranee Lee.
Information: (888) 515-0515. Schedules and ticket sales at
www.montrealjazzfest.com.
 &HT;    The last weekend of the jazz festival, July 7 to 9, is also the
weekend for Carifiesta, Montreal's Caribbean carnival. Like almost
everything else here, the festival has a French touch, drawing on
the traditions of Guadeloupe, Haiti and Martinique, with blasting
bands to lure 150,000 people into the streets. A parade will be
followed by a free party at the Champ-de-Mars, behind city hall.
Information: (514) 735-2232.
 &HT;    The Afro beat picks up July 13 with Nuits d'Afrique for 10 days,
some 30 concerts and nearly 300 musicians from Africa, the
Caribbean and Black America. Information: (514) 499-9239. The
schedule includes Miriam Makeba on opening night at the Spectrum
nightclub (tickets $35) and Tiken Jah Fakoly, reggae singer from
the Ivory Coast, in one of the free nightly concerts at Place
Emilie-Gamelin.
 &HT;    What's so funny about Montreal? Find out at the Just for Laughs
festival, July 13 to 23. Many of the 1,500 performances in French
and English by stand-up comics and troupes from around the world
will be free on outdoor stages along Rue St.-Denis. Among the
headliners are Tim Allen, Eric Idle and William Shatner. For
information, call (514) 845-3155, or visit www.hahaha.com.
 &HT;    July finishes with the Lesbian and Gay Pride celebration on the
31st. It draws from all over North America, with attendance
expected to hit half a million for the Pride Parade on the last
day, Aug. 6. An outdoor big-band concert is planned for
Emilie-Gamelin Park at 8 p.m. on Aug. 1, and a street fair will
take place at Ste.-Catherine East between Berri and Papineau on
Aug. 5. Information: (514) 285-4011.
 &HT;    Through Oct. 15, the Museum of Fine Arts, 1380 Sherbrooke West,
(514) 285-2000, will display 81 paintings, including Cezannes,
Renoirs and Picassos, on loan from the Musee de l'Orangerie in
Paris through Oct. 15. Open daily 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission $10.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    The delights of a Montreal summer require footwork: strolling
centuries-old blocks and streets, inspecting architectural details,
reading historic plaques, window shopping on streets lined with
antiques shops, or sipping an allonge coffee at a sidewalk cafe.
 &HT;    The best neighborhoods for walks are Vieux-Port, the Old Port
section where the city began life 358 years ago; the Rue St.-Denis
restaurant, cafe and shopping streets; and Rue Ste.-Catherine, the
shopping and entertainment district.
 &HT;    For $13.50, the Montreal Museum Pass allows holders to visit 21
museums over two days. A good place to start is just off the docks
in the old port section.
 &HT;    The new Pointe-a-Calliere Montreal Museum of Archaeology and
History, Place Royale at Rue de la Commune, offers visitors a good
background on the city's development, starting with a fast-paced,
Monty Python-style bilingual multimedia show on Montreal's history.
The tower provides a bird's-eye view of Old Montreal and the St.
Lawrence River. Open 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Tuesday to Friday, 11 a.m.
to 5 p.m. weekends; (514) 872-9150. Admission $5.75, $2 ages 6 to
12.
 &HT;    If you need a break from the heat (yes, it can happen even in
Montreal), slip into the cool and soothing, robin's-egg-blue
interior of Notre-Dame Basilica, about three blocks up the hill
from the history museum, at 110 Rue Notre-Dame West. This graceful
Gothic Revival church was believed to be the largest religious
edifice in North America when it opened in 1829.
 &HT;    The architect, a New Yorker named James O'Donnell, was so taken
with its soaring, gold-leaf interior and stained-glass windows
depicting the history of Montreal that he converted to Catholicism
in order to be buried there. Admission is $1.35.
 &HT;    Four blocks away, at the corner of Rue St.-Laurent and the
river, Cirque du Soleil, the cultural ambassadors of modern
Montreal, offer their first large-screen film, ``Journey of Man,''
at the IMAX Old Port. Filmed all over the world, it follows a child
as he travels from birth to adulthood. $8.45, seniors and
teen-agers $7. Information: (514) 496-4629, or www.imaxoldport.com.
 &HT;    The Montreal Botanical Garden, 4101 Sherbrooke East, one of the
world's largest, hits full bloom in late June. With 21,000 species
of plant, the gardens sprawl over 30 acres, ranging from formal
European gardens, to a Chinese pavilion in the style of the Ming
Dynasty, to a 16-acre arboretum and 10 exhibition greenhouses.
Admission $6.45, seniors and students $4.75, ages 6 to 17 $3.20;
(514) 872-1400.
 &HT;    After stopping to smell the roses, you may desire more vigorous
activity. There's bicycling along an eight-mile lighted, paved path
from Rene Levesque Park to the Pere Marquette Promenade, a route
that passes by the Lachine Rapids. Bikes can be rented at any of
several kiosks in the Old Port.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    American tourism is expected to surge this summer, so expect
higher seasonal rates. Rooms can be scarce during major festivals.
 &HT;    With 487 spacious rooms, the Holiday Inn Montreal-Midtown, 420
Sherbrooke St. West, (514) 842-6111, fax (514) 842-9381, is a good
bet during the peak season. Many of the rooms have views along
Sherbrooke, Montreal's Fifth Avenue. Doubles are $114 to $150.
 &HT;    For the charm of Old Montreal, the Auberge du Vieux-Port, 97 Rue
de la Commune East, (888) 660-7678, fax (514) 876-8923, is a
late-19th-century stone building converted to a hotel. The 27
neo-classical rooms, in great demand, have brass beds, stone or
brick walls, and large casement windows overlooking the port docks.
Doubles are $129 to $179, including full breakfast.
 &HT;    Budget: At the junction of the busy bar, restaurant and boutique
scene, at the corner of Rue Ste.-Catherine and Rue Crescent, the
Comfort Suites, 1214 Rue Crescent, (514) 878-2711, fax (514)
878-0030, offers 96 simple, comfortable rooms, each with balcony.
Doubles: $80 to $112.
 &HT;    One block to the east, the Novotel, 1180 Rue de la Montagne,
(514) 861-6000, fax (514) 861-0992, offers slightly higher priced
rooms on a street lined with boutiques and restaurants. The 227
rooms have bright, modern decor, and there is a fitness center.
Doubles: $87 to $135.
 &HT;    Luxury: The Ritz-Carlton Montreal, 1228 Sherbrooke West, (514)
842-4212, fax (514) 842-4907, the 88-year-old empress of Montreal's
Golden Mile, has just emerged from a renovation that added luster
to its marble bathrooms, its rooms appointed with antiques, and to
its piano bar and delightful garden restaurant. The
turn-of-the-century ambience melds nicely with two-line phones in
the 229 rooms. Doubles are $288.
 &HT;    The largest of half a dozen inns to open in historic buildings
in old Montreal in recent years, the Auberge Bonaparte, 447
St.-Francois Xavier, (514) 844-1448, fax (514) 844-0272, offers
views of Montreal's historic heart from many of its 30 individually
decorated rooms. On a quiet side street, the Bonaparte has an
excellent restaurant of the same name. Doubles $98 to $132.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    It used to be said that, after language and politics, food was
the favorite topic of conversation in Quebec. But now, judging by
the expanding waistlines of the graying separatist leaders, food
may be winning out .
 &HT;    My introduction to the sensuous culinary delights of Montreal
came last winter when a waitress at Toque instructed me to place a
chunk of warm foie gras on my tongue and feel it dissolve around
the sides. In an unpretentious setting on Montreal's restaurant
row, Toque, 3842 Rue St.-Denis, (514) 499-2084, is near the top of
the city's dining pyramid. Giving Quebecois products a new spin,
the chef, Normand Laprise, serves maple-syrup-glazed quail as an
appetizer, and roasted saddle of lamb with butternut squash and
fiddlehead ferns among the main courses. Dinner for two, with wine,
was $150. Reservations are essential.
 &HT;    Within walking distance of the Sherbrooke Street hotels is an
old favorite for a quiet romantic dinner by the fireplace, Chez la
Mere Michel, 1209 Rue Guy, (514) 934-0473. As flute music warbled,
we had lobster souffle Nantua and tournedos bearnaise. Dinner for
two, with wine, was $142.
 &HT;    In heavily French-speaking East Montreal, Laloux is an elegant
restaurant popular with the business crowd at lunch. It is run by
an expatriate French chef, Andre Besson, and is at 250 Avenue des
Pins East, (514) 287-9127, on a quiet street far from the tourist
flow. Laloux offers veal escalope with dried apricots, almonds,
muscat wine sauce and linguini, or poached red snapper with white
wine, a la mandarine, and crispy vegetables. Dinner for two, with
wine, $68.
 &HT;    An affordable place in the Old Port neighborhood is Stash's
Cafe, 200 St.-Paul West, (514) 845-6611, a Polish restaurant with a
Warsaw counterculture air. Ensconced behind thick stone walls with
views of pedestrian traffic, Stash's offers four-course menus for
$13 to $16.50. Specialities include zurek (a white borscht), wild
boar and strudel.
 &HT;    Pino, 1471 Rue Crescent, (514) 289-1930, with a heavily Italian
menu, is strategically perched on a second-floor corner, with
tables placed by the curving windows for people-watching along Rue
Ste.-Catherine. Calamari with garlic butter, a three-cheese green
pasta and beers came to $36 for two. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James Brooke is the Canada bureau chief of The Times.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James Brooke 
