<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMP-BUILDING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A FOXY LADY, A SMASHED GUITAR _ IT'S THE EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A purple haze has settled over Seattle and it's not going away.
Make that a red, silver, gold and baby blue haze with a purple
accent.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gehry's design for the Experience Music Project is a
rising tide that lifts all boats. Not only does EMP look smashing
on its own, it casts a festive air over its drab neighbors. They
include most of the buildings at Seattle Center, those forlorn
survivors from the 1962 World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   The Monorail also gets a big boost. Thanks to Gehry, there's
finally a reason to ride it. Its trains cruise through the
undulating folds of his building's exterior, causing adults to
blink and babies to chortle.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Center owes a big debt to the Los Angeles architect, but
he in turn owes one to Seattle Center. The place is perfect for
what he wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   That goal is easy to define: He wanted to make something new.
With this painted aluminum, glass and steel extravaganza, he
succeeded. As he put it himself when he was in town last month,
``Nobody has seen this before or will see it again. Nobody will
build another one.''
</P>
<P>
   The voluptuous splendor of Gehry's Guggenheim Museum, which
opened in 1997 in Bilbao, Spain, earned him worldwide acclaim.
Acclaimed work has its downside, because it becomes the measure of
everything else an architect does.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry didn't want EMP to be Bilbao II. EMP isn't as elegant, but
it wasn't designed to be elegant. It strikes out on its own to
pursue different ends and come to different conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbao put a dazzling cap on 20th-century architecture, and EMP
greets the new century with a novel way for a building to take up
space yet stay in motion.
</P>
<P>
   EMP is Gehry's first major foray into 21st-century architecture,
and it was inspired by rock 'n' roll. Since rock 'n' roll got its
start in the 1950s, Gehry dipped back to a 1950s/early 1960s
futurism to animate his building.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Seattle Center needs to take a bow. When it comes
to back-to-the-future chic, few places are as well-endowed. The
Space Needle and the Monorail are classics of the genre, as is the
center's fountain, that stranded, soaker-hose of a flying saucer.
</P>
<P>
   EMP could be a stage set for an updated version of the old movie
serial, ``Terry and the Pirates,'' especially inside, where the
walls give the impression of being on the verge of shrinking in on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Flash Gordon wouldn't need to go inside. He could fight off evil
forces with the lightning bolts he'd send zigzagging from the
flying edges of the building's colorful gown.
</P>
<P>
   If Bilbao were a jewel, you'd have to insure it and keep it in a
bank vault. If EMP were a jewel, you could buy it at Woolworth's
and wear it to upstage the queen.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll is democratic. I.M. Pei's Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame Museum in Cleveland is high-toned, and it's a disaster. Paul
Allen and his sister Jody Patton wanted Gehry to do more than
create a house for their memories of rock music.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted the building to be a kind of rock music, and that's
what it is. It gives physical form to a backbeat as basic as a
heart's.
</P>
<P>
   Rock has acquired its own highly educated experts, but the music
has been hedonistic from the start. To convey this, Gehry got
another gift from Seattle Center. EMP is right next to the Fun
Forest amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   The front entrance to EMP on Fifth Avenue is not the best place
to see it. For the full effect, stroll through the amusement park
on the west side.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry's building picks up on the blue water rippling down the
front of the log ride, amplifies it and bounces it back off the
multicolored roller coaster. What was a vacancy at the heart of the
park now has focus and direction. The once-tired Fun Forest is born
again, and this time it's born to boogie.
</P>
<P>
   Because he prefers Haydn to Hendrix, Gehry said he relied on his
staff for rock 'n' roll expertise. Thinking that over as reporters
wrote it down, he went on to claim some familiarity with 1960s
rock, from Rambling Jack Elliott to the Mamas and the Papas. ``Cass
Elliott (Mama Cass) was a friend,'' he said. EMP and Elliott: The
two have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that Allen's $100 million tribute to his idol, Jimi
Hendrix, is actually a tribute to Gehry's friend? Remember, she was
the large one who could dazzle when she danced.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the kind of grace Gehry's building has, the grace
of a fat person with fleet feet.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five feet high at its top, EMP is broad of beam, flaring
out in lumbering sections to curve in at a surprisingly dainty
base.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry loves the exuberant assemblages of Robert Rauschenberg,
and it's easy to see Rauschenberg's influence in the lumbering
blocks of the building's colors nestled side to side like buffaloes
at a watering hole.
</P>
<P>
   But EMP is even closer to Gaston LaChaise's bronze homages to
the fine figure of his wife early in the last century. Her huge
breasts, belly, hips and thighs extend down to tiny, tapered feet.
She floats in place as if she were made of air.
</P>
<P>
   LaChaise's nudes have an unabashed sexuality never seen before
in American sculpture. EMP is sexy, too. It's a building devoted to
the spirit of a sexy fat girl. It honors Elliott and all the other
big mamas in rock who just want to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the fun gets a little crowded. EMP officials say 2,250
people can be in the 140,000-square-foot museum at any one time,
but that many people better be in a friendly mood. Claustrophobics
beware: EMP's interiors will stick to you like a cheap suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry designed the front lobby, the bookstore and the cafe. All
are appropriately swoopy. They undulate through space with a
frenzied energy. They bear a resemblance to the stage sets for the
1919 silent movie, ``The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari,'' which were
created to reflect the mind of a madman.
</P>
<P>
   The interior design of the rest of the space doesn't rise to
Gehry's level. It's Gehry-lite, but so packed with heady,
interactive experiences, it won't matter much.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, EMP is an experience worth having. Is it
based on the shape of smashed guitars, the inner ear or the outer
hills of Mongolia? Because Gehry is not a literalist, he welcomes
all metaphors, especially when they pile on top of each other. The
building is what you think it is.
</P>
<P>
   Roll over, Beethoven, and wake up, Little Susie. London may be
calling, but Seattle is now world headquarters for rock history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SHARKATTACKS-1100(3Ta     06-22 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARKATTACKS-1100(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARK ATTACKS IN GULF OF MEXICO EMPHASIZE UNPREDICTABILITY OF
SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by SHARK ATTACKS-ODDS and SHARK ATTACKS-TIPS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This mid-Saturday in June is one of the few times Kenny
Alexander, 17, has ever surfed off Texas' Padre Island and not seen
a shark. A flash of silver here. A fin over there. An underwater
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of miles away, tropical depression Bud is forming in
the Pacific, causing gradual shifts in the Gulf of Mexico's
weather. Thunderclouds pile high, and the wind picks up. The water
this day is murky with seaweed and sand kicked up by the 60,000
people attending a radio-station sponsored sandcastle contest just
down the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Rock music blares. Fishermen on the nearby pier at J.P. Luby
Surf Park dangle bloodied bait into the water. Other fishermen
farther up the shore stand in the surf, chest deep in water,
strings of recent catches dangling from lines tied to their waists.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny and his surfing pals tease one another. ``Shark! Get out
of the water!'' they yell, and then laugh. Only 14 shark attacks
have been recorded off the Texas coast since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   But within two days in this very June, three people are attacked
by sharks in the Gulf of Mexico. Kenny is one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   He is straddling his board, his feet dangling off as he paddles
out to about the third row of waves offshore. The whiteness of the
untanned sole of his foot is in contrast to the murky water. And
then comes the pain. Something is bearing down on his foot, shaking
it, then letting go. He never sees the shark. Instinctively he
yells. ``Shark!''
</P>
<P>
   He swims to shore. Blood pumps from a row of puncture wounds on
his foot. Doctors would later say he was bitten by a 4- to 6-foot
shark. Beachgoers just stare at him, dumbfounded. This doesn't
happen here.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``A shark! I've never heard of that around here. You see one
once in a while, but they never do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ellen Brody, wife of the police chief in Peter Benchley's
novel ``Jaws,'' released as a Steven Spielberg movie 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The shark that bit Kenny Alexander on June 10 severed two
tendons in his foot. One of the tendons is the one that lifts his
foot, the other is the one that lifts his big toe. It is the first
known shark attack in Texas waters in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Just the day before, on June 9, two men training for a triathlon
off the coast at Gulf Shores, Ala., were attacked by a shark. Chuck
Anderson, 44, lost his right arm a few inches below the elbow and
Richard Watley, 55, was bitten all the way up the right side of his
body. He was hospitalized for two days, then released. The incident
was the first known shark attack in Alabama waters in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   No connection has been made between the shark incidents, and
scientists haven't pinpointed why the pair of attacks happened.
</P>
<P>
   But subtle environmental changes may be responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Quenton Dokken of Texas A&AMP;M's Center for Coastal Studies told an
ABC affiliate television station in Corpus Christi that after last
year's warmest year on record nationally, the water temperature in
the Gulf of Mexico is gradually increasing, making sharks more
active and thus, more likely to bite.
</P>
<P>
   H. Dickson Hoese, a retired marine biologist and co-author of
``The Fishes of the Gulf of Mexico,'' says previous serial-shark
attacks in the Gulf have been preceded by quirky environmental
shifts, such as coastal freezes or red tides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the recent drought has had some impact on the food
chain,'' Hoese theorizes. ``That's speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be the sharks were females, who come in closer to shore
in late spring or early summer to give birth, Hoese says.
</P>
<P>
   Or, then again, coincidence may be at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you get when you kick a shark with your foot in
the surf,'' Corpus Christi Police Sgt. R.L. Merrow told The
Associated Press. That's how Merrow was bitten when he was 13. He
was dog-paddling in the surf and struck a shark with his foot. He
said there was a slight pause before the shark turned on him. Time
enough for him to wonder: ``This can't be a good thing, can it?''
Because with sharks, it's hard to tell how they will react.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely uncharacteristic, but sharks do so many
uncharacteristic things that the erratic becomes the normal. Anyone
who'd risk money _ not to mention his life _ on a prediction about
what one big shark will do in a given situation is a fool.
Personally, I don't think he's sick. There are other things that
could cause him to stay here _ many of them things we'll never
understand, natural factors, caprices. ... changes in
water-temperature or current flow or feeding patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   _ oceanographer Matt Hooper, ``Jaws''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   With so many sharks in the Gulf _ probably millions, says marine
scientist Buck Sutter of the National Marine Fisheries Service _
it's a wonder there aren't more attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, crowds of swimmers were beached on a June day when an
estimated 2,000 sharks roamed close to the Padre Island shore,
mostly in 5- to 6-foot-deep water, but some in water as shallow as
18 inches. Biologists then said they were hard-pressed to explain
the huge school, but a full moon creating strong tides, plus an
influx of shrimp, may have drawn the sharks. An aerial photograph
of the enormous group of sharks is still talked about by Padre
Island residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If sharks wanted people, they could have them. There's
gazillions of sharks out there,'' says Gulf Coast native Sgt.
Merrow of the Corpus police.
</P>
<P>
   Go to any pier or charter boat business along the 112-mile
stretch of Padre Island and you'll see the photographs of sharks
hauled ashore, sometimes from as close in as 100 feet from the
almost-white sand beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people knew how often sharks were swimming next to them,
even swimming between their legs, they'd probably never go swimming
again,'' says Darrell Echols, National Park Service resource
manager at Padre Island National Seashore. The park service is
working with a Texas A&AMP;M graduate student to set up a data base of
numbers and types of sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerhead. Blacktip. Bull shark. Tiger shark. Four to 6 feet
long are common for most sharks. Some caught in the Gulf,
particularly the hammerhead or tiger sharks, are 10 to 15 feet
long. All are known to be dangerous to humans, and all frequent the
waters off Padre Island. About 30 other types of shark also live in
the Gulf, but are unlikely to bite unless provoked, says Hoese.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Even the great white shark _ the main character in ``Jaws'' _
visits the Gulf of Mexico, but it prefers colder water and seldom
is seen near the shoreline, Hoese says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, sharks are like tornadoes. They touch down here, but
not there. They wipe out this house but suddenly veer away and miss
the house next door. The guy in the house that's wiped out says
`Why me?' The guy in the house that's missed says, `Thank God.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Hooper, in ``Jaws''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hoese and his colleague Richard Moore attempted a study of local
shark attacks, only to find that most stories they heard were
unverifiable rumors. Even if they could trace the attack story,
they found victims are seldom able to give any information about
the type of shark responsible. Only occasionally do sharks leave
teeth behind to aid in verification. Often, the victims don't ever
see the shark coming. Sometimes, even experts can't say for sure
why a person was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1984, two girls were injured by shark bites off South
Padre Island. The attacks occurred two hours apart in different
locations, with no explanations ever surfacing.
</P>
<P>
   And even a verified case can have mysterious qualities that make
it impossible to add to a Texas data base, because researchers
can't always tell where attacks take place. The first and only
known Texas shark-bite fatality was in 1962, when a surf fisherman
on the Gulf Coast strung a line of just-caught fish too close to
his waistline. The bleeding fish drew a shark, which attacked the
fisherman. There may have been another Texas fatality. In April
1976, the remains of a young, white male were found in the stomach
of a 15-foot tiger shark caught by shrimpers in the Gulf of Mexico,
about 8 miles out off Galveston. Or maybe the attack didn't occur
in Texas waters at all.
</P>
<P>
   So much about the shark remains mysterious. Scientists know,
based on fossilized shark teeth, that sharks have changed little in
their more than 350 million years on Earth. They were alive at the
same time as dinosaurs, managing to survive even when ``T. rex''
did not. How? We don't know.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beautiful _ God, how beautiful they are! They're like
an impossibly perfect piece of machinery. They're as graceful as
any bird. They're as mysterious as any animal on earth. No one
knows for sure how long they live or what impulses _ except for
hunger _ they respond to. There are more than 250 species of shark,
and every one is different from every other one. Scientists spend
their lives trying to find answers about sharks and as soon as they
come with a nice, pat generalization, something shoots it down.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Hooper, ``Jaws''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious aura of the shark lures fishermen, who use a
multistrand steel leader, 400- to 600-test-weight line, and cut
bait that bleeds to catch sharks off Padre.
</P>
<P>
   They fish in the Big, Bad and Ugly shark tournament in June,
sponsored by Sharkey's restaurant. Or families come and the little
kids want to catch a shark, says Cami Dungan, of Wharf Cat and Scat
Cat Charters.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service, concerned about
overfishing, has limited the shark catch to one 4-foot-long or
larger shark per vessel per trip, plus no more than one of the more
plentiful Atlantic sharpnose shark per person per trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep killing them at the same rate, eventually there
won't be any,'' marine scientist Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they are trophy fish, but the smaller sharks are good to
eat, says Debbie Ochoa, who works at the Horace Caldwell Pier on
Mustang Island. Here's her recipe: Soak shark steaks or fillets in
salt water and lime juice for one hour. Pat dry. Dip shark in
breading seasoned with garlic powder or Cajun seasoning. Fry. Fish
takes about 10 minutes per inch of thickness.
</P>
<P>
   This way, man-bites-shark.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always crazy about the ocean. When I was 12 or 13, my
idea of a big time was to take a sleeping bag down to the beach and
spend the night lying in the sand listening to the waves, wondering
where they had come from and what fantastic things they had passed
on the way. What I got hooked on in college was fish, or, to be
really specific, sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Hooper, ``Jaws''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The shark attack on June 10 did little, if anything, to deter
Padre Island surfers and swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't get sunbathers and surfers off the beach with a
shotgun,'' says Jose Ochoa, a Horace Caldwell Pier employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure they wouldn't want me. I don't think I'd taste very
good,'' says surfer Ryan Steglich, 25, of Austin, who heard that a
surfer had been bitten, but, basically, doesn't worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure that's a freak thing. Like winning the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Alexander figures the bite was a freak thing as well. The
defensive tackle for the Flour Bluff High School Falcons football
team quit his job as a maintenance man for a Padre Island
condominium and plans on spending the summer on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor told me I am lucky I didn't lose my foot. He says I
still can if I get an infection,'' Kenny says.
</P>
<P>
   He has had one surgery to repair tendons (that's when it really
started to hurt, Kenny said). The Bay Area Medical Center doctor
who treated him says he may need another surgery, said hospital
spokesperson Julie Renniger.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny, however, would rather that didn't happen, and he is
intent on healing so that he can be well in time for football
practice in early August.
</P>
<P>
   And he says the incident won't keep him from swimming in the
warm-as-bathwater Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because I didn't lose anything, I'm pretty sure I'll
go back in the water,'' Kenny says.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are just so against a shark ever biting him again.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
