<HEADER>
A1901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-3R     06-22 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: in 11 years.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The city's most visible industry is film, its natural vocabulary
melodramatic. From D.W. Griffith to Marilyn Monroe to Steven
Spielberg, film has carried Hollywood values around the globe.
Television joins in the pop culture wars, portraying an unreal
world filled with youth, beauty and virility.
</P>
<P>
   Legions of gawkers flock to Hollywood Boulevard, hoping like the
hicks in Nathanael West's memorable Hollywood novel, ``The Day of
the Locust,'' to catch a glimpse of a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As the critic Shelley Fisher Fishkin writes in a forthcoming
book, ``Landmarks of American Literature,'' these are people,
``cheated out of their dreams by the illusions Hollywood held out
to them,'' for whom ``movies and the world that surrounds them are
more real than life itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But the city need make no apology for its grander artistic life,
even if New Yorkers and San Franciscans often talk as if culture in
Southern California were confined to yogurt. Hollywood actors and
directors do not often lend their talents to the legitimate stage
in Los Angeles; many limit their work to the movies, and some
prefer the London or New York theater. But there are exceptions.
Last summer, stars like Donald Sutherland, Al Pacino and Kelly
McGillis were seen at the Mark Taper Forum and Ahmanson Theater in
productions of plays by Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt, O'Neill and
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the arrival in 1984 of Peter Hemmings, a gentlemanly
English arts administrator, did the city have an opera company.
Hemmings, 65, is retiring as general director of the Los Angeles
Opera at the end of this season, to be replaced by Placido Domingo,
who will carry the title of artistic director, as he does in
Washington. He is bowing out with Francesca Zambello's eye-filling
production of Benjamin Britten's mordant ``Billy Budd.''
</P>
<P>
   Though criticized for excessive caution, Hemmings nurtured the
company through adolescence and lured some big Tinseltown talents,
including the painter David Hockney and the director Herb Ross, to
the Chandler Pavilion as designers and directors. He did it on an
annual budget of $20 million, compared with San Francisco's $50
million and the Met's $170 million. Philharmonic's New Home
</P>
<P>
   The disconn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
