A1905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-4T     06-22 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: rains on weekends.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of attractions:
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   BEL AIR, 701 Stone Canyon Rd., Bel Air, (310) 472-1211. The Bel
Air never, ever lapses into Hollywood-style ostentation, creating
instead the illusion that you're staying with rich, relaxed
friends. Gardenias and birds-of-paradise bloom in 12 lush acres of
gardens. Superb food on a terrace overlooking a swan-filled pond,
and superb management by Frank Bowling. Double room: $375 to $485.
</P>
<P>
   CASA DEL MAR, 1910 Ocean Way, Santa Monica, (310) 581-5533.
Built in 1926 and flawlessly restored, it faces the Pacific across
a broad beach near the Santa Monica Pier. Nothing here is
commonplace. The 129 guest rooms, decorated in sherbety
Mediterranean tones, are outfitted with wood-slatted Venetian
blinds, VCRs and pictures in the vein of Matisse. Rubber duckies
wait beside Jacuzzi tubs to soothe the road-weary. Double room:
$335 to $495.
</P>
<P>
   L'ERMITAGE, 9291 Burton Way, Beverly Hills, (310) 278-3344.
Tucked into a residential neighborhood, L'Ermitage is sleek, serene
and stylish after a four-year renovation. Guest rooms have three
phone lines, plus a cell phone, 40-inch television set, DVD player
and bar with free soft drinks; openwork sycamore panels slide shut
to divide sleeping areas from dressing rooms and bathrooms. From
the rooftop pool, you can see the Hollywood Hills _ sometimes.
Double room: $330 to $780.
</P>
<P>
   PENINSULA, 9882 South Santa Monica Boulevard, Beverly Hills,
(310) 551-2888. Bentleys and Ferraris crowd the courtyard, and
weird and wonderful people populate the lobby; this is a prime
show-biz port of call. But even lowly folk get Frette sheets on
their beds, oversize towels, breakfast served on Limoges china and
still lifes of fresh fruit. Order a Cobb salad to eat on the plane.
Double room: $395 to $450.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT
</P>
<P>
   CHINOIS, 2709 Main St., Santa Monica, (310) 392-9025. This is
the restaurant where Wolfgang Puck, an Austrian, put California in
a wok and begat dishes like Shanghai lobster with ginger curry
sauce. After 16 years, the gold-faced Buddha behind the bar still
surveys a happy, noisy, well-fed crowd nightly.
</P>
<P>
   GINZA SUSHIKO, 218 North Rodeo Drive, Beverly Hills, (310)
247-8939. This may be the most expensive restaurant in America; I
don't know. I do know that the food is sublime _ full of pure,
miraculously fresh flavors. Fugu, or blowfish, is potentially
poisonous in the hands of lesser mortals, but in those of Masa
Takayama, in this tiny, tidy room, it is poetry. Served only rom
November to March, it will set you back $400, with tax, tip and
sake.
</P>
<P>
   LUCQUES, 8474 Melrose Ave., West Hollywood, (323) 655-6277.
Lucques is hot, hot, hot. In Harold Lloyd's old brick-walled
carriage house, Suzanne Goin whips up hearty, satisfying dishes
like a Technicolor salad of heirloom tomatoes and a bone-in rib-eye
steak with reduced pan juices and a gratin of microscopically thin
potatoes. Seth, the head barman, mixes the town's best martini.
</P>
<P>
   MATSUHISA, 129 N. La Cienega Blvd., Beverly Hills, (310)
659-9639. From this unprepossessing little place grew Nobu
Matsuhisa's worldwide empire. The sushi is perfect; notice the
marbling of the pale pink toro and the subtle crunch of the fried
soft shell crab roll. But innovative hot dishes made Nobu's name.
So try the cod marinated for three days in miso, or the fabulous
fried oysters bathed in a spicy, garlicky sauce. Go at off-hours,
sit at the bar and order the Hoku Setsu sake.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLIPE, 1001 N. Alameda St., Los Angeles, (213) 628-3781.
Phillipe (say fill-EEP-ay) sells a million French dip sandwiches a
year to a motley cast of customers. The sandwich was invented here
in 1918. Stand in line, shuffle your feet in the sawdust on the
floor, order a twice-dipped beef with cole slaw and potato salad,
both delicious, on the side. Then slather the sandwich with the
house's hot house mustard and dig in.
</P>
<P>
   LA SERENATA DE GARIBALDI, 1842 E. First St., Los Angeles, (323)
265-2887. Reborn after two years of renovation, La Serenata is
again the city's favorite Mexican haunt. Once a hole-in-the-wall,
it now boasts handsome tiles, carved beams and bright textiles. The
food remains light, authentic, greaseless and glop-free; vegetables
in the fajitas, for example, are fresh and gently cooked.
</P>
<P>
   SPAGO BEVERLY HILLS, 176 N. Canon Drive, Beverly Hills, (310)
385-0880. Wolfgang Puck's surprisingly unsnobby, unshowbizzy
flagship has no weaknesses. Lee Hefter has shaped a winning menu
ranging from authentic wienerschnitzel to sweet-corn agnolotti.
Sherry Yard prowls farmers' markets for fruit in peak form for her
succulently simple desserts (boysenberries and sugar-lipped peaches
on our last visit). Michael Bonaccorsi, possibly the best young
sommelier in the country, springs surprises from California, Italy,
France and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   VALENTINO, 3115 Pico Blv., Santa Monica, (310) 829-4313. I know
no better Italian restaurant in the United States, nor any better
(and more fairly priced) wine list. Forget about the menu; put
yourself in the hands of Piero Selvaggio, the suave, warmhearted,
Sicilian-born owner. He will give you a taste of this and a sip of
that.: for instance richer Chianti than you ever imagined.
ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYHOCK HOUSE, 4800 Hollywood Blvd., (213) 913-4157. Closed
until spring of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ENNIS-BROWN HOUSE, 2655 Glendower Ave., (323) 668-0234.
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH SCHINDLER MUSEUM HOUSE, 835 N. Kings Rd., West
Hollywood, (323) 651-1510.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES COUNTY MUSEUM OF ART, 5905 Wilshire Blvd., (323)
857-6000. Hours: Mondays, Tuesdays and Thursdays, noon to 8 p.m.;
Fridays, noon to 9 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays 11 a.m. to 8 p.m.
Admission: $7; $5, students and those 62 and over; $1, ages 6 to
17.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES MUSEUM OF CONTEMPORARY ART, 250 S. Grand Ave., (213)
621-2766. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Thursdays to 8 p.m. Admission: $6; $4, students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   GEFFEN CONTEMPORARY, 152 N. Central Ave., (213) 621-1727. Hours:
Tuesdays through Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Thursdays to 8 p.m.
Admission: $6; $4, students and the elderly
</P>
<P>
   GETTY CENTER, 1200 Getty Center Dr., (310) 440-7300. Hours:
Tuesdays and Wednesdays, 11 a.m. to 7 p.m.; Thursdays and Fridays,
11 a.m. to 9 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Free.
Parking: $5 a car; advance telephone reservation required.
