<HEADER>
A1906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-SUNSHINE23-COX     06-22 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUNSHINE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Epic `Sunshine' can be dark, but moral compass is true
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title, ``Sunshine,'' couldn't be more misleading. It
suggests a smiley-face family movie _ maybe something starring the
Olsen twins.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the three-hour ``Sunshine'' is a bleak, sweeping epic,
depicting the first half of the 20th century through the painful
prism of three generations of a Jewish family living in Hungary.
One interesting twist: In each passage, the major male figure is
played by Ralph Fiennes, which imposes an added layer of fated
destinies.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonnenscheins _ the name translates as ``sunshine,'' thus
the title _ make their fortune at the turn of the century with a
health elixir called Taste of Sunshine. They move to Budapest,
where the eldest son, Ignatz (Fiennes), becomes a lawyer and falls
for Valerie (Jennifer Ehle), his adopted ``sister'' _ actually his
cousin _ who's been raised with him. He also, in order to advance
his career, changes his name to the less Jewish-sounding Sors.
</P>
<P>
   The two marry and have a son, Adam (Fiennes), who furthers the
family's assimilation. In order to have a shot at becoming the
fencing champion of Hungary and being on the Olympic team, he
converts to Roman Catholicism. But when the Nazis goose-step into
Hungary, his adopted religion is no protection.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's Adam's son, Ivan (Fiennes), who survives the
concentration camps and embraces the Communist Party. But again his
religious heritage becomes a problem when the party goes
Zionist-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of compromise and its costs is one that director
Istvan Szabo has dealt with before, most memorably in his
Oscar-winning ``Mephisto.'' Thus, while ``Sunshine'' deals with
anti-Semitism in particular, it also examines the larger issues of
collaboration in any form, of going along to get along, so to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Szabo worked on the script with playwright Israel Horowitz, and
there are some clumsy, soap opera scenes. Still, overall, this is
an ambitious and affecting film, guided by a strong moral compass.
It also offers an excellent cast. Along with Fiennes, whose
passionate portrayals hold it all together, there's fine work by
Rosemary Harris as the older Valerie (nice touch; she's Ehle's
mother in real life); William Hurt as an ardent Communist done in
by his religious roots; and Deborah Kara Unger as a lusty comrade
with designs on Ivan.
</P>
<P>
   By personalizing history, the characters' plights and choices
become immediate and involving.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the family patriarch, Emmanuel (John Neville),
Fiennes' narrator notes, ``When joy approached, Emmanuel always
asked himself, `What will come of this? What price must I pay?'''
``Sunshine'' shows us that there is always a price. How you pay it
is what makes the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunshine''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ralph Fiennes, Jennifer Ehle and Rosemary Harris.
Directed by Istvan Szabo. Rated R for nudity, sex and violence. At
Tara. 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Long and not very sunshiny, but certainly worth the
time and effort.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
