u e BC-KRALL-CABARET-REVIEW-     06-22 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRALL-CABARET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA KRALL: VULNERABILITY SHOWS ITSELF, IF BRIEFLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months ago, at a tribute concert to Joni
Mitchell, Diana Krall surprised everyone by forsaking her crisply
emphatic jazz piano style to perform Mitchell's impassioned
folk-pop ballad ``A Case of You'' without the usual support of bass
and drums. Freed from the austere jazz settings she favors, Krall's
sharply accented, blues-embellished piano relaxed into a minimalist
pop mode, and her voice took on a startling dramatic intensity.
Certain lines were punched out (``Constantly in the
darkness/Where's that at?''), while other words and phrases
(especially the word ``darling'') found her trailing off into a
smoky whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a performer as diffident as Krall, the shift in mood
and style was a small revelation. Exploring the musical world of
her fellow Canadian, Krall exposed a vulnerability that had only
been hinted at in her recordings, most notably in the title song of
her recent best-selling album, ``When I Look in Your Eyes''
(Verve).
</P>
<P>
   Krall's JVC Jazz Festival concert on Wednesday evening at the
Supper Club offered two such moments. Once again, she performed ``A
Case of You'' as the unguarded meditation of someone dreaming out
loud. During her encores, she recaptured the same mood in a
performance of the Sinatra-identified ballad ``I Fall in Love Too
Easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the piano faded into the background, and Krall's clear,
dark alto transformed a sugarcoated valentine into a love junkie's
piercingly critical self-assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the concert found Krall leading a quartet (featuring
the spiky blues guitar of Dan Faehnle) through a program dominated
by the 1940s and '50s material she has always favored, but
interpreted from a wised-up perspective that makes her suggest a
jazz-oriented answer to the rock singer Chrissie Hynde. Even at her
softest, Krall never tries to be sweet and ingratiating. What
emotion she reveals tends to leak through a tough, assertive facade
as her voice momentarily cracks into a quivering vibrato.
</P>
<P>
   Krall's vocal style is really a reflection of her spare,
hard-driving pianism, whose very austerity reinforces a certain
defensiveness. When singing songs associated with that sorcerer of
seduction, Peggy Lee (the concert included ``I Love Being Here With
You'' and ``I Don't Know Enough About You''), Krall divested them
of the flirtatiousness that Lee employs to soften her toughness.
Throughout the concert, Krall maintained a rhythmic tension by
phrasing songs like an acrobat swinging from bar to bar, using
consonants to build momentum for the many quick tumbling leaps. It
was all quite impressive, if a little forbidding. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WARHOL-GWATHMEY-ART-N     06-22 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARHOL-GWATHMEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTISTIC ODD COUPLE: CAMP VS. CONSCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2,3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRACE GLUECK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Here's a stretch: One of the more improbable
pairings in recent exhibition history puts the work of Andy Warhol
(1928-1987) with that of the Social Realist painter Robert Gwathmey
(1903-1988), the idea being that the underappreciated Gwathmey and
the canonized Warhol shared an outlook as ``social commentators''
on American life.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts here, each is given
a separate show, ``Robert Gwathmey: Master Painter'' and ``Andy
Warhol: Social Observer.'' But each is meant to complement the
other in this ill-conceived double feature. The museum's aim in
mounting the two together, it says, is nothing less than reshaping
conceptions of postwar American art.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK. It's not a bad idea to reshape conceptions from time
to time, and the pairing is certainly well-intentioned. But it's
more than a little on the silly side. Gwathmey's earnest,
injustice-hating paintings about the hardscrabble lives of black
sharecroppers in the rural South and his later meditations on the
human condition are on a different wavelength from Warhol's campy
infatuation with the sensations and celebrities of the
media-saturated American scene. Moreover, although only a
generation apart in age, he and Warhol had totally different
notions of the premises of art.
</P>
<P>
   True, Warhol caught the meretriciousness of late 20th-century
life, and his repetitive paintings of dollar signs, for instance,
could be construed as an indictment of American society's prime
priority. But in Warhol _ nevertheless a far more complex and
interesting artist than Gwathmey _ there is more cynical acceptance
than social criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gwathmey's work, like that of his better-known
colleagues Philip Evergood, Jacob Lawrence and Ben Shahn, found a
ready audience in the protest era and aftermath of the Great
Depression _ the '30s, '40s and '50s _ it fell out of fashion when
the doctrine of art for art's sake came in. Social protest, too,
ran low on fuel as the United States surmounted the Depression. The
reformist '60s saw some renewal of interest in Gwathmey, but from
1972 to the late '90s, no museum show was held. Trying to introduce
Gwathmey to a new generation, the Butler Institute of American Art
in Youngstown, Ohio, has organized this touring survey of his work,
including more than 60 oils, drawings and watercolors, now making
its final stop.
</P>
<P>
   Gwathmey, an eighth-generation white Virginian, grew up in
modest circumstances in Richmond. As a child, his visits to
relatives in the Tidewater countryside acquainted him with the
struggles of rural black people. Their striving, which had its full
impact on the artist only years later, became a major theme of his
spare, highly stylized paintings, works that deal with the rigors
of sharecropping and racial inequities, but also _ more positively
_ with the flavor of black family life.
</P>
<P>
   His work developed, it's worth noting, at the same time and with
similar content as that of photographers like Walker Evans,
Dorothea Lange and Marion Post Wolcott, who worked for the federal
government's Farm Security Administration documenting American life
during the Depression. Gwathmey himself often took inspiration from
photographs of sharecroppers and tenant farmers by his wife,
Rosalie, also a Southerner.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the Pennsylvania Academy and then for years a
teacher _ including a long stint at Cooper Union in New York City _
Gwathmey was an innovative colorist and a clever designer of
pictorial space. His primary influences were Picasso and Cubism,
from which he learned respect for the flat, two-dimensional canvas
surface. A less felicitous source of imagery was medieval
stained-glass windows, which inspired the bold linearities that
define Gwathmey's forms and give his compositions an overly
schematized, at times even cartoonish, look. His figures, as in the
unusually lighthearted beach scene ``Winter's Playground'' (1947),
more than occasionally suggest the anatomical dummies used in art
classes.
</P>
<P>
   His subjects, too, while often moving and tender, like
``Children Dancing'' (1948), a view of mother, father and children
in a sweet family celebration, can be sentimental and derivative,
like ``The Ballad Singer'' (1939-40), a Picassoesque study of a
black guitarist, mouth open in song. Set within a geometric space,
the singer's presence is asserted _ and assaulted _ by the heavy
lines that accentuate his body.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Gwathmey's most effective work deals with contrasts
between his have-not subjects and their materialistic surroundings.
In ``The Hitchhiker'' (circa 1936), one of his earliest surviving
paintings, the figure of a man, presumably in search of work,
thumbing a ride is backed by an array of billboards advertising
out-of-reach consumer goods. The more satirical ``Poll Tax
Country'' (1945) pits a posturing group of white Southern racists
against a crowd of black laborers. As a pompous speaker exhorts the
laborers, they go unheedingly about their chores. A black bird,
Gwathmey's ubiquitous symbol for Jim Crow, is perched above the
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gwathmey, who was under surveillance by the FBI from 1942 to
1969 because of left-wing sympathies, took up other subjects in his
later years, like the horrors of war, exemplified in ``Homo
Sapiens, Late Twentieth Century'' (1973). In it, two battling
figures struggle while a solar eclipse goes on above. The barren
ground they fight on is a horrific no man's land. But Gwathmey was
more at home exploring his native turf than wallowing in
apocalypse, and paintings like these are not the works to remember
him by. If he was not a great artist, he was certainly a committed
one.
</P>
<P>
   The Warhol show, organized by Jonathan P. Binstock, assistant
curator at the museum, is bigger, with more than 80 paintings,
photographs, prints and a film ranging over the artist's career.
This reprise is arranged in seven sections that include death and
disaster, politics, celebrities, advertising and symbolism. On
view, yet again, are famous icons like his ``Self Portrait''
(1986), the artist as a mystery guru with feathers jutting from his
head and amorphous abstractions playing across his face; the
repetitive close-ups of Jacqueline Kennedy taken at the time of the
president's assassination in 1963; the four-image ``Electric
Chair'' series and ``Race Riot'' (both 1964); and the screen prints
of Mao and Nixon (the latter is titled ``Vote McGovern'') from
1972.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt is to show that the artist's famous facade of
blandness and disengagement from social issues was a giant miscue;
that the chosen seven themes characterized his involvement ``with
what he perceived as socially relevant issues in art and life,''
Binstock writes in his catalog essay. To make this exhibition a tad
more relevant to the Gwathmey show, a photograph of an early
Gwathmey work, ``Street Scene'' (1938), is included in the Warhol
catalog, which notes that a 1970 monograph by the art historian
Rainer Crone described Warhol as ``socially conscious, politically
motivated, and heir to the tradition of American Social Realists
such as Ben Shahn and Robert Gwathmey.'' But by Gwathmey's
standards, Warhol had the social conscience of a grasshopper.
</P>
<P>
   Binstock's shilly-shallying arguments are unconvincing. He
himself admits in his essay that Warhol leaves us with feelings of
ambivalence. ``In the end, Warhol did care about people, politics
and current events,'' he writes, ``and from time to time he did
choose sides. But it is also fair to conclude that he probably
would have preferred not to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
