u e BC-FILM-IRENE-SPI &LR;      06-22 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IRENE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPOSSIBLE TO REDEEM DISMAL `IRENE'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: F  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news about Jim Carrey's ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' is pretty
much all bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's by far the worst comedy either he or the Farrelly Brothers
have ever made _ so abysmal in every way that it makes their last
collaboration, 1994's ``Dumb and Dumber,'' look like a comic
masterpiece in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey plays a hard-luck Rhode Island state trooper who, after
being jilted by his wife for a midget, gradually develops a split
personality and becomes two people: Charlie, a mild-mannered chump,
and his alter ego, Hank, a sadistic tough guy who speaks in a low,
Clint Eastwood-like growl and frequently explodes into violence.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, this must have seemed an inspired idea that would give
the star _ still glowing from his ``Truman Show'' and ``Man on the
Moon'' reviews _ an opportunity to do more than just mug through
the sex gags. But in execution, his Jekyll-and-Hyde routine is
painfully unfunny: almost none of it works and some of the routines
just go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Farrellys _ still glowing from their
``Something About Mary'' reviews _ also have decided to expand
themselves, by trying to make their film work not just as a comedy
and psychological study, but as a love story and a thriller as
well. Both tracks are half-baked, to say the least, and further add
to the movie's excruciating air of tedium.
</P>
<P>
   In between this relative seriousness, of course, the movie is
also out there with the usual Farrelly gross-outs and the familiar
litany of cruelty, sex jokes, bathroom humor, racial slurs and
in-your-face visual incongruities _ most of them pale repeats of
what they've given us in earlier movies and signifying a definite
wan of inspiration on their part.
</P>
<P>
   And since these gags are merely thrown in here and there and
work against the plot line (and against Rex Allen Jr.'s ponderously
folksy narration), they never add up to the kind of guilty pleasure
that, say, ``Kingpin'' was. Here, when we're suddenly treated to an
explicit close-up of a Great Dane defecating on the lawn _ or
worse, Carrey defecating on the lawn _ it's not funny, it's just a
repulsive intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an ugliness between the lines of this movie that's
shocking even in context of a summer gross-out comedy, and that's
its gleefully cavalier attitude toward violence against children.
At one point, we see Hank torturing what appears to be a 7-year-old
girl by repeatedly dunking her head under water, holding it down
and growling, ``Take that, f---face.''
</P>
<P>
   If a moment _ even a brief, tongue-in-cheek, throw-away moment _
as criminally mean-spirited as this one isn't considered by the
MPAA rating board to be offensive and dangerously irresponsible
enough to earn a movie an NC-17 rating, why even bother to have a
rating system?
</P>
<P>
   Me, Myself &AMP; Irene. Directed by Bobby and Peter Farrelly.
Written by Bobby and Peter Farrelly &AMP; Mike Cerrone. Cast: Jim
Carrey, Renee Zellweger, Chris Cooper, Robert Forster, Richard
Jenkins. 20th Century Fox. 110 minutes. Rated R for bad taste
humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: F
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
