<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1914 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      06-22 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE CASE FOR U.S. MISSILE DEFENSE SUFFERS A SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     A News Analysis 
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A thaw in relations on the Korean peninsula and
North Korea's decision to stop testing intercontinental ballistic
missiles have dramatically undercut the rationale for a costly U.S.
missile defense system, military experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the continuing U.S. debate over whether President Clinton
should give the go-ahead to the proposed National Missile Defense
program, supporters of the $36 billion anti-missile system have
cited North Korea's potential threat as the major reason to develop
a National Missile Defense _ a network of rocket interceptors,
radars, sensors and computers.
</P>
<P>
   But peace appears to be breaking out on the Korean peninsula, as
evidenced by the historic visit last week by South Korean President
Kim Dae Jung to North Korea, where he met with his counterpart, Kim
Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was widely heralded as ending 55 years of intense
hostility between the two Koreas and was followed by North Korea's
promise to halt long-range missile tests after the United States
announced it was ending some economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   An array of independent defense analysts say these developments
blunt the argument in favor of the U.S. National Missile Defense
program.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cirincione, a senior associate with the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace, a non-profit think tank, said
that `if you take North Korea out of the equation, the missile
threat all but disappears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if the North Korean threat were to disappear, there is no
other threat in the world that justifies a rush to deploy a
National Missile Defense system,'' Cirincione added.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, North Korea had been spewing harsh rhetoric
against South Korea and the United States while rushing to develop
long-range missiles capable of striking the U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatically isolated and economically backward nation was
one of two so-called ``rogue nations'' cited as potentially capable
of launching missiles against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Defense Secretary William Cohen told a Senate panel
in April that the purpose of NMD was to protect the United States
``against a rogue nation attack, a limited missile attack, a few
missiles that might be fired from North Korea or from Iran or some
other country.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department last week officially dropped the ``rogue
nation'' category and substituted ``nation of concern'' to cover
North Korea, Iran and several other nations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence assessments say that North Korea could have
such a missile in place by 2005, and Iran possibly by 2010 or
sometime shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Blair, a strategic weapons expert with the non-profit
thinktank Center for Defense Information, said that if North Korea
is sincere about terminating its ballistic missile program, ``then
that pulls the rug out from under national missile defense'' for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   John Steinbrunner, director of the Center for International and
Security Studies at the University of Maryland, said North Korea's
missile program was far ahead of Iran's. If North Korea terminates
its program, ``one would be hard-pressed to find an alternative
source for this missile technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mendelsohn, a former U.S. negotiator on the Strategic Arms
Reduction Talks with the Soviet Union, said that with the North
Korean missile program shut down, ``the worse-case missile threat
to the U.S. would be undercut.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rhinelander, a former legal adviser for the State
Department in the Nixon administration who helped negotiate the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty with the Soviet Union, said that
``the rationale for National Missile Defense was weak to start
with. Now, the rationale disappears and would be undercut
severely'' if the North Korea shuts down its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, boosters of the missile defense plan insist that
the program should still go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General George Roberston said Thursday that ``the
real issue NMD is addressing is the potential for proliferation of
ballistic missiles. That is not confined to one country.''
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. Air Force's top officer, Gen. Michael Ryan, said
Wednesday that there ``are other nations striving to be able to
deliver weapons of mass destruction ... North Korea is not the only
one.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. efforts to develop a missile defense system have been
hindered by the demanding technology required in order to ``hit a
bullet with a bullet,'' as one scientist put it.
</P>
<P>
   A key test is scheduled for July 7 over the Pacific Ocean. If it
is deemed a success, Cohen is expected to recommend to Clinton that
the system be built.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
