<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TARBOX-PHOTOS-REVIEW-     06-22 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARBOX-PHOTOS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIONEER IN A MAN'S WORLD, SHE WAS TOUGH ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Calif.)   By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Give people a picture or two with the news, and
they'll come crying for more. When Joseph Pulitzer bought the
faltering New York World in 1882, he planned to increase
circulation by inserting sensational woodcuts, then gradually
decreasing their number to restore the paper to dignity. A trade
journal condemned the new images as pandering to low interests and
predicted they would persuade people that ``a newspaperman has no
conscience, and that when he enters the house it is a good time to
lock up the spoons.'' But readers would not give them up. When
Pulitzer began to weed out the woodcuts, circulation plummeted
until he gave the public what it wanted once again.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only sensation people wanted, though that helped. It
was sensation with pictures, news with pictures, stories with
pictures. By the turn of the century, when newspapers began to
print photographs in some numbers, readers had their own cameras,
courtesy of Kodak, and had decided that the medium had advantages.
In 1900, The Daily Mail in London, which dished out news and gossip
in small servings generously garnished with photographs, was the
first British paper to achieve a circulation of one million. Press
photography had become a profession.
</P>
<P>
   The profession was difficult, poorly paid and cordially
despised, but that never stopped a photographer. A few women, a
very few, even got into the act. One of them, Jessie Tarbox Beals
(1870-1942), is currently being celebrated in a show called
``Jessie Tarbox Beals: On Assignment,'' at the New-York Historical
Society. Beals, hired by The Buffalo Inquirer in 1902, was the
first woman hired as a newspaper staff photographer. She never sat
still long; In 1904 she parted company with the paper and headed
west to St. Louis in pursuit of big news: the World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons so few women entered the profession was that
equipment was so heavy. Small cameras like Kodaks were not reliable
in adverse conditions. Beals carried an 8-by-10 view camera, glass
plates and a tripod, close to 50 pounds of equipment. (She was
further encumbered by a whalebone corset and a hat the size of a
flying saucer.) Still, when a judge in a murder trial locked the
photographers out, she climbed a tall bookcase up to a transom
window, snapped a picture before she was detected and had a
five-column front-page photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Beals' pictures of the World's Fair Air Show contest are
remarkable technically and historically: technically because she
managed, with slow and cumbersome equipment, to record moving
airships and people rushing to see them; historically because they
provide an extended glimpse into early attempts to fly. The Wright
brothers had achieved 59 seconds of powered flight in 1903, but not
many people knew about it or believed it, and the Wrights could not
yet sustain and control heavier-than-air flight. On both sides of
the Atlantic, men feverishly strove to overcome gravity.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, the air was full of gliders and propeller-driven
dirigibles. Beals, who had difficulty getting access to the fair
but finally became the only woman officially recognized as a
photographer there, had herself photographed in the gondola of one
of the airships: she had a knack for self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Her pictures of the exhilarating attempt to conquer the skies
are the most compelling in the show. Beals was a good journalist
but was more exceptional for who she was and what she did than for
brilliant images. Early in the century, when news photographers
were almost entirely anonymous and did not expect to be otherwise,
she was famous because she got the pictures, had what she called
the ``hustle'' that photojournalists require _ she once insisted
that a colonel on dress parade make his troops halt so she could
get a photograph _ and had honed her talent for publicity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1905 she moved to New York, but even her St. Louis fame could
not get her a newspaper job, so she freelanced and ran her own
studio. Her portraits of celebrities, many of them writers and
artists, were praised at the time as equal to those of Gertrude
Kasebier and Alvin Langdon Coburn, both important portraitists,
because she used sharp focus, as news photographers did, rather
than soft, artistically inclined pictorialism.
</P>
<P>
   Today the comparison seems wrongheaded. She did make a
contribution to history, taking numerous pictures of professional
women (including Emily Post, the social arbiter of manners,
luxuriously dressed and curled up on a sofa with her typewriter in
her lap) when women in professions were still a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Beals left the studio behind to photograph her subjects in their
own surroundings, with available light, but sometimes the
surroundings reduced the sitter to the dominant piece of furniture.
Her close-up of the Japanese-born Sadakichi Hartmann, a major
photography critic, achieves real force through the ravaged face
and emotional openness of the man, a telling example of the
subject's power to take over a portrait sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Beals took some strong pictures of immigrant and tenement life,
but these are not on display. Then, in 1917, she separated from her
husband, Alfred Tennyson Beals, moved to Greenwich Village and
opened an art gallery. She photographed bohemian society and the
tea rooms and clubs that catered to it, often selling the images as
postcards. These unprepossessing pictures have the easy naturalness
and the sense of casual, momentary observation that painters like
George Luks, John Sloan and Everett Shinn had been putting on
canvas for a decade or more. These painters, who had all been
newspaper men and trained as quick and sharp observers, believed
that urban life deserved its chroniclers. The camera was a natural
for this kind of focus on modern life, and it seems fitting that a
newspaper photographer would follow the same path.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering woman that she was, Beals faced some of the problems
that confront all working women, problems that photojournalism
compounds. She trained her husband in photography and he became her
assistant, particularly in the darkroom, but the marriage was
troubled, and who knows if Beals was willing to take a back seat to
her hustle and her fame?
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I had abnormal strength,'' she wrote in her diary.
``Mere feminine, delicate, Dresden china type of women get nowhere
in business or professional life. They marry millionaires, if they
are lucky. But if a woman is to make headway with men, she must be
truly masculine.'' She told an interviewer, regretfully, that
because she had to work and be away, she had no time to cuddle her
daughter or sing her lullabies.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, her very success worked against her. Her publicity
and frequent lectures encouraged other women to follow in her
footsteps, and by the mid-1920s there were said to be 150 female
professional photographers in New York. Jessie Tarbox Beals, by
then in her 50s, found the competition too stiff and went to
California for a while to take pictures of Hollywood estates.
</P>
<P>
   Constrained to earn a living for herself and her daughter, she
took every kind of photograph rather than concentrating on one area
or style. ``I had too many keys that opened too many doors, in too
many places,'' she said. This left her without a distinctive
signature, but she could have signed her name ``Pioneer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
