u a BC-WINE-ONLINE-NYTR     06-22 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-ONLINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$6 MILLION RAISED FOR ONLINE WINE MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 By TED APPEL   
 Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Winebusiness.com, a publishing company in
Sonoma, has raised $6 million to start an online marketplace for
winery supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The company is the latest to enter the increasingly crowded
business-to-business market, which uses the Internet to facilitate
transactions between vintners and their suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Winebusiness.com plans to start its e-commerce site in the
United States and France before the grape harvest this fall, said
Richard Shell, the company's founder and chief executive. Localized
versions of the online marketplace will follow in other
wine-producing countries.
</P>
<P>
   The site currently offers access to the company's two trade
publications, Wine Business Insider and Wine Business Monthly,
along with a job board and calender of industry events. Later this
year, the site will be expanded to include a virtual market for
bulk wine, grapes, bottles, corks, barrels, equipment and other
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our online efficiencies will allow wineries to cut procurement
costs while accessing a larger array of suppliers, at the same
time,'' Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   Two wine industry suppliers were the major investors in
Winebusiness.com's second round of financing: Sabate SA, the
world's second-largest cork manufacturer, and Diosos SA, the
world's largest cooperage company.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to financing, the two French companies will provide
access to their international clients bases and will share
technical content and expertise. Shell said that neither company
would have an advantage over other suppliers on the Web site.
Winebusiness.com hopes to attract other investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shell was part of a group that acquired publishing company in
bankruptcy court in 1998. In February, Shell bought out the
majority owner, New World Wine Group, after raising $1 million in
the company's first round of financing.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from publishing into the business-to-business market is
``a natural extension,'' Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which employs about 20 people in Sonoma and San
Francisco, plans to double its work force as it beefs up technology
and sales departments, Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   Wine Business Monthly has a circulation of 9,100, sent to almost
every winery and major supplier in the United States, Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
