   EDITORIAL-PRISONS _ Unless action is taken quickly, the free
world's largest prison system will be hit with another crisis that
again will hit Texas taxpayers in the pocketbook. (Waco
Tribune-Herald). 12. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION: Texas editorial page editors.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _WACO, Texas _ An article in The Wall Street
Journal offers some unsettling news about Texas prisons. The Texas
Department of Criminal Justice is already out of room and there
will be at least 3,500 more inmates than beds in state prisons by
next year. (Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily
News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Lord, the bugs. There is
only one good thing about a drought, which doesn't outweigh the
harm it causes in lost crops, dying lawns and trees, hungry
livestock and a general pessimistic attitude among people used to
seeing the clouds open on a regular basis: There are fewer
bugs.(Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's run for the
presidency is putting Texas' death penalty on trial. And the
convention to celebrate Bush's choice to carry the national GOP
banner provided a made-to-order backdrop for the execution
protests. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ What were you doing on the day of
April 19, 1993? Probably watching the Branch Davidian compound burn
on TV. This makes you an expert _ and us a nation of them. After
all, we saw fire, and footage of the botched ATF raid in February.
We monitored nightly the stoic blob that was the Davidians'
bullet-riddled home. We all knew what we saw. (John Young is
opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
