<P>
   CAMPING-GADGETS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The call of the wild doesn't
chime in to the tune of ``La Cucaracha.'' It appeals to your desire
to break free from your cubicle's confines and actually rough it.
Fear not the flora and fauna of that forest or state park. Armed
with a few discreet gadgets, you can escape the city limits without
venturing too far outside your own personal comfort boundaries.
Compiled here is a survival guide for that high-maintenance camper
whose heart's in the right place, but whose feral instinct requires
a AA battery or two. (Jackson, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SHOWTIME _ Diversity, thy name is premium cable. Last year,
after prolonged finger-wagging by civil rights groups and
predictable hand-wringing by the major television networks, a deal
was struck to put more minorities on both sides of the camera. But
while NBC, ABC, CBS and Fox are still figuring out how to honor
that promise in their upcoming fall lineups, cable's Showtime
network is unveiling a pair of weekly dramas this summer that are
deliciously, and daringly different. ``Soul Food'' is based on the
1997 box office sleeper of the same name, and ``Resurrection
Boulevard'' revolves around a multi-generational Mexican family. In
their own way, both shows prove it's possible to produce top-notch
television with minority casts and grown-up themes. (LHarris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   IAN-ANDERSON _ Ask Jethro Tull frontman Ian Anderson if he sees
a connection between his band and the cinematic rock spoof This Is
Spinal Tap and he responds with a laugh. I suppose Jethro Tull
along with Black Sabbath, Deep Purple and a whole bunch of other
bands contributed wittingly and unwittingly to the movie,'' he
says, speaking by phone from his home in England. ``I'm a great fan
of it. It's not too far away from real life.'' Interview with Ian
Anderson. (Passy, Palm Beach Post). 31.
</P>
