<P>
   AOL _ WASHINGTON _ AOL shareholders will be voting Friday on a
merger with Time-Warner. But even after the vote, the deal still
needs approval from many regulators. AOL's reputation for arrogance
has some consumers wishing the merger would get stopped. (Geewax,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving on the NYT wire in (w) Washington and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ REDMOND, Wash. _ In what Chairman Bill Gates called
a bigger change for personal computer users than the advent of
Windows, Microsoft Corp. on Thursday unveiled a new generation of
software designed to provide a wide range of services via the
Internet. The ambitious vision, however, flies in the face of the
government's pending antitrust suit. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving on the NYT wire in (a) General News and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-PARTNERS _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola will be joining a growing
number of companies that provide health-care benefits to same-sex
domestic partners of its employees. The new policy, affecting all
U.S. workers, will take effect Jan. 1, the company announced
Thursday. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-GAFIRMS _ A gay rights group is targeting nine key
employers in Georgia to get them to offer the same benefits given
married couples. Georgia Equality Project's campaign for domestic
partnership benefits comes on the heel of Cokes announcement that
they would offer such benefits to their workers. The nine companies
are Home Depot, Atlanta Gas Light, BellSouth, Georgia Pacific,
Delta Airlines, Wachovia, United Parcel Service, Shaw Industries
and GulfStream Aerospace. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
14.
</P>
<P>
   TEXTILE-EARNINGS _ June-quarter earnings estimates for WestPoint
Stevens and several textile manufacturers are creeping lower as
analysts adjust their views to reflect slowing sales and tighter
inventory control among major retailers. Retailers are focused on
the economy, and some aren't reordering as quickly as products are
selling in an attempt to limit markdowns. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
