<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1930 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      06-22 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RULING PARTY CANDIDATE IN UPHILL BATTLE FOR PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In years past, Francisco Labastida Ochoa would
have been a shoo-in for the Mexican presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He is a stalwart of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI),
which has ruled Mexico since 1929, steadily climbing the ranks to
hold some of the highest posts in the government.
</P>
<P>
   But Labastida's ascendancy comes as the political landscape is
changing in Mexico, where the people are demanding greater
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   As the July 2 presidential election approaches, Labastida is in
the midst of a shootout with a real opponent.
</P>
<P>
   An energetic, experienced politician and economist who has
worked in government for 37 of his 57 years, he is the first
candidate in modern Mexican history to face a bona fide challenge
for the country's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from five generations of public servants, 200 years. I
have it in my blood,'' the PRI candidate said in a recent
interview. ``My family wanted me to become an electrical engineer
so I could have a reasonable economic life, but it's not what I
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Labastida said, ``I never imagined one day that I would
be running for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in the small town of Los Mochis in western Sinaloa state,
Labastida said his father, a doctor who treated the rural poor free
of charge, instilled in him a compassion for the underprivileged.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was never nouveau riche,'' he said. ``I always
imagined what I could do if I had money.''
</P>
<P>
   Before launching his candidacy last year, Labastida was minister
of the interior, overseeing internal security in the Cabinet's most
powerful post.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 until 1992, he was governor of Sinaloa when drug lords
threatened his wife and killed his bodyguard. Because of that, he
left the country in 1993 to become the ambassador to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   He has served as secretary of agriculture and energy secretary
in Mexico City. In between government posts, he taught and
published books about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, in a country where a PRI candidate has never lost
the presidency, Labastida would be practically assured of winning
the election.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and his party face a serious challenge from an
opponent, Vicente Fox Quesada, who has linked Labastida to the
corruption that has defined some PRI governments.
</P>
<P>
   Recent opinion polls show a virtual dead heat between Labastida
and Fox, the candidate of the center-right National Action Party,
and many observers believe Fox has a good chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   In these tense electoral days, nothing irks the PRI more than
the notion expressed by political pundits that for there to be true
democracy in Mexico, the PRI must be kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida predicts he will win by a margin of 10 percent in an
election in which nearly 50 million people, 70 percent of eligible
voters, are expected to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's prediction is not coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has been accused of voter fraud in past elections,
notably in 1988, and Fox has said that if Labastida wins by less
than 5 percent, the result would be tainted. Such a scenario could
lead to post-electoral violence and instability, many political
analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility of fraud is zero,'' Labastida maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the assertive and towering Fox, Labastida, who is
almost rail-thin from tennis, golf and scuba diving, can seem
lacking in charisma. He is a tireless campaigner, often putting in
18-hour days. But in many Labastida rallies, the energy that marks
Fox's public gatherings is missing.
</P>
<P>
   An avid reader, he is most at ease with small circles of
supporters and reporters. He makes jokes and has ready, snappy
answers to the array of charges made against his party by
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox is 90 percent image and 10 percent substance,'' said
Javier Trevino, Labastida's senior campaign adviser. ``When you
take the image away, there is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But image counts, and this election has been marked by more
U.S.-style, negative television ads than previous campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida got off to a victorious start after the party's
first-ever presidential primary election in November. He faced
three PRI opponents, but was viewed as the ``official'' candidate,
the heir to President Ernesto Zedillo, and he won in a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the outgoing Mexican president selected the PRI
candidate in an internal elimination process. But Zedillo, who
leaves office in December after a six-year term, ended the practice
to the surprise of most Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of free trade and closer U.S. ties, the primary was
one of many attempts at a democratic opening to clean up the PRI's
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new PRI, closer to you,'' is a party slogan.
</P>
<P>
   At the start, Labastida touted change and renovation. But as Fox
rose in the polls, the PRI fell back on some of its discredited
veterans _ the so-called dinosaurs _ whose methods may have been in
question but not their ability to win elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``By linking arms with the party's dinosaurs, Labastida is
betraying the party's modernizers,'' political analyst Denise
Dresser wrote in the weekly Proceso magazine. ``The PRI's strategy
of bringing back the dead and mobilizing the party's machine is
going to backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fiscal conservative respected by the business community
because he would maintain Mexico's international trade ties,
Labastida proposes continuing Mexico's steady 5 percent annual
economic growth, the creation of new jobs _ through incentives for
small-and medium-size businesses _ and building 700,000 new units
of public housing.
</P>
<P>
   Although his pitch is not much different from that of Fox,
Labastida is believed to have an edge with women voters, who make
up 52 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see what's on their minds, women are just as worried
about the economy, security and the system,'' said Victoria
Rodriguez, a sociologist at the University of Texas at Austin who
is completing a book about women's roles in Mexican elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just more skittish about change.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Labastida's biggest assets is his wife, Maria Teresa
Uriarte, a respected historian at the National Autonomous
University in Mexico City who is rallying the female vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is a real man, not a macho,'' she said recently,
referring to the rugged-looking Fox who has been compared by the
news media to John Wayne and the ``Marlboro Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say that Labastida will revitalize the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is a big organization. There are many voices but only
one leader, and that is Labastida,'' Trevino said. ``You will see
the great transformation of the PRI on Dec. 2, when he is
president.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Susana Hayward by e-mail at
shayward(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
