<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NASCAR-BUMPING-NYTR &LR;      06-22 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-BUMPING-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMPER CARS ARE RISKY ON NASCAR TRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER    
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say payback is hell. Ask Dale Earnhardt about that.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-day-delayed Pocono 500 at the Pocono Raceway in Long
Pond, Pa., on Monday, Earnhardt saw certain victory go skating off
the track when Jeremy Mayfield tapped him from behind on the last
lap, causing Earnhardt, nicknamed the Intimidator, to momentarily
lose control of his car.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he recovered, Mayfield had taken the checkered flag
and Dale Jarrett and Ricky Rudd had darted under Earnhardt as well
to leave him a furious fourth.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Earnhardt, who got his nickname in part because
he has never been bashful about knocking other drivers out of his
way, did not criticize Mayfield's move publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But he did come up alongside Mayfield on the cool-down lap and
make several animated gestures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just letting him know he was No. 1,'' Earnhardt said,
his voice laced with sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many have complained that Earnhardt gets away with
moves NASCAR would never tolerate from other drivers because he is,
well, Earnhardt, and he made his reputation by bumping and banging
in close quarters.
</P>
<P>
   At last season's second race in Bristol, Tenn., Earnhardt spun
leader Terry Labonte on the last lap, winning the race but leaving
crumpled cars, including Labonte's, in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the most unpopular victories in NASCAR history,
with Earnhardt greeted by a resounding chorus of boos as he
celebrated in the victory lane. Incidents like that leave NASCAR
officials in a difficult situation. Bumping and close-quarter
racing are what make the sport, but there has to be a limit.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately putting another competitor into a spin means
putting him in harm's way, and serious injury, or worse, could
result.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, racing is risky. What should a driver do when
the lead car cuts in front of him to prevent a pass? Should there
be a rule that drivers must always leave a lane at the bottom of
the track? How could NASCAR ever enforce that?
</P>
<P>
   And should the faster driver be content to follow a slower one
just because the driver in front won't let the one behind him by?
</P>
<P>
   About the only rule that applies now is common sense.
Competitors need to have enough respect for each other to keep
things under control.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1939 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w BC-STATES-ERRY-PA     06-22 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ERRY-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; State of His Union &QL;   &UR; By Laura J. Winter &QL;  &QC;  C. 2000 States
News Service &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON (June 22) - He organizes.
</P>
<P>
   From every corner of the political map all parties must contend
with the union this son of Philadelphia commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an ally he is great to have. You tell Jerry what you need
and he finds some way to achieve it,'' said Ed Rendell, the
chairman of the National Democratic Committee, and Philadelphia's
former mayor. ``As an enemy, he's tough. Real tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry McEntee, international president of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, is coming back
to the very spot where his father organized the city employees
first union in 1938 - Philadelphia. Starting Monday some 7,000
AFSCME delegates will descend upon the city for the union's 34th
international convention.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.3 million-strong union is a modern-day pillar of the
AFL-CIO with councils across the nation and in Puerto Rico and
Panama. McEntee, 65, is expected to be re-elected international
president Thursday for his sixth consecutive four-year term.
McEntee first took over the reins in 1981, after the death of Jerry
Wurf.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts between the city, the hospitals and Philadelphia's
105,000 AFSCME members are due to expire the last day of the
convention, Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This week-long fete registers high enough on the ``must do''
list that President Bill Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, House
Minority Leader Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and Senate hopeful Rep.
Ron Klink, D-Murraysville, are expected to don their blue-collar
shirts inside the Pennsylvania Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and their campaign managers know that showing
support for McEntee in front of AFSCME's rank and file can result
in an organized army of volunteers hunting and gathering money and
votes for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The power of organizing was evidenced early to McEntee by
growing up in a family involved in the labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you grew up in the McEntee house, you talked about the
labor movement breakfast, lunch and dinner,'' said long-time friend
Ed Keller, the executive director of AFSCME's Council 13,
representing Pennsylvania's state and county workers.
</P>
<P>
   McEntee's father Bill, a Sanitation Department truck driver, led
the strike that eventually forced the city to recognize and
negotiate with the union. McEntee, just a child at the time, ate
his scrapple while his father told the family about pitched battles
between city workers, the mounted police and the scabs under their
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The unionists' weapons of choice included Molotov cocktails
dropped from bridges onto tarpaulin-covered trash trucks. Flung
from the hands of strikers, milk bottles, fresh from the dairy,
smashed through windshields into the faces of scabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in the days when the Republican machine ran the whole
city. It was in the days of the patronage system when you job
depended on politics,'' McEntee said. ``When they won the strike
they got another nickel or another dime, but what was more
important was that they started a union in the city. They were now
involved in the political arena.''
</P>
<P>
   McEntee represents AFSCME as the chairman of AFL-CIO's Political
Committee. And he endowed enough clout that when the vice president
named Treasury Secretary Bill Daley to the post of campaign
chairman Saturday, he and AFL-CIO President John Sweeney were
invited over to Gore's private residence for a huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it was important that two of us be there to
confirm the fact that we are speaking on behalf of the total labor
movement,'' Sweeney said. ``He is highly respected by the vice
president as well as the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first union job with the Philadelphia's Department of
Transportation, McEntee conducted the city's business from behind
the wheel of a blue Chevy coupe. He was doing organizing of a sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had writing on the side which said 'Bureau of Traffic
Engineering,' which sounded so important,'' McEntee said.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with determining whether an intersection was in
need of a traffic light, a stop sign or nothing at all - to improve
safety and the flow of traffic. In order to make the determination,
he was supposed to stake out an intersection and count the number
of cars and trucks going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I would give certain intersections stop signs that
they really didn't deserve. Right? Or red lights. Or maybe I'd mix
them up,'' McEntee said. ``So if you are ever in Philadelphia and
in traffic jam well maybe because I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be very funny but he can also express himself very well
when is not funny - as people on the wrong side of him have
learned.'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   As was evidenced in the 1998 mid-term elections when the
Republican majority in both houses of Congress was drastically cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did extremely well. We beat the hell out of Gingrich.
Right? He had to go back to Atlanta. Quit the House. He was no
longer the speaker,'' McEntee said. ``We whacked 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, McEntee is planning on getting enough
labor-friendly candidates elected to take back the Congress - to
have the majority votes on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   And locally he may have some influence too.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell believes that McEntee and the convention could cut down
on the negotiation time for a new four-year contract between AFSCME
members and the city and the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry was helpful in bringing about cooperation in '92. He was
helpful in ironing out the kinks in '96,'' Rendell said. ``I think
that in the city's position there is a framework for a contract. I
think the city needs to do some things that are good for the
laborers and the union needs to give a little to the city. And I
think Jerry will lend a force to help that come to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry is a great motivator,'' Rendell said. ``When you get
Jerry you get the whole package.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
