<HEADER>
A1940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-22 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH TIME FOR HIGH TECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Switzerland)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, with no established
exhibition like the Biennial surveys of contemporary work at the
Whitney Museum of American Art, has decided to do the next best
thing: Take a theme, in this case technology, and take the pulse of
contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   ``01.0.01: Art in Technological Times'' will be one giant
exhibition in two parts. At one minute after midnight on Jan. 1 the
museum, in collaboration with Intel, will open a show of Web-based
work that will be available on the museum's Web site,
www.sfmoma.org, and on a museum gallery site presented by Intel,
www.Artmuseum.net.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the show, from March 2 to July 8, consists of
more than two dozen installations, video works, sound pieces and
digital projects in the museum's galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by five curatorial departments _ painting and
sculpture, photography, architecture, design, and media arts and
education _ the exhibition is to include about 35 artists,
architects and designers whose work is responding to technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web has become the greatest venue for public art,'' said
David A. Ross, the museum's director. ``It reaches directly to the
viewer in a way that bypasses the museum as a physical space.''
</P>
<P>
   In deciding on a way of capturing what is happening in
contemporary art, Ross said, ``art making in this moment is defined
by technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the world's largest chip maker, has helped finance
several art projects, notably ``American Century Art and Culture:
1900-2000'' at the Whitney last year, and the San Francisco show
dovetails perfectly with the core of its business, said Kevin
Teixeira, program manager for arts and technology at Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest is to see how artists are responding to our time
and the impact technology is having,'' he said. While neither
Teixeira nor Ross would say just how heavily Intel has invested in
the exhibition, people involved in the project say the figure is
close to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if a survey exhibition would become a regularly scheduled
event, Ross (who was director of the Whitney for seven years,
overseeing its Biennial) said nothing had been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the West Coast there is no periodic exhibition to take the
temperature of art of our time,'' he said. ``Let's see how people
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen Up
</P>
<P>
   FREE AT THE WHITNEY
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney Museum never offered visitors audio guides until
this spring's Biennial. But while most museums charge visitors to
use an audio guides, the Whitney's was free.
</P>
<P>
   It was also popular. About 30 percent of the 124,153 visitors to
the show used it, twice the proportion who generally opt for a
museum audio tour. This high success rate prompted the Whitney,
with support from Cendant, the direct-marketing and hotel-franchise
company, to begin offering visitors audio tours of its permanent
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in October visitors will be able to take an audio
guide tour of the prewar work on the fifth floor and a new
installation of postwar and contemporary collection on the second
floor. The tour will trace the development of American art since
the turn of the century, with voices of critics, collectors,
curators and other scholars. Visitors will also hear interviews
with artists culled from the museum's archives as well as music.
</P>
<P>
   The tour will also be accessible at the museum's Web site,
www.whitney.org, so that visitors can see images online and preview
selected works from the tour before going to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this to be universally accessible,'' said Maxwell L.
Anderson, the Whitney's director.
</P>
<P>
   The audio guides will offer new random-access equipment so
visitors may view the collection in whatever order they choose. The
guides will also be available in several languages yet to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   For tour groups the museum will offer a new kind of audio guide
system. Each person will have a unit the size of a cellular phone,
and the guide will speak into a headset microphone, so the group
can clearly hear what is being said without disturbing other
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   HELLO, SUNSHINE
</P>
<P>
   Florida is becoming a hotbed of art and antiques fairs. Every
February Palm Beach is the site of the International Art and
Antique Fair. Now the organizers of Art Basel, the giant modern-
and contemporary-art event held every June in Switzerland, are
taking their show on the road. From Dec. 12 to 16 they will present
a smaller version of the Basel fair in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   This month the fair's management signed a multiyear contract
with the City of Miami Beach and the Miami Beach Convention Center.
About 270 dealers participate in the fair in Switzerland; in Miami
the organizers expect 100 to 150. ``We also want the event to
include architecture,'' said Samuel Keller, the show's manager. As
a result the organizers plan to use various indoor and outdoor
spaces throughout Miami Beach to show art. ``It's important to have
it in a cultural context,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Beach has its own contemporary-art scene, and Keller said
fair organizers hoped to attract exhibitors and collectors from all
over the United States as well as Latin America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE, GETTY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Walsh announced this week that he was stepping down as vice
president of the J. Paul Getty Trust and director of the Getty
Museum after 17 years, effective on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The news came as no surprise in the art world. Even before the
museum opened it sprawling $1 billion campus on a hilltop in Los
Angeles two years ago, there were rumors that he was planning to
leave once the building was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is being replaced by Deborah Gribbon, the museum's chief
curator, who has also been the Getty's deputy director for two
years, overseeing the museums day-to-day operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
