<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1941 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POLL-0623-COX     06-22 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S ``MOVING PICTURES'' HEADED IN WRONG DIRECTION
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore's presidential campaign strategists like to
dismiss national polls as ``moving pictures,'' signifying very
little beyond the moment. But a lot of ``moving pictures'' are
moving in the wrong direction for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The latest is the Voter.com-Battleground poll released Thursday
showing Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the likely Republican
presidential nominee, widening his lead over Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee, by a margin of 12 percentage points, double
Bush's lead in May.
</P>
<P>
   It comes on the same day that a Gallup poll shows Bush leading
by 4 points, a day after an NBC-Wall Street Journal poll showed
Bush with an 8-point lead, a week after a Los Angeles Times poll
showed Bush leading by 10 points and nearly two weeks after a
Washington Post-ABC poll showed Bush with a 4-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Gore campaign officials in Nashville insisted
Thursday that the vice president's campaign is right on track.
``The campaign is ready for the fall election,'' said Mark Fabiani,
the Gore campaign's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, however, Gore has to reverse the polling trend
that has favored Bush since the two men secured their parties'
presidential nominations this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane has repeatedly said that
``polls are moving pictures,'' without much significance prior to
the presidential nominating conventions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, polls taken in June in past presidential elections have
not necessarily predicted the winner in November. In 1968, 1980,
1988 and 1992 the leader in June lost in November. Two of those
elections involved Bush's father, former President George Bush, who
trailed in June 1988 but won and led in June 1992 but lost.
</P>
<P>
   But last April, after Gore and Bush had vanquished their primary
foes, the Gore campaign pointed to the polls at that time showing
the two candidates in a virtual dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Gallup had Bush holding a statistically
meaningless 46-45 percent lead over Gore. But since then, the Texas
governor has been inching away from Gore. Gallup had Bush at 48
percent and Gore at 44 percent in their poll released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Voter.com-Battleground 2000 poll, widely
respected for its bipartisanship, showed Bush and Gore in a virtual
dead heat in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But in May, the poll showed Bush leading 48-42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And the poll released Thursday, the last before the Republican
and Democratic conventions this summer, shows Bush widening his
lead to 52-40 percent over Gore in June.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Goeas, the Republican pollster who conducts the Battleground
poll, said the Bush campaign ``appears to be healthy and in full
force'' following a tougher-than-expected primary contest with Sen.
John McCain of Arizona and is reaching a broad spectrum of voters,
including such Democratic-leaning groups as seniors, union
households and women.
</P>
<P>
   His only cautious word about the Bush campaign was that the
governor has just about ``maximized'' his appeal to core Republican
voters and must be careful not to lose the moderate swing voters -
``the voters you can rent but never buy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Celinda Lake, his Democratic counterpart in the Battleground
poll, said Bush has benefited from a Republican base ``much more
energized'' that traditional Democratic voters, but insisted that
the upcoming Democratic convention would focus their attention on
the race, especially women.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have kids, work, laundry to juggle,'' she said. ``Women
have traditionally been late to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goeas argued that Gore's lag in the poll is the result of
the vice president's inability to connect with voters rather than
the voters' attention being elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``By last count, the Gore campaign has tried to reinvent
candidate Al Gore five or six times,'' he said. ``The message the
Gore campaign seems to be sending, and reinforcing, with the voters
is that Al Gore is an empty shell.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake said turnout would be crucial to a Democratic victory.
``We'll need a strong grass-roots campaign to win in November,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Voter.com queried 1,000 likely voters between June 11 and 13.
The poll had a margin of error of 3.1 percentage points. Gallup
polled 1,032 likely voters June 6 and 7. Its margin of error was 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   www.voter.com
</P>
<P>
   www.gallup.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
