<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1953 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-BOOTCAMP-COX     06-22 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BOOTCAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young missionaries from Hobe Sound Bible College spend a week in
the wilds of Okeechobee
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH FLORIDA _ Thirty miles north of Lake Okeechobee, past a
dirt road that peters out into two ruts in the woods, 18-year-old
Levi Adams is preparing to spend four weeks in South Africa
preaching the Word.
</P>
<P>
   And sweating _ a lot. It's 88 degrees in the shade and the shade
is the closest thing to air conditioning in sight. This is
missionary boot camp, South Florida style, and the order of the day
is readying 30 teenage and twentysomething evangelists like Adams
for a month in the mission fields of some far-flung places.
Sweating is part of that preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he going to South Africa? ``I think the Lord wants me to
go,'' said Levi. ``I'm hoping to put an impact on the kids' lives
so when they get older they'll remember that there is a God and
that no matter what kind of poverty they are in or whatever, they
can still feel loved.''
</P>
<P>
   During the five-day camp, the four groups heading to Mongolia,
Alaska, the Dominican Republic and South Africa help build and
maintain the handful of structures on the 26-acre camp, memorize
Bible verses, cook in a rustic kitchen and take part in games and
exercises to build cohesiveness. At night they sleep in tents and
by day they are strictly graded on how well they clean their camp
sites and do their chores.
</P>
<P>
   It's a clean-cut and high-spirited crew from all over the United
States. The boys wear blue pants and the girls wear blue,
ankle-length denim skirts with their hair in braids. Everybody has
on the same blue and white T-shirts with the name of their
destination on the back. Reveille is at dawn and the first order of
business is to run an obstacle course worthy of Fort Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough but if I wasn't here I'd be a bum sleeping till 2
every day,'' said April Delgado, an 18-year-old from Hollywood,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 13th year the Hobe Sound Bible College has run the
camp. The hardships shared by the kids are designed to teach them
to rely on one another and to prepare them for life away from the
comforts of the United States. Ideally, says Director George
Vernon, when they arrive at their destinations they will be able to
help the full-time missionaries already there spread the Gospel,
and not waste too much time acclimating to their new surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to break them down a little bit and then build them up
so they'll be stronger,'' says Vernon. ``We want them to operate as
a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The interdenominational Protestant camp is part of the Bible
college's Touching Lives for Christ program (TLC) which tries to
spread the Christian Gospel through service projects. To pay for
their trips the kids raise about $2,500 a piece, usually by
soliciting friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   Camps like this are becoming more popular since they first began
in the 1960s. About 20,000 kids will train this summer in one- and
two-week courses across the country before heading out to mission
fields all over the world. Though the TLC program is evenly split,
overall the trips tend to attract about twice as many girls as
boys.
</P>
<P>
   Teen Missions International on Merritt Island is the granddaddy
of the teen boot camps, growing from just a handful of kids 30
years ago to 1,500 this summer. Programs have gotten so popular
that in the last few years the camp opened courses for 10- to
13-year-olds and, more recently, for 7- to 9-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This all started because when we began taking kids to the
mission fields they were a danger to themselves and they had
terrible culture shock,'' said Camille Haddock, a camp director at
Teen Missions International. ``This makes them much more
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Curriculum at these camps typically stresses how to travel
safely, work with people from other cultures and evangelize
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The group from TLC heading to Mongolia, for instance, learned
never to point, pass anything with their left hand and to expect
some pushing and shoving when they are waiting in line. And if they
accidentally step on someone's toes in a crowd? Shake hands and
smile.
</P>
<P>
   They also learn what to do if they are abducted or arrested.
(Maintain a physical and mental routine and try to remain
positive.)
</P>
<P>
   Youth organizations like TLC and Teen Missions International are
major feeding grounds for full-time, adult missionaries, said
Haddock. There are about 40,000 missionaries from the United States
working abroad at any given time, according to Operation World in
Colorado Springs, Col., an organization that compiles missionary
statistics. About 35,000 are Protestant and 5,000 are Catholic.
Most missionaries spend two to four years abroad and then come back
to the United States for a year to meet with their sponsors and
raise money.
</P>
<P>
   What makes missionary work so fulfilling, says Bud Hannold, a
TLC camp counselor and a veteran of four missions, is that in most
Third World countries people are more willing to listen to the
Gospel than they are in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very hardened here,'' Hannold said. ``People are
much more open in the places where we go. They're a lot easier to
talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   The sort of evangelical work the teens will do is pretty basic,
said Hannold. Mostly they will teach children Bible stories and
songs and pass out religious pamphlets. In Mongolia they will work
at a missionary orphanage. The aim of that particular orphanage is
to teach the children to become evangelists to their countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really fun to teach and to watch people grow with the
Lord,'' said Leah Delamarter, a 22-year-old team leader who grew up
the daughter of missionary parents in Papua, New Guinea. She has
taught Bible class since she was 9 years old. ``We tell them a
story, a true story, and they decide whether to follow it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they decide to follow it, it can make their lives better
and that feels good to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
