<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-EMP-BUILDING-SPI &LR;      06-22 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMP-BUILDING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A FOXY LADY, A SMASHED GUITAR _ IT'S THE EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A purple haze has settled over Seattle and it's not going away.
Make that a red, silver, gold and baby blue haze with a purple
accent.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gehry's design for the Experience Music Project is a
rising tide that lifts all boats. Not only does EMP look smashing
on its own, it casts a festive air over its drab neighbors. They
include most of the buildings at Seattle Center, those forlorn
survivors from the 1962 World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   The Monorail also gets a big boost. Thanks to Gehry, there's
finally a reason to ride it. Its trains cruise through the
undulating folds of his building's exterior, causing adults to
blink and babies to chortle.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Center owes a big debt to the Los Angeles architect, but
he in turn owes one to Seattle Center. The place is perfect for
what he wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   That goal is easy to define: He wanted to make something new.
With this painted aluminum, glass and steel extravaganza, he
succeeded. As he put it himself when he was in town last month,
``Nobody has seen this before or will see it again. Nobody will
build another one.''
</P>
<P>
   The voluptuous splendor of Gehry's Guggenheim Museum, which
opened in 1997 in Bilbao, Spain, earned him worldwide acclaim.
Acclaimed work has its downside, because it becomes the measure of
everything else an architect does.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry didn't want EMP to be Bilbao II. EMP isn't as elegant, but
it wasn't designed to be elegant. It strikes out on its own to
pursue different ends and come to different conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbao put a dazzling cap on 20th-century architecture, and EMP
greets the new century with a novel way for a building to take up
space yet stay in motion.
</P>
<P>
   EMP is Gehry's first major foray into 21st-century architecture,
and it was inspired by rock 'n' roll. Since rock 'n' roll got its
start in the 1950s, Gehry dipped back to a 1950s/early 1960s
futurism to animate his building.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Seattle Center needs to take a bow. When it comes
to back-to-the-future chic, few places are as well-endowed. The
Space Needle and the Monorail are classics of the genre, as is the
center's fountain, that stranded, soaker-hose of a flying saucer.
</P>
<P>
   EMP could be a stage set for an updated version of the old movie
serial, ``Terry and the Pirates,'' especially inside, where the
walls give the impression of being on the verge of shrinking in on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Flash Gordon wouldn't need to go inside. He could fight off evil
forces with the lightning bolts he'd send zigzagging from the
flying edges of the building's colorful gown.
</P>
<P>
   If Bilbao were a jewel, you'd have to insure it and keep it in a
bank vault. If EMP were a jewel, you could buy it at Woolworth's
and wear it to upstage the queen.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll is democratic. I.M. Pei's Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame Museum in Cleveland is high-toned, and it's a disaster. Paul
Allen and his sister Jody Patton wanted Gehry to do more than
create a house for their memories of rock music.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted the building to be a kind of rock music, and that's
what it is. It gives physical form to a backbeat as basic as a
heart's.
</P>
<P>
   Rock has acquired its own highly educated experts, but the music
has been hedonistic from the start. To convey this, Gehry got
another gift from Seattle Center. EMP is right next to the Fun
Forest amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   The front entrance to EMP on Fifth Avenue is not the best place
to see it. For the full effect, stroll through the amusement park
on the west side.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry's building picks up on the blue water rippling down the
front of the log ride, amplifies it and bounces it back off the
multicolored roller coaster. What was a vacancy at the heart of the
park now has focus and direction. The once-tired Fun Forest is born
again, and this time it's born to boogie.
</P>
<P>
   Because he prefers Haydn to Hendrix, Gehry said he relied on his
staff for rock 'n' roll expertise. Thinking that over as reporters
wrote it down, he went on to claim some familiarity with 1960s
rock, from Rambling Jack Elliott to the Mamas and the Papas. ``Cass
Elliott (Mama Cass) was a friend,'' he said. EMP and Elliott: The
two have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that Allen's $100 million tribute to his idol, Jimi
Hendrix, is actually a tribute to Gehry's friend? Remember, she was
the large one who could dazzle when she danced.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the kind of grace Gehry's building has, the grace
of a fat person with fleet feet.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five feet high at its top, EMP is broad of beam, flaring
out in lumbering sections to curve in at a surprisingly dainty
base.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry loves the exuberant assemblages of Robert Rauschenberg,
and it's easy to see Rauschenberg's influence in the lumbering
blocks of the building's colors nestled side to side like buffaloes
at a watering hole.
</P>
<P>
   But EMP is even closer to Gaston LaChaise's bronze homages to
the fine figure of his wife early in the last century. Her huge
breasts, belly, hips and thighs extend down to tiny, tapered feet.
She floats in place as if she were made of air.
</P>
<P>
   LaChaise's nudes have an unabashed sexuality never seen before
in American sculpture. EMP is sexy, too. It's a building devoted to
the spirit of a sexy fat girl. It honors Elliott and all the other
big mamas in rock who just want to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the fun gets a little crowded. EMP officials say 2,250
people can be in the 140,000-square-foot museum at any one time,
but that many people better be in a friendly mood. Claustrophobics
beware: EMP's interiors will stick to you like a cheap suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry designed the front lobby, the bookstore and the cafe. All
are appropriately swoopy. They undulate through space with a
frenzied energy. They bear a resemblance to the stage sets for the
1919 silent movie, ``The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari,'' which were
created to reflect the mind of a madman.
</P>
<P>
   The interior design of the rest of the space doesn't rise to
Gehry's level. It's Gehry-lite, but so packed with heady,
interactive experiences, it won't matter much.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, EMP is an experience worth having. Is it
based on the shape of smashed guitars, the inner ear or the outer
hills of Mongolia? Because Gehry is not a literalist, he welcomes
all metaphors, especially when they pile on top of each other. The
building is what you think it is.
</P>
<P>
   Roll over, Beethoven, and wake up, Little Susie. London may be
calling, but Seattle is now world headquarters for rock history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
