<SLUG> BC-TREK-JAMES-MARSDEN-IN-X-MEN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE CONTACT: JAMES MARSDEN TALKS ABOUT `X-MEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of James
Marsden with Hugh Jackman, Patrick Stewart, Famke Janssen and Halle
Berry in a scene from ``X-Men.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Sometimes your best fans are your worst enemies.
 &HT;    James Marsden, who plays Cyclops in ``X-Men,'' knows that untold
numbers of X-maniacs are counting the days until the release of
director Bryan Singer's megamovie.
 &HT;    And Marsden also knows that those selfsame aficionados of ``The
Uncanny X-Men,'' the planet's most popular comic book, are already
more than a little keyed up and concerned about the July 14
release.
 &HT;    ``When somebody is a big fan of something and has been reading
it their whole life, they have certain expectations,'' the actor
says. ``That's not me, actually, because I haven't ever really been
into comic books.
 &HT;    ``But I do know how seriously people take `X-Men,''' he adds.
``After I got the role and read the comic, I wanted to go by the
comic.''
 &HT;    Like the comic book, the film introduces us to Scott Summers,
a.k.a. Cyclops, a mutant who can fire a concussive, explosive beam
of red light from his eyes _ a beam which can be controlled only by
a visor holding ruby-quartz lenses. Cyclops is one of the good
guys, joining Professor X (Patrick Stewart) and his followers in
combating the machinations of Magneto (Ian McKellen), a mutant
determined to annihilate mankind.
 &HT;    Marsden _ best known as the chiseled star of the television
series ``Party of Five'' and the films ``Disturbing Behavior''
(1998) and ``Gossip'' (2000) _ describes Cyclops as young, stoic
and deadly serious, though the film does make time to explore the
love triangle between Cyclops and fellow X-Men Jean Grey (Famke
Janssen) and Wolverine (Hugh Jackman).
 &HT;    The pairing of the 26-year-old Marsden and the 35-year-old
Janssen has created a stir among die-hard fans, who know Scott and
Jean as contemporaries, classmates at Professor X's school for
mutants.
 &HT;    ``To be completely honest, the age issue was Bryan's problem
through the whole casting period,'' Marsden says. ``I met Bryan
five or six times, and around the fourth time he said, `Well, look,
if I go younger you have the role.' Thank God he decided to go
younger!
 &HT;    ``People freak out because, in the comic, Scott and Jean are the
same age,'' Marsden says by telephone from his Los Angeles home.
``I don't worry about it too much, because I don't see any reason
why you can't have an older woman with a younger guy. You see it so
often in Hollywood, where it's a way-older guy with a younger girl.
 &HT;    ``When I say `older woman,' in our case it's by just a few
years,'' he hastens to add. ``I also have to point out that `X-Men'
has been out for 37 years, and the characters have all aged five
years. So we've got to start somewhere if we're going to do this as
a franchise.''
 &HT;    The comic-book Cyclops is a troubled, brooding character, torn
between his duties as team leader and the isolation imposed by his
potentially lethal power. But Marsden reports than this aspect of
the role is largely absent from the movie.
 &HT;    ``In the early versions of the script, there was a bit of Scott
being insecure and struggling with the idea of being the group's
leader,'' Marsden says. ``He didn't feel well suited for the group,
and felt everyone was at risk being around him.
 &HT;    ``Some of that's still there, but there are so many story lines
and characters that it was hard to get in the last little detail
from the comic,'' the actor says. ``The tragic-hero element is not
really in the movie, but I tried to show a little of it in my
scenes. People can decide for themselves if it's in there.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, Marsden emphasizes, ``X-Men'' does retain the
comic book's overall theme of outsiders fighting for acceptance by
mainstream society.
 &HT;    ``We're not preaching to anybody,'' he says, ``but Bryan saw a
great story in this group of people who, by nature, against their
will, have been condemned and threatened by the human race, but who
need to figure out a way to live with the human race.
 &HT;    ``If, in real life, you're any sort of minority, you've probably
felt that way,'' he adds. ``Everybody has felt like an outcast, and
everybody wants to fit in and belong. That's the idea that Bryan
liked about the comic, and he just went with that raw
information.''
 &HT;    Next up for Marsden is the comedy ``Sugar and Spice,'' opposite
Mena Suvari. After that he'll plunge into ``Ocean Warrior,'' a
biopic in which he'll portray Greenpeace founder Paul Watson.
 &HT;    And after that Marsden might slip on Cyclops' visor again _
always assuming, of course, that ``X-Men'' is popular enough to
warrant a sequel, which the actor thinks it will be.
 &HT;    ``Bryan is a really talented director,'' he says. ``The film
won't have a silly, tongue-in-cheek style, with people running
around in leotards. It's a grounded-in-reality movie.
 &HT;    ``If Bryan's going to do a comic-book movie, he's going to do
one that will shock the world.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``X-Men,'' consult the official
Web site at www.x-men-the-movie.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
