<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-NYT &LR;      06-22 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PLANS INTERNATIONALLY RUN COURT IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The head of the U. N. mission in Kosovo,
Bernard Kouchner, plans to create an internationally run court to
try war and ethnic crimes in the province, which has lacked a
credible judicial system under his administration.
</P>
<P>
   The new court, the Kosovo War and Ethnic Crimes Court, would be
headed by international judges and prosecutors, and supplemented by
equal numbers of Albanian, Serb and other ethnic minority jurists.
The court is expected to break new ground in the pursuit of
postconflict justice, providing the impartiality and scope of an
international tribunal with the immediacy of locally executed
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed by a commission of Albanian and international legal
experts last year, the court has languished as only an idea until
now, neglected as the U.N. administration tried to put a local
judiciary in place.
</P>
<P>
   But as Serb judges have refused or been intimidated from serving
on the local courts, leaving the judicial system hopelessly
one-sided, the special court has emerged as the crucial element,
and perhaps the last chance, to bring justice and reconciliation to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The court is conceived as a local specialized court, with
primacy over other local courts, and concentrating specifically on
war crimes committed during the armed conflict in Kosovo, and on
serious crimes committed on racial, ethnic or political grounds
since the war ended. Its mandate would cover war crimes committed
by Serbs during the conflict, and the court would also try
Albanians responsible for the abductions and killings of Serbs and
other ethnic minorities during and after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner is expected to sign a regulation bringing the court
into existence within the next 15 days, and according to one U.N.
official close to him, he has made the decision in recognition that
attempts to give the local judiciary a chance to dispense justice
have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kouchner thinks we need a credible judiciary. Taking stock of
one year in office, that is our failure,'' the official said,
referring to the lack of a court system. ``The only way to kick
start it now is with internationals.''.
</P>
<P>
   As violence continues to simmer between the majority Albanian
and the dwindling Serb communities here, a judicial system is
essential if international peacekeepers, police and administrators
are to stabilize the province, said Kosovare Kelmendi, an Albanian
lawyer who heads the Pristina office of the Humanitarian Center for
Law. ``It has to start as fast as possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian victims of war crimes committed by Serbian forces
during the armed conflict have yet to see justice done in the
courts a year after the conflict ended and the United Nations took
over. While the International War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague has
issued indictments against Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, and four others, and is preparing more, prosecutors
admit that they cannot handle all the cases.
</P>
<P>
   It could take as long as two years before the first Serbs go on
trial for war crimes in Kosovo, Graham Blewitt, deputy prosecutor
of the tribunal, said during a visit to Kosovo this week. But the
Kosovo war crimes court could start trying cases as early as the
fall. Also, officials said they would not limit their sights to
only low-level perpetrators or the less significant crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs, gypsies and other ethnic minorities, victims of revenge
attacks and abductions by Albanians, have also seen months of
lawlessness go unchecked. Some local courts have now begun working
but offer little promise of a fair trial since the panel of judges
are predominantly Albanian. Serb defence lawyers have already
requested for trials to be referred to the special court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the first court of its nature, it is a response
to such a need for justice,'' said Fernando Castanon, head of the
prosecution services in the U.N. administration, who is
coordinating the installation of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Castanon who headed the truth commission in Guatemala, and had
experience in postwar justice in African countries, agreed he is
breaking new ground with this court. He explained that however a
war ends, with a peace treaty or victory of one side, ``there is
always a question of what to do with the crimes of the past or the
most serious crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternatives to date have been the ad hoc solutions of the
international war crimes tribunals for Yugoslavia and Rwanda, or
local courts which are often not ready to respond. Castanon's plan
for the Kosovo special court would provide, he says, a sustainable
solution that could serve as a blueprint for many other postwar
societies.
</P>
<P>
   The court is intended to complement the Hague Tribunal, which
would retain primacy, and could demand to transfer a trial to the
Hague. Yet, unlike the Hague, it would implement local law in
Kosovo which the local communities could see and understand. ``They
can see the building, they know lawyers are going in there, they
have at least, in practice, justice,'' Castanon said.
</P>
<P>
   The international leadership of the court would remove the
pressure and intimidation that local jurists, both Serb and
Albanian, are already experiencing in Kosovo. The offices of the
prosecution, defence and trial chambers will all be headed by
internationals and each panel of judges trying cases will have one
or two international judges, one Albanian, and one Serb or other
ethnic minority judge.
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of almost 100 people, approximately half of them
internationals, and extras like a witness protection program, the
court is expected to cost $10 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
