<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT     06-22 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DATELINE': INSURANCE DENIED ... IS SECOND OPINION TO CUT COSTS? 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Alaska, Idaho)  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By DAVID DeWITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1993 Lecreca Duffy of Alaska was in an auto accident. In 1992
Cindy Robinson of Idaho was in an auto accident. Each woman's
doctor diagnosed activity-reducing injuries and suggested extensive
treatment. Each woman's auto insurance company required a second
medical opinion before authorizing payment.
</P>
<P>
   Each company _ actually, the same company in both cases _
sharply reduced compensation based on that second opinion, each
time from evaluators who had never met the patient and based their
report solely on a review of medical records.
</P>
<P>
   The practice, known as a ``paper review,'' falls under the
critical gaze of ``Dateline NBC'' Friday night in a segment that
proves network news magazines can still produce compelling reports
in a genre that has lately seemed desperate for material.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Dateline'' segment, titled ``The Paper Chase,'' is based
on a 15-month investigation. The correspondent, John Larson,
narrates the bureaucratic and apparently profit-minded system that
denied payment for vital treatment to Duffy, Robinson and, by
implication, many other policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Each woman had a policy with State Farm Insurance, which often
employs outside companies, as do other large insurance companies,
for objective analyses of medical information when it evaluates
claims. The ``Dateline'' report acknowledges that such analyses may
be medically useful, but not in the chilling practices of two such
paper review companies, Comprehensive Medical Review and Medical
Claims Review Services.
</P>
<P>
   In Duffy's case, for instance, ``Dateline'' interviews a former
employee of Comprehensive Medical Review. He is a journalist who
acknowledges he has no medical training; he says he basically
cobbled his reports from stock paragraphs suggested by the company,
almost all intended to minimize injuries. Injury is a word that
company policy suggests writers avoid because it is
``inflammatory.'' Pain is also risky, the policy says; it suggests
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   These reports are supposed to be approved by doctors, but
another company insider, interviewed on camera with features
obscured, says such approvals amount to little more than
``autograph sessions'' by often uninterested doctors handling 30 or
more files an hour. Worse, Duffy's report bears the approval of a
doctor who says his signature was forged; ``Dateline'' suggests the
evaluation was approved not by a medical expert, but by management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could this really be true?,'' Larson asks after one such
revelation, a hype-inducing moment atypical of this mostly sober,
authoritative report. ``The Paper Chase'' concentrates on the
larger systemic issues of its subject, focusing on the human
consequences of paper reviews and their apparent motivation: money.
``Dateline'' interviews a former State Farm executive who says,
``There's only one motivation for using a paper review, and that's
to increase profits by reducing costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The disturbing comment resonates in the context of the struggles
of Duffy and Robinson, who are shown grappling with pain, debts and
despair. Both women have since reached settlements, but they retain
reason to distrust their insurance. After seeing this report, many
viewers may feel the same way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DATELINE: Paper Chase'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Friday on NBC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neal Shapiro, executive producer; Allan Maraynes, senior
producer; John Larson, correspondent; Lynn Dale, producer; Richard
Platt, editor; Andy Lehren, Mable Chan, associate producers; Rachel
Burstein, assistant producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
