<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1966 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-EDIT-DEATHPENALTY-TEX     06-22 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEATHPENALTY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT THE PAUSE BUTTON ON EXECUTIONS; FIX A FRACTURED JUDICIAL
SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The evidence continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, death penalty cases are mishandled at an
alarming rate, with defendants often provided inappropriate counsel
and scant hope of relief in appellate courts. Americans can't
continue to ignore legal incompetence, ineffective defense and
perfunctory judicial oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Until the states enact meaningful reform, it's time to stop
executing criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Let us be clear: There is little question in most cases that the
person involved needs to be in prison. What is less clear is
whether this society has taken all available steps to determine
that they deserve to be put to death. It is that process that
separates us from them.
</P>
<P>
   This issue runs deeper than election-year politics. Republicans
and Democrats, death penalty supporters and opponents alike want a
criminal justice system that is fair and efficient, and respects
due process for all.
</P>
<P>
   Recent reports indicate that this is not the case in America
today. The Chicago Tribune recently studied the 131 death penalty
cases in Texas that were carried out since January 1993. The
results confirm the anecdotal evidence that once someone is facing
capital punishment in Texas, that person is at the mercy of a
judicial system so tilted toward imposing death sentences that
meaningful constitutional protections are rendered virtually moot.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune found that one-third of the defendants in the Texas
cases were represented at trial (or in initial appeals) by
attorneys who had been or were later disbarred, suspended or
sanctioned in some other way.
</P>
<P>
   In 40 of the cases, either no evidence or only one witness was
presented during the sentencing phase of the trial. In 23 cases,
testimony from fellow inmates _ notorious for its lack of
credibility _ played a role during the sentencing or guilt phases
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   And 29 of the cases included testimony by a psychiatrist whom
the American Psychiatric Association labeled unethical and
untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, seven cases involved testimony by one psychiatrist,
Dr. Walter Quijano, who used a statistical model to infer that a
defendant's race was a predictor of ``future dangerousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Quijano's ``junk science'' was roundly rejected by
Attorney General John Cornyn, who has initiated a review of all
cases involving such testimony, it would be foolish to say that
this is indicative of a system that works.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is just one example. Evidence of equally egregious
problems was found in Illinois, where the pro-death-penalty
governor has taken the bold stand of calling for a moratorium on
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   How can Americans know for sure that every capital defendant has
received a fair trial in light of cases in which defense attorneys
were unqualified and less-than-reliable witnesses and questionable
evidence are presented _ and accepted?
</P>
<P>
   How can we believe that due process is upheld when criminal
appeals courts find no reversible error in cases with sleeping
lawyers and determinations of a defendant's ``future
dangerousness'' that rely heavily on ethnicity?
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty is not merely about criminals or a society's
collective sense of justice served. To exact the most final of
penalties, we must demand rigorous safeguards. And it is incumbent
upon the 39 states that use capital punishment as a sentencing
option to put those safeguards into place.
</P>
<P>
   For Texas, state Sen. Rodney Ellis's judicial reform package is
a start.
</P>
<P>
   _ Standardize and fund indigent defense systems throughout the
state to ensure vigorous, qualified counsel for all defendants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use DNA testing in the post-conviction phase when a
defendant's identity is in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create an oversight commission with subpoena powers to review
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The time has come for a moratorium on the death penalty in
America. The Texas Legislature can do its part by following the
lead of Illinois Gov. George Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial should not be seen as a stand against imposing
the death penalty. This isn't about lessening sentences or
shielding criminals from their deserved punishment.
</P>
<P>
   It's about defending constitutional protections and securing
justice for all.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
