<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GAYPRIDE-ATLANTA22-CO     06-22 1580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYPRIDE-ATLANTA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THOSE WHO FOUGHT FOR GAY RIGHTS RECALL THE STRUGGLE TO BECOME
VISIBLE
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This weekend's Atlanta Gay Pride celebration boasts a
float-filled parade down Peachtree Street; 30 grand marshals,
including Mayor Bill Campbell; and a performance in Piedmont Park
by the B-52's. Organizers are bracing for an estimated 300,000
attendees from across the South.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1970, Atlanta's first Gay Pride rally comprised a ragtag
group of about 100 people, mostly white men in jeans and T-shirts,
bravely strolling down a downtown sidewalk carrying ``Equal Rights
for Gays'' placards. The event marked the first anniversary of a
1969 police raid and subsequent riot at the Stonewall Inn, a gay
bar in New York's Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with acceptance of homosexuality at an all-time high
across the nation, Stonewall's anniversary is widely celebrated.
Atlanta Gay Pride has become a Midtown party endorsed by mainstream
politicians and funded by corporations. Sponsors including Coors,
Pepsi, Jose Cuervo, Stoli and Showtime have donated about $250,000
in cash and services for Pride 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1970, when gays were very much on the fringe, Atlanta was
one of only a handful of cities to hold a rally marking Stonewall.
There were no big-bucks sponsors _ most Atlantans paid little
attention at all until anti-gay activist and singer Anita Bryant
appeared here at the time of a march in 1978 _ but there was also
little harassment and no major attempt to block the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta had a liberal leadership and attitudes that were
compassionate and peaceful,'' says Sam Massell, who became mayor in
1970. ``Not only for lesbians and gays but for blacks, Jews and all
people. The city's gay population also exhibited a willingness to
become a part of the larger community as well. That helped with the
city's acceptance of such activities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta being the cradle of the civil rights movement only
helped the gay rights movement,'' says Gene Holloway, 43, of
Norcross, who helped organize the 1976 event. ``It's unlike any
other city in the South because of Dr. King. People always say
there's a difference between the movements. To my thinking, a
struggle is a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the early years of Pride, some attendees chose to hide
their faces under bags or costume masks.
</P>
<P>
   A photo from 1973's march published in ``The Atlanta Barb,'' one
of the city's first gay newspapers, shows a woman marching with a
paper sack over her head. One hand firmly grasps the bag while the
other holds a sign: ``If I Showed My Face I Would Lose My Job. How
Would You Like to Live Like This?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I marched next to a woman once who was fired after her boss
saw her on the news,'' recalls Linda Bryant, 52, who opened Charis
Books &AMP; More, one of the nation's first feminist bookstores, in
Little Five Points in 1974. ``Even being self-employed, there have
been times in my life when I would not allowed myself to be on the
front of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's Living section. When my
son was in high school, I was very aware that he could be hurt by
my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Brown, 62, is now a high-profile gay figure who has helped
raise $2 million for the city's AIDS service organizations. But he
was wary of Pride in the early years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a while to even go to Pride,'' he says. ``If you
were part of corporate America, you just didn't march down
Peachtree Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Murphy, an editor of the Pride Guide 2000 magazine to be
distributed in Piedmont Park this weekend, first marched in 1976 as
a Georgia Tech architecture student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dangerous thing to do,'' Murphy, 45, says of walking
down the one-lane parade route on Peachtree Street. ``All these
things were running through my mind: What if one of my classmates
sees me? What if a carload of rednecks drives into us?
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time it was exhilarating. It was an incredible
feeling of not being alone anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally grew from 1970 to '71, when marchers obtained their
first permit to make the event an official parade. About 150
marchers received cheers from onlookers along the parade's
Peachtree Street route. Kendall Green, a member of the city's newly
formed Gay Liberation Front, told a United Press International
reporter that the march was evidence ``the gay people in Atlanta
are proud, they are good citizens and are not ashamed of their
homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Massell appointed Charles St. John, a youthful Atlanta
Journal copy runner _ now deceased, who is credited with obtaining
that first parade permit _ to the city's Community Relations
Commission. The appointment of an openly gay man to a city
commission was a first. Pride grew to a weeklong celebration and
was featured on the cover of the Great Speckled Bird, the city's
alternative newspaper. More than 300 people attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a melding of the civil rights, anti-Vietnam, feminist
and gay rights movements,'' says Dave Hayward, who was a
21-year-old aspiring actor and writer in 1972. ``The moment was
ours to seize, and we did it. We walked down the street chanting,
`What do we want? Gay rights! When do we want them? Now!' It was
all very militant.''
</P>
<P>
   According to accounts published in Atlanta Barb, the 1973 Pride
event attracted more than 200 marchers. Hand-painted signs read:
``Homosexuals Are Human'' and ``Better Blatant Than Latent.''
</P>
<P>
   A weeklong event in 1974 began with a press conference at the
2-year-old, gay-centric Metropolitan Community Church, which held
services in a movie theater in Virginia-Highland. A carnival,
beauty contests, worship services, film screenings, a parade,
picnic and multiple ``rap sessions'' followed.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of the nation's Bicentennial, the city's gay
rights movement was attracting young people from across the South.
Holloway, then an energetic 19-year-old from Daytona Beach, Fla.,
pitched in to help organize the event. ``It was empowering,
especially as a young black person,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, the crowd of 3,000 along the Peachtree
Street parade route resulted in Channel 5 dispatching a cameraman.
Clifford Martin, a recent Florida State theater graduate, took a
break from performing Gladys Knight and Aretha Franklin songs in
his drag persona as Tina DeVore at the Onyx bar downtown to watch
the marchers go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were selling drink specials out on the sidewalk, but I
wasn't very political then. I was young, and it was before AIDS. I
was there for the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Martin says he felt isolated from the rest of the parade
participants. ``In 1977, the drag community was not terribly
welcome to join Pride. The organizers wanted to sweep that element
under the carpet. They certainly didn't want us representing the
gay population in front of those TV cameras. It wasn't until the
1980s that we were invited to really be a part of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Pride organizers moved activities to the weekend of
June 10 and relocated marchers to the Georgia World Congress Center
downtown. Inside, anti-gay crusader Bryant was attending the
Southern Baptist Convention. Her appearance proved to be a turning
point for Gay Pride in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of several thousand gathered outside to chant ``Out of
the closet and into the streets'' and ``Hey, hey, ho, ho, Anita
Bryant's got to go.'' Many carried oranges, a reference to Bryant's
role as a pitchwoman for orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with a microphone, activist Maria Helena Dolan
addressed the protesters. ``It was important to speak out against
Bryant,'' says Dolan, now 46 and a MARTA quality assurance
engineer. ``Now she's a forgotten joke, but in 1978 ... we had to
let her know that she didn't have the power she thought she had.
She had to know that our unity for rights was stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the mainstream press thoroughly covered the
Pride rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Monday, I walked into my job as a diesel mechanic in a shop
with 70 men,'' Dolan says. ``About 30 of the guys came up, patted
me on the back and said, `We saw you on TV giving that lady hell!'
It was a shock to find that level of acceptance from a group of
ultra-macho straight guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anita Bryant actually helped our movement here grow,'' says
Gene Holloway, who also attended the Baptist Convention protest.
``What she was doing offended so many people that it brought new
folks out to Pride who had never marched before. It brought out
(ticked)-off straight people who said, `These people are our
friends, our neighbors, our children, our brothers, our sisters. We
won't allow you to treat them like this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And those people have been involved with Pride ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, ``Celebrate'' banners are hung on utility poles
across Midtown, and throngs are expected to attend what's more a
party than political statement. Still, some fear remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people, mainly schoolteachers, have e-mailed me on the
Pride Web site or have sent in checks supporting the event but
informing me that they can't attend. By being seen on TV or in the
newspapers, people can still lose their jobs,'' says Pride 2000
executive director Donna Narducci. ``Those paper bags might not
physically be there now, but there's still work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Eldredge writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
