r l BC-PRIDE-B52S23-COX     06-22 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIDE-B52S23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    B-52's can still add altitude to any party
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roam if you want to, but don't go too far or you'll miss a free
show by one of this state's most popular party bands ever, the
B-52's.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Wilson, Kate Pierson, Fred Schneider and Keith Strickland
are making their first appearance at the Atlanta Pride Festival for
its 30th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The B-52's' music has always displayed a definite gay
sensibility from the band's formation in Athens in the late 1970s.
The obvious points of reference are the campiness of Wilson and
Pierson's outrageous outfits and wigs and lyrical references to
dyed poodles named ``Quiche Lorraine,'' but they've also been a
magnet for the young outsiders of the past 20 years. in 1980, a
Rhode Island teenager named Aaron Fricke won a battle to take a
male date to his high school prom. When he later told the story in
a book, it was titled ``Reflections of a Rock Lobster'' in homage
to the first B-52's single ``Rock Lobster,'' which he and his date
danced to at that difficult prom.
</P>
<P>
   The band also has a sadder connection to the gay community. In
1985, original guitarist Ricky Wilson died of AIDS complications.
He was one of the most prominent early casualties of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The B-52's have always been regarded as being out of the
mainstream,'' says his sister, vocalist Cindy Wilson, ``and we
embrace Pride's mission to show that every member of the community
contributes to the good of the whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't be too proud to dance, because the B-52's are still
one of the best party starters there is.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SHOWTIME23-COX     06-22 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOWTIME23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Showtime for minorities in new dramas
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diversity, thy name is premium cable.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after prolonged finger-wagging by civil rights groups
and predictable hand-wringing by the major television networks, a
deal was struck to put more minorities on both sides of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   But while NBC, ABC, CBS and Fox are still figuring out how to
best fulfill that promise, cable's Showtime network is unveiling a
pair of weekly dramas that are deliciously and daringly different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Food'' is based on the 1997 box office hit of the same
name, and ``Resurrection Blvd.'' revolves around a
multigenerational Mexican family in East Los Angeles. In their own
ways, both hourlong shows prove it's possible to produce top-notch
television with minority casts and grown-up themes.
</P>
<P>
   Like the movie, ``Soul Food'' the TV series is produced by
LaFace music mogul and one-time Atlantan Kenneth ``Babyface''
Edmonds along with his wife, Tracey. The original actors, including
Vivica A. Fox, Nia Long and Michael Beach, have been replaced by a
cast of lesser-known but equally talented performers.
</P>
<P>
   The story follows the domestic exploits of three
African-American sisters in Chicago after the death of the family
matriarch who kept her troubled clan together with homespun wisdom
and mouth-watering Sunday dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the movie may be disappointed to find the show has
stronger language and sexual content. The early episodes give
plenty of screen time to the lead actors' chiseled physiques, which
appear to have been nourished by Lean Cuisine rather than Mama's
high-calorie cooking.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, baby sister Bird (Malinda Williams) is in the
final month of her pregnancy while enjoying a rare romantic
interlude with her hubby, Lem (Darrin Dewitt Henson), an ex-con
struggling to straighten out his life. It's a warm and fuzzy moment
until Lem makes a request that ruins the mood for Bird, and which
may put a damper on viewers expecting more family friendly fare.
</P>
<P>
   During the second episode, middle sister Maxine (Vanessa
Williams, no relation to the movie star in the film) has a
memorable scene with her precocious 14-year-old son, Ahmad (Aaron
Meeks), who also is the show's narrator. After being accepted into
a snobby prep school, Ahmad is mortified when his mom insists on
chaperoning his class on a school trip and then winds up
breast-feeding his baby sister on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   When it clicks, ``Soul Food'' is a feast of strong drama and
incisive, knowing humor. When it doesn't, it plays like a sudsy
nighttime soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Food'' screenwriter and co-producer Felicia D. Henderson
says the show isn't about being raunchy or risque for shock value.
It's about keeping it real, even if it that means having uptight
elder sister Teri (Nicole Ari Parker) falling in love with hunky
delivery man.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, a University of Georgia business school grad, says
many of the stories were inspired by the experiences of her
thirtysomething friends juggling careers, relationships and
children. She says that perspective often is missing from
mainstream TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the language and the nudity that we're trying to
convey,'' says Henderson, an African-American. ``My goal is to open
up every episode with some real slices of life ... things anybody
can identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer Dennis E. Leoni captures that same appeal with a
distinctly Latino flavor in ``Resurrection Blvd.'' Tony Plana
(``JFK'') is Roberto Santiago, a bull-headed widower who presides
over an extended family battling for survival inside and outside
the boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   Plana and his co-stars are first-rate. The cast includes Michael
DeLorenzo (''New York Undercover'') as eldest son Carlos; Elizabeth
Pena as lovingly meddlesome Aunt Bibi; Cheech Marin of Cheech
andChong fame as Roberto's boss; and comedian Paul Rodriguez as a
boxing promoter and friend.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show telegraphs some of its punches, that doesn't
dull their impact. After winning a match that guarantees him a
title bout, Carlos has a run-in with vengeful gang-bangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection'' also handles class and color consciousness with
a deft touch: The pilot has sister Yolando Santiago (Ruth Livier)
on the verge of a fling with a WASP-y associate at her law firm.
Sister Victoria (Marisol Nichols) is the typical smart kid hanging
out with a dumb crowd because she doesn't want to be seen as a nerd
or, even worse, a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Leoni says he has been trying to bring a story about a Latino
family to TV for a decade. He had no luck with ``La Reforma,'' an
earlier, autobiographical effort first pitched to the broadcast
networks and, he says, dismissed as being ``too narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Showtime programmers also didn't bite at first but later gave
Leoni a full 22-episode deal after he retooled ``La Reforma'' with
the boxing angle to give it a grittier feel.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime ``wanted to do this kind of programming and so did I.
There's this homogenous demographic that regular TV lives in and
that advertisers want, and I wanted to created a more diverse show
where everybody is represented,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Leoni is at least half-right: HBO also has a reputation for
taking creative risks on programs.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Asians and Native Americans are mostly MIA from TV
starring roles, even on cable. And while the casts of
``Resurrection'' and ``Soul Food'' are integrated, whites often are
reduced to caricatures. Leoni and Henderson will have to do a
better job of dramatically rendering other racial and ethnic groups
in order to build crossover appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For now, executives with the NAACP and other groups involved in
the campaign to increase minority representation on TV say they're
monitoring ``Resurrection'' and ``Soul Food'' as well as shows
premiering this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``These shows are a good start, but unfortunately, they are
still unique events,'' says Lisa Navarrette, a spokeswoman for the
Latino advocacy group La Raza. ``Our hope is that these shows will
be so successful that advertisers can no longer ignore them. I
think that's what will eventually raise the bar for the broadcast
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.'' debuts 10 p.m. Monday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Food'' debuts 10 p.m. Wednesday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more information: www.showtimeonline.com
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris
</P>
