<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEEKEND-TVGUIDE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV weekend viewing guide
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Senior PGA Golf (4 p.m. on ESPN) _ The only golf tournament
Tiger Woods can't win.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Walt Disney World Summer Jams Concert'' (8 p.m. on ABC) _
Christina Aguilera sings ``Genie in a Bottle'' and ``What a Girl
Wants.'' Thank goodness _ these tunes were in danger of being
completely overlooked. Also appearing: Smash Mouth and Enrique
Iglesias.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Biography: William S. Paley'' (8 p.m. on A&AMP;E) _ William S.
Paley would have loved the show ``Survivor.'' The founder of CBS
cultivated the image of a high-brow patron of the arts and
supporter of serious news. But at crunch time, he loved ratings and
profits, the bigger the better. This new ``Biography'' shows us the
man who gave us the careers of Ed Sullivan, Edward R. Murrow and
Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nick at Nite 15th Anniversary'' (9 p.m. on Nickelodeon) _
Nick at Nite made reruns cool. Before Nickelodeon started packaging
oldies and marketing them in clever ways, reruns were the gum on
the sneaker of television.
</P>
<P>
   But in no small part because of Nick's giving them a hip spin,
we have national ``Brady Bunch'' mania and new generations that
appreciate ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and ``The Dick Van Dyke
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate, Nick spends five hours talking to some of TV's
great sitcom creators, who then shut up and show their favorite
episodes. Among them: Norman Lear (``All in the Family''), Carl
Reiner (``Van Dyke''), James L. Brooks (``Moore''), Garry Marshall
(``Laverne &AMP; Shirley'') and, of course, Sherwood Schwartz, the man
who gave us ``The Brady Bunch'' and ``Gilligan's Island.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sex and the City'' (9 p.m. on HBO) _ You ought to know that,
yes, that is singer Alanis Morissette guest-starring as a bisexual.
She has a moment at a wild party with Carrie (Sarah Jessica Parker)
in a gender-bending episode of the hormone-addled comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Man Show'' (10 p.m. on Comedy Central) _ Hosts Jimmy
Kimmel and Adam Carolla visit Snoop Dogg at his home and set a new
high in indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Iron Chef in New York'' (9 p.m. Sunday on Food Network)
</P>
<P>
   The cult of ``Iron Chef'' has been growing like Thai grocers on
Buford Highway as word-of-mouth has spread about this wacky little
import. A Japanese cooking competition in which two chefs square
off in an arena-like kitchen, it's hilarious camp because of its
frenzied, life-or-death commentary and breathless play-by-play
announcing.
</P>
<P>
   This special brings the Iron Chefs to New York for the first
time, where one, Morimoto, crosses carving knives with Bobby Flay,
a New York chef who happens to have his own Food Network show. As
always, the chefs are told at the very last second what ``secret
ingredient'' must be included in all their dishes (usually it's
something unexpected like yogurt).
</P>
<P>
   As the announcer, dubbed into English, goes berserk over this
``rivalry of galactic proportions,'' the chefs prepare gourmet
feasts, all done in real time, one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this special is two hours long. The 9-10 p.m.
block is a lot of silly hype and preparation, including a lengthy
plug for another Food Network show, ``Door Knock Dinners.''
``Chef''-heads should skip that and tune it at 10, when the
cleavers start flying.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   If you channel-surf your way through a weekend of films noir
full of femmes fatale, by the end you'll be on your hands and knees
barking at the set: ``For God's sake, man, don't trust her!''
Here's three to get you barking:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Palmetto'' (7 tonight on the Movie Channel) _ In this
pretty-OK 1998 flick, Woody Harrelson is the dupe who gets involved
in a faked kidnapping. Elisabeth Shue plays the rich witch who
shows Woody a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Chinatown'' (4 p.m. Saturday on WATL) _ In Hollywood, the
script-writing classes still teach Robert Towne's 1974 screenplay
as an example of near-perfection. Faye Dunaway is more
dysfunctional than fatale, but as always in noir, it doesn't end
well for the guy, nosy Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Double Indemnity'' (8 p.m. Saturday on Oxygen) _ One of the
templates of the noir genre has Barbara Stanwyck putting Fred
MacMurray through hoops in a classic based on James M. Cain's
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
