<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EDUCATION STAYS IN THE CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is about to do a very
good thing _ for education, for the country and for his own
political prospects.
</P>
<P>
   He is getting rid of a piece of right-wing ideological deadwood
that never made sense in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Republican National Convention will dump the party's
20-year-old plank demanding that the Department of Education be
abolished, which sought to formally downgrade the teaching of our
children to a status lower than, say, farming or promoting
veterans' interests.
</P>
<P>
   A Cabinet seat often carries more psychological than practical
impact. But its visibility and proximity to the presidential ear
announce to voters that the issue it represents has the highest
national priority.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism matters.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, who says he wants to be ``the education president,''
is sending a signal that he intends to end the strait-jacket
against federal assistance to teach the young that Ronald Reagan
and the religious right embedded in the Republican platform in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he would put government money behind the new
philosophy. It can be argued that platforms don't matter. But if
Bush is elected, his secretary of education will be the first such
Republican who doesn't feel obliged to argue before Congress for
the abolition of his or her own department.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently proposed ambitious new federal spending to improve
math and science education in public classrooms. His $2.3 billion
plan does not spend as much to improve public schools as would the
programs of his rival, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a remarkable shift from the next presidential nominee
of a party that has been belittling the public schools since
Reagan's election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not given up promoting private schools. He still wants
to hand out taxpayer-funded vouchers to subsidize students who flee
from public schools, a favorite GOP theme. But Bush genuinely seems
less dogmatic about tilting educational advantages to private
schooling and away from the public schools than his Republican
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the war against the Department of Education has run its
course. The public has won and the Republicans have lost.
</P>
<P>
   When Reagan came to power, he targeted the department because it
was created by his predecessor, Jimmy Carter, and shaped by the
National Education Association (NEA), which backed Carter and
correctly viewed Reagan as anti-union. Reagan also listened to
complaints of the Christian right, which charged that public
education was immoral because it promoted what the professionally
pious called godless ``secular humanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get Congress to kill the department outright, Reagan
strangled it financially. From 1980 until 1992, its budget remained
static at $14 billion despite inflation, deterioration of school
buildings, security and equipment and steady increases in student
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton has consistently pushed for a greater
investment. The current department budget is nearly $39 billion,
still relatively small as Cabinet offices go. This year Clinton
wants a jump to more than $43 billion, which would be more than
three-fold boost from the 1992 figure.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Americans have consistently told pollsters they
want a greater federal investment in the schools, not less. They
don't buy the conservative complaint that federal money means
parents, teachers and communities will be pushed around for no
good.
</P>
<P>
   Female voters in particular have contributed to Clinton's
victories, listing education as one of their top issues.
</P>
<P>
   For years, congressional Republicans ignored this reality and
repeatedly pressed ahead with hearings to kill the Education
Department as a sign of their determination to downsize government.
</P>
<P>
   The negative response finally sank in when GOP focus groups gave
their presidential nominee, Bob Dole, an immediate thumbs down in
1996 after he vowed to kill the department during a debate with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After Dole's decisive defeat at the polls, congressional
Republicans shifted their attack from the department itself to the
NEA, which was politically satisfying to the partisan right wing
but still left the party looking anti-education. Being against
teachers is rather like being against firefighters, nurses and
other good guys that society looks to for help. Not a popular
position.
</P>
<P>
   When Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, the Republican platform
chairman, announced that at Bush's behest the Education Department
would no longer be a target, it caused little stir. The party
reaction was mostly one of relief. Some reality had set in at last.
</P>
<P>
   Education issues are more complex than the existence of a
Cabinet seat, and Bush has made his peace with the religious right
by capitulating on another controversial issue, abortion. But this
is progress nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbing the presidential nose at the importance of education
was always the wrong way to go. The symbolism was dreadful. Common
sense has prevailed. And now we can go on to the real struggles
over what works and doesn't work in public education and who should
do what about it.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
