<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1979 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS &LR;      06-22 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOUSE NEGOTIATORS WOULD CUT SAN FRANCISCO AIDS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Key House negotiators have cut San Francisco's
share of federal AIDS funding by millions of dollars over five
years while increasing money for 50 other cities hard hit by the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., said Thursday that San Francisco's
share of federal Ryan White program money would be slowly reduced
until the city receives the same level of funding as other cities
with high rates of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the best funding of any place in the country and
they can't document that they have a greater need,'' said Coburn,
who negotiated the deal with Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., also a
member of the House Commerce Committee panel that oversees the Ryan
White Care Act.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White Care program authorizes the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services to pay for care and medication for people
with HIV and AIDS who aren't poor or sick enough to receive
Medicaid, but who don't have private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., a longtime advocate for people with
AIDS, vowed to fight the House deal and warned that it could cut
millions of dollars from the city's $35 million annual funding from
the Ryan White program. She said she didn't know the exact size of
the cut and Coburn declined to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't live with that,'' Pelosi said. ``This is unfair to
us. The fact is, we can never agree to a funding level that stands
in the way of meeting the needs of people with HIV/AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she supports a Senate-passed version of the Ryan
White care program that would freeze San Francisco's share of the
money at no less than 98 percent of the current $35.3 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Once the House passes its version of the Ryan White program, the
different House and Senate bills will go to a joint House-Senate
conference committee where negotiators will try to iron out
differences.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ryan White program began in 1991, San Francisco's share
of the money was relatively large because the epidemic was rooted
there before it spread to other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the funding formula was based on two factors: the
density of AIDS cases in a city (the ratio of people with AIDS
relative to the city's total population) and a city's cumulative
number of AIDS cases, living and dead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress changed the funding formula so it was based on
the estimated number of people alive with AIDS in a city. That
change would have slashed San Francisco's funding because so many
AIDS patients there had died of the disease, but Congress decided
to limit any cuts to the city's funding so as not to disrupt
existing AIDS programs.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi noted that the designers of the original Ryan White
program had assumed that people would die earlier of AIDS. But then
scientific researchers developed protease inhibitors that
dramatically prolong the life of people with HIV, the virus that
leads to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a growing population of HIV patients and a
shrinking number of AIDS sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's need for federal aid ``is greater because people
are living longer,'' Pelosi said. ``We cannot be penalized for
intervening earlier and prolonging life.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said in an interview that HIV patients in other parts of
the country, especially women and minorities, must wait for someone
else in their area to die of AIDS before they can get federal
funding to pay for medications that can slow the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, executives at San Francisco AIDS
organizations are being overpaid. He cited one executive who he
said is paid $200,000 year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard position for San Francisco to defend,'' Coburn
said, adding that 16 states ran out of Ryan White money last year.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn added that his intention was not to punish San Francisco,
``although that's the perception. The perception is that they are
being picked on We're trying to do the right thing for San
Francisco as we try to do the right thing for everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said Los Angeles city officials have been leading the
charge in trying to cut San Francisco's share of the money, a
development she said was ``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White program is named after the hemophiliac teenager
from Kokomo, Ind., who contracted the disease through tainted blood
and died in 1990 at age 19. The program serves about a half-million
people each year and, since 1991, has distributed $6.4 billion to
states and local governments for local use.  &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
