A1981 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      06-22 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, June 23 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ A top Justice Department
prosecutor has recommended a special counsel be appointed to
investigate Vice President Al Gore in the 1996 campaign
fund-raising controversy, government officials said Thursday. The
recommendation came from Robert Conrad, supervising attorney for
the Justice Department task force investigating 1996 fund-raising
abuses. (Summary from wires) By David Johnston and Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT13.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ A Special Report: A
reconstruction of the decision-making involved in the missile
defense proposal shows that both the Clinton administration and its
Republican rivals have long been driven by domestic political
calculations as well as by strategic concerns. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTE (Huntsville, Texas) _ The Texas parole board
refused to block the execution Thursday evening of Gary Graham in
the latest death penalty case to put Gov. George W. Bush under
pressure as he runs for president. Graham's lawyers filed
last-minute appeals with the Supreme Court and the Texas Court of
Criminal Appeals, but the state court turned him down. Both had
previously rejected his arguments that he was convicted on shaky
evidence from a single eyewitness and that his trial lawyer did a
poor job. Bush's office said the governor would not comment until
the courts had ruled. (Summary from wires) By Jim Yardley and Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUGS-COURTS (New York) _ New York will become the first
state to mandate that nonviolent criminals be offered the option of
drug treatment instead of jail time, New York chief judge Judith
Kaye announced Thursday, putting in place statewide a system that
has been tried in some parts of the state. Many states offer some
kind of drug treatment program as an option to jail time now, but
New York will be the first to do so statewide. Kaye said the new
program could divert as many as 10,000 inmates a year to drug
programs, reducing the state's inmate population by as much as 10
percent and saving $500 million a year in prison costs. By
Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   NADER-LABOR (Washington) _ Months after they dismissed Ralph
Nader as a fringe third-party candidate who would fade quickly,
Democratic and Republican strategists now say that the consumer
advocate has emerged as more politically potent than Patrick
Buchanan and could deeply complicate the candidacy of Vice
President Al Gore. Nader, who is expected to capture the Green
Party's nomination in Denver this weekend, is in single digits in
most polls. No one thinks he has a chance of rising to the
electoral heights of Ross Perot in 1992. Even so, Nader already is
forcing Gore to fight harder for the enthusiastic support of labor
and other groups that are reliably Democratic. Nader's potential
for mischief was on display here Thursday, when James P. Hoffa, the
Teamsters president, appeared beside him at a news conference and
ridiculed the vice president. By Richard R. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-AUCTIONS (Irvington, N.Y.) _ Tired of plain old house
sales through a realtor? Increasingly, high-end home buyers are
turning house sales into events by selling them at high-end catered
auctions. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT15,16, sent on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEATHER-FOSSIL (Undated) _ Scientists have discovered fossil
evidence of the oldest known feathered animal, a small reptile that
probably glided among the trees 75 million years before the
earliest known bird. They say this challenges the widely held
theory that birds evolved from dinosaurs. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
