<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAIRIE VIEW: LAW AND MEDICINE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be an alumnus or alumna of Prairie View A&AMP;M
University or the child, parent, relative or good friend of one to
say an ``amen'' to a recommendation offered by Glenn Johnson, a
graduate from Texas' second-oldest public institution of higher
learning.
</P>
<P>
   In recent testimony before the Texas Higher Education
Coordinating Board's Task Force on Office of Civil Rights Issues,
Johnson _ no relation _ called for adding both a medical school and
a law school at Prairie View.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Houston-area real estate investor's recommendation
didn't get any play in the media, it is being passed along to make
certain that enough people hear about it to prevent its being
discarded without consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson insists that Prairie View has served the
African-American community ``with dignity and vision since 1876''
and that it has earned the opportunity to provide education in the
disciplines of medicine and law.
</P>
<P>
   He offers that suggestion as a way to help Texas satisfy the
U.S. Department of Education's Office of Civil Rights that this
state has eliminated the remaining vestiges of segregation in its
higher education system.
</P>
<P>
   One of the task force's primary duties is to explore ways to
achieve that objective. The medical and law school proposal for
Prairie View was not included in the ``Access and Equity 2000''
initiative, the third state plan for addressing Office of Civil
Rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will become part of the next initiative. There will
have to be one, because the Hopwood ruling eliminating the use of
racial criteria for admissions to state colleges and universities
dealt a serious setback to efforts to increase minority enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1998 status report on higher education in Texas, the
coordinating board said that the Hopwood ruling fosters a
perception that blacks and Hispanics ``are no longer welcome at
Texas higher education institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   That status report said that Hopwood struck hardest at the
state's most selective undergraduate institutions and added: ``Also
hard hit have been the state's graduate, medical and law schools.''
</P>
<P>
   That development helps make the case for Johnson's
recommendation. However, his primary justification for a medical
school at Prairie View is that it would serve a crying need for
community-oriented health-care services by increasing the pool of
minority physicians; providing hospital services in a an area of
sore need; and conducting research into health problems that beset
African-Americans at a higher rate than other segments of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   In his effort to justify the need for a law school at Prairie
View, Johnson recited a telling list of statistics relating to
juvenile incarceration. His main point was that minority youths are
being sent to correctional institutions at rates that are highly
disproportionate to their percentage of the population and to the
total numbers of youths arrested, primarily because of inadequate
legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson's case for a Prairie View law school is less
compelling than the one he makes for a medical school, he has a
good argument. If the Hopwood ruling continues to decrease the
number of African-American applicants to other law schools in the
state, a Prairie View law school could fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   One can justify Prairie View's offering both disciplines. But,
if a choice had to be made, the medical school would be the more
pressing need.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson's proposal is to stand any chance of becoming a part
of Texas' effort to remove the last vestiges of segregation from
the state's higher education system, the coordinating board must
hear from more people than him.
</P>
<P>
   One does not have to be a Prairie View alumna or alumnus to call
the coordinating board at (512) 483-6101 and express one's
sentiments on the subject. It is not a mission impossible. Florida
is evidence of that. On May 1, that state's legislature funded a
law school and a medical school at Florida A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
