<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPLES-LOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES, A FAIRYLAND OF ILLUSION, FADS AND CARS 
</HEADLINE>
 ANGELES-4TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT  
 (Repeating for all needing)  (Editors: the 4th take is 1250 words on hotels, restaurants and
attractions.) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ My earliest memories of Los Angeles are the
wisecracks of the old radio comedians. Fred Allen, as I recall,
described this as ``a nice place to live, if you happen to be an
orange,'' and Oscar Levant said that when you stripped away the
tinsel here, you uncovered more tinsel.
</P>
<P>
   I formed an indelible picture of L.A. noir from Bogart and
Bacall in ``The Big Sleep,'' Howard Hawks' sardonic, hard-boiled
tale of spoiled rich girls, con men, gunmen and other rogues, which
William Faulkner and others adapted from Raymond Chandler's novel.
Later, on television, I watched Jack Webb, as the laconic Sgt. Joe
Friday in ``Dragnet,'' probe the city's underbelly.
</P>
<P>
   More than anywhere else in America, Los Angeles has been defined
by popular culture _ that is, by the entertainment industry, which
is based, after all, in Hollywood. Most of us, even people who live
here, carry show-business images of Southern California around in
our heads. But they are mere fragments of reality, snippets of
grainy black-and-white or gaudy Technicolor, and splicing them
together into an accurate picture is a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   One might begin with the idea of the place. For several
generations of Americans it has been a 20th-century Eden, a garden
at continent's edge where almost anything seemed possible. Today
much of it is a paradise defiled, spoiled by sprawl, smog and
selfishness. Fires and mudslides, repeated riots and the Northridge
earthquake have scarred landscapes and psyches.
</P>
<P>
   Splendors remain _ and not just the chicks on Melrose Avenue and
the biceps boys on the beach at Venice. Contemplate the Santa
Monica mountains at dusk, wade into the surf at Malibu, glide
through the tunnel of lavender-blue jacaranda blossoms on Palm
Drive in Beverly Hills in May and June or walk along the placid
residential streets of Pasadena, past glorious Arts and Crafts
houses by the brothers Charles and Henry Greene, set on broad lawns
maintained only by heroic irrigation and the sweat of gardeners,
and you will understand the lasting allure of this vast, inchoate
metropolis by the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   There are days when hibiscus, jasmine and oleander scent the
air, and you imagine yourself in Grasse. There are days when the
air is so acrid with exhaust fumes that your eyes sting.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has always traded in glamour and illusion, ephemeral
merchandise that is here today and gone tomorrow, like movie sets
and the sex appeal of leading ladies. ``The back lot was 30 acres
of fairyland,'' wrote F. Scott Fitzgerald in ``The Last Tycoon,''
``not because the locations really looked like African jungles and
French chateaux and schooners at anchor and Broadway at night, but
because they looked like the torn picture books of childhood, like
fragments of stories dancing in an open fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a fairyland, the home of hype and hyperbole, and it
was also the home of two of the important presidents of the latter
half of the last century, Richard M. Nixon and Ronald Reagan. Their
libraries are nearby, Nixon's in Yorba Linda, where he was born,
Reagan's in Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Colonized in 1781, as El Pueblo de Nuestra Senora la Reina de
los Angeles de Porciuncula, Los Angeles had but 102,479 people in
1900. A half-century later, it had 1,970,358 and by 1996 the city
and the satellites that surround it, spilling over mountains and
stretching out into the desert, were approaching 16 million. By
2025, demographic experts say, the region will grow by another 6
million people, roughly twice the present population of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Los Angeles already covers 34,000 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Explosive growth is creating a radically different society.
While the area's black and non-Hispanic white populations remain
relatively stable, its Asian and Hispanic populations are
skyrocketing. Drive down the streets in and around the center of
the city _ yes, skeptics, there is one _ and you see signs written
in a Babel of languages and alphabets: Korean and Hindi, Lao and
Japanese, Thai and Vietnamese, Russian and Spanish and Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Unified School District is the nation's second
biggest, after New York's, with 713,000 pupils; for 70 percent,
English is a second or third language, if spoken at all. In the
lifetime of most of those students, whites will be a minority in
the city and in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Mayor Richard J. Riordan has made education
his top priority. He succeeded last year in gaining control of the
school board, but pushing through reforms has proved harder than
building the new Staples Arena or landing the Democratic National
Convention, which will take place there in August. The dropout rate
in the district is twice the statewide average.
</P>
<P>
   As did immigrants in New York in the 20th century, newcomers
give Los Angeles much of its kinetic energy. But they present
tremendous challenges. For the foreseeable future, the region will
need to build 25,000 new housing units a year, and partly because
of the city's seemingly unstoppable expansion, the state needs
300,000 new teachers almost at once.
</P>
<P>
   Castles, Real and in the Air
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are more insecure than most,'' said Allison
Silver, the New Jersey-born opinion editor of The Los Angeles
Times. ``They come here in search of new identities, and they sense
that this place out at the end of the line is the last chance that
they will ever get to reinvent themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That has its good side and its bad side. When Tom Bradley was
mayor, he said Southern California provided people with ``a place
where they can be free, where they can do things they can't do
anywhere else.'' Such as wearing purple hair or founding sects,
both religious (like Aimee Semple McPherson's) and political (like
the John Birch Society). They cut themselves loose from the
restraints of tradition, obligation, even family.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone makes it, and not very many who make it keep it.
For every fabulous fortune, there are graveyards full of shattered
dreams. So people don't hold back. If you have a body, you flaunt
it; if you have money, you spend it. Buy a Bentley (and take it to
the Bel Air or the Peninsula for lunch so people can see it) and
build a narcissist's castle.
</P>
<P>
   Angelenos create and they innovate. They launch fads.
Eccentricity reigns, as Ogden Nash observed: ``Yes, it is true, Los
Angeles is not only erratic, not only erotic, Los Angeles is
crotchety, centrifugal, vertiginous, esoteric and exotic.'' Carey
McWilliams, who knew the place well, described it as ``a circus
without a tent.''
</P>
<P>
   The zaniest zaniness of all is the city's love-hate relationship
with its cars. ``Hand wash'' shops are everywhere. People drive two
blocks to buy a loaf of bread; go slowly, exquisitely mad in
freeway traffic jams and show up an hour and a half late (or a
half-hour early) for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Hertz feels compelled to warn those who rent its vehicles here,
``Unfortunately, many Californians are in a hurry and usually
ignore yellow lights (and sometimes red lights).''
</P>
<P>
   In ``L.A. Story,'' Steve Martin had a hilarious go at the car
culture, putting pedestrians in gas masks. He lampooned the city's
mania for decaf, diets and nose jobs, its compulsive consumption
and its linguistic primitivism. He made even the traffic signals
speak Valley: ``Uh, Like, Don't Walk.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But nutty or not, the place still makes converts. Michael
Karnow, a comedy writer, grew up in Washington, the son of a
Pulitzer Prize-winning author and journalist, Stanley Karnow, and
graduated from Harvard. Since he moved here nine years ago, he has
become an improbable Jamba Juice junkie _ ``I have their number on
my speed dial'' _ and guzzles power boost and wheat grass drinks
``to increase mental agility.'' He's into yoga and he's learning to
surf.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-     06-22 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: to surf.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But with so many people panning for gold here, so many people
from somewhere else, Los Angeles itself suffers from an identity
crisis. It is not so much a city as a concatenation of cities, from
Anaheim to Azusa and Cucamonga, as they said on Jack Benny's show.
Now more than ever, under the pressure of demographic and economic
change, it is hard to unify.
</P>
<P>
   The oil and aircraft industries have all but disappeared as
bulwarks of the regional economy, and most of the formerly
influential banks have been merged into out-of-town institutions.
Even The Los Angeles Times, once a pillar of the city's civic
architecture under the stewardship of the Chandler family, has been
sold to the Tribune Co., a Chicago media conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   These seismic shifts have weakened the city's power structure.
Barry Munitz, president of the J. Paul Getty Museum, probably the
pre-eminent local cultural institution, compared today's Los
Angeles to a ball poised at the top of an incline _ stuck up there
because of ``a lack of enough educational, artistic, civic,
economic and social leaders ready to shoulder the burdens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department, its once-mythic reputation in
tatters, is struggling to eradicate rampant corruption. Already
battered by evidence of officers' planting evidence, lying in court
and shooting unarmed suspects, Chief Bernard C. Parks suffered an
additional tragedy and humiliation recently when his granddaughter
was murdered in the city his men protect.
</P>
<P>
   With expansion of the city's rudimentary subway system stalled,
several sections of the city are studying the possibilities of
secession.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that the vernacular architecture, indeed the only
architecture, of Los Angeles is the ticky-tacky bungalow. But in
fact this is a place full of architectural fascination, ranging
from things that look exactly like what they are _ the Tail o' the
Pup hot dog stand, an oversize stucco and sheet-metal wiener, and
the Capitol Records tower, shaped like a stack of 45's _ to things
that evoke a world that never was, like Mann's (formerly Grauman's)
ornate Chinese Theater, whose like never graced the streets of Old
Cathay.
</P>
<P>
   In the old downtown, along Broadway, which is as animated as the
new downtown is sterile, stand the Bradbury Building (1896), chaste
tan brick on the outside, lacy metalwork and skylighted sparkle
inside, and the Grand Central Market (1917), a survival of the
city's past, where the ethnic stew of its present simmers. Lawyers
and construction workers, African- and Mexican- and
Asian-Americans, crowd the aisles, buying tin toys and purslane and
chop suey and (if they're smart) following the crowds to Roast to
Go, which has been dispensing the city's best tacos since 1952 _
soft tortillas filled with hand-chopped pork (or hog maw or tripe,
as you will) with hot red sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The Gamble House in Pasadena (1908), with its
Japanese-influenced woodwork of unmatched elegance, is the Arts and
Crafts masterpiece of the Greene brothers. Art Deco landmarks stand
along Wilshire Boulevard, including the zigzag Moderne tower of the
old Bullocks department store (1928). For the Public Library
downtown (1930), topped with a gilded hand holding aloft the torch
of truth, Bertram G. Goodhue adopted a more pared-down if richly
allusive Deco style, and in the Textile District, Robert Derrah
produced a streamlined Moderne icon for Coca-Cola (1937), a
bottling plant masquerading as a cream-and-scarlet ocean liner,
complete with portholes, gangways and a flying bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright did some of his best work in the hills and
canyons on the north side of town. Two of his buildings are open
episodically to the public: the low-lying Hollyhock House (1920),
containing much of its original furniture, and the Ennis-Brown
House (1924), a ``Mayan'' temple in patterned concrete block,
clinging to a cliff overlooking the city, whose preservation has
been the life's work of Gus Brown, a former labor union official.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Viennese-born architects, Richard Neutra and Rudolph
Schindler, created what we know as the California style. Neutra's
Lovell House (1929), near the Ennis-Brown House, is a stack of
gray-and-white steel-and-stucco planes jutting from a hillside,
perhaps as good a modern building as California has. It remains a
private residence, but the innovative little house that Schindler
designed for himself in Hollywood in 1921, a series of rooms made
of cheap, utilitarian materials (concrete, canvas, composition
board) with sliding walls that open onto gardens has been turned
into a museum house. Seminal Gehry Buildings
</P>
<P>
   Frank O. Gehry, triumphant in Bilbao, planning great things for
New York, lives here and has done some of his seminal buildings
here, starting with a minimalist Hollywood studio for Lou Danziger
(1964) and continuing with the Dutch-gabled cottage in Santa Monica
that he rebuilt in 1978 (what must the neighbors have said?), using
plywood and chain-link.
</P>
<P>
   Flamboyant though he sometimes is, Gehry can also work almost
anonymously. He turned a police department garage into the Geffen
Contemporary, a highly successful branch of the Museum of
Contemporary Art, with a simple series of baffles and platforms,
and he opened the formerly dark and disorganized Norton Simon
Museum into a sunny, free-flowing series of galleries. His Disney
concert hall, some critics think, may well cap his career.
</P>
<P>
   But until the hall is completed, the building all Los Angeles
wants to see is Richard Meier's Getty Center, a series of
interconnected travertine and enameled aluminum pavilions on an
isolated hilltop near the western end of Sunset Boulevard. From
afar, it looks like a village on a Greek island; up close, it, too,
evokes the mystique of an ocean liner. Different levels linked by
railed gangways feel like different decks, and fountains project
the sound of splashing water everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.75 million people a year visit the Getty, and many of
them come just to see the gardens and the views. It is chic in
certain circles in Los Angeles to say that the pictures aren't up
to the building, but people who have bothered to look at them don't
say that. Not people who like Masaccio and Mantegna, or F.X.
Winterhalter, that sadly underesteemed portraitist of empire.
Surely not students of Rembrandt, represented here by two of his
most vibrant portraits. And van Gogh's ``Irises'' could seduce a
stone.
</P>
<P>
   In Pasadena, the great names march with no less majesty through
the halls of the Simon: Giovanni di Paolo, Bellini, van Gogh again
(his best ``Mulberry Tree''), Cezanne, Klee; reaching a climax in
Zurbaran's exquisite ``Still Life With Lemons, Orange and a Rose.''
It is one of the world's choice small collections. A mile or so
away, in manicured San Marino, the Huntington Library offers great
manuscripts, a Greene and Greene collection, thousands of roses and
Gainsborough's famous ``Blue Boy.'' Some year soon it will place on
view this continent's greatest assemblage of works by the English
designer and polymath William Morris, purchased last year from a
California collector.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest museum in town, the Los Angeles County Museum of
Art, is a work in progress, with a major building program
incomplete. Only 36 years old, it has put together an encyclopedic
collection of some 150,000 works of art, including an extensive
group of German Expressionist paintings, but it of course cannot
match the Getty's staggering financial resources. The Museum of
Contemporary Art, whose red sandstone headquarters was the Japanese
architect Arata Isozaki's first American commission, has acquired
more than 120 works in the last year in a bid to keep pace with its
rival up north, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, which has
spent $125 million in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Locals bemoan the fact that Los Angeles, almost alone among
world-class cities, failed to mount a gala celebration of the new
millennium. They decry the city's lack of a professional football
team, which in the eyes of some puts L.A. behind Charlotte,
Nashville and Jacksonville. They complain about the teams the city
does have, which lose so often that sports columnists call the city
Loss Angeles. (This year's NBA championship, won by the Lakers
under the avuncular coach Phil Jackson, was the city's first title
in 11 years.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
