u e BC-R-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-     06-22 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPLES-LOS-ANGELES-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: 11 years.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The city's most visible industry is film, its natural vocabulary
melodramatic. From D.W. Griffith to Marilyn Monroe to Steven
Spielberg, film has carried Hollywood values around the globe.
Television joins in the pop culture wars, portraying an unreal
world filled with youth, beauty and virility.
</P>
<P>
   Legions of gawkers flock to Hollywood Boulevard, hoping like the
hicks in Nathanael West's memorable Hollywood novel, ``The Day of
the Locust,'' to catch a glimpse of a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As the critic Shelley Fisher Fishkin writes in a forthcoming
book, ``Landmarks of American Literature,'' these are people,
``cheated out of their dreams by the illusions Hollywood held out
to them,'' for whom ``movies and the world that surrounds them are
more real than life itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the city need make no apology for its grander artistic life,
even if New Yorkers and San Franciscans often talk as if culture in
Southern California were confined to yogurt. Hollywood actors and
directors do not often lend their talents to the legitimate stage
in Los Angeles; many limit their work to the movies, and some
prefer the London or New York theater. But there are exceptions.
Last summer, stars like Donald Sutherland, Al Pacino and Kelly
McGillis were seen at the Mark Taper Forum and Ahmanson Theater in
productions of plays by Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt, O'Neill and
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the arrival in 1984 of Peter Hemmings, a gentlemanly
English arts administrator, did the city have an opera company.
Hemmings, 65, is retiring as general director of the Los Angeles
Opera at the end of this season, to be replaced by Placido Domingo,
who will carry the title of artistic director, as he does in
Washington. He is bowing out with Francesca Zambello's eye-filling
production of Benjamin Britten's mordant ``Billy Budd.''
</P>
<P>
   Though criticized for excessive caution, Hemmings nurtured the
company through adolescence and lured some big Tinseltown talents,
including the painter David Hockney and the director Herb Ross, to
the Chandler Pavilion as designers and directors. He did it on an
annual budget of $20 million, compared with San Francisco's $50
million and the Met's $170 million. Philharmonic's New Home
</P>
<P>
   The disconnect between high culture and pop culture in Los
Angeles has been most visible in the 10-year struggle to build the
Walt Disney Concert Hall _ another fascinating swirl of titanium
designed by Gehry. The money has finally been raised, the
foundations are going in, and the Los Angeles Philharmonic is
scheduled to take up residence in 2002. But except for the Walt
Disney Co., none of the studios, whose executives make hundreds of
millions of dollars a year, and very few of the stars contributed a
single dime.
</P>
<P>
   Without the exertions of the city's No. 1 supporter of the arts,
Eli Broad, who heads the SunAmerica company, the fund-raising drive
might well have foundered. Broad (the name is pronounced to rhyme
with ``road'') made his money on annuities, not movies, and he
collects modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted by the glamorous young Finn Esa-Pekka Salonen, managed
by the highly regarded Deborah Borda, who resigned from the New
York Philharmonic to come here, the Philharmonic plays 30 weeks in
downtown Los Angeles and 12 weeks under the stars in the Hollywood
Bowl in hillside Griffith Park. It ranks among the best orchestras
in America, a worthy challenger to the traditional Big Five bands
in Boston, Philadelphia, New York, Cleveland and Chicago. Musical
life in the city deepened during the war years and afterward, when
both Igor Stravinsky and Arnold Schoenberg lived here. The
orchestra has had a long series of truly outstanding conductors,
among them Otto Klemperer, Zubin Mehta and Carlo Maria Giulini.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fine high-culture facilities here,'' said Tom
Werner, the producer, with his partner Marcy Carsey, of many of the
most wildly successful situation comedies of the last decade. ``But
it isn't really that sort of place. When I was growing up in
Manhattan, when it rained on Saturday, my mother took me to the
Metropolitan Museum. When it rained on Sunday, she dragged me to
hear Leonard Bernstein's concerts. Here, it never rains on
weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
