<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CABINET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK GOVERNMENT SECURE AFTER RESIGNATIONS WITHDRAWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHOSHANA LONDON SAPPIR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's fractious coalition
pulled back from the brink of collapse Thursday as four cabinet
ministers from the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party withdrew their threats
to quit, preserving Barak's government as he focuses on making
peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In an eleventh-hour deal, the Shas ministers made an about-face
after three left-wing ministers, who had clashed heatedly with
Shas, resigned their posts instead. The three, members of the
dovish Meretz party, pledged to continue supporting Barak's peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The result of Israel's two-week government crisis was to
preserve Barak's 68-52 majority in the parliament, while his Shas
partners, who hold the balance of power with 17 seats, promised not
to challenge Barak again while the peace talks continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that Shas's continued participation in the
government is important for the state and for the challenges we are
facing,'' Barak told a meeting of his Labor Party after the Shas
ministers retrieved their letters of resignation less than an hour
before they were to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call upon all of the parties to stop with the hatred and the
fighting,'' Barak said in a speech broadcast live on Israeli radio.
``It is impossible to make peace with our neighbors unless we first
make peace amongst ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the crisis ended, Barak met with US envoy Dennis
Ross, who arrived ahead of next week's visit by Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright. Ross was shuttling between Barak and
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat in an attempt to close gaps in
the difficult negotiations, which aim to reach a peace treaty by
September.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's shaky coalition, made up of six parties, began to
unravel more than two weeks ago when Shas joined the opposition on
a preliminary vote calling for new elections. Shas threatened to
press ahead with elections unless the government came through with
a $6 million aid package for its network of religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Education Minister Yossi Sarid, head of the left-wing Meretz
party, had refused to provide the funds unless Shas accepted state
supervision of its schools.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks of intense negotiations, Barak's One Israel bloc
met most of Shas's demands. But a longstanding enmity between the
ultra-conservative Shas _ a party that excludes women as a matter
of principle _ and the liberal Sarid, blocked a final agreement.
The resignation of Meretz's ministers cleared the way for Shas to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our resignation was inevitable,'' Sarid said. ``We
don't want to be responsible for the collapse of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Meretz, with 10 seats in the 120-seat parliament, is eager to
see Barak conclude land-for-peace deals with the Palestinians and
with Syria, and promised its continued support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the prime minister that although we are leaving our
cabinet posts and the government, we are not abandoning him or the
goals of this administration,'' Ran Cohen, Meretz's industry and
trade minister, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Shas voters, largely observant Jews of Middle Eastern descent,
are less amenable to a peace deal that would entail Israel's
withdrawal from West Bank land it captured in 1967, calling it part
of the Jewish Biblical heritage.
</P>
<P>
   But Shas indicated it would support a peace deal if its rabbis
approved. ``As long as it is a sane and normal agreement I see no
reason Shas should vote against it,'' said Health Minister Shlomo
Benizri.
</P>
<P>
   David Franklin, political correspondent of the Jerusalem Post,
an English-language daily newspaper, said Barak might have a more
harmonious coalition with Meretz out. ``Barak has a more
disciplined Shas party, and with Sarid out, Shas has more incentive
to be disciplined,'' Franklin told the Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarid's resignation is what ended the crisis. Once he was out,
all the remaining issues were resolved. Barak agreed to make Shas a
full partner in the peace process and update Rabbi Ovadia on the
developments on a regular basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
