<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT23-COX     06-22 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT UNVEILS NET-BASED STRATEGY FOR THE FUTURE
 &HT;    Moving in (a) national and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ With an antitrust sword hanging over its head,
Microsoft Corp. on Thursday sought to convert itself into a
dominant force in the next generation of advanced Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say it's a 'bet the company' thing,'' Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman and co-founder, told an invited audience of
reporters and industry analysts at the company's sprawling campus
nested between Seattle and the Cascade Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Gates described a new software system, called ``Microsoft.net,''
that within a few years would let consumers and businesses use a
host of powerful and integrated services from computers, handheld
PCs, Web-enabled cell phones and TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   It would let users run all these programs from a single Internet
browser window.
</P>
<P>
   ``You no longer have to leave the browser,'' Gates said. ``You
are always in the browser.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said its new products would let users anywhere
access their favorite software and personal information, such as
schedules, contacts and e-mail, stored on Internet servers. The
products would respond to spoken as well as typed commands, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said the new computing platform _ pronounced ``dot-net'' _
was the most ambitious project from the world's largest software
company since it launched the Windows graphical operating system in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy faces challenges. Large networking, database
and Internet access companies are racing to tap the same market for
Web-based services. And the court-ordered breakup of Microsoft, if
upheld on appeal, might make the plan difficult to carry out.
</P>
<P>
   The five-hour briefing by Gates and other top Microsoft
executives skirted the company's antitrust woes. But one theme
running through the often technical talk was the ``open'' quality
of Microsoft-written Internet standards and the embrace of
third-party developers and ``partners'' in seeing the plan to
fruition.
</P>
<P>
   The briefings were punctuated by a series of short video
presentations from current Microsoft ``partners.''
</P>
<P>
   In one, Michael Dell, chief executive of Dell Computer Corp.,
said that ``Microsoft's vision for Microsoft.net is a whole new
level of capability, interaction, and customization in the user
experience. It will really leverage the power of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft even managed to elicit a blurb _ but not on videotape
_ from Marc Andreessen, a key prosecution figure in the 78-day
Microsoft antitrust trial that ended with a federal judge ruling
that the company was an abusive monopolist that should be split in
two.
</P>
<P>
   Andreessen was a co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp., a
Microsoft arch-rival in the Internet browser wars which now has
been absorbed into America Online Inc. Microsoft's threats against
Netscape figured largely in the guilty verdict rendered by U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, which has been stayed
pending an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Andreessen chairs an advanced Web-design venture named
Loudcloud Inc. whose interests are in line with Microsoft's
ambitious plans _ ``a world of networked services.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six months have been wild,'' said Microsoft chief
executive Steve Ballmer, who served as an enthusiastic clean-up
speaker after the other presentations ended.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer described himself as a ``caged animal'' since the
``public relations people told us we had to put this off.'' The
briefings, dubbed ``Forum 2000,'' were originally scheduled to take
place a week before Jackson's June 7 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer also assured the nervous analysts, who have watched
Microsoft lose about a third of its market value since settlement
talks with the government failed, that the company's Windows-based
revenue stream would continue for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows isn't going away,'' Ballmer said, ``but to take
advantage of this new technology, we need this new platform.''
</P>
<P>
   The first results of the initiative will not be seen until next
year, while most of the plan will not be ripe for actual use until
at least 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal,'' Gates said, ``is to move beyond today's world of
standalone Web sites to an Internet of interchangeable components
where devices and services can be assembled into cohesive
user-driven experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Gates revealed, Microsoft will seek to impose a
common set of Internet standards for a wide range of online devices
known as extensible markup language or XML. Microsoft claims XML is
open to all. But its critics claim it is being tuned to run best on
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
