<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OLD-THEATERS-ART-3TAK     06-22 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-THEATERS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMATIC REVIVALS, AGAINST THE ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MINDY ALOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you want to orient yourself in a new city or to see a
familiar one in a new way, it is useful to have an obsession. Just
about any will do: The key is to decide how long you will yield to
it, then to let it take over. Obsessions select related bits of
information from the chaotic pool of data streaming into your
consciousness, providing focus and structure.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years I revisited three Northeastern cities I
know well: Boston, Buffalo, N.Y., and Philadelphia. During those
visits I looked at them from the idiosyncratic standpoint of what
had become of their historic theaters, those built before World War
II. I also made a trip to Washington to visit the nation's most
famous and sacred historic theater, Ford's; actually, it is a
facsimile, as the original structure in which Abraham Lincoln was
assassinated was torn down by government order soon after his
death.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of these trips I learned much about the dynamics
and histories of the cities themselves. I saw the tremendous energy
and sometimes heartbreaking compromises necessary to maintain a
performing-arts center today. And I learned how intensely it is
possible to love a theater and to believe in a city, so much so
that some people may devote most of their adult lives, sometimes as
volunteers, to keeping an old theater alive.
</P>
<P>
   I was moved to make this pilgrimage by two developments. One was
the brilliant success of renovations to several prewar theaters on
42nd Street in New York, just off Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were the buildings gracefully remodeled or restored,
but their stages are also vibrant, with plays, music and dance; and
the street is thronged with people. Was this kind of renewal
possible only in New York, or have other cities revived their
downtowns by renovating theaters from earlier eras? Could they go
forward by, in some respect, going back?
</P>
<P>
   The other motivation was my sadness over what had happened to
many theaters in my hometown, Philadelphia. A city of flourishing
theaters during the 19th and early 20th centuries, it has suffered
from a declining tax base, civic mismanagement and the depredations
of unplanned real estate development. Most of the theaters I grew
up with, including the sumptuous movie palaces, appointed for kings
and priced for laborers, are now gone, are boarded-up ruins or have
been transformed into other commercial uses. Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   New theaters have been built in Philadelphia, but they are
small, and their designs reflect ruthless cost cutting. Only a
handful of historic theaters survive as working theaters in Center
City. In trying to bring its decaying downtown back to health,
Philadelphia has chosen to knock down much of its business
district, once lovely and humanely scaled, and build aggressively
new and much higher buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the situation has been the city's longtime hope of
establishing an Avenue of the Arts in its downtown core. Its hub is
to be a new concert hall for the Philadelphia Orchestra, which
musicians argue has outgrown the compromised acoustics and
restricted production space of the Academy of Music, its home for
most of the past century. (The new hall, partially completed, is
projected to open in September 2001. The Academy, with its
old-fashioned raked stage, will be remodeled to accommodate more
dance and opera.)
</P>
<P>
   One heartening new theater opened last year in the completely
gutted ``picture palace'' that was built in 1921 as the Karlton and
that I used to attend when it was called the Midtown. This is the
Prince Music, a producing and presenting house for films and live
performance, operated by a visionary organization founded in 1984
as the American Musical Theater Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Prince is named for the director-producer Harold Prince, a
longtime festival board member and mentor of the festival
co-founders, Eric Salzman, Ron Kaiserman and Marjorie Samoff (who
is also the theater's producing director). It has two auditoriums:
a 450-seat hall, which includes an orchestra pit for dance and
musicals as well as equipment for the screening of films; and a
150-seat black-box space in what was one of the Karlton's two
ballrooms.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the oldest theater in the United States in
continuous use as such is in Philadelphia: the Walnut Street,
founded in 1809 as a circus for equestrian shows. When I was
growing up, it was the main showcase for traveling modern-dance
companies. Although the facade of the building was refurbished to
approach its early, simple elegance, the interior has suffered from
nearly a century of modernization. Two years ago the main
auditorium was completely gutted, rehabilitated and repainted a
light gray; the results are austere and impersonal compared to my
memories of the graciously ornamented house of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, over the last two decades, the Walnut's nonprofit
organization managed to achieve seasonal programming based on new
plays and musicals, along with some revivals. These are performed
in its main auditorium and in a smaller studio space; at least 70
percent of the audience members are subscribers. Under its current
artistic director, Bernard Havard, the Walnut functions as a
producing theater and as a theater school.
</P>
<P>
   In the company of the historic Academy of Music; the Merriam
(once the Shubert), where the Pennsylvania Ballet dances; and the
Forrest, a house used primarily for musicals but too frequently
dark these days, the Walnut keeps the flame of a theatrical
Philadelphia, whose larger memory is still cherished by many
writers, historians, librarians and natives.
</P>
<P>
   Boston
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Philadelphia, Boston has made an extraordinary
civic effort to light up its downtown with the original chandeliers
of a number of carefully restored and maintained historic theaters
and playhouses, most of them within walking distance of one another
in the historic district. Some are excellent houses for theatrical
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Among these are the sumptuous Italianate Wang Center for the
Performing Arts (1925), where the Boston Ballet performs; the
Emerson Majestic (1903, owned by Emerson College), whose proscenium
is especially well proportioned for dancers, although many kinds of
shows are presented there; the elaborately ornamented Colonial
(1900), a gilded wonder where Fred and Adele Astaire performed; the
snow-and-gold Shubert (1910); and the Charles Playhouse (1843),
built originally as a church.
</P>
<P>
   The spoken word is also accommodated beautifully in the
pristinely restored Wilbur (1914), site of the world premieres of
``Our Town'' and ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' and, a little way
across town, my favorite Boston theater, the arboreal Huntington
(1925, owned by Boston University), which is decorated with
quotations from Shakespeare and houses its own nonprofit resident
company.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with newer theaters and playhouses in Boston and
adjacent Cambridge, such historic structures help to provide city
residents with a sense that, here, history is valued.
</P>
<P>
   Although no individual can be credited completely with
leadership in a citywide effort to maintain the life of any art,
Boston's theatrical legacy would not be what it is today without
the commitment and enlightened voice of Elliot Norton, the
97-year-old drama critic and historian. His prodigious memory and
beneficial open-mindedness, developed over 48 years as a drama
critic for Boston newspapers and more than 25 years as host of a
program devoted to theater on WGBH-TV, has provided Bostonians with
a model of intellectual perspective and beneficial passion for the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
