<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OLD-THEATERS-ART-2NDT     06-22 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-THEATERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the subject.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington
</P>
<P>
   Ford's, one of two theaters in the United States overseen by the
Department of the Interior (the other is at Wolf Trap in Virginia),
attracts thousands of tourists yearly. They come because of its
unfortunate notoriety: it is the place where the actor John Wilkes
Booth burst through a door and fired the shot that killed Lincoln.
From the auditorium travelers can descend to a museum devoted to
the assassination and its aftermath; they can then walk across the
street to the house where Lincoln was carried and spent his final
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ford's is an energetic producing theater as well as a
national memorial. Its artistic director, Frankie Hewitt, has been
associated with it since it was rebuilt and reopened in 1968. She
recently noted that in addition to serving adult theatergoers with
plays like Steve Martin's ``Picasso at the Lapin Agile,'' Ford's
also presents shows for young people, many of whom visit the
theater on school trips.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's is the perfect place for plays with a historical basis,
like ``Give 'Em Hell, Harry'' about Harry S. Truman and ``Will
Rogers' U.S.A.'' Ford's has a yearly production of ``A Christmas
Carol,'' based on the story by Charles Dickens, who declaimed it
himself in Carroll Hall in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's is the only theater I've been to in the United States,
outside the New Victory in Manhattan, where each member of the
audience downstairs is offered an individual upholstered chair.
(And after visiting the theater museum, I can tell you that today's
audiences at Ford's are much more cossetted than those of the
19th-century original.)
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   Of all the theaters I visited, however, the most affecting was
Shea's Performing Arts Center, a jewel of a civic heirloom in the
heart of Buffalo's downtown. Built as a movie palace in 1926 by
Paramount, it was immediately nicknamed Shea's after its manager,
Michael Shea. Today it is a nonprofit institution that houses
touring commercial shows.
</P>
<P>
   Its interior, designed in the Spanish Baroque style by Louis
Comfort Tiffany, is glowing burgundy and gold with cooling touches
of aquamarine. It is a wonderful place, full of light and warmth;
and its human story is wonderful, too.
</P>
<P>
   For the fact that Shea's still exists, in a tenderly renovated
condition, is directly attributable to the continuing determination
by many Buffalonians over the last 30 years not to let it go. Even
a fire that destroyed much of the surrounding downtown in 1986,
rendering the block on which the theater stands a ghost town, did
not daunt its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the handsome entrance lobby, clad partly in real
marble and partly in a laboriously manufactured artificial marble
known as scagliola, have been painstakingly repaired and
repolished. The original swirling, marbelized abstractions once
again seem to corruscate under the light of four crystal-beaded
chandeliers, each nearly 10 feet long. Their renewed brilliance
alone represents 350 man-hours of restoration, cleaning and
rewiring, all of it performed by volunteers, who since 1997 have
worked under the leadership of Doris Collins, director of the
docent program.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers have been central to the survival of Shea's since the
day in 1975 when a group of them interposed themselves between the
building and the wrecking ball that was to reduce it to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Shea's is not currently a producing theater: it houses touring
Broadway shows, mostly, as well as some pop music groups and other
prepackaged entertainment. But Patrick Fagan, its president for the
last 14 years and the person most strongly identified with the
community's efforts to keep the theater alive, said Shea's was
operating reasonably well. In 1999 it offered some 200 events for
some 300,000 theatergoers. And it recently completed a backstage
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Further construction is needed: a second lobby, more bathrooms,
a decent coat check, more room for concession stands. The city has
contributed $2 million of the $13 million required. The remainder
will be sought from corporate sponsors and private patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo is a city with a distinguished history of private
patronage of the arts; corporate support is comparatively recent.
Over the last few years, for example, the Buffalo Philharmonic,
once sustained largely by private patrons, has been actively
looking to corporations as well. The Philharmonic's home theater is
another prized historic structure: Kleinhans Music Hall, a W.P.A.
project that opened in 1940 with a modernist design by Eliel
Saarinen, first-rate acoustics by Charles C. Potwin and poetic
lighting by Stanley McCandless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the city has suffered economically for many decades, and
both its audiences and its leading arts patrons are aging. Neither
group seems to be readily replaced by a younger generation, even
though artists themselves keep trying to renew the Buffalo scene.
</P>
<P>
   Across Main Street from Shea's, for instance, is a newly
designed arena theater in a former store. It serves the Irish
Classical Theater Company, founded in 1990 by two young Irish
actor-brothers, Vincent and Christopher O'Neill, and by Dr. James
Warde. A recent season consisted of plays by Brecht, Ibsen, Eugene
O'Neill, Shakespeare and Martin McDonagh. I found out about the
Irish Rep when Collins, who was guiding me around Shea's, spoke
proudly of it as a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Terrance L. Demas, the executive director of the League of
Historic American Theaters, based in Baltimore, said that many
historic theaters in the United States were restored with some
sweat equity. Shea's, though, is singular in its continuing program
to train volunteers in restoration jobs, like fine painting, for
which craftsmen are usually hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make choices about what historic theaters you
save, because you can't save them all,'' Demas said. ``People
turned to theater restoration in the 1960s and '70s. It was a time
when cities were trying to save their downtowns. Theater
restoration revives an interest in the downtown, and anecdotal
studies show that their economic impact on cities is quite
substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Restoration can also be more economical than building new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the Palace Theater in Chicago, where Elton John's `Aida'
opened,'' Demas said. ``That took $25 to $30 million to restore; to
build it new today, in a comparable space, would cost $100 million,
at least.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that we can't build theaters like the old ones
anymore,'' he continued. ``Well, we do have the craftsmen; we do
have the artisans. It's the cost. Our field is one where a lot of
these theaters get saved not because it's economically feasible but
because the people there want them to happen. They believe in them.
With the theaters they will get an important piece of their
history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
