<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-BO     06-22 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT SUPPORTERS DEFEND PRE-ELECTION VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIENDAMBUYA, Zimbabwe _ The first time Priscillah Masunda was
attacked, she said, 68 men drove up in four flatbed trucks, burned
her hut, destroyed her corn crop, and stole two cows and 53
chickens. They chanted pro-government slogans and demanded that she
join the ruling party. Another time, the men took her husband and
beat him for three days before he escaped.
</P>
<P>
   But Masunda, who openly supports the opposition to President
Robert Mugabe, isn't changing her vote.
</P>
<P>
   For four months, Zimbabwe has been jarred by state-sponsored
violence ahead of this weekend's parliamentary elections. At least
30 people have been killed. More than 1,300 commercial farms have
been attacked by thugs supporting Mugabe's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Not since independence in 1980 has an election in this southern
African nation had so much riding on it. Nationwide, the democratic
ideals of aspiring younger generations are clashing with the
hardened values of their elders, who toppled colonialism and claim
the sole right to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Without the violence, political analysts say, a labor-based
opposition would sweep into power on the people's desperation for
jobs and cheap bread. Nearly all agree that urban voters, insulated
from the rural mayhem, will vote for change this Saturday and
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of voting, as the government denies accreditation
to international monitors and as opposition candidates fend off
attacks to campaign across their districts, the key question is
whether the ruling party has kept its rural voters in line. Is
Masunda, short, plump and girlish, a courageous exception or part
of a defiant majority?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago we were told that nobody in the rural areas
would have moved around openly,'' said Tana de Zulueta, deputy head
of a European Union observer mission. ``Now people seem more
determined and intent on exercising their right of choice. We'll
only know on the polling days.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, the newly formed Movement for Democratic Change
successfully rallied voters to reject a government-sponsored draft
constitution in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread violence began shortly after the referendum, which
not only handed Mugabe his first ballot defeat in 20 years but also
underscored the depth of popular frustration over corruption and
economic decline. Blaming the white minority and Zimbabwe's former
colonial power, Britain, for the country's woes, Mugabe encouraged
his supporters to invade white-owned commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
   Government supporters defend the violence as the only way
Zimbabwe can break foreign oppression. The opposition, they claim,
is just a puppet of Britain and white Zimbabweans and South
Africans. The party has taken money from the latter. Mugabe used
the same argument after denying accreditation to two US observer
teams this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sending monitors ``is meant to ensure that they continue to
plunder our resources and we forever remain their pawns. We are
saying `No' to this. We will never accept this,'' Mugabe was quoted
as saying in the state-owned Herald newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The EU observers this week declared Zimbabwe's pre-election
violence the worst they had ever seen, an assessment echoed by
Lorne Craner, president of the US-based Independent Republican
Institute, after his group was denied credentials. ``Zimbabwe's
pre-electoral administration and environment are so flawed that the
election process as a whole will inevitably fall below even minimal
international standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition hopes the violence will only deepen the public's
desire for change. ``People reach a cut-off point,'' said Charlene
Smith, an opposition party spokeswoman. ``We saw the same thing in
South Africa. In the beginning, when they started to torture and
terrorize, people caved. But when something like this goes on long
enough, a spirit of resistance develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 25,000 people turned up for the last major opposition rally
in Harare last weekend. On the same day, just 5,000 turned to hear
Mugabe across town. But Mugabe has always tapped rural Zimbabwe for
his strength, and there, the numbers were less encouraging for the
opposition. An estimated 40,000 showed up at Mugabe' rally
Wednesday in Mount Darwin, north of Harare. ``By this massive
turnout, we have demonstrated who has the support of the people,''
Mugabe told the rally.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the countryside has been hostile
terrain for the opposition. One rural opposition candidate has fled
the country. Several more have been beaten so badly that they are
hospitalized. The party cannot deploy its polling agents in four
districts, which means it cannot monitor the voting. Attacks occur
daily, Smith said, and candidates from at least half rural
districts have been affected.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many opposition candidates campaign at night,
traveling door to door under cover of darkness to spread the party
message. Ironically, the liberation movements, like Mugabe's party,
employed the same tactics prior to independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet a lot of people who come to me in private and say they
are will us, they are fed up with the ruling party,'' said
Valentine Ziswa, an opposition candidate from a district 90 miles
east of Harare. ``But people don't feel safe enough to come out
openly.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in clothes promoting the ruling party, Nickson Musonga
led a small group that broke up one of Ziswa's rallies Tuesday in
Chiendambuya, a tiny rural town far down a dirt road. They chased
the opposition candidate and destroyed his posters and leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a one-party state,'' he said. ``People who did not
fight to liberate the country will never rule it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
