<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZE WELCOMES EXPANSION DRAFT STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ When a player finds out he is left
unprotected for an expansion draft, normally that realization is
met with anxiety at the prospect of changing teams. For most, an
uncertain future can be stressful and difficult.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the case of Bruins veteran Steve Heinze, he asked to
be left unprotected when the NHL stocks Minnesota and Columbus in
Friday's expansion draft. By his own admission, Heinze had a brutal
season last year, scoring just 12 goals and 25 points in 75 games.
A native of the area, his struggles really hit home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really lived outside Route 495 in my life, so in
that case, it's time for a change,'' said Heinze, who figures he's
played his last game in a Bruins uniform. ``It's time to try
something new, not only hockeywise, but lifewise, and check out
another part of the country. Just a change of scenery can fire up
not only your personal life, but your hockey as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze is viewing the draft as a beginning, no matter where he
lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of excited actually,'' he said. ``I enjoyed playing
here and playing in front of my family and all that. The grass may
not always be greener, but when it's pretty brown where you're at .
. . a change can be good. If you get picked up by an expansion
team, you're going to be relied on. You're going to be on special
teams and out there in the last couple of minutes of the game if
it's close. Some of those things have slipped away from me over the
last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze's likely departure may be the best option for him and the
Bruins. Heinze said management, initially reluctant to the idea,
thinks a move would be for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was tough personally and teamwise,'' Heinze said.
``My ice time and things have just slowly tailed off over the last
two, maybe three years, but you only look to yourself. You blame
yourself for things. There could be other factors but I'm not going
to get into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one reason or another, I wasn't the player who was being
relied on like I used to be around here. That's one of the things
that brought us to the conclusion that this was a good way to get
moved out of here. (President/general manager Harry Sinden) was
accommodating from what my agent (Steve Mountain) told me. At first
it was `no' to get on the (unprotected) list and then a `maybe.' If
you see the (players) they protected, they're a core part of the
team. My agent made it sound to me as if Harry had done us a favor
and made this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze said he knows that even if Columbus or Minnesota selects
him, he could be traded. Expansion teams do a great deal of
wheeling and dealing. Heinze said if he's not taken, the Bruins
might trade him. Playing at home can be a safety net, but as Heinze
found out, struggling in front of the home crowd can be
suffocating.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as everybody means well, when you're not playing well,
everybody is in your ear,'' said Heinze. ``I'll certainly be buying
less tickets now. The only thing I'm really worried about is
logistics. What do you do with your house _ do you sell it or rent
it? I've been in the league nine years, I'm 30 years old. I'm adult
enough to know I can survive in other places. I've done a lot of
traveling throughout the world. I don't think I'm that nervous
about that. I love this town, I love living here. We appreciate
that, now it will be a chance to see if we can live without it.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Bruin likely to be selected is 27-year-old goalie Rob
Tallas. Tallas has been preparing for a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at this is as a positive,'' said Tallas. ``This
might be the best learning year I could've had. Going into games,
we were struggling and I was facing hard, hard shots and tested
every night, and no matter how you play, sometimes the outcome
wasn't what you wanted. A lot of times that is what happens in
expansion. We experienced it last year firsthand. I know how to
bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   There was very little bouncing back by the Bruins last season.
High expectations were a factor. With a first-year club, the
expectations are more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year was just one of those years where I think the guys
who had the best stats were the guys who got hurt and got out
early,'' said Tallas. ``To know I'm going to be up for expansion, I
tried to look at the positives and that's what hit me, that I'm
going to be tested a lot of nights. I'm a strong believer in that
there's a reason for everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
