<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSMART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $20 MILLION SEDAN, THE LAST WORD FROM BUICK
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By CHERYL JENSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Mich. _ What we have here is a failure to communicate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am sitting in the elegant Buick LaCrosse, a design study for
an elegant, futuristic sedan, at General Motors' proving ground
here. It looks as though I won't be getting out soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The LaCrosse's features include voice-activated controls. After
a brief and very gentle drive with Gary Mack, one of the car's
designers, as I conversed with the car in an attempt to make my
exit, I had the distinct sense that I was dealing with HAL, the
control-freak computer in ``2001: A Space Odyssey.'' This is what
happened: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Me: LaCrosse. Door open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: (Silence). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Me: LaCrosse. Door open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: Dialing 921. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Me: LaCrosse. Door open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: Out of range. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mack: Try ``Door open.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Me: Door open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: Opening hood.
</P>
<P>
   Mack (quickly trying to take over as the hood starts to rise),
loudly: Hood close!
</P>
<P>
   It is an extremely windy day and the prospect that the fragile,
hand-built hood will fly open panics three of the car's handlers
and sends them running our way.
</P>
<P>
   A GM representative: No. No. No. It's too windy! It'll become a
sail! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mack: Hood close. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: Temperature set 79 degrees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mack: Hood close. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: Stopping trunk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mack: Hood close. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaCrosse: Closing hood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such is life when driving concept cars _ which after all, are
really designed to be seen and not necessarily to be driven, or
even sometimes to be heard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to resist when GM offers a chance for even a
short drive in $20 million worth of futuristic hardware. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Driving these vehicles is not useful for evaluating vehicle
dynamics. It's an exercise in make-believe, like sitting in your
father's car in the driveway when you were 8, sawing at the
steering wheel and imagining that you were really on the road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this is better because there is a little more than
imagining. You can drive them up to about 25 mph and get a glimpse
of what one might be like as a real car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, not far from the surly LaCrosse is the Chevrolet
SSR, for Super Sports Roadster, one of six concept vehicles on hand
and a sure bet for production. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an elegant move, I fall down and over the sill into the
cockpit, which has the visual impact of the Plymouth Prowler but is
much more practical, thanks to a pickup bed with a hard cover.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's seat doesn't slide; we don't have working
seatbelts, and the speedometer and other electronics are shut off
to save battery power. But we have plenty of other power. The
6-liter V-8 is capable of sending more than 300 horsepower to the
rear wheels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I turn the key and fire up the engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm holding onto a large, three-spoke steering wheel, a design
cue from the past. The automatic transmission is shifted by pushing
a button on the steering wheel. Three taps and I'm in ``drive''; a
second later we're moving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ride is a bit stiff, even on the ultra-smooth track, and the
body shakes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all hand-built cars,'' said Andre Hudson, a
23-year-old designer who worked on the SSR. ``This is actually one
of the best ones; the other ones are quite a bit more fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   The tires don't help the ride. The tread was hand-cut by
Goodyear in a pattern that mimics Chevy's bow-tie emblem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the SSR changes direction quickly and you realize how strong
a performer the SSR will be if GM can keep the weight down. It is
all too easy to imagine how great a package this could be. Plus,
when we finish the drive, it lets me out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
