<SLUG> BC-GORE-HILLARY-PROBES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROSECUTORS HAND AMMUNITION TO RIVALS OF GORE, HILLARY
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Separate actions by government prosecutors Thursday
dealt Vice President Al Gore a potential political setback and
handed First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton a begrudging exoneration
in connection with unrelated activities during the Clinton
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The actions involving the vice president's fund-raising
activities in 1996 and the first lady's possible role in firing
White House travel office employees in 1993 come in the midst of
heated campaigns for both. Gore faces a battle with Republican Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas for the presidency, while the first lady is
running for Senate in New York against Republican Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's bid to distance himself from President Clinton faces
fresh legal and political headaches as a result of a recommendation
by a top Justice Department prosecutor that Attorney General Janet
Reno appoint a special prosecutor to investigate the vice
president's role in raising money for the Clinton-Gore re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The development also undercuts the credibility of Gore's attacks
on the Bush fund-raising machine. The Republican has raised record
sums to finance his presidential bid without accepting federal
matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Conrad, the supervising attorney in the Justice
Department's broad inquiry into campaign fund-raising abuses four
years ago, has recommended that Reno take the investigation of Gore
to the next step, according to Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he had learned of Conrad's recommendation during a
Senate inquiry into the Justice Department's handling of the
money-raising investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that I found out about in an official
investigation,'' Specter said in an interview on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Committee on
Government Reform, welcomed disclosure of Conrad's recommendation
as ``a positive development.'' Burton said that FBI Director Louis
Freeh, former Justice Department task force leader Charles La Bella
and now Conrad ``have made it clear that Janet Reno's Justice
Department is incapable of conducting a thorough and unbiased
investigation of the president and vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad declined to publicly discuss his recommendation Wednesday
under questioning by Specter at a hearing of the Senate Judiciary
Committee's panel on administrative oversight and federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has twice declined to appoint special prosecutors to
investigate Gore in connection with telephone fund-raising from the
White House in 1996. Federal law prohibits solicitation from
government property.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he would press Reno on the issue when she is
scheduled to testify before the subcommittee next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never called for her resignation; I've never called for
impeachment,'' said Specter, who served as a Republican counsel
during the Senate Watergate investigation of Richard Nixon in the
1970s. ``What I have done is lay facts on the line. There could be
a different reaction (by Reno) at this time. It's up to the
attorney general.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had no immediate comment on the developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that so I'll have to inform myself,'' Gore
told reporters during a campaign visit to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Kennedy, a senior White House spokesman, said the White
House had ``received no word'' of the development form the Justice
Department, adding: ``The Vice President has cooperated fully with
the investigation every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Deportment spokesman Myron Marlin said the investigation
into Clinton-Gore fund-raising in 1996 was ``still ongoing'' and
had already led to the prosecution of 25 individuals, adding: ``It
is inappropriate to comment on ongoing matters or internal
deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and FBI have battled over whether to
expand the investigation into the fund-raising activities since the
controversy came to light during the last presidential campaign.
Those abuses included:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democratic Party's receipt of campaign donations from
foreign donors. The party eventually returned more than $3 million
in illegal contributions from foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Personal telephone solicitations of prospective donors by Gore
from the White House office. Gore later said there was ``no
controlling legal authority'' barring such telephone solicitations,
but he promised not to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hillary Clinton won a legal battle but suffered a
public relations blow from special prosecutor Robert W. Ray, who
announced that he was closing a protracted investigation into the
firing of seven White House travel office employees after Bill
Clinton became president.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he unearthed ``substantial evidence'' that the first
lady ``had a role in the decision'' to sack the political
appointees, including some who had worked at the White House for 30
years. The Clintons were accused to dismissing the employees to
make way for a distant cousin of the president, Catherine
Cornelius, who was installed as the new travel office director.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray added that he had ``declined prosecution'' because ``the
evidence was insufficient to prove to a jury beyond a reasonable
doubt'' that Mrs. Clinton's statements had been ``knowingly
false.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray decried the ``substantial resistance'' from the White House
to prosecutors' quest for evidence in the case, including legal
efforts to assert ``unfounded privileges'' to protect the material,
``inadequate searches'' for requested documents and failure to
``make timely production'' of requested documents.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Dale, the former head of the White House travel office
fired by the Clintons and subsequently acquitted of federal charges
of embezzlement, said he was ``deeply disappointed'' by Ray's
refusal to prosecute Mrs. Clinton, who he said had ``falsely
accused'' him.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
