<HEADLINE>
SHAW'S SELLS REAL EASTATE AS PART OF EXPANSION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to expand aggressively after its 1999 acquisition of
Star Markets Co., Shaw's Supermarkets Inc. is selling 19 strip
shopping centers to a consortium of buyers led by Northstar
Properties for about $117 million.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, announced Thursday, is for the East Bridgewater, Mass.
chain to use the money to replace old stores and open new ones.
</P>
<P>
   By exiting the real estate business, Shaw's _ it's the
second-largest supermarket chain in New England with 167 stores _
can focus on its core business of retail food, it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funds received as a result of the sale will be utilized in
continued growth and development of new stores and shopping centers
by Shaw's Supermarkets,'' said Steve Jackson, the chain's vice
president of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   According to Spaulding &AMP; Slye Colliers, the Boston real estate
firm that brokered the deal, the transaction may represent the
largest portfolio sale of strip shopping centers in the region's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping centers are in five New England states and together
represent 1.4 million square feet of floor space; 15 of the 19
centers are anchored by a Shaw's.
</P>
<P>
   About half the shopping centers are in Massachusetts, including
locations in Cohasset, Plymouth, Quincy, and Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's said it will continue to operate stores in those centers,
but as a tenant rather than as a property owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This portfolio gives us a solid base in New England and
property interests from Hawaii to Maine,'' said Fredric Leopold of
Northstar Properties. ``We plan to develop and acquire more
supermarket projects in the Northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling off ``ancillary businesses'' has become increasingly
common in the intensely competitive grocery business, said Jeff
Metzger, publisher of Food World and Food Trade News, two regional
trade industry publications.
</P>
<P>
   Spaulding &AMP; Slye noted that in 1996 it brokered a similar $96.3
million deal for Stop &AMP; Shop Supermarket Co. of Quincy, the
region's largest supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Stop &AMP; Shop announced plans to exit some of its
ancillary businesses, including production of its store-brand dairy
products, so it can focus on food retailing.
</P>
<P>
   A decade or so ago, it wasn't unusual for a supermarket chain to
dabble in several related businesses, Metzger said. But as the
supermarket industry has consolidated, the remaining big players
seem to be adopting a stick-to-the-basics philosophy and shedding
their sidelines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months ago, Shaw's British parent, J Sainsbury PLC,
completed its acquisition of Star Markets. After digesting Star,
Shaw's seems poised to enter a new phase of aggressively opening
more stores. For its most recent fiscal year, Shaw's said it had
sales of nearly $4 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
