<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-ACCORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEP RIFT SEPARATES CONQUERERS OF HUMAN GENE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS AND RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday the competing factions in the race to map the human
genome will come together in Washington, in a rare moment of
comity, to announce their completion of a ``rough draft'' readout
of all the human genes, a monumental scientific achievement that
promises to open a new era in medicine and a deeper understanding
of human life.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the smiles, handshakes and lofty rhetoric will remain
a deep rift.
</P>
<P>
   Both efforts, the federal government's massive Human Genome
Project and aggressive biotech startup, Celera Genomics Inc., want
to publish their work in an eminent research journal, Science _ the
gold standard of scientific acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   But the journal's editors have that they won't allow Celera to
publish unless the company agrees to release its data on a free
government website, called GenBank, where all the Human Genome
Project's data already resides.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, a Wall Street darling that has in some eyes made the
genome research effort a race by its rapid gene decoding, insists
its data be kept on its private website, according to scientists
close to the Rockville, Md. company. The raw data would be free to
researchers but would also allow Celera to attract potential
customers willing to pay for various pre-packaged forms of the
complex genomic code. One day, Celera says it hopes to sell
personal genetic disease tests over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Celera also worries that if its data goes on GenBank,
competitors will snatch and sell it, depriving the firm of profits
on its investment _ said to be hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two sides reportedly have forged a detente enabling
the Monday's joint appearance, the divisive publication issues were
unresolved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No agreement has been reached yet with respect to publication
in Science,'' said a scientist familiar with the behind-the-scenes
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   One motivation for the new truce is to restore some dignity to
the genome project, which the federal government began 13 years
ago. Celera jumped into the project less than two years ago, saying
its high risk-high payoff sequencing strategy would leave the
public effort in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Several attempts at collaboration over the past few months
failed as meetings broke down amid bickering and name-calling. So
much has been made of the rivalry that scientists on both sides
worry that the public feels ``that the genomic revolution is being
left to people who can't even act civilly in public,'' said one
scientist who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest source of conflict has been Celera's determination
to withhold for a time its gene sequence data from public view, so
that its subscribers can search it for patentable genes.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves Celera's chief, former government scientist Craig
Venter, with a difficult choice: agree to Science's terms and gain
scientific legitimacy but perhaps hurt his company; or forego
publication and risk missing out on scientific immortality and a
possible Nobel prize.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kennedy, the editor of Science, said Thursday, ``We're
not active negotiators. We're very hopeful that the parties will
reach an agreement on publishing the data.''
</P>
<P>
   The original timetable for the human genome project called for
completion by 2005. Once Celera declared its intention to beat the
federal effort, that timetable shortened by at least two years.
Last January, Celera said it had decoded 90 percent of the genome.
</P>
<P>
   Government scientists point out that a large fraction of
Celera's sequence is based on public data from GenBank, whereas the
Genome Project has no access to Celera's findings.
</P>
<P>
   Celera did not return repeated calls for comment. But they
reiterated to concerned money managers, who follow Celera's
high-flying but volatile stock, that they would not relent on
demands to put their data on GenBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it clear that they firmly want to have data
available only on Celera's website,'' said Winton G. Gibbons, an
analyst with Chicago-based William Blair &AMP; Co. who spoke with
Celera officials. ``The company wants to maintain control of their
intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, five large pharmaceutical companies have paid Venter's
company for a genome subscription. But a looming problem, from a
business standpoint, is the Humane Genome Project's
ever-accelerating effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their competitive window is on the order of 5 months. They'll
need to sell their database in that window, because it will be a
rapidly wasting asset by 2001,'' said a scientist working on the
government's project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
