<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTER REGISTRATION CONFUSION COULD MAR WEEKEND ZIMBABWE ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Overshadowed by the political violence that
has dogged this country for months, large-scale problems with
registration of voters remain unresolved and could lead to
significant confusion when voters arrive at the polls this weekend,
election monitors say.
</P>
<P>
   More than two million people registered to vote for the first
time in this year's election, swelling the national rolls to nearly
6 million, but inexplicably many newcomers' names have not made it
onto the books, the monitors say.
</P>
<P>
   While the central government has acknowledged the problem,
exactly what is being done to correct it is unclear, the monitors
say. They fear that many voters will only discover they are not
registered when they show up at polling stations.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the matter, voters were not given receipts when
they registered, as was done in the past, leaving them no recourse
if they discover on election day that their names were omitted.
</P>
<P>
   But adding voters to the rolls has not been the only
registration problem. Removing them has been similarly troublesome.
A study earlier this year by the U.N. Development Program found
that anywhere from 10 percent to 25 percent of the people
registered to vote were dead but remained on the rolls, raising the
possibility of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, the process was handled in a very unfortunate
way,'' said Phil Matsheza, chairman of the Zimbabwe Election
Support Network, an umbrella organization of civic groups involved
in election monitoring. ``These things will definitely affect the
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many unanswered, unresolved questions, voters here might
think that the problems are the result of something more than
benign neglect, Matsheza said. ``You want people to believe there's
transparency in an electoral process,'' he said. ``But we're all
going into the election with one question. Why? Why has the
government handled it this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Moyo, a spokesman for President Robert Mugabe's ruling
party, the Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front, said
the concerns that have been raised are unfounded, fueled by biased
Western international observers who favor the opposition and have
turned their jobs into a ``partisan exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't invite them,'' Moyo said. ``They expressed an
interest and we said fine, but they are getting carried away,
acting like we are East Timor or Somalia with no constitution and a
breakdown in the social order.''
</P>
<P>
   With the country's economy suffering and many of its people
weary of the old guard, the ruling party and its leader, President
Robert Mugabe, are facing their first bona fide political challenge
in the 20 years since they took control of this former British
colony. A new opposition party has drawn widespread support, and
the ensuing struggle between them has been ugly, and often bloody.
</P>
<P>
   The fight to lead the country has drawn considerable
international attention, and the way the government has handled
independent election monitoring has been another source of a
concern in recent days, as both local and international observers
have faced new limitations and considerable scrutiny by the central
government.
</P>
<P>
   The most restrictive step would have prohibited civic groups
from assigning more than one observer to a polling station. The
organizations, which had been planning to send four observers to
each site, complained that the strain for one monitor to shoulder
the responsibility alone during two, 12-hour days of voting would
undermine the effort. On Thursday, in a sharp turnabout, the
government said it would ease the policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
