<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PARTNERS0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola plans to add domestic partner health coverage
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. will be joining a growing number of
companies that provide health care benefits to same-sex domestic
partners of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy, affecting all U.S. workers, will take effect
Jan. 1, the company announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola is ``currently researching its opportunities for
implementing this policy'' for employees outside the United States,
the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based beverage giant is the 99th company on the
Fortune 500 list to offer such benefits, said Kim Mills, education
director of the Human Rights Campaign, the country's largest gay
and lesbian political organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news,'' Mills said. ``We had been working with
people at Coca-Cola for some time on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke President Jack Stahl said the company ``is committed to
attracting and retaining the most diverse work force in the world.
... Today's announcement is another step toward achieving that
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 1990s, Mills said she was aware of only
about two dozen employers that offered domestic partner health
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we know of more than 3,400 employers,'' she said. So
far this year, Mills added, about five employers per week have
announced new coverage for domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said the cost for employers is ``minimal'' because
enrollments in plans generally increase by only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
