<SLUG> BC-TEXTILE-EARNINGS0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WestPoint Stevens expands Lauren deal
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WestPoint Stevens has expanded a deal with Polo Ralph
Lauren Corp. to make more designer label goods for the licensing
giant.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next year, the West Point-based sheet and towel maker
will produce Ralph Lauren bed pillows, mattress pads, feather beds,
down comforters and blankets. WestPoint Stevens already has an
exclusive license for Ralph Lauren sheets and towels. That license
was renewed, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded, five-year deal will add $90 million to $100
million to WestPoint Stevens' annual revenue in 2002, said Lorraine
Miller, the manufacturer's new senior vice president of investor
relations. WestPoint Stevens expects to receive about half that
amount next year because the new license starts in July of 2001,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens will take over the bedding license from rival
Pillowtex Corp. Dallas-based Pillowtex will continue to manufacture
and distribute the products until June 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, analysts have trimmed second-quarter earnings
estimates for WestPoint Stevens and other textile makers. Analysts
expect demand for towels and sheets to taper off a bit with the
slowdown in the housing market.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said they expect sales at Springs Industries,
the largest U.S. home textiles producer, to fall short of Wall
Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   And at least five analysts cut their estimates for WestPoint
Stevens this week. First Union cut its estimate by a nickel to 33
cents a share. Goldman Sachs decreased its estimate by 2 cents to
35 cents a share. WestPoint Stevens is expected to earn 36 cents a
share, according to a survey by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens is rebounding from a derailed plan to go
private. In late March, Chairman and Chief Executive Holcombe Green
Jr. led a buyout team that offered $22 a share for the company
shares they didn't already own. But the buyout plan collapsed when
rising interest rates prompted an investor to pull out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to release a new operating plan next
week when it holds its annual stockholder meeting in Buckhead.
Analysts and investors have been frustrated in recent months with
WestPoint Stevens' secrecy as it worked out its leveraged buyout
plan.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens' stock has lost half its value this year and
hit a 52-week low of $8.38 on Wednesday. The shares closed Thursday
at $8.81, down 19 cents, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
