u r BC-CAR-SHAWNA-ROBINSON06     06-22 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SHAWNA-ROBINSON0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'That girl' earning respect
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shawna Robinson can tell how much respect she has
earned since the beginning of the season by listening to the
headsets during her ARCA races.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 35, is trying to become the first woman to complete a
full schedule in a national stock-car racing series. She drives the
No. 8 Ford of Michael Kranefuss and Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   ARCA is a minor-league circuit, ranked just behind the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series. But the ARCA cars are considered to be more
similar to Winston Cup rides _ same weight, same engine _ than even
those on the Busch circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Daytona, the spotters would be telling their drivers `that
girl' was coming up on them,'' Robinson said. ``After they saw how
seriously everybody is taking this and how competitive our whole
team is, they started accepting all of us more, me and the guys as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we showed up at the first short track and gave it
everything we had, I think the respect value rose some,'' she said.
``I know this much: Now the spotters usually say, `That Kmart car'
is coming up on them, instead of `that girl.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Racing is nothing new to Robinson. She drove in the Busch Series
part-time from 1991-1995 and was the first woman to win a pole, in
1994 at Atlanta. She also finished 23rd in the Busch points
standings in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson left motorsports for four years to start a family and
build a business as an interior decorator. She got back behind the
wheel at the end of last season and will quit if she does not make
it to Winston Cup within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Through eight of the 21 races on the ARCA standings, Robinson
has four top-10 finishes and ranks fifth in the points. The mother
of two won the pole at Michigan two weeks ago. She will race
tonight in the event in Toledo, Ohio, and Saturday in DeGraff,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once that engine cranks, you don't know if it's a guy or girl
behind the wheel of the car, and it really doesn't matter,''
Mayfield, a Winston Cup driver, said. ``I think Shawna has a lot of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she is going to run Winston Cup someday, these are the
types of cars she is going to have to push around the race
tracks,'' he said. ``I'd put her up against just about anybody in
ARCA and up against most in Busch. She probably has some Winston
Cup guys beat, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
