<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SPYDER-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA MR2 SPYDER: A CLOTHING-OPTIONAL SPORTS CAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By DAN NEIL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To drive the new Toyota MR2 Spyder is to appreciate the Mazda
MX-5 Miata all over again. For more than a decade, an eternity for
a sports car, the plucky little Mazda roadster has defined the
road-going romantic idyll. The Miata is small, intimate even, with
a trunk that can handle a couple's bags for a romantic weekend
getaway. Leave the golf clubs at home; you're going no farther than
the hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   The Miata is also a terrific little open-top sports car, with
whip-smart handling, excellent balance and rorty, eager power. For
a generation of older-but-wiser fans of British sports cars, the
affordable Miata delivered all the windblown pleasures of the old
MG's and Triumphs without the fear of being becalmed by mechanical
failures.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the Toyota MR2 Spyder, another overachieving,
underpriced small sports car intended to win over Miata lovers;
but, alas, even in Virginia, the MR2 is not for lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its midengine design _ the motor is situated behind
the seats and slightly ahead of the rear axle _ the MR2 has no
trunk. Storage is limited to a plastic bin behind the seats (you
have to move the seats to get to it) about the size of a viola
case, plus a smaller-than-a-breadbox space in the nose, next to the
spare tire. Thus, a simple trip to the supermarket becomes an
exercise in Solomonic reasoning: Who gets to sit in the passenger
seat, your spouse or the groceries? As for the cozy weekend
getaway, unless you are heading for a nudists' retreat, forget it.
Carry-on bags are not permitted; nor can you check your luggage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this way, the MR2 has a strangely feral feel, as a car that
must be enjoyed alone _ quite a contrast to the congenial Miata.
Toyota could answer quite reasonably that utility was never part of
the car's mission statement. Yet after a week in the MR2, this
seems a miscalculation. A car with no storage is merely a toy, and
toys, as the Plymouth Prowler proves, become boring.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers, the MR2 and Miata are strikingly similar. The
MR2's length (153 inches) is a couple of inches shorter than the
Miata, though the MR2 is slightly wider and taller. The MR2 is
about 100 pounds lighter than the Miata, which can be loaded with
luxury options not available in the MR2. Both cars are powered by
1.8-liter aluminum engines, though the MR2's variable valve timing
gives it the edge in usable torque (125 pounds-feet at 4,400 rpm,
vs. the Miata's 117 pounds-feet at 5,000 rpm).
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the MR2 seems oddly derivative. The top
latches appear to have been purchased by the same supplier who
sells the parts to Mazda. Imitation is the sincerest form of
flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, however, the two cars come from very different
sides of the drafting table. Compared with the Miata, with its
lozenge-like curves, the MR2 is crisply geometric, with slab sides
punctuated by scalloped air ducts and an anthropomorphic face
reminiscent of Mike Mulligan's steam shovel _ all grin and bright
eyes. The rear of the car features a long louvered decklid and
prominent taillights above a Ferrari-like rear grille. From this
angle, the current Spyder has more in common with the
first-generation MR2 of the late 1980s _ itself a riff on the old
Fiat X1/9 _ than its immediate forebear, a sort of Mini-Me
Testarossa.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Miata, whose top folds down with the inside panel
exposed to the elements, the MR2's top folds in a Z pattern,
leaving the canvas top clamped down behind the seats and minimizing
the need for the tonneau cover.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the MR2 is well organized and comfortable, with simply
superb bolstered buckets that you may be tempted to unbolt and
install in your living room. The bluff and upright dash keeps the
climate and audio controls well sorted; handsome materials, like
brushed aluminum and dimpled vinyl on the steering wheel, dash and
door pulls, a serenely technical feel.
</P>
<P>
   The Achilles' heel in any midengine car is packaging, since the
engine takes up so much prime real estate in close proximity to the
driver. Yet the MR2's engine seems isolated from the cabin. It
makes its presence known under hard acceleration, as it should,
with a hoarse, mechanical burr; but in the putter of city streets
it remains pleasantly sotto voce. Legroom is ample for a small
midengine car (compared with the cruelties of the X1/9, for
instance), allowing you to move the seat up for a few degrees of
seat-back rake. Credit the MR2's expansive wheelbase of 96.5
inches, which sets the wheels in the far precincts of the fenders.
</P>
<P>
   Considering its myriad packaging problems, why bother with a
midengine design, anyway? Because placing the engine near the
center of the car allows the vehicle to turn more quickly,
pirouetting around a vertical axis like a skater with her arms
drawn in tight. For pure performance, nothing beats a lightweight,
midengine, rear-drive car _ as a glance at the grid of the Indy 500
will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   And the MR2's performance is sparkling, lively, alert and well
composed, transitioning evenly from one sliding corner to another.
The car's rack-and-pinion steering answers instantly to command,
and the sensations from the tires feed up through the wheel so you
intuitively know what each wheel is doing at all times. Considering
how much steel is in the car's unit body, the MR2 is remarkably
light (about 2,200 pounds unloaded), so the suspension and tires
needn't battle high inertia loads pitching from side to side. The
independent suspension (struts and springs with control links) is
supple but firm, giving up a few inches of body lean in corners
before stiffening in a muscular, shoulder-down stance.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota wisely chose to put 15-inch radials on the car. Bigger
tires might have given the car more overall grip (and filled in
what appears to be overly generous wheel wells), but the ride would
have suffered without really improving the car's fun quotient.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the MR2's toggle-like gearshift, well-placed pedals
and hearty antilock brakes all make it a wildly amusing car to
drive. The MR2 dances and darts like an aerobatic kite in a stiff
spring breeze.
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves the MR2 in a virtual dead heat with the
Miata in general joie de vivre. So why would anyone choose the MR2
over a gold-plated classic with a trunk? Cheap exclusivity, for one
thing. There are about a quarter-million Miatas running around the
United States. The MR2 will be sold in limited numbers, only 5,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   So if you buy an MR2, you will definitely turn some heads. And
you will have bought a car with the fit and finish of a Toyota, the
oaken solidity of a car costing thousands more. If only it didn't
make you feel so lonely. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
