<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-WORLDBIZ-BRAZIL-$ADV2     06-22 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDBIZ-BRAZIL-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A BRAZILIAN BANKER, THE HIGHEST PERCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By SIMON ROMERO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ There are the investment bankers who talk of
things like deficit figures and inflation targets when discussing
Brazil, Latin America's largest economy. Then there are the
bankers, like Francisco Gros, who talk of Piggy.
</P>
<P>
   As a high-ranking executive at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Gros
wrote in an online newsletter late last year that ``we Brazilians
suffer from what could be called `Piggy' syndrome _ we believe
ourselves to be wonderful, while others, unfortunately, do not see
us quite that way.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of Brazil's leading figures on Wall Street, Gros
developed a reputation for talking tough. Now, however, he is
toning down his approach after being named in February to one of
the most coveted posts in Brazil's government, the presidency of
the country's powerful development bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that stuff doesn't come back to haunt me,'' said Gros,
who is 57.
</P>
<P>
   He probably does not have much to worry about, given his
reputation as a consummate insider among the coterie of Ivy
League-educated economists, bankers and academics who have run
Brazil for much of the past decade. But many other Brazilians
question whether their interests are best served by a group of
bankers bent on globalization.
</P>
<P>
   Among this worldly group of financiers, perhaps none are
worldlier than Gros. The son of a French diplomat, he grew up on
three continents, in Brazil, France and the United States, and
attended Princeton as an undergraduate. After graduate school in
economics at Columbia, he returned to Brazil and began a career in
the high-flying financial circles of Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he began playing the game of musical chairs that is
familiar in Brazil, in which leading figures from the private
sector accept high-profile jobs in government, then return to the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Between stints as an executive at Unibanco, one of Brazil's
largest banks, and as president of Aracruz Celulose SA, a large
manufacturer of eucalyptus pulp used in paper products, Gros served
twice as president of the country's central bank. He was also a
partner in a small investment bank, Banco BFC SA.
</P>
<P>
   After his last term at the central bank, which ended in 1992, he
returned to the private sector. He joined Morgan Stanley as its
chairman for Latin America, helping to build the institution into a
leading investment banking presence in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Jetting between his homes in New York and Rio, Gros became a
fixture on network television, discussing the direction of the
world's ninth-largest economy, his candid assessment of Brazil's
challenges making him a favorite among journalists.
</P>
<P>
   So few people were surprised by his appointment by President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso to head the National Bank for Economic
and Social Development, a secretive institution that rivals
international lending organizations like the World Bank in its
size. It is known as the BNDES, its initials in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Banco do Brasil SA, another institution
controlled by the government that focuses more on consumer banking,
the development bank is probably the most powerful financial
institution in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a banker's dream to run the BNDES,'' said Edmar Bacha, a
former president of the development bank who now heads the New York
office of Banco BBA-Creditanstalt. ``It is the only domestic
provider of long-term capital and its size makes it one of the most
powerful institutions, financial or otherwise, in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank has the largest lending budget of any Brazilian bank,
at nearly 20 billion reais, or about $11 billion. During the
Cardoso administration, which began in 1995, a five-fold increase
in its government support transformed the bank from a financier of
infrastructure projects into the main arm of economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   As Brazil opened its economy to foreign investment and
competition, the bank was there at every step. The bank guided the
world's largest privatization program in the 1990s, selling some
$90 billion of state assets. Often, this role put it in touch with
the world's leading investment banks, which competed to handle the
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gros' tutelage, Morgan Stanley won one such contract,
serving as co-manager with Salomon Smith Barney for the $21 billion
privatization of Brazil's telecommunications monopoly in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Through its investment banking unit, modeled on the
International Finance Corp., a subsidiary of the World Bank, it
financed many of these takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   The free-wheeling use of its funds, which it provided to
companies regardless of their national origin, has been a major
source of criticism by opponents to the government's privatization
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why a public institution in a poor country like
Brazil is providing money to foreign companies that have cheap
access to borrowing overseas,'' said Aloizio Mercadante, a Sao
Paulo congressman from the Workers Party.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the bank's big role in guiding policy, Gros will have
to mitigate the tension resulting from a government seeking to
rapidly modernize the economy and an opposition questioning whether
Brazil is bending too far in its rush to globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is at a stage in which it needs something more than
people who see the country as a balance sheet,'' said Clovis Rossi,
a columnist for Folha de Sao Paulo, Brazil's most widely read
newspaper. ``It may be that neo-nationalists don't help the economy
to grow further, but a collection of bankers does not seem to be
the best alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gros is not alone among high-ranking officials in
having a background in international finance. The central bank
president, Arminio Fraga, a close friend, is a former hedge fund
manager for George Soros. Another former banker, Development
Minister Alcides Tapias, is Gros' immediate superior.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gros' tutelage, the bank is seeking to temper its worldly
investing approach with a renewed emphasis on lending to small and
medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a cosmopolitan bunch but that alone is not enough,''
Gros said. ``Accepting the inevitability of an open economy and
preparing Brazil for a growing global role are the challenges
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
