<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller's workout impresses Hawks
 &HT;    By John Hollis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mike Miller knows a thing or two about getting things
turned around in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   He played a big part in putting the Florida Gators back on the
college basketball map over the past two seasons. Now, Miller could
be the man the Hawks select to pace what it hopes is a similar
reformation, with its sixth overall pick in Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like we did at the University of Florida,'' said Miller,
referring to the Gators' Sweet 16 and Final Four berths during his
two-year stay in Gainesville. ``We had a young team come in and we
did a lot of special things there. I think that this organization _
from the front office to the players _ that's what they want to do
here, and I think that would be fun to be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 6 feet 8, 218 pounds, was the most impressive of three
potential first-round draftees in a 90-minute workout before Hawks
officials at the Philips Arena practice courts Thursday morning.
Former Cincinnati guard DerMarr Johnson (6-9, 200), back for his
second workout, and former Oklahoma State forward Desmond Mason
(6-5, 215) both played well. But Miller stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the workout went well,'' said Miller, who last season
led Florida in scoring (14.1), minutes (28.6), free throws (124)
and free-throw attempts (170). ``We've been to enough teams where
it's all starting to be repetition. `` Miller already had worked
out for the Orlando Magic, Houston Rockets and Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials were impressed with Miller's overall
understanding of the game, athleticism and all-around skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very talented, . . . very, very fluid,'' general
manager Pete Babcock said. ``He shoots the ball so easily with deep
range. It's like a 15-foot jump shot from 3-point range. Not
everybody can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hawks coach Lon Kruger knows Miller's game, after watching
him get 19 points and nine rebounds to power Florida past his
Illinois team in this year's NCAA Tournament second-round matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's workout did nothing to change Kruger's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was going to work hard,'' the coach said. ``We knew
he was going to shoot well, and we knew he was going compete like
crazy _ all good stuff and he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason played well, even though his luggage did not arrive on his
flight Wednesday. The new basketball shoes he wore during the
morning's workout were courtesy of the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks probably will conclude their pre-draft workouts today
with guards Courtney Alexander (Fresno State) and Justin Love (St.
Louis), and swingmen Lavor Postell (St. John's) and Quentin
Richardson (DePaul).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
