<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GAYS-GAFIRMS0623-COX     06-22 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-GAFIRMS0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gay rights group pressures nine firms
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Equality Project is pressuring nine major
Georgia companies to provide gay and lesbian workers with the same
health care and other benefits offered to married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The gay and lesbian rights group plans to ask participants at
this weekend's Lesbian and Gay Pride celebration to write letters
and call the chief executives of the targeted companies. The group
won't call a boycott now, but its leaders say they have not ruled
it out.
</P>
<P>
   The nine companies are Home Depot, Atlanta Gas Light, BellSouth,
Georgia Pacific, Delta Air Lines, Wachovia, United Parcel Service,
Shaw Industries and GulfStream Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to take whatever action is necessary,'' said
Harry Knox, executive director of the Atlanta-based organization.
The group sent letters to the heads of the companies June 12 but
has not heard from any of them, Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the companies on the GEP list said Thursday that they
are considering domestic partner benefits. None of eight companies
contacted said they would refuse to consider them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize this is an emerging issue,'' said Ken Haldin, a
spokesman for Georgia-Pacific Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for AGL Resources, parent of Atlanta Gas Light Co.,
said the issue is ``very important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're looking at,'' said AGL spokesman Nick
Gold. ``We have to determine whether it's feasible and how many of
our 2,200 employees would be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Same-sex partners lose $2,000 to $3,000 a year in benefits that
are given to straight couples, Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an issue of equal work for equal pay,'' Knox said.
``My partner and I have taken on all the financial responsibilities
of being married and yet we don't get any of the benefits. These
are companies that self-insure and could offer domestic partners
benefits. The cost to employers is inconsequential.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox estimates there are 500,000 lesbians and gay men in metro
Atlanta and north Georgia _ more than the region's United
Methodists. GEP, formed in 1995 as an advocacy group, has about
1,500 members statewide and a database of more than 10,000
individuals, Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   The group's campaign comes on the heels of Coca-Cola's
announcement Thursday that it will offer domestic partner benefits.
Coke initially was among the companies GEP targeted, Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic partner benefits has been a controversial issue for a
decade, said Ken McDonnell, a research analyst with the Employee
Benefit Research Institute, a nonprofit nonpartisan think tank in
Washington. About 3,000 U.S. companies and government agencies
offer the benefit, according to the Human Rights Campaign Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But fewer people than expected use the benefit. In fact,
unmarried heterosexuals are more inclined than gay couples to use
the benefit to cover partners, a recent survey by Hewitt Associates
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't cost a company any more to cover a domestic partner
than a legal spouse,'' McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   But it does cost gay couples, because they pay income taxes on
the value of the partner benefit. Married couples don't pay taxes
on coverage for spouses and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a low cost benefit (for companies),'' McDonnell said.
``If we look at the example of Coke, the company wants to
demonstrate that they value diversity among their work force.
Domestic partner benefit is an excellent tool to communicate that.
It makes good PR and it's cheap to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
