<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WHITENESS-CONFERENCE-     06-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITENESS-CONFERENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP TO PLUMB THE MEANING OF `WHITENESS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul Marcus likes to describe his early years in
working class East Hartford, Conn. as a ``life of privilege'':
During the summers, he spent the days hauling heavy boxes of
produce onto a massive truck, and the nights with his family in the
stuffy top floor of a triple decker.
</P>
<P>
   But even in this simple existence, he explains now, he had great
advantages. If his father had not risen to the top of an all-white
union, he might not have had any job at all. And if his family had
not been white, he said, he probably would have lived an even
humbler house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear to me now, even though I had a working-class
background, that I had benefits,'' said Marcus, now 47. ``We often
think privilege is only for the rich people but all whites have
some privileges because of the color of their skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus is one of the organizers of a controversial conference
being held Friday at Simmons College on ``whiteness.'' The unusual
topic, expected to draw some 100 liberal activists, religious
leaders and academics, is another sign that what was once a fringe
academic pursuit _ called ``white studies'' _ is gaining followers.
</P>
<P>
   In just the last few years, estimated those in the field, some
200 books have been written on ``whiteness.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind white studies, explained conference organizers,
is to dismantle racism by focusing on white culture, and the
privileges that come with it. Race relations, they insist, should
no longer just be a topic for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the conference, the second in Boston, is to help
whites and ``those who work with them'' to embrace white culture
while abandoning their privileges, said Marcus. Many whites, he
explained, see themselves as having no race at all _ that to be
white is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many whites that are blind to everyday realities
and racism,'' said Marcus. ``We are saying as whites we don't even
see ourselves as racialized.''
</P>
<P>
   But even supporters caution that the so-called whiteness
movement, which focuses on ``white culture,'' could provide
ammunition for white supremecist groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to study what whiteness is all about,'' said Chip
Berlay, who heads the Political Research Associates. ``But my main
concern is that there is another whiteness movement _ the white
supremist.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus worries that poor whites, who often are forced to compete
for jobs with other groups, are now the ones being labeled racist,
while white middle- and upper-class Americans, who historically
have enjoyed the best treatment, are let off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear that South Boston is racist but you never hear
anything about Wellesley or the other surburbs,'' said Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights of the conference, said Marion Groot,
co-director of the Women's Theology Center, will be a tour of
Boston's neighborhoods, with tour guides like Rep. Byron Rushing on
hand to explain how white privilege and power throughout history
changed the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, if you were to take the South End and look at the
people who lived here and then look at what has been the
demographic over time _ what you see is that people get displaced
based own their lack of economic access,'' said Groot.
</P>
<P>
   A walk through Faneuil Hall where dozens of paintings of past
white leaders in Boston hang on the walls, will also be a clear and
powerful snapshot of white dominance, said Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   That dominance has brought a windfall, argues Randall Robinson,
who rekindled the idea that black Americans should be paid
trillions in reparations with his book ``The Debt: What America
owes Blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   And as whites make up a smaller percentage of the population,
more and more of them will be forced to confront their past, said
Edward Ball, author of the nationally-acclaimed ``Slaves in the
Family,'' the story of his own family's slave-owning roots.
</P>
<P>
   Groot said the conference is an attempt to show whites that they
are a part of the country's racial dynamic. But ``white studies''
also tries to analyze white culture, in the same way that
anthropoligists might examine the common language, art, and
traditions of a far away tribe.
</P>
<P>
   As the world globalizes, Groot added, it will force a change of
attitude: ``I personally think that what is happening is that
whites can no longer assume ...that the majority of the world
population thinks just the way white people think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
