<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MARS-WATER-BOS &LR;      06-22 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS HAS WATER, SCIENTISTS SAY, BUT IN UNUSUAL PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA scientists' announcement Thursday that they have discovered
traces of water flowing recently on Mars came wrapped in a
perplexing enigma: Water on Mars seems to crop up in all the wrong
places.
</P>
<P>
   The new images from the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft show
steep slopes that appear to reveal a layer of water just a few
hundred feet below the surface, contradicting theorists who had
been sure that any water would have to be at least 2 miles
underground.
</P>
<P>
   Even more puzzling, all the signs of water seeping from the
walls of canyons and craters seem to occur in the wrong parts of
the Martian surface, and to be flowing on slopes that face in
exactly the wrong direction. Instead of the sunniest, most tropical
slopes, where the sun's warmth might be expected to help melt
exposed ice, the seeping water and the channels it produces are all
more than 30 degrees from the equator, and on the poleward-facing
slopes where they are in perpetual cold shadow.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer unexpectedness of finding water in such places led
Kenneth Edgett, co-author of the new report to be published in
Science magazine next week, to say that ``I was dragged kicking and
screaming to (the) conclusion'' that the grooves and channels they
found must have been carved very recently by flows of running
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very much disturbed'' by the fact that the locations of
the features just don't seem to make sense, Edgett said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Zuber, a planetary scientist at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology who specializes in Mars but was not
involved in this research, said in an interview Thursday that
``people are befuddled, because no one has thought about this. . .
. Nobody had thought about present-day (liquid) water on Mars, or
close to present day.''
</P>
<P>
   Any attempts to explain the location of these features so far,
Zuber said, amount to ``grasping at straws.''
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicable as the findings may be, they've sent a surge of
excitement through planetary researchers because water is the most
basic prerequisite for life. Michael Carr, a geologist with the US
Geological Survey who wrote a book called ``Water on Mars,'' said
the new findings are perhaps the most exciting since the first
images of river-like channels _ signs that water had flowed over
the planet in the distant past _ were sent from Mars in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The only explanation offered so far, by Edgett and Michael
Malin, the principal scientist of the Mars Global Surveyor camera
and lead author of the new report, is that in sunnier areas, any
ice that was present slowly vaporized over time, leaving not enough
in place to produce flowing water. But this doesn't explain what
source of heat eventually came along to melt the ice and produce
the steep channels seen in the new pictures.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the location of these gullies does make sense:
Many are grouped in regions that suggest large, underground
aquifers that could be the source of many individual outflows.
</P>
<P>
   And, if there are substantial aquifers present on Mars today,
that has profound implications for the future of Mars exploration.
On the one hand, they would provide the ideal setting in which to
conduct any searches for signs of microbial life on Mars. In
addition, they could provide a crucial resource for any future
human exploration of the planet, offering a source of drinking
water as well as an air supply and fuel for rockets and rovers when
the water is converted to oxygen and hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
   While scientists find the evidence for liquid water compelling,
they emphasize that further work is needed and that it is possible
that someone may yet find an alternative explanation for the
features. One goal of the ongoing research is to take new pictures
of some of the same areas already examined, in hopes of finding
signs of recent changes, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see one that changes before our eyes, wow. We'll be
back'' to give another press conference, Edgett said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, scientists and amateurs alike can help in the
search for water. Some 27,500 pictures taken by the present
orbiting spacecraft have been posted on the Internet, but many have
gotten little more than a cursory look so far.
</P>
<P>
   So it is entirely possible, the scientists said, that the next
great breakthrough could come from some student or amateur
scientist studying the images at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on the science teams have not gotten close'' to being
able to scrutinize most of the images in any detail, Zuber said.
``It's going to be a treasure trove for a decade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
