<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AT DAVIDIAN TRIAL, LAWYERS SPAR WITH VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DICK J. REAVIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``A live witness? My goodness!'' U.S. District
Judge Walter Smith said Thursday after lawyers in the Branch
Davidian wrongful death suit against the federal government ended a
showing of videotaped depositions that ran for nearly five hours.
</P>
<P>
   The video witness, Joe Servel, an FBI agent who commanded a
Bradley tank during the 1993 Waco siege, remembered little and cast
only a slim light on the fatal events of April 19, when the home of
cult leader David Koresh and his followers burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh and 75 others died in the fire. Survivors and families of
the victims are seeking $675 million, saying the government agents
are responsible for the fiery end to the 51-day siege. The
government says the Davidians set the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI tank commander's testimony provided relief and human
touches to a courtroom so bored that Justice Department lawyer
Marie Hagen was nodding off to sleep, as The Day of the Dueling
Videos turned into the Day of the Drowsy.
</P>
<P>
   The lead lawyer for the plaintiffs, Mike Caddell, introduced
excerpts from a half-dozen videotaped depositions for the jury. In
lieu of cross-examination, federal attorney Mike Bradford, played
excerpts that were more to the government's liking.
</P>
<P>
   The videos left jurors and three dozen spectators _ half as many
as on Wednesday _ yawning.
</P>
<P>
   The video depositions were of a half-dozen men, including former
FBI Director William Sessions, who were government officials at the
time of the 1993 events near Waco. Caddell's aim was to show that
on April 19, the day of the fatal fire, the FBI brass did not
expect tanks to be used to penetrate and destroy parts of the
building, or even to enter it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the FBI officials, Danny Coulson of Arlington, Texas,
appeared in the video wearing a sport coat and open-neck shirt,
with mussed hair and bags under his eyes. He was squirming and
defensive as he spoke, sometimes drinking deeply from a white
Styrofoam cup filled with an iced beverage. Coulson looked more
like a suspect in an early morning precinct interrogation than a
law enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of halting and reluctant statements, Coulson told
his interrogators that he and a subordinate, Mike Kahoe, watched
the April tank-and-tear gas assault from a television monitor in an
FBI war room in Washington, D.C. When Kahoe first saw a tank
entering the building, crushing a wall as it went, he exclaimed
``Holy s---!'' Coulson said.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Coulson nor any of the others would flatly say that
the tank attacks were, as Caddell believes, in violation of the
orders or plan that Attorney General Janet Reno gave to field
commanders Jeff Jamar and Dick Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the final of several draft plans for the raid,
Caddell argued on the videotapes that no tank assaults should have
been made until efforts to flush out the Davidians with tear gas
had been under way for 48 hours. The assaults had begun within
minutes of the tear gas attack.
</P>
<P>
   In the rebuttal excerpts that federal lawyers chose to play, the
FBI executives defended Jamar and Rogers, saying such things as,
``any tactical plan does not presuppose that it can anticipate
anything that can occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
