<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2044 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOUSE-AUCTIONS-ART-2T     06-22 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-AUCTIONS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST TREND: SELLING THE HOUSE, AT AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ala., Fla., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT15 and NYT16 were sent on June 21 to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINGTON, N.Y. _ The auction was barely under way, but already,
Thomas and Gloria Fatato were feeling out of place in the
Tudor-style house they had built 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Strangers were nibbling on hors d'oeuvres and sipping on fume
blanc. A ponytailed musician teased out ``Puttin' on the Ritz'' and
``Cheek to Cheek'' on a Yamaha synthesizer. A veritable army of
auctioneers from the National Auction Group of Gadsden, Ala., all
wearing matching American-flag ties, were doing their officious
best to prod, prod, prod.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the bidding for the Fatatos' house stagnated at
$975,000, one of the guys with the American-flag ties, Jack Ogle,
rapped his knuckles on a glass shelf in the living room. In a
Southern drawl, he bellowed: ``That's opportunity knocking tonight
like it's never knocked before in this area!''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the modus operandi was not pitch-perfect for the
grizzled New York crowd. Still, for most people at the auction
earlier this month, this odd cocktail of one part culture clash,
one part high-stakes poker, was their first taste of a phenomenon
that has proliferated: the sale of houses and apartments at
auction.
</P>
<P>
   These slick events with the trappings of a wedding or a
fund-raiser are a far cry from the enduring image of a foreclosed
house being sold on the courthouse steps. Instead, the auctions
appeal to a faster-paced, time-pressed society accustomed to
speculating on art, stocks and everything else, in person or over
the Internet _ a society, in short, with an eBay mentality.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole generation of Internet babies who love the
auctions and are used to it,'' said Lee Mills, a lawyer, investment
banker and powerboat racer from Key West, Fla., whose 13-acre
estate in Woodstock, was sold at auction for a higher-than-expected
$2 million several years ago. ``It's a lot of entertainment, a lot
of theater, and I believe it's the trend of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneers and real estate brokers estimate that there are now
at least 1,000 auctions of residential properties each year,
compared with 200 five years ago and only a handful 10 years ago.
Meanwhile, the value of all real estate sold at auction increased
to $49 billion in 1998 from $21 billion in 1986, according to the
Gwent Group, an auction-research company in Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   On average the auctions can net 80 to 90 percent of the
property's appraised value, which is a shade below what traditional
sales can bring. But some traditional brokers dismiss the auctions
as marketing ploys or annoying competition, said Jan Tarnow,
manager of the auction department of the National Association of
Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some of that us-versus-them mentality,'' Tarnow
said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, these auctions usually involved lavish estates,
owned by people like former Senator Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and the
singer Kenny Rogers. On June 8, Christie's Realty International
auctioned a newly listed 2,800-square-foot brownstone on
Manhattan's East Side designed by Philip Johnson and once owned by
Blanchette Rockefeller. The winning bid was $11.16 million _ or
more than double the estimate _ and set a record for the highest
sale price per square foot in Manhattan, according to Christie's.
(The winning bidder was not disclosed.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the auctions are becoming less stratospheric.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sheldon Good &AMP; Co. of Chicago plans to auction 50
condominiums in Battery Park City and midtown Manhattan for
$200,000 to $800,000 apiece, both in person and over the Internet,
said Steven L. Good, the company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some real estate has been sold on eBay on the Internet. But so
far, the company that has come closest to offering a consistent,
virtual real estate auction has been Homebid.com, which has sold
about 20 homes since January 1999, mainly on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In other countries, particularly Australia, selling real estate
at auction is considered the norm. But in the United States, the
word ``auction'' still conjures up bad images of fast-talking
hucksters preying upon vulnerable people. And the recent fiasco
involving a painting's price being manipulated on eBay does not
help.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And for some people, the packaging _ Want a mariachi band? A
harpist? Some bacon-wrapped quail? _ is a distraction and a
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a circus,'' said John Aronian III, a retired surgeon in
Westchester, who attended the Fatatos' auction. ``It was good ol'
boys from down South. It was like a hog auction.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, with prime real estate in short supply in a good
economy, more buyers and sellers are willing to gamble on an
auction.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For sellers, auctions may be appealing because they can greatly
accelerate the sales process. Buyers, who must bring a certified
check _ $50,000 in the Irvington sale _ are expected to do their
own inspections or buy the house on an as-is basis. They then have
a set period of time, usually 30 days, to arrange financing and set
a closing date.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of sellers are opting for auctions because
their job or family situation has changed suddenly, or their
property is unusual, said J. Craig King, president of the J.P. King
Auction Co., in Gadsden, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   People are naturally competitive, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch the people sizing each other up: it's like, `Hmm,'''
said Barbara Corcoran, president of the Corcoran Group, a Manhattan
real estate company, which plans to auction properties solely on
the Internet. ``It puts any French cafe to shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as William R. Bone, president of the National Auction Group,
put it: ``It reaches a point where egos take over. It's not dollars
and cents; it's egos.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Tuesday, it was the Fatatos' turn. The owner of a
beer distribution company in the Bronx, Fatato, 58, and his wife,
52, had tried unsuccessfully for more than a year to sell their
house to move to a smaller one in Rockland County. The original
price was $1.7 million, but the house was too opulent for the
neighborhood, with glass-and-mirror decor that had not changed
since it was designed 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, rain forced the event indoors. Still, there were
10 bidders, an unusually high number, most of whom did not want to
give their names.
</P>
<P>
   Some were young professionals from Manhattan. At least two
people were considering auctions for their own properties, one on
the Hudson River, the other in Litchfield, Conn. Everyone was
itching with expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, shortly after 8 p.m., show time. The auctioneer, Eddie
Haynes, a member of the Oklahoma Auctioneers Hall of Fame, tried to
oil the crowd with folksy charm. First, he auctioned a bottle of
Dom Perignon to Fatato for $125 for charity. Then he asked loudly:
``We having fun yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun!'' blurted another auctioneer, Wayne Thorn.
</P>
<P>
   The Fatatos chose perhaps the riskiest method: an absolute
auction, without reserve, where the final price is the final price,
even if it is $1. The Fatatos did have the option to cancel at the
last minute, but they did not, and soon, Haynes started the bidding
at $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was loud and chaotic, with people spilling into the living,
dining, kitchen and foyer areas. And slowly, tentatively, the price
climbed; past $800,000, past $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   When the bidding halted at $975,000, Haynes tried repeatedly to
whip the crowd into a frenzy, to no avail. The hammer price was
$975,000, a bid by a young Russian family in Manhattan, said their
broker, Neil Singh.
</P>
<P>
   There was some confusion. A woman in the back, talking on a cell
phone, was apparently trying to bid $1 million, but Haynes did not
notice her. When told about it afterward, Haynes muttered with
disgust.
</P>
<P>
   The final price, actually, was almost $1.1 million, because of
the additional 10 percent charged by the auction company.
</P>
<P>
   The Fatatos were overwhelmed and exhausted by the experience.
``You put your whole life into their hands, and whatever they say,
you believe,'' Fatato said, a few days after the auction. ``Who
knows, it could have gone higher. But it happened so quick. I'm
still trying to figure it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
