<HEADLINE>
FURNITE WEB SITE LAYS OFF 80 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Furniture.com Inc., which was tossed a $27 million lifeline this
week, laid off 80 employees Thursday, slashing its work force by 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Like other online retailers, Furniture.com has been struggling
to rein in costs, hoping that the capital markets will eventually
swing back into their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, these are downsizing days for dot-coms. Drkoop.com,
Salon.com, and PlanetRX.com also have laid off employees. Other
firms, including Craftshop.com and Toysmart.com, have given up.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com executives said in January they hoped to raise up
to $50 million in an initial public offering. But by April, it was
clear that Wall Street investors had lost their appetite for
Internet retail stocks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Furniture.com formally withdrew its offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they're focusing on the bottom line and trying to
achieve profitability in a quicker time frame,'' said Jeffrey
Quinn, an analyst with Internet research firm Gomez Advisors in
Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   This is Furniture.com's second round of layoffs. In April, the
Framingham, Mass. furniture seller laid off 30 people by asking
them to sit by their desks and wait for their phones to ring.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the company's troubles, chief executive Andrew
Brooks had been urging employees to stick around. Key executives,
however, continued to walk out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Quinn said Furniture.com executives recently had
considered filing for bankruptcy, along with other options. But an
investor group led by (at)Ventures, the venture capital arm of
Andover-based CMGI Inc., rescued the firm this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support of the company continues,'' said Krista Thomas, a
spokeswoman for (at)Ventures, one of Furniture.com's original
investors. ``Everybody continues to believe that the company has
the opportunity to pursue its original strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear how the $27 million financing had been
structured, however. Dot-coms have complained that deals have
become more restrictive and more expensive. For example, eToys Inc.
raised $100 million earlier this month _ but on terms less
favorable than in previous financings.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com officials could not be reached Thursday. Thomas
said she did not know the details of the company's latest
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that online retailers may have to wait a while
longer for the financial markets to improve. Many investors have
lost interest in unprofitable and cash-burning online stores that
have little chance of leading their respective categories, such as
toys, pets, or books.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture retailers also face unique challenges, such as selling
products that are bulky, pricier, and often more expensive to ship.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research predicts that $3.9 billion, or 5 percent of
all furniture sales, will migrate to the Internet by 2004. About 9
percent of apparel purchases and half of all software purchases are
expected to be rung up in cyperspace that same year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
