<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-FOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICAHN SWEETENS OFFER FOR NABISCO GROUP HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Icahn, the financier who owns about 10 percent of Nabisco
Group Holdings, sweetened his offer for the company Thursday, the
second time in two days that he has raised his bid.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn's revised offer was disclosed in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission after the stock market closed.
It came after a telephone conversation he had Thursday morning with
Steven Goldstone, chairman of Nabisco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion took place less than a day after Nabisco Group
Holdings received bids for its 80.4 percent stake in Nabisco
Holdings, the food company, and an offer from Icahn to buy the
holding company.
</P>
<P>
   The Philip Morris Cos. and a joint venture of Danone SA and
Cadbury Schweppes PLC submitted bids for the food company, The Wall
Street Journal reported. The Journal said Philip Morris had bid
close to $55 a share and the Danone-Cadbury bid was close to $50 a
share. Shares of Nabisco Holdings fell $1.6875 Thursday, to
$51.5625.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Icahn offered $28 a share for Nabisco Group
Holdings, $19 a share in cash and $9 in two-year 14 percent notes.
Icahn then revised and increased that bid Thursday. Shares of
Nabisco Group Holdings rose 6.25 cents, to $25.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Goldstone, Icahn said he was prepared to pay 88
percent of the after-tax cash price Nabisco Group Holdings receives
for the food company.
</P>
<P>
   The revised offer is structured along the lines of an offer R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Holdings reportedly made for Nabisco Group
Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that Reynolds had
submitted a bid that would price the holding company at a 20
percent discount to the net proceeds received from the sale of the
food company.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Smith, a spokeswoman for R.J. Reynolds, declined to comment.
Spokesmen for Philip Morris and Danone also declined to comment, as
did Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although Icahn's offer is not fixed in stone, analysts said it
was clearly superior to the bid he made on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``By offering to buy Nabisco Group Holdings at a 12 percent
discount to net asset value, Mr. Icahn has raised substantially his
bid,'' said Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``The impact of this bid is that it has raised the bar
materially for other bidders for Nabisco Group Holdings, including
R.J. Reynolds.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members of Nabisco Group Holdings are expected to meet
Friday morning to consider the offers.
</P>
<P>
   But Feldman and others said they did not consider the bids
submitted thus far to be the final offers the company will receive.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to the fact that Goldstone called Icahn and
encouraged him to raise his bid as evidence that the bidding was
not over. If Goldstone spoke with Icahn, the analysts reasoned, he
probably placed similar calls to executives at Philip Morris and
Danone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven Goldstone is going to do everything he can to grow the
sale price between now and the time the holding company and the
food company are eventually sold,'' Feldman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
