<HEADER>
A2051 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-22 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PAGING FRANK CAPRA 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Lazio, the current Republican Senate candidate from New
York, once told a reporter that his favorite movie was the old
Jimmy Stewart film ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington.'' This is always
a popular choice among people who hope to go to Washington
themselves. But it had particular reverberations back in 1992 for
Lazio, who was running for Congress as an idealistic young hero
bucking the entrenched forces of corrupt politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels weren't perfect. For one thing, Smith was a
professional scoutmaster, while Lazio was a lawyer and longtime
protege of the Suffolk County Republican Party. Smith was a perfect
political virgin, who managed to get appointed to an interim Senate
seat without ever having noticed that his home state had been in
the grip of a corrupt machine for several decades. Things like that
do not generally occur on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   We digress, however. The idea of `` Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington'' was very much the theme of Lazio's career-defining
House campaign in 1992. His battle cry was ``No perks, no
privileges, no pay raises,'' and his pitch was that the incumbent,
Tom Downey, had become an out-of-touch, junket-taking insider.
</P>
<P>
   After his upset victory, the new congressman demonstrated his
determination not to join the Washington establishment by embarking
on a perpetual commute. Every Monday Lazio, his pregnant wife and
1-year-old daughter crammed into the family Infiniti and drove five
hours from Long Island to Washington. Every Thursday, they drove
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uninterrupted family time,'' he said. ``You can talk
about life.''
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now Lazio is running against Hillary Rodham
Clinton, and he seems to have adjusted his view on perks,
privileges, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newly released financial records show that Lazio led the New
York delegation in number of trips taken on other people's tabs in
1999. A good-government group called one outing to Virginia that
was paid for by the Mortgage Bankers Association ``a good example
of a trip that a member shouldn't take'' when he happens to be head
of a subcommittee that regulates home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   _ He turns out to have voted for a congressional pay raise after
all. Recently Lazio told The Washington Post it was because the
bill included a provision that would help find missing children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last week Lazio skipped a close vote on a bill to create a
home heating oil reserve for the Northeast to rush home to
campaign. A spokesman said he needed to catch the last shuttle out.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times recently revealed that in 1997 Lazio made
an uncharacteristically risky investment in stock options in a
company that was controlled by some of his contributors. He
realized a 600 percent gain after it became a takeover target two
weeks later. ``Some stocks you get lucky on and some you're unlucky
on,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   This was all in the last week or so _ a Senate campaign start-up
worthy of the early Hillary Clinton. There was also a flap over a
CBS report in which Lazio vowed to run a clean campaign without
acting like ``a pansy.'' When a gay journalist objected, the Lazio
campaign said he was referring to the flower.
</P>
<P>
   I think I am speaking for everyone in saying that it was a
relief when Lazio stopped dragging his family up and down the
Northeast Corridor. But you'd think he'd have hung around to
support that heating oil bill and taken the opportunity to get
re-acquainted with the federal highway system. (Defenders quickly
pointed out that five members of the New York City delegation also
left before the vote. But the New York City delegation, which has
the average intelligence of a large turnip, is not the ideal we
want to shoot for.)
</P>
<P>
   If you win your seat by running pictures of the incumbent Jet
Skiing in the Caribbean, as Lazio did in 1992, you really should
not let the Developers Tax Credit Conference fly you to Florida, as
he did in 1999. And a guy like Lazio, who never made a fancy
investment until he was appointed to two committees that regulate
the securities industry, must have known this was not the time to
start playing the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   At minimum, he ruined his chance to make an issue of Clinton's
cattle futures deal. At worst, he opened the door for us to point
out that Jimmy Stewart would have put his investments in a blind
trust.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
