<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: DE GAULLE RUNNING
</P>
<P>
   The head of the far-right National Front, Jean-Marie Le Pen,
announced that the grandson of Charles de Gaulle will head a list
of candidates vying to represent the 20 districts of Paris in
municipal elections next year. Le Pen said he was proud to be able
to count on such an ``emblematic figure'' as the grandson, also
called Charles de Gaulle. Other family members have been outraged
at de Gaulle's affiliation with the National Front, a party long
accused of fostering racism and anti-Semitism. De Gaulle, a lawyer,
already represents the party in the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: SECT CRACKDOWN
</P>
<P>
   The National Assembly has unanimously passed a bill to make it
easier to crack down on sects. The legislation, which still has to
pass the Senate, creates a specific criminal offense of ``mental
manipulation,'' or brainwashing. It also sets up procedures for
courts to ban a group regarded as a sect and it provides for sects,
as well as individual members, to be punished for fraud, illegal
practice of medicine, wrongful advertising or sexual abuse. The
bill has set off protests by the Church of Scientology and the
Unification Church among others.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL'S `GAFFE'
</P>
<P>
   Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl was accused of trivializing the
Nazi persecution of the Jews after he compared it to his treatment
by the ruling Social Democratic government. In a television
interview, Kohl said calls for a boycott of his fund-raising
campaign to pay for fines imposed on the Christian Democrats for
his acceptance of secret donations resembled the Nazi-era boycott
of Jewish shops. Jewish leaders said this was an ``inexcusable
gaffe,'' and politicians called the comparison ``horrendous'' and
``incredibly embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: ROYAL UPKEEP
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers spent $22 million maintaining royal palaces last year,
a saving of $1.2 million from 1998. An auditors' report itemized
the upkeep costs on Buckingham Palace; Windsor Castle; St. James'
Palace, where Prince Charles has his office and London apartments;
Clarence House, home of the Queen Mother; and Kensington Palace,
former home of Princess Diana. Sir John Bourn, the chief auditor,
noted some delays and overruns but said, in general, ``They are
managing this work well.''
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: ARMY MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   A British Army band will perform in Dublin today for the first
time since Irish independence from British rule in 1921. The
appearance at a charity event was seen by London and Dublin as a
sign of improved British-Irish relations, but Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army, said it would protest
outside the hall.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: KREMLIN CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   An investigating magistrate said he plans to indict five people
next week in a continuing inquiry into possible bribery to win
lucrative Kremlin renovation contracts. The magistrate said he
would indict two heads of construction firms based in Lugano. Also
to be charged will be a Geneva lawyer and two asset managers. The
charges follow the indictment of former President Boris Yeltsin's
Kremlin property manager.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: STUDENT CLASHES
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 people were hurt in clashes at the National
Autonomous University of Mexico after a rally for Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas Solorzano, a left-leaning presidential candidate. Students
who supported a recent strike at the university attacked Cardenas
followers with burning flags, paint, eggs and chicken entrails,
causing a 10-minute brawl.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: REBEL PLEDGE
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista guerrillas announced that they will not disrupt
voting in Chiapas State in July 2 elections. In an open letter,
Subcomandante Marcos, the Zapatista leader, acknowledged that
elections are part of the democratic process. In legislative
elections in 1997, Zapatistas did not allow polling stations in
areas they control.
</P>
</TEXT>
