<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONTHEJOB-MESSAGES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MESSAGES THAT GOT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., Fla.)   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without question, modern technology, notably in the form of the
telephone, voice mail, e-mail and the fax, has speeded
communication. Whether it has enhanced communication is another
matter. As these anecdotes indicate, haste continues to make waste,
chips prove no substitute for the human brain and many an
ill-considered word find an unintended audience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janice M. Cauwels, a writer and consultant in Maywood, N.J., ran
into a problem when she was assisting a celebrity on a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had picked the worst possible time to contact a renowned
academic psychiatrist and ask him to double-check a chapter on
eating disorders that I had rewritten,'' Cauwels recalls.
``Impossibly busy anyway, he was preparing for two major
conferences only a few weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faxed my material to the psychiatrist, then followed up with
notes repeatedly apologizing for the inconvenience. Upon returning
to my office a few days later, I found a long voice-mail message
from him, indicating that my write-up was fine. I was one of a
`steamed group of people,' he added in what sounded like his
typical vernacular, who had been trying to reach him without
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent a thank-you note mentioning my surprise that he thought
I was angry, despite my expressed regrets for bothering him at a
bad time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back came a highly amused reply: More careful enunciation
would have made clear that actually I belonged to `an esteemed
group,' hence his prompt attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a business acquaintance who relies heavily on voice
recognition and e-mail to do his job,'' writes Jay Vivian of
Stamford, Conn. ``A year or two ago, I received a broadcast e-mail
from him addressed to about seven of us, obviously a distribution
list of people who shared an interest in investment risk
management. After discussing some ideas, he proposed a work plan
and then suggested that we get together to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``His note concluded, `I think it would be a good idea for us to
get enemas all together. Hope you agree.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that he had said into his voice recognition
microphone, `I think it would be a good idea to get en masse, all
together,' but his voice recognition software was not familiar with
the French phrase and had replaced it with the closest match in its
dictionary. He had proofread it quickly and missed the replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent it back to him, suggesting that this was an unusual way
to evaluate ideas. He was mortified.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A colleague and I had a complicated task to complete, and our
manager decided we could do it best off site, in the quiet of my
colleague's home,'' writes Nancy Cheser of Naples, Fla., recalling
her days as a systems analyst in Springfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two days of working, I phoned my manager, who I thought
was doing a particularly poor job of coordinating the project, to
give him a status report on our work. He was not at his desk, so I
left a message on his voice mail. I was using my colleague's
cordless phone and put it down on the desk. I then proceeded to
give a detailed rehashing of my complaints against my manager to my
co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, when Cheser returned to her office, she says:
``My manager approached me and asked me to step out into the
corridor. Apparently I had not turned off the cordless phone, and
my rampage was recorded, along with my status report, on his phone
mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I expected him to be angry, he was more concerned that
I had not approached him in person with my dissatisfaction. I still
cringe when I remember our walk in the hall.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lest all blame for miscommunication fall upon modern technology,
leave it to Horace Hone, a retired aircraft engineer in Palm Coast,
Fla., to note that this electronic age has no monopoly on
transmissions gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``A devastating example of a garbled message occurred long
before voice mail, e-mail, etc., and it ruined the day for every
British subject,'' he writes. ``After the Battle of Waterloo, a
cross-Channel transmission, probably by semaphore, was received at
Dover, saying `Wellington Defeated.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, maybe fog, no further details were
forthcoming. But a one-word continuation of the message the next
day changed gloom to jubilation. The word was `Napoleon.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lesson here,'' Hone concludes. ``Be careful how you
draft your communications.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
