<HEADER>
A2060 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NADER-LABOR-ART-2TAKE     06-22 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-LABOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADER'S POPULARITY WITH LABOR POSES THIRD-PARTY THREAT TO GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Months after they dismissed Ralph Nader as a fringe
third-party candidate who would fade quickly, Democratic and
Republican strategists now say that the consumer advocate has
emerged as more politically potent than Pat Buchanan and could
deeply complicate the candidacy of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, who is expected to capture the Green Party's nomination
in Denver this weekend, is in single digits in most polls. No one
thinks he has a chance of rising to the electoral heights of Ross
Perot, who in 1992 won 19 percent of the vote. And few people
predict that he will reach the 15 percent threshold required to
assure a spot in the nationally televised candidate debates this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Nader already is forcing Gore to compete more
vigorously for the enthusiastic support of labor and other groups
that are reliably Democratic. And many pollsters and analysts said
that in a tight general election race with Gov. George W. Bush, a
few points could make a difference _ and force Gore to reconsider
his electoral calculations in important states.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where Gore is running comfortably ahead, a Field
Poll this week showed Nader drawing 7 percent of the vote. He is
also showing strength in Oregon, Washington and New Mexico. In a
close race, he could also potentially tip the balance in Ohio,
Michigan and other battleground states of the Midwest. A Quinnipiac
University poll in Connecticut this week showed he had 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling for some Democrats is that Nader, who has
ridiculed Gore and Bush as sounding identical and has emphasized
his own record as a consumer and environmental advocate, is
becoming more and more popular with labor. By campaigning
aggressively against the China trade deal, which passed in the
House last month, Nader has effectively capitalized on labor's
distress with Gore for his support of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Nader has made the vice president battle for a
constituency that his campaign thought it could count on. In fact,
pollsters say that most of Nader's backers are not the swing voters
that Gore needs to win over, but staunch Democrats that should
already be on his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush people, I'm sure, are thrilled about Nader,'' said
one of Gore's most senior aides.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's potential for trouble was on display here on Thursday,
when James P. Hoffa, the Teamsters president, appeared beside him
at a news conference and ridiculed the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no distinction between Al Gore and George W. Bush
when it comes to trade,'' Hoffa asserted after Nader met privately
with the Teamsters' 24-member executive board. He added that Gore
was ``wrong on trade'' and that ``We agree wholeheartedly with what
Mr. Nader has said.'' Nader won a standing ovation from the board
members.
</P>
<P>
   Imploring the audience to take him seriously, Nader said,
``People are always asking, `Am I worried about taking votes away
from Gore?' No. I'm worried about Gore taking votes away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers said they have moved aggressively behind the
scenes to try to keep Hoffa from endorsing Nader, to the point
where they have directed projects through federal agencies that
would use Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts may be paying off _ at least for now. ``We're not
going to hurry to endorse,'' Hoffa said on Thursday. But even Gore
aides said a Teamsters endorsement of the vice president seems
increasingly less likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have options of endorsing or not endorsing,'' Hoffa added.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harry Reid of Nevada, the assistant Democratic leader who
is a Gore loyalist, contacted several labor leaders on Thursday,
discouraging them from defecting to Nader. In an interview, he
bluntly condemned Nader as a spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph Nader is a very selfish person and he's on an ego
trip,'' Reid said. ``He has no respect for the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, most political strategists viewed Buchanan as
the biggest third-party threat _ and a potentially big problem for
Bush. He has run twice for the Republican presidential nomination,
even winning the critical New Hampshire primary in 1996. And if he
wins the backing of the Reform Party, whose nomination he is
seeking, he would draw $12.6 million in federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Buchanan's windfall, strategists now say Nader has a
greater potential impact on the race because polls show that he
takes his support almost exclusively from Gore. Buchanan, with
backing both from protectionist Democrats and conservative
Republicans, does not appear to have as much potential to wound
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Buchanan gets the Reform Party nomination, he is
weakened because many in that party do not like him. And despite
Buchanan's staunch position against free trade, many unions see
Nader as more of a soulmate because, unlike Buchanan, he is not
conservative on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Nader is a far more popular figure than the
controversial Buchanan. Fifty percent of registered voters have a
negative view of Buchanan, while only 15 percent have a negative
view of Nader, according to an NBC News/Wall Street Journal Poll
taken June 14-18. The poll found that 12 percent had a positive
view of Buchanan, while 33 percent had a positive view of Nader.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to be Al Gore looking at the third-party horizon
this year,'' said J. David Gillespie, a political scientist at
Presbyterian College in Clinton. S.C., who is an authority on
third-party candidacies. ``Nader's draw in key states may be very
crucial in determining the outcome of this election.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of the Gore and Bush campaigns thus far has been to
ignore Nader and Buchanan _ and not do anything to raise their
profile. That is why during the primaries, Bush did not join Sen.
John McCain in condemning writings by Buchanan that some Jewish
groups derided as anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, the national chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, echoing some Gore advisers, insisted that he was not at
all unsettled by Nader. ``I'm not worried about it,'' he said. ``It
doesn't make much difference if Ralph Nader is an angel or not:
people aren't going to throw their votes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Most voters, he said, do not know much about Nader _ and his
backers will sour on him when they realize he is just ``a human
being'' and not a loftier figure. ``He's reached his high point
right now,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   A strategist for Gore put it this way: ``In June, you're wasting
your energy if you worry about these things. In October, it would
be worrisome.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster, said Nader has a better
chance of holding on to his support than Buchanan because ``the
Nader voter tends to be a higher educated group of voters'' who are
less likely to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goeas, like many Republicans, said he knows not to
underestimate Buchanan, who has a history of surprising his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the grant Buchanan will get if he is the Reform
Party nominee, he said, ``Twelve million dollars is not a huge
megaphone. But it's a megaphone. And any time Pat Buchanan gets a
megaphone, that can be dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
