<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2065 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOKS-$ADV25-NYT &LR;      06-22 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATING THE TALKERS FROM THE DOERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By FRED ANDREWS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Knowing-Doing Gap: How Smart Companies Turn Knowledge into
Action'
</P>
<P>
   By Jeffrey Pfeffer and Robert I. Sutton
</P>
<P>
   Boston, Harvard Business School Press, 2000
</P>
<P>
   Why can't companies get off the dime? Jeffrey Pfeffer and Robert
Sutton have studied the ways of business for decades, and they come
away puzzled as to why so many companies fail to act on what they
know. Too often, the solution to a business problem is obvious to
all, yet the company can't bring itself to seize the nettle.
</P>
<P>
   In their pragmatic book, ``The Knowing-Doing Gap'' (Harvard
Business School Press, $27.50) Pfeffer and Sutton offer the voice
of experience about companies that know what to do but just can't.
Some businesses mistake talk for action; they perfect their plans
and presentations, yet no one follows up. And some enterprises are
too happy, creating a bliss that no one wants to disturb with
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Still others get locked in the past, sometimes because their
identities are too strong to adapt. A great many businesses are
chilled by a climate of fear that discourages feedback and
paralyzes initiative. Many, if not most, enterprises rely on faulty
yardsticks of performance, favoring financial measures that do not
truly capture their businesses. And most companies routinely do
business in a way that divides the work force and discourages
employees from cooperating with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Like most business books, ``The Knowing-Doing Gap'' instructs
mainly by example, supported here and there by hard data. The book
offers judgments, case histories, impressions, surmise. The ``gap''
is the difference between what a company knows and what it does.
The reader must take on faith that the gap is indeed pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   The book does seem a touch dated. It discusses downsizing but
not the Internet and the new economy. The argument also lacks the
surprise and paradox of the research by Clayton Christensen, the
Harvard Business School professor, about adapting to technology.
Christensen found that smart companies often missed out on emerging
technologies not because they were lax, but rather because they
were obsessed with serving their best customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the book's judgments are good, the examples
instructive, the advice sensible, the thesis tightly argued.
Business readers will find that the shoe fits. Many will agree with
one finding in particular: ``There is far more talk than action
about using enlightened management techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors teach organizational behavior at Stanford
University, Pfeffer in the business school and Sutton in the
engineering school. They are prolific authors of books, papers and
case studies.
</P>
<P>
   True to thesis, they declare up front that reading a book, their
book or any other, is never enough _ that one has to know how to
act upon it. Their book concludes on the same note: ``This knowing
is insufficient. Action must occur.'' And the authors never leave a
topic without prescribing seven or eight steps that companies can
take.
</P>
<P>
   Their favorite enterprises include the Men's Wearhouse, a
clothing chain that puffs up its sales staff as ``wardrobe
consultants'' and insists that the employees help one another; SAS
Institute, the software company famous for its peerless benefits
and working conditions; AES, the global electric power producer,
which operates with minimal headquarters staff and expects its
units to solve their own problems; and numerous others, from Sears,
Roebuck to Intuit, Southwest Airlines, British Petroleum, Barclays
Global Investors and even the New Zealand post office.
</P>
<P>
   As the authors pick apart the failings afflicting other
companies, their own theory of the workplace emerges, chapter by
chapter. It centers on employee satisfaction and appears to mark
employee opinion as the single most important gauge of progress.
They admire Intuit, for example, which closely monitors its
employees' assessment of whether the enterprise is living up to its
values.
</P>
<P>
   In their ideal workplace, no boss would be vindictive, and the
only failure would be a failure to act. People would feel free to
take chances and make mistakes, even colossal ones. Co-workers
would cooperate to the utmost, with all their considerable juices
focused on the competition. Anyone who pursued only his own
short-term interest would be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The authors argue that even in a knowledge economy, no company
can sustain a a competitive edge simply from what it knows. The
marketplace in ideas is too efficient; the best business ideas get
around too fast. Businesses must succeed with superior execution _
by doing rather than knowing. Famed competitors like Toyota show
off their techniques to all comers, yet no one else ever appears to
match their performance.
</P>
<P>
   They also conclude that businesses do not excel at learning. If
they did, then all their branches would perform uniformly well, by
borrowing the best practices from their sister units. Yet oil
companies commonly find one refinery three times as efficient as
another. Fast-food chains live with huge differences in their
outlets' profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Some barriers to action are universal. Even the way people
handle themselves in daily corporate discourse sets up a bias
against action. When judged by others, one naturally wants to
appear smart, and negative people are consistently judged to be the
smartest. The authors cite a 1983 Harvard study of reactions to
book reviews: ``Only pessimism sounds profound,'' it found.
``Optimism sounds superficial.'' They warn that a company can wind
up with a collection of ``clever put-down artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors say that among the unsuccessful companies they
studied, they found ``a pervasive atmosphere of fear and
distrust.'' People were afraid to make mistakes, hesitant to speak
the truth. They learned to keep their heads down and to mind their
own business.
</P>
<P>
   The authors suggest some steps to expel fear and distrust:
Praise and promote people who are willing to deliver bad news to
the boss. Learn from, even celebrate, mistakes; encourage leaders
to talk about their mistakes and the lessons learned. Give people
second (and third) chances. Banish people, especially leaders, who
humiliate others. Don't punish people for trying something new.
</P>
<P>
   Yet exorcising fear can be difficult to accept. Many people
believe that a boss is supposed to be demanding. Shouldn't his or
her wrath count for something? Jack Welch of General Electric did
not become ``Neutron Jack'' by handing out cupcakes. And the
authors acknowledge the strong feelings of Andrew Grove, the Intel
chairman, that fear _ fear of the competitor, fear of failure _ is
essential in fueling a passion for winning in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitiously, the authors would root out intramural competition
from the office. Competition, they say, is by its nature divisive,
pitting employee against employee and encouraging individuals to
pursue personal gain at the expense of larger, shared goals. So
they would eliminate employee recognition awards, as well as public
rankings of top performers, contests among departments or
individuals, merit raises from a small pool _ anything in which the
winners are few and everyone else is pronounced a loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing well is not the same as winning,'' they write.
``Dominating others in a zero-sum contest is just one form of
success.'' They believe that people can achieve high goals by
working cooperatively. But they acknowledge that it is tough to
persuade companies that competition is bad when the people at the
top have been winning competitions all their lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
