<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-DANCERS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCERS WHO DARE TO OWN THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, La., Pa., N.C., Brazil, France, Romania)  (Editors: RhythMEK is cq.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What makes a dancer stand out from the crowd? A
dazzling technique helps, though multiple turns and high jumps are
par for the course today. Beautiful bodies and appealing faces draw
the eye. But stages are full of performers who fit the prescribed
notion of physical perfection. There are so many dancers to claim
the heart and mind and eye, yet only a few do each season.
</P>
<P>
   Ease, physical eloquence and quiet daring are common
denominators among seven outstanding new or unfamiliar performers
who will dance this weekend in New York, as well as the three
former Alvin Ailey dancers whose new modern-dance troupe has made
its debut this week at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in the
Berkshires. All occupy the stage with a look of unassuming
ownership. Each catches the eye with something more than skill or
physical beauty, an often elusive quality that remains in the mind,
like a flash of bright unexpected color on a bustling city street,
long after the curtain falls.
</P>
<P>
   Take Hope L. Boykin, who performs with Philadanco at the Joyce
Theater this weekend. Boykin would be the first to admit that she
does not have a typical dance body. Compact and round, she was told
for years that she would never become a dancer. Onstage, however,
she is so fully engaged in every moment of dancing that the vibrant
performing around her pales a little in comparison. Adam
Hendrickson has a strong, often dazzling technique, but it is the
undercurrent of sly subversiveness in his dancing that makes him
fascinating. Janie Taylor, like Hendrickson a City Ballet corps
dancer who is cast in major parts, brings a fugitive, synesthetic
perfume to all that she dances.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Thomas scorched the stage with his quiet intensity
during his years with the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.
Elizabeth Roxas was a cool, still, lyrical center of the Ailey
storm. Karine Plantadit-Bageot's dancing was suffused with an
understated wit. The three dancers see their new company RhythMEK _
a name formed in part from the first initials of their own given
names _ as a response to their lives in dance.
</P>
<P>
   At American Ballet Theater, which seems to have more than its
share of attention-grabbing young performers, four corps dancers
stood out this season in a variety of roles. Sean Stewart is the
rare classical dancer who is equally believable and
committed-looking in modern dance and ballet. Like Stewart, Michele
Wiles seems to extend and expand everything she dances so that the
shape of a step or gesture and the line of her body and its
rhythmic response to music look unbounded. Herman Cornejo brings
out the fine detail in choreography without fussiness, his quick
light attack making the most of every moment. Although Marcelo
Gomes is Brazilian, he looks like the quintessential American
classicist, a dancer who just dances, big and boldly, without a
hint of ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   How did they get where they are today? Each has a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   MARCELO GOMES
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo Gomes, who has just been promoted to soloist, began his
training at 6, studying jazz dance at a school in Manaus, in
northwest Brazil, where he was born. ``I was always dancing around
the kitchen and living room,'' Gomes, who is 20, he said. ``My
parents thought dance classes would be nice as an activity thing.''
By 9, when he had begun training with Helena Lobato and Dalal
Aschar in Rio de Janeiro, Gomes knew he wanted to be a ballet
dancer. ``Not anything else, and that was that,'' he said,
laughing. ``My family had been 100 per cent there for me. Always,
always.''
</P>
<P>
   He studied at the Harid Conservatory in Boca Raton, Fla., for
three years before leaving for a year's study at the Paris Opera
Ballet school on a Prix de Lausanne scholarship. ``I wanted to go
there because of the great tradition and training. I learned French
a little bit and ate some cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined Ballet Theater in 1997. ``I love the repertory. I love
the classical stuff, Petipa, everything about it. But contemporary
ballet and modern dance is very important for a dancer. You have to
be able to roll on the floor and then the next day become a
prince.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his big, unadorned way of dancing, Gomes said that
Brazilian dancers tend to be exaggerated about their technique but
they also give their all. ``I do that,'' he said. ``Maybe the
bigness is what Brazil gave me. In Paris, they cleaned me up. I
felt so confident about my dancing afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he will not be repeating his performance of one of
two major male roles in ``Etudes,'' Gomes recommends seeing the
Harald Lander ballet on Ballet Theater's closing weekend at the
Metropolitan Opera House, June 30 and July 1. ``If you really like
ballet, it's a great way of seeing how ballet technique has
developed.'' He is moved, he said, watching the journey from basic
tendus or foot stretches to bravura dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes will be seen in Twyla Tharp's new ``Brahms-Haydn
Variations'' on closing night, July 1. ``Twyla's stuff is very
hard, even though it looks like we're having a hell of a time.
Everything needs to be very precise in the big group. If we're not
together, you can really see it. But it is enjoyable. You can get a
lot from working with Twyla. And we're at the point now where we
have fun with the ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   HERMAN CORNEJO
</P>
<P>
   Herman Cornejo, also just promoted to soloist, began ballet at 8
in his native Buenos Aires, where he was accepted two years later
into the Teatro Colon school. ``At first it was like a game, but
when I got into Teatro Colon I knew that I loved to dance,''
Cornejo, who is 19, said. ``I just loved the music.'' His first
ballet hero was Maximiliano Guerra. ``I loved him. He jumped a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornejo, who himself has one of those dream jumps that seem to
pause at the top and hover in mid-air, was spotted by Julio Bocca
for his Ballet Argentina troupe. In 1997 Bocca entered his young
dancer in the international ballet competition in Moscow, where he
won a gold medal in 1995 in the senior category even though he was
only 15. In 1998, Cornejo joined Ballet Theater, where his sister
Erica, another promising newcomer, also dances.
</P>
<P>
   He will perform the Bronze Idol in ``La Bayadere'' on Saturday
night. ``Wow, that variation is amazing,'' Cornejo said of his
solo, a killer exercise in pyrotechnics. He may also be seen in the
Tharp ballet. Sean Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Sean Stewart dances with the silken restraint and fastidiousness
of English ballet classicism. His performing suggests that dancing
is, for him, a great private pleasure that he is willing to share
with his audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The unforced fullness of his dancing allows him to let the
choreography grow and breathe with him on the stage, an ability he
put to revelatory use this season as the Fourth Man in Martha
Graham's ``Diversion of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart started training in ballet at 12 to improve his jazz
dance technique. Dance _ both frequent performing as a child and
the physical demands even classes made _ was an escape from
problems at school in his hometown of Vacaville, in northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's face shines with that delight in the physicality of
dance when he talks of the energy of favorite ballets like
``Etudes'' and George Balanchine's ``Theme and Variations,'' in
which he will dance next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to New York City at 15 to perform for two years with
the Joffrey II ballet, the Joffrey Ballet's junior ensemble, then
went to Paris for a year on his own to study at the Paris Opera
Ballet school. ``I just wanted to see a different kind of traning
and work on my technique,'' Stewart, who is 21, recalled.
Performing in Ballet Theater, which he joined in 1997, was ``kind
of like a big fantasy, the place to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other dreams are to dance Romeo and the slave in ``Le
Corsaire.'' ``It's really soft and powerful,'' he said of the
latter role, describing neatly his own look. ``And Romeo is so
free, the character and the movement.''
</P>
<P>
   MICHELE WILES
</P>
<P>
   Like Stewart, Michele Wiles started ballet training to improve
her jazz dance technique. She still takes jazz classes to loosen up
stiff muscles. Wiles enrolled at 10 in the Kirov Academy of Ballet
in Washington. Soon after, dancing in a children's role in ``Swan
Lake'' with the Royal Ballet of London at the Kennedy Center for
the Performing Arts, she knew she wanted to dance ballet
professionally. ``I guess because the ballerina is put on such a
pedestal,'' she said. Wiles, who has just been promoted to soloist,
joined Ballet Theater in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She will dance the third solo in the ``Kingdom of the Shades''
scene in ``La Bayadere'' tonight, tomorrow afternoon and on
Tuesday. ``It's one of the most difficult variations,'' Wile said.
``So slow and controlled. You have to be right on your leg. And you
can't make any mistakes. It shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiles, who is 20, has won a number of jazz dance and ballet
awards, among them a gold medal at the international competition in
Varna, Bulgaria, in 1996. It takes aplomb to compete, and hers
shows in all that she dances. She likes to become someone else on
the stage, she said, and feel a part of a fantasy. But her primary
goal is ``to give people a good show.'' ``I want them to see how
I'm enjoying myself. I'm happy in what I do. I don't even think
about it, I just let my body do it.''
</P>
<P>
   RhythMEK
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that I was bored altogether with what I was doing
and what was out there for me,'' Karine Plantadit-Bageot said with
a throaty laugh when asked why she helped to found RhythMEK. ``I
was always very interested to see if dancers could actually
collaborate and change the recipe arond a little bit.'' Her
sentiments were not unlike those of Michael Thomas and Elizabeth
Roxas. All had performed with the Ailey troupe in the 1980s and
'90s, leaving at the same time in 1998. All went on to perform
freelance with other modern troupes, a ballroom company and on
Broadway. Plantadit-Bageot is on leave from ``Saturday Night
Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   The character of the company and its repertory evolved through
endless get-togethers in the dancers' apartments. Roxas thought
initially of a company for dancers over 40, but their ages ranged
from 33 to 42. RhythMEK, it was decided, would show off its 12
dancers, who include the three founders and Desmond Richardson,
Elizabeth Parkinson, Sarita Allen and Roger Bellamy. They would be
seen initially in a suite of 7 dances created by a wide range of
choreographers. There is ballroom dance by Gary Pierce, Broadway
dance from Bill Hastings, jazz dance by Mia Michaels and modern
dance by Thomas, Zvi Gotheiner, Dwight Rhoden and Ulysses Dove, who
will be represented by excerpts from ``Episodes.''
</P>
<P>
   Roxas said of Dove: ``He'd say that `Episodes' was about
relationships in the moment, and then move on to the next stage,''
Roxas recalled. That seemed peculiarly appropriate for RhythMEK.
Collaborating with living choreographers has had its nervous
moments, she added. But such collaborations were a part of the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we actually do it?,'' Thomas remembered the three
dancers asking themselves early on. ``It's one thing to be a dancer
and totally another to be a director, especially when you're still
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worked so hard in my life. But this is ours, and it
feels so good. We know who we are and no one is trying to prove
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   JANIE TAYLOR
</P>
<P>
   Janie Taylor began her ballet studies at 4 with Gilbert Rome in
Houston, where she was born, and continued with Richard Rholden and
Joseph Giacobbe in New Orleans when her family moved there. At the
City Ballet-affiliated School of American Ballet, where she trained
in two summer sessions before enrolling full time, she was singled
out as the 1998 recipient of the Mae L. Wien Award for promising
students. That same year she joined City Ballet and soon attracted
attention in challenging featured roles like Dewdrop in ``The
Nutcracker'' and the doomed young girl in ``La Valse,'' both
choreographed by Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   She cherished the latter role. ``It's fun to do acting as well
as the dancing,'' Taylor, who is 19, said. ``And I get to die. It's
so creepy, watching the ballet from the front.'' Taylor will be
seen tonight in Peter Martins' new ``Harmonielehre,'' set to
famously difficult music by John Adams. She talks with relish of
the ballet's difficulties. ``The partnering is really awkward,
though my partner, Jared Angle, is amazing. Peter never really said
anything to all of us about it, but it seems to be about three
different worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor seems dubious when asked about her seemingly total
confidence on stage. ``I know you should look like you're
confident,'' she said. ``I always want to reach the audience,
affect them somehow, on some sort of level.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ADAM HENDRICKSON
</P>
<P>
   For Adam Hendrickson, dancing classical ballet has been more of
an internal struggle. First there was the battle to come to terms
with ballet after the ``boot camp'' experience of nine years at the
Central Pennsylvania Youth Ballet, where Hendrickson, a native of
Harrisburg, trained with Marcia Dale Weary. Next came the
relatively relaxed but still difficult demands of the School of
American Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Does he feel himself to be a dark or subversive presence on the
stage? ``Yeah,'' Hendrickson said, laughing. ``It's not so much the
ballet that I like doing, it's the energy that it requires. A lot
of my dancing is driven by anger rather than by love of it. It's
not that I'm not happy. That's just what it takes to get me going.
It's like proving _ well, I don't have anything to prove but it's
that mentality. I was always told my body's terrible, and I have
this whole short complex. I try to dance as big as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson, who is 19 and is a corps dancer like Taylor, joined
City Ballet in 1998. His sister Jessy, also considered promising,
dances with the company, too. He suffered through the misery that
hits new company members who have been acclaimed in school but now
have few challenges in the corps. Then he began to get featured
roles and was told by the company, though encouragingly, that he
would have to clean up his dancing and make it more classically
pure. Dancing the technically demanding role of Bluebird in
``Sleeping Beauty'' was his reward.
</P>
<P>
   Was there a moment when he realized he wanted to dance
professionally? ``When it happens, it's really weird. Dumb times,
like when I almost get hit by a cab. I think, Oh my God, this is my
body and that's what I use. My brain is almost worthless in my job.
I'm carrying around my whole career with me. Other people can leave
it in their computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Martins' new ``Harmonielehre,'' he adds, does require an active
brain. It is ``a cool ballet'' but difficult because of its complex
score by John Adams: ``My calves are swollen from tapping my foot
to the music in the wings,'' he said, laughing. ``Trying to hear
the beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson will spend his week off, before City Ballet opens on
July 5 in Saratoga, teaching at the Central Pennsylvania Youth
Ballet. He talks of Stanley Williams, a much-admired teacher at the
School of American Ballet who died in 1997. ``I loved Stanley to no
end. I want to teach his way. If he hadn't been there, I wouldn't
be here. And just the struggle I had keeping things up after he
died that last year made me feel like I needed to go back home and
teach there.''
</P>
<P>
   HOPE L. BOYKIN
</P>
<P>
   Hope L. Boykin is, like Hendrickson, the rare dancer who loves
to teach. It was not a skill she noticed much as a student in
Nina's School of Dance in Durham, N.C., where she was born. She was
just happy that she, a black child with her share of baby fat, was
accepted as a dancer by Nina Wheeler, the school director, and her
teacher Jennifer Potts. They encouraged her to go on to the
American Dance Festival in Durham, where she trained on a work
scholarship and came to know and be influenced by such
choreographers as Pearl Primus, Talley Beatty and Donald McKayle.
</P>
<P>
   To calm her mother's worries about her interest in dancing, she
enrolled in Howard University, where she majored in psychology
before dropping out. ``I wanted to dance, but I didn't really know
it,'' Boykin, who is 28, recalled. She began performing with the
New World Dance Company in Washington and then came north to New
York City at the encouragement of Chris Freeman, a dancer who put
her up in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   She landed a job with Rhoden's Complexions company where,
dancing with Richardson, a dance hero of hers, she suddenly
understood that she wanted a career in dance. ``I was just having a
good time at Nina's,'' she said. ``At Ailey, I was just seeing how
far I could get. Four pirouettes tomorrow instead of three today.
But standing next to Desmond I thought, `I can do this. I could
live my life like this.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Boykin joined Philadanco, her first major dance troupe, six
years ago. She will leave after the Joyce season to join Ailey,
just in time for the Lincoln Center Festival. ``I learned so much
at Philadanco,'' she said regretfully. ``There is no dancing like
the dance there.'' Much of her life and those of other black
performers of her generation will be reflected in the program in
which she will perform. Called ``On the Shoulders of Our
Ancestors,'' it pays tribute to pioneers like McKayle and Primus
and Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   She attributes her look of being entirely present in the moment
to her struggles to become a dancer. ``When you see something you
like, take it, try to nurture it,'' Boykin said. ``Take everything
you've learned and lay it on the line. I also pray for guidance
before every show. I want people to know that it is not me but my
Lord that has helped me overcome the obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   She recognizes the same struggles in her students at the
University of the Arts in Philadelphia. ``I know that times are
hard for them. Dancers are a dime a dozen. You have to have your
special thing. A lot of them can't finish school, or have been told
they can't dance, that they are too heavy. I want them to know that
if they really want this, it's theirs. They can give it away but no
one can take it from them. They have brought me so much joy. They
made me know what I want to do after the dance is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Will these performers make it into the first ranks of dance? To
be a professional dancer in a major company is to sink or rise with
equal unexpectedness. Anna Liceica, a big-eyed and piquant
ballerina who arrived at Ballet Theater via the National Ballet
School in Bucharest in Romania and the City Ballet, was surprised
when she was summoned recently to the office of Kevin McKenzie,
Ballet Theater's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice of you to talk to each of your dancers during the
crazy Met season,'' she told McKenzie. But he had not called her in
for a chat, he said. Her heart sank. Was she about to get fired?
But the news was good, though a total surprise. She was being
promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work for it,'' Liceica said. ``It's your dream. But it's
not going to change much. It's nice to be acknowledged, but now
I'll work even harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
