<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2075 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MIDSTREAM-COLUMN-$ADV     06-22 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDSTREAM-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 OF EGGS AND SINGLE BASKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As baby boomers, we are getting a reputation. We take heat for
our questionable cell-phone habits, the big trucks we drive and our
overall obsession with money. Now investment advisers are shaking
their heads over how we invest. We are, they say, incredibly
risk-prone and oblivious to the lessons of history.
</P>
<P>
   We know that, of course, and it seems that many of us don't
care.
</P>
<P>
   But I do. I stubbornly hang on to my Coca-Cola and Disney stock,
refusing to dump these stodgy issues and invest in dot-coms. I own
Treasury bills. About 45 percent of my 401(k) account is in
money-market and bond funds, the remainder in a stock fund. I have
four children, and that makes me cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the rest of my generation, said Steven W. Kaye, president
of the American Economic Planning Group in Watchung, N.J. Kaye
advises many people my age and is amazed at the chances they take.
</P>
<P>
   ``No group in history has taken on the risks that the baby
boomer generation has,'' he said. ``People were more diversified in
the past. The generation just before the boomers had a high
concentration of health stocks, but nothing like the baby boomers
and their technology craze. The group as a whole doesn't seem to
care about risk as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mucciolo, 45, president of Medianet Inc., a Manhattan
company that teaches people how to make presentations, said he does
care _ but is confident that he has made the right choice. Almost
all of his investments are in stocks, and about 65 percent of those
are technology companies. Yes, he knows it's risky. Yes, he knows
he's not diversified. ``I'm banking on technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to an investment adviser, they'll say this guy
should have his head examined,'' Mucciolo added. ``But I'm
comfortable with the risk, because it is my risk. I have continual
earnings power and time to recover'' if the market falls.
</P>
<P>
   Howard S. Cohen, 49, a cardiologist in Warren, N.J., said he has
about 80 percent of his portfolio in technology stocks. Like
Mucciolo, he is confident in the sector, and in his ability to
recover from any downturn. Still, he said, his position makes him
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, I'm scared,'' he said about the spring meltdown in the
Nasdaq. ``When the stock market takes a 30 percent correction, and
I'm looking at my savings taking a 30 percent hit, it's very
unsettling.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he watches the market closely and that he would
become more conservative if the market fell into an extended
decline, an event he conceded he has never experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye says that is part of the problem. ``Older people have a
better chance of remembering 1972 through '74,'' he said. ``Boomers
can't conceive that the S&AMP;P could lose 50 percent over a three-year
period. We're seeing them not being afraid to put 70 percent of
their money in technology, because they think that's where the
entire future is. They don't realize that there have been other
booms and busts, like oil stocks in the early 1980's.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some boomers had another habit: loading up exclusively
on their employer's stock, leaving them doubly vulnerable if their
company falters.
</P>
<P>
   Diane M. Hogan, 43, of Flemington, N.J. accepted that risk with
her company, Charles Schwab, which at one time made up most of her
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   She bought the stock through the employee stock plan, and
although she said many friends thought she was crazy, she stuck
with the strategy for more than a decade. When she left Schwab last
year, the value of her stock had grown to about $4 million. It's
hard to point fingers when a strategy works. ``I don't want to say
that it was dumb luck, but I just left it there and forgot about
it,'' she said. ``I never thought that I would become a
multimillionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   She has since sold much of the Schwab stock, but she remains
about 70 percent invested in equities _ although in a more diverse
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very risky person,'' she said. ``I sort of feel that you
have to take some chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with my money, I don't. Those four college educations I'm
facing chase me to work every day, and I'm not about to start
playing with the money I've worked so hard to put aside. When my
T-bills mature, I'm planning to roll them over, not put the money
in the latest start-up. I don't have the stomach for what Mucciolo
thinks is fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game itself is the excitement, more than the actual
reward,'' he said. ``If every stock went up 1,000 percent, would I
stop playing? No, because it's about the activity, not the result
of the activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Cohen said: ``It's almost like going on a roller-coaster.
You look forward to it, it's scary, but if you get through it
successfully, it was quite a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, I hate roller-coasters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
