<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-SPI &LR;      06-22 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH INSISTS NO INNOCENTS EXECUTED `ON MY WATCH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, in an interview hours
before the scheduled execution of convicted murderer Gary Graham,
insisted Thursday that ``under my watch'' no innocent person has
been put to death in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's claim of innocence had been ``looked at a lot'' at all
levels of the court system, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has approved 132 executions while issuing only a
single 30-day stay since he became governor in 1995, said he wants
to know about DNA evidence when it is available because ``we should
be very careful in death penalty cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican presidential candidate said he was not swayed
by the Scripps Howard Texas Poll published Thursday in which 57
percent of Texans said they believe innocent people have been
executed, nor moved in the Graham case by the fact that ``we've got
two or three jurors who say they're not sure anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all being weighed out, there is a process in the state
of Texas,'' Bush said in an interview that was conducted just
before the Texas parole board rejected Graham's clemency appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man had access to, gosh, I want to say 30 different
judges,'' Bush said. ``This is a case that has had full analyzation
and has been looked at a lot. I understand the emotionality of
death penalty cases. A lot of people did not support the death
penalty. I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Texas scheduled to execute an average of one man a week
through Election Day, the death penalty has become a campaign issue
that won't go away for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators dogged Bush throughout his three-day campaign tour
of the West Coast this week, but he shruged off any consequences
the Graham execution could pose to his bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent 45 minutes Thursday fielding questions from a small
group of reporters. He commented on topics ranging from fan
violence at baseball games to his very private search for a vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   He touched on Northwest regional environmental issues, accusing
the Clinton administration of wanting to breach four dams on the
lower Snake River, and saying that Vice President Al Gore refuses
to take a stand on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salmon runs in the lower Columbia are the highest they've
been in years,'' Bush said. He said the government ``should not
destroy the whole way of life in Eastern Washington and Eastern
Oregon'' to restore threatened fish populations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, former part-owner of the Texas Rangers, gave reporters a
brief tour of his private office, proudly displaying two cabinets
filled with autographed baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   He said he agrees with the stiff fines and penalties handed out
by baseball's new enforcer, former Major Leaguer Frank Robinson.
``I believe in discipline,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With the eyes of the nation on Texas, however, Bush found
himself defending his exercise of life-and-death responsibility in
a state that executed 35 prisoners in 1999 and has more than 450
people on its death row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've reviewed every case and I'm confident no innocent person
has been put to death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was convicted and sentenced to death for killing a man
during a 1981 supermarket robbery, based on the testimony of a
single eyewitness. He was represented by Ronald Mock, an attorney
who has been disciplined five times. Mock has defended 19 capital
murder cases in which 16 of the defendants have been sentenced to
death. Three of the defendants have been executed while Bush was
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Two eyewitnesses to the 1981 murder have said the killer did not
fit Graham's appearance. ``The prosecutor gave the names and
addresses to defense counsel and they were never investigated and
never testified in a court of law,'' Jack Zimmerman, Graham's
appellate lawyer, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted that the Board of Pardons and Parole was carefully
weighing all evidence, including new evidence given by a court
bailiff. ``The bailiff said, `Well, on the way out of court, Gary
Graham said next time there won't be any living witnesses','' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he welcomes the debate over the death penalty,
believes it is ``healthy for democracy,'' and that it is ``fine''
that people have traveled to Texas to protest the execution of
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their right for people to come to express their opinion,
but I'm going to uphold the law,'' Bush said. ``I'm sworn to uphold
the law. It's my job and I'm going to uphold the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposed a 1999 legislative proposal to ban the execution of
defendants who were mentally retarded, and opposed legislation that
would have required the pardons board to put on public meetings in
cases of clemency requests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has vetoed bills requiring appointment of counsel for
indigent defendants within 20 days, and a bill that allowed
counties to take the power to appoint defense attorneys from
elected judges who have been accused of naming political cronies.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty has wide support in Texas. The Texas Poll
showed 73 percent of Texans backing executions even while, by a
57-23 ratio, believing that innocent defendants have been put to
death in the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Bush appeared highly committed to maintaining
states' rights and prerogatives when it comes to the prosecution of
high-profile crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Askd if he would support the bipartisan Innocence Protection Act
_ a U.S. Senate bill that gives a federal right to DNA testing in
death penalty cases _ Bush said he is not familar enough with
provisions of the bill to take a stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is DNA evidence relative to the particulars of a
case, I want to know,'' he said. Bush noted DNA questions in the
one case in which he has issued a stay of execution, for a man
named Ricky McGinn convicted for the 1993 rape and murder of his
12-year-old stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes that McGinn clearly committed the murder,
but that new tests could bring his exoneration on the rape
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush voiced reservations about legislation, which passed the
Senate earlier this week, providing for an expanded federal role in
prosecuting hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some misgivings and the main misgiving is that the
federal government overrides, (resulting in) the federalization of
criminal laws at the state level,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the bill would help states like Texas
prosecute hate crimes, the Byrd case is a good example, I would
appreciate federal help in the prosecution of hate crimes,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to the case of James Byrd Jr., a black man
who was dragged to his death behind a pickup truck in Jasper,
Texas. The state provided financial aid to the rural county that
successfully prosecuted his killers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead over Gore has been growing in recent public opinion
polls, but he said the gains haven't gone to his head. ``I'm not
even close to thinking about a Cabinet,'' he said. ``I haven't even
won.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that he has a ``judgment and vision'' lacking in Gore,
and proposals for reform of Social Security and education that will
sustain the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a tough competitor, by the way,'' he added. ``That's what
the primaries showed, that I could take a punch and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he takes seriously statements by his presidential
rival Sen. John McCain that he does not want to be considered for
the vice presidency, and retired Gen. Colin Powell's statement that
he is ``genuinely not interested'' in the No. 2 spot on the GOP
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   On the selection of a running mate, Bush added, ``There's only
three people who know what's going on: Dick, myself and my wife.''
Former Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney is in charge of vetting
potential GOP vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave a philosophical answer when asked about what
punishment he would suppport if abortion were once again made
illegal in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission is to encourage respect for life,'' Bush replied.
He said such respect should extend not just to the unborn, but to
the elderly and children in schools who have been victims of
indiscriminate violence.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Bush added, he would ``focus on the common ground.
The common ground that exists today is on partial birth abortion.''
He said he would penalize doctors performing such operations, but
not their patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
