<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BAXTER-0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Execution: Bush stands firm as killer meets fate
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin, Texas _ On the day set for Gary Graham's execution, Gov.
George W. Bush had arranged a session with political reporters from
around the country to talk about the progress of his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both men kept their appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sat down with the reporters in his office a couple of hours
before the Texas Board of Pardons and Parole re- fused to block
Graham's execution.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published Thursday in the Dallas Morning News showed that
73 percent of Texans agreed with Bush's support of the death
penalty. But 57 percent also said they believed innocent people
sometimes are put to death in that state.
</P>
<P>
   Was that acceptable? Bush was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not acceptable, and under my watch, I'm telling you
that I've analyzed every case, and I don't believe that's the case.
I'm confident that it's not the case _ that the people who have
been put to death have been guilty of the crime charged, and have
had full access to the courts,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Texas law gives the governor only limited powers to
intervene in capital cases _ powers already exhausted in the Graham
case by former Gov. Ann Richards, a Democrat _ Bush has found
himself in a political bind over the past few days. He has been
held accountable for the execution, without technically having
anything he could do about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, serving his second term as governor, expressed
reluctance about changing the law to make the governor more
directly accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should the governor have the power to say yes or no? Shall we
do away with the Board of Pardons and Parole? I don't think so,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the governor has the power to grant only a 30-day
reprieve in a death penalty case (he also appoints the parole
board), Bush said he has carefully reviewed every case during his
term, including that of Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case that has had full `analyzation' and been looked
at,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He said jurors from the Graham trial who expressed doubts in
recent days about their verdict may have been influenced by ``two
weeks of publicity suggesting . . . (that Graham might not be
guilty).''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also expressed misgivings about federal legislation
proposed by Sen. Slade Gorton (R-Wash.) that would establish a
right to DNA testing for people accused in capital cases and give
the federal government a larger role in investigating hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   While he said he would ``appreciate federal help on prosecuting
hate crimes,'' such as the murder of an African-American dragged
behind a truck in Jasper, Texas, Bush said he was concerned about
the federal government encroaching on the states' role in criminal
cases.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed a similar mis- giving about the DNA legislation,
but said he favored using DNA evidence when it can be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in fielding similar questions on the campaign trail,
Bush sought to soften some of the frictions between himself and
anti-death penalty demonstrators who have dogged his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious matter and I welcome the debate. I think
it's healthy for a democracy. But I'm sworn to uphold the law.
That's my job,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
