<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS TAKE CHANCE BY MAKING HEBERT AVAILABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Guy Hebert has been a fixture in goal for the
Mighty Ducks since the beginning. He beat out Ron Tugnutt for the
No. 1 spot early in Anaheim's inaugural season (1993-94) and is the
last remaining original Duck.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Pierre Gauthier took what he describes as a
``calculated risk'' when he decided not to protect the 33-year old
veteran in today's NHL Expansion Draft in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, who used a second-round draft choice to acquire
promising young goalie Jean-Sebastian Giguere from Calgary on June
10, elected to protect only one goalie (Giguere) and gamble that
neither Minnesota or Columbus would want to take on the last two
years of Hebert's hefty contract.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert's deal _ which will pay him $3.6 million next season and
$3.8 million in 2001-2002 _ also includes a no-trade clause,
another thing Gauthier hopes will discourage the expansion teams.
</P>
<P>
   When Anaheim announced that Hebert was going to be left
unprotected, Gauthier sounded very optimistic that the longtime fan
favorite would not be lost. But as the draft approaches, the GM
obviously doesn't want to sound !ital!overly optimistic even though
Minnesota and Columbus have both recently traded for young
goaltenders who might step in and become starters.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota acquired Dallas backup Manny Fernandez and Columbus
picked up Colorado backup Marc Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm confident,'' the GM said. `I'm hoping he
will be not be taken; we will have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert suffered through a sub-par season in 1999-2000, but it's
unlikely the Ducks relish the idea of beginning the 2000-2001
campaign without an established No. 1 like him. He has 161 of the
Ducks' 215 wins to his credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he is a better goalie (than he showed last season),''
Gauthier said. ``He has been a good goalie in this league before
and he will be again.''
</P>
<P>
   If Anaheim's gamble is successful, the Ducks could escape from
the draft relatively unharmed. Five of their top seven defensemen
are protected and first-year players Vitaly Vishnevski and Niclas
Havelid did not have to be protected. Unrestricted free agents Kip
Miller, Ted Donato, Kevin Haller and Stu Grimson are up for grabs,
but it's rare for expansion teams to risk a pick on a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves winger Jeff Nielsen, swingman Pascal Trepanier and
backup goalie Dominic Roussel as the most likely candidates to be
selected.
</P>
<P>
   No team can lose more than one goalie or defenseman, according
to the draft guidelines. A team that loses a goalie can't lose a
defenseman.
</P>
</TEXT>
