<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROADSIDE-MEMORIALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MOST STATES, ROADSIDE MEMORIALS TO CRASH VICTIMS ARE ILLEGAL,
BUT TOLERATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ore., Fla., Tenn., Mont.)  (Note to editors: In graf beginning `Our son was cremated,' Mount
Si is cq.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH BEND, Wash. _ Shortly after the second anniversary of the
day their 19-year-old son, Brandon, was killed in an automobile
accident a few blocks from their home, Amy and Tony Blount received
a phone call from the King County Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The small white cross erected at the scene of his death, and the
shrine of flowers and photographs that his friends had maintained
around it, needed to come down, an official gently explained. It
was, after all, illegally placed on a public right of way.
</P>
<P>
   But that was eight months and about 70,000 pro-memorial petition
signatures ago. The cross is still there, and the Blounts have no
intention of allowing it to come down. Mr. Blount has even vowed to
chain himself to the cross if a road crew tries to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by friends and bolstered by their drive to gather the
signatures needed to get an initiative on the state ballot in the
fall that would make such memorials legal, the Blounts have forged
a crusade out of their grief that has generated a vigorous
political and legal debate here. But the Blounts' campaign also
points up the quandary facing highway officials in every state:
What, if anything, should be done with such memorials?
</P>
<P>
   No one has an exact count, of course. But highway officials
estimate that there are tens of thousands of memorials to the dead
on roads and highways across the nation. Officials in charge of
these traffic arteries agree that the number of such memorials has
soared in recent years, a phenomenon generally attributed to the
myriad ways in which grieving has become an ever more public
process _ and even a communal one, as evidenced by the Vietnam
Memorial in Washington, D.C., or the huge impromptu shrine at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Roadside memorials are often in the form of small wooden
crosses, erected at the scene of a traffic accident, in some cases
within hours. Some bear the initials of those killed, or a personal
message from family members or friends, and some are much more
elaborate, with flowers or mementos of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Such memorials, if placed on public property, are almost always
illegal, though some states, including Washington, have programs to
erect signs at the scenes of traffic deaths with safety messages or
warnings against drinking and driving. Often, though, the memorials
are left alone, unless they pose a clear safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Lloyd Ensley, the traffic regulations specialist for the
Washington Department of Transportation, puts it, ``over time, most
of these seem to come down on their own without us getting
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cross memorializing Brandon Blount here in North Bend,
just beyond the fringe of Seattle's eastern suburbs, has not come
down. And what is really unusual about it is the way the memorial
ignited the petition drive, which is intended to make it legal for
roadside memorials up to 2 feet high and 2 feet wide to be placed
near the scene of any traffic death.
</P>
<P>
   The Blounts are deeply angered by any suggestion that the
memorial be removed from the small hill near the spot where
Brandon, a passenger in a car driven by a friend, died in a head-on
collision with another vehicle as the two youths were headed to the
local McDonald's early one evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our son was cremated,'' Mrs. Blount, a retired owner of a
mobile delicatessen, said of Brandon, who was rated one of the
state's top chess players and graduated from Mount Si High School a
few months before his death. ``That's all we have left of him, and
this memorial is so important to us, it's just not right to remove
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go down there and there are always new little flowers, or
sculptures or necklaces. It makes me feel really good when I see
all that. It makes me feel Brandon has not been forgotten by his
friends. We raised a decent enough kid that a lot of other people
still love him, too, and he won't be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blounts need to gather a total of about 175,000 signatures
by next month to get an initiative on the November ballot, and
state officials say the Blounts really need tens of thousands more
than that to protect against duplicated or other unacceptable
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Such a law could raise thorny constitutional issues, because so
many of the memorials include a cross, a Christian symbol. It was
precisely for this reason that Oregon lawmakers shelved discussion
of a measure to legalize small roadside memorials, after it was
pointed out that so-called hate groups or fringe religious sects
considered widely offensive could assert their right to erect
memorials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you open the door, you open the door to all kinds of
memorials,'' said David Fidanque, executive director of the
American Civil Liberties Union of Oregon. ``You might not be very
happy with what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Oregon Legislature was discussing the issue, some
swastika symbols and placards with ``KKK'' and the satanic mark
``666'' were placed, anonymously, alongside cross memorials on a
few Oregon roads. In an unsigned letter to The Statesman-Journal in
Salem, Ore., someone asserted that the placards were a protest
against religious memorials on public roadsides.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of what to do with memorials has flared up in other
ways.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, state transportation officials announced this month
that they would halt, at least temporarily, a policy under which
road crews removed all roadside memorials except those involving a
victim in a drunken-driving incident.
</P>
<P>
   The policy was intended to highlight the dangers of alcohol on
the road, but friends and family members of people killed in
accidents not involving alcohol were offended that their memorials
were accorded different treatment, and by the notices road crews
had attached to them: ``We at the Texas Department of
Transportation deeply regret the death of your loved one and extend
our sympathies to you and your family. We understand your desire to
memorialize your loved one. However TxDOT permits only properly
constructed DWI-related memorials on the highway right of way.''
The notices said, ``Unapproved memorials will be removed and may be
reclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A spot check of states around the nation indicates that most
officially discourage roadside memorials, but often, in deference
to the bereaved, take their time in removing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are against the law,'' said Deborah Fehr, a spokeswoman
for the Tennessee Department of Transportation. ``But we are
sympathetic to the reason people put them up. So we don't drive
around the state trying to take them down. Generally, unless we
feel they're unsafe, we leave them in until we have some mowing or
some maintenance to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida, after banning the unofficial memorials in 1997,
instituted a program in which road crews replace crosses with
special highway safety markers noting the accident site.
(Originally in the shape used by the International Red Cross, the
design was changed to include a circular black-and-white marker
with the words ``Drive Safely'' after complaints that the cross
symbol was too evocative of a Christian cross.) In Montana, the
state has long had an informal agreement with the American Legion,
allowing that organization to erect small crosses at fatal crash
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Here in King County, which includes North Bend, officials have
backed off plans to take the Blount memorial down, which might not
be all that simple an operation. Originally a wooden cross, the
memorial was vandalized and set afire, and it is now made of steel,
embedded in about 250 pounds of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go out of our way to remove memorials,'' said Linda
Dougherty, acting manager of the road services division for the
King County Department of Transportation. ``We have what I would
describe as a sort of a tolerance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But some neighbors of the Blount memorial have phoned in
complaints, and Dougherty said the county continued to hope that
the Blounts would remove the memorial, perhaps reconstructing it on
their own property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will need, eventually, to come down,'' she said. ``We're
just trying to do the reasonable and right thing here.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been little solid research on whether highway
memorials constitute a safety hazard, said Julie Rochman, vice
president for communications at the Insurance Institute for Highway
Safety, a nonprofit organization in Arlington, Va., financed by
insurers.The institute and several similar organizations have not
taken an official position on what to do with memorials.
</P>
<P>
   Some defenders of the memorials suggest that they improve safety
by encouraging people to slow down and realize that a death
occurred at a particular spot, but Rochman said she was skeptical
of such claims. ``I don't think, for most drivers, that it changes
their behavior,'' she said. ``Most people think they're good
drivers and aren't going to be involved in crashes. The people who
died at the spots where those memorials are placed didn't think
they were going to be involved in fatal crashes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
