<HEADLINE>
FIRE TRAGEDY DEFENDANT'S BABY SUBJECT OF CUSTODY FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JBOSTON _ oshua Barnes, the 2-week-old son of Julie Barnes _ the
homeless woman charged with manslaughter after December's Worcester
warehouse fire _ is the focus of a growing custody dispute that
could pit his relatives and family friends against the state
Department of Social Services.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Barnes, 19, whom relatives say is mentally disabled, has
been incarcerated since December, held on $75,000 bail and charged
in the deaths of six firefighters after Barnes and her boyfriend
allegedly started the fire by accident during an argument inside
the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The department took custody of Joshua several days after his
birth and placed him in a foster home.
</P>
<P>
   But friends and relatives of Julie Barnes, concerned they could
lose contact with the baby if he is given to an adoptive family,
are making efforts to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, an attorney for Julie's mother, Evelyn Menard, filed
a motion to become a third party in the case, allowing her to
request guardianship or visitation rights. A judge has yet to rule
on her request.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday an attorney for Debb and Tim King of Ellsworth, Maine
_ friends who are working to raise money for Julie's release _ will
file a petition of their own asking to intervene in the case and
seeking guardianship of the baby.
</P>
</TEXT>
