<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT UNEVEILS MOVE TOWARD INTERNET-BASED SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft Thursday unveiled an ambitious effort to
transform some of the company's software into Internet-based
services, a move top officials described as one of the biggest
gambles the company has ever taken.
</P>
<P>
   The complex initiative, called Microsoft.NET, will let software
developers create Internet applications that easily interact with
each other even though they're developed in different computer
languages by different companies. The applications will be fully
usable, without modification, on personal computers, handheld
organizers and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said the threat of being split into two
companies by a pending antitrust suit won't slow their efforts to
realize Microsoft.NET, and they denied the initiative might provoke
further wrath from the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   What consumers will notice is that the new software essentially
replaces the computer's hard drive with the storage and programming
capabilities of the Internet. On a PC, people store programs such
as games or word processing on a hard drive. They use the
computer's operating system to request access to those programs.
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft.NET, people will store their programs and files
on larger computers called servers, which they can access via the
Internet. A programming language called XML (for eXtensible Markup
Language) will serve the purpose of the operating system, linking
the user's request to the data needed.
</P>
<P>
   Because the programs don't need a hard drive, they will be
accessible from a wide variety of devices, such as ``smart'' cell
phones and handheld computers _ in theory, any device with a screen
and a microchip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the opportunity to take this vision of a digital world
and apply the magic of software to make this a reality,'' said
chairman and chief software architect Bill Gates, the prime mover
behind Microsoft.NET.
</P>
<P>
   Previews of the new services _ which will include online
versions of Microsoft's popular Office software and features of its
Windows operating system _ will begin in 2001, but full services
will not be widely available until at least 2002, Gates said. The
first .NET product rolled out will be Visual Studio 7, which will
let developers create .NET-compliant applications.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ballyhoo of Thursday's announcement, Microsoft is
only the latest entrant into the market for Web-based services.
Oracle Corp. has invested heavily in providing similar services to
corporations, while Sun Microsystems Inc. will unveil a Web-based
office software suite by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some analysts have said that the kind of integration
needed to make Microsoft.NET a reality could run afoul of the
company's antitrust battle. Microsoft is appealing a court-ordered
breakup after a federal judge found it had broken antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Microsoft, full speed ahead, damn the torpedoes,''
said Chris LeTocq, an analyst with the Gartner Group. ``But if the
(Justice Department) doesn't look at this and say it proves their
point, I'd be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates, however, insisted the company has not further jeopardized
itself with the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the law encourage companies like Microsoft to ... do new
features and products? Yes, there's no case that's ever come out
against that at the appeals level,'' he said. ``Nothing here was
influenced by any thinking about the (District) court's influencing
it. This is the right technical direction for where software
platforms ought to go.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of now-suspended restrictions on Microsoft's business
practices, if upheld, could severely hamper the company's progress
on Microsoft.NET. Ballmer said that's not a problem, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another'' the company will finish work on
Microsoft.NET, he said. ``It would be better for consumers if this
product was tightly integrated, but we will definitely finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft plans to take its popular software products, including
Windows, Microsoft Office and the Microsoft Network online service,
and make their features readily available over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Both home and business users would pay a monthly subscription
fee for Web-based services, said Rick Belluzzo, a Microsoft group
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Network Web sites and services will become MSN.NET,
and will continue to offer such services as free online e-mail,
bill paying, appointment management and instant messaging.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has already received backing from Compaq Computer
Corp. and Dell Computer Corp., among others, including Marc
Andreessen, founder of rival Netscape Communications Corp. and now
the chairman of Loudcloud Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Microsoft closed down 81 cents at $79.88, and fell
another 13 cents in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Material from The Associated Press was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
