<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY'S ALL-STAR GAME RESTRICTED BY THE UNION LABEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Believe it or not, there are some things
at the racetrack more mysterious than the exact nature of jockey
Donnie Meche's shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the past week not knowing the extent of Meche's injury.
Was it a strain, or something worse?
</P>
<P>
   The question became moot Wednesday night, when Meche returned to
the track and rode in three races.
</P>
<P>
   This much, we know: Meche, who went to his left-handed stick 15
times and not once to the injured right-handed side, isn't 100
percent. But that's not stopping him from riding a winner, as he
did in the third race.
</P>
<P>
   He's the leading jockey at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie. And
with that distinction, Meche has earned the right to represent the
track tonight in the $125,000 National Thoroughbred Racing
Association All-Star Jockey Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for his participation is clear-cut. But that's not
exactly the case for the other 11 riders.
</P>
<P>
   In more than one interview, All-Star Jockey Championship
selection committee member Chick Lang has indicated one of the
loose guidelines to participation in the event is that the rider be
a member of The Jockey's Guild. It's a union, a ``players
association,'' for jockeys in North America.
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of jockeys this loose guideline excludes.
Corey Nakatani has been winning Breeders' Cup races since 1996, and
he's the leading money-earner this year. Even if he's riding on the
``B-level'' Northern California circuit, Russell Baze might one day
break the world record for number of career victories. And Chris
McCarron's horsemanship is such that one person wondered out loud
if McCarron also was training a horse he rides.
</P>
<P>
   If the All-Star Jockey Championship follows a Guild-only
selection guideline, the event will fall short of what some
promoters have envisioned: horse racing's answer to Major League
Baseball's All-Star Game. It would be closer to The Guild's annual
company picnic than the ``Midsummer Classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're a member of the Major League Baseball Players
Association or not, it won't help anyone get selected to the
All-Star Game. Agree or disagree with their selections, at least
baseball fans have a say in who plays in the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   The Guild, which contracts with Lone Star to put on this event,
likely will chip in with the right opinion on this one. It has in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   It's not kissing up to The Guild to say that horse racing fans
are lucky The Guild acts as the ``players association'' with
racetrack owners regarding labor issues. At least twice in the
previous decade, it seemed quite possible that the jockeys might
not hammer out an insurance agreement with racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   If the jockeys were represented by the likes of Billy Hunter,
Donald Fehr or Gene Upshaw, who led players in negotiations with
owners in the NBA, Major League Baseball and the NFL, respectively,
horse racing would have been hit with some kind of work stoppage.
Instead, the deal got done.
</P>
<P>
   That's to The Guild's credit. But regardless of how The Guild
and racetracks split the pie, the money they're splitting comes
from betting made by racing fans.
</P>
<P>
   And racing fans have been pretty good to them the past decade.
It's a good idea to always, always return the favor with the
strongest product possible.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
