<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-GLASGOW-NYT &LR;      06-22 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GLASGOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON ARRIVES AND SCOTLAND NOTICES A WEE BIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: See sidebar, BOX-TYSON) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland _ When Mike Tyson arrived at his hotel in
downtown Glasgow on Wednesday evening, his affable Scottish hosts
were too polite to protest.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the local rape crisis center had gone to court to
bar Tyson's entry to the country; the one-year-old Scottish
Parliament had petitioned to have his Saturday fight with Lou
Savarese denied a license; and a poll of readers in the local
newspaper _ where Tyson is continually referred to in print as
``the convicted rapist'' _ had made it obvious that an overwhelming
majority of Scots did not welcome Tyson's presence.
</P>
<P>
   But when Tyson was finally here in this revived port city, there
was the shrug of indifference, hiding perhaps an aggrieved disdain
and a frustration tinged with nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of immigration law in the United Kingdom, it was
Jack Straw, the home secretary in London, who had the power to
grant Tyson permission to fight in Scotland's national soccer
stadium, Hampden Park.
</P>
<P>
   It was a decision that rankled some locales as the most recent
example of England's flaunting its will over Scotland, and it
eventually touched off a lengthy debate in the Scottish Parliament
that devolved into the centuries-old debate about Scottish
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion is easily stirred up in Glasgow's streets and
pubs, where the patrons acknowledge that Tyson's visit has everyone
``a wee bit off-temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they are trying not to show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all are very disappointed,'' said Mary Mulligan, a
member of the Scottish Parliament and head of that body's
education, sports and culture committee. ``To actually see somebody
like Tyson brought here and put up as a sporting hero is
unacceptable. Because of his prior conviction for rape and because
he's not made any efforts to say he's sorry. It flies in the face
of what we're trying to stand for. The people I talk with are all
very uneasy about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are just plain perturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kelvin of Glasgow sized up the bevy of police officers and
bodyguards surrounding the entrance to Tyson's hotel Thursday as he
worked to repave a nearby street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the security for one man in there,'' Kelvin said,
scoffing as he nodded toward the hotel. ``Come on now; he's a
boxer, not a royal.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at Hampden Park, where seating capacity for boxing is
51,500, nearly 40,000 seats, priced from $50 to $850, have already
been sold. There were at least 40 people who cheered Tyson on
Wednesday and called out for autographs. As in most places Tyson
visits, there always seems to be some kind of a love-hate
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But there are theories to explain the huge expected gate as
well. Some Scots believe it is the English fans who are buying up
the tickets, turning Saturday's fight into an exhibition for
out-of-towners in a revered Scottish sporting venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody who is actually going to buy a ticket,''
Mulligan said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, meanwhile, in an interview Tuesday with The Evening Times
of Glasgow, likened himself to Scotland's national hero William
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my situation has been very similar to his,'' the
newspaper quoted Tyson as saying. ``Wallace was betrayed by nearly
everybody he trusted, and in many ways I feel that is similar to my
fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in his only news conference of the week, Tyson was
asked how he felt about those opposing Saturday's fight _
organizations like the Glasgow Rape Crisis Center, which plans a
protest rally outside Hampden Park on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them,'' said Tyson, who later in the day donned a kilt
during a public appearance and insisted that most Scots were
supportive of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if I can understand what they're saying,''
Tyson said, referring to Scottish accents. ``I understand their
heart and their heart is with me.''
</P>
<P>
   But a week ago, there were protesters at the building that
houses Glasgow's city government bearing placards and wearing
T-shirts with the slogans, ``Tyson: Money Before Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the promise of economic gain for city businesses that
many Glaswegians consider the real reason that the fight, which was
twice postponed, ended up in Glasgow. Some officials originally
estimated that the local boon could be as high as $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Few now believe _ even with Tyson's enormous entourage _ that
Glasgow will see such a windfall. Still, the pursuit of profit with
Tyson in the mix, irritated Sandy Brindley, the development officer
at the Glasgow Rape Crisis Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was particularly angering, that it came down to economic
gain,'' Brindley said. ``Because we felt that was prioritizing
economic concerns over the pain and the suffering women have
experienced because of sexual violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's arrival in Glasgow is also oddly timed. Ten or 15 years
ago, about the time Tyson was calling himself ``the baddest man on
the planet,'' people were referring to Glasgow as one of Europe's
roughest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Once the principal dropping point in the British Isles for
American tobacco and cotton during the 17th and 18th centuries,
Glasgow was later known for its lynchpin role in the Industrial
Revolution. Scotland's biggest city with more than a million
residents, it was also where, along the River Clyde, that the
mammoth and fabled ocean liners Queen Mary and QE II were
constructed.
</P>
<P>
   But by the early 1980s, the city's renowned Victorian
architecture, and the prescient, ground-breaking work of a local
architect, Charles Rennie Mackintosh, were enveloped in a
blackening soot from years of smoking industrial buildup.
</P>
<P>
   A massive clean-up operation _ aimed at more than just the
building exteriors _ was organized in 1983. The civic and cultural
renaissance took root. It was designated the cultural capital of
Europe in 1990 with more architectural and art awards following
throughout the decade, recognition usually reserved for its eastern
urban neighbor, Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Glasgow, built on blue-collar values, is also chic,
vibrant and highly progressive.
</P>
<P>
   It is into this setting that Tyson has come, to earn a purse of
about $8 million, bringing with him the controversy that has
accompanied him wherever he goes for a decade. This time, in some
measure, he has even spawned a nationalistic furor in a people to
whom he would seem to have no connection _ Tyson's William Wallace
analogies aside.
</P>
<P>
   But Mulligan, a member of the first parliament to sit in
Scotland since 1707, does not see the discord Tyson's presence has
provoked as another battle over national rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are unhappy, they should make that understood loud
and clear to the home secretary in London,'' Mulligan said. ``But
this isn't about borders; it's an issue of principle. This man is
someone who shouldn't be allowed in Scotland, to fight in a sport's
stadium, or to do anything else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
