<HEADLINE>
TULSA BASKETBALL JOB STILL ALLURING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, Tulsa's basketball program has won
424 of 624 games. That's a .679 winning percentage. In 15 of those
20 seasons, Tulsa has reached postseason play, including 11 trips
to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   All those numbers and accomplishments are impressive, but not as
impressive as this fact: Tulsa has had five coaches during the past
20 years. No Division I school has had the sustained success in the
face of such frequent coaching turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a top-25 job,'' SMU coach Mike Dement said. ``And because
of the history of the coaches there leaving for better jobs, it's a
very attractive job.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Richardson left for Arkansas. Tubby Smith left for Georgia
(and is now at Kentucky). Steve Robinson left for Florida State.
Earlier this month, Bill Self cashed in his 32-5 season and left
for Illinois. Only J.D. Barnett, who was a respectable 106-65 in
six seasons as Richardson's successor, didn't make good use of his
Tulsa time.
</P>
<P>
   Self's replacement will be Buzz Peterson, hired away from
Appalachian State. Peterson is one of the nation's hottest young
coaches and eventually might win enough games that his claim to
fame won't be sharing a North Carolina dorm room with Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa athletic director Judy MacLeod, who hired Self, received
about 75 applications for the Tulsa job. Considering it is a job in
neither a major market nor in a power conference, why do so many
coaches line up at the Golden Hurricanes' drive-thru window?
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tulsa was in Dallas-Fort Worth, there's no question it
would be considered a top 25 program,'' said Southwest Missouri
State coach Barry Hinson, who followed Self as the coach at Oral
Roberts. ``But in the coaching ranks, I don't think there's much
doubt that, right now, it's a top-25 school. Tulsa used to be
viewed as a steppingstone. Now, I think it's a stone.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tulsa's Elite Eight performance last season, Golden
Hurricanes boosters boosted Self's contract. Although that kept him
from taking the Nebraska job, Illinois was too good to turn down.
While Tulsa supporters are getting tired of losing coaches to
bigger programs, they should take solace in the fact that the
school can hire a coach such as Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the community, being considered a `steppingstone' job has
been an issue,'' MacLeod said. ``When the fans have emotional ties
with the coach, there can be some hurt feelings and frustration. We
want to have a coach that other people are interested in. We've
tried to improve our program each year. Anybody can have a top-25
team one year. It takes some effort and commitment to have a top-25
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really felt like with Buzz that we got a combination of a
great recruiter and a proven head coach with a wonderful
personality. Buzz had some other coaching opportunities in the last
few years, so it was special that he thought enough of this job to
make the move. He thinks he can get to the Final Four here.''  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Dibler, director of basketball officiating for the
Mountain West Conference and a former Southwest Conference
basketball official and former director of Western Athletic
Conference officiating, deserves your thoughts and prayers.
Dibler's wife Carroll, 53, and daughter Kristin, 20, were murdered
Sunday in El Paso. William Edward Henschel, Kristin's former
boyfriend, has been charged with capital murder and attempted
capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's athletic department hopes to be under budget by
approximately $100,000 for the 1999-2000 fiscal year. If athletic
director Joe Castiglione's projections are correct, it will be the
first time in a decade that the department has had a year in the
black. Since 1989, the athletic department has borrowed nearly $8
million from the school. That debt is still on the books.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Sportsline.com has rated TCU's football schedule as the
softest in the Western Athletic Conference and Texas' schedule as
the softest in the Big 12 Conference.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
