<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON DENIES SCUFFLE WITH PROMOTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BOX-GLASGOW) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland _ Responding to published reports in several
British newspapers, Mike Tyson on Thursday denied that he recently
punched and broke the ribs of Frank Warren, the promoter of Tyson's
fight with Lou Savarese on Saturday night, during a scuffle said to
have taken place at a London hotel earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some newspapers reported the fight as only a rumor while one
London daily newspaper reported that sources said Tyson attempted
to throw Warren out a window and that the fight was over money
Tyson believed Warren owed him.
</P>
<P>
   Other reports said that Tyson broke Warren's jaw and that Warren
was treated at a London hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Tyson was asked if he hit Warren.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' Tyson said. ``I love Frank Warren.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he threatened to push Warren out a window, Tyson said,
``No, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter then asked, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there's a long line ahead of him,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is highly unusual for a promoter not to attend the
biggest and last media event to promote his own fight, Warren did
not appear at Thursday's news conference, which had been scheduled
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Also not in attendance was Jay Larkin, a Warren associate and
the executive producer and senior vice president of Showtime, the
American network broadcasting the fight from Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Warren said that he missed his plane from
London to Glasgow and was busy with some legal matters. The
spokeswoman also said that the promoter was preparing to sue
several British newspapers for ``false and libelous statements.''
</P>
<P>
   A Showtime spokesman said Larkin was in a production meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning of Tyson about whether he did or did not scuffle
with Warren added a sense of chaos to a news conference that was
bizarre even by the eccentric standards that boxing has set.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, for example, alternately said he knew he was well liked
by the boxing public, then said he did not care if the public liked
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why I don't care,'' Tyson said. ``I enjoy what I
do. I enjoy hurting people. That's what you come to see: to see me
hurt people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I don't know if they want to like me. Sometimes I
don't like myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
