<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-HELLING-TEX     06-22 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HELLING-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rick Helling's five-game losing streak has
him courting personal disaster. Forget what it has done to the
Rangers' standing in the American League West, or that it has
probably ruined a once-sure chance of making the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   The true tragedy is it has seriously damaged his chances of
winning a record-tying third consecutive Dick Siebert Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The what?'' Helling said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Siebert Award. Named after the distinguished longtime
University of Minnesota baseball coach, the award is given each
year to the Upper Midwest Player of the Year. Helling has won it
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has ever told me anything about it,'' Helling said
incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there it is on page 204 of the Minnesota Twins' media
guide. The award was started in 1962, one year after the Twins
moved to Minnesota and is voted upon annually by the Twin Cities
chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't there be a trophy or a plaque or something?'' said
Helling, who qualifies for the award by proudly hailing from Fargo,
N.D. ``I haven't even received a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of winners is actually an impressive bunch, headed by
Minnesota natives Dave Winfield, Jack Morris, Terry Steinbach, Kent
Hrbek and Paul Molitor, who is the overall leader with seven
Siebert Awards. But Helling has a shot this year at becoming only
the second player in history to win the Siebert Award three
consecutive years. Former New York Mets pitcher Jerry Koosman, who
is from Appleton, Minn., accomplished that unprecedented feat in
1969-71.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty select group,'' Helling admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Molitor, now a coach for the Twins, played for Siebert at the
University of Minnesota and said he has heard of the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember winning it a few times,'' Molitor said. ``I know I
have a couple of plaques, but I think they're in a box in the
basement. I don't think they're prominently displayed.''
</P>
<P>
   At least somebody told him he won.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Helling knows the award exists, he is utterly
dismayed that his five-game losing streak could cost him a shot at
a third award. Anaheim Angels outfielder Darin Erstad is also from
North Dakota, and there's no use denying the fact that his .364
average through Wednesday's game has made him a threat to steal the
award from Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erstad's got to be the favorite,'' Helling admitted. ``But why
didn't he win it in '98? He was an All-Star. It just goes to show
you that some people appreciate pitching more than hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning three in a row might also induce the Rangers to
recognize Helling's achievement. Not only has he never been
notified of the award, it's not included in his official biography
in the Rangers' media guide. If not for the diligence of the Twins'
public relations staff, Helling's achievement might have been lost
to history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about five states \RMinnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa,
North and South Dakota\S that's 10 percent of the country,''
Helling said. ``Ten percent of the country considers me the best
player in the country, and I don't even get mentioned in the media
guide? That's disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with Koosman sitting out there, Helling could
eventually accomplish something much more impressive: tying
Molitor's all-time record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I don't even know if I have seven years left in my
career,'' Helling said. ``Let's see, I'd have to win five
consecutive right? The main thing is I have to turn it up in the
second half, three-peat, and then win four consecutive. I could
retire and my career would be complete: seven-time Upper Midwest
Player of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Molitor, however, is determined not to let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to have to start campaigning for Darin
Erstad,'' he said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
