u w BC-RAY-TRAVEL-OFFICE-980     06-22 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAY-TRAVEL-OFFICE-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CHARGES IN WHITE HOUSE TRAVEL OFFICE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel investigating President and
Hillary Rodham Clinton said Thursday he would seek no criminal
charges against Clinton for her involvement in the firing of seven
longtime White House employees in 1993. But the prosecutor, Robert
Ray, said there was substantial evidence she played a greater role
in the affair than she had portrayed in her sworn testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing he will not prosecute the first lady, Ray made a
point of asserting that she ``ultimately influenced'' the decision
to fire the employees by repeatedly expressing her concerns to
senior White House officials.
</P>
<P>
   The seven employees in the White House travel office were
summarily dismissed a few months after the Clintons first occupied
the White House and were replaced with supporters and relatives of
the Clintons from Arkansas. In sworn testimony, Clinton insisted
that her role in the firings had been only peripheral.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said Thursday
night that the completion of the investigation of the travel office
firings after several years only confirmed ``what the president and
first lady have always said about this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart strongly objected to Ray's statement, which
summarized a final report on the investigation that he filed
Thursday under seal with a three-judge panel which oversees the
operation of the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``By inappropriately characterizing the results of a legally
sealed report through innuendo, the Office of Independent Counsel
has further politicized an investigation that has dragged on far
too long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first gave her version of what part she played in the
firing when questioned by congressional investigators in 1996. She
depicted her role as marginal, saying she had been only vaguely
aware of the situation in the travel office, which makes
arrangements for the White House press to accompany the president
on trips.
</P>
<P>
   She testified that she had informally asked to be kept abreast
of developments but was preoccupied with other matters and that she
had no idea how and why the shake-up was initiated.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said in his statement Thursday that his investigation
demonstrated that Clinton's conversations with several White House
officials about problems at the travel office produced the climate
that resulted in the dismissals of the employees by David Watkins,
a senior White House administrator.
</P>
<P>
   He listed several senior officials with whom she shared her
concerns about the travel office, including Watkins and said that
``these officials discussed her concerns among themselves which
produced a momentum to take immediate action.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Thus, Mrs. Clinton's concerns ultimately influenced
Watkins' decision to fire the Travel Office employees.''
</P>
<P>
   In deciding not to prosecute Clinton, Ray did not use the same
kind of generous exculpatory language he used three months ago in
declaring her innocent of any wrongdoing in the investigation of
the White House's improper acquisition of hundreds of FBI files.
Instead, his words clearing Clinton Thursday were spare.
</P>
<P>
   He said that despite Clinton's role as disclosed by the
investigation, ``The evidence was insufficient to prove to a jury
beyond a reasonable doubt that any of Mrs. Clinton's statements and
testimony regarding her involvement in the Travel Office firings
were knowingly false. Accordingly, the independent counsel has
declined prosecution of Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The report filed with the special three-judge panel contains a
fuller narrative of Clinton's involvement in the firings and the
testimony of several other witnesses, including Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   The report will be kept under seal by the judicial panel for at
least three months during which time Clinton, Watkins and any other
people mentioned in it are given a chance to review portions about
them and respond if they choose. Its contents might then be
disclosed in the final weeks of Clinton's senate campaign in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said that his office had also declined to prosecute Watkins
for any false statements to investigators, particularly those in
which he said that he had been pressured by Clinton to dismiss the
employees.
</P>
<P>
   It was Watkins who initially raised questions about Clinton's
statements under oath. While she had depicted herself as marginally
involved, Watkins wrote a memorandum to Thomas F. Mack McLarty 3rd,
who was then the White House chief of staff, giving a different
version.
</P>
<P>
   The memo, which Watkins said was an effort to cleanse his soul
about the matter, said that, ``we both knew there would be hell to
pay'' if ``we failed to take swift and decisive action in
conformity with the first lady's wishes.'' In a chronology he wrote
of events leading up to the firing, Watkins quoted Clinton as
saying: ``We need those people out and we need our people in.'' He
also wrote that he spoke directly to Clinton about his efforts to
fire the travel office employees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a week before the dismissals, he was told by Harry
Thomason, a Hollywood producer and Arkansas friend of the Clintons,
that Clinton told him she was ``ready to fire them that day.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House initially said that the travel office employees
were dismissed because of evidence of financial improprieties, but
none was ever proved.
</P>
<P>
   White House political aides arranged for the FBI to conduct an
investigation after the shake-up. The head of the office, Billy R.
Dale, was prosecuted for misuse of funds but was acquitted by a
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Ray also said in his statement that the White House was
disappointingly uncooperative in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In contrast to the cooperation received from the White House
in the FBI files investigation concluded in March of this year,
this office experienced substantial resistance in its efforts to
obtain relevant evidence in the Travel Office matter,'' he said in
his statement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ray's words three months ago praising White House cooperation
seemed to signal a possible softening of relations between the
independent counsel and the White House. Ray's predecessor, Kenneth
Starr, was regularly assailed by White House aides and Clinton
supporters as someone trying to harm the president for political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's statement and the Lockhart's response suggest his office's
relations with the White House remain strained.
</P>
<P>
   The final reports about the FBI files matter and the travel
office are two of the last three reports Ray is planning to make
before he shuts down the office. He is expected to complete a
report this fall on the Clintons activities in connection with the
Whitewater real estate development, which gave its name to the
collective investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Ray has also said that he will decide whether the President
should be indicted after he leaves office for any offenses in
connection with his concealment of a relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DAVIDIAN-TRIAL0623-CO     06-22 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIAN-TRIAL0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former FBI officials testify attack on compound was contrary to
approved plan
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The premature partial destruction of the Branch
Davidian compound with tanks deviated from the Washington-approved
plan to end the 51-day siege at Mount Carmel, two former top FBI
officials testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth day of the multimillion dollar wrongful death trial
against the government focused on the morning of April 19, 1993,
and the FBI's plan to use tear gas on David Koresh and his
followers and drive them from their sprawling home.
</P>
<P>
   Danny O. Coulson, former deputy assistant FBI director,
testifying by videotape, said he and his Justice Department
colleagues in Washington were surprised as they watched on
television as a tank plunged through a wall of the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Coulson said an FBI official seated next to him uttered a
shock-induced expletive, and he said, ``I hope that's a bad camera
angle,'' as the tank rammed through the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it didn't go into the building as far as it
looked,'' Coulson said.
</P>
<P>
   Before playing the videotaped depositions of Coulson and former
assistant FBI director Larry A. Potts, lead plaintiffs' attorney
Mike Caddell of Houston distributed copies of the FBI's proposed
operational plans to end the siege and Attorney General Janet
Reno's briefing book to the seven-member advisory jury. Caddell
told jurors the plan underwent at least five revisions before Reno
approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Coulson said the FBI's dismantling of the gym on the back side
of the compound with modified tanks known as combat engineering
vehicles was ``inconsistent with what I understood the plan to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions from Caddell, Coulson said he ``never
contemplated'' that under Reno's plan the gym would be demolished
with the roof collapsed within the first five hours of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Potts said he, too, was surprised to see the tanks taking out
huge chunks of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, 'What are they doing going into the building? Is
there an emergency? I wasn't sure what the reason was, absent an
emergency,'' Potts said.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell showed Potts a letter from the FBI on-site commanders in
Waco that recommended a tank crew for the FBI Shield of Bravery.
The letter says that the crew ``slowly and methodically began
dismantling the gymnasium in a very deliberate and surgical
manner'' at great personal risk to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Potts said he was surprised by the language in the letter of
commendation, saying that the destruction of the gym was
inconsistent with the approved plan of operation as he understood
it ``unless there were exigent circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Although tank crews reported taking heavy gunfire from Branch
Davidians, Potts said he was not aware of any conditions that would
have required the on-site commanders to change the plan without
conferring with Justice Department officials in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In other videotaped testimony, former FBI director William
Sessions and former deputy director Floyd I. Clarke both testified
that FBI agents in charge at scenes are given wide latitude to use
discretion when emergency situations arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a plan is in place, the people at the scene have a
tremendous amount of discretion,'' Clarke said. ``I don't think
there was a decision made to destroy the building,'' Clarke said.
``If there was a decision to do that, I would expect notification
from Waco.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clarke acknowledged that in 30 years with the FBI, he
never told an on-site commander that he could deviate from an
approved plan without permission from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The plan approved by Reno called for the slow and deliberate
introduction of tear gas through compound windows, if possible,
using booms on the military vehicles. No weapons would be displayed
by the agents and a loud speaker would announce that the moves were
not meant to be threatening or constitute an assault.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell asked several of the former FBI officials, including
Sessions, if they couldn't see a conflict in announcing that the
tear-gas operation was not an assault as a tank ``is driving into
your living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions conceded that under those circumstances, ``I would
assume it was an assault.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan Reno approved called for the systematic destruction of
the building only 48 hours after it was determined that the tear
gas had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh and 75 followers, including 21 children, died later than
morning after a fire swept through the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in the lawsuit also are alleging that the government
failed to have a plan to fight the fire and held back firefighters
once it began.
</P>
<P>
   Government attorneys have said that the Davidians started the
fire and died in a fulfillment of Koresh's apocalyptic prophecies.
The fire trucks were held back because of the Davidian gunfire
earlier in the day, government officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions disagreed with Caddell's characterization that the
tanks had embarked on a course to intentionally destroy the
building. He said some damage to the building was necessary to
insert the gas and to create what the government thought would be
escape routes for the Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way anybody contemplated anything other than to
get those people out safely. It was not the beginning of the
systematic destruction of the compound in a way that was not
consistent with the plan,'' Sessions said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that FBI commander Jeffrey Jamar and other FBI officials
in Waco had ``implied authority'' to order demolition of portions
of the compound without higher approval if they thought that was
necessary to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell called FBI agent Joseph Servel Jr. to the stand in the
afternoon session, a move that pleasantly surprised U.S. District
Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. after a day of videotaped deposition
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``A live witness?'' the judge asked.
</P>
<P>
   Servel said he was the leader of a tank team that fired about 65
``ferret rounds'' of tear gas into windows on the back side of
Mount Carmel. While he later learned that some military pyrotechnic
tear-gas devices were fired that morning, Servel said his crew
fired only non-explosive ferret rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell presented a snippet of an April 7, 1993, video taken by
an FBI SWAT team member. It captured a briefing by a supervisor who
had spoken with negotiators and Jamar the day before. The
supervisor noted that plans to punch holes in the building had been
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``... The reason headquarters rejected that is because it would
be perceived by the Davidians, the people inside, as an act of
aggression or an attack,'' the supervisor said. ``They're using
that as a defense already, that they were attacked by the ATF. So
for us to go in and punch holes in and throw gas in there, they're
gonna perceive that as an attack and they will retaliate, with
gunfire...''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor said instead a fence would be put around Mount
Carmel and tear gas rounds would be lobbed into the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're accomplishing the same thing by getting gas in there
... in a less aggressive manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
