<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GAS-PRICES-ART-NYT &LR;      06-22 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS STEP UP SCRUTINY OF PRICE INCREASES IN GAS MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   with EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Oil prices showed no sign of retreating Thursday, a day
after OPEC decided to increase production, and lawmakers stepped up
calls for investigations into ``price gouging'' in the gasoline
market.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are especially concerned about the Midwest. While pump
prices are at record levels in much of the nation, they have
skyrocketed in the Midwest. Retail prices in Milwaukee and Chicago
have soared as much as 70 cents a gallon in the last two months
because of pipeline disruptions and a federally mandated switch to
a new cleaner-burning fuel that incorporates ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 2.6 percent rise in crude-oil prices Thursday, the
price of gasoline in the Midwest may have finally leveled off, some
officials said. New supplies are coming on the market, refiners
have increased production of the new gas and wholesale prices have
fallen.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission, which is investigating whether the
soaring prices are a result of industry collusion, expects to
report its findings to Congress by the third week of July, said
Robert Pitofsky, the agency's chairman. The FTC is expected to
begin issuing subpoenas within days, and some lawmakers want
industry chief executives to be required to testify on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, facing a political firestorm over the issue,
said he believed that there was ``no economic explanation'' for the
high Midwest prices. Vice President Al Gore, the presumed
Democratic presidential candidate, reiterated his belief that
industry collusion was fueling the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials blame supply problems, low inventories of
gasoline and the June 1 switch to the cleaner fuel, and they point
to a recent Congressional Research Service report suggesting that
the cleaner-gas mandate and pipeline problems have added 50 cents
to the price of a gallon of gas in some parts of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have been high this year, following OPEC's move
in March 1999 to reduce oil production. But since the beginning of
May, average pump prices for regular gasoline have soared almost 30
cents nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange on
Thursday, the price of crude oil for August delivery rose 82 cents,
to $32.19 a barrel. And the price of gasoline for July delivery,
which reflects wholesale prices, soared more than 4 cents, to
$1.0813 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up has become a major political issue, as Gore and
officials at the Environmental Protection Agency have sought to
deflect criticism that the high prices are a result of the mandate
for cleaner-burning reformulated gas. They have suggested that some
companies are making money at the expense of drivers.
</P>
<P>
   For certain, industry profits are soaring. About three months
ago, Wall Street analysts were predicting second-quarter profits of
$5.5 billion for the seven major U.S. oil companies, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks corporate earnings. Now
analysts are predicting that combined profits will be about $6.5
billion. That compares with about $3 billion during last year's
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts are skeptical that federal officials will find
evidence of illegal behavior. ``This is a political sop,'' said
Philip K. Verleger, who has served as a consultant to the FTC and
the state of California on past investigations into high gas prices
and is now a senior analyst for the Brattle Group, an economic
consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass. ``They aren't going to find
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican
presidential nominee and a former oilman, has taken almost $1.5
million in political contributions from the oil and gas industry,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics. Bush said he
welcomed the investigation into industry collusion but blamed the
Clinton administration for failing to persuade OPEC to increase
production. Lawmakers in Congress also took a swipe at OPEC on
Thursday, saying they would introduce a bill to allow the Justice
Department to look into possible antitrust violations by the
cartel.
</P>
<P>
   But OPEC ministers in Vienna, Austria, who met this week and
agreed to raise production by 708,000 barrels a day, complain that
the United States is to blame for the high prices. They blame the
new cleaner-burning gas rules, which affect about one-third of the
nation, and they also contend that American refiners cut back
purchases significantly last year to avoid buying oil at prices
they considered temporarily high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not an OPEC problem,'' said Ali Rodriguez, Venezuela's
oil minister and the president of OPEC. ``In the last year,
refinery runs have been very low and we saw a great decline'' in
inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Saud Nasser Al-Sabah, Kuwait's oil minister, said: ``This
is also a responsibility of the major consuming countries. They
should get their own houses in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Top Saudi officials, who have been the leading advocates of
production increases, say they are alarmed about prices they
believe are too high to be stable. But they contend that the supply
of crude oil is only a peripheral part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   One Saudi official contended that U.S. oil companies refused to
invest in added capacity even when refining margins were high, and
asserted that the cleaner-burning fuel rules were imposed without
paying attention to the situation of U.S. oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Since their decision to increase production three months ago,
OPEC ministers have said they want to keep oil trading within a
band from $22 to $28. But Saudi officials believe that the price
band is being constantly tested by the markets, and they now
believe that they should not be held hostage by short-term price
movements, especially those being driven by speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's oil minister, Bijan Namdar Zanganeh, was more
conciliatory. Having angrily denounced Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson in March, Zanganeh went out of his way Thursday to note
that there was no external pressure on OPEC this time, and said
that was the reason Iran had no difficulty in joining the OPEC
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and me and Mr. Richardson have all learned a lesson,''
Zanganeh told reporters. ``It was a very good test for the market.
Many sources expected the volume of production would decrease the
price of oil significantly, but it hasn't happened. It means we
have some new factors in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought the biggest culprit behind high oil prices
was, he said, ``RFG,'' referring to the new cleaner-burning
reformulated gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
