<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2106 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-ART-     06-22 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-ART-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPOINTMENT OF SPECIAL COUNSEL RECOMMENDED IN GORE FUND-RAISING
INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT13 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of the Justice Department's campaign
finance unit has recommended that Attorney General Janet Reno
appoint a special counsel to investigate Vice President Al Gore's
political fund-raising activities during the 1996 presidential
campaign, government officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Conrad Jr., who heads the agency's campaign finance
team, told Reno in a meeting late last week that new evidence had
revived questions about whether Gore has been truthful to
investigators about his fund-raising activities. Gore has been
questioned five times under oath, most recently in a four-hour
interview on April 18 at the vice-presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were dissatisfied with Gore's answers during the
interview, which was conducted in a far more confrontational manner
than previous sessions had been, the officials said. At times, Gore
reacted angrily to the questions, which covered an array of issues
related to the vice president's fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Of the interview, one official said: ``It was sure as hell a
different approach. It was real confrontational and put him on the
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The rekindled inquiry has revived a long-running internal battle
within the Justice Department over the issue and, according to
several current and former officials, has pitted Conrad against
powerful advisers to Reno. Among them is Lee J. Radek, the head of
the unit within the Justice Department that investigates public
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, according to several current and former Justice
Department officials, has expressed frustration over what he views
as resistance from his superiors in the Justice Department. The
officials said that Conrad had been told to avoid putting his views
in writing and at times felt stymied in his efforts to communicate
directly with top officials.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the resurgence of an issue that had seemed to be
running out of steam could not come at a worse time for Gore. The
vice president has been attempting to reinvigorate his presidential
candidacy, and the reemergence of campaign finance problems could
hobble him with legal trouble and provide a potent weapon for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, campaigning in Minnesota on Thursday, was asked by a
reporter whether he knew about the recommendation for appointment
of a special counsel. ``You're privy to news I don't have,'' he
said, seeming a bit startled by the question..
</P>
<P>
   James F. Neal, Gore's personal lawyer, did not return calls
placed to his law office in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, James E. Kennedy, a vice-presidential
spokesman, said his office had ``received no word from the
Department of Justice about the reported campaign finance
development.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, the vice president has cooperated fully with the
investigation every step of the way,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department spokesman, Myron Marlin, declined to
comment Thursday on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign finance task force has been investigating
irregularities in the 1996 election cycle since 1996,'' Marlin
said. ``That investigation is still ongoing and has prosecuted 25
people to date. It is inappropriate to comment on ongoing matters
or internal deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is no indication that Reno has reached a decision
on Conrad's recommendation. In 1997 and then again in 1998, the
attorney general refused to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Gore, over the objections of FBI Director Louis J.
Freeh and several senior Justice Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   The rules have changed since then. In place of the independent
counsel law, which expired in 1999, the Justice Department has
adopted regulations that give Reno the sole authority to appoint an
outside prosecutor if she determines that the department would have
a conflict of interest in an investigation, or if she decides that
an outside inquiry is in the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgent inquiry is focused on several issues that the
Justice Department has investigated for years. These include a
fund-raising appearance by Gore's at a Buddhist temple in
California in 1996; fund-raising coffees for campaign donors at the
White House; and whether Gore was truthful when he told
investigators he was unaware that fund-raising telephone calls he
made from the White House in 1995 and 1996 were intended to raise
both soft money, for general campaign purposes, and hard money, for
specific re-election expenses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Conrad is the fourth lawyer to head the Justice Department's
Campaign Financing Task Force. In late December, he replaced David
Vicinanzo, a former New Hampshire prosecutor. Vicinanzo succeeded
Charles LaBella, who had repeatedly and unsuccessfully pressed for
the appointment of an independent counsel in 1998 and quit in
frustration. Laura Ingersoll was the first task force leader.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1992, Conrad had served as a federal prosecutor in
Charlotte, N.C., where he was the chief of the office's criminal
division. He has prosecuted a wide variety of criminal cases,
including public corruption, white-collar fraud, money laundering,
organized crime and drug-trafficking cases. Colleagues have
described him as both aggressive and candid.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad would not discuss the matter on Thursday. In testimony
before a Senate panel on Wednesday, he was asked whether he had
discussed the appointment of a special counsel related to Gore or
the questions that he posed to Gore in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The matters that I inquired into on April 18 are pending
matters,'' he replied. ``I don't feel at liberty to discuss the
subject matter of the examination.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has remained a highly confidential matter
within the Justice Department and the FBI. Freeh, who has long
urged an independent investigation of Gore, has met privately in
recent weeks with lawmakers in the House and Senate to avoid being
asked to appear as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh, whose relationship with the White House and with Reno has
eroded badly over the issue, told the lawmakers that he did not
want to be drawn into a public discussion of a pending inquiry, and
that he did not want give the White House further cause for
complaint. FBI officials would not comment on the matter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's refusal to appoint an independent counsel to investigate
campaign finance has proven to be one of the most controversial
issues of her tenure. Republicans have at times demanded her
resignation, accusing her of attempting to protect the White House
from a politically perilous inquiry. House and Senate committees
are continuing to investigate the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the controversy has resurfaced with the release
of memos from Freeh and LaBella in which both officials urged the
appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vice president attended the fund-raising event at
the Hsi Lai Temple event on April 29, 1996, investigators did not
ask him about it until the April 18 interview.
</P>
<P>
   The event, a luncheon attended by about 100 community leaders,
became one of the first important campaign finance controversies to
embroil the vice president. It is unclear what Gore has told
investigators about the event that has drawn renewed scrutiny. In
public statements, Gore at first said the event was intended for
community outreach, not fund raising. Later he said it was
``finance related.''
</P>
<P>
   An official with knowledge of the interview said on Thursday
that Gore was also asked about more than 100 coffee sessions at the
White House used to reward past donors. Gore insisted in the
interview that the coffees had not been fund-raisers, an official
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The event at the temple was not among the subjects the Justice
Department was investigating in late 1997 when Reno first
considered seeking an independent counsel to investigate Gore. In
that deliberative phase, Reno pondered a single question: Whether
45 telephone fund-raising phone calls that were made from his White
House office had violated an 1883 civil service law that barred
elected officials from using government offices to raise donations
covered by federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   Over La Bella's and Freeh's strong objections, Reno concluded
that Gore's actions had been lawful. ``Evidence found by the
investigators shows that the vice president solicited only soft
money in these calls, not hard money,'' she said. Soft money
donations fall outside federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, campaign finance prosecutors focused on
whether Gore had lied to investigators during the initial inquiry
into his fund-raising phone calls. Most of Reno's advisers,
including Robert S. Litt, a highly influential political deputy at
the department, urged her to appoint an independent counsel. But
again, Reno declined to appoint an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's aides are continuing to investigate whether Gore lied
when he insisted that he did not know the difference between
regulated ``hard money'' and unrestricted ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had repeatedly told investigators he believed his White
House telephone calls were only used to raise soft-money donations,
which are not limited by campaign law. But a belatedly disclosed
fund-raising memo by David M. Strauss, a deputy chief of staff to
the vice president, suggested that in the 1997 inquiry, Gore might
not have been truthful about what he knew about his phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   According to other recently released documents, the former White
House chief of staff, Leon A. Panetta, and three other witnesses
recalled that the hard money/soft money breakdown was discussed at
a meeting where Gore was present. Ten or eleven other participants
in the meeting could not recall that discussion. Panetta also
recalled that the vice president seemed attentive when there was a
discussion of how money would be split among party accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1988 interview with the FBI, Gore said he had often been
inattentive to detail at fund-raising meetings and that he
sometimes missed parts of them, notes from the interview show. He
told the FBI that ``he drank a lot of iced tea during meetings,
which could have necessitated a restroom break.''
</P>
<P>
   An official with knowledge of the Gore inquiry said that some
investigators were ``punching holes in the iced tea defense.''
Another official said that some FBI investigators ``are really
pushing the perjury stuff, because they are convinced he lied to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vice president's April 18 interview with
investigators, Gore played down the significance to reporters,
saying he was not a focus of the investigation. ``I answered every
question,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
