<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-22 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FANS HAVE SHORTSTOP CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A -Rod! A-Rod! A-Rod!
</P>
<P>
   This chant could be heard from the famous First Base Dugout a
Cappella Choir during batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Having been taught to take nothing for granted, a journalist
ambled over to inquire, ``Say, just who is this A-Rod, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers know when they are being twitted. The fans did not
dignify the question with a response.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you already have a shortstop,'' the journalist persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's broken,'' one fan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to move on,'' another fan said.
</P>
<P>
   Cold. Very cold. But realistic, nevertheless. Even before Rey
Ordonez was injured, the Mets were already a logical candidate for
the future services of Alex Rodriguez, known to all and sundry as
A-Rod.
</P>
<P>
   A-Rod for Rich Rod! A-Rod for Rich Rod! A-Rod for Rich Rod!
</P>
<P>
   The choir also delivered this chant before the Mets played the
Phillies last night at Shea Stadium. They were referring to Rich
Rodriguez, the resident mop-up pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Rich-Rod trade reached the ears of Steve Phillips, the
general manager of the Mets, who was chatting with reporters over
the din of the public address system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't respond to trade rumors,'' Phillips said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   There are trade rumors all over the place, what with the Yankees
making feints toward Juan Gonzalez of Detroit and fakes toward
Sammy Sosa of the Cubs. The Yankees probably cannot afford A-Rod,
currently in the employ of the Seattle Mariners, but soon to become
a free agent. He is a friend of Derek Jeter, but the two are not
likely to wind up together on the left side of the Yankee infield.
Meanwhile, the cold, cold hearts behind the first base dugout at
Shea are on the case: A-Rod! A-Rod! A-Rod!
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez has, however, just become even more expensive due
to the broken left ulna suffered by Rey Ordonez on May 30. The arm
is not healing, and a plate and screws must be installed on Monday,
which will keep him out for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez is current in the first year of a four-year, $19 million
contract. Rodriguez, who can actually hit, will come even higher.
Before Ordonez was hurt, his batting average had regressed from
.258 last year to .188 this year, but the Mets' players appreciate
his fielding skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the best I've ever seen,'' said Todd Pratt, who started
at catcher last night. ``I saw Ozzie Smith when I started in '92.
Rey makes plays look ordinary that are great for other shortstops.
He's got great feet, great hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been struggling with the bat, but if he gets a little
more confidence, he could be among the greatest shortstops,'' Pratt
said. ``He's worth 15 or 20 wins a season. I don't know if you can
say that about anybody else. I see it when I catch especially. He
lowers the earned run average for every pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Ordonez, who may be several years older than
his listed age of 27, does not come across as a student of the
game. If he could bunt at all, the Mets might have won their uphill
struggle against the Braves last October.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who can keep tapping a golf ball in the air with
his wedge, could probably bunt better than Ordonez. In fact, Woods
has so much free time on his hands that he was out caddying for his
college roommate in a tournament near Las Vegas Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Tiger needs a hobby. Meanwhile, the Mets do not seem
locked in to Melvin Mora and Kurt Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done an adequate job but we're not committed to
anything,'' Phillips said. ``We're continuing to evaluate the
alternatives, to see if we could upgrade what we already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora might look like a regular if he played shortstop for a week
or two straight. And there is the very real possibility that
Ordonez, before he was injured, had already bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his minimal offensive skills, the Mets disappear into
a nether region at the bottom of the batting order. Weak hitters in
the National League only get worse from year after year of batting
ahead of the pitcher, rarely getting fat pitches. Ninth-place
hitters in the American League, with its designated hitter gimmick,
see better pitches because the top of the order is looming ahead.
You could call it the Scott Brosius Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   There are surely teams that would be thrilled to have Rey
Ordonez scooping up just about everything _ if his arm heals at a
healthy angle, that is.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Phillips and the Mets cannot avoid that growing
chorus that chants, quite rightfully: A-Rod! A-Rod! A-Rod!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
