<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIESEL-POLLUTION0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refined diesel pushed by FedsBy Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal proposals to make smelly diesel-powered trucks
and buses as clean as family cars represent the biggest step since
the advent of unleaded gas to clean up vehicle emissions, several
public interest and other groups declared Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental and public health experts said the new rules could
prevent thousands of cases of cancer, cardiovascular-related deaths
and tens of thousands of hospitalizations and emergency room visits
for asthma and other chronic lung problems.
</P>
<P>
   The experts and other representatives from a smorgasbord of
environmental and public health groups, business organizations and
state agencies spoke Thursday at a public hearing in Atlanta by the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency on its proposed new rules
requiring low-sulfur diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaner fuel would mean that for the first time heavy-duty
trucks and buses could use pollution control devices, such as
catalytic converters, to meet emission standards just as passenger
cars have been doing for the past 25 years. The devices are
sensitive to sulfur and won't work unless sulfur levels in the fuel
are dramatically reduced.
</P>
<P>
   When the new rules are fully implemented by 2010, it will be
equivalent to removing the pollution generated by 13 million of
today's heavy-duty trucks and buses, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   The smelly, thick clouds of exhaust emissions from the vehicles
would be a thing of the past, said June Deen of the American Lung
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules will result in a very, very significant reduction in
air pollutants, and can prevent thousands of premature deaths
around the nation,'' said Ron Methier, head of the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division's air protection branch. ``It
will also greatly benefit our efforts to clean up the air in
Atlanta and Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in mid-2006, the EPA's proposal would cut sulfur levels
in diesel fuel by 97 percent. The rules also require a 95 percent
reduction in diesel-vehicle nitrogen oxide emissions (ingredients
that form ground-level ozone) and a 90 percent reduction in
particulate emissions, or soot, beginning in the 2007 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel engine manufacturers can meet the new standards, said
Marie Valentine of DaimlerChrysler Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Oil industry representatives, however, said Thursday the
proposed standards could raise diesel fuel prices by 7 to 10 cents
per gallon, instead of the EPA's estimate of 3 to 4 cents a gallon.
The cost would hurt anyone who has to fill up a tractor-trailer
rig, garbage truck or school bus, the oil spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they said, the EPA was going ``too far too fast.''
The new rules could cause fuel shortages as oil companies strive to
meet standards for low sulfur in both gasoline (required by 2004)
and diesel fuel, they warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The EPA proposal is a recipe for enormous marketplace
problems,'' said John Medley of the ExxonMobil Refining &AMP; Supply
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
