<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Court Rules in AT&AMP;T's Favor Over Sharing of Cable Lines
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court ruled that local governments may not
force companies that offer Internet access to share their
telecommunications lines with rival cable modem providers. But in
ruling in favor of AT&AMP;T in its case against Portland, Ore., the
court defined the cable broadband business as a
``telecommunications service,'' a distinction some industry experts
say may ultimately force such businesses, including AT&AMP;T, to open
their lines to competitors on a national level.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Profit Rises 27 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Profiting from gains in stock trading and investment banking,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter reported second-quarter earnings that
were up 27 percent compared with results in the period a year
earlier but down 6 percent from those in the first quarter.
Although the results exceeded forecasts, the company's shares
dropped $2.4375, to $83.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Court Upholds Law on HMO Suits
</P>
<P>
   In an important test case, a federal appeals court has upheld a
Texas law allowing patients to sue health maintenance organizations
in state court for medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn Raises Bid for Nabisco Group
</P>
<P>
   Carl Icahn, the financier who owns 10 percent of Nabisco Group,
sweetened his offer for the company, the second time in two days he
has raised his bid. On Wednesday, Icahn offered $28 a share for
Nabisco Group. He then increased that bid, saying he was prepared
to pay 88 percent of the after-tax cash price that Nabisco Group
received for its food company, Nabisco Holdings. Both Philip Morris
and a joint venture of Danone and Cadbury Schweppes have bid on the
food unit.
</P>
<P>
   Profit-Taking Sends Stocks Down
</P>
<P>
   Stocks declined as investors cashed in on recent gains,
particularly in technology shares. The Nasdaq composite index
tumbled 127.17 points, or 3.1 percent, to 3,936.84. The Dow Jones
industrial average declined 121.62 points, or 1.2 percent, to
10,376.12. And the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was off 26.95
points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,452.18.
</P>
<P>
   Snapple Division to Be Spun Off
</P>
<P>
   Triarc said it would spin off a part of its beverage division,
which includes the Snapple, Mistic and Royal Crown brands. Shares
in the new company, to be called the Snapple Beverage Group and
consisting of up to 20 percent of Triarc's soft drink holdings,
would be sold during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   No Big Changes Seen at Universal
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi, the French conglomerate that is buying Seagram, said
that it planned to make no significant changes in top management at
Seagram's Universal film and television operations. Although there
had been speculation that Ron Meyer, the president of Universal
Studios, would depart, Pierre Lescure, who will be in charge of the
combined company's film units, said he was intent on keeping Meyer
and his top executives.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo to Sell 20 Percent of Burger King
</P>
<P>
   Diageo, the British food and spirits company, said it planned to
sell a 20 percent stake in Burger King, the fast-food chain. The
sale could be a first step in an eventual spinoff, a goal of the
parent company for years.
</P>
<P>
   Four Airlines Form an Alliance
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines, Air France, Aeromexico and Korean Air announced
an alliance that will stretch across three continents in an attempt
to compete with partnerships already formed by rivals. The four
airlines will share airport lounges, pool frequent-flier miles
programs, and collaborate on schedule coordination and other
ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
