<HEADER>
A2117 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LAD     06-22 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS LOOKING FOR REDEMPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; When the green flag finally drops on the NASCAR Winston West
field at Irwindale Speedway on Saturday night, four area drivers
will be fighting for a victory in the Home Depot 250.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those drivers, Bill Sedgwick of Acton and Jerry Cain of
Canyon Country, are regulars on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Woodside of Saugus, the defending Winston West champion,
will be turning double duty  &UR; _ &LR;  at Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma
during the day and at Irwindale later that night.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth area driver is Ben Walker of Canyon Country, a NASCAR
Super Late Model driver at Irwindale who has four victories in two
seasons at the half-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old Sedgwick brings tons of experience to the race.
He has 17 victories and 15 poles during his career on the Winston
West Series. Still, he considers himself a student of racing in
some aspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my experience is on short tracks,'' said Sedgwick, who has
two Winston West titles. ``We didn't have super speedways out here
when I was learning how to race. So I'm on a learning curve for
someone's who supposed to be a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   In what Sedgwick has described as a disappointing season, coming
to Irwindale might be just the thing to turn his year around.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick turned in two top-10 performances last year at
Irwindale, proving that he feels more at home on short tracks
rather than super speedways. In the June 19 race at Irwindale,
Sedgwick fell one lap short of winning as Steve Portegna passed him
on the last lap. On Aug. 21 1999, Sedgwick finished sixth at
Irwindale. He led 19 laps of that race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy this track. It's a state-of-the-art facility,''
Sedgwick said. ``There are three or four grooves to race on. It's
not a single-file race track. There's a lot of side-by-side racing.
It's the way the track's designed.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodside, 29, finds himself pulling a unique doubleheader. He
will race in the NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Series Snap-On
Tools/AAA 200 at Sears Point Raceway, a 1.949-mile road course,
then fly to L.A. and compete in the Home Depot 250 and make his
season debut on the Winston West Series.
</P>
<P>
   Woodside, who is fifth in points and has one win on the
Southwest Series, has been struggling lately. Through the battles
though, Woodside said he has been enjoying his time on the
Southwest Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every race is like a sprint. There are no pit stops. It's a
lot like Saturday night Late Models,'' said Woodside, a former
NASCAR Sportsman champion at the now defunct Saugus Speedway.
``We've been struggling a little bit and not qualifying well. When
you do that, you deserve whatever you get.''
</P>
<P>
   While Woodside appears to be excited about racing at Irwindale
Speedway and in a Winston West race, his history at Irwindale has
been far from successful. In two races at Irwindale, his best
finish was 10th. His 13th place at Irwindale on June 19 was his
second worst finish of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Leaders of the pack: The winners of both Winston West races
at Irwindale in 1999 will be returning for Saturday night's race.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Cameron of El Cajon, who won on Aug. 21, is ninth in
points on the Winston West circuit this year. Steve Portegna of
Sparks, Nev., is third in points. Both drivers won their first
Winston West races at Irwindale Speedway last year. Neither has
returned to victory lane in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Gaughan of Las Vegas leads the Winston West Series. In
his two previous races at Irwindale Speedway, Gaughan finished
ninth and 15th.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Mears entered in Home Depot 250: Making his debut in
Winston West racing will be a familiar auto racing name &UR; _ &LR;  Mears.
Clint Mears, son of former Indianapolis 500 winner Rick Mears, is
entered in the Home Depot 250.
</P>
<P>
   He's a veteran of open-wheel competition, having driven in the
Toyota Atlantic and Indy Lights circuit. However, he will be making
his first appearance in stock car racing Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he is inexperienced in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   He tested for a team on the NASCAR Craftsman Truck series in
1996. In fact, Mears said he is hoping for a full-time Truck Series
ride in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, however, his stint in Winston West
competition might only last this one race. He said there's also a
possibility he could race in the November event at Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   He has tested only once on the Irwindale track. After competing
in open-wheel cars, Mears says the main difference in the two types
of cars is speed. The open-wheel cars go much faster than the
Winston West stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can hustle these cars around the track and drive a
little harder,'' Mears said. ``You have to drive aggressively. I
need to be smooth and more consistent so I can be there at the end.
I just want to finish and finish well if we can. I don't know the
drivers and I don't know what they're like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
