u w BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-NYT     06-22 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL PASSES PARTISAN CAMPAIGN DISCLOSURE BILL
</HEADLINE>
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Ways and Means Committee on Thursday
approved along party lines a Republican-written bill to require
tax-exempt groups that conduct political advocacy to disclose their
donors and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to broker a bipartisan bill collapsed Thursday
afternoon, and Democrats criticized the committee's legislation as
unworkable, unwieldy and unconstitutional. The margin was 23 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   The vote clouds the outlook for Congress approving legislation
this year that would at least end a provision in the tax law that
permits a growing number of secretive groups to raise money, buy
television and radio advertisements and conduct polling, but not
report their contributors or spending.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising vote two weeks ago, the Senate approved
legislation sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that imposed
such a disclosure requirement on scores of groups formed under
Section 527 of the Internal Revenue Code.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from House Republican moderates and the Senate
vote, the Republican leadership in the House reversed itself and
promised to allow a vote before the July 4 recess on a broader
political advocacy disclosure bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved on Thursday fits that description, Republican
leaders said, because it goes well beyond the narrow issue of the
Section 527 organizations to cover other tax-exempt groups, from
labor unions and trade associations, to the Christian Coalition and
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have a right to know what groups are running ads or
writing letters, and who is paying for them,'' said Rep. Bill
Archer, a Texas Republican who is the committee's chairman. ``It
shouldn't be disclosure for some and secrecy for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, organizations that spend more than $10,000 on
political activities would have to disclose contributions of $1,000
or more. Currently, there is no such requirement. The bill would
require all Section 527 organizations to disclose contributions and
expenses of $200 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would take effect upon enactment, leaving open
at least the possibility it could be used in the current election
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately complained that the legislation was overly
broad in defining what type of political activity or advocacy would
require disclosure. Democratic leaders also criticized the bill for
singling out labor unions, traditional Democratic benefactors, but
not for-profit corporations, whose political leanings run
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``By covering educational activities clearly beyond
electioneering activities, the bill would trigger very intrusive
donor disclosure for all advocacy groups, including those not
inherently political,'' said Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, the
House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans rejected that criticism, saying the Ways and
Means Committee did not have jurisdiction over corporations in what
would amount to wide-ranging campaign finance legislation.
Republican leaders retorted that Democrats were hypocrites for
opposing the broad disclosure requirements they have been
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``When push comes to shove, their vote clearly shows that these
Democrats are all for disclosure for their political enemies, but
not for their big labor campaign contributors nor their political
allies,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the majority whip, who
opposes the bill on the grounds it violates constitutional
free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of bipartisan legislation to tighten the nation's
campaign finance and disclosure laws expressed concern over the
sharp party-line attacks traded over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any response to this problem needs to be even-handed and
bipartisan,'' Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., said. ``This base
bill should be a good starting point, but we need to work toward a
consensus and build a bipartisan solution.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he was disappointed by the committee's vote: ``My
recommendation is to go back and if they can't agree on full
disclosure, at least attack the Section 527's, the most egregious
manifestations of campaign finance abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   He is to meet on Friday morning with House Republicans,
including Rep Michael Castle of Delaware and Amo Houghton of New
York, who drafted the bill passed on Thursday, to try to work out a
compromise that can win a majority in both chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Mitch McConnell of Kentucky and Gordon Smith of Oregon,
both Republicans, have proposed their own broad-based political
advocacy disclosure bill. Senate Democrats and McCain oppose it, in
part because it does not cover corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to expand the scope so long as everybody is
included,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic
leader.
</P>
<P>
   When the House bill comes up next week, probably on Tuesday,
Rep. Lloyd Doggett, a Texas Democrat on the Ways and Means panel,
said the bare minimum should be addressing the shadowy political
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't clean up all the mess in the campaign finance system,
but we should deal with the most horrendous consequences,'' Doggett
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
