<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TV-FBN-ABC-NYT &LR;      06-22 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FBN-ABC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC WILL TRY MIX OF COMEDY AND FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The roster of ``Monday Night Football'' during 30 seasons
featured a dozen announcers, from Keith Jackson to Dan Dierdorf.
Frank Gifford endured the longest, Don Meredith warbled and Howard
Cosell enraged and outraged.
</P>
<P>
   But Al Michaels was the last voice standing when Boomer Esiason
was fired in March and Don Ohlmeyer, the show's former producer,
was rehired to revive the series, which was ABC's highest-rated in
prime-time until ``Who Wants to Be A Millionaire'' transformed
network television.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, ABC altered the perception of a series that thought of
itself as half-sports, half-entertainment by hiring Dennis Miller,
an irreverent comic known for his witty and profane rants, to work
in the booth with Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ABC also hired Dan Fouts, the former San Diego Chargers
quarterback, for the traditional analyst's role. But Miller's
hiring was the type of bold and risky gambit ABC officials believe
the show needs to be unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know football like a nerd,'' Miller, who stars in a weekly
HBO program, said Thursday in a conference call from Los Angeles.
``I've watched it my whole life. I have a nerd's knowledge, but I
don't know what kind of intestinal fortitude it takes to go across
the middle. So I won't try to pontificate about what someone should
or shouldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he would not inject his views on politics, which he
freely discusses on his HBO show. ``I'm on this to escape
politics,'' he said. ``The reason I watch football is to get away
from that, to see a black-and-white resolution. I'm going to be the
furthest thing from political.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Miller and Fouts caps a three-month talent
search that began with Ohlmeyer's looking to hire Jimmy Johnson and
Bill Parcells. Ohlmeyer maintained a level of secrecy about
prospective analysts rare in the sports and entertainment
businesses while auditioning 15 to 20 candidates for each job in a
small studio in Burbank. Each candidate analyzed a tape of last
January's Tennessee-Buffalo American Football Conference
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was originally on Ohlmeyer's list of candidates as
someone who might be a guest a few times during the season. Said
Michaels, ``I walked out of there thinking that Dennis knew as much
about the National Football League as anybody we've brought in.''
He added, ``Don and I walked out during a break in the session and
we were speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   Fouts is a conventional choice for analyst. But his previous
work on National Football League games for CBS and his recent
college football stint for ABC had not put him on the fast track
for ``Monday Night,'' pro football's highest rated series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I sat down and met with him and did the workout
sessions, all I had to work with what was I saw on tapes,''
Ohlmeyer said. ``I saw a competent professional, but when I pushed
him in the workout session, I saw sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Dan: `The Dan Fouts I see on these tapes is not the one
I want on `Monday Night.' I want more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fouts has called college games with Jackson and Brent Musburger.
``I'm not afraid of anything,'' Fouts said. ``And last I checked,
Dennis was about 125 pounds, so we'll be able to shut him up
without any problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the others who auditioned were Rush Limbaugh, the
conservative radio talk show host, and Steve Young, the newly
retired 49ers quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer denied making any attempts to try to pry John Madden,
Terry Bradshaw, Howie Long or Cris Collinsworth from their Fox
Sports contracts, although Long said he had received a call seeking
his level of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered Rush very seriously,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``He
auditioned with Al, and to listen to two professional broadcasters,
both of whom use the English language correctly, talk about sports
was a pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he felt Limbaugh could not devote the time necessary
to the show. But he expects Limbaugh to make guest appearances.
</P>
<P>
   To augment Michaels, Miller and Fouts, Ohlmeyer hired Melissa
Stark, of ESPN, and Eric Dickerson, the former Los Angeles Rams and
Indianapolis Colts running back, as sideline reporters. On
Wednesday, Ohlmeyer dismissed Lesley Visser after her two seasons
on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer said he will push the booth and sideline teams to
create a more free-flowing telecast, altering the standard rhythm
of a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer insisted that the dramatic changes in ``Monday Night''
were not initiated to recreate the singular style of the series in
the 1970s, when Gifford, Cosell and Meredith were more carnival
stars than sportscasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard is gone and Don is counting his money in Santa Fe,'' he
said. Gifford's last season was 1997; in 1998, he played a minor
role in an ill-conceived pregame studio show. Dierdorf left after
the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to recreate the past,'' Ohlmeyer added.
``We're trying to create a telecast that's relevant, accessible and
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer's mandate for change was given to him by Howard Katz,
the president of ABC Sports and a longtime friend. ``I didn't enjoy
watching it last year as a fan,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``What I'm trying
to do is make sure that regardless of the score, people want to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there is no guarantee of success. What works well in
tryouts may not translate during the season. Ohlmeyer called the
new team a ``work in progress'' that he expects will hit its stride
in October. ``You can't manufacture chemistry,'' he said. ``It
takes time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
