<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEXAS-GRAHAM-EXECUTE-     06-22 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GRAHAM-EXECUTE-1ST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED MURDERER EXECUTED AFTER 19 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE-BOS  
 (Ledes with execution; budgeted as Death-Penalty)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL AND PATRICIA KILDAY HART GLOBE
CORREPSONDENT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ After a flurry of last-minute legal appeals failed,
convicted murderer Gary Graham was executed Thursday night as the
135th person put to death by Texas under Governor George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who had promised to ``fight like hell,'' saw his
execution delayed by several hours with a series of tense legal
maneuvers. He was convicted of shooting Bobby Lambert during a
bungled 1981 hold-up in a Safeway parking lot in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and top aides met in the governor's office in the state
capitol through the afternoon and early evening, waiting for the
legal process to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   After all the appeals had run out, a somber Bush appeared before
reporters Thursday night and recounted the evidence in the case.
``After considering the facts, I am confident justice is being
done,'' Bush said. ``May God bless the victims, the families of all
the victims, and may God bless Gary Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's legal wrangling began when the Bush's appointees on
the Texas Board of Paroles and Pardons refused Graham's request for
clemency. Minutes before the scheduled exection time of 6:30 pm
CDT, the US Surpreme Court ruled 5-4 not to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's lawyers then filed a civil suit in federal district
court here, alleging that the Texas clemency system was
unconstitutional. Though their argument was rejected, their appeal
forced a delay in the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Graham refused a last meal and struggled with the prison guards
who moved him to a final holding cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for the victims of Gary Graham's deadly crime spree
to have the closure they deserve and the finality that our criminal
justice system provides,'' said Texas Attorney General John Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham's defenders claimed that he had inadequate legal
representation at his trial, and was convicted on the basis of a
mistaken eyewitness's testimony. ``It is an extraordinary case of
an innocent person being executed,'' said his lawyer, Richard Burr.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case is the latest example of how Bush's presidential
candidacy has helped revive the debate over capital punishment in
America. Bush has presided over more executions than any other
governor since the death penalty was reintroduced in 1977, and
Graham is the 23rd person put to death by the state of Texas this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Though popular support for the death penalty has dipped
recently, it remains strong, with two-thirds of Americans
supporting capital punishment in recent polls. Vice President Al
Gore reaffirmed his support for the death penalty in a campaign
appearance in Minnesota Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a recent spate of studies and stories about the dozens of
convicts who have been freed from prison _ on eight occasions from
death row _ by the advent of DNA testing has raised questions about
the fast pace of executions in America and prompted calls for a
moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to acknowledge as much when he gave convicted
Texas murderer Ricky McGinn a 30-day stay of execution this month
so that DNA tests could be conducted on the evidence from that
case.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not likely to go away, as Texas is expected to
average an execution per week between now and Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to uphold the law of the land,'' Bush told reporters
during a campaign swing through California and Washington
Wednesday. ``If it costs me politically, it costs me politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to ``stand my ground in the face of (a) pretty
significant movement to try to undermine the credibility of the
death penalty in the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham waited out the final hours in the Huntsville, Texas,
prison with the group of witnesses he had invited to attend his
execution, including US Representative Shiela Jackson Lee, a
Democrat from Texas, and political activists Al Sharpton, Jesse
Jackson, and Bianca Jagger.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the prison, several hundred protesters chanted
anti-death penalty slogans, under the watchful eye of Texas Rangers
and state troopers. As the time for Graham's execution approached,
about a dozen protesters charged through police lines and were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before his execution, Graham ``was amazingly
upbeat,'' Jackson said. ``There were no tears shed. He had a sense
of inner peace. He feels he was being used as a kind of change
agent to expose the system. With every passing hour ... there is
mass education around the world about what is happening in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told reporters that he dreaded watching the execution,
but had agreed to attend at Graham's request. ``I feel some need to
go all the way to the end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas parole board, appointed by Bush and generally
respectful of his wishes, voted 14 to 3 to turn down Graham's
request for a 120-day reprieve, and by 12 to 5 to reject his plea
for a lesser penalty. The board also voted unanimously against
granting Graham an unconditional pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the governor cannot stop the execution without
a majority vote from the 18-member parole board. Aides noted that
under Texas law, the governor was powerless to step in and give
Graham a 30-day reprieve because the inmate had already received
one such stay from former Texas Governor Ann Richards in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's eleventh-hour appeal with the Supreme Court was turned
down by a 5-4 vote. Justices John Paul Stevens, David Souter, Ruth
Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer voting to grant the stay.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was convicted of shooting Lambert, a 53-year-old alleged
drug dealer, largely on the basis of a single, unwavering
eyewitness's testimony. Bernadine Skillern, the eyewitness in the
case, appeared on the NBC ``Today'' show Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a doubt in my mind,'' Skillern said. ``Mr.
Lambert was killed by Mr. Graham in the parking lot that night.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graham's lawyers claimed that the police unfairly influenced
Skillern's identification when they showed her a photo lineup of
five men. Four of the men in the photographs had facial hair; only
Graham fit her description of a clean-shaven killer.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was given the death penalty during the sentencing stage
of his trial after jurors heard of a two-week crime spree,
including several armed parking lot robberies and shootings, he
admittedly undertook in the days after Lambert's death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hart reported from Austin, Farrell from Washington, D.C. Wire
service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
