<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS TEXAS LAW ALLOWING PATIENTS TO HMOS
</HEADLINE>
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a major test case, a federal appeals court has
upheld a Texas law allowing patients to sue health maintenance
organizations in state court for medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   But the judges struck down a part of the law that gave patients
the right to an independent review of HMO decisions denying
benefits or coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision on Tuesday, the U.S. Fifth Circuit Court of
Appeals in New Orleans, ruled on the first of a wave of state laws
expanding the legal liability of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The court upheld the liability provisions of the Texas law by
construing them narrowly, allowing patients to sue an HMO for
providing substandard care, but holding that they may not sue when
a health plan denies care on the ground that it is not a covered
benefit or is not medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was not a complete victory for either patients or
insurance companies. The plaintiffs, all units of Aetna Inc., said
they were pleased with the decision. Consumer advocates said the
ruling showed why Congress must define patients' rights, including
the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   The court struck down a part of the Texas law that allows
patients to seek review, from an independent panel of medical
experts, when they are denied specific benefits. Federal law
prescribes the exclusive remedies for a denial of benefits, and
states may not supplement those remedies with ``a
quasi-administrative procedure for the review of such denial,'' the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling applies only to states in the Fifth
Circuit: Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi. But the reasoning could
have broad implications. Thirty-eight states have laws authorizing
independent, or external, review of health plan decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups, HMOs and insurance companies all support such
review as a way to resolve disputes without litigation. HMOs can
still provide such review voluntarily, and Aetna said it would do
so.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas law allowing patients to sue HMOs was the nation's
first, adopted in 1997. Since then at least six states _ Georgia,
California, Washington, Arizona, Oklahoma and Maine _ have passed
laws permitting patients to sue on various legal theories.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state laws are broader than the Texas statute and
allow suits in a wider range of disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The House and the Senate have passed bills to define patients'
rights, including the right to an independent review of HMO
decisions. The House bill would also make it easier for patients to
sue, but Republican senators said it would increase the cost of
health insurance. Negotiators from both houses are deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Griffiths, a spokeswoman for Aetna, said: ``We are pleased
with the decision by the court of appeals in the Texas case. The
decision confirms federal pre-emption of all state law claims for
benefit administration and coverage disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie W. Kanwit, a lawyer who represents insurance companies
and HMOs, said the ruling ``was the first major challenge to one of
the seven states that have laws allowing a person to sue an H.M.O.
for medical malpractice.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Hustead, a lawyer at the National Partnership for Women
and Families, a consumer advocacy group, said the ruling
``underscores the need for Congress to change'' a 1974 federal law
regulating employee benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under the court decision, a patient may sue an HMO in Texas for
providing care in a negligent way. But the patient may not sue if
the HMO refused to furnish any care at all, on the ground that the
care was not covered or not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Hustead said, this distinction is untenable. The U.S.
Supreme Court observed last week that, in the real world of medical
practice, many decisions involve questions of both treatment and
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a
consumer group, said: ``This is the most harmful federal court
decision to date affecting patients' rights. If the Supreme Court
does not reverse it, consumers will be left virtually helpless when
HMOs improperly deny or delay needed health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Patrick E. Higginbotham wrote the opinion for a
three-judge panel in the Texas case, Corporate Health Insurance vs.
Texas Department of Insurance. The other members of the panel were
Judges Robert M. Parker and Nancy F. Atlas.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Higginbotham upheld the liability provisions of the Texas
law as an exercise of the state's ``police power to protect its
citizens'' by regulating ``the quality of medical practice.'' The
law, he said, imposes liability on an HMO for certain negligent
acts committed by doctors acting as agents of the health plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
