<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO-, ANTI-DEATH PENALTY DEMONSTRATORS RALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ A tense standoff between supporters of Gary
Graham and law enforcement officials played out on the streets
outside the Walls Unit Thursday night as the capital murder
defendant waited to learn whether a last-chance appeal would save
his life.
</P>
<P>
   As Graham supporters chanted, ``George Bush, you can't hide, we
charge you with genocide,'' Department of Public Safety troopers
dressed in riot gear tried to keep the angry throng from breaking
through barricades.
</P>
<P>
   About five minutes before the scheduled 6 p.m. execution time,
several protesters raced past troopers but were quickly arrested as
they ran in front of TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Several U.S. flags were burned in front of troopers. And as the
delay continued, Graham's supporters raced onto the streets to
block traffic and run toward Ku Klux Klan members on the other side
of the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was executed shortly before 9 p.m. Thursday after several
appeals were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere became uneasy Thursday night after a relatively
calm afternoon. Groups such as the New Black Panthers and the Klan
played to the TV cameras but caused few incidents.
</P>
<P>
   With well-known Graham supporters such as the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.MDNM/ and Bianca Jagger on hand to witness the execution,
the streets resembled a politically charged festival.
</P>
<P>
   No violence was reported in the afternoon, although Graham
supporters marched to confront Klan members about an hour before
the scheduled execution, only to be turned back. Other than an
exchange of words, DPS troopers prevented any altercations.
</P>
<P>
   Max Gorkey, 20, of Houston, demonstrated in support of Graham,
who has taken the name Shaka Sankofa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here today to support Shaka,'' Gorkey said. ``The death
penalty is inherently racist. It is inherently classist. He is the
victim here. Let the evidence be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston teacher Gloria Rubak blamed Gov. George W. Bush for
Graham's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blood is on George Bush's hands. What we are seeing here
today is a legal lynching,'' Rubak said, echoing an anti-Bush chant
that was heard throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Huntsville businesses closed early.
</P>
<P>
   As pro-death penalty demonstrators rallied behind barricades,
the scene was initially calm.
</P>
<P>
   Standing among a group of death penalty supporters, Mandy Burks
said she had no qualms about the impending execution.
</P>
<P>
   With some of her friends joking about getting drunk after
Graham's demise, Burks said the hundreds of Graham supporters
weren't considering the crimes Graham committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he shouldn't die for this one, he should for one of the
other crimes he committed,'' Burks said. ``I don't think anybody on
that other side wants to talk about all of the victims he left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burks, a Sam Houston State University student, became a
curious bystander when a dozen Ku Klux Klan members arrived about
two hours before Graham's execution.
</P>
<P>
   Low-key death penalty supporters stood in the background as
grand dragon Charles Lee said Graham should die for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
