<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMATE IS EXECUTED IN TEXAS AS 11TH-HOUR APPEALS FAIL
</HEADLINE>
  (2nd take will move by 11 p.m.)  
 By FRANK BRUNI with JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Gov. George W. Bush's tacit assent, Texas
executed convicted killer Gary Graham Thursday night, after
officials at the state prison in Huntsville waited as his lawyers
worked their way through all possible appeals to spare his life.
</P>
<P>
   The execution was carried out even though five members of the
Bush-appointed parole board in Texas argued against it, and the
Supreme Court of the United States was also divided sharply over
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   As the hour when the execution was originally scheduled came and
went, tension mounted both in the state capital, where Bush issued
a statement and in front of the state prison, where an increasingly
anxious crowd grew into the hundreds. As the scheduled hour of the
execution approached, a group of armed men paraded near the prison
in a show of support for Graham.
</P>
<P>
   After Graham's appeals were exhausted, Bush spoke to reporters
in Austin, saying that he had an oath to uphold the laws of the
state. ``This is a responsibility I take very seriously because the
final determination of innocence or guilt is among the most
profound and serious decisions a person can make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that there are good people who oppose the death
penalty,'' he said. ``I have heard their message and I respect
their heartfelt point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke in a somber voice and wore a solemn expression as he
delivered a written statement about the case. He did not make eye
contact with reporters, as he typically does, and walked briskly in
and out of the room. He did not take questions.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's execution had been scheduled for 7 p.m. after the Texas
Board of Pardons and Parole declined by a vote of 12-5 to grant a
request for clemency and the U.S. Supreme Court declined in a 5-4
vote to hear a last-minute appeal by his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   A third appeal was denied by the state's Court of Criminal
Appeals, the highest criminal court in Texas. But minutes before 7
p.m., Graham's lawyers filed still another one, this time a civil
lawsuit against the board of pardons. Although it, too, was
ultimately rejected by U.S. District Judge James Nowlin, the legal
maneuver caused yet another delay.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was the 135th person to be put to death in Texas since
Bush became the governor 5-and-a-half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, Graham had to be executed by midnight or he
would receive an automatic stay. As the appeals worked through the
courts, he remained in a holding cell only steps from the death
chamber accompanied by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, the Rev. Al Sharpton
and Bianca Jagger, a representative of Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who had insisted he is innocent of the 1981 murder of a
man in a holdup outside a Houston supermarket, was declared dead at
8:49 local time.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the execution, as Bush was dogged
along the campaign trail by questions about Graham's fate, he said
repeatedly that he was powerless to intervene in Graham's case if
the board of pardons authorized his execution _ an interpretation
of Texas law that some legal experts disputed.
</P>
<P>
   The board gave that authorization Thursday despite clear
disagreement among the 17 members who voted today, five of whom
recommended that Graham's sentence be commuted to life in prison.
On the separate matter of whether Graham should be given a
conditional pardon, all 17 members voted no. Only a simple majority
of board members is required to allow an execution to proceed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
