<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTION UNLIKELY TO HURT BUSH POLITICALLY, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
and R.A. DYER c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions about the execution of Gary Graham may dog Gov. George
W. Bush for the rest of his presidential campaign, but several
political experts said Thursday that the debate is unlikely to
seriously impede his run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Heckling from death-penalty opponents has become a fixture at
Bush's recent campaign events as he faces criticism for not using
his political clout to block the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn, however, maintained there
was nothing the governor could have done after the state Board of
Pardons and Paroles rejected Graham's last-day pleas.
</P>
<P>
   ``His hands are really tied,'' Cornyn said of the Republican
governor.
</P>
<P>
   The execution continued to fuel national debate on whether Bush
is certain that justice has been dispensed fairly to each prisoner
on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, within minutes after Graham's attorneys gave up
on their appeals, Bush stepped out of his Capitol offices,
appearing solemn, and issued a short statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize there are good people who oppose the death
penalty. I have heard their message and I respect their heartfelt
point of view,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Graham's murder conviction remained intact through
appeals in more than 20 state and federal courts, involving
decisions by 33 judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``After considering all of the facts, I'm confident justice is
being done,'' Bush said in a prepared statement, declining to take
questions.
</P>
<P>
   He closed by saying: ``May God bless the victims, the families
of the victims, and may God bless Mr. Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not heard the last about Graham, experts agreed. But it
was unclear how long the execution will loom large in the
presidential race, or how significant it will become, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, ultimately, it's not going to have any serious
political ramifications for George W. Bush,'' said Gregory Wawro, a
political science professor at Columbia University in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Wawro said he believes that the highly emotional debate on
whether Bush should have stepped in at the last moment was
``largely manufactured'' by Bush detractors, using the news media
as a conduit.
</P>
<P>
   The public is overlooking the more important question of whether
the appeals process is flawed in death penalty cases, Wawro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's disappointing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Warr, a criminologist and sociology professor at the
University of Texas at Austin, concurred that it is unlikely that
Graham's death will do much to derail Bush's political aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   But it may become a nuisance for the governor, at a time when
nationwide support for capital punishment appears to be eroding
somewhat, Warr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this is going to do is crystallize the opposition,'' he
said. ``It's going to be the rallying point, I believe, for those
who oppose the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush will continue to be perceived as someone who
considers capital punishment to be ``morally justified.'' But
Bush's decision not to intervene in a questionable death-penalty
case could portray him as someone who ``fails to appreciate the
possibility of error in the criminal justice system,'' Warr said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had blocked Graham's execution, Warr added, the action
would have angered some supporters who believe strongly in the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that it would have hurt him
politically if he had intervened,'' Warr said.
</P>
<P>
   The execution of Graham, and the questions about whether he
received equal and fair justice, will be raised throughout the
campaign, said Jim Riddlesperger, political science professor at
Texas Christian University in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But Riddlesperger and other experts agreed that the execution
will do little to hurt Bush's core support among Republicans, who
overwhelmingly believe that the death penalty deters violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, most people who are opponents of the death
penalty were not going to vote for George W. Bush under any
circumstance,'' Riddlesperger said.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the highly charged debates over abortion and gun
control, he said, there is little evidence to suggest that capital
punishment is a ``stirring issue in terms of helping people make
voting decisions.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
This report contains material from The Associated Press. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
