<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
 
GORE PALS AROUND WITH VENTURA By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNETONKA, Minn. _ They stayed up past midnight chitchatting
about ``everything under the sun.'' Their wives went horseback
riding together. They chuckled at each other's jokes, took turns
poking fun at reporters and even dressed alike, in chinos and polo
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore visited a junior high school here on
Thursday with Gov. Jesse Ventura, combining the earnestness of a
policy forum with the forced joviality of a buddy movie, to promote
a proposal to increase federal aid for special education.
(Ventura's 16-year-old daughter, Jade, has a learning disability.)
</P>
<P>
   But the broader political point Gore seemed intent on hammering
home was his growing closeness to Ventura, a former professional
wrestler who won election on the Reform Party line in 1998 and
remains a favorite of independent voters across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that I'm reaching out to independents and
independent-minded Republicans,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Many polls suggest that Gore needs a boost with those
unaffiliated voters. Two weeks ago, for instance, a Los Angeles
Times survey showed that Gore trailing his likely Republican rival,
Gov. George W. Bush, by 23 points among independents.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his wife, Tipper, spent Wednesday night at Ventura's
home, the third get-together between the two men in four months.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint appearance on NBC's ``Today'' show, Ventura described
their budding friendship this way: ``I think the vice president
looks at me more as a break, getting away from the rigors of the
campaign trail.'' He added: ``We really don't talk that much on
issues when we get together. We talk on other things. We tell old
war stories. We, you know, enjoy the company of each other and have
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he would endorse Gore, Ventura said he would
consider it a betrayal of the third party movement. But he added
that if the vice president came up ``with a policy that I agree
with, like the one on special ed, I will come out and endorse that
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore jumped in, saying: ``I'm not working on his endorsement.
I'm working on his vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The cheerful patter continued in a joint interview on MTV, where
the famously stiff vice president said he had been trying to teach
the famously bawdy governor how to loosen up, while the bald-headed
governor said he had given the balding vice president hair-styling
tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm even thinking about a feather boa,'' Gore said, referring
to one of Ventura's favorite accouterments as a wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a joint news conference, Gore praised Ventura for
bringing a ``spontaneous, freewheeling, candid style'' to
governing. Moments later, as if on cue, Gore grabbed the cell phone
that a CBS producer had just been talking on. ``This is the vice
president,'' he said. ``Do you have a question?''
</P>
<P>
   The caller asked to speak to Ventura, so Gore passed the phone
to him. Just then, a phone belonging to a CNN producer rang, and
Gore answered it. ``Gore news conference,'' he said, and then
chatted for several minutes while the television cameras rolled and
the press corps cackled.
</P>
<P>
   In his visit to North Junior High School, Gore said he would
increase federal aid for special education to $1.5 billion in his
first year in office, from $700 million. He also called for
protecting a portion of the federal surplus each year to use
exclusively on education, including money for expanding preschool
programs, increasing teacher salaries and recruiting new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But other than announcing his spending plan, Gore said little
about the problems of special education. He did, however, praise
Ventura and his wife, Terry, for ``helping to educate me'' on the
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
