<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GRAHAM-SCENE0623-COX     06-22 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-SCENE0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A crowd divided
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ The distance was hardly a hundred yards that
divided the two camps. But it was all the difference in the world.
It was the difference between good and evil, truth and lies,
justice and injustice, black and white. And which was which
depended on who you were and where you stood.
</P>
<P>
   There was G. George, 40, of Houston. He was holding a sign high
that said, ``Send Graham to hell.'' George, who said only that he
worked inside the city of Houston in identifying himself, had not
been to a protest in a long time. The last one he remembered he was
a little boy being ``dragged around by my parents.'' At an anti-war
demonstration in the '60s. Now, when you ask him, he'll say he
couldn't even say which side of the issue his parents were on.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll tell you he wants to go back to ``electric chairs and
hard labor'' for prisoners. ``If they want to eat, let them grow
their own food. If they want clothes, let them make their own.
That's the way it used to be in Texas,'' he said. ``Everything is
out of balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, hardly that hundred yards, under a banner which
said ``Give innocence a chance. Let the evidence be heard.'' Lynn
Furray, 67, of Houston, a gray-haired, retired school teacher,
looked very much out of place among those protesting the execution.
``I'm against the death penalty and in this case I think Graham did
not have a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Furray became an activist in opposing the death penalty in 1989
after moving to Houston from Michigan where there is no death
penalty. ``I really didn't think about it until I moved down here.
I don't think people have the right to take another life. And that
includes the state,'' she said. ``As a taxpayer,'' she said, ``I
feel like I'm in cahoots with Texas executions.'' Furray said she
writes letters, lobbies and is ``very political.'' She added, ``I
don't like being here, but I think it is an obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleb Ortiz, 29, a senior majoring in criminal justice at Sam
Houston State University here, was standing next to a Confederate
flag held by someone in a group of supporters of the death penalty.
Ortiz, however said he had been visiting both sides, acknowledging
that the Klan wouldn't have him _ a Hispanic_ as a member nor would
the Nation of Islam or the New Black Panthers. ``But I can't hate
anyone. God loves everyone here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who sometimes spoke as if he was a preacher and other
times as if he was a lawyer, said he believes in any state system
that was ``man made'' there would be instances of the innocent
being punished and the guilty going free. ``I must say that in this
particular case, I think the state is justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, another young man, 24, who was wearing a mask
fashioned from a dirty mechanic's red rag, declined to give his
name, acknowledging only that he was a member of the Revolutionary
Communist Youth Brigade from Houston. He said, ``I'm very much
aware of what is happening to young black men. They are being shot,
arrested and harassed by racist police. Under communism, there
wouldn't be a death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   And while white himself, he said he had suffered as well. ``I
had run ins with police when I was young mainly because they didn't
like the way I looked. That's when I came to realize you need an
organization to spearhead the struggle for human rights for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Ray, 48, a bookseller, was here to wave the Confederate
Battle Flag and hold a sign that said, ``Die N-word, Die.'' He said
he came because he was ``tired of the media glorifying Graham. If
you will excuse me for saying so, the media has been acting like
dogs in heat.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ray flaunted the Confederate flag, the New Black Panthers
were wiping sweat from their faces onto the Texas flag and then
throwing it down to the asphalt streets and stomping it with their
boots.
</P>
<P>
   Ashanti Chimurengh, a member of the Gary Graham justice
coalition, was making her speech over a loud speaker. She was
flanked by a sign with a picture of Gov. George W. Bush that said,
``The burning Bush burns black men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two black men's children and everyday I face the fear
of them being killed by racist cops. Everyday we face it. We're
gonna win this g--d--- war. I don't know what will happen but I'm a
warrior princess. But it is important that whatever happens we must
take this struggle forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
