u s BC-MNF-NEWANALYST0623-CO     06-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MNF-NEWANALYST0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Monday Night' Miller: Comedian joining football booth
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When ABC announced it would revamp the booth for
``Monday Night Football,'' the big question was the casting of the
``fan'' role that was handled so brilliantly in the 1970s by the
late Howard Cosell.
</P>
<P>
   The network answered that question Thursday by selecting
comedian Dennis Miller to the MNF booth. Miller will join returning
play-by-play announcer Al Michaels and Hall of Fame quarterback Dan
Fouts, who was drafted from ABC's college football roster to take
the Monday night stage.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, who is back after producing MNF during the days of
Don Meredith and Cosell, also announced ESPN's Melissa Stark will
replace Lesley Visser as a sideline reporter and will be joined in
that role by Hall of Fame running back Eric Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to re-create the past,'' said Ohlmeyer. ``We
want to create a more enjoyable telecast that will make the game
relevant to hard-core fans, accessible to casual fans and
unpredictable to both. I didn't enjoy watching `Monday Night
Football' last year as a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nielsen ratings for MNF have decreased the past five
seasons, from an average of 17.8 with a booth of Al Michaels, Dan
Dierdorf and Frank Gifford in 1994, to last season's record-low of
13.7 with Michaels and Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer said Miller was chosen from a list of 15 to 20
candidates, which included radio talk show host Rush Limbaugh, who
wasn't ruled out for guest appearances during the season. Ohlmeyer
also said Miller was the first name he thought of, even though, ``I
didn't think he would be interested in, or capable of, being in the
booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who will continue his weekly show on HBO, secured the
job with an audition 2-1/2 weeks ago that Ohlmeyer and Michaels
both said blew them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Sebastian Janikowski slip something in Don's coffee,''
quipped Miller, referring to the arrest Wednesday of the Raiders
rookie kicker on charges of possession of an illegal drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty quirky hire. I think I can do the job, but I'm
not going to try to be Howard. In sports broadcasting, Cosell was
the most stunning talent we've had. He's the guy who always did it
best. You don't try to compete with that. I'm just going to be me,
and at the end of the year, it'll either play or it won't play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nielsen ratings for ``Monday Night Football'' have decreased
each of the past five seasons, from an average of 17.8 with a booth
of Michaels, Dan Dierdorf and Frank Gifford in 1994, to last
season's record-low for the program of 13.7 with Michaels and
Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he'll ask questions a fan might ask and give on his
thoughts or certain strategies and plays. But he won't delve into
politics, ``and I'll never question a player's fortitude. I'd look
lame doing that having never played the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where Fouts and Dickerson will come in. In
Dickerson's case, Ohlmeyer spoke of having different
responsibilities than traditional sideline reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the NFL may be more concerned about Eric's opinions
than Dennis' opinions,'' Ohlmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have a lot of television experience,'' Dickerson
said, ``but I know football. And I've always believed that honesty
is the best policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer also spoke of seeking a different rhythm for calling
the game, perhaps departing at times from the standard
``play-by-play does this, then analyst does that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This job for me is a dream come true,'' Fouts said. ``And
unlike Dennis who has another job, I will change to keep this job.
I grew up the son of a broadcaster and played 15 years with the
Chargers. The last time I worked with a coach named Don, Coryell
(the former Chargers coach), it turned out pretty well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the disparity in ages between Visser, 46, and Stark,
26, Ohlmeyer, dismissed the question as a ``non-issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcaster Donna deVarona, 52, filed a $50 million lawsuit
against ABC Sports in April, saying she was fired because of her
age and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Visser, who joined ABC in 1994, covered a variety of sports,
including college football, figure skating, baseball and
thoroughbred racing's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer also said changes are forthcoming on the halftime show.
ESPN's Chris Berman will return, but his role will be changed, and
the show will not originate from an ESPN Zone restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
