<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 06/22/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   The following photos have moved with the latest installment of
the New York Times series on race relations slugged: RACE-KIDS:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT801) MALEWOOD, N.J. -- June 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
25 -- RACE-KIDS-1 -- Aqeelah Mateen, Kelly Regan and Johanna
Perez-Fox, left to right, became friends in grade school. As they
began high school, they had so far managed to maintain their
friendships. While the world around them had increasingly divided
along racial lines, they had stuck together. But where their
friendship would go was hard to say. And like a Greek chorus, the
voices of other young people warned of tricky currents ahead.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT802) MALEWOOD, N.J. -- June 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
25 -- RACE-KIDS-1 -- Despite all the personal history, all the
community good will, race divides children in this community as
they grow up. As racial consciousness develops -- and the practice
of grouping students by their perceived ability sends them on
diverging academic paths -- race becomes as much a fault line in
their world as in the world their parents hoped to move beyond.
Third graders like Melissa Charles and Tess Skoller mix easily at
South Mountain Elementary School. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT803) MALEWOOD, N.J. -- June 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
25 -- RACE-KIDS-1 -- Despite all the personal history, all the
community good will, race divides children in this community as
they grow up. As racial consciousness develops -- and the practice
of grouping students by their perceived ability sends them on
diverging academic paths -- race becomes as much a fault line in
their world as in the world their parents hoped to move beyond.
Aqeelah Mateen, Kelly Regan and Johanna Perez-Fox, frolicking in
Kelly's room, mix more easily than their peers. (Suzanne
DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT804) MALEWOOD, N.J. -- June 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
25 -- RACE-KIDS-4 -- Despite all the personal history, all the
community good will, race divides children in this community as
they grow up. As racial consciousness develops -- and the practice
of grouping students by their perceived ability sends them on
diverging academic paths -- race becomes as much a fault line in
their world as in the world their parents hoped to move beyond. By
the time they enter high school, students tend to split into racial
groups, sitting apart in the Columbia High cafeteria, for example.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT805) SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. -- June 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 25 -- RACE-KIDS-5 -- Despite all the personal history, all the
community good will, race divides children in this community as
they grow up. As racial consciousness develops -- and the practice
of grouping students by their perceived ability sends them on
diverging academic paths -- race becomes as much a fault line in
their world as in the world their parents hoped to move beyond. A
close friendship that defies the rule is that of Ari Onugha, right,
and Jordan BarAm. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT806) SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. -- June 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 25 -- RACE-KIDS-6 -- Despite all the personal history, all the
community good will, race divides children in this community as
they grow up. As racial consciousness develops -- and the practice
of grouping students by their perceived ability sends them on
diverging academic paths -- race becomes as much a fault line in
their world as in the world their parents hoped to move beyond.
Clockwise from top, left: Malika Oglesby, Sierre Monk, Jason
Coleman and Marian Flaxman. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   Our report today also includes:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) OKEECHOBEE, Fla. -- June 22, 2000 --
RELIGION-BOOTCAMP-COX -- Missionary training camps are becoming
more popular since they first began in the 1960s. Curriculum at the
camps typically stress how to travel safely, work with people from
other cultures and evangelize effectively. Young missionaries from
Hobe Sound Bible College spend a week in the wilds of Okeechobee,
Fla, part of a missionary boot camp, South Florida style, where the
order of the day is readying 30 teenage and twentysomething
evangelists for a month in the mission fields of some far-flung
places. (David Lane/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- June 22, 2000 -- NY-CARLYLE-HOTEL-2 -- The
Carlyle Hotel is for sale and there is serious worry that this
oasis of sophistication -- the preserve of presidents, prime
ministers and popular legends -- will fall into the wrong hands.
Have no fear, says Norman L. Peck, the managing partner of the
Carlyle, who insists that he wouldn't think of permitting an
unqualified suitor to buy ``this very high-bred animal.'' Peck
stands in one of his favorite corners of the hotel's lobby, before
a Dutch painting by Jan Weenix. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- June 22, 2000 -- NY-CARLYLE-HOTEL-1 -- The
Carlyle Hotel is for sale and there is serious worry that this
oasis of sophistication -- the preserve of presidents, prime
ministers and popular legends -- will fall into the wrong hands.
Have no fear, says Norman L. Peck, the managing partner of the
Carlyle, who insists that he wouldn't think of permitting an
unqualified suitor to buy ``this very high-bred animal.'' The main
entrance of the hotel last week. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   EDS: PLEASE NOTE THAT THERE WILL BE NO NYT's, 20 and 21 sent
tonight
</P>
<P>
   Editors please note that the following photo, NYT19 is
eliminated for incorrect date of trial; photo was taken during a
trial in May.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) GNILJANE, Yugoslavia -- June 22, 2000 --
OFFICIAL-ELIMINATION-NOTICE ------- KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-1 -- While the
International War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague has issued
indictments against Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, and
four others, and is preparing more war crime indictments for
attrocities committed during the the Kosovo War, prosecutors admit
that they cannot handle all the cases. Dragan Nikolich, a Serb, is
brought in for trial in Gniljane, Yugoslavia. Nikolich is accused
of murdering an 18-year-old Albanian, Xhemaje Ademi, during the
period of the NATO bombardment last year. (Andrew Testa/The New
York Times) OFFICILA-ELIMINATION-NOTICE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SHEMYA ISLAND, Alaska -- June 22, 2000 --
MISSILE-DEFENSE-2 -- The Western Aleutians and some uninhabited
islands in Hawaii were outside the sphere of coverage from a
national missile defense. Faced with this and other obstacles, the
Clinton Administration resigned itself to deploying 100
interceptors in central Alaska and erecting a powerful
battle-management radar on Shemya, a remote island in the
Aleutians. A photo from the Defense Department of Shemya island and
proposed contruction sites. (Department of Defense/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KWAJALEIN MISSILE RANGE, Republic of the Marshall
Islands -- June 22, 2000 -- MISSILE-DEFENSE-1 -- The administration
has long argued that its plan to build a limited missile defense
was a response to emerging missile threats from countries like
North Korea, Iran and Iraq. But from the start it has also been a
defense against Republican attacks. A payload launch vehicle
carrying a prototype interceptor is launched from Meck Island in
the Kwajalein Missile Range on Jan. 18, for a planned intercept of
a ballistic missile target over the central Pacific Ocean.
(Department of Defense/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NORCORSS, Ga. -- June 22, 2000 -- GAYPRIDE-ATLANTA-COX
--Today, with acceptance of homosexuality at an all-time high
across the nation, Stonewall's anniversary is widely celebrated.
But in 1970, when gays were very much on the fringe, Atlanta was
one of only a handful of cities to hold a rally marking Stonewall.
Gene Holloway, 43, who helped the gay rights movement grow in
Atlanta, has been a gay rights activist since 1974. ``Atlanta being
the cradle of the civil rights movement only helped the gay rights
movement,'' says Holloway. ``It's unlike any other city in the
South because of Dr. King. To my thinking, a struggle is a
struggle.'' (T. Levette Bagwell/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- SCHOLARS-ROCKS-- The oddly
shaped tabletop objects known as Chinese scholars' rocks rate
barely a mention in most art history books, and then only as
decorative accessories. But when the Asia Society presented an
exhibition of them four years ago they caused a minor sensation and
quickly became the pet rocks of the 1990's. A very different show,
``The World of Scholars' Rocks: Gardens, Studios and Paintings,''
is now showing at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. A scholar's rock
in the form of a mountain range with a lake, at the Met.
(Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 22, 2000 -- NADER-LABOR-B&AMP;W --
Months after they dismissed Ralph Nader as a fringe third-party
candidate who would fade quickly, Democratic and Republican
strategists now say that the consumer advocate has emerged as more
politically potent than Patrick Buchanan and could deeply
complicate the candidacy of Vice President Al Gore. Nader during a
Green Party rally in March. (Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) EUGENE, Ore. -- June 22, 2000 -- GORE-FUNDRAISING -- A
top Justice Department prosecutor has recommended a special counsel
be appointed to investigate Vice President Al Gore in the 1996
campaign fund-raising controversy, government officials said
Thursday. Gore greeted supporters during a campaign stop in
October, 1996. (James Estrin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEWPORT, Mass. -- June 22, 2000 -- HOME-DUKE-BOS-2 -- It
may not be as grand as the homes of the Vanderbilts and Astors, who
spent fortunes trying to outmarble, outgild, and outbuild one
another at the turn of the century, but Doris Duke's baronial
mansion, Rough Point, on Bellevue Avenue in Newport, Mass., still
stands as a monument to the excess of America's Gilded Age. On July
5, the gates of Rough Point will be thrown open to the public for
the first time. The bedroom of Doris Duke. (Janet Knott/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEWPORT, Mass. -- June 22, 2000 -- HOME-DUKE-BOS -- It
may not be as grand as the homes of the Vanderbilts and Astors, who
spent fortunes trying to outmarble, outgild, and outbuild one
another at the turn of the century, but Doris Duke's baronial
mansion, Rough Point, on Bellevue Avenue in Newport, Mass., still
stands as a monument to the excess of America's Gilded Age. On July
5, the gates of Rough Point will be thrown open to the public for
the first time. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 22, 2000 -- SPECTOR-RONETTES -- Ronnie
Spector Greenfield, 56, of Ronnie and the Ronettes, the shimmying
bad girls once so famous that their opening act was the Rolling
Stones, received only a one-time check of $14,482.30 from Phil
Spector for such '60s hits like ``Be My Baby,'' ``Baby I Love You''
and ``Walking in the Rain.'' Now, a 13-year-old lawsuit over
royalties from the various songs she recorded with her sister and
cousin, has just been resolved in their favor to the tune of $2.6
million. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEWBURYPORT, Mass. -- June 22, 2000 -- AUTHOR-DUBUS --
After two decades of laboring in the shadow of his famous father
Andre Dubus, the celebrated short-story writer whose 1991 book
``Broken Vessels'' was a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize, Andre Dubus
III has come into his own. Last year, Dubus's novel, ``House of
Sand and Fog,'' was named a finalist for the National Book Award
and there is talk of a film based on it. Dubus III at his home in
Newburyport, Mass. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DURHAM, N.H. -- June 22, 2000 -- COMPUTERS-DIALECT-BOS --
Sam Stoddard, 26, who founded ``Rinkworks.com,'' where visitors can
type in text or an entire Web page to be translated into seven fake
dialects: Redneck, Cockney, Elmer Fudd, Swedish Chef, Pig Latin,
Moron, and Jive. Stoddard who started Dialectizer two years ago as
a parody, has become enmeshed in an Internet free-speech battle.
Trouble began when people started translating entire Web pages into
the dialects. Some Web site developers and companies were not only
not amused, but they began protesting. (Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- SCI-FEATHER-FOSSIL-2 --
Scientists have discovered fossil evidence of the oldest known
feathered animal, a small reptile that probably glided among the
trees 75 million years before the earliest known bird, and they say
this challenges the widely held theory that birds evolved from
dinosaurs. An artist's rendering of what scientists believe the
animal may have looked like. (Oregon State University/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- SCI-FEATHER-FOSSIL-1 --
Scientists at Oregon State University have discovered this fossil
which they claim indicates evidence of the oldest known feathered
animal. Paleontologists with the university believe the small
reptile probably glided among the trees 75 million years before the
earliest known bird, and they say the find challenges the widely
held theory that birds evolved from dinosaurs. (Oregon State
University/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PHILADELPHIA -- June 22, 2000 -- OLD-THEATERS -- It is
possible to love a theater and to believe in a city, so much so
that some people may devote most of their adult lives, sometimes as
volunteers, to keeping an old theater alive. The Walnut Street
Theater. (Salvatore C. DiMarco Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 22, 2000 -- NEW-DANCERS -- There are so
many dancers to claim the heart and mind and eye, yet only a few do
each season. A trio of new faces: from left, Karine
Plantadit-Bageot, Elizabeth Roxas and Michael Thomas of RhythMEK.
(Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- PHILLY-WARHOL-GWATHMEY-2 --
In one of the more improbable pairings in recent exhibition
history, the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts is exhibiting
the work of Andy Warhol with that of the Social Realist painter
Robert Gwathmey. The idea being that the under-appreciated Gwathmey
and the canonized Warhol shared an outlook as ``social
commentators'' on American life. One of the works on exhibit, Andy
Warhol's ``Race Riot'' (1964). (Andy Warhol Foundation for the
Visual Arts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- PHILLY-WARHOL-GWATHMEY-1 --
In one of the more improbable pairings in recent exhibition
history, the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts is exhibiting
the work of Andy Warhol with that of the Social Realist painter
Robert Gwathmey. The idea being that the under-appreciated Gwathmey
and the canonized Warhol shared an outlook as ``social
commentators'' on American life. One of the paintings on exhibit,
``Children Dancing'' (1948), by Robert Gwathmey. (Butler Institute
of American Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 22, 2000 -- METEORITE-INDIANS -- The
Museum of Natural History has announced a settlement with an Oregon
Indian tribe over the Willamette Meteorite, seen in the museum
earlier this year. The Indians wanted the meteorite back, saying
they hold it sacred, but removing it would have required
dismantling the museum's new building. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
