Sam Stoddard, 26, who founded ``Rinkworks.com,'' where visitors can
type in text or an entire Web page to be translated into seven fake
dialects: Redneck, Cockney, Elmer Fudd, Swedish Chef, Pig Latin,
Moron, and Jive. Stoddard who started Dialectizer two years ago as
a parody, has become enmeshed in an Internet free-speech battle.
Trouble began when people started translating entire Web pages into
the dialects. Some Web site developers and companies were not only
not amused, but they began protesting. (Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- SCI-FEATHER-FOSSIL-2 --
Scientists have discovered fossil evidence of the oldest known
feathered animal, a small reptile that probably glided among the
trees 75 million years before the earliest known bird, and they say
this challenges the widely held theory that birds evolved from
dinosaurs. An artist's rendering of what scientists believe the
animal may have looked like. (Oregon State University/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- SCI-FEATHER-FOSSIL-1 --
Scientists at Oregon State University have discovered this fossil
which they claim indicates evidence of the oldest known feathered
animal. Paleontologists with the university believe the small
reptile probably glided among the trees 75 million years before the
earliest known bird, and they say the find challenges the widely
held theory that birds evolved from dinosaurs. (Oregon State
University/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PHILADELPHIA -- June 22, 2000 -- OLD-THEATERS -- It is
possible to love a theater and to believe in a city, so much so
that some people may devote most of their adult lives, sometimes as
volunteers, to keeping an old theater alive. The Walnut Street
Theater. (Salvatore C. DiMarco Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 22, 2000 -- NEW-DANCERS -- There are so
many dancers to claim the heart and mind and eye, yet only a few do
each season. A trio of new faces: from left, Karine
Plantadit-Bageot, Elizabeth Roxas and Michael Thomas of RhythMEK.
(Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- PHILLY-WARHOL-GWATHMEY-2 --
In one of the more improbable pairings in recent exhibition
history, the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts is exhibiting
the work of Andy Warhol with that of the Social Realist painter
Robert Gwathmey. The idea being that the under-appreciated Gwathmey
and the canonized Warhol shared an outlook as ``social
commentators'' on American life. One of the works on exhibit, Andy
Warhol's ``Race Riot'' (1964). (Andy Warhol Foundation for the
Visual Arts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- June 22, 2000 -- PHILLY-WARHOL-GWATHMEY-1 --
In one of the more improbable pairings in recent exhibition
history, the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts is exhibiting
the work of Andy Warhol with that of the Social Realist painter
Robert Gwathmey. The idea being that the under-appreciated Gwathmey
and the canonized Warhol shared an outlook as ``social
commentators'' on American life. One of the paintings on exhibit,
``Children Dancing'' (1948), by Robert Gwathmey. (Butler Institute
