<P>
   (NYT16) NORCORSS, Ga. -- June 22, 2000 -- GAYPRIDE-ATLANTA-COX
--Today, with acceptance of homosexuality at an all-time high
across the nation, Stonewall's anniversary is widely celebrated.
But in 1970, when gays were very much on the fringe, Atlanta was
one of only a handful of cities to hold a rally marking Stonewall.
Gene Holloway, 43, who helped the gay rights movement grow in
Atlanta, has been a gay rights activist since 1974. ``Atlanta being
the cradle of the civil rights movement only helped the gay rights
movement,'' says Holloway. ``It's unlike any other city in the
South because of Dr. King. To my thinking, a struggle is a
struggle.'' (T. Levette Bagwell/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
