NYT-06-22-00 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2155 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-2NDTAKE     06-22 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: to proceed. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Jones, a spokesman for Bush, said early Thursday night that
he did not know what would become of the last-minute legal appeals
but that the state was waiting to make sure courts got a chance to
consider them. Bush was at the state capitol, meeting with aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in uncharted territory here,'' Jones said, referring to
the particular arguments that Graham's lawyers were pursuing and
that had clearly taken state officials by surprise. ``It's all
brand new. This is unprecedented for somebody to attempt to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   David R. Dow, a professor of law at the University of Houston,
said the last-minute uncertainty that suddenly descended over
Graham's execution reflected how sophisticated his lawyers were and
how sensitive Bush and the state of Texas were to the intensity of
public attention to the case. Under different circumstances, he
said, the state might have gone ahead with the execution, because
Graham's lawyers had already exhausted all the traditional
arguments in all the usual venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is almost always a new permutation that a very, very
thoughtful lawyer can think of,'' Dow said. ``But you have to have
a combination of two things _ real legal capability but also enough
of a faith in your client to think that it's worth it and crank out
papers even beyond the eleventh hour _ this is the eleventh and a
half hour.''
</P>
<P>
   If the state were not so acutely aware of all the eyes on the
case, he added, ``I don't think this would be happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case attracted a remarkable amount of national and
even international attention, for many reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's conviction rested on the testimony of a single
eyewitness, his court-appointed lawyer provided only a nominal
defense and several jurors later expressed doubt that they would
have convicted him if they had been aware of certain facts and
testimony during the trial. Many legal experts cast Graham as a
perfect example of all that was wrong with the judicial system and
the death penalty, although many others noted that his appeals were
lodged in dozens of courts and been considered by an even larger
number of judges as he avoided execution for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the case also came at a time of deepening debate over
capital punishment, provoked by advances in DNA technology, new
studies that question the fairness with which the death penalty is
administered and the emergence of Bush, who presides over a state
that executes more inmates than any other, as a candidate for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The governor steadfastly maintained that he was treating this
case no differently than any other and that any action he did or
did not take would be impervious to political considerations,
immune to public protests and unaffected by a campaign that has
pivoted on his portrayal of himself as a sensitive, compassionate
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a lot of hand-wringing,'' said one adviser. ``But
everyone recognizes that the environment has changed now that he's
running for president.'' The adviser added that there was some
minimal concern _ though not too much yet _ that all the attention
to the death penalty in Texas was at times eclipsing the other
issues Bush wanted to discuss on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   But this adviser and others stressed that there was absolutely
no coordination or discussion between Bush and his campaign
advisers about the actual decisions that Bush faced on individual
death penalty cases. They said that the governor rendered these
judgments based on the merits of each case, not on any wider
political concerns.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had taken any kind of action stop Graham's death, it
would have been the second time this month that he had intervened
to halt an execution in defiance of the board's recommendation.
Prior to June 1, he had never done so, although he did concur in
1998 with the board's vote to commute the death sentence of Henry
Lee Lucas, a confessed serial killer, to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Several political analysts said that one of the challenges
before Bush, now that almost everything he did was being evaluated
through the prism of his presidential ambitions, was not to come
across as vulnerable to public pressures or unsteady in his
convictions. Bush has repeatedly assailed Vice President Al Gore as
someone who bends too readily with the political winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing for him to do is remain consistent,''
said Don Sipple, a Republican strategist. Sipple said that he
believed it was voters' impressions of Bush's constancy that
explained the high marks he received in many recent public opinion
polls for his leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, there has been some evidence in polls of a softening in
public support for the death penalty, but those same polls showed
that roughly two-thirds of Americans are still in favor of it. And
several political analysts said that that was a large enough
majority, on a subject that was not at the top of most voters'
concerns, for Bush to rest assured that he was on the right side of
the issue. Gore also supports the death penalty and has been
relatively reticent to challenge Bush on the brisk rate of
executions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the governor has extremely limited discretion
if the board authorizes an execution. All the governor can do under
those circumstances is grant the inmate a one-time reprieve of 30
days, though that time often grows as the inmate undertakes new
court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said that in this case, he could not do even that. A
64-year old clause in the Texas constitution says that the governor
``shall have the power to grant one reprieve in any capital case,''
and only one reprieve. Both Bush and lawyers for the state have
interpreted that to mean that because Gov. Ann Richards had granted
Graham such a reprieve in 1993, Bush was unable to.
</P>
<P>
   But other legal experts said that the constitution could be
interpreted as permitting one reprieve per governor, not per
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's plain old ambiguous,'' said Dow, noting that no court in
Texas had ever considered the language or issued a ruling on its
precise meaning. He went on to say, ``It's easier to say you have
no power than to exercise it.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was convicted for the May 13, 1981, nighttime murder of
Bobby Lambert in the parking lot of a Houston grocery store. His
conviction provoked little fanfare at the time, but his case
gradually attracted the attention of death penalty opponents.
</P>
<P>
   His advocates argued that Graham's trial lawyer, Ronald Mock,
put up a lackluster defense and scarcely investigated the case. No
physical evidence linked Graham to the scene, and ballistics tests
found that a .22-caliber revolver confiscated from him did not
match the murder weapon. His conviction rested on the testimony of
a woman sitting in her car who saw the killer as he confronted and
shot Lambert about 30 feet away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
