<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-GRAHAM-EXECUTION-TEX     06-22 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-EXECUTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM EXECUTED AFTER DAY OF DELAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Defiant, combative and stalling with a
flurry of 11th-hour legal maneuvers, Gary Graham went to his death
Thursday night after his attorneys reluctantly gave up their fight
to stop the lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   The end came at 8:39 p.m., when doctors pronounced him dead, his
sentence carried out 19 years after a Houston killing that
punctuated a crime spree of at least 10 robberies, two shootings,
an abduction and a rape.
</P>
<P>
   Graham protested that he was innocent and that his execution,
which he called a ``lynching,'' was a ``murder that must be avenged
... by any means necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Graczyk of the Associated Press, who served as a pool
reporter and witness, said Graham put up a futile struggle to avoid
placement on the gurney.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials, he said, took the rare step of handcuffing
Graham to the bed in addition to using leather and Velcro straps.
</P>
<P>
   Graczyk said Graham entered the death chamber with bruises on
his arms and other parts of his body.
</P>
<P>
   While the drama and Graham's battle for life played out in the
courts, hundreds of supporters, including political leaders,
Hollywood celebrities and civil rights activists, protested outside
the Texas prison unit housing the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's execution came more than 2 1/2 hours after he was
scheduled to die. He lost his final appeal before the U.S. Supreme
Court shortly before 6 p.m., but his attorneys then filed suit in a
federal court contending that his civil rights had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   With U.S. District Judge James R. Nowlin of Austin rejecting
that petition, Graham's attorneys decided that they had exhausted
their appeals and that it would be fruitless to take the case to
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit, legal experts speculated, was a last-ditch
attempt to win Graham a stay or keep his case in limbo until
midnight, when his death warrant would have expired and delayed the
execution at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
declined by a 14-3 vote to recommend that Gov. George W. Bush grant
Graham a 120-day reprieve, a commutation or a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Graham had escaped execution in 1993 when then-Gov. Ann Richards
granted him a one-time, 30-day reprieve allowed under Texas law.
Some believed that Bush could have granted another 30-day reprieve,
even without a recommendation from the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that `a' governor can give `a' defendant
one 30-day reprieve,'' said Jerry Perry, a government professor at
Angelo State University in San Angelo, Texas. ``I know that Ann
Richards in 1993 gave Graham a 30-day reprieve. What I don't know,
and I'm not sure anybody knows, is whether or not another governor
can give another reprieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush supported the board's recommendation, saying that 33 judges
had heard Graham's appeals and decided they were ``without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize there are good people who oppose the death
penalty,'' Bush said. ``I have heard their message and I respect
their heartfelt point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``After considering all of the facts, I'm confident justice is
being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham had steadfastly maintained that he was not guilty of the
killing that sent him to Death Row, the 1981 robbery-shooting death
of 53-year-old Bobby Grant Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   The execution capped almost two weeks of tense rhetoric and
demonstrations and a full day of angry protests outside
Huntsville's Walls Unit, a few hundred yards from the execution
chamber. Some demonstrators shouted anti-death penalty slogans with
bullhorns and banged drums.
</P>
<P>
   They called the execution ``a legal lynching.'' Death penalty
supporters, cordoned off in a separate area, said the condemned got
what he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson and the Rev. Al Sharpton, along with U.S.
Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston, social activist Bianca Jagger
and minister Robert Muhammad watched the execution on Graham's
behalf. A protective glass separated them from the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hanners, Lambert's grandson, was joined in a separate room
by crime-victims rights activist Dianne Clements and family friend
Rick Sandford.
</P>
<P>
   A circuslike atmosphere enveloped the area surrounding the Walls
Unit, beginning in the early afternoon. Graham supporters began
assembling on a blocked-off street that connects the prison to
downtown Huntsville about a quarter-mile to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the New Black Panthers, the Nation of Islam and
Amnesty International were among those who held out hope that an
11th-hour stay might come from the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court, however, rejected the plea on a 5-4 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most protesters carried signs proclaiming Graham's innocence or
suggesting that an African-American cannot be guaranteed justice in
Texas. Despite Graham's call for armed revolt a year and a half
ago, when he faced an execution date, several speakers urged the
crowd, which numbered several hundred, to remain peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a frequent critic of Texas' use of the death penalty,
gave successive interviews to the reporters who descended upon
Huntsville from across Texas, from the major TV networks and from
Europe. He said the decision by the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles to reject Graham's plea came as no shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pained by it, but not surprised,'' said Jackson, who had
met with Graham earlier in the day. ``Many other people might be
saved by the attention that Gary Graham has received. This system
is evil. His life will have tremendous meaning if this vicious
system is exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eastern edge of the prison unit, several hundred yards
from Graham's supporters, proponents of the execution, including
someone dressed as a Ku Klux Klansman and several others waving a
Confederate flag, applauded the parole board's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had 19 years,'' said a man wearing Army fatigues who
identified himself only as ``a Texan.'' ``That's enough. Let him
get what he deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Another man carried a sign saying: ``Give him old-fashioned
justice. Use a rope.'' The man said he feared retaliation from
Black Panthers if his name was published.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, whose age has been reported as 38 by prison officials
and 36 by his supporters, spent his final day in defiance. He
refused to cooperate with the order that he leave his cell on Death
Row in the Terrell Unit in Livingston. An extraction team removed
him by force and placed him in the prison bus to Huntsville, 45
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The team also had to remove Graham from the bus and place him in
the cell a few feet from the death chamber. His defiance caused
prison officials to deny him an opportunity for a farewell visit
with relatives. He also declined to order a last meal.
</P>
<P>
   Jagger, the former wife of rock star Mick Jagger, was allowed to
visit Graham, who since 1995 has called himself Shaka Sankofa to
reflect his African heritage. She described him as subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really did believe that the Board of Pardons and Paroles
would grant him a reprieve,'' Jagger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case was seen as a political minefield for Bush, the
probable Republican presidential nominee who has presided over 135
executions as Texas governor. Graham's supporters urged Bush to
influence the parole board, whose members he appointed, to halt the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's conviction rested in large measure on the testimony of
one eyewitness. His lawyer did not call witnesses who later said
they could provide him an alibi during his trial. Appellate lawyers
have tried in vain to have their testimony heard in a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, meanwhile, said that the eyewitness testimony was
rock-solid and
</P>
<P>
   that Graham was in the midst of a violent crime spree when he
was arrested. He had been found passed out in the bed of a
57-year-old woman he had raped. Graham has admitted to the crime
spree.
</P>
<P>
   The case was a mere blip on the criminal justice radar screen
until 1993, when Graham's new lawyers gained attention as they
began pointing out what they saw as flaws in the case.
</P>
<P>
   They said others who witnessed the late-night shooting outside
of a Safeway store did not identify Graham as the gunman, and that
the gun found on Graham during his arrest was tested and proved not
to be the murder weapon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writers Bill Hanna, R.A. Dyer and Bob Mahlburg contributed to
this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-DALEY-NYT &LR;      06-22 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DALEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALEY JOINS THE GORE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ William M. Daley, the new chairman of Vice
President Al Gore's presidential campaign, acknowledged Thursday
that one of the biggest challenges facing Gore was that George W.
Bush was getting credit for the economy, the issue on which Gore
had been basing his hopes.
</P>
<P>
   But, Daley said, that was a ``knee jerk'' reaction and he hoped
to counter it by recruiting supporters from big business and labor
to come to Nashville, where Gore's campaign is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is right now,'' Daley said of Bush's receiving credit. ``I
don't know if it's just kind of a gut thing, but Republicans have
always historically got more credit for running the economy, and
being good for the economy, even at the height of the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think we've got a challenge to remind people what things
were like in 1992, and we've got a challenge to remind them that,
fine, you may take this eight years of economic expansion for
granted, but tough decisions were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Daley hastened to add that he understood the size of the
task ahead of him. ``I'm not being Pollyannish about how difficult
a presidential campaign is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, the secretary of commerce, spoke in an interview here as
he made his debut in Gore's headquarters as chairman on a day when
the Gore camp had to absorb another round of bad news.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official has recommended that an
independent counsel be named to investigate Gore's role in the
Democrats' questionable fund-raising activities of 1996. Two new
national polls showed Gore slipping further behind Bush. And James
P. Hoffa, the powerful labor leader, appeared with Ralph Nader, the
Green Party candidate who could siphon enough votes from Gore to
cost him a few key states.
</P>
<P>
   A new Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll, taken during the start
of Gore's ``prosperity and progress tour,'' which was intended to
showcase the booming economy, put Bush ahead of Gore 49 percent to
41 percent. A bipartisan Battleground 2000/Voter.com poll showed
Bush ahead by 12 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said part of his task would be to bring business and labor
interests together and urge officials to move to Nashville to
dedicate themselves to Gore's candidacy. The Journal/NBC poll
showed that voters give Gore an advantage of only a single
percentage point _ statistically meaningless _ on his ability to
handle the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get people from labor and business down here,''
Daley said in an interview in his office, which will serve as his
command post until the November election. ``I'm asking people, `You
want to help? Fine. When are you going to leave your job and come
to Nashville?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get other validators _ Bob Rubin isn't
exactly some crazed, crazy liberal out there,'' Daley said of the
former Treasury secretary's backing of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As for internal concern that the Gore campaign lacks focus and a
theme, Daley said that at this point in 1992, Bill Clinton lacked
focus, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think there was a theme to Bill Clinton's candidacy?'' he
asked. ``I don't think that really connects until people connect,
and all of a sudden it's like, `Yeah, here's what's going on with
the race.' You can't say, `OK, there it is, there's the answer.' A
theme evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley takes the reins officially on July 15, when he leaves his
cabinet post. He succeeds Tony Coelho, the campaign's former
chairman, who resigned last week for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho said in an interview with Bloomberg.com that his health
was worse than he had indicated last week. In addition to his
epilepsy and inflammation of the colon, he told the news service,
he has a brain cyst, though he does not know whether it is
malignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My seizures were getting worse,'' Coelho said of his epilepsy.
``I was having stomach cramps, but I would work my way through
them. I just had too much to do. Then, my sinuses above my eyes got
infected and they became inflamed and shut down, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   After arriving from Washington, Daley met with Tennessee
Democrats on Thursday morning. He then shook hands with all the
campaign staff members, including about 80 paid workers and 70
interns and volunteers, at their desks, and spoke to them
collectively for about 15 minutes. Listeners described his comments
in the meeting, which was closed to reporters, as welcoming and
inspirational.
</P>
<P>
   Daley described his message to the staff as being ``all about
grinding it out for four and a half months.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was too soon to discuss any changes he had in mind,
but cautioned that the campaign would ``not lurch this way and
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just lay out a strategy and go for it, and you don't jump
around,'' he said. ``But I'm just getting immersed in the daily
give and take, the flow. It's really easy for someone who's not
following the ebb and flow every day to be criticizing it. You've
got to really get into it to understand what the hell's going on,
and that takes a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
