<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-EXECUTION-1600(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM EXECUTED AFTER DAY OF DELAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Defiant, combative and stalling with a
flurry of 11th-hour legal maneuvers, Gary Graham went to his death
Thursday night after his attorneys reluctantly gave up their fight
to stop the lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   The end came at 8:39 p.m., when doctors pronounced him dead, his
sentence carried out 19 years after a Houston killing that
punctuated a crime spree of at least 10 robberies, two shootings,
an abduction and a rape.
</P>
<P>
   Graham protested that he was innocent and that his execution,
which he called a ``lynching,'' was a ``murder that must be avenged
... by any means necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Graczyk of the Associated Press, who served as a pool
reporter and witness, said Graham put up a futile struggle to avoid
placement on the gurney.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials, he said, took the rare step of handcuffing
Graham to the bed in addition to using leather and Velcro straps.
</P>
<P>
   Graczyk said Graham entered the death chamber with bruises on
his arms and other parts of his body.
</P>
<P>
   While the drama and Graham's battle for life played out in the
courts, hundreds of supporters, including political leaders,
Hollywood celebrities and civil rights activists, protested outside
the Texas prison unit housing the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's execution came more than 2 1/2 hours after he was
scheduled to die. He lost his final appeal before the U.S. Supreme
Court shortly before 6 p.m., but his attorneys then filed suit in a
federal court contending that his civil rights had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   With U.S. District Judge James R. Nowlin of Austin rejecting
that petition, Graham's attorneys decided that they had exhausted
their appeals and that it would be fruitless to take the case to
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit, legal experts speculated, was a last-ditch
attempt to win Graham a stay or keep his case in limbo until
midnight, when his death warrant would have expired and delayed the
execution at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
declined by a 14-3 vote to recommend that Gov. George W. Bush grant
Graham a 120-day reprieve, a commutation or a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Graham had escaped execution in 1993 when then-Gov. Ann Richards
granted him a one-time, 30-day reprieve allowed under Texas law.
Some believed that Bush could have granted another 30-day reprieve,
even without a recommendation from the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that `a' governor can give `a' defendant
one 30-day reprieve,'' said Jerry Perry, a government professor at
Angelo State University in San Angelo, Texas. ``I know that Ann
Richards in 1993 gave Graham a 30-day reprieve. What I don't know,
and I'm not sure anybody knows, is whether or not another governor
can give another reprieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush supported the board's recommendation, saying that 33 judges
had heard Graham's appeals and decided they were ``without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize there are good people who oppose the death
penalty,'' Bush said. ``I have heard their message and I respect
their heartfelt point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``After considering all of the facts, I'm confident justice is
being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham had steadfastly maintained that he was not guilty of the
killing that sent him to Death Row, the 1981 robbery-shooting death
of 53-year-old Bobby Grant Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   The execution capped almost two weeks of tense rhetoric and
demonstrations and a full day of angry protests outside
Huntsville's Walls Unit, a few hundred yards from the execution
chamber. Some demonstrators shouted anti-death penalty slogans with
bullhorns and banged drums.
</P>
<P>
   They called the execution ``a legal lynching.'' Death penalty
supporters, cordoned off in a separate area, said the condemned got
what he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson and the Rev. Al Sharpton, along with U.S.
Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston, social activist Bianca Jagger
and minister Robert Muhammad watched the execution on Graham's
behalf. A protective glass separated them from the death chamber.
MORE: &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
