<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000622.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REEL-REEL-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 2255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEL-REEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 By CAROLYN SAID  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It started simply, &LR;  with a guy who really loved
movies. He scribbled his film recommendations on note cards and
stuffed them into videotape boxes in the small video-rental store
he opened in the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward a decade. From that decidedly low-tech beginning,
Stuart Skorman blazed a trail as an e-commerce pioneer, founding
video seller Reel.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company became a market leader, was sold for a jaw-dropping
sum of money, then proceeded to lose an equally jaw-dropping sum.
And last week, Reel.com had the plug pulled on its e-commerce
operations and laid off most of its staff, amid similar shutdowns
at a score of other dot-com companies.
</P>
<P>
   Reel.com's rapid rise and fall resembles the plot line of
innumerable other e-tailers who went from sizzle to fizzle
practically overnight.
</P>
<P>
   All Skorman wanted to do was share his enthusiasm for movies.
Creative and unconventional, Skorman describes himself as
resembling Doc Brown, the kooky scientist in ``Back to the
Future''; his employees viewed him as Ben and Jerry (of ice cream
fame) rolled into one open-hearted hippie/entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Skorman devised an elaborate, cross-referencing system to help
his video store customers find movies they'd like. Customers loved
the guidance; he was able to add more stores. The seven outlets of
his Empire Video chain in New England became among the
highest-grossing video stores in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster noticed and hired Skorman to create movie kiosks. He
sold Empire to Blockbuster and moved to the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint as a high-stakes professional poker player,
Skorman plunged back into the video business using what he
considered the perfect vehicle: the World Wide Web, which was just
starting to take off.
</P>
<P>
   He started a company in Berkeley, Calif., (it later moved to
nearby Emeryville) and launched a Web site,  &LR; reel.com, &LR;  in January
1997 with a giant database of movie reviews and movie-matching
technology to suggest films people would like based on &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; their past preferences. It was a high-tech version of his note
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Skorman realized people wouldn't pay for the movie suggestions,
so he decided to add an online video store. It opened in April 1997
with 35,000 titles for rent _ five times as many as the average
video store _ and 85,000 for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding people to films they'd like was still his passion. The
fledgling company put thousands of hours into its database of film
reviews. ``We hired the best video store kiddos in town'' _ young
clerks who loved movies as much as he did _ ``paid them $25 an
hour, which was a big deal for them. Sometimes you couldn't walk
through our office, there were so many people lying on the floor
debating about movies.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, Reel opened an 8,000-square-foot walk-in store in
Berkeley to help drive business to the Web site and provide a
stronger income source. It was the first Web site to establish a
physical presence, a strategy that would be called bricks and
clicks two years later. The store used the movie matching
technology in kiosks; had tons of classic, cult and foreign movies;
and carried four times as many titles as most video stores.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Physical Presence a Mistake
</P>
<P>
   The store was a hit, but in retrospect, Skorman says it was a
mistake. ``We only had $4 million (in venture money and private
placement) and we split it between the store and the Web site. We
should have put all our resources into the Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Reel was like producing a major motion picture with a
terrific concept and brilliant cast, but broken-down cameras and an
ever-evolving script. The individual reviews were engaging, and the
movie matching concept worked, but the underlying technology was
rickety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand the importance of the technical side,''
Skorman said. As a result, he didn't invest much time or resources
developing it. ``Our first six months the site crashed daily,
sometimes dozens of times. At one point, we lost 5,000 orders.''
</P>
<P>
   The Keystone Kops pace meant Reel let some big breaks pass by.
Marvin Skorman, Stuart's older brother, flew in from his Rochester,
N.Y., psychotherapy practice one week a month to act as unofficial
chief technology officer. ``Big-name people like TV Guide would
call us and say, `We want to partner,''' he recalled. ``We'd say,
`We don't have time.' They'd offer a bigger percentage. We'd say,
`We're drowning here.' They'd say, `OK, complete creative control.'
We'd say no.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of REEL23 (597 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The site didn't have basic e-commerce features like a way to save
repeat customers' data. Every single time customers placed an
order, they had to type in their address and credit card number.
</P>
<P>
   Renting online was cumbersome _ customers had to order two or
three days in advance, then mail back the videos _ and expensive.
Each title cost $4.50 (later $5) plus shipping, versus $3 or less
at the corner video store.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Skorman considered renting online a stop-gap measure:
He saw Reel's future in video on demand, when consumers would
download movies instantly to their TVs and computers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Unique Site
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the glitches, there was nothing else like it and
the site attracted a growing number of devotees, especially for
video and DVD sales. Sales zoomed from $745,000 for all of 1997 to
about $1 million a month during the first nine months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For movie fans, Reel was a treasure trove. One customer, a guy
named Paul, would frequently call to talk with customer service
reps as he ordered dozens of movies, many so esoteric that even a
film buff like Skorman had never heard of them.
</P>
<P>
   Paul turned out to be Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen. He became
an investor in Reel, along with Intel Corp., a private bank and two
existing investors _ a former Blockbuster executive and
CMGAtVentures _ to the tune of $10.5 million in spring 1998.
</P>
<P>
   With continued growth, Skorman brought in more-experienced
management in the person of Julie Wainwright, who had helped turn
Berkeley Systems from a screen-saver company into an entertainment
company. Wainwright became chief executive in March 1998 and
eliminated the unpractical rentals so Reel could focus on sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' had just shattered box office records and won the
1998 Best Picture Oscar. Wainwright came up with the idea of
selling the video at $9.99, half the studio's recommended price.
Reel would lose $6 on each of the 300,000-odd ``Titanic''
videotapes it sold but gained new customers and brand awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Reel's technology problems were still out of control. Skorman
felt like he was driving a runaway stagecoach. He decided to sell
and talked to the top two video store chains, Viacom's Blockbuster
and Hollywood Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood was still run by its founder, Mark Wattles, who had
parlayed a single Portland, Ore., video store into 1,000 Hollywood
Video outlets in a decade, creating the country's second biggest
video chain after Blockbuster. Viacom was a multinational
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   For Skorman, the choice was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the entrepreneurial spirit Mark Wattles had was
better than a big company like Viacom,'' Skorman said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Selling the Company
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood was eager for an entree to the Internet and Reel
looked like just the ticket. Even though in its brief history Reel
had lost almost $19.8 million on revenues of $9.3 million,
Hollywood paid a princely $96.9 million, a third in cash, the rest
in stock. It was a sevenfold return for Reel's investors, instant
access to millions of customers and great synergy with a leading
brand. The deal made Skorman, who left the company, a
multimillionaire and many of the employees rich.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like the perfect happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Then Godzilla stomped in.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com added videotapes to its product lineup a month after
the Hollywood/Reel deal's October 1998 close. Within 45 days,
Amazon was the No. 1 video retailer on the Web, according to
``Amazon.com,'' Robert Spector's account of the Seattle company's
rise.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Amazon was already the online leader in both books
and CDs. Amazon had bought the Internet Movie Database, an
extensive compendium of movie reviews and trivia, so it had
competitive content. It had a huge customer base and could easily
cross-sell videos to all those book and CD buyers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of REEL23 (597 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Computer seller Buy.com also added movies to its site in
November, plus books and video games. Its philosophy was
rock-bottom prices, dispensing with niceties like reviews. It had
technology to check rivals' Web sites constantly, to make sure its
prices were the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos' take-no-prisoners style and ``Get big
fast'' motto meant he wouldn't be undersold. Suddenly, Reel found
itself in an ugly price war.
</P>
<P>
   Videos never had much margin to begin with. In fact, Amazon,
Reel and Buy.com all bought them from the same distributors. There
wasn't much they could do to differentiate them. Sure, Reel had a
great database, but now so did Amazon. And both Buy and Amazon
could play hardball with pricing because they had other product
lines.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Reel fought back, saying it would match any price.
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright clashed with the new owners and left in February
1999; she soon landed at San Francisco startup Pets.com, partially
funded by Amazon, the company that was crushing Reel.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood started bringing in new management and investing
heavily to fix Reel's shaky technology and market the company.
During the first nine months of 1999, Reel expanded from 115 to 174
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood kept the Reel name, which some saw as a big mistake.
``Had Hollywood Entertainment immediately changed Reel's name to
Hollywood, rerouted all the traffic, educated people that it was
the same Reel but with better backing and selection, they would
have been able to create greater marketing synergies between the
two companies,'' said Ken Cassar, Internet analyst with Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Wattles took over as CEO of Reel after Wainwright left but spent
most of his time in Portland running Hollywood. Some employees said
it was difficult not having an on-site CEO. ``It was like there was
nobody at home,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing Reel's technology underpinnings was a huge task. In
August 1999, Reel introduced a rebuilt site, which finally had
``express ordering'' to let repeat customers store their basic
information so they wouldn't have to type it in with every order.
It was absurdly late.
</P>
<P>
   Reel's losses continued to mount, although that was nothing new
for the world of e-commerce. In 1999, Reel lost $98.5 million on
sales of $40.2 million. The discounting wars had forced it to slash
prices so low that it lost 13 cents on every $1 sale, not including
the costs of marketing, staff, offices and other fixed expenses.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Change of Plans
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Hollywood stopped Reel's deep price cuts; DVDs were no
longer 50 percent off, for example. Reel's gross margins climbed to
7 percent, but it still lost $28.4 million (or $15.9 million
excluding goodwill amortization) on revenues of $14.3 million for
the first quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily leveraged Hollywood couldn't convince its investors to
prop up Reel. Financiers insisted on capping how much Hollywood
spent on the e-commerce operation; it was starting to approach that
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood had hoped to cash in on Wall Street's seemingly
insatiable appetite for e-commerce. But it waited too long.
Hollywood filed registration papers for an IPO in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rumblings about whether e-commerce companies really had
sustainable business models had started to crescendo. By January
2000 pundits were predicting the sector's death and IPOs were being
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's store profits were up 40 percent but its stock had
plunged 75 percent because investors saw Reel dragging it down.
Wattles, who owns about 25 percent of the company, personally lost
more than a quarter of a billion dollars on paper.
</P>
<P>
   He needed to act fast.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of REEL23 (597 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Last week, Hollywood shut down Reel's e-commerce operations and
laid off all of its employees. Reel will continue to exist as a
movie-information site; buyers are referred to former rival
Buy.com. The Berkeley store, one of the country's highest-grossing
video stores, remains open; in fact, Hollywood plans to replicate
its format.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood still hopes that eventually Reel will be its front-end
to video on demand, but expects it will be five to 10 years before
that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart-breaking thing was we had an incredibly talented,
smart group of people at every level,'' said Rosie Ruley Atkins,
who was a vice president from shortly after Reel's inception until
April. In recent months, with its technology problems resolved,
Reel had started ``to mature as an organization,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Skorman has gone on to start another dot-com, online learning
site HungryMinds.com. In his spare time, he plays in a rock 'n'
roll band with friends. They're recording a new song called ``Easy
Dot Com, Easy Dot Go.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Easy dot com, easy dot go &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The market crashed, no more easy dough &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  There was a gold rush that ran out of gold &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  We were moving too fast, now it's time to go slooooooow. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of REEL23 (597 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
