<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GAS-GAS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-GAS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Net's Latest Challenge _ Find Cheaper Gas Prices &HT;    By DAVID LAZARUS 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ From his cluttered apartment in El Cerrito,
Calif., Tom Lu is doing what he can to liberate motorists from the
tyranny of high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right thing to do,'' he said. ``Gas prices are
just insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Lu and a handful of comrades are running a Web site called
PriceHive.com, where users can search free of charge for the
cheapest gas in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   PriceHive is just one example of how the Internet is helping
consumers deal with an extraordinary surge in gas prices
nationwide. Another service launched yesterday by e-commerce
heavyweight Priceline.com allows users to name their own price at
the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense,'' said Derek Leckow, an analyst with
Barrington Research in Chicago, where gas prices are topping $2 a
gallon. ``People are pretty price conscious. It's pretty much the
only differentiating factor when it come to gas.''
</P>
<P>
   At PriceHive, Lu said the idea of allowing users to search for
the cheapest gas in a specific area came to him this spring as pump
prices throughout the Bay Area soared to ``We're drivers, too,'' he
said. ``We felt like victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims, that is, who just so happened to have a proprietary
search engine designed to seek out the cheapest book prices on the
Net _ PriceHive's original focus.
</P>
<P>
   Lu, who had helped develop the software while also working as a
database consultant for clients like Kaiser Permanente health care,
realized the search engine would be equally efficient at
pinpointing low gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   After launching the service in March, Lu said hundreds of
visitors to PriceHive have posted about 1,000 gas prices at more
than 400 gas stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Because the service originally focused only the San Francisco
Bay Area, about three-quarters of the listings are for this region.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a search of San Rafael, Calif., shows that unleaded
regular gas can be had for as little as $1.63 a gallon at Smog Pros
on Second Street or as much as $1.97 at Montecito 76 on Third.
</P>
<P>
   PriceHive also provides a bulletin board for users to trade tips
and rants about gas prices. Recently, one user named Karen alerted
others that the Town Pump station in Roseburg, Ore., was selling
gas for just $1.49 a gallon. ``I suggest you fill up while the
prices are still low,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Doyle in Ohio lamented that pump prices were up another 20
cents in his state and blamed the increase on the Clinton
administration promoting use of cleaner-burning fuel. ``Is there
ever going to be an end to this?'' he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Lu, privately held PriceHive's president and chief executive,
said he sees the site playing a role in organizing boycotts of
especially high-priced oil companies or service stations.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GAS23 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``It's C2B _ consumer-to-business,'' he said. ``Consumers are
telling businesses that they can't afford these prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices skyrocketed in the Midwest this week as reformulated
gas was introduced in several states. The same thing happened in
California several years ago when a similar blend of fuel made its
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Amid such turmoil, not to mention growing political uproar in
Washington, Priceline fortuitously launched its name-your-own-price
gas service yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The service is set up along the same lines as Priceline's
original offering of discount airline tickets and hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Padgett, a spokesman for Priceline WebHouse Club, the
affiliate handling the gas operation, said about 1 million people
had preregistered for the gas service before its official
unveiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very viable business,'' he said. ``I believe Priceline
has proven that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Priceline has yet to earn a nickel in profit, but
that's beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   The company's registered gas customers name a per-gallon price
they would be willing to pay and select three service stations they
would be willing to visit.
</P>
<P>
   If one of those stations agrees to the price, Priceline
automatically deducts the amount of the sale from the user's credit
card and authorizes the pump purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Padgett said average gas prices on Priceline are as much as
20 cents a gallon less than at the pump. Priceline itself makes up
the difference to participating service stations through a
combination of fees paid by oil companies, advertisers and
affiliated sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   While the profitability of such a venture may not be readily
apparent, the crux is that sponsors and advertisers are helping pay
for each purchase in return for being able to promote their goods
and services to Priceline users, and oil companies are cutting into
sales to attract new customers.
</P>
<P>
   Not San Francisco's Chevron Corp., though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at their model,'' said Fred Gorell, a company
spokesman. ``We think it's interesting. But we have decided against
selling motor gasoline online at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Priceline won't say which oil companies or service stations are
participating in its service. But industry sources said none of the
leading players is involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the point?'' Gorell asked. ``The market is competitive
enough as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Not competitive enough for PriceHive's Lu. ``Chevron's profit
tripled recently,'' he said. ``Can you attribute that only to
OPEC?''
</P>
<P>
   Although PriceHive makes no money from its gas-search service,
Lu said he would continue offering it until pump prices return to
earth. And he thinks his site will help.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices in the San Francisco Bay Area, Lu pointed out,
remained largely unchanged as Midwest prices went into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no proof,'' he said, ``but I think we have contributed
to gas-price stability in the Bay Area.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of GAS23 () &QL;
</P>
