Giants Find New Way to Score at Home Field 
By PETER SINTON &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Giants  &LR; have figured another
way to hit homers out of Pacific Bell Park _ renting the popular
stadium to business and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   The whole park rents for up to $125,000 for four hours. America
Online and Time Warner rented it May 11 for a corporate bash, and
on October 28 the Catholic Archdiocese is taking it over for a Mass
for 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit and religious groups get no price break, not even if
they pray for the Giants, said Patrick Gallagher, president of
Giant Enterprises, a subsidiary of the ball club that handles
non-baseball activities. After all, the stadium was privately
financed for $319 million and has major mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the San Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureaus held
its annual luncheon  &LR; at the park, serving a picnic basket lunch and
pitching the 40,800-seat stadium to 1,200 members, including
meeting organizers, event planners and hoteliers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the crowd filled only a small section of field-level
seats, it was influential enough to bring out the three Willies _
Brown, Mays and McCovey.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants and the city both know how important tourism is to
their fortunes. Each year, about 17 million visitors leave $6.6
billion in San Francisco. That's even more important than their
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Business conventions and meetings account for about 25 percent
of the total and pose a potential bonanza for Pac Bell Park. The
Giants play fewer than 90 days a year, which leaves about 275 days
for others to rent the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BALLPARK (90711 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Corporate incentive programs and trade shows are looking for
more than ballrooms,'' said Doug Neilson, vice president of the San
Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. Pac Bell Park with all its
attractions and ferry boat access is quickly joining the ranks of
San Francisco City Hall and local museums as a favorite venue for
corporate parties.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher expects that the park will book about 100 events this
first year and should generate $10 million to $15 million annually
within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to rent the whole stadium for $100,000
weekdays or $125,000 evenings and weekends, you can rent just a
piece of the park. For example:
</P>
<P>
   --Diamond and outfield _ $20,000 each
</P>
<P>
   --90-minute presentation using Astrovision Scoreboard and
seating for 2,500 _ $20,000
</P>
<P>
   --Coca-Cola fan lot _ $12,500
</P>
<P>
   --Luxury suites _ $10,000 each
</P>
<P>
   --Visitors clubhouse _ $2,000
</P>
<P>
   --Giants clubhouse (off-season only) _ $5,000
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher said the Giants also are working with Total Adventures
to rent out the field, or portions of it, to organizations for
team-building events. And for $50,000, you can rent the field to
play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Beware: The listed prices do not include food, beverages or
anything above base rental. When AOL and Time Warner rented Pac
Bell Park to celebrate the launch of eCompany Now magazine, it had
to pay an extra $25,000 just for a large tarp to cover center field
where the band Bare Naked Ladies performed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BALLPARK (90711 ) &QL;
</P>
