<HEADLINE>
HOFFA PRAISES NADER TRADE STANCE, WARNS GORE TO GET `IN TUNE WITH
US' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader
at his elbow, Teamsters President James Hoffa called Thursday for
Vice President Al Gore to get in step with organized labor or risk
losing his bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa stopped well short of endorsing Nader but said his
opposition to recent U.S. trade agreements and advocacy of American
workers' rights should earn him a place in any of this fall's
presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who really wants to see a debate between Al Gore and George
Bush?'' the Teamster chief asked. ``I mean they're somewhat the
same on trade, the same mindless debate on Social Security goes on
and on. We want to broaden the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a meeting of the Teamsters board of directors and
Nader, Hoffa told reporters the union is not close to making an
endorsement decision and is ``not locked into one party or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to wait,'' he said. ``We are not in a
hurry to endorse. We think there is time. We have options of
endorsing or not endorsing.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the vice president gets ``more in tune with us,'' Hoffa
said, the Democrat faces the prospect of going into the November
election without help from the 1.4 million-member Brotherhood of
Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore can't get elected without organized labor,'' Hoffa
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamster board is scheduled today to interview Bush, the
probable Republican presidential nominee, by telephone. In addition
to meeting earlier this year with Gore, the board has interviewed
Pat Buchanan, who is seeking the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa said the Teamsters wants the national Commission on
Presidential Debates, a group appointed by the Republican and
Democratic parties, to open up their forums this fall to Nader and
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's rules allow only candidates with at least 15
percent support in five national polls. An NBC-Wall Street Journal
poll released Thursday had Nader at 7 percent and Buchanan at 4
percent. Bush led the field with 43 percent. Gore was favored by 38
percent of the voters surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's news conference with Hoffa, Nader urged the
union to reject Gore. ``I hope labor unions will rethink their
position when they are taken for granted and told by the Democratic
Party that they have nowhere else to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's support of improved trade relations with China and the
North American Free Trade Agreement has rankled the Teamsters and
the United Automobile Workers union enough that both have refused
to endorse his candidacy. More recently, Hoffa said, the Teamsters
leadership was angered by Gore's naming of Commerce Secretary
William Daley, the administration's chief lobbyist on the China
trade issue, to run his campaign for president,
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems with Gore is (he does) not listen to
labor,'' said Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Gore could do to mend fences, Hoffa said: ``He's got
to articulate a comprehensive policy with regard to organized
labor, with regard to working people in this country, with regard
to how do we keep jobs in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's support for the China and North American trade agreements
and the possible impact on turnout among union voters also bothers
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, whose organization endorsed Gore in
late 1999. ``We have members who are still bitter over NAFTA,
especially in the industrial states,'' said Sweeney, who is among
Gore's more vocal supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message is to convince workers and their families that we
don't agree on everything with any candidate,'' Sweeney said. ``But
you have to look at the total record.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
END OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail in Minnesota, Gore said he hadn't read or
heard Hoffa's comments, but said, ``I have great respect for him.
I've worked closely with the Teamsters and other members of
organized labor. I believe in the right to organize. I want to see
a change in the laws that now allow permanent striker replacements
and actually interfere with the legitimate right of people in the
workplace to have a majority-rule vote on whether or not they want
to organize. I think that's just a basic American principle that
ought to be respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``On issue after issue, I have been with them and although there
have been a few issues where we disagree, I will continue to work
for what I think is in the best interests of working families in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
