<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2275 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-22 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE HAS WORLD AT HIS FEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thoroughbred-racing world got smaller in the 1980s, when the
Breeders' Cup first drew European stars to America, and smaller
still in the 1990s, when the Dubai World Cup became a destination
for America's best older horses.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the world shrank further, to the point that you might
want to picture the globe as a green rubber ball bouncing on the
nose of a horse named Dubai Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Dubai Millennium's eight-length victory Wednesday at England's
Royal Ascot in a 1-mile turf race called the Prince of Wales's
Stakes had implications on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   __ The brilliant victory over five others enhanced Dubai
Millennium's reputation as the best horse in the world.
</P>
<P>
   __ It marked the first victory in Europe for American Hall of
Fame jockey Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   __ It kept Dubai Millennium on course for a U.S. debut in the
Nov. 4 Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   More in a moment about that last point, and the problems it
implies for Horse of the Year voters. First, the glowing reviews of
Dubai Millennium's performance Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything on the other (U.S.) side of the pond
that could touch him,'' Bailey said after subbing for Frankie
Dettori, the champion English jockey who is recovering from
injuries suffered in a small-plane crash three weeks ago at
Newmarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the best horse we have ever had,'' said Dubai's Sheikh
Mohammed, whose powerful Godolphin Racing owns Dubai Millennium.
``You don't come across a horse like this in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most fabulously handsome thoroughbred you have ever
seen in your life,'' said Godolphin racing manager Simon Crisford.
</P>
<P>
   While Crisford works up the courage to propose marriage, let's
move on.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has 4-year-old Dubai Millennium racing in the Sept.
9 Irish Champion Stakes, then in the Breeders' Cup, and then
retiring. Assume he wins both and becomes the first horse to win
the Dubai World Cup and the Breeders' Cup Classic in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Can he be voted the !ital!North American Horse of the Year after
racing on this continent only once?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a similar debate centered on Daylami, the Irish-bred,
Godolphin-owned horse who won three major European races in the
summer and won the Breeders' Cup Turf at Gulfstream Park in Florida
by 2 lengths in November.
</P>
<P>
   I thought Daylami turned in the outstanding performance of
Breeders' Cup day and was the best horse I saw in 1999, so I voted
for him for Horse of the Year. There were precedents for blurring
international boundaries in championship voting: Cigar's victory in
the Dubai World Cup helped him win Horse of the Year in 1996, the
season of his decline; and Miesque's victories in the Breeders' Cup
Mile were the French filly's lone U.S. starts when she was named
champion turf female in 1987 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Other voters refused to go for a horse with only one American
race. As it turned out, Charismatic, the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness winner, was named Horse of the Year, with Daylami second.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guidelines for Horse of the Year voting, and there
is no movement to implement any. The debate over what to do with
brilliant foreign horses was dropped as soon as the Eclipse Award
trophies were handed out. Almost as if the issue was a one-year
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't. From now on it's likely to be an every-year
phenomenon. Horse racing is more and more international. Jockeys
and horses travel the globe as never before. Godolphin's far-flung
power ensures a foreign presence even at a bastion of Americana
like the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   As in every other sport, the international flavor is only making
racing stronger and more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Horse of the Year voters can either embrace the trend or resist
it. But they'd better decide soon. Dubai Millennium threatens to
force the issue.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Riboletta can earn some lofty comparisons by
winning the Vanity Handicap for fillies and mares on Sunday to
become the fourth to sweep Hollywood Park's Hawthorne, Milady and
Vanity.
</P>
<P>
   Cascapedia (1977), Bayakoa (1989) and Brought to Mind (1991)
scored that triple. Riboletta's trainer, Eduardo Inda, was Ron
McAnally's assistant when McAnally had Bayakoa and Brought to Mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brought to Mind was a very nice filly, but Bayakoa was
special,'' Inda said. ``She's the best mare I've ever been
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayakoa won Eclipse Awards as outstanding filly or mare in 1989
and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Riboletta, to be ridden by Chris McCarron, was assigned 123
pounds for the Vanity, three more than Excellent Meeting (Corey
Nakatani).
</P>
<P>
   __ Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies winner Cash Run _ like Dubai
Millennium an offspring of Seeking the Gold _ runs at Hollywood
Park for the first time Saturday in the Princess Stakes for
3-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Ridden by leading jockey Victor Espinoza, Cash Run will carry
122 pounds, four more than anybody else in the field of seven. She
comes off a fourth-place finish in the Black Eyed Susan at Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   Her trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, already owns the record for
Princess victories with four, most recently with A Wild Ride in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   __ Laffit Pincay, Kent Desormeaux and Alex Solis will be among
12 riders in the NTRA All-Star Jockey Championship at Lone Star
Park in Texas tonight. Pincay won it in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The last two races of the four-race competition will be
simulcast to Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   The event benefits the Jockeys' Guild's Disabled Riders Fund.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking ahead: The field expected for the $1 million
Hollywood Gold Cup on July 9 grew to eight Thursday with the
addition of K One King. The 4-year-old son of Apalachee won the
Oaklawn Handicap in Arkansas in April but will go into the Gold Cup
off sixth-place finishes in the Pimlico Special and the Stephen
Foster Handicap at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made by Madeleine Paulson, who owns K One
King with her husband Allen, who had Gold Cup winners in Blushing
John (1989) and Cigar (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Also expected for the Gold Cup: General Challenge, Cat Thief,
Big Ten, Chester House, David, Early Pioneer and Out of Mind. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
