<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VENTURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE COURTING INDEPENDENTS WITH SPECIAL EDUCATION PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNETONKA, Minn. _ Vice President Al Gore, hoping to woo
independent voters in his close race for the White House, spent
Thursday touting his education initiatives on the arm of former pro
wrestler turned maverick governor Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that I'm reaching out to independents and to
independently thinking Republicans,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he isn't expecting an endorsement from Ventura,
but would like his vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit with the governor, the third in as many months, was
dampened Thursday afternoon by the announcement in Washington that
another Justice Department official is calling on Attorney General
Janet Reno to appoint a special counsel to investigate alleged fund
raising abuses during the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore appeared to be caught off guard when asked about the
announcement and declined to comment. ``You're privy to news that I
don't have,'' he told reporters. ``I don't know about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and governor got up early Thursday to greet
students as they stepped off the bus at Hopkins North Junior High
School in suburban Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The two spent the day at the school meeting with teachers,
students and parents as Gore promised the largest-ever increase in
federal special education funding, from $720 million to $1.5
billion a year, beginning his first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case elsewhere in the country, Gore and Bush are
running neck and neck in Minnesota, but Republican leaders here
have said they believe Bush can win the state. No Republican
presidential candidate has done that since Richard Nixon beat
George McGovern in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, an advocate of the third-party movement who was elected
on the Reform Party ticket before he bolted the party, has refused
to endorse either Gore or his Republican opponent, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. But Ventura said Thursday he is willing to endorse
policies from either camp if he agrees with them.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota governor said his experience in rearing a daughter
with learning disabilities convinced him to throw his support
behind the vice president's education plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which Gore first announced earlier this year in Iowa
and New Hampshire, calls for creating an Education Reform and
Children's Trust Fund to set aside part of the projected federal
budget surplus for education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Thursday that he's committed to special education
advocates' longtime goal of having the federal government foot 40
percent of the bill for educating children with physical and mental
disabilities, who sometimes require extraordinarily expensive
services in order to attend public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's overall education plan also includes universal preschool,
smaller class sizes and better-qualified, better-paid teachers. It
would create an early identification and intervention fund to
target children with reading and behavioral problems in
kindergarten or first grade.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura characterized the meeting and the Gores' stay at the
governor's mansion Wednesday night as more of a social call than a
political one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his visit here is in some ways more of a break for him
to get away from the hectic pace of what it's like campaigning out
there,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his wife could be friends with the Gores without
necessarily endorsing the vice president as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good time in Washington when we were out there and I
invited the vice president and Tipper back here when they got to
Minnesota, and I hope they equally had a good time,'' he said.
``And if he wins the presidency, well then I hope I get invited to
the White House at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
