<HEADLINE>
BUD SELIG CONFIRMS RANGERS TO PLAY ASTROS NEXT YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball commissioner Bud Selig said yesterday that a
realignment plan that would move the Rangers to the American League
Central remains alive, but the proposal that's adopted for next
season depends on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``That plan is certainly very much under consideration,'' Selig
said. ``We have four or five formats we're looking at, and we're
testing each one with an actual schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the plan that's approved, Selig confirmed what
Rangers owner Tom Hicks said earlier this month: The Rangers and
Astros will be paired in an interleague matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that's pretty definite,'' Selig said. ``We're
definitely trying to accomplish that no matter what the schedule is
because they are natural geographical rivals. We want to pursue
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig wants baseball to go back to an unbalanced schedule next
season that would have clubs playing more games against teams in
their divisions than those outside. To accomplish that, he proposed
an alignment that would move Arizona from the National League West
to the AL West, Texas from the AL West into a six-team AL Central
and Tampa Bay to the National League, which would then have four
four-team divisions with no wild card.
</P>
<P>
   A vote was expected at owners meetings that were scheduled for
June 13-14 in Detroit, but the meetings were postponed amid
speculation that the plan didn't have enough support to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   The players' union, which has the power to block major changes
in the game, including realignment, complicated the issue by
circulating a memo with an alternate proposal that would have three
divisions of five teams each in the two leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, though, broadly hinted then he had enough votes among the
owners to push the plan through, and said he didn't expect major
problems with the union. The delay was, and remains, a matter of
getting the schedule to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to solve some of the problems we have with the
schedules,'' Selig said yesterday. ``I'll know more when I see the
schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said he hopes to get the schedules within the
next week. He'll determine which works best, then bring it up for a
vote at the next owners meetings, sometime in July.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has said he's willing to remain in the West because of
rivalries with the Seattle Mariners, Oakland Athletics and Anaheim
Angels, even though an unbalanced schedule would mean more games
starting late on the West Coast. His priority is playing the Astros
in interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the realignment plan adopted, or even if there's
no realignment, that should happen.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
