<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-WRESTLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLER GREG GIBSON ISN'T READY TO QUIT SPORT AT AGE 46
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He has won so many titles, earned so many medals, on so
many mats in so many countries, that surely Greg Gibson, age 46, is
headed for wrestling's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, admittedly, there is a hitch. A wrestler has to be retired
_ for five years _ before he becomes eligible for election.
</P>
<P>
   And Gibson, still wrestling at 213.75 pounds, doesn't sound
ready to retire yet from anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you'll probably see me at nationals next year,'' Gibson
said without hesitation, despite a defeat yesterday in his
opening-round match at the U.S. Olympic Team Trials. ``Maybe I can
sneak up on some people when they're not hyped up over this
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbon-dating indicates that Gibson was born in Redding, Calif.,
in 1953. The start of his wrestling career, 1968, predates
Woodstock. Gibson had won a national title and a World
Championships silver medal by the time (1981) that his weight
class' current No. 1 seed, Jason Gleasman, was in first grade.
</P>
<P>
   But _ sigh _ that was then, and yesterday was now.
</P>
<P>
   Matched against veteran four-time national champion Randy
Couture, Gibson was routed, 10-0, in a Greco-Roman bout stopped
with 1:50 to go in the second period. He fell into the losers
bracket and can finish no better in these trials than third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I got blown out,'' Gibson conceded. ``I don't match
up real well with his techniques and his style. It's too bad I had
to have him in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them _ the young guys _ I've been around a long time,
and they've figured out that a lot of movement and a lot of
changing levels works real well against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Age, it seems, is seldom kind to a wrestler. The edge in
experience is mitigated by the dulling in reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young,'' Gibson said, ``you've got that energy and
that spark. A lot of it is reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``My old self would trash my current self pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson joined the U.S. Marine Corps in 1978 and is still on
active duty, holding the rank of master sergeant. He left the U.S.
Greco-Roman national team in 1990 and served in Saudi Arabia during
Operation Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``For six years, I didn't even step on a mat,'' Gibson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1996 that Gibson, transferred to Quantico, Va., walked
into the base's gym for a workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up beating the heavyweight, and I said, `Hey, I must
still have it,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since then, Gibson has placed in the top five at
the U.S. championships three times.
</P>
<P>
   He has already lived his Olympic dream. It came in 1984 when
Gibson won a silver medal at 220 pounds at the Los Angeles Games.
</P>
<P>
   The medal was the fourth major bauble in Gibson's shining
career. As a freestyle wrestler, he had won silver medals at the
1981 and 1983 World Championships and a bronze in '82. He remains
the only U.S. wrestler to win medals at both the worlds and
Olympics in both the freestyle and Greco-Roman competitions.
</P>
<P>
   His most memorable feat, Gibson said, was winning the World Cup
in Trelleborg, Sweden, in 1980 _ the first American ever to win a
gold medal in Greco-Roman wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That keeps you motivated,'' he said yesterday. ``It keeps you
hanging in, trying to relive that experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's getting harder every day.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing fifth at this year's U.S. championships, Gibson
knew that his bid for the Sydney Olympics would be a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to speak realistically,'' he confessed. ``I've seen
those guys before. I knew where I stood.''
</P>
<P>
   His muscle-rippled body belies his 46 years. His 2000 Olympics
dream may be over, someone asked, but, well, what about 2004 ... at
age 50?
</P>
<P>
   Gibson half-smiled and half-winced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll still be wrestling,'' he said, ``but I don't know
how well I could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have to go into the old man's league or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame, in other words, will just have to wait.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
