<SLUG> BC-NY-PIRRO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMINENT BUSINESSMAN, DISTRICT ATTORNEY'S HUSBAND, IS CONVICTED  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ A federal jury on Thursday convicted Albert
J. Pirro Jr., the influential Republican businessman and husband of
Jeanine F. Pirro, the Westchester County district attorney, of
conspiracy and tax evasion, imperiling his business career and
perhaps her political one.
</P>
<P>
   For Pirro, 53, the verdict, if upheld, could derail his career
as Westchester's most powerful real estate development lawyer and
one of New York state's most prodigious Republican fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeanine Pirro, 49, who could have been a strong contender
for the Republican nomination for the U.S. Senate this year were it
not for her husband's legal woes, the verdict jeopardizes her
immediate prospects for higher office. And for Anthony G. Pirro,
Albert Pirro's brother and accountant, who was also convicted
Thursday on similar charges, the result transforms an anonymous
middle-class life into part of a messy public scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Given the star quotient of the principals, the trial, at times,
seemed to be more about celebrity than about conspiracy. A woman
who filed a successful paternity suit against Albert Pirro
threatened to confront him in court, only to be thwarted by federal
authorities in Newark, N.J., on an unrelated warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors suggested that Albert Pirro lusted for money in much
the way that Richard Nixon lusted for power. And a parade of
contractors reluctantly offered intimate details about the Pirros'
lavish expenditures on everything from a $13,250 Chinese rug to a
$1,800 wrought-iron fence for their Vietnamese pot-bellied pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, prosecutors had argued that by improperly
deducting $1.2 million of Albert Pirro's personal expenses as
business write-offs, thereby reducing Albert Pirro's taxes by
$413,000, the brothers had brazenly violated a fundamental tenet of
the American tax system: that every taxpayer must pay his or her
fair share, regardless of wealth or influence.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro and his legal team had argued that Pirro was too busy and
aloof a businessman to pay close attention to such mundane tasks as
bookkeeping. Pirro's team also suggested that the government had
overzealously pursued Pirro, since only 5 percent of his company's
business deductions had been deemed improper.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pirro's lawyers noted that he had repaid about $1
million in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But in withering, meticulous fashion, the government called
about 60 witnesses and referred to thousands of pages of tax
returns, invoices and canceled checks in presenting its portrait of
Albert Pirro as a wealthy man who simply wanted to become wealthier
_ on the taxpayers' dime. Then, the final witness, John Dennehy, a
revenue agent with the IRS, linked the expenses with the fraudulent
tax returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
