<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEFEATS DRUG PLAN IN PARTISAN VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democrats on Thursday night abruptly forced
the first vote of the year on their prescription drug plan, a
politically potent issue on the campaign trail, but the measure was
swiftly defeated by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would lower drug prices for all Medicare
beneficiaries, was rejected by a vote of 53 to 44. Two Republicans
voted in favor of the measure; one Democrat voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when opinion polls show the rising prices for
prescription drugs as a priority among voters, Senate Democrats
seized on a parliamentary trick to force a vote on their bill. In
so doing, they accomplished two political goals: They got the
chance to talk about their plan for making prescription drugs more
affordable to senior citizens and they forced Republicans to cast a
difficult vote, perhaps the only one of the year, on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Medicare was passed, there was a fundamental commitment
by the government to senior citizens,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., who accused Senate Republicans of stalling on a bipartisan
plan. ``Every day we fail to pass a prescription drug program, we
are violating that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans called the maneuver a political stunt that was
rushed, short-sighted and counterproductive. The prescription drug
bill was brought up as part of a larger appropriations bill to fund
the departments of Labor, and Health and Human Services, and was
allowed on the floor with no notice and with less than one hour of
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a politics-first amendment,'' an outraged Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, said. ``Nobody knows what it costs, how it works,
what it does to the solvency of Medicare. This is politics at its
worst. This body is offended by it. I'm offended by it. I don't
think voters will be impressed by circumventing the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also voted to approve a contentious and heavily
lobbied amendment to delay by one year federal regulations that
would require employers to take steps to prevent repetitive motion
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which was bitterly contested by labor unions who
want these worker protections as soon as possible, passed by a vote
of 57 to 41, after Democrats spent the day filibustering the
measuring.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it would recommend a veto of the
spending bill if the measure is not removed. Business groups
vigorously pushed to delay the regulations that would make the work
place ergonomically correct, rules they say are too broad and too
expensive, and could cost employers, by their estimate, $60 billion
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will have the most dramatic effect upon business and the
economy ever promulgated by a federal agency,'' said Sen. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``We are talking about $60 billion a year
imposed upon the business community.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most surprising turn of events involved prescription
drugs, which descended on the Senate seemingly out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Democrats have accused Senate Republicans of
stalling on the issue of prescription drugs, and some predicted
today's vote could be the only Senate vote of the year on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee, chaired by Sen. William Roth Jr.,
R-Del., is working on a bipartisan bill that would address concerns
about prescription drug prices. But Democrats say the committee is
inching along and is unlikely to move this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prescription drugs is a matter before the finance committee,''
Roth told Democrats on the floor. ``It is undoubtedly the most
important domestic legislation that will be considered this year.
Nothing will happen if we permit this legislation to become
partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans voted their own drug plan out of committee on
Wednesday, but Democrats called it faulty, saying it should be
better integrated into the Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thursday's Democratic bill, written by Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla., drug insurance companies' premiums for Medicare
beneficiaries would be $35 to $40 a month, the same as under the
House Republican measure.
</P>
<P>
   The beneficiary would have to pay the first $250 a year in
prescription drug expenses. The government would share costs beyond
that amount, paying a larger proportion as drug expenses increased.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats signed on to the bill once Graham agreed to
drop a provision that would have forced people with high incomes to
pay higher premiums. Now premiums will not be dictated by income.
</P>
<P>
   This is significantly different from the proposal offered by
House Republicans. Under that plan, Medicare would pay half of drug
costs from $250 to $2,100, but the patient would then be solely
responsible for several thousand dollars of drug costs, and the
insurer would not step in again until the beneficiary had incurred
$6,000 of costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clearly a part of modern medicine today,'' said Sen.
Charles Robb, D-Va., referring to the drug plan. ``It is not a
luxury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
