<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND QUARTER INCOME UP 27 PERCENT FOR MORGAN STANLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Profiting from gains in stock trading and investment
banking, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. reported on Thursday that
net income in its fiscal second quarter rose 27 percent from the
period a year earlier but fell 6 percent from the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, the biggest securities firm measured by market
value, said it earned $1.46 billion, or $1.26 a diluted share, in
the quarter that ended May 31, compared with $1.15 billion, or 97
cents a share, in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although the results exceeded the analysts' consensus estimate
of $1.13, according to First Call/Thomson Financial, Morgan
Stanley's stock dropped $2.4375, to $83.1875. Its shares are more
than $10 below the high mark they hit in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their trading profitability was much stronger than most people
thought it could be'' in a quarter that was interrupted by a sharp
decline in Nasdaq stocks, said Guy Moszkowski, a Salomon Smith
Barney analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley benefited from a strategy that positioned the
firm to gain whether stocks rose or fell, Moszkowski said. As long
as stock prices were volatile, which they were, the firm would
profit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Scott, the firm's chief financial officer, said it made
more money trading stocks, oil and other commodities last quarter
than in any other quarter. ``Having lots of volume, lots of
uncertainty, lots of price volatility fits our trading style very
well,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the firm's securities businesses rose 28 percent,
to $5.45 billion and total net revenue _ revenue minus interest
expense _ rose 25 percent, to $7.07 billion. The money it took in
as investment banking fees and commissions, much of it from
customers of its Dean Witter brokerage unit, increased by more than
30 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Return on shareholders' equity was 33 percent, up from 31
percent a year earlier, but down from an unusually high 36 percent
in the first quarter.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
