<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PAT-DAY-ALL-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT DAY HAS UNCANNY KNACK FOR GETTING THE MOST FROM HORSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Donnie Meche knows a jockey can be a
familiar face, a household name in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Meche, the leading jockey at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie,
began to realize stardom was possible when he quietly rode in the
back seat of a car driven by fellow jockey Robby Albarado through
the streets of Lexington, Ky., one day last spring. Meche looked
out his window and saw how people reacted to the guy riding
shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would drive by, our windows would be up, and we'd be
out on the highway, but you could see how people noticed him when
they drove beside us,'' Meche said. ``You could read their lips.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Look! That's Pat Day! It's Pat Day!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day will join Meche and 10 other jockeys tonight at Lone
Star for the $125,000 National Thoroughbred Racing Association
All-Star Jockey Championship.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first year for the 25-year-old Meche to ride in the
event, and his first chance to ride in front of a national TV
audience (ESPN2, tape delayed at 10:30 p.m.). But Day has
participated each of the three previous years the competition has
been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   He's old hat at the national-network-TV thing, too. He's one of
the older jockeys in the competition; at 46, he's the third-oldest
All-Star and eight years older than the average age of the 12
riders. But that doesn't mean he should be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of that came the most recent time Day was on national TV.
He was riding Commendable, a 16-1 long shot in the Belmont Stakes
two weeks ago, and the colt was dismissed by most prognosticators
because he hadn't won a race since August. But the colt is trained
by D. Wayne Lukas, and Day has teamed with Lukas to win the
Preakness Stakes three times and the Belmont one other time. In
November, they paired to win the Breeders' Cup Classic on long-shot
Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great relationship,'' Lukas said. ``I think he suits
our horses, but I think he suits everyone's horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his own words, he tries not to hinder the horses he rides.
He has a marvelous sense of pace.''
</P>
<P>
   And pace is what got the job done for Day with Commendable in
the Belmont. He was able to run out alongside fellow long-shot Hugh
Hefner and glide through easy fractions of 1 minute, 14 seconds
through the opening half of the 1 1/2-mile race. That's two seconds
slower than horses of that caliber typically run for that distance.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hugh Hefner tired, Day still had plenty of horse left
with Commendable. Race favorites Aptitude and Unshaded _ ridden by
Alex Solis and Shane Sellers (both also in the All-Star
Championship tonight) _ had too much ground left to cover. They
advanced to second and third, and Day cruised home on Commendable
without touching him with the whip once.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best jobs between a trainer and rider that
I've seen in a big race like that,'' said William Allen, who owned
Wild Again when Day rode him to victory in the first Breeders' Cup
Classic in 1984. ``Those guys knew that everyone else with a chance
in the race was going to take back \Roff the early lead\S and leave
the front wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we needed a rider on Wild Again, we flew to Oaklawn Park
to see if he would be available. Pat called Ray Sibille \Rwho had
ridden Wild Again\S and found out that Wild Again didn't like to be
hit with the whip. That was pretty conscientious of Pat, and if he
had hit Wild Again in the Classic he would have lost the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Day somehow finds the way to communicate with horses. It starts
with communication between himself and the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne and I spoke briefly in the paddock before the Belmont,''
Day said. ``Our horse had shown some speed in previous races, and
the only thing Wayne really told me was that the colt was better in
the clear and if I could get inside of Hugh Hefner it would be
great. That was about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne brings them over \Rto the races\S prepared. And he has
great confidence in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Day _ who lives outside Louisville, Ky., and is a
regular rider on the Kentucky racing circuit _ has won more than
7,700 races. That places him third in career victories behind
Laffit Pincay Jr. and Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, 53, likely will retire after he gets to career victory
No. 9,000, a milestone he will probably reach this year.
</P>
<P>
   Day has been winning 250 to 275 races per year. So it would take
him at least five years to match Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   Day can't give a guarantee that he'll be around to put a run in
at the record. His religious convictions are deep, and he said if
the Lord calls him to do something else, he'll do it even if it
means leaving the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   He said he almost gave up riding for the ministry when he made a
commitment to Christianity on Jan. 27, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, right now, this is what he wants me doing,'' Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Day credits his beliefs in turning his life around from drug use
and carousing. Followers at the racetrack have an easy time
noticing the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same every day,'' Lukas said. ``He's at peace with
himself. He's not fighting any demons within himself like a lot of
riders are.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to the major races, you know he's going to
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   And that includes tonight in the All-Star Jockey Championship.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
