r s BC-OLY-WRESTLING-TRIALS-     06-22 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLING-TRIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WRESTLER WANTS ONE MORE SHOT AT RUSSIAN ICON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The clean-shaven head collapsed into his left hand; the
thumb and forefinger clenched the bridge of the nose.
</P>
<P>
   Tears streamed from the giant's eyes while his neck supported
the silver medal suspended by a green ribbon. There in Atlanta at
the 1996 Olympic Games, Matt Ghaffari wept for all the world to see
during the medal ceremony, as Alexander Karelin stood to his left
on the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin, a Russian Army general and a three-time Olympic gold
medalist, remains Greco-Roman wrestling's icon, and Ghaffari longs
for one more crack at his undefeated archrival at 286 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my dream,'' Ghaffari said yesterday after his
quarterfinal victory in the challenger tournament of the U.S.
Olympic Team Trials at Reunion Arena. ``I want him to have one
loss. He always jokes about how I'm a worthy opponent, but I don't
want him to retire undefeated. Nobody is bigger than our sport,
although he thinks he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghaffari, 38, nears the end of an illustrious career as this
country's most decorated medalist from Olympic and World
Championships competition. Yet, unfinished business remains.
</P>
<P>
   Three men and four victories separate him from a berth on the
U.S. Olympic team and perhaps another bout with Karelin during the
2000 Sydney Games. Ghaffari earned a berth in today's challenge
tournament semifinals with his 7-0 victory against Paul Devlin
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ghaffari must defeat Billy Pierce in the semifinals and either
Corey Farkas or Dremiel Byers in the challenger final today to earn
a best-of-three match tomorrow with reigning U.S. national champion
Rulon Gardner for an Olympic berth. Ghaffari's vast international
experience makes him the favorite to meet Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but I'd have to say Ghaffari is going to be the
odds-on favorite with all of his experience,'' U.S. Greco-Roman
coach Dan Chandler said before the Olympic trials. ``With all the
World medals _ and he's won an Olympic medal and multiple Pan
American championships _ you've got to look at him to be the guy to
beat in the challenge tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Paulson (119 pounds), Dennis Hall (127.75), Kevin
Bracken (138.75), Heath Sims (152), Matt Lindland (167.5), Quincey
Clark (187.25), Jason Gleasman (213.75) and Gardner (286) drew byes
into tomorrow's best-of-three finals as reigning national
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Their top challengers _ Steven Mays (119), Jim Gruenwald
(127.75), Glenn Nieradka (138.75), David Zuniga (152), Keith
Sieracki (167.5), Dan Henderson (187.25) and Garrett Lowney
(213.75) _ also advanced with victories yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Each must remain focused to avoid a premature exit and see years
of dedication go for naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's harder to get up for matches, and especially for
guys you've beaten over and over,'' Ghaffari said. ``But if you
don't get up, that's the guy that will upset you. Every one of them
is like Karelin for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian giant must fall, Ghaffari says, and three Americans
remain in his path before another potential shot at Karelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is myself proving to everybody that I'm the best
representative this country has,'' Ghaffari said. ``I get motivated
representing the United States, and if I'm the best representative
this country has for the Olympics to win a medal, it's my job to
make the team.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
