u f BC-SNAPPLE-NYT &LR;      06-22 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAPPLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIARC WILL SPIN OFF SNAPPLE BEVERAGE UNIT
</HEADLINE>
  By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Triarc said on Thursday that it would spin off part
of its beverage division, which includes the Snapple, Mistic and
Royal Crown brands.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the plan will be filed in the next few days with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, a spokeswoman said. Shares in
the new company, to be called the Snapple Beverage Group and
consist of up to 20 percent of Triarc's soft-drink holdings, would
be sold in the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the public offering, which is being underwritten
by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Lehman Brothers, Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette and ING Barings, would be used to pay off debt. Over time,
some analysts believe, Triarc will relinquish more of the
soft-drink division to the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Triarc fell 43.8 cents, to $19.75 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   As a separate company, Snapple could become a takeover target or
an acquirer of other soft-drink brands. Its namesake lineup, which
includes noncarbonated drinks with flavors like peach, lemonade and
iced tea, represents the new age beverages that consumers have been
flocking to in recent years. The trend has diminished growth of
colas, and soft-drink giants like Coca-Cola and PepsiCo say they
intend to widen their array of brands to capture more market share.
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewel of the Triarc beverage division is Snapple,
which the company bought from Quaker Oats in 1997. Snapple's volume
grew 6 percent last year, when the industry overall was essentially
flat. Other company brands did not do as well: Royal Crown fell
13.5 percent and Mistic declined by 22 percent. A fourth brand,
Stewart's, grew by 13 percent on a base far smaller than Snapple's.
</P>
<P>
   The division had revenues last year of $770 million and adjusted
pretax earnings of $101 million. Within the highly competitive
soft-drink industry, Triarc's beverages are the country's sixth
largest in volume, said John D. Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest,
an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Triarc's other holdings include the Arby's restaurant franchise
and two smaller franchises. At various times, the company has owned
petroleum companies and textile makers, and is considered complex
both structurally and financially. In late 1998, Triarc's chairman,
Nelson W. Peltz, announced that he would take the company private
for $18 a share, or $420 million, because Wall Street was
underappreciating its value. Almost as abruptly, he changed his
mind in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this deal does is, it creates a pure play,'' Sicher said.
``They are trying to unlock what they believe is some unrecognized
value in the beverage business, which has been part of this
complicated Triarc picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Weinstein, Triarc's chief executive for beverages, will
become chief executive of the new company. Peltz will become its
chairman and Peter W. May, president and chief operating office of
Triarc, will be vice chairman. All three will become directors of
Snapple, which is based in White Plains, N.Y., along with four
outside directors.
</P>
<P>
   Sicher said Weinstein had done much to rebuild Snapple after the
brand was acquired from Quaker. Quaker purchased Snapple, which was
then publicly traded, for $1.7 billion in 1994. After a disastrous
period in which sales and market share plummeted and Wendy the
Snapple Lady, the brand's distinctive, loud-mouthed spokeswoman,
was fired, Quaker put the brand on the block and sold it to Triarc
for just $310 million. Among Weinstein's moves was bringing Wendy
Kaufman back in mid-1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
