u a BC-WATER-MARS-HNS &LR;      06-22 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-MARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOS OFFER `COMPELLING' EVIDENCE OF WATER ON MARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists on Thursday presented photographic evidence from
NASA's Mars Global Surveyor of 120 sites where water appears to
have oozed from crevices in the walls of craters, cliffs and
gullies scattered across the Martian south and north poles.
</P>
<P>
   The findings made by geologists Mike Malin and Ken Edgett of San
Diego, Calif., who developed and operate the cameras aboard the
orbiting Global Surveyor, were culled from 65,000 images of the
planet's surface taken since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is some of the most exciting data we have had concerning
this issue,'' said Mike Carr, an expert from the U.S. Geological
Survey who has studied the Martian water mystery for more than 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The images I've seen are really quite compelling.``
</P>
<P>
   Working from images gathered by much less sophisticated cameras
aboard American robotic spacecraft launched to Mars in the late
1960s and throughout the 1970s, scientists had formed a consensus
that water flowed across the planet billions of years ago leaving
traces of river beds, gullies, watersheds and possibly shorelines
where the liquid pooled.
</P>
<P>
   The contemporary Mars is a rugged desert, frigid and with an
atmosphere much too thin for liquid water to flow or pool on the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   The latest images from the sharper-eyed Mars Global Surveyor
appear to dash the belief among experts that the once plentiful
liquid water on the surface of the planet has filtered to depths of
at least several miles and frozen, accessible only with excavation.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting a few of the 150 highest quality images from Global
Surveyor to make their point, Malin and Edgett pointed to narrow
elongated openings at the tops of meteor crater rims, gullies and
cliffs where water appears to have emerged in a rush, carving a
narrow V-shaped channel that winds down an incline to a wider
outfall.
</P>
<P>
   The topography suggests the outflows emerged repeatedly from
depths of less than 1,300 feet in the Martian crust in quantities
equivalent to about 90,000 cubic feet, enough water on Earth to
sustain a neighborhood of 100 households for about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Other clues in the features suggest the water has flowed as
recently as the last 1,000 years if not later and certainly within
the past one million years, said Malin and Edgett.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, who unveiled the findings at a news conference
in Washington, base their chronological estimates on the absence of
meteor craters on the features. The oldest Martian terrain bears
the scars of extensive cratering by meteors.
</P>
<P>
   The two scientists say the features and hydrology they describe
is common on Earth, accessible to any tourist who travels through
the Colorado plateau in the American West.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike a more hospitable Earth, the water that flows
from the Martian subsoil evaporates in the cold, thin atmosphere
before it can collect into pools.
</P>
<P>
   The finding is the most significant yet for NASA's $273 million
Mars Global Surveyor mission. But the space agency joined Malin and
Edgett in cautioning that their initial conclusions must hold up
under prolonged scrutiny from other scientists, who may offer other
explanations for the phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are no volcanoes in the widely scattered regions to
suggest lava flows, there could be a combination of
little-understood activities under way in the subsoil that would
contribute to a gaseous flow of carbon-rich material, said Carr.
</P>
<P>
   And experts will likely quarrel over the source of the heating
that would convert water frozen in the subsoil to a liquid. The
scientist speculated that the decay of radioactive materials could
furnish the warmth, much as it does deep in the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The debate should begin in earnest next week with the
publication of a formal report in Science, this country's premier
journal of new discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not found lakes and rivers flowing on Mars. They
have not found hot springs sprouting out of Mars. They certainly
have not found a hot tub with Martians swimming in it either,''
said Ed Weiler, NASA's associate administrator for space science.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the announcement is sure to stir public and
scientific interest in Mars exploration for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   If water is abundant close to the surface of Mars, it
strengthens the case that the neighboring planet may now be or was
in the past a suitable host for primitive life.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, surface water would furnish an accessible vital
resource for future human explorers, though NASA currently has no
exploration plans for its astronauts beyond the assembly of the
U.S.-led international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Water is easily broken down into its constituent chemicals,
hydrogen and oxygen, which are also rocket fuels. The oxygen and
water could be consumed for life support, easing the need to
transport continuous supplies from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally unexpected,'' said David McKay, a planetary
scientist at NASA's Johnson Space Center, who professed to be among
those most pleased with the finding.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail in Minnesota, Vice President Al Gore said
during a news conference that the Mars finding was ``a very
exciting development.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore serves as the point man for the Clinton White House on
space policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is yet another finding that will make it inevitable that
one day you will see a worldwide expedition to place people on the
surface of Mars,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
