<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAGEO-BURGER-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAGEO PLANS TO SELL 20 PERCENT STAKE IN BURGER KING 
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diageo PLC, the expansive British food and spirits company, said
Thursday that it planned to sell a 20 percent stake in Burger King,
the fast-food chain. The sale could be a first step in an eventual
spinoff, a goal of Diageo for years.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo officials said that the offering of Burger King stock on
the New York Stock Exchange could be made by spring 2001, and that
the remainder could be sold as early as December 2002, when the
company's tax liabilities would fall significantly.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as Diageo also announced the surprise
departure of Dennis Malamatinas, Burger King's chief executive.
Malamatinas, who left his family in Britain four years ago to run
Burger King from its Miami headquarters, said he was unwilling to
remain for the extra time needed to take Burger King public.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo said that Malamatinas would take a job in Europe at an
unspecified American company and that Colin Storm, head of Diageo's
Guinness division, would temporarily replace him at Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   Since the food giant Grand Metropolitan and the beer maker
Guinness merged to create Diageo in 1997, company officials have
talked about selling Burger King. But they have been hampered by
the prospect of paying roughly $1.5 billion in taxes if they did so
before 2002. Analysts have estimated the entire value of Burger
King at somewhere between $2.4 billion and $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, company officials say, U.S. tax law was changed to
allow foreign companies to sell up to 20 percent in an American
subsidiary at a lower rate. That change provided Diageo with the
window it was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   With such widely recognized names as Haagen-Dazs, Smirnoff and
Pillsbury, Diageo has come under investor pressure to strengthen
its stock by taking some brands public. Analysts say Burger King, a
retail chain that never quite fit within the company's rubric of
packaged goods, is a logical choice, particularly because conflict
with owners of franchises has made it increasingly difficult to
manage.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by an increase in royalty rates scheduled for July and
an expensive refurbishment plan for Burger King restaurants,
franchise owners, who run more than 90 percent of Burger King's
restaurants, pressed for a separation from Diageo in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The renovations could cost well over $100,000 per store,''
said Mitchell Speiser, senior analyst at Lehman Brothers. ``That's
a lot of money for someone who owns a couple of stores and is
trying to put their kids through college, especially since it's not
proven it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Burger King lost market share to competitors last year, slipping
from 20.4 percent of the American market to 19.6 percent, according
to Technomics, which tracks the industry. Sales were also flat,
compared with increases of 3 percent at McDonald's and 8 percent at
Wendy's.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King made a run on McDonald's dominance in the American
fast-food market in the mid-1990s, but a slowdown in marketing,
promotions and new products last year has kept it in second place.
``It's not fun competing against McDonald's,'' said Emanuel
Goldman, an analyst with ING Barings. ``It's sort of like taking on
the Lakers in the Forum.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a Burger King spinoff raised speculation
Thursday that a spinoff or sale of Pillsbury could follow. Company
officials did not rule out that possibility, but stressed that the
Burger King sale should not be interpreted as a ``dry run'' for its
Pillsbury division, which has also been facing increased
competition recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
