<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-1STLD-W     06-22 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMATE IS EXECUTED IN TEXAS AS 11TH-HOUR APPEALS FAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for complete writethru adding 1,200 words  
By FRANK BRUNI with JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Gov. George W. Bush's backing and his
somberly stated conviction that ``justice is being done,'' the
state of Texas Thursday night executed Gary Graham, who had been
convicted for the 1981 murder of a man outside a Houston
supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The execution was carried out even though five of the 18 members
of the Bush-appointed parole board argued against it, and the U.S.
Supreme Court also divided sharply over the issue, declining to
review the case by a 5--4 vote.
</P>
<P>
   When the moment of Graham's execution finally arrived, Bush did
not merely issue a written statement, but spoke to a crowd of
reporters in a solemn voice that contradicted his often
light-hearted nature. His facial expression and his words matched
his tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a responsibility I take very seriously,'' Bush said,
reading from a statement, ``because the final determination of
innocence or guilt is among the most profound and serious decisions
a person can make. I recognize that there are good people who
oppose the death penalty. I have heard their message and I respect
their heartfelt point of view.'``
</P>
<P>
   Then he recited a series of heinous crimes attributed to Graham
and noted that Graham had even confessed to some of them. He said
that Graham's case, over the 19 years since the murder for which he
was executed, had been reviewed ``more than 20 times by state and
federal courts'' and by 33 judges.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he backed the board's vote Thursday afternoon to
authorize the execution. ``After considering all the facts,'' he
said, ``I'm confident that justice is being done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case attracted a remarkable amount of national and
even international attention, for many reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Questions arose about the testimony of the sole witness in the
case as well as the fact that his court-appointed lawyer provided
only a nominal defense. In addition, several jurors later expressed
doubt that they would have convicted him if they had been aware of
certain facts and testimony during the trial. Many legal experts
cast Graham as a perfect example of all that was wrong with the
judicial system and the death penalty, though many others noted
that his appeals were been lodged in dozens of courts and been
considered by an even larger number of judges as he avoided
execution for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's execution was delayed for nearly two hours as his
lawyers mounted last-minute appeals that took state officials by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 36, died at 8:49 p.m. Central Daylight Time, becoming
the 135th person to be put to death in Texas since Bush became
governor 5 1/2 years ago. That statistic, combined with Bush's
prominence as the presumptive Republican presidential nominee,
partly explained why Graham's case received such scrutiny from news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Bush had said repeatedly that if the Texas
Board of Pardons and Paroles authorized Graham's execution, he had
no power in this particular case to grant Graham a reprieve an
interpretation of Texas law with which some legal experts
disagreed. But Bush made no mention of that Thursday night as he
publicly endorsed the board's decision.
</P>
<P>
   His demeanor suggested a sensitivity not only to the passions
that Graham's case had inflamed but also to his own need to project
an impression of approaching such enormously heavy, life-and-death
responsibilities with the utmost thoughtfulness and seriousness.
Advisers to Bush's presidential campaign said that they are
conscious of and have discussed the importance of Bush's tone and
bearing when discussing the death penalty, but they said his
decisions in each case were never subjected to political
considerations and were entirely his own.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, there is little evidence that Bush's fervent
advocacy of the death penalty carries any political risks. Although
recent polls have shown some softening in public support of the
death penalty, the surveys also show that roughly two-thirds of
Americans still favor it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the ground has shifted remarkably,'' said Linda
DiVall, a Republican pollster. ``I don't think he's got any
problem. I think he's showing the proper sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's execution had been scheduled for 7 p.m. after the Texas
Board of Pardons and Parole declined by a vote of 12-5 to grant a
request for clemency and the U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear a
last-minute appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A third appeal was denied by the state's Court of Criminal
Appeals, the highest criminal court in Texas. But minutes before 7
p.m., Graham's lawyers filed still another one, this time a civil
lawsuit against the board of pardons. Though it, too, was
ultimately rejected by U.S. District Judge James Nowlin, the legal
maneuver caused yet another delay.
</P>
<P>
   Nowlin called the civil action ``an extremely tardy effort to
delay the execution.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the appeals worked through the courts, he remained in a
holding cell only steps from the death chamber accompanied by the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, the Rev. Al Sharpton and Bianca Jagger, a
representative of Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the execution, as questions about
Graham's fate dogged Bush along the campaign trail, he said
repeatedly that he was powerless to intervene in Graham's case if
the board of pardons authorized his execution _ an interpretation
of Texas law that some legal experts disputed.
</P>
<P>
   On the separate matter of whether Graham should be given a
conditional pardon, all 17 members voted no. Only a simple majority
of board members is required to allow an execution to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Dow, a professor of law at the University of Houston,
said the last-minute uncertainty that suddenly descended over
Graham's execution reflected how sophisticated his lawyers were and
how sensitive Bush and the state of Texas were to the intensity of
public attention to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Under different circumstances, Dow said, the state might have
gone ahead with the execution, because Graham's lawyers had already
exhausted all the traditional arguments in all the usual venues.
</P>
<P>
   The case also came at a time of deepening debate over capital
punishment, provoked by advances in DNA technology, new studies
that question the fairness with which the death penalty is
administered and the emergence of Bush, who presides over a state
that executes more inmates than any other, as a candidate for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The governor maintained that he was treating this case no
differently than any other and that any action he did or did not
take would be impervious to political considerations, immune to
public protests and unaffected by a campaign that has pivoted on
his portrayal of himself as a sensitive, compassionate
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a lot of hand-wringing,'' said one adviser. ``But
everyone recognizes that the environment has changed now that he's
running for president.'' The adviser added that there was some
minimal concern _ though not too much yet _ that all the attention
to the death penalty in Texas was at times eclipsing the other
issues Bush wanted to discuss on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had taken any kind of action to stop Graham's death, it
would have been the second time this month that he had intervened
to halt an execution in defiance of the board's recommendation.
Prior to June 1, he had never done so, although he did concur in
1998 with the board's vote to commute the death sentence of Henry
Lee Lucas, a confessed serial killer, to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Several political analysts said that one challenge before Bush,
now that almost everything he did was being evaluated through the
prism of his presidential ambitions, was not to come across as
vulnerable to public pressures or unsteady in his convictions. Bush
has repeatedly assailed Vice President Al Gore as someone who bends
too readily with the political winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing for him to do is remain consistent,''
said Don Sipple, a Republican strategist. Sipple said he believed
it was voters' impressions of Bush's constancy that explained the
high marks he received in many recent opinion polls for his
leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, there has been some evidence in polls of a softening in
public support for the death penalty, but those same polls showed
that roughly two-thirds of Americans are still in favor of it. And
several political analysts said that that was a large enough
majority, on a subject that was not at the top of most voters'
concerns, for Bush to rest assured that he was on the right side of
the issue. Gore also supports the death penalty and has been
relatively reticent to challenge Bush on the brisk rate of
executions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the governor has extremely limited discretion
if the board authorizes an execution. All the governor can do under
those circumstances is grant the inmate a one-time reprieve of 30
days, though that time often grows as the inmate undertakes new
court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said that in this case, he could not do even that. A
64-year old clause in the Texas constitution says that the governor
``shall have the power to grant one reprieve in any capital case,''
and only one reprieve. Both Bush and lawyers for the state have
interpreted that to mean that because Gov. Ann Richards had granted
Graham such a reprieve in 1993, Bush was unable to.
</P>
<P>
   But other legal experts said that the constitution could be
interpreted as permitting one reprieve per governor, not per
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's plain old ambiguous,'' said Dow, noting that no court in
Texas had ever considered the language or issued a ruling on its
precise meaning. He went on to say, ``It's easier to say you have
no power than to exercise it.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was convicted for the May 13, 1981, murder of Bobby
Lambert in the parking lot of a Houston grocery store. His
conviction provoked little fanfare at the time, but his case
gradually attracted the attention of death penalty opponents.
</P>
<P>
   His advocates argued that Graham's trial lawyer, Ronald Mock,
put up a lackluster defense and scarcely investigated the case. No
physical evidence linked Graham to the scene, and ballistics tests
found that a .22-caliber revolver confiscated from him did not
match the murder weapon. His conviction rested on the testimony of
a woman sitting in her car, Bernadine Skillern, who saw the killer
as he confronted and shot Lambert about 30 feet away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
