<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-GONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES MAY TENTATIVE DEAL TO ACQUIRE GONZALEZ 
 
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Yankees have agreed to a trade in
principle for the Detroit slugger Juan Gonzalez and have until
Sunday to negotiate a contract extension with the two-time most
valuable player, several baseball officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In return for Gonzalez, the Yankees have agreed to swap Drew
Henson, their best prospect, as well as outfielder Ricky Ledee and
the left-handed pitcher Randy Keisler, currently in Class AA.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are still negotiating with the Chicago Cubs for
Sammy Sosa, but have found the asking price of five or more players
to be high. The Yankees will not complete trades for both players.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Gonzalez, who drove in more than 100 runs seven
times with the Texas Rangers, controls his future because a limited
no-trade clause in his contract allows him to veto any proposed
trade to a New York team. He could say no to the Yankees, flatly,
because he does not want to play in New York. Luis Mayoral, a
friend of Gonzalez and the Tigers' Latin American liaison, told The
Detroit Free Press that ``New York is too fast for Juan's persona.
He likes Arlington and Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees contacted Gonzalez's agent, Jim Bronner, on
Thursday, but made no immediate progress toward securing the
player's approval either for the trade or for a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who is in the last year of his contract, could agree
to play for the Yankees, but refuse to sign a contract extension.
This would give the slugger a stage with a contending team in the
months before he can become a free agent. But the Yankees probably
would not be interested because they do not want to give up top
prospects for what would essentially be a three-month rental.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez could agree to a contract extension, although he has
already rejected a huge offer from the Tigers _ something in the
range of eight years for $140 million, or about $17.5 million per
year _ and, reportedly, Bronner asked the Tigers for $148 million
over eight years. The Yankees presumably would have to make a
similar commitment to Gonzalez to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   With the Tigers and Yankees on the cusp of a deal, Detroit
officials went to Toronto, where the team was playing, and are
believed to have met with Gonzalez. Whatever Gonzalez told them did
not discourage the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the 20-year-old Henson could be a huge coup for Detroit.
He attended high school in Michigan and expects to be the starting
quarterback for the University of Michigan this fall. There remains
a question of whether Henson will play baseball or football
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   In return for Sosa, the officials said, the Cubs have asked the
Yankees for at least five players, among a group that includes the
Class AAA shortstop Alfonso Soriano; Henson; Ledee; Keisler; the
recently promoted pitcher Jake Westbrook and the Class AA
right-hander David Walling. The market for Sosa has not been
robust, and the Yankees may be trying to use the Gonzalez
negotiations to push the Cubs. Many of the advisers to George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, have told him that
Gonzalez is a better all-around player, but Sosa possesses more
marquee value.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Gonzalez would propel the Yankees' payroll to
astronomical levels. If an agreement were reached, the Yankees
would most likely have to pay Gonzalez about $17 million per year.
They already have to pay Bernie Williams $12.5 million a year
through the 2006 season. Derek Jeter is making $10 million this
year and will make much more than that; negotiations for a $118.5
million deal have fallen apart and Jeter's long-term deal could
eventually approach $20 million per season. Mariano Rivera, the
closer, is making $7.25 million this year and soon could command in
excess of $20 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are paying second baseman Chuck Knoblauch $6 million
for this year and next, and at the time they traded for him in
1998, they agreed to give him a two-year, $18 million extension
that has never been announced. Similarly, Roger Clemens is expected
to receive a two-year extension for about $14 million to $15
million per year for 2001-2002, an agreement made at the time the
Yankees acquired him. The Yankees' payroll, now at $92 million,
could approach $140 million to $150 million in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees continue to search for pitching help. They had a
scout watch the Rangers righthander Esteban Loaiza on Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
