<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HERBALIFE-1STLD-WRITE     06-22 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBALIFE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERBALIFE FACES CHALLENGES AFTER FOUNDER`S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite 15th graf for accuracy, bgng: To keep
Hughes'...)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Herbalife International was built on Mark Hughes' story.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager who had spent time in a reform school, Hughes saw
his mother die from an accidental overdose of prescription diet
pills and set out to find a safer, better way to help people lose
weight. At 23, with only a ninth-grade education and after stints
with two direct-sales weight-loss companies that went out of
business, he went out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   He found a formula and started selling. His grandmother was his
first success, and her example brought in friends as new customers.
``Lose Weight Now, Ask Me How,'' became the mantra for Herbalife,
which started in the trunk of Hughes' car in 1980. It found its
footing in a small storefront in Beverly Hills, Calif., and grew
into a weight-loss, nutrition and personal care products company
with worldwide sales of nearly $1.7 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 21, the Hughes story came to a tragic, almost ironic
end when Hughes was found dead in the bedroom of the $25 million
Malibu beachfront house that he shared with his third wife, Darcy
LaPier. The company said he had drunk alcohol at a birthday party
for his 87-year-old grandmother at his home and later took the
antidepressant Doxepin, which had been prescribed to help him
sleep. Officials ruled the death an accident, noting that neither
the drugs nor the alcohol in his system would have been fatal
alone. But the combination was lethal.
</P>
<P>
   The death of the handsome and charismatic Hughes at 44 is a
serious blow for the company _ both because he was Herbalife's head
cheerleader and because of the possibility that his message of a
better life through herbal products might be diminished by the way
he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously an image problem,'' said Scott Hood, portfolio
manager at First Wilshire Securities Management, which has owned
Herbalife shares since late 1989. ``But how bad is it? It's not
like he was taking their own products.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond image, though, a number of other issues face the
executives who now run the company. A new team has taken up the
challenge of motivating and expanding a vast network of
distributors who buy the products from the company and in turn
recruit new distributors. Other worries include a slumping domestic
market for herbal products, a tight job market that could make it
more difficult to draw in distributors, a damaged relationship with
Wall Street after a failed attempt to take the company private, and
stock transactions that left investors crying foul.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 58 percent of the stock is now held in a trust. The
trustees are Christopher Pair, formerly the chief operating officer
of Herbalife and now the president and chief executive; Conrad
Klein, the chief business affairs officer and a longtime legal
adviser to the company; and Jack Reynolds, Hughes' father. (As a
young man, Hughes took his mother's maiden name.)
</P>
<P>
   Pair, who was a counselor at the reform school that Hughes
attended and later became a friend, said in an interview at company
headquarters in Los Angeles that he had no intention of trying to
substitute for Hughes, who at his death was chairman, president and
chief executive of the company..
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never fill his shoes,'' he said, adding with a
chuckle, ``I don't have his looks.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say he does not have a story to share with
distributors. When Pair was a young man, overweight and struggling
with back problems, Hughes persuaded him to try his product, a
weight-loss powder that was so new it came in plastic bags rather
than cans.
</P>
<P>
   He said he dropped 50 pounds in four months and became a
distributor for a short period before returning to the University
of Redlands in California to get his business degree. Though he
says his experience as a distributor will help him in managing the
company, he intends to focus more on operations and on mending the
relationship with Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   To motivate distributors, he said, there are plenty of other
stories to be told and thousands of hours of tapes of Mark Hughes
selling his vision.
</P>
<P>
   On Herbalife's Web site (www.herbalife.com), the voice of Hughes
still tells how his mother ``totally destroyed her life just trying
to lose 30 pounds'' as the company promotes its vision of realizing
monetary dreams through selling its vast array of products. Beyond
its core weight-loss and nutritional supplements, they feature a
wide variety of skin-care items, vitamins, shampoos, even a natural
sleep product. Among the company's competitors are Amway, Nature's
Sunshine and Weider Nutrition International.
</P>
<P>
   To keep Hughes' message fresh, Herbalife will rely more on the
stories of its top sellers. Members of the Chairman's Club and the
President's Team, who have networks bringing in hundreds of
thousands of dollars a month, already train new distributors and
conduct seminars, and those elite categories give distributors a
goal to strive for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success is just a reflection of his power,'' said Paco
Perez, who was a bellboy at an airport hotel in Los Angeles before
becoming Hughes' first employee and is now a member of the
President's Team. ``He taught us all by example. We're committed to
his dream.''
</P>
<P>
   To realize that dream, the network must keep growing. Despite
setbacks, it has always done just that.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, the company came under intense scrutiny by
regulators. The company paid $850,000 to settle a lawsuit by the
state of California that accused it of having made false medical
claims and having run an illegal marketing scheme. The Food and
Drug Administration forced it to remove two products from the
market for relabeling.
</P>
<P>
   Business issues have been of more concern in recent years.
Currency turmoil in Asia and Russia resulted in a steep drop in the
stock price, and Wall Street developed concerns about how the
company, which went public in 1986, was handling its stock and how
it was preparing to go private again.
</P>
<P>
   Though officials say the product and marketing issues of the
1980s did not amount to much and are of no concern now, Pair said
he would focus on rebuilding the company's relationship with Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Crawford, an analyst with B. Riley &AMP; Co., a Los Angeles
brokerage house, said, ``There's one significant hurdle standing in
the way of Herbalife regaining the trust of Wall Street, and that's
showing management is there for shareholders and not for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, whose firm stopped covering Herbalife last year, noted
that in 1998 management stock options with original strike prices
of about $14 were reset between $6.63 and $8. Such a move is not
uncommon when a company's stock price drops, as Herbalife's did
then, but this adjustment would have meant large profits for
executives had Hughes' buyback attempt gone through at $17.81 a
share. That effort, which would have repurchased all the company's
stock, was terminated because of bond market turmoil and increased
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Also of concern was a complex transaction in 1998 in which
Hughes ultimately received $18 a share for 5 million shares. Add to
that the buyback attempt, which led to a lawsuit by shareholders
who felt the offer was too low, and Pair has plenty to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we've had some very valid issues internally,'' he said,
referring to the legal fees and other costs of the buyback attempt,
``the company is extraordinarily sound, the distributor base is
absolutely committed to building the business, and we've got a
management team in place that is going to continue to do what Mark
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Pair said he would try to increase the price of the stock, which
he says is greatly undervalued. It closed at $8 Thursday on Nasdaq,
down from a 52-week high of $16.375 on Jan. 14. He declined to
offer specifics before sharing them with shareholders in July, but
he said plans call for continuing overseas expansion and adding new
products and new technology to aid distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's over 130 countries in the world; we're in 49,'' Pair
said. ``We haven't even touched China yet, which is going to be
potentially the biggest market in the world for direct selling.''
</P>
<P>
   He said at least a dozen products were being developed for the
United States, probably six to eight of which will come on the
market next year. Extensive new products are also to be introduced
in Japan and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Some institutional investors agree that the stock is
undervalued. They note that the company, with nearly $100 million
in cash (over $3 a share) and no long-term debt, trades at 4.6
times earnings and pays a 7.8 percent dividend.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said Herbalife's new team could send Wall Street a
strong message by buying back shares and returning the value to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   At such a low price, he said, the company is an attractive
takeover target, particularly to a company looking for a strong
distribution base. Herbalife has about 750,000 distributors
throughout the world and recently began operations in Ireland and
India. Though analysts say Herbalife has been able to maintain its
domestic sales while sales have slid at other companies selling
herbal products, there are concerns that with the job market tight
Herbalife will have a hard time holding distributors and finding
new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Herbalife said that it had not found that to be a problem and
that the strong economy was resulting in more sales.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Boesenberg, a Los Angeles distributor who was called at
random last week, said she would stop selling Herbalife in August
after 24 years. She said her decision was made before Mark Hughes'
death and was based on lack of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very fickle about vitamins, and I'm tired of having
people order thousands of dollars of vitamins only to get stuck
with them,'' she said. ``There's too much other stuff out there to
choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   She also cited an increase, to 7 percent, in shipping and
handling charges, which she said she had to pay even if she drove
to a warehouse to pick up supplies. In addition, she said,
distributors who had brought her in, as well as those she had
recruited, were gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've signed up a total of five or six distributors in the time
I've done this, and they've all dropped out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hughes' death, though, she did not expect that to have
any negative effect ``for the people who believe in Herbalife.''
</P>
<P>
   A conference in Philadelphia the weekend after the coroner's
report about Hughes' death supported her speculation.
</P>
<P>
   John Tartol, a Malibu-based distributor who is part of the
Chairman's Club, said 3,500 distributors turned out.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had expected to get phone calls after the release of
the coroner's report. Only one came. He also expected distributors
at the conference in Philadelphia to have questions about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not concerned,'' he said, adding that Hughes had
struggled with pneumonia and asthma this year, perhaps coming back
to work too quickly and weakening himself. ``It's kind of
interesting there's been a new commitment. We're going to go out
there and do it for Mark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
