</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-CHILDREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SAYS ONLINE PRIVACY LAW FLAWED  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal law intended to shield children from
online pornography was dealt a second setback on Thursday, as an
appellate court upheld a lower court order against enforcement and
declared that the statute was probably fatally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the case an agonizing conflict between the cherished
right of free speech and the profound duty to watch over children,
a three-judge panel of the Third U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals let
stand an injunction issued by a federal district judge.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous appeals panel in Philadelphia made it clear that
it saw a struggle not just between the First Amendment and a
society's moral obligation to its young, but a struggle to devise
laws compatible with the Internet's instant access and global
reach.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the panel said, the 1998 Child Online Protection Act
falls well short of meeting First Amendment standards, as the
American Civil Liberties Union and other plaintiffs contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will affirm the district court's grant of a preliminary
injunction because we are confident that the ACLU's attack on
COPA's constitutionality is likely to succeed on the merits,'' the
circuit court said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had appealed the district judge's
injunction and declined to say tonight whether it would appeal
today's ruling. ``We will review the decision and take appropriate
action,'' a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The protection act would require commercial Web sites to collect
a credit card number or some other access code as proof of age
before allowing Internet users to view on-line material deemed
harmful to minors. First-time violators would face criminal
penalties of six months in jail and $50,000 in fines. Repeat
violators would face an additional $50,000 a day in fines. The law
also provides for civil penalties of up to $50,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The law has never been enforced. Soon after it was passed by
Congress and signed by President Clinton it was challenged by a
coalition of 17 groups and businesses represented by the ACLU. The
plaintiffs include a condom dealer, an online art site, a gay and
lesbian online service and the Internet Content Coalition. The
coalition consists of some two dozen publishers with online
ventures, including Time Inc., MSNBC and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Child Online Protection Act was introduced in Congress after
an earlier effort to regulate children's access to Web smut, the
Communications Decency Act of 1996, was ruled unconstitutionally
broad by the Supreme Court in 1997. The high court held, among
other things, that the Communications Decency Act had failed to
sufficiently define its key terms, and noted that it was aimed not
just at commercial speech and entities but at nonprofit
organizations and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the Child Online Protection Act argued that the
latter law was far narrower, zeroing in on commercial Web-porn
traffickers and their ``teaser ads.'' Opponents of the law argued
that it could be applied to high-minded Web ventures that carry
sexually explicit material _ those dealing with gynecological
issues, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Leonard I. Garth, Theodore A. McKee and Richard Lowell
Nygaard praised efforts by Congress to protect children. But
turning to the concept of ``community standards'' of decency in
defining pornography, they noted the virtual impossibility of a Web
site meeting the standards of, say, Chicago, Amsterdam and Teheran
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling upheld District Judge Lowell A. Reed Jr. of
Philadelphia who, as a father and grandfather, had expressed
``personal regret'' at having to issue an injunction against the
child-protection act.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate judges said they shared his sentiments. They said,
too, that ``in light of rapidly developing technological advances,
what may now be impossible to regulate constitutionally may, in the
not-too-distant future, become feasible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
