<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TELECOMS-ATT-NYT &LR;      06-22 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOMS-ATT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SAYS AT&AMP;T CAN'T BE FORCED TO SHARE LINES TO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reversing a lower court, the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals ruled Thursday that a local jurisdiction could not
force a cable company that offered Internet access to share its
telecommunication lines with rival cable modem providers.
</P>
<P>
   But in ruling in favor of AT&AMP;T in its case against the city of
Portland, Ore., the appeals court defined the cable broadband
business as a ``telecommunications service,'' a distinction some
industry observers say may ultimately force such businesses,
including AT&AMP;T, to open their lines to competitors on a national
level.
</P>
<P>
   The decision left AT&AMP;T, the city of Portland and a coalition of
Internet companies seeking access to AT&AMP;T's telecommunications
lines each claiming victory in a suit closely watched by the
Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   And it left industry analysts and telecommunications experts
grappling with a decision they say raises as many questions as it
answers about how the cable modem business will be regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T won the battle but lost the war,'' said Scott Cleland, a
regulatory analyst with the Legg Mason Precursor Group, a
Washington-based market research firm. ``They lost the broader
fight over whether their service is regulated or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T executives disputed that assessment, arguing that it
was premature to conclude that federal regulators will force them
to open their cable lines to rivals. ``This is a complete
victory,'' said Mark C. Rosenblum, an AT&AMP;T vice president. ``Our
point was that local authorities are not allowed to regulate
telecommunication services and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission officials said the decision is
likely to bring all sides in the dispute to Washington seeking
clarification.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the officials said, neither the cable industry nor
its opponents had sought regulators' guidance on their view of the
cable modem business. A central issue is whether cable modem
operators are more like cable companies, which are not required to
open their lines to rivals, or more like telephone companies, which
must.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are open questions on which the commission has not yet
ruled and presumably will rule soon,'' an FCC official said. ``I
suspect all of this will be brought to our doorstep very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the FCC has embraced a policy it calls
``vigilant restraint'' with regard to Internet access, arguing the
marketplace _ not the government _ should determine which
technologies prevail and which fall by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   The case stemmed from a Portland City Council decision in
December 1998 to make the transfer to AT&AMP;T of a cable franchise
owned by Tele-Communications Inc. contingent on AT&AMP;T's opening
access to its high-speed Internet connections. In June of last
year, a federal judge in Portland upheld the move, despite
objections from AT&AMP;T that regulatory authority belonged to the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the case is of growing interest to major
telecommunications providers, Internet access companies and a
growing number of consumers seeking higher-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the Internet over cable lines is one of the nascent
technologies proffered as a high-speed alternative to the
conventional dial-up Internet access, but its distribution has been
held up in part by questions of whether local jurisdictions can
govern who controls the lines.
</P>
<P>
   In light of Thursday's decision, AT&AMP;T said it would start
offering the (AT)Home cable modem service in Portland starting
Friday. The company had refused to offer access previously because
the Portland city council mandated that if AT&AMP;T offered its
(AT)Home service, it would have to offer service to rivals as well.
</P>
<P>
   In December, AT&AMP;T announced plans to give rivals access to its
cable lines to deliver Internet access, asserting in a letter to
the FCC that access would be available by 2002. The company said it
could not open the lines before that time because it has an
exclusive deal to lease those lines to (AT)Home, a high-speed cable
service of which it is partial owner.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in November, AT&AMP;T plans to conduct a trial in Boulder,
Colo., in which rival Internet access providers will share the same
cable lines. AT&AMP;T says the effort will help it address unresolved
technical problems with open access. But several local
jurisdictions across the country, including Portland, have sought
to force AT&AMP;T's hand, arguing that competition will yield faster,
better-quality Internet access. The municipalities have sought to
force AT&AMP;T's hand by making such open access a condition of their
approval of AT&AMP;T's purchase of TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Sten, a Portland city commissioner, said Thursday that the
city had not decided whether to appeal the decision, in part
because city officials view it as a partial victory. ``If the
decision is interpreted as we think it will be,'' he said, AT&AMP;T
will be deemed to be a telecommunications service provider and thus
required to open access on a national level.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the 9th Circuit wrote that under ``the
principle of common carriage governs cable broadband as it does
other means of Internet transmission such as telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland, along with a coalition of Internet service providers,
pointed to the language of the decision as evidence that AT&AMP;T will
ultimately be subject to the same regulatory requirements as local
telephone companies, which must open their lines to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open access is the law of the highest court that has reviewed
this,'' said Greg Simon, co-director of the openNET Coalition, a
group of Internet companies joining Portland and other
municipalities. ``The law is now open access in the Ninth
Circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T's Rosenblum said that even if the cable modem business
were construed as a telecommunications service, it would not
necessarily be subject to open access requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FCC official said that just because the 9th
Circuit defined AT&AMP;T as a telecommunications service does not mean
that decision is a binding legal conclusion. The official said the
question before the court was about Portland's right to regulate
AT&AMP;T, not about how AT&AMP;T's status should be defined before the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   The official, as well as executives from AT&AMP;T, also noted that
the court decision stated clearly that, even if the cable modem
business were deemed a telecommunications service, federal
regulators have broad powers to exempt the technology from
open-access requirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
